<HEADLINE>
DAVIS SCOLDED BY PAC-10
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA guard Baron Davis was publicly reprimanded
and placed on season-long probation by the Pacific-10 Conference on
Tuesday for criticizing referee Terry Christman after Sunday's loss
at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any subsequent public comments on officiating by Mr. Davis . .
. will result in a substantial penalty,'' Pac-10 commissioner Tom
Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Steve Lavin _ who was ejected from the game but did
not mention Christman in his postgame comments _ is expected to
receive a private letter of reprimand for his actions, according to
league sources.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10's master officiating schedule, designed months ago,
called for Christman to work four of the Bruins' first nine games:
Oregon State, Stanford, USC and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   However, Christman is not scheduled for any UCLA games for the
remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid immediate suspension, Davis was required to apologize
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't have said what I said,'' he said. ``I was thinking
off emotion and I didn't take the high road.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis fouled out with 4:34 remaining and threw his mouthpiece in
frustration, prompting Christman to assess a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Davis said he felt ``cheated'' _ a term that
infuriated league officials.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he still feels that way, Davis said: ``I think, I mean,
yeah, I think so. But it's just the way I feel. Did I do the right
thing? No. No, I didn't. Did I say the right thing? No. . . . I was
just acting off emotions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
