<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELIG'S BIGGEST CRIME IS FAILURE TO FIX SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Never one to be intimidated by irony, Bud Selig came
to town this week and said that his history with major league
baseball in Seattle was, ahem, ``checkered.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a little like Lucy saying Charlie Brown has trouble with
his kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Selig, now baseball commissioner, came here to slobber all over
the new ballpark, Safeco Field, site of the 2001 All-Star Game.
Almost 30 years ago here, he was also drooling.
</P>
<P>
   As the head of a group of business pirates from Milwaukee, Selig
swooped in and stole the Pilots right out of spring training after
the team's single tremulous season in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years of litigation later, Seattle regained what Selig had
stolen when the Mariners took to the new Kingdome carpet.
</P>
<P>
   While much has changed in the intervening years, there remains a
constant _ major league baseball is still wobbling in Seattle.
Selig might be around for a remarkable milestone _ watching
baseball fail in three Seattle stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Sicks' Stadium, a converted minor league park, was fingered as a
big culprit in the financial failure of the Pilots. The Kingdome,
almost from its inception, has been targeted by the Mariners as the
source of almost all of their ills short of jock itch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after the public bought the club's argument to the tune of
$372 million in tax money, word is circulating that the huge new
ballpark revenues really might not fix all of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner officials have said quietly all along that the park is
not a panacea. In fact, they knew more than two years ago, when the
park was barely in the cocktail napkin stage, that it didn't pencil
out.
</P>
<P>
   That fear was a big part of their dramatic stunt in December
1996, when John Ellis tearfully announced the club was for sale
because some local politicians said mean things.
</P>
<P>
   But after Sen. Slade Gorton (R-Nintendo) came in and laid waste
to opponents and gave the owners a sweetheart deal, they
reluctantly went ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the park is six months from opening, their reluctance
is visible. The Mariners froze their player payroll at around $53
million, while their more profligate brethren went on a spending
spree worthy of Barbara Hedges. The upshot is that the Mariner
roster, patched together with the lame and the halt from other
teams, is barely on the outskirts of contention in the smallest
division in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the ballpark will make no payroll difference in 1999.
It remains to be seen whether payroll will increase thereafter. The
only long-term vision articulated by management is the paying down
of ballpark debt.
</P>
<P>
   Which explains the colorful new marketing slogan: ``Ya Gotta
Love This Balance Sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news in the 30 years of Selig's influence over baseball
in Seattle is that the local club is no longer a real threat to
leave. The bad news is that the club is also no longer a real
threat to win a championship. The end of the millennium offers
major league ball in Seattle as mediocrity in a pretty place.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of this is Selig's fault, of course. Nor does the
current ownership group bear all the blame for the systemic failure
of America's oldest professional sport and monopoly to pull itself
together in a fashion slightly more harmonious than the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the happy-face talk from Selig about the All-Star
Game coming to Seattle in the face of continued economic travail is
so much hypocritical claptrap that it's obvious the man has no more
conscience now than when he was wearing his buccaneer's outfit 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the impending financial debacle when the Mariners
attempt to extend the contracts of Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez to keep them in Seattle _ requiring an amount of money
approximating the gross national product of Norway _ Selig said:
</P>
<P>
   ``As commissioner of baseball, I want it to be Griffey of the
Seattle Mariners and Rodriguez of the Mariners going into the Hall
of Fame, and it's my job to work on it and see that that can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   You betcha, Bud. While you're at it, you go out there and stop
the salary spiral, halt the impending move of the Expos from
Montreal, redistribute fairly the game's revenues, compel the
players union and the umpires union to think of something beyond
themselves, subsidize the new ballparks, and get the World Series
TV ratings ahead of a Martha Stewart doily derby.
</P>
<P>
   In 30 years as owner, pseudo-commissioner and now commissioner,
Selig has had exactly no influence in curbing baseball's loopy
lunge toward self-destruction. He did come up with a novel idea to
blow up the 1994 World Series, and that didn't seem to do much
good.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a Mariner ownership group with the guts and
money of Turner, Steinbrenner or Murdoch, it's hard to imagine
Selig coming up with a plan to keep Griffey and Rodriguez in
Seattle without surrounding them with a team of Furbys.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the All-Star Game, Bud. But please don't be offended
if Seattleites clutch their wallets and purses when you walk by.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
