<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9593 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-PREVIEW-SP     02-03 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-PREVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS RELOAD WITH SEVEN NEW PLAYERS AND NEW COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Fans who enjoy television talk shows as much as they
do basketball might be disappointed in the Sonics this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of wholesale changes, it is evident the Sonics have
treated their Jerry Springer symptoms _ controversy and
questionable mental health off the court _ with at least a pristine
disposition heading into the abbreviated 1999 season that tips off
Friday against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   You know it is a new era when about the only teaser before
tipoff has to do with who is going to start opposite Gary Payton.
Not exactly a spellbinding situation, but it is fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after appearing in the NBA Finals, trading an icon
and making a head coaching change, the Sonics could not be more
invigorating. Hersey Hawkins looked around the team's practice
facility recently and observed that for the first time in his four
years in Seattle, everyone was present, happy and ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Sonics' quest to win a championship is the plot,
subplot and complete story line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to recast the team,'' team president Wally Walker
said, ``and firm up our weak spots. I think we've gone a long way
toward that. We're much better off than we were a year ago on a lot
of fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   There are seven new players, but hiring Paul Westphal to replace
George Karl as head coach is Walker's boldest move yet.
</P>
<P>
   Under Karl, the Sonics won three straight Pacific Division
championships and compiled more wins over a six-year period than
any team except the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But Walker concluded that the trapping, relentless pressure
defense that Karl stressed did not work well in a seven-game
series. Since reaching the Finals in 1996, the Sonics have not made
it past the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Walker expects that to change with Westphal. He stresses more
man-to-man coverage with occasional trapping. Offensively, the
Sonics plan to use the fastbreak whenever possible and use more
players _ up to nine _ in the regular rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new era,'' said assistant coach Nate McMillan. ``We're
trying to establish our own identity. Paul's just now trying to lay
that down. It's hard when you only have two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``George is gone. There's no reason to compare. And now Paul has
his group. Right now, Paul is trying to get the team to believe in
his system.''
</P>
<P>
   How different is this edition of the Sonics?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the team took an aggressive approach in the draft.
Vladimir Stepania was the 27th player selected in the first round,
but already he is showing signs of becoming a star. His biggest
hurdle now is learning the difference between European basketball
and the NBA game.
</P>
<P>
   Rashard Lewis, the 19-year-old high school player taken in the
second round, is sufficiently skilled that Westphal might change
his original plan and play him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I've learned about the NBA is that you have to
be flexible,'' said Westphal, whose style stands in stark contrast
to Karl's.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Westphal stepped into a completely different situation
than Karl left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The essential cornerstones _ Payton, Hawkins, Vin Baker and
Detlef Schrempf _ remain in place. Gone are McMillan, Jim
McIlvaine, Sam Perkins, Jerome Kersey and Greg Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is the infusion of new blood that has pumped
confidence into the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Center Olden Polynice and guard/forward Billy Owens were
significant free-agent additions considering the Sonics' salary-cap
constraints. The team spent $1 million on Polynice and paid a
little more than $2 million to Owens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has all the makings. It has a good mix of youth and
veterans, a good mix of complementary talent and a real commitment
to winning,'' Walker said. ``On pure size, we may not be much
different, but we'll be a more physical and better rebounding
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice brings toughness and solid rebounding ability to the
starting lineup, two qualities the Sonics haven't had in the center
position in years.
</P>
<P>
   Owens gives the Sonics versatility, a 6-foot-9 player who can
perform at three positions. He's a good ball-handler who can post
up either guard, which presents match-up problems whenever he's on
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   That Owens also can grab offensive and defensive rebounds is
further proof that the Sonics should be as advertised: A more
versatile and better rebounding team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year things have really changed and hopefully we'll get
over the hump,'' Payton said. ``Maybe this will be it for us. This
year, we're starting out fresh. We don't have any big holes. There
won't be any excuses. It's all going to be about winning and
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   This is, arguably, a Sonic squad that boasts more depth than
ever. It is a nice quality to have considering the
50-games-in-90-days schedule. The Sonics twice will play five games
in six nights between now and May. There also is a stretch when the
Sonics have 16 games in 23 days.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal plans to compensate by playing a combination of
different lineups and rotating starters. During weeks when the
schedule reads three games in as many days, Westphal said he will
rest players in the second or third game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to have to start it off (fast). Paul's
going to try some things the first couple weeks of the season,''
Payton said. ``But he knows me and Vin want to be in the game and
he knows how competitive we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal figures it will be hard to lose many games as long as
Payton and Baker are on his side. Having established himself as
arguably the best point guard in the league, Payton is a legitimate
candidate for the most-valuable-player award.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baker did not fare well in the playoffs last season, he
is establishing himself as a money player next to Payton. They are
as proficient a tandem as any in the league, and Westphal clearly
expects Payton and Baker to shoulder the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's worked harder or shown more leadership than Vin and
Gary,'' Westphal said. ``And I don't think you can want to win more
than Gary does. It just burns in him. If anything, sometimes he
forgets how talented he is. His competitiveness and quickness is in
another class. He's for real.''
</P>
<P>
   One still has to wonder, just how real are the Sonics?
</P>
<P>
   So far, they have been a mere blip on the preseason championship
radar, to which Walker responds, ``I'm not too concerned with what
people are saying about us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many of the Western Conference powerhouses seem too
concerned about the Sonics, either.
</P>
<P>
   But as Westphal pointed out tongue-in-cheek, each team is in the
same predicament: Each is in first place in February. And that
means absolutely nothing in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly hard to get to the Finals. Everybody's got a
story,'' Westphal said. ``In Utah, they couldn't get past Houston
for a long time. The Lakers can't seem to get past Utah. There's
always some nemesis out there.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be the year the Sonics have cleared their biggest
hurdle: themselves. Now, whenever someone mentions Shawn Kemp's
trade demand and Karl's contract squabbles, it is like hearing
about a tired, old rerun.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics clearly have switched the channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about the past,'' assistant coach Dwane
Casey said. ``Paul's brought a refreshing personality to the table.
It's a new day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
