<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCFOOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEIDMAN SET TO SIGN WITH UCLA TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Westlake Village tight end Mike Seidman ends
months of secrecy and speculation today when he signs a letter of
intent with UCLA, according to recruiting sources.
</P>
<P>
   Seidman had narrowed his choices to USC and UCLA, and no one _
not family, not friends, not teammates _ has uttered a public peep
about his decision.
</P>
<P>
   The school he selects will have landed the No.1 tight end in the
state and one of the best prospects, at any position, in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Sylmar's George Wrighster, who wants to play either tight end or
linebacker, is expected to sign with Arizona or Oregon. UCLA is no
longer involved, a source said, because it recruited Wrighster
strictly as a linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins promised Seidman they would not recruit another tight
end, the source added.
</P>
<P>
   Slow to receive commitments in December, UCLA is fast
approaching its 21-scholarship maximum.
</P>
<P>
   The latest to commit is Kevin Brant, a 5-11 multiposition player
from Bethesda, Md. He is the son of television commentator Tim
Brant and chose UCLA over Maryland, his father's alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Gardena defensive back/sprinter DeShaun McCullough committed to
UCLA last week and instantly became the Bruins' fastest recruit.
However, the scholarship will be nullified if he does not attain a
qualifying SAT score.
</P>
<P>
   Add Monrovia tailback Akil Harris, and the Bruins have 18 firm
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills lineman Blane Kezirian, son of UCLA athletic
department administrator Ed Kezirian, will receive a scholarship if
the Bruins do not reach their limit. If they do, Kezirian will
enroll next year.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Bruins are recruiting Harvard-Westlake's 300-pound
tight end, Alex Holmes, who is petitioning for college eligibility.
He could play any one of four or five positions in college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
