<HEADER>
A9596 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-WESTPHAL-S     02-03 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-WESTPHAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOOTH OPERATOR: WESTPHAL OFFERS FLEXIBILITY, EXPECTS RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Great person. Tremendous family man. Dedicated in his
faith. Play word association with Phoenix Suns owner Jerry
Colangelo on the subject of new Sonics coach Paul Westphal, and
those values come right to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Another one, too. ``He is his own person,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   It's the way Westphal was as a player, blending skill, smarts
and independent thinking to become a three-time All-NBA guard for
the Suns. And it's the way he was as coach in Phoenix, trusting
players to act in the best interest of the team. When Colangelo
felt that approach had stopped working, he fired Westphal midway
through the 1995-96 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's a very bright, intelligent guy, and he'll do only what
he wants to do,'' Colangelo said. ``And you have to respect the man
for doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Earning the Sonics' respect is Westphal's challenge now, and he
doesn't have some of the usual tools. He's not a taskmaster,
doesn't control personnel moves and makes less money than Don
MacLean.
</P>
<P>
   But he's coaching here as he did in Phoenix _ the way (start
ital)he (end ital) wanted to be coached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot of personal responsibility on them to do the right
thing, because I think that's the only way they can achieve the
utmost,'' Westphal said. ``And there's a risk that goes with that,
because if you don't dictate every move they make, they might make
some mistakes. But if they have it burning inside them to win, I
don't want to stifle that.''
</P>
<P>
   In that statement, Westphal is paraphrasing a quote that's
important to him. He had it posted in his office in Phoenix, in its
Sparky Anderson incarnation: ``When you get a group that wants to
win, you've got to let them.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds almost like ``get out of the way,'' and Westphal
will, in some cases. He won't worry much about his veterans, and
they're happy with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's allowing us to be professionals, and that doesn't happen
very often in this game,'' said 38-year-old swingman Dale Ellis,
whose rookie season of 1983-84 was Westphal's last as a player.
``He's a veteran coach, he's played the game, he understands what
it takes to win. And whenever you give some of the power back to
the players, you appreciate it and respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   That worked for a while in Phoenix with Charles Barkley, who
responded to Westphal's free hand and led the Suns to the 1993
Western Conference title. But it wore off eventually, and the
freedom Westphal gave Barkley alienated teammates A.C. Green and
Kevin Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Westphal must find a way to placate star Gary Payton
without losing the rest of the team. Both are pledging peace, but
Payton retains his loyalty to former coach George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand, Coach Karl was my coach, and he put
me where I'm at right now,'' Payton said. ``So I can't compare him
to anybody right now. I'm sorry and I hate that I lost him, but
I've got a new coach now and I've got to deal with it. I'm going to
try to deal with it as best I can, and right now Paul is a great
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said he'll treat Payton the same way he treated
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I treat people with respect and try to allow them to be
themselves as much as possible. That's what I did with Charles, and
that's what I'll do with Gary or any of the players,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary's a straightforward person, and I think I am. I've never
thought I was going to have a problem with him, because he's a
steel-eyed competitor. If you give me a guy that wants to win, why
should I have a problem with it? We're going to be going in the
same direction.''
</P>
<P>
   After Westphal took the Sonics job last June, he met with Payton
and his agent for lunch in Oakland. They agreed not to try to
change anything about each other, and Payton told Westphal he
enjoyed the freedom Karl gave him and wished to keep it that way.
At 30, Payton said, he was too old to play for a disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, no, he wasn't like that, and that was it,'' Payton
said. ``We sat there and ate our salads and a little chicken and we
left.''
</P>
<P>
   (start ital) When you get a player who wants to win. ... (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always going to come onto the court every night and play,
so that's just one thing he knows,'' Payton said. ``I'm not going
to create problems, I'm not going to create none of that. I'm not
going to be the kind of guy where I'm always loud and always
disturbing the plane and stuff like that. I'm going to have fun
sometimes, but he is not going to have to worry about me too
often.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal doesn't think so, either. He's not going to dictate
Payton's life. Payton, he said, is his own man.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL SIDEBAR/BREAKOUT)
</P>
<P>
   20 THINGS YOU DIDN'T KNOW ABOUT PAUL WESTPHAL
</P>
<P>
   1 _ An active child, Westphal earned the nickname ``Perpetual
Motion'' from his parents.
</P>
<P>
   2 _ Idolized Elgin Baylor while growing up near Los Angeles: ``A
lot of people compared me, because of physical similarities, to
Jerry West, but Baylor was always the guy I patterned myself
after.''
</P>
<P>
   3 _ His junior high basketball team sometimes played games
preceding Lakers games at the L.A. Sports Arena. One of those
Lakers games turned out to be the last of Celtics legend Bob
Cousy's career.
</P>
<P>
   4 _ The son of an aircraft designer, Westphal graduated from the
coincidentally named Aviation High School in Redondo Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   5 _ Quit a job at Baskin-Robbins 31 Flavors when the ice cream
store stopped selling his favorite flavor, boysenberry sherbet. It
was Westphal's only job during high school.
</P>
<P>
   6 _ Collected complete sets of baseball cards for three years as
a Little Leaguer, but his mother threw them all out when he
graduated high school. ``It still hurts to this day,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   7 _ Toughest player for him to guard: Nate Archibald. Had the
most trouble when guarded by: Norm Van Lear.
</P>
<P>
   8 _ After retirement from NBA, took the Suns to arbitration
hearings twice, charging the club cost him incentive money by
conspiring to keep him from getting playing time. Lost both cases.
</P>
<P>
   9 _ Founded basketball program at Southwestern Bible College in
Phoenix in 1985-86; team finished 21-9 and played for championship.
</P>
<P>
   10 _ Was succeeded by his brother, Bill, at Grand Canyon College
after leading the school to the 1988 NAIA title.
</P>
<P>
   11 _ Jersey No. 44 was retired by Phoenix Suns in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   12 _ Pulled a different kind of ``Chris Webber'' in the famous
Game 5 of the 1976 NBA Finals vs. Boston. With his Suns down by one
late in the fourth quarter, Westphal deliberately called a sixth
timeout, even though his team had none. The technical foul put
Phoenix down two, but under old rules, the Suns got the ball at
halfcourt. That put Gar Heard in position for a last-second shot
that fell, sending the game into double overtime. (Suns lost in
third OT.)
</P>
<P>
   13 _ Seventeen years later, enjoyed another fine Game 5 as Suns'
head coach. After hearing the Bulls urging fans to safely celebrate
their pending championship, Westphal strode into the Phoenix locker
room and wrote ``Save The City'' on the black board. The Suns, down
three games to one, beat Chicago to send the series back home.
</P>
<P>
   14 _ Gary Payton isn't the only Sonic who knows TV commercials.
As Suns coach, Westphal was featured in a popular ``Whataburger''
TV ad with his mother, Ruth. They argued over who makes the better
burger _ Whataburger or Mom.
</P>
<P>
   15 _ Non-basketball fantasy is to hit a home run in the major
leagues: ``Nothing feels better than a home run. It's probably the
best thing to do in sports.
</P>
<P>
   16 _ Wife Cindy and he sponsored friend Steve Jones in his first
year on the PGA Tour, ``keeping him out there until he made enough
money to keep himself out there.''
</P>
<P>
   17 _ While away from NBA coaching, wrote a book of stories he's
gathered through his years in basketball, patterned after Harvey
Pennick's ``Little Red Book of Golf.'' Book hasn't been published,
but Westphal says, ``I really like it.''
</P>
<P>
   18 _ Took a two-week family vacation to Israel in 1997, doing
color commentary on the NBA playoffs for an Israeli TV station.
</P>
<P>
   19 _ Was a volunteer assistant basketball coach for a year at
son Michael's Chaparral High School team in Scottsdale, Ariz.
Michael is a walk-on at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   20 _ Is good friends with conservative commentator Rush
Limbaugh, and wants Limbaugh's critics to give him equal time: ``He
can defend his positions, but he can't defend people calling him
names. Not that I agree with everything, either _ I don't cast
myself as a political guy _ but it's only fair to listen to what
somebody says before you call him names.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
