</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE MAKES SETON HALL SECOND STRAIGHT VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-SETON HALL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Tuesday night's Big East matchup against Seton Hall,
Boston College coach Al Skinner told his young players that the
Pirates, who limped into Conte Forum looking to snap a four-game
losing streak, would likely regard the 13th-place Eagles as ``the
pill that would cure everybody's ills.''
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall, however, found no such relief.
</P>
<P>
   BC pinned the Pirates with another Excedrin headache, taking an
81-66 decision before an ESPN2 audience and a crowd of 2,734. It
was the second straight win for BC (5-14, 2-9), which snapped an
eight-game skid with its first conference victory of the season
last Wednesday against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, the Eagles ``are accustomed to being
successful,'' Skinner said. ``Now they're starting to feel success,
and as Kenny Harley said in the locker room afterward, `This is the
way it's supposed to be.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that they've come to expect, and it's something
that they've been working towards.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than a week, the Eagles have gone from a team simply
hoping to win its first conference game to a confident group ``that
knows we can win our next conference game, against West Virginia
Saturday,'' said freshman forward Kenny Walls, who led four BC
players in double figures with 24 points on 7-for-12 shooting in
just his second career start.
</P>
<P>
   Harley chipped in 17 points on 6-for-9 shooting, while Michael
Cotton added 12. Jonathan Beerbohm came off the bench to score 11
points before spraining his left ankle late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence is getting there,'' Walls said. ``We know we
can win some basketball games in the Big East if we just play
defense for 40 minutes. Earlier in the season, the reason we were
0-9 was that we weren't playing 40 minutes of basketball. Tonight
we played 40 minutes of basketball, and if we continue to do that,
we'll to be successful _ no matter how young we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Walls knew it was going to be his night when he knocked down
back-to-back 3-pointers, sparking an early 14-2 run that gave BC a
16-6 lead. The Eagles had a sizzling start, hitting nine of their
first 10 shots, to streak to a 22-11 lead but cooled off
considerably by making only five of their last 15 shots in the half
to control a tenuous 34-33 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our drought that continues for our team and our program,
I'm very disappointed with the way our kids played defense,'' said
Seton Hall coach Tommy Amaker, whose team (11-10, 5-7) got a
career-high 24 points from Rimas Kaukenas. ``You've got to give
credit to Boston College for their (54 percent) shooting. We shot
over 40 percent (for the first time in seven games), but our
defense was lousy. Kenny was tremendous with the shots he was
making for threes.''
</P>
<P>
   Walls knocked down a trey that sparked a 10-2 run at the start
of the second half. After the Eagles thrice increased the lead to
10 (48-38, 50-40, and 52-42), Beerbohm threw down a dunk to make it
54-42. BC then went on a decisive 16-6 run _ Walls scored 8 on a
pair of 3-pointers and a jumper _ to put the game out of reach,
70-50, with 3:25 to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles just might climb out of the cellar before too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not overly concerned with the place that we're in,''
Skinner said. ``We've still got a lot more to go. There's a lot
more games to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, there's not much difference between 13th,
12th, or 11th, as far as I'm concerned. But what I am concerned
about is how we compete and how we play. Right now we may be 13th,
but we're not playing like a 13th-place team.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Seton Hall and Notre Dame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
