r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBACOL-COLUMN-LAD     02-03 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBACOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S GET IT ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A collection of lawyers and accountants, petty owners and
petulant players, all greedy and myopic beyond belief, denied us
all the best hoops action on Earth for six unbearable months.
</P>
<P>
   They gave us posturing instead of post-ups, drivel in place of
dribbles, bickering instead of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the powers that run the NBA gave fans probably $2
billion worth of reasons why they should tune out what's left of
the season. And reason No. 2,000,000,001 came when Michael Jordan
retired.
</P>
<P>
   But the season opens Friday night, and rest assured, you will be
back anyway. In part because to be a fan is to be a born sucker. We
can't help ourselves but to return to baseball parks and basketball
arenas anymore than we can turn away from the umpteenth televised
freeway chase.
</P>
<P>
   And yet this basketball season will provide so much more. For
the fence-sitters out there, for the ones pouting over the lockout,
you have our empathy and understanding. But here's why you should,
and will, come back to the game:
</P>
<P>
   __ No MJ. As much as Jordan meant to the game, his retirement
brings back the suspense of the season. The Bulls are gone and the
void could be filled by any number of successors, from the Lakers
to the Jazz to the Pacers to the Rockets to the Knicks to the
Sonics to the Nets. That competition is good for the game.
</P>
<P>
   __ The 50-game season. Face it, 82 games is too many, and most
fans readily admit they don't really pay attention until February
anyway. The compacted schedule will be fast and furious, with teams
playing three straight nights and five games in a week. There will
be no shortage of intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   __ Larry Bird's Pacers. Want to see the good guys finally win
one? The guys who win not on talent but on hard work and dedication
and teamwork? Jump on the Indiana bandwagon and watch the only team
that had 11 players practice together throughout the lockout
steamroll over the league's slackers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Latrell Sprewell's Knicks. For pure entertainment, how can
you beat a group that includes the foot-in-mouth union president
(Patrick Ewing), the man poised to steal Ewing's role as No. 1
scoring option (Allan Houston), the guy who suffered a
profanity-laced meltdown while addressing a group of children
(Dennis Scott) and of course, the coach-choker (Sprewell)?
</P>
<P>
   __ Kobe's comeuppance. Bryant, the Lakers' young star, is poised
to become a dominant force, even if he's coming off the bench. And
by the end of the season, it might be difficult to keep him out of
the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   __ George's genius. George Karl tamed Gary Payton and made the
Sonics perennial contenders, and he's inheriting a Milwaukee Bucks
squad with enough talent to become a darkhorse favorite in the
East, with a lineup featuring Terrell Brandon, Ray Allen and Glenn
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   __ Malone's make-up with Utah. The Jazz star renounced his team
during the lockout, then made a tearful return and might well cap
off all this soap-opera drama with a storybook ending, a
championship in June.
</P>
<P>
   __ Nice-guy Nets. Jayson Williams wasn't only one of the top
voices of reason during the lockout, he was also the only player we
know of who donated thousands of dollars to workers at Continental
Airlines Arena, a small but genuine form of apology for the havoc
the players and owners caused. Williams and fellow nice guy Keith
Van Horn also form the backbone of one of the league's
up-and-coming contenders.
</P>
<P>
   __ Top 50 reunion. Clyde Drexler retired and Scottie Pippen took
his place on the Houston roster, giving the Rockets another
three-man core of NBA-top-50 players with Hakeem Olajuwon and
Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sacramento vs. Denver. Not that anyone wants to watch the
Kings play the Nuggets, but there will be a season-long battle for
most improved status among these two perennial dogs. Each helped
itself immensely in the offseason, the Kings getting Chris Webber
and Vlade Divac, the Nuggets landing Nick Van Exel and Antonio
McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   __ And finally . . . inclement weather. A single snowstorm could
throw Shaq-sized wrenches into the NBA's rewritten, airtight,
no-room-for-error schedule, and simple karma guarantees it will
happen. Watch the folks at NBA headquarters in New York become
Weather Channel addicts, and then watch them go postal when a
mid-February blizzard snows out the Midwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
