u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-RODMAN-HN     02-03 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-RODMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Antoine Carr, whom the Rockets acquired to back up Hakeem Olajuwon,
will undergo arthroscopic surgery on his right knee today and will
miss the next two to three weeks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Left with few alternatives, sources said Tuesday the Rockets
will pursue free-agent forward Dennis Rodman, who has played on
five NBA championship teams _ two in Detroit (1989 and 1990) and
three with the Chicago Bulls (1996-98).
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, 37, a Dallas native, has led the NBA in rebounding the
past seven years, a league record. He averaged 15 rebounds per game
last season while playing in 80 games for the Bulls, the most games
he had played since the 1991-92 season, when he was with Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman has led the league in offensive rebounding six of the
past eight years, averaging 5.3 offensive boards last season. He
played 2,856 minutes last season, his highest total since 1993-94,
when he was with San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, who recently fired his agent, Dwight Manley, could not
be reached for comment. He had been rumored to be heading to Miami,
but Heat coach Pat Riley said Monday night that Rodman would be
``better off in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a veteran team; Scottie (Pippen) knows him,'' Riley
said. ``(Charles) Barkley understands him. It's a very, very
experienced, veteran team.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Rockets agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would definitely help us,'' said one Rocket, preferring to
remain anonymous. ``With Dennis, Charles and Dream (Olajuwon), we'd
get two and three shots every trip downcourt. That's how many
offensive boards we'd be getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman and Stanley Roberts, who has battled weight problems his
entire career, were the only big men of note available.
</P>
<P>
   Carr's injury forced the Rockets to look elsewhere for help.
Carr, 37, who has a medial plica, a fold of tissue in the knee
similar to what Olajuwon endured last season, was supposed to give
the Rockets an experienced big body (a 6-9, 272-pound 14-year
veteran) who can play defense, hit the boards and set rock-hard
picks for the shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to play on it (at Tuesday's practice),'' said Rockets
coach Rudy Tomjanovich of Carr. ``He was out there for a while, but
he just couldn't be himself. He couldn't make his moves without
some pain. So we feel the best thing is to go and get this thing
fixed now and have him for a portion of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it hurts us. I never really got into a real good feel
with him, because he got hurt early and he wasn't able to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he was here, I really loved the effect he had on the
team, and it will be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how long before Carr is ready to contribute,
Tomjanovich just rolled his eyes and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking the wrong guy,'' he said. ``I just do the X's
and O's.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but after all the injuries they've had over the past two
seasons, everyone assumed Tomjanovich was the basketball equivalent
of Marcus Welby. But if there's one area where Tomjanovich would
rate as an expert, it's filling the holes created by those
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Carr's is the second serious injury to hit the Rockets this
season. Second-year swingman Rodrick Rhodes tore a right pectoral
tendon while lifting weights. After undergoing surgery last month,
Rhodes does his rehabilitation work every day and is about five
weeks away from returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going great,'' Rhodes said. ``The scarring in my muscle
is healing fast. Everything's looking good. They (the doctors) like
the progress. I've been working hard just trying to stay in
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The time away is distressing to Rhodes, who would love nothing
more than to be on the court, learning from Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is killing me,'' Rhodes said. ``I have a hard time even
watching it. You feel like an outcast because you see the whole
team doing one thing and you're doing another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though you know you're injured, you still feel like an
outsider. It's the competitiveness that makes you want to do stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to do little things to occupy my time _ I work out while
they practice, or I try to get iced. Yeah, it's that hard to watch.
But the addition of Scottie, that makes me want to watch because
he's one of the top 50 players. I try to watch him to see how he
goes about his business and how he handles things.''
</P>
<P>
   What Rhodes sees, in the glimpses he manages when he's up to it,
is a player he thinks will help his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt,'' Rhodes said. ``That's another thing. With Scottie,
you can't relax in practice. He brings intensity to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a good work ethic, so every day he comes to practice
with a lot of energy. He's a high-energy guy, he's competitive and
he likes to practice, so that makes you have to go harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's not just the big games that get you up, it's an
every-day thing for me because I've got Scottie to go up against. I
think he'll make me a great player in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, you want to test your talent against the best.
That's when I'm at my best, when my back is against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``And also, when you have to compete against great players, they
make you compete better. You're so nervous and want to get
everything in detail that you want to play a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes said the Rockets will be all that much stronger when he
and Carr return to the active list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make my presence felt,'' Rhodes said. ``I have
to, to establish myself on the team and to get the confidence of my
teammates back. You start to get into a rhythm with the guys you're
playing with.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I'm not out there getting the rhythm and getting
accustomed to certain guys, I have to come back and establish
myself. Whatever they want to mold me into, I'm going to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
