<HEADER>
A9606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     02-03 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SEND in the clowns.
</P>
<P>
   And the juggler and the fire eater and the sword swallower and
the human cannonball and the trapeze artists.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the bearded lady. The Rockets may already have one
eye on her twin sister in Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   As Friday's hurry-up season opener against the Lakers nears, the
air is filled with the sounds of a calliope. Will that be an NBA
championship contender that takes the floor at the Great Western
Forum? Or a circus?
</P>
<P>
   If necessity is indeed the mother of invention, then crisis is
most certainly the stork that delivers desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what dropped down the Rockets' chimney Tuesday when
they got the word that Antoine Carr's right knee will require
surgery and force him to miss as much as the first three weeks of
the season. In this compressed 50-games-in-90-days schedule, that
is possibly one-fourth of the season for a 37-year-old who does not
know the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Mix in the fact the remaining backup widebodies are a pair of
newcomer journeymen in Pig Miller and John Coker with the idea that
contenders are putting heavy emphasis on getting out to a healthy,
fast start _ figuring home-court advantage in the playoffs can be
won or lost in the first weeks _ and the cause for alarm is
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, tentative feelers go out to Mars or Jupiter or the
headquarters of World Championship Wrestling for the only player in
NBA history with the qualifications to appear on the covers of both
Sports Illustrated and Modern Bride.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it is still only talk. But Rodman told a
newspaper in South Florida on Tuesday that if he plays this season,
it will be for either the Rockets or the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic that after years of trying to beat the Chicago Bulls,
the Rockets may actually try to become them. First Scottie Pippen,
now Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   What will we call this Bulls-Rockets hybrid _ the Buckets? Will
orange hair become the rage in Houston? Will Mayor Lee Brown get
his tongue pierced? Or willeven the wedding-gown-,
leather-skirt-,feather-boa-, dog-collar-wearing Rodman decide the
Rockets' pajama-striped uniforms are an affront to good taste and
cast his lot in LA?
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Rodman from the Lakers, where he would make a formidable
frontcourt partner for Shaquille O'Neal, is one reason to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   The other is, of course, his ability. Rodman is a voracious
rebounder, a smothering defender who moves well without the ball,
and a great passer, a talent that often goes unnoticed but would
fit well into coach Rudy Tomjanovich's half-court offense.
</P>
<P>
   Also, because of the compact, grueling schedule, Charles Barkley
has said he likely won't be at his best in every game. With a
player of Rodman's stature on hand, Barkley might feel less
pressure to push on when he's hurt or fatigued and therefore might
not break down before the playoffs. Those occasions would give
Rodman a chance to stand out, which is what the phenomenon of
``Rodzilla'' is all about, frequently to excess.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dennis is on the court, he's cool,'' Pippen said.
``Getting him there is a problem sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The question: How much of their core beliefs are the Rockets
willing to sell off for a third championship?
</P>
<P>
   Remember their motto from the 1995 campaign: ``Be hungry, stay
humble.'' Does that remotely sound like Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   This is not a blue-nosed screed against body piercing and
tattoos. It is merely a reminder that Rodman's kicking of
cameramen, goonish mugging of opponents and referee-baiting make a
mockery of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Word is Rodman ruled out signing with Miami because Heat coach
Pat Riley was going to make him toe the line, be punctual for
practice and actually show up for the start of all games. The
thinking is that Rudy T, known as more of a player's coach, would
be tolerant of a few idiosyncrasies, as long as Rodman performs.
Tomjanovich did, after all, have gun-brandishing Vernon Maxwell as
a starter on the 1994 title team.
</P>
<P>
   From the standpoint of Leslie Alexander, it would seem to be
another case of the team owner doing whatever it takes to give the
fans a winner. But there is a line where you can cross into
Steinbrennerism, trying to buy a title.
</P>
<P>
   In matters of chemistry, homemade explosives can be dangerous,
especially in regard to the sensitivity of Hakeem Olajuwon. He did
not at all like the constant bickering between Barkley and Clyde
Drexler the past two years. So it's hard to imagine his being
comfortable as part of a carny sideshow the third, fourth and fifth
times Rodman goes bonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Hurry! Hurry! Step right up!
</P>
<P>
   But at what price the clown show?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
