<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9607 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PAYTON-HNS &LR;      02-03 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PAYTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
HONOLULU _ Walter Payton, the NFL's all-time rushing leader and a
member of the Pro Football Hall of Fame, came forward Tuesday with
the shocking news he needs a liver transplant.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Payton, 44, is suffering from a rare disease, primary sclerosing
cholangitis, that blocks the bile ducts in the liver. Patients in
his condition have a two-year survival rate without a transplant.
Payton is on a transplant list and will get no preferential
treatment over less famous patients, according to his doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm still healthy, even though I look like I've
lost a lot of weight,'' Payton said at a news conference outside
Chicago during which he broke into tears. ``To the people that
really care about me, just continue praying.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who rushed for 16,726 yards and won a Super Bowl during
a 13-year career with the Chicago Bears, called a news conference
to reveal his disease because of speculation about his health.
</P>
<P>
   When his son, Jarrett Payton, announced last week at a news
conference that he would play football at the University of Miami,
his father appeared ill, prompting the speculation about his weight
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get everything straight before things got bad,''
said the elder Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Lagattuta, one of Payton's physicians, says the
disease is so rare that only about three of every 100,000 people
suffer from it. With a transplant, Lagattuta said, the one-year
survival rate is ``88 percent'' and long-term survival is ``very
promising.'' He said most transplant patients return to a normal
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was scared, Payton snapped: ``Am I scared? Hell,
yeah, I'm scared. Wouldn't you be scared? What can you do? It's not
in my hands anymore; it's in God's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pro Bowl practices in Honolulu, players from the AFC and
NFC were stunned by Payton's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo quarterback Doug Flutie was Payton's teammate with the
Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter's the guy who took me under his wing when I came to
Chicago,'' Flutie said. ``I threw my first NFL touchdown pass to
Walter. In a tough situation there, he was a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to him. I wish the best for him and his
family. He's a competitor. He'll come through it. I'm praying for
him and keeping my fingers crossed. Everyone's pulling for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just goes to show that no one's exempt from illness. No
matter how much money you make or how successful you are, no one
ever has the world by the tail. Walter's a fighter, and I'm sure
he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Bruce Smith, Flutie's teammate in Buffalo, is a
14-year veteran who played against Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him personally,'' Smith said of Payton. ``I think he's
a wonderful individual who meant so much to this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to God there's a way he can get this transplant and get
it in a hurry and live the rest of his life in a normal and active
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Payton's liver disease isn't caused by alcohol,
steroids, hepatitis or any kind of immunodeficiency disease.
Symptoms are chronic fatigue and a yellowing in the pigment of the
eyes and skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always respected Walter, and my thoughts and prayers are
with him,'' said Green Bay defensive end Reggie White. ``I hope his
doctors can save him. I know God is watching out for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton, Chicago's No. 1 pick out of Jackson State in 1975,
retired after the 1987 season. He was enshrined in the Pro Football
Hall of Fame in 1993 and named to the Bears' board of directors in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Payton thought he had problems with his gall bladder
and underwent a series of tests. He was diagnosed two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lagattuta said Payton has significant bile-duct blockage. To aid
his digestion and give him adequate nutrition, a plastic tube was
surgically inserted in the vessel that carries bile from the liver
to the intestines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing _ I can eat anything I want, as much as I want,
and I still can't gain any weight,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   In his final season with the Bears in 1987, the 5-11 Payton was
listed at 202 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much he weighed now, Payton wouldn't say.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he replied: ``You want to pick me up?''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Oilers running back Eddie George grew up idolizing
Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows that everybody's vulnerable, that no man is
untouchable,'' George said. ``Walter was a great player who's meant
so much to the game. He's a strong and determined man, and I'm sure
he'll get the transplant he needs and pull through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Arizona Cardinals cornerback Aeneas Williams: ``We're
praying for Walter and his family, and I know the Lord is watching
over him. Walter was such a great player and a great man. I pray
that he gets the transplant as soon as possible and everything is
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who resides in South Barrington, Ill., a wealthy Chicago
suburb, is involved in a number of businesses. He continues to
endorse products.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction is a Bob Marley lyric _ `Even the biggest
man was once a baby,''' Seattle Seahawks linebacker Chad Brown
said. ``It shows that no matter how great your accomplishments are
on the field, you're not invincible.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction to hearing about Walter's illness is that we
should live our lives like it's the last day, because we never know
when our last day is going to be. I'm sure he'll be fine, but it
shows you should live your life to the fullest, because you just
never know what's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
