r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN     02-03 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT WAITS ... AND SITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Last year he was the only nonstarting
All-Star in the league. This season he'll be the only $71 million
man playing a supporting role. These aren't exactly the kind of
honors Kobe Bryant had in mind for his resume.
</P>
<P>
   As the 20-year-old swingman embarks on his third season for the
Los Angeles Lakers, he is again slotted to come off the bench.
Eddie Jones has a lock on shooting guard. Rick Fox is entrenched at
small forward. And coach Del Harris has scrapped the idea of
rotating the three players as starters.
</P>
<P>
   So Bryant waits.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' precocious superstar-in-waiting won't pout, though.
He'll just issue warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can do. I just have to be patient, wait
until my turn, and when I get my turn, I'm going to explode,'' he
said, then laughed, then repeated, ``I just have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Bryant wasn't thrilled with the three-man rotation
idea, even though its main purpose was to get him into the starting
lineup on a semiregular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, once you throw me in there, throw me in there
(as a permanent starter),'' he said. ``I think having that rotation
kind of just threw everybody off balance. . . . You can't please
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Bryant's sixth-man role has been in any way
insignificant. He was sixth on the Lakers in average minutes played
with 26, only four minutes per game fewer than starting forward
Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   And Bryant's scoring average, 15.4 points per game, was the
highest among nonstarters in the NBA. Remaining in that role offers
a familiarity of routine, but it also poses a nightly challenge as
he subs at three positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have starter status, you pretty much know what your
matchup is gonna be. You know who you're gonna guard,'' Bryant
said. ``Last year, coming off the bench I didn't know who I'm
coming into the game for, so you really have to study three
different game plans. . . . Starting is definitely more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   He figures he'll have that chance soon enough. Bryant's due to
make $9 million next season, the first of his new six-year
contract, and it's a pretty sure bet he'll be playing the minutes
to earn it by then. But he admits disappointment over his continued
second-team status.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know me, man. I'm ready to go. That's what I worked all
summer long for,'' he said. ``But I'm always an optimistic person.
Everything happens for a reason. If it's not meant to happen this
year, all it does is give me another year to prepare. Simple as
that.''
</P>
<P>
   So one more season on the bench won't kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Joked Bryant, ``It's a shortened season anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Exhibitionists: Shaquille O'Neal scored a game-high 40 points
as the Lakers held a four-quarter intrasquad scrimmage for a
private audience Tuesday night at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Fox, nursing a sore right foot, was the only player to sit
out the game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Popular: Friday night's season opener against Houston at the
Forum is sold out. About 500 tickets remain for Sunday's game
against Utah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
