<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-PEP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA PROVIDES KEY HIT IN PEPPERDINE VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tony Garcia insists he's American of Cuban
descent, yet his Pepperdine baseball teammates like to kid him
about his heritage.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Garcia was born in Cuba but has lived in the
United States since age 3. He hasn't returned since but feels pride
whenever a Cuban baseball player defects or succeeds in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're Cuban and you don't play baseball, you're kind of
weird,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He knows all about Rey Ordonez, Livan Hernandez and Orlando
Hernandez. He would like to be the next great Cuban player, but for
now he's happy to be a freshman starting for the Waves.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth game, he helped his team remain undefeated with
the game-winning double in the eighth inning that gave Pepperdine
an 8-6 victory over UCLA Tuesday at Jackie Robinson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine is 4-0 for the first time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Although Garcia is a freshman, he's hardly inexperienced. His
family is as baseball-mad as any other Cuban family. His
grandfather played semipro in Cuba before getting hurt, and his
father played in high school.
</P>
<P>
   The family arrived in Miami via Mexico 15 years ago with its
baseball passions intact. Garcia moved to Temecula for high school
and was good enough to be the USA captain on the under-14 team that
played in the 1996 Pan-American Games in Brazil. He also played on
the under-16 team two years later in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving at Pepperdine, which he chose over USC and Arizona
State, his teammates teased him aboutbeing Cuban. To get back at
them, he listed in his bio it would be his dream to return to Cuba
and work in the sugar-cane fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be anyone's goal,'' he said. ``It's hard to be a
baseball player in Cuba. Castro, nobody likes, but he puts a guilt
trip on you. If you want to leave, you're seen as a traitor. I
encourage every Cuban to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's winning hit came in the eighth inning after UCLA (2-4)
tied the score at 6 half an inning before. Damon Katz singled and
took third on a throwing error, bringing the infield in. Garcia
doubled down the left-field line off reliever Bobby Roe (0-2) to
give the Waves a 7-6 lead. He later scored on a passed ball.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Reed (1-0), Pepperdine's third pitcher, won in relief going
12/3 innings. Jay Gehrke pitched the ninth for his second save.
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for 14 walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching has got to come through more,'' said UCLA right
fielder Brian Baron, a Hart graduate who transferred from
Northwestern. He started in right field and went 1 for 4 with a run
scored and a catch at the wall. ``You're not going to hit every
game, but your pitching and defense have to be consistent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
