<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLOWOKANDI DELIVERS _ SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Olowokandi participated in his first
Tinseltown dress rehearsal at the Sports Arena on Tuesday and
delivered the seemingly forgettable line of 11 points and 12
rebounds in 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the message might be more important than the production
values.
</P>
<P>
   During the Clippers' free-to-the-public, split-squad scrimmage,
the 7-foot rookie demonstrated an abundance of quickness, fancy
low-post footwork and a willingness to mix it up on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't too bad,'' said Olowokandi, the first pick in last
year's NBA Draft. ``Right now, I'm doing the best I can, and I'm
gradually adjusting and getting used to it. I'm just trying to help
make this team better.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't seem to be a problem, although first-year coach Chris
Ford is preaching patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot to learn,'' said Ford, ``but he's getting along
pretty well. Michael's just going to have to learn how to adjust
his game. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael will learn from his mistakes, and that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Thriving: According to franchise watchdogs, Olowokandi is
thriving and surviving, on the court and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will do well,'' said Ford in a point-blank answer to those
who already have judged the NBA's top pick to be a bust based on
low numbers and shaky circumstances during his six-game tour of
Europe. ``Allow the kid time to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's starting to fit in. He's shown he's a tough guy and he's
been moving right along. He's demonstrated that he can do
everything people have been saying he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   So, after three full workouts, the reviews from coaches and
teammates are in: If you see only one rookie center this year,
check out the 7-footer from Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I think he's going to be great for our team,'' said
Clippers forward Maurice Taylor, who was earning similar praise as
a rookie last season. ``It's good to have a big body out there to
watch your back.''
</P>
<P>
   __ And now, the bad news: Rookie power forward Brian Skinner
will undergo an arthroscopic examination to repair possible damage
to the lateral meniscus ligament of his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Baylor star, selected with the 22nd pick in the first
round, averaged 2 points and 6 rebounds in last weekend's
exhibition games against the Lakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 0138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
