<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEKELEC-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEKELEC GAINS FAIL TO SATISFY INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Telecommunications equipment maker Tekelec
disappointed investors Tuesday with quarterly earnings well below
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of network equipment and diagnostic tools reported
earnings of $13.8 million, or 16 cents per share, for October,
November and December. That was well above the $8.9 million earned
in the same quarter a year ago. But it was 15 percent below a mean
estimate of 19 cents per share from five analysts surveyed by First
Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not what we were expecting,'' said analyst Brian Modoff
at BT Alex Brown in San Francisco. Modoff said there had been no
indication from Tekelec officials before the report that it would
be so far off estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that lower your confidence? Yes,'' Modoff said.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts after the release of its
earnings report, Tekelec blamed the fact that several anticipated
sales did not go through for fourth-quarter performance weaker than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Though Tekelec made its report after the close of trading, its
stock still fell more than 6 percent Tuesday, despite the fact it
also announced a new contract with U.S. West worth an estimated $5
million to $6 million. Tekelec shares closed at $21.875, down
$1.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec performed better for the year, earning $39.2 million, or
59 cents per share. Analysts had expected annual earnings of 60
cents per share. Revenues for the year totaled $176.6 million,
including $49.1 million in the final three months.
</P>
<P>
   Though a supplier of telecom network equipment to small and
newcomer phone companies for much of the 1990s, Tekelec in the last
year has emerged as a growing favorite among big players, too. In
addition to the U.S. West deal, the company has recently penned
deals with Sprint and Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
