 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 419 - February 3, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 419 -- Feb. 3, 1999 We are offering
the following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. JEREMY DAVIES : MILD AT HEART Jeremy Davies, who may get an
Oscar nomination for his role in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' is a
modest, low-key actor who takes Hollywood stardom in stride.
Interview by Jessica Kerwin. From W Magazine. 800 words + photo. 2.
LAURA DERN : BORN TO ACT Laura Dern has been in movies since
literally before she was born - her mother, actress Diane Ladd, was
pregnant with her in the biker movie ``Rebel Rousers'' (1970) - and
the former Oscar nominee is considered one of her generation's best
actresses. Her latest film, ``October Sky,'' opens soon. Dern talks
about the new film, her acting talent, why her parents (Bruce Dern
and Diane Ladd) opposed her wish to be an actress and how she got
together with her current boyfriend, actor/director Billy Bob
Thornton. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo. 3. HIP-HOP'S
TIPTOP Compared with rock 'n roll, jazz and salsa, hip-hop is a
baby, just over 20 years old. But a look at the Billboard charts
makes it clear that hip-hop reigns. On any given week, it
dominates, with at least four albums in the Top 10. It's no longer
music of the underground. Many predict 1999 will be the year that
rap and hip-hop explode, snatching the music industry's limelight,
as it expands with more artists, more producers ... and more fans.
The list of successful hip-hoppers would fill pages; this article
narrows down the most talked-about contemporaries so you know
exactly who's who. By Cindy Rodriguez. From The Boston Globe. 1,500
words + photo. 4. FOR WILLIE NELSON, ALL ROADS LEAD TO MUSIC At 65,
singer Willie Nelson is as busy as he's ever been. Besides a hot
new album - ``Theatro'' - he's also busy with charitable endeavours
on behalf of the Campaign for a Landmine Free World and his own
group, Farm Aid. And he's keeping up a tour schedule that would
wear down plenty of much-younger musicians. Nelson talks about his
new album, the roots of his music, how he balances music with
activism and why the boy who grew up on a farm is now the singer
who fights hardest to preserve family farms. By J. Poet. 1,300
words + photo. 5. THE RISING TIDE OF 'DAWSON'S CREEK' ``Dawson's
Creek'' is the hottest thing in teen television. Simon Houpt
explores why as he visits the show's North Carolina set, watches a
hot love scene being filmed and talks with stars James Van Der
Beek, Katie Holmes, Michelle Williams and Joshua Jackson about the
series, writer/executive producer Kevin Williamson, sex scenes and
why no one can kiss Van Der Beek without laughing. By Simon Houpt.
From TV Guide Canada. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
JORDANA BREWSTER TAKES ON THE '60s It's difficult for someone born
in 1980 to understand what the turbulent 1960s were all about, but
Jordana Brewster has a better idea than most, after starring in
NBC's epic miniseries ``The 60s.'' Brewster, who also stars in the
current film ``The Faculty,'' talks about the mini-series, why she
postponed her first semester at Yale to make it, what she learned
in her three years as Nikki Munson on ``As The World Turns,'' and
how the music of Bob Dylan helped her to understand life in the
1960s. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
THE SIXTIES ARE BACK The '60s are back. But relax - it's only on
TV. It was probably inevitable : The baby boom generation are now
running the world. They are also producing its movies and
television, and the '60s for them was the best of times. Says Lynda
Obst, producer of the four-hour TV mini-series ``The Sixties,''
``The music that gave tempo to that decade, the community that was
forged at that time, the values that were stirred up at that time
still live with us, and inside all of us.'' She's not alone. Other
'60s projects are coming up. By Ivor Davis. 1,000 words + photos.
(Not available in Great Britain and Australia.) 8. GIRL INTERRUPTED
AT HER MUSIC By the time she was a year old, Amy Marcy Cheney could
hum 40 tunes accurately in key. Finally permitted to play her
mother's piano when she was 4, Amy immediately played her favourite
tunes, aptly harmonized, picked out bass accompaniments to any
melody and also made up original pieces in her head, without
recourse to a keyboard. Simmering just below the surface of
Adrienne Fried Block's biography of America's first notable female
composer (''Passionate Victorian : The Life and Work of an American
Composer, 1867-1944,) is the profoundly disquieting question : If
this prodigiously gifted person had had the nurture and the
opportunities to explore that Mozart had, might she have
accomplished as much? By Lawson Taitte. From The New York Times
Book Review. 1,300 words. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or
33.1.47.42.18.81 I am interested in story no. ______ from summary
