<SLUG> BC-DELCO04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delphi's ancestor Delco was truly born in a barn
 &HT;    By Benjamin Kline
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For all its sleek lines and curves, gleaming
paint and plush interiors, onboard computers and music systems, the
automobile is still pretty much what the motor car was 90 years ago
when Delco, the ancestor of today's Delphi, was born in a barn in
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   It's a conglomeration of parts. And some of the most important
parts were developed and made here.
</P>
<P>
   Charles F. Kettering and Edward A. Deeds incorporated the Dayton
Engineering Laboratories Co. on July 22, 1909 with capital stock of
$150,000. The company name, suggested by their colleague William A.
Chryst, soon was being shortened to D.E.L.Co. The first three
letters are preserved in the modern Delphi, which is being spun off
by General Motors Corp. this week.
</P>
<P>
   Kettering, a near-sighted young electrical engineering graduate
from Ohio State, had come to Dayton in 1904 to work in the
inventions department at National Cash Register Co. The invitation
came from Deeds, the plant superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Deeds had been tinkering with a motor to replace the crank on
cash registers. He needed someone to take over the project.
Kettering accepted the job and the two men clicked.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they were moonlighting in the hayloft of Deeds' carriage
barn, behind his house at 319 Central Ave., where he and a mechanic
had built a car they called the Suburban Sixty. The informal group
of 12 men that grew from their partnership became known as the
``Barn Gang.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first success was an electrical spark ignition system that
Kettering and Deeds sold to Henry M. Leland of Cadillac Motor Car
Co. for the 1910 model. The sale of 5,000 units forced them into
manufacturing, with rented space in the Beaver Power Building,
still standing at East Fourth and St. Clair streets. The slogan:
``Nothing on the dashboard but the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Kettering's next success was the electrical self starter for the
1912 Cadillac, followed almost simultaneously with electric
lighting for automobiles. Soon Delco had grown to 1,200 employees,
mostly in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   The company became the first General Motors Dayton division in
1918. It has mainly descended through the years as Delco Products,
but with other historical branches on the family tree, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Delco Remy Division, Anderson Ind., founded in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   _ A.C. Spark Plug Division, Flint, Mich., 1908.
</P>
<P>
   _ Delco Appliance/Rochester Coil Co., Rochester, N.Y., 1908.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inland Division, formerly Dayton Wright Airplane Co., 1923.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sphinx Manufacturing Co., Birmingham, England, 1898.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Delphi starts out as a huge organization doing business
globally, a far cry from the ``Barn Gang.''
</P>
<P>
   In the uncertainties of a harsh and competitive world, Delphi
employees can recall what Boss Ket said about failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure is permissible,'' he said, ``just as long as it's only
temporary. The one time you don't want to fail is the last time you
try.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
