<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELPHI-HACHEY04-COX     02-03 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELPHI-HACHEY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delphi: Company looks to Hachey for manufacturing know-how
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Guy C. Hachey, the new president of Delphi
Chassis Systems, agreed to be the subject of a newspaper profile on
one condition: no photographs of him sitting in his Kettering
office, please.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hardly ever in his office,'' explained Delphi spokesman
Michael McCurdy. ``More than any GM executive I've known since I've
been here, he spends an enormous amount of time on the (factory)
floor. He's trying to understand the plants.''
</P>
<P>
   He has good reason to take a close look. Those plants are key to
Delphi's future.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old native of French-speaking Quebec started with
General Motors fresh out of college as a 22-year-old foreman in
Canada's Ste. Therese assembly plant. He has been elbow-deep in
GM's manufacturing operations ever since, including managing the
Oshawa, Canada, fabrication plant and, more recently, the worldwide
manufacturing of Delphi Interior and Lighting Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Hachey holds a key position in the new Delphi corporation that
GM is expected to spin off Friday with an initial stock offering.
From his Kettering headquarters, Hachey will oversee 43 Delphi
Chassis operations in the Dayton area and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole background is in the plant,'' said Hachey (pronounced
HASH-ee). ``What I've found is that it's amazing how much you can
accomplish if you give people a chance to prove themselves. I've
met very, very few people in my career who don't want to do a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Delphi's 15,000 employees in the Dayton area are counting on
Hachey's manufacturing acumen _ and his people skills _ to steer
their newly independent operation through some rough competitive
waters. GM officials have said the spinoff will better enable
Delphi to do business with companies other than GM. But it also
will free GM to buy parts from Delphi's competitors.
</P>
<P>
   As part of GM, Delphi has had its share of plant troubles here
in recent years, including a 17-day strike in 1996 among brake
plant workers and a threatened strike again this past summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, and remember it's been a very short period of
time, we've had very good working relations'' with Hachey, said
Gary Hill, president of United Auto Workers Local 696. ``He has
been more open with the whole work force, and he has challenged his
side of the house as well as ours to be more competitive in a
global economy. That's been the main difference from the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Other union officials are more open in their praise. ``There
have been some positive changes already (in the work environment),
and we expect even more in the future,'' said Kenny Woolum,
president of the International Union of Electronic Workers Local
755, which represents 6,000 Delphi employees in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Clark, chairman of IUE Local 755, agrees. ``I think he
really wants to see the operation turn around and succeed. This is
a feeling we really didn't have in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolum said Hachey made a good first impression with the union's
rank-and-file. ``When he came on board, he not only met the
officers of the local, but he also took time to come over and meet
our entire bargaining committee. He's really a very personable type
person, especially for the position that he holds.''
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in the small town of Charlemagne, 20 miles from
the city of Quebec, Hachey grew up speaking primarily Canadian
French, which accounts for his slightly accented English ``mostly
on longer words,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His father started out as a payroll clerk for Purina Chow in
Canada before working his way up into management. ``He was making
just $35 a week back then, and he never lets me forget that,''
Hachey said.
</P>
<P>
   Hachey was able to have his college education paid for by
gaining admission to St. Jean Military College, Canada's equivalent
of West Point. But wanting more control over his destiny following
graduation than the military would allow, he applied in his last
year and half to McGill University in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   There, on a bulletin board near the admissions office, fate
reached out: An application for GM scholarships caught his eye.
Hachey applied for and won a full ride from GM, including his
tuition and fees, his books and his first summer job.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing up the GM ladder, Hachey moved from French-speaking
Canada to upstate New York and then to Detroit _ a far bigger jolt
for Hachey and his family than his most recent move to Dayton,
where he says the people are warmer and the pace of life more
laid-back than in the Motor City.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we moved here, we must have had 15 neighbors come in with
cookies and cakes _ people who didn't know who I was or what I did.
It was just that I was a new neighbor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons of privacy, Hachey prefers not to say where he now
lives in the Dayton area with his wife, Christiane, 43, and their
two teen-age children.
</P>
<P>
   Hachey concedes that he is still in his honeymoon period with
Delphi employees, but he said there's no reason those good
relations can't continue well into the future. ``The best thing we
can do to extend the positive momentum we've got right now is to
stay ahead of the (industry) curve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hachey said there are many things both management and labor can
do to increase the company's competitiveness. They include not only
leaner, more modern plant operations ``but how we manage our
materials and our supplies . . . (and) our overhead costs,
including my salary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials declined to share that figure with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Hachey also cites the design of Delphi products as vital to the
company's success. ``You can have the best (labor-management)
relations in the world, but if you don't have a product that sells,
you're not going anywhere in today's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim DeBrosse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
