<HEADER>
A9838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN04-CO     02-03 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Send money along with a mentor
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ One hour a week. Not much time to
educate a youngster, but when an adult spends time one-on-one
helping a child to learn, remarkable progress can occur. The
student feels valued. Learning becomes important. Someone in
authority believes he can achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush understands these dynamics. As a candidate, he visited
more than 200 schools. On Wednesday mornings, he begins his day at
Augusta Raa Middle School a few miles from the Capitol in
Tallahassee. There, in the library, before the first class of the
day, he spends an hour reviewing the homework of a 13-year-old
seventh-grader who is behind in his studies. Since the governor has
been tutoring him, the boy named Trayvon _ whom Gov. Bush describes
as ``a smart kid'' _ is already showing signs of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics may dismiss the governor's effort as political posturing,
comparable to Gov. Chiles' walk across Florida and Gov. Graham's
workdays in varied jobs. I caution against such a response. Making
time to mentor children is a worthwhile endeavor not to be
trivialized. And, may I add, touching the lives of children with
different backgrounds is an excellent way for powerful people in
all organizations to get in touch with the reality that is Florida.
I hope other leaders in high places follow the governor's example.
</P>
<P>
   For a child at risk, a few minutes of individualized attention
can be a life-saver. Clearly, Gov. Bush, who has asked his
high-level appointees to follow his example, understands this need.
So, I wonder whether he knows many children in our public schools
never get a total of an hour per year of individualized instruction
from their teachers. Typically, such students drop further and
further behind until they drop out _ or graduate without an
education.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the monumental failure of our public schools are
many, but the main problem is that we have too many classes too
large for teachers to be effective. Class sizes, especially in
Florida's elementary and middle schools, are too large for teachers
to give students in regular classes the individualized help they
need as they struggle to master the basics. Overwhelmed by the
numbers, many teachers survive by fulfilling the requirements of
the system rather than individual needs of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Check the paper trail of written goals, progression charts and
other reports teachers must complete and file with school
administrators. (Often, this voluminous paperwork is filed away
without being read unless a school is audited.) Add to this work
lesson-plan preparation and paper correction.
</P>
<P>
   The larger a teacher's student load, the less likely the
students are to receive adequate feedback. With more students in
any given class than is reasonably possible to deal with, too many
teachers begin with hope and end in despair that children can
learn. The result is more discipline problems, more failures, more
frustration for teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   If we are to hold teachers accountable _ and we must _ they must
be given a manageable student load. That's why I urge Gov. Bush to
reconsider his tax-cut plan, though such largess is sure to have
the support of shortsighted politicians and gain favor among others
who feel no responsibility for all of our children.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Mr. Bush said during his campaign, he truly believes in
children first, he will reverse the plan announced this week to
give the biggest tax cut _ $1.2 billion _ in Florida's history.
That's twice as much in reduced taxes as the $600million increase
in the state education budget. Such a massive cut, given the needs
of our schools, is not in the best interest of our children.
</P>
<P>
   More than tax relief, we need smaller public school classes that
allow teachers adequate time to reach more than the youngsters who
automatically rise to the top of any crowd, the ones like Trayvon,
who need a guiding hand up. There are more like him than Florida
can afford to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
