<HEADER>
A9839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN04-COX     02-03 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The nose knows where termites lurk
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Exterminator Mark Langford says there's one
little detail you've got to remember when you use a dog to find
termites in someone's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``One important thing is to walk the dog before inspections,''
said Langford, an owner of ASAP Termite Pest Control.
</P>
<P>
   Langford's termite-detecting beagle is named Woody. What else
are you going to name a termite dog? Aluminum Siding? Langford has
been using Woody for about a month to sniff out the wood-eating
bugs. He says Woody's the only termite dog in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a nose on him,'' Langford said. ``I'm going to get
him his own business cards with his picture on it that says,
'Woody, termite finder.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Woody is getting this special treatment because he's already
helped Langford land six extermination jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to keep up the pace to pay his way, though.
Langford's company has invested about $12,400 in Woody. Langford
says it cost $7,900 to have Woody trained to sniff out termites at
the Beacon Academy for dogs in Annapolis, Md. The program lasted 3
1/2 months.
</P>
<P>
   Langford also had to buy plane tickets to and from Annapolis for
himself and Woody. Langford spent a week at the school to learn how
to work as Woody's termite-finding handler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We train the handler to carry out a very thorough house
inspection,'' said Andrew ``Doc'' Solarz, vice president and
trainer at Beacon Dogs Inc. in Annapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the $2,400 for a full-page color advertisement in
the Austin Yellow Pages to plug his business as the ``HOME OF
WOODY! Austin's Only Beacon Trained Termite Detection Dog!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called marketing; we've got something no one else has,''
Langford said. He added that Woody really can find termites,
carpenter ants and wood-boring beetles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will alert on them by pawing at the wall,'' Langford said.
``If there's some other kind of bug around, he just passes it by.''
That's nice, because you'd hate to tear down a wall for a couple of
roaches.
</P>
<P>
   It's all done by smell, Solarz said. A properly trained termite
dog, he said, can smell the termites that are eating your house
from the inside out. Termites release methane, Langford said.
</P>
<P>
   Termite dogs ``respond to the odor that's coming out from that
termite infestation,'' said Solarz, who has trained 34 dogs to
detect termites. ``It's like if you had an onion, and that odor is
going out from that onion.''
</P>
<P>
   People can't smell termites, because we don't have the amazing
sniffers that doggies have. ``A dog's olfactory system contains
some 200 million olfactory cells,'' Solarz said. ``Man has only
about 5 million olfactory cells.''
</P>
<P>
   Langford ran the dog through his paces at a vacant apartment
Tuesday in Southeast Austin. Langford hid three small plastic
containers with a few termites in each one at various places around
the apartment. The dog found all three in short order.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the advantage of having a dog search for termites
instead of looking for them yourself? Langford said it's that the
dog can tell you they're in the wall before the damage shows up on
the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Termites are working inside walls, inside floors; termites
never come out into the light,'' Solarz said. ``So a visual
inspection isn't effective until the termites have done quite a bit
of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of cutting holes in walls, he can pick up on things that
you can't see going on,'' Langford said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's cuter to watch Woody work than some guy with
plumber's cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   Woody has one drawback. Like any dog, he is distracted by
high-priority doggie items such as, say, Fifi.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be a reason to abort an inspection with him,''
Langford said. ``For instance, if they'd had a female dog around in
heat in the last 30 days.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
