<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's in a name? Probably a copyright
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Just when you think nothing is safe from the
filthy halls of commerce, you learn that, well, nothing is safe
from the filthy halls of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Take my daughter's name, for instance. A time-honored Catholic
name, I thought, even if a tad old-fashioned. My mother's name,
although everybody calls her Vera.
</P>
<P>
   Little did I know the name really belongs to Archie Comics. Yep,
that's right; the comic book company claims to own the trademark.
Lawyers had threatened legal action against the father of
22-month-old Veronica Sams unless he pulled the Web site
Veronica.org.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything in our society that somebody isn't trying to
own? Riverfront Stadium can't simply be Riverfront Stadium; it's
Cinergy Field. And now, heaven forbid, the gods of industry are
going after our kids' names.
</P>
<P>
   What can you expect in a world in which Harley-Davidson tried to
trademark the sound of its engine? The company claimed that the
roar was distinctive, describing it as ``potato'' repeated quickly
several times. (If you stammer at the dinner table _ ``Could you
pass the potatoes-potatoes-potatoes?'' _ is that a trademark
violation?)
</P>
<P>
   That's the Alice in Wonderland territory in which David Sams
found himself when he created the Veronica.org domain in honor of
his daughter's birth. Sporting a teddy bear bathrobe and chubby,
Gerber-smeared cheeks, the cyberspace Veronica laments: ``We've hit
a snag _ the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can a company own my name? It's a common first name. Since
Veronica's friend in Archie Comics is named Betty, do they own her
name, too?''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to attorneys representing Archie Comics, David Sams,
a California businessman, warned, ``Should you wish to take legal
action, it is going to have to be against a toddler and her
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Count my Veronica in. Poor deluded child, she thinks she owns
the trademark on the name. If you ask her name, and she's in the
mood to answer such an ignorant question, she'll sing-song
``Ve-RON-i-ca,'' as if it were one of those names, like Elvis or
Cher, that require no further embellishment.
</P>
<P>
   Archie Comics recently backed down, saying the company will take
no legal action unless the Web site contains offensive material.
Depending on how company execs view the Teletubbies, little
Veronica just might get to keep her Web site.
</P>
<P>
   It's a compromise that still suggests ownership of the name,
and, on behalf of Veronicas everywhere, I resent that. If anybody
owns a trademark on the name Veronica, it's the Catholic church.
She's a patented saint, enshrined in cathedrals and churches all
over the world centuries before that brunette met Archie. (For
those of you who haven't perused your Picture Books of the Saints
lately, Veronica is the saint who wiped Christ's bleeding face on
the way to Calvary. Legend has it that his image appeared on her
handkerchief.)
</P>
<P>
   Hence the name means ``true image,'' according to the baby
books. What company in the world, come to think of it, wouldn't
want to put their trademark on that?
</P>
<P>
   But there are some things you just can't own.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't understand that, you're a real Jughead.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
