<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9841 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX     02-03 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attorneys not user-friendly to software that could aid clients
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Any day now I expect Texas' jackbooted
lawyer-protection police to kick in my front door and ransack my
house for my copies and upgrades of Quicken Family Lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In an touching effort to protect Texas consumers, U.S. District
Judge Barefoot Sanders has released a summary judgment to prevent
Parsons Technology Inc. from selling copies of its popular home
computer software Quicken Family Lawyer and Quicken Family Lawyer
'99 in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A ban on the sale of self-help legal software may be a defeat
for the First Amendment and common sense, but it's a slam-dunk
triumph for the Unauthorized Practice of Law Committee, which is
fully funded by the State Bar of Texas and also an extension of the
Texas Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Although Judge Sanders and the Texas lawyers who support his
decision claim they only want to protect the public, there's
nothing new about lawyers using the law to protect and enrich
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are attracted to lawmaking the way buzzards are
attracted to road kill or reporters are attracted to train wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike buzzards and reporters, lawmaking lawyers get to
manufacture business for themselves by passing more laws. More laws
beget business and more lawyers. No laws mean no lawyers. It's a
simple concept.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmaking lawyers and judges, who by law must be lawyers, get to
make the laws and hand down the rulings that control the practice
of law.
</P>
<P>
   So Judge Sanders is ruling that Parsons Technology Inc. is
violating the law that prohibits the unauthorized practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons' Quicken Family Lawyer software sells for under $30 and
offers more than 100 suggested legal forms, which just might cost a
non-lawyer rube a second mortgage on his house if a lawyer filled
out and handled those same forms.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers, of course, make the reasoned argument that the laws
that make the unauthorized practice of law unlawful are on the
books only to protect non-lawyers who otherwise might be taken to
the cleaners if they follow the legal advice of anyone except a
lawyer. Follow that?
</P>
<P>
   Some versions of Quicken Family Lawyer give instructions on how
to file wills, real estate leases, employment contracts and other
legal documents.
</P>
<P>
   Generic forms for wills, real estate leases and such have been
around for years. Lawyers, due to their tender feelings for their
fellow citizens, have never liked the sale of these blank forms.
But they have never come up with a constitutional way to prevent
the publication and purchase of these forms.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers also do not like to see non-lawyers read law books and
attempt to handle their own legal affairs. Non-lawyers, after all,
might make an expensive and heartbreaking mistake.
</P>
<P>
   But even lawyers deeply concerned about self-inflicted legal
injuries have been unable to figure out how to stop citizens from
reading law books in public libraries and taking their own legal
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Computer software, however, is another matter. The software puts
generic legal forms together with the knowledge of how to file the
forms in a handy interactive package that asks questions needed to
pick the right legal form and fill it out.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, howdy. That's getting very close to stealing the butter
right off a lawyer's biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   By making the sale of self-help legal software illegal in Texas,
lawyer-protection police will have to beef up anti-smuggling
efforts along the Texas-Mexico border, the Gulf of Mexico coastline
and at every crossing coming into Texas from New Mexico, Oklahoma,
Arkansas and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer jokes surely will be probable cause to search for
anti-lawyer software.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my best friends are lawyers, but this is absurd. I hope
I don't get in legal trouble for saying that.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is a Senior Editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(AT)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
