<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE     02-03 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORS: THIS IS PART ONE OF A TWO PART FILE
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did it become law that you did not have to live in a
congressional district to be eligible to run for Congress from that
district?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's been the law for a rather long time, because the
requirements for running for election to the U.S. House of
Representatives are established in Article 1, Section 2 of the U.S.
Constitution. The requirements are that candidates must be 25 years
old, U.S. citizens for at least seven years, and residents of the
state from which they are chosen. When it comes to political
reality, however, most U.S. representatives live in the district
from which they are elected. What you may have in mind are laws for
some state and local elections.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there an Internet site for checking up on charities?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Philanthropic Advisory Service of the Council of Better
Business Bureaus maintains files on hundreds of national and
international charity organizations, and publishes information on
whether an organization meets standards established by the BBB. One
such standard, for example, is whether the organization spends at
least 50 percent of its donations on the activities for which it
seeks funds. The advisory service can be reached on the Net:
http://www.bbb.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent newspaper article told of a 31-year-old man who
stabbed two people in a Social Security office in Alabama. How
would a 31-year-old be eligible for Social Security benefits in the
first place?
</P>
<P>
   A: Social Security could pay benefits to a 31-year-old who had
been judged disabled. It's also possible in limited situations that
a 31-year-old could receive survivors benefits paid on the record
of a deceased spouse. Social Security pays more than just
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Republicans say that the $1,000-a-year, long-term health
care plan for seniors proposed by President Clinton was in the
Republicans' Contract With America in 1994. Was it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Contract With America promised to give unspecified tax
breaks to seniors who purchased private long-term care insurance
and to adult children caring for elderly patients. In 1996,
legislation passed that allows taxpayers who buy long-term care
insurance to deduct a portion of the premiums if they itemize
deductions and if their medical deductions surpass 7 percent of
their gross adjusted income. Tax breaks for adult children caring
for elderly parents stalled. The legislation proposed by Clinton
allows a $1,000 annual tax credit for people who need long-term
care, including at-home care, or for the adult children who care
for them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the ``k'' stand for in 401(k)? And in Y2K?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``k'' in 401(k) doesn't represent a word. A 401(k) is the
employer-sponsored retirement program allowed under Section 401(k)
of the Internal Revenue Code, which is written by Congress. The
code is broken up into sections, with 401 being Qualified Pension,
Profit Sharing and Stock Bonus Plans, said Anthony Burke of the
IRS. The section starts with 401(a); 401(k) is the section on cash
or deferred arrangements, he said. The ``k'' in parentheses simply
represents its order in the alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   In Y2K, the ``K'' represents kilo (thousand), as in kilometer
(1,000 meters) or kilogram (1,000 grams). So ``Y'' is Year, and
``2K'' is two thousand, designating the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I still have some Breast Cancer Awareness stamps, which are
undenominated. Must I add a 1-cent stamp when I use them to mail a
letter?
</P>
<P>
   A: These stamps are priced at 40 cents each. Before the Jan. 10
rate increase, when first-class letter postage was 32 cents, the
Postal Service allotted 8 cents of that amount to breast cancer
research. On Jan. 10, when the cost of first-class letter postage
rose to 33 cents, the amount for breast cancer research dropped to
7 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the tricky part. If you're using Breast Cancer Awareness
stamps purchased before Jan. 10, you're ``honor-bound'' to add a
1-cent stamp, said Don Smeraldi of the Postal Service in
Washington. But if you bought them after Jan. 10, he added, you
don't need to use the extra 1-cent stamp, because the portion going
to research has dropped by that same amount. So it's up to you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With Jordan's King Hussein in the news for his relapse of
cancer, I'm reminded of his wife, Queen Noor. Can you refresh my
memory about her? How many children do she and King Hussein have?
</P>
<P>
   A: Her Majesty Queen Noor was born Lisa Najeeb Halaby on Aug.
23, 1951, in Washington. She was the oldest of the three children
of Najeeb Halaby and Doris Carlquist. Her father, who was in the
Defense Department at the time of her birth, went on to become head
of the Federal Aviation Adminstration and chief exeutive officer of
Pan American World Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Before she married Hussein Ibn Talal (King Hussein), Lisa Halaby
attended schools in Los Angeles, Washington, D.C., New York and
Massachusetts before entering Princeton University in its first
coeducational class. After receiving a B.A. in architecture and
urban planning from Princeton in 1974, she participated in
international urban design projects in Australia, Iran, the United
States and Jordan. At one time she was director of planning and
design projects for Royal Jordanian Airline.
</P>
<P>
   Halaby married King Hussein on June 15, 1978, taking on the name
Noor al-Hussein (``Light of Hussein'' in Arabic). Several days
before the wedding, the nominal Protestant expressed her adherence
to Islam, which entailed her declaring before an Islamic court that
there is only one God, that God is Allah, and that the Messenger of
Allah is Muhammed the Prophet. She and her husband have four
children of their own: Prince Hamzah (born in 1980); Prince Hashim
(1981); Princess Iman (1983); and Princess Raiyah (1986). In
addition to the children of the late Queen Alia whom she has
adopted, Queen Noor is the stepmother of the five children from the
king's two other marriages.
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan, Queen Noor is active in a number of projects
concerning mother and child health care, education, women's
development, environmental protection, culture and public
architecture and planning. She also is involved in various
international projects, such as the agriculture-oriented Future
Harvest and the Landmine Survivors Network.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the law regarding the photographing of U.S. currency?
I'm trying to reproduce pictures of some bills for a brochure, but
my printer says it's against the law.
</P>
<P>
   A: Federal law sharply restricts photographs or other printed
reproduction of U.S. paper currency, as well as checks, bonds,
revenue stamps and securities of both U.S. and foreign governments.
It's done, obviously, to prevent counterfeiting. However, color
illustrations are permitted by the Counterfeit Detection Act of
1992 (Public Law 102-550, in Section 411 of Title 31 of the Code of
Federal Regulations), under these conditions: (1) the illustration
is either less than three-fourths, or more than 1 1/2 times, of the
bills' actual size; (2) the illustration is only one-sided; (3) and
all negatives, plates, postives, digitized storage medium or
anything else used in the illustration are destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Title 18, United States Code, Section 504, permits black and
white reproductions of currency and other obligations, so long as
the reproductions meet size requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that a huge chunk of ice, maybe 30 miles wide
and 90 miles long, had broken off Antarctica. What do scientists
say about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The world's largest reported iceberg in more than a decade
was documented Oct. 13 by National Ice Center scientist Mary
Keller. She observed in satellite imagery that a mass of ice about
the size you described had broken off the Ronne Ice Shelf in
Antarctica. Almost a year ago, it was widely reported that a
75-square-mile chunk of an ice shelf called Larsen B had crumbled
and dispersed into the sea along the Antarctic Peninsula. And there
have been other such incidents, such as in October 1987, when a
96-mile-long iceberg snapped off from the Ross Ice Shelf. The Ronne
and Larsen ice shelves both face the Weddell Sea, but aren't close
to each other. The Ross Ice Shelf is on the other side of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   While environmentalists and scientists point to such activity as
evidence of global warming, they say the near-term impact on sea
levels and climate conditions is uncertain. The Intergovernmental
Panel on Climate Change, the scientists responsible for predicting
likely effects of climate change, is on record as saying the
Antarctic will have a zero net contribution to sea-level rise in
the next century. Increased snowfall, they reason, will balance out
meltwater from retreating glaciers.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
