<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Feb. 3, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-TEACHERS (San Francisco) _ A critical shortage of
California teachers has led to the first statewide advertising
campaign to recruit a qualified crop. The need is enormous: from
260,000 to 300,000 new teachers will be needed during the next 10
years, according to various estimates. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   UAL-PARTNERS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
says he will continue flying United Airlines, when convenient,
unless the Board of Supervisors officially votes to boycott the air
carrier to protest the company's opposition to San Francisco's
domestic partners law. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS (San Francisco) _ Five civil rights groups
have filed a federal lawsuit alleging that UC-Berkeley's new
undergraduate admissions process illegally discriminates against
minority students. The suit contends that the process violates
civil rights laws and has unfairly denied entrance to more than 750
well-qualified African American, Filipino American and Latino
students. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS (Undated) _ The creators of the new ``Winds of Mars''
recording say the music, which overlays Bach piano pieces with
sounds collected by a spacecraft, is the ``world's first
all-digital, extraterrestrial music production.'' By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-CUPID (Undated) _ ABC lied. That shouldn't be a surprise to
any veteran TV-watcher. But the network really redefined the art
when it canceled ``Cupid'' after telling the nation's TV critics
that it liked the show quite a bit and was moving forward. By TIM
GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TEXAS-COAST (Rockport, Texas) _ We explore the lower Gulf
coast, from Rockport-Fulton to the Mexico border _ a region whose
people exhibit a love of nature, of good food and conversation and
a leisurely pace of life. By HARRY SHATTUCK. (Photos available on
the NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TEXAS-CORPUS (Corpus Christi, Texas) _ Easily the largest
city along the lower Texas coast, Corpus Christi maintains a
low-key ambience. Its heart is at the waterfront, where restaurants
tempt with the mouth-watering catch of the day and old-style
seafood shops market a bounty of riches. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Kingsville, Texas) _ The King Ranch, which is
spread over 825,000 acres and larger than the state of Rhode
Island, is renowned for developing two major breeds of cattle and
producing the first registered American quarter horse. It is now
becoming known as a haven for bird watchers. The 1,300-square-mile
ranch has more than 300 species of birds. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
