<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9846 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE     02-03 1777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: A crossword puzzle I was working on worded the answer as
``president who originally was named Leslie Lynch King Jr.'' It
turned out to be ``Ford.'' What were the circumstances leading to
Gerald R. Ford's name change?
</P>
<P>
   A: The only child of Leslie Lynch King, a western wool dealer,
and Dorothy Ayer Gardner King was born July 14, 1913, in Omaha,
Neb., and was named Leslie Lynch King Jr. About two years after his
birth, his parents were divorced and his mother moved with him to
Grand Rapids, Mich., where her parents lived. In 1916, she married
Gerald Rudolff Ford, a paint salesman, who soon afterward adopted
and renamed her son. The younger Ford later changed the spelling of
his middle name, preferring to use only its initial. He also chose
to spell his nickname Jerry rather than Gerry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I bought a Big Game Quik Pik ticket that had the number 21
twice. The numbers were 11-21-23-31-42 and then 21 again. Am I
correct in believing that it's impossible to win with the same
number twice? How common is it for this to happen?
</P>
<P>
   A: The second 21 was the Big Money Ball number, which is
separate _ and is drawn separately _ from the first five numbers.
The Big Money Ball is always the last number on the player's Big
Game play slip. It's very common, and perfectly all right, for the
Big Money Ball to be the same as one of the first five numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you confirm reports that White House attorney Cheryl
Mills, who defended President Clinton in the Senate impeachment
trial, is being investigated by the Justice Department on charges
of perjury and obstruction of justice?
</P>
<P>
   A: Last September, Rep. David McIntosh (R-Ind.) asked the
Justice Department whether Mills obstructed a congressional
investigation into the possible misuse of a taxpayer-financed White
House database. It was alleged that in 1996, Mills located two
subpoenaed documents suggesting that the president and Hillary
Rodham Clinton sanctioned the use of the White House database for
political purposes, such as soliciting donations, but withheld them
from a Republican-led subcommittee for months, until after the 1996
election. Mills also was accused of lying to the committee about
aspects of the database.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said she didn't believe the documents were responsive to
the subpoena when she first reviewed them, and sought the advice of
her superiors, who agreed. She denied any effort to mislead
investigators. A Democrat on the Government Reform Committee wrote
the Justice Department to say he disagreed with the Republican
referral, adding that Mills may have made a mistake, but there was
no evidence of willful obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   In its Feb. 1 issue, Time says McIntosh's request for an
investigation into the matter is still being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to the NBC program ``Trinity''? I enjoyed it,
but haven't heard anything about if for months.
</P>
<P>
   A: Production has been suspended and the program has been taken
off the air, said NBC publicist Joanna Giddon in New York. The
network has no plans to bring it back. The reason Giddon cited: too
few viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently told us about new commemorative coins. Can I buy
them directly from the U.S. Mint, rather than going to a dealer who
would charge more? Where can I get more information? Is there an
Internet site?
</P>
<P>
   A: Commemorative coins are available from the Mint only for a
limited time, although they may remain available from collectors
and coin dealers afterward. Mint spokesman Michael White says only
one commemorative, the Dolley Madison silver dollar, is currently
available for direct purchase from the Mint. As of Dec. 31, the
other most recent ones _ Robert F. Kennedy; Crispus Attucks Black
Revolutionary War Patriots; and National Law Enforcement Officers _
were discontinued for direct order. The Jackie Robinson gold $5 and
silver dollar, and the Franklin Delano Roosevelt gold $5, also were
closed out recently. Information: 1-800-872-6468 or 202-283-2646 On
the Internet: http://www.usmint.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain how football's ``sudden death'' works? In the
Falcons-Vikings game, for example, if Minnesota had scored in its
first possession in overtime, would the Falcons have gotten the
ball back? Or would that have been the end of the game?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, the game would have been over. ``Sudden death'' is an
extra 15-minute period of play to decide a game tied at the end of
regulation play in the NFL. The period begins with a kickoff
(decided by a coin toss) and ends when one team scores, or when
time runs out. If neither team is able to score in the overtime
period, 15-minute periods continue to be played, with two-minute
intermissions in between, until somebody scores. If the Vikings had
scored first in any manner, they would have won; but of course they
didn't. Morten Andersen sealed the Falcons' victory with his
history-making 38-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw where ``Dr. Laura,'' at a big party in Atlanta
recently, raised $60,000 for her foundation. What does the
foundation do?
</P>
<P>
   A: The stated purpose of the Dr. Laura Schlessinger Foundation
is ``to provide in-kind gifts and financial grants to charities
with a 501(c)3 tax-exempt status that meet the needs of families
and children.'' Its mission statement says special attention will
be given to those services that discourage abortion and teen
sexuality; promote adoption; prevent the abuse and neglect of
children; and provide support and encouragement to stay-at-home
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's board of advisers considers requests for
assistance three times a year. Such requests must be submitted in
writing to: The Dr. Laura Schlessinger Foundation, 6520 Platt Ave.,
816, West Hills, CA 91307. Groups or individuals requesting in-kind
or financial support should not expect to hear from the foundation
until the end of the quarter in which the submission is made.
Internet users can get online information at the Dr. Laura Website:
http://www.drlaura.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Before the 1996 Olympics, Atlanta organizers projected a huge
profit. Did it make as much as predicted? What was the final tally?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Atlanta Olympics broke even. Although the corporation is
not legally dissolved, and won't be until June, the books are
essentially closed. After bills were paid, less than $20 million
was left in the bank account of the Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games, and that sum is going to the U.S. Olympic Committee
to cover earlier debt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At the end of the Robin Williams movie ``Patch Adams,'' it's
stated that a hospital is either being planned , or has been built,
in West Virginia with a thousand doctors waiting to volunteer to be
on the staff. Where in West Virginia will it be? Where can we send
donations?
</P>
<P>
   A: The would-be hospital is so far only a group of buildings,
some half-finished, on 310 acres of West Virginia's Droop Mountain.
The real-life Dr. Hunter D. ``Patch'' Adams (portrayed in the film
by Williams) founded the Gesundheit! Institute, a health care
reform movement, more than 20 years ago. The film depicts Adams as
a maverick medical student who espouses the healing power of humor
and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   There's some controversy about the institute's funding. Adams
has been raising money for it since the early '70s. Published
accounts have put the total raised so far at $1.1 million. Adams
hopes for $25 million more to complete the project, but some people
question where the money is going, and whether the movie dream will
ever become reality. One recent article reported that there are no
patients, just two staffers who answer an endless stream of calls
and letters from people suddenly enchanted with the concept of free
health care from seeing the movie. Although the institute has its
detractors, the real-life Adams insists that $25 million from now,
a hospital will stand.
</P>
<P>
   Donations can be sent to Gesundheit! Institute, P.O. Box 268,
Hillsboro, WV 24946, or for credit-card donations by calling the
toll-free number 1-877-745-5937. General information also is
available at the toll-free number or at 304-653-4338, or online at
the institute's Website: http://www.patchadams.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), one of the House managers in the
impeachment trial who seems to be consumed by hatred for President
Clinton, ever serve in the armed forces?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about presidential pardons. What kind of crimes
may be pardoned? How does one apply for a pardon? How long does the
process take? If one actually gets a presidential pardon, does it
completely clear the crime from one's record, or is it just a
symbolic gesture?
</P>
<P>
   A: The president's pardon power extends only to ``offenses
against the United States,'' said Chris Watney of the Justice
Department. This means violations of federal law (including
military offenses), but it doesn't include state offenses, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   To apply for a presidential pardon, the applicant must file a
formal petition with the Office of the Pardon Attorney, the Justice
Department office responsible for processing pardon petitions on
behalf of the president. There's a minimum five-year waiting
period, which runs from the date of release from incarceration, or
from the date of conviction if no period of incarceration was
served, Watney said. The amount of time necessary to process a
pardon petition varies from case to case, but the process can be
lengthy and generally takes upward of a year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pardon does not erase or expunge the judicial record of a
conviction, but it will remove certain disabilities imposed by
reason of the conviction for which the pardon is granted,'' Watney
added, ``and it can be helpful in obtaining licenses and other
occupational certificates. It also is a sign of forgiveness and
therefore serves to lessen the stigma associated with the
conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Photos of Chief Justice William Rehnquist show stripes on the
sleeves of his robe. What's the significance?
</P>
<P>
   A: As reported previously, Rehnquist is the first modern-day
Supreme Court member to depart from tradition and wear something
other than a plain black robe. His bold, gold, naval-style fashion
statement dates to 1995, when he appeared at the State of the Union
address displaying four gold stripes on each sleeve. The inch-wide
horizontal stripes were inspired, it was explained, by Rehnquist's
having seen the Gilbert and Sullivan comic opera ``Iolanthe'' the
previous summer. In the operetta, the Lord Chancellor wore gold
stripes on his sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
