<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Switch to digital means more choices for cable customers
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: Texas Editors. Three boxes at bottom of story.)
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Too lazy to go to the gym? How about flipping on
the TV and following along with a full-body workout by Jake?
</P>
<P>
   Want to win a few thousand bucks on a game show without standing
in line in Hollywood to do it?
</P>
<P>
   Couch potatoes can do those things in some parts of the country,
but not in Austin. Not yet anyway. In some cities, cable companies
offer channels with first-run British variety shows, wall-to-wall
American game shows and enough aerobic workouts and weightlifting
sessions to last a healthy lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The world of cable television is a world of choice, and as we
enter the digital age, viewers will have even more choices. The
audience decides which of the dozens of channels to watch, but the
cable providers decide which channels to offer them.
</P>
<P>
   Central Texans have a plethora of cable networks available on
Time Warner Cable, the chief provider of cable service. We can
watch news all day and all night. We can watch everything from
wrestling to independent films to museum tours to cartoons to
cooking shows. And lots more.
</P>
<P>
   So who decides which cable channels we get, and how are those
decisions made?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this business a long time, 25 years, and I've
adopted a very conservative approach to adding channels,'' said
Bill Carey, president of Time Warner. He calls the shots in Austin.
``We have a maximum capacity of 79 channels in our expanded areas,
and that makes selecting channels a challenge. It's especially hard
here because we have more access channels than any other system I'm
aware of.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Austin has nine public access channels, and the cable
company's charter with the city allows for the possibility of five
more. The cable company also must carry all local stations, and
Austin has eight. The must-carry channels take a chunk out of the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last couple of years, Time Warner has expanded its
channel capacity through a fiber-optic upgrade and added several
new cable networks, including Animal Planet, History Channel, Golf
Channel, Home &AMP; Garden, Food Network, Travel Channel, TV Land and
the Independent Film Channel. There are currently 50 cable
networks, 10 pay-per-view movie channels and premium channels (such
as HBO and Showtime) and two preview channels.
</P>
<P>
   Carey says Time Warner's surveys in Central Texas show that
viewers here are especially fond of live programming, such as news
and sports events; movies; children's programming; and arts and
science programming.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner is testing digital service in Austin and plans to
offer the new tier of service by the end of the year. The digital
service could increase options by 50 new video channels and as many
as 30 new audio channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot out there, but a lot of them are concepts on a
drawing board,'' Carey said. ``It takes awhile for a channel to
establish itself nationally and reach critical mass.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey makes the final decisions on what to carry and what not to
carry, and he makes those decisions based on surveys of people who
already have the new networks in other Time Warner cities. Central
Texas customers are surveyed every year, too, to find out the
relative mix of programming people want. But to decide what new
services to add, the company goes outside our area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surveying customers who don't have a service can be very
unreliable,'' Carey said. ``Asking their opinions based on a
description of something they haven't seen can lead to skewed
survey results. And a description of a service doesn't take into
account the execution of the programmer. What I've learned from
experience is you have to go to customers who have used the
service, the longer the better, and ask them to rate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say Austin area customers don't have plenty of
opinions. When ads ran on cable channels touting the debut of the
new nature network Animal Planet, which Time Warner wasn't carrying
at the time, hundreds of people called the company's customer
service lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took that into account,'' Carey said. ``We knew there would
be great demand for Animal Planet, and we also knew from surveys of
people who already had it that the service was very popular and
delivered on its promise. That one was a no-brainer. ... We do get
feedback and requests, and sometimes those are the most intensely
interested viewers. The Golf Channel is a good example of that. It
has a fairly narrow focus, but you're considered out of touch these
days if you don't have the Golf Channel.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Time Warner took the entertainment news channel E! off
temporarily during its upgrade construction, customers flooded the
office with phone calls, prompting the company to send out a
reminder that the channel would return soon.
</P>
<P>
   Taking off any channel is risky business. Several years ago, the
cable company stirred up a ruckus when it took off the religious
channels Trinity Broadcasting and Odyssey. The channels eventually
were brought back. And when C-SPAN2 was taken off, angry viewers
once again complained, resulting in the return of the channel in a
shared capacity with Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every service has some viewership,'' said Sharon Radziewski,
spokeswoman for the National Cable Television Association in
Washington, D.C. ``That's what people love about cable _ all the
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey says Time Warner hasn't had to take any channels off
permanently during his 4 1/2-year tenure because the channels added
have been part of the company's expansion. Right now Carey is
trying to decide what to add to the new digital tier, which will
add about $10 to customers' cable bills. The latest edition of the
National Cable Television Association's channel directory lists 170
cable networks in operation and dozens more in development, so
there's a lot to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of channels will be allocated to pay-per-view,
and we'll add more multiplex channels'' like HBO's three-channel
service, Carey said. ``Our digital service will evolve over time.
Since we're going to be one of the very first digital systems in
the nation, we don't have the luxury of seeing what will work
elsewhere. We'll take a conservative approach, because we want to
make sure we don't add services with little appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: dholloway(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   CABLE BOXES
</P>
<P>
   Cable networks out there
</P>
<P>
   _ America's Health Network: With support from the Mayo Clinic,
the channel has ask-the-doctor segments, health news and features.
</P>
<P>
   _ BBC America: The best of British TV, including dramas,
comedies, world news and top documentaries. Not the same as the BBC
stuff that airs on PBS and A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   _ c/net: An on-air and online source for news, info and
resources related to computers and digital technologies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fit TV: A health and fitness network with aerobic conditioning
segments, full-body workouts by Jake and product sales segments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Game Show Network: New interactive game shows with prizes and
reruns of old game shows just for fun.
</P>
<P>
   _ Knowledge TV: Informational programming about finance,
business, personal computers, culture and health.
</P>
<P>
   _ Locomotion Channel: Animation from all over the world for
teens and young adults.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ovation: From B.B. King to Bach, Pavarotti to pop art, Alvin
Ailey to architecture, programming includes arts news and programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outdoor Life Network: Programming for outdoors folks includes
shows on hunting, fishing, camping and hiking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speedvision: Programs for car, boat and plane enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sundance: A showcase for new independent films.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toon Disney: Cartoons, movies and specials for kids and
families from the Disney archives.
</P>
<P>
   Most-watched cable networks nationwide:
</P>
<P>
   TBS
</P>
<P>
   USA Network
</P>
<P>
   Cartoon Network
</P>
<P>
   TNT
</P>
<P>
   ESPN
</P>
<P>
   CNN
</P>
<P>
   CNBC
</P>
<P>
   Sci-Fi Channel
</P>
<P>
   Country Music Television
</P>
<P>
   ESPN2
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Cable Television Association; fall '98 ratings
</P>
<P>
   New networks on the horizon:
</P>
<P>
   _ Anti-Aging Network: (no launch date set) Features health tips,
rejuvenation therapies, makeover segments and a celebrity corner.
</P>
<P>
   _ CHOP TV: (no launch date set) Programming on the martial arts
and related fields of fitness, health and mental well-being
presented in magazine-style format.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fox Boyz and Fox Girlz : (launches '99) Gender-segregated
programming for boys and girls.
</P>
<P>
   _ Noggin: (Feb. 1) Educational children's programming, a joint
effort of the Nickelodeon and the Children's Television Workshop,
which produces ``Sesame Street.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Oxygen: (launches late '99) Programming for ``modern women.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Theater Channel: (launches late '99) Theatrical productions
from the United States and around the world will include
mainstream, alternative/avant-garde and children's theater, plus
live backstage interviews, theater reviews, workshops and
festivals.
</P>
