</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIPHOP-COMEBACK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death-defying hip-hop boom survives, thrives
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Tupac Shakur and Notorious B.I.G. were
murdered within months of each other two years ago, many people
predicted the iconoclastic gangsta rappers would take the
popularity of hip-hop music with them to the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and call it a comeback, then, that hip-hop music
dominated the Billboard charts during this past holiday season and
continues to weigh in as the most popular music of the day. Last
week, five of the 10 best-selling albums in the country were
rap-oriented, including the new No. 1 album by New Orleans rapper
Silkk the Shocker and the Grammy-ready solo debut by Fugees singer
Lauryn Hill (No. 5)
</P>
<P>
   What's most surprising about this boom is that even the
stereotypically rap-less Austin is feeling its ripples. Record
store workers have seen hip-hop albums fly off the shelves, while
radio listeners are hearing it more and more on the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   A new radio station called ``The Beat'' (KQBT, 104.3 FM) emerged
last fall as the first semi-consistent hip-hop stop on the local FM
dial. According to Arbitron ratings released last week The Beat,
which also plays R&AMP;B music, is already the No. 3 station in town.
Its competitor, KHFI-FM, has also started playing more hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was definitely a void in Austin that had to be filled,''
said Beat program director Scooter Stevens, who estimated that a
little less than 50 percent of his station's songs are hip-hop.
``Clearly, we play enough to have benefited from it.''
</P>
<P>
   While increased radio play undoubtedly has helped raise the
profile of hip-hop music in Austin, the question of where the
genre's most recent boom originated is really a chicken-or-egg
issue. MTV, for instance, airs more music videos by hip-hop artists
than ever before. But that may be because record companies are most
willing to spend money on promoting and making videos for hip-hop
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Two things are certain about the current hip-hop boom: Rap acts
have wildly overshadowed and outsold rock acts lately, to the point
where many music-industry insiders are again raising the ``rock is
dead'' mantra. And regardless of whether rock is dying, hip-hop
continues to grow in the creativity department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of really good rappers out there right now,''
is how 19-year-old Kenny Wilson, a hip-hop fan shopping at the Best
Buy store in South Austin, explained the craze. ``It seems like
there's always something new worth getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McCorkle, assistant manager at the hip-hop-geared record
store Musicmania, 3909-D N. Interstate 35, described hip-hop fans
as ``the most loyal CD buyers out there.'' The store held a
midnight sale to promote the release of the Silkk the Shocker album
two weeks ago, and within a couple of days all 300 copies of the
disc were sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of hip-hop is well-marketed these days, and that
might have something to do with the artists doing it themselves,''
McCorkle said, pointing to Silkk the Shocker. His ``Made Mann'' CD
was released and promoted by his brother, rapper Master P and P's
company, No Limit Records. Another album in the Billboard Top 10,
DMX's ``Flesh of My Flesh, Blood of My Blood,'' benefited from
similar, incestuous promotion: DMX has done duets with and
otherwise been connected with popular rappers such as Mase and the
Lox.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop's marketing has changed, clearly, but so has its sound.
Gangsta rap is out, for the most part. What's in, as the Hill and
Jay-Z will attest, is the trend of combining rap with singing, so
that the street-level rhymes of rap are featured alongside age-old
soul and R&AMP;B harmonies. Many other artists have followed a less
appealing trend _ started by Puff Daddy and Wyclef Jean _ of
sampling old songs by purely Anglophile acts such as the Police,
Bruce Hornsby and even the Bee Gees.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop still isn't perfect, and one of the arenas it may have
to improve on the most to stay at the top is in live performance.
That's especially true in live-music-happy Austin, which sees only
a handful of touring hip-hop shows each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There still isn't really any trust,'' said Pace Concerts
promoter Brad Roosa, who books shows at the Austin Music Hall and
the Backyard. ``The promoters don't trust the performers, and vice
versa. More important, the fans don't trust either of them because
shows often get canceled or the acts simply let them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Roosa said, Austin should get more hip-hop concerts
in upcoming years, just as more hip-hop music is being played and
sold here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beat could definitely help because radio play is
essential,'' he said. ``But I think people were ready for the
floodgates to open anyway. It's been a long time coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Riemenschneider writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
