<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAE-BO04-COX     02-03 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAE-BO04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My day with the Tae-Bo master: I'd rather just have a pizza
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ Billy Blanks wants my ``will.'' And I'm
thinking I should've written one before coming here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want your will, I want your will!'' he barks into my ear as
I gasp like a guppy on hot pavement. ``I want your WILL!''
</P>
<P>
   I want my mommy.
</P>
<P>
   Blanks, 6 feet of glistening granite in size-13 Reeboks, is the
creator of Tae-Bo (rhymes with ``my woe''), a hybrid of aerobics,
boxing and martial arts that has Hollywood gushing and housewives
doing lunges in the living room. His infomercials have sold a
million video sets since August, and his L.A. gym has celebs lining
up (``they have to wait like everyone else,'' says Blanks' manager,
Jeff Greenfield).
</P>
<P>
   Today, Blanks _ who's in South Florida for the Super Bowl _ is
leading a session on the basketball court at the Eden Roc Resort &AMP;
Spa. This, my friends, is the county seat of the Land of the
Beautiful People. Fake breasts, fake nails, fake hair, perhaps, but
you can't fake being in shape. Really good shape.
</P>
<P>
   These folks are, and I'm not. It's like Baywatch here, what with
all the chiseled physiques. And I wandered in from The Drew Carey
Show.
</P>
<P>
   There's 40 minutes of Tae-Bo to go, and Blanks isn't cutting any
slack. When a gal on the front row (a skinny gal! ha!) saunters off
and sits down, he escorts her back to class.
</P>
<P>
   Blanks, mind you, isn't a militant motivator a la Susan Powter.
He's more like a concerned parent who won't let you quit no matter
how hard you beg.
</P>
<P>
   He's Cliff Huxtable with a beefcake bod and a headset
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   The session begins with a deceptively gentle warmup _ easing our
heads from side to side, walking in place, squatting, then standing
up straight. But next comes gravity defiance. Knee in the air,
kicking out to each side, thighs wailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put most of your weight on your butt,'' he instructs.
</P>
<P>
   Can't you see that it's already THERE?
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing about working out is you've got to
have a purpose. You've got to focus on every move.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Erie, Pa., Blanks' purpose became karate, which he
took up to imitate his idol, martial arts legend Bruce Lee. The
fifth of 15 kids (10 boys, five girls), Blanks was a shy, clumsy
youngster who suffered from dyslexia, which wasn't diagnosed until
35.
</P>
<P>
   His dad was a foundry worker, his mom, a homemaker. The family
lived in a ghetto, and young Blanks toiled as a garbage man to pay
for karate lessons.
</P>
<P>
   His parents were both Christians, he says before class. ``They
taught me that no matter what I do, God comes first. They taught me
how to share and love.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 20, Blanks was wed to high school sweetheart
Gayle Godfrey, who had a 2-year-old daughter, Shellie, from a
previous relationship (Shellie, now 25, works as a trainer at
Blanks' gym). ``We'd only gone out for a year, so we didn't really
know each other,'' he says. ``We married out of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the couple had a son, Billy Jr. (now 22, who also works
with Dad), and four years later, Blanks was named captain of the
U.S. Olympic karate team.
</P>
<P>
   The team didn't compete, though, because the States boycotted
the Summer Games in Moscow. But Blanks, now 43, went on to rack up
seven world karate titles, including 36 gold medals in
international bouts.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Olympians today in the Eden Roc gym, just folks
leaping about in reflecting pools of their own sweat. I, meanwhile,
am using my notepad as a crutch. When my lungs feel like they're
going to burst through my heaving body like that gooey creature in
Alien, I reach for my pen to jot ``reporter thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I'm writing letters to family. Grocery lists. War &AMP;
Peace, Part II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just doin' my job!'' I holler to Blanks, who, wise to my scam,
delivers The Eye. Ashamed, I rejoin the jab sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Twist at the waist, punch left, punch left. Twist at the waist,
punch right, punch right. Blanks is big on technique _ no
limp-armed air slaps like tussling schoolgirls on a playground.
He'll pluck you from the crowd and correct you on your form.
</P>
<P>
   Kindly, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Tae-Bo's like boxing, but there are no gloves. It's also like
karate, but there are no opponents (unless you mistakenly TKO the
poor schmuck next to you).
</P>
<P>
   Slip in some hip-hop tunes, and behold! Your class roster
includes Pamela Anderson, Paula Abdul, Brooke Shields and Neve
Campbell. Even the prince of the puck, Wayne Gretzky, and hoopster
Shaquille O'Neal. And, oh, don't forget Queen Latifah, Ashley Judd
and comic Sinbad.
</P>
<P>
   Blanks, however, isn't one to drop names. He'd rather we drop
our elbows to our waists during the uppercut punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your waist,'' he yells, ``is your shock absorber.''
</P>
<P>
   My waist, kind sir, is my chocolate absorber.
</P>
<P>
   A TV cameraman trails Blanks as he weaves through the gym, and
he wheels around, gets inches from the lens and bellows, ``You GOT
it, brother, right HERE!!''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of class, though, Blanks is low-key, exhibiting the
quiet confidence of someone who gets up at 5 each morning to do 40
minutes on the Lifecycle, 20 minutes on a rowing machine, 1,000
sit-ups and then some.
</P>
<P>
   His fitness level, though, isn't the only thing that makes him
proud. So does his gold wedding band and his silver WWJD? bracelet,
which stands for What Would Jesus Do?
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Blanks left Pennsylvania _ where he worked at a
chemical plant _ for Boston. He continued training, taught karate
and toyed with boxing. Just four years later, he won a
Massachusetts Golden Gloves title in the light heavyweight class.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Blanks split for L.A., where he first worked as a
bodyguard for Catherine ``Daisy Duke'' Bach. (``She liked to
flirt,'' he recalls, smiling. ``I often had to step in. The job was
awesome.'')
</P>
<P>
   While watching over Bach on location in the Philippines, Blanks
was cast in his first flick, Bloodfist, already in production
there. In 1990 he played a crazed, gun-toting football player in
The Last Boy Scout, then moved on to a string of B-list martial
arts films (i.e., Expect No Mercy, Tough and Deadly, Balance of
Power).
</P>
<P>
   TV credits, meanwhile, include the starring role on Soldier of
Fortune and guest spots on Street Justice and Spenser For Hire. At
the same time, Blanks was refining Tae-Bo, which stands for Total
Awareness, Excellence, Body Obedience. Also, Tae is the Korean word
for leg, and bo is short for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Blanks was technical director for a kick-boxing scene
in Ally McBeal. (Ally, by the way, sports a size 2. I, you should
know, do not.) Time for true grit, literally
</P>
<P>
   Blanks had warned me that anybody could survive the first half
of class, but the second required clenched-teethed tenacity. By
now, even Eden Roc's supremely fit spa director and aerobics
coordinator are endangering their dental work.
</P>
<P>
   We're down on all fours, ``leg up so the thigh and knee are
parallel to the ground like your foot's holding a cup of coffee.''
Kick out. Again, again, again. Kick out. Again, again, again.
</P>
<P>
   I joke that the blue plastic wristbands we received upon arrival
(to verify a $45 payment for the session) look like hospital issue.
``Will make it (pant) easier (pant) when the ambulance arrives.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Blanks begins our cooldown and has us ``sway as if we're being
blown by a gentle breeze.'' He doesn't add ``after being gutted by
gale-force winds.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being hooked up in Hollywood, Blanks is a man of simple
bliss. No Ferrari in the garage, just a Ford F150 pickup. No
leftover caviar for breakfast, just an O Henry bar and a Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people sacrifice to lose weight,'' he says as water
bottle-clutching refugees stagger to the door. ``That's not what
it's about. It's about doing what's good for you. If you ask, God
will give you the will and endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll settle for a pizza and an ice pack.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
