<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweating for the Girl Scout sweets
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You made your regular new year's resolution to
watch those calories, and now you're downing Girl Scout cookies by
the fistful. But don't feel guilty. Work it off. And if you're
wondering how much work you need to do, just consult our helpful
guide:
</P>
<P>
   Caramel deLites
</P>
<P>
   140 calories per serving (2 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   15 minutes of basketball
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Butter Patties
</P>
<P>
   150 calories per serving (2 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   30 minutes of walking at the rate of a 20-minute mile
</P>
<P>
   Reduced Fat Lemon Pastry Cremes
</P>
<P>
   130 calories per serving
</P>
<P>
   (3 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   10 minutes of boxing
</P>
<P>
   Shortbread
</P>
<P>
   130 calories per serving
</P>
<P>
   (4 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   10 minutes of running at the rate of
</P>
<P>
   an 8-minute mile
</P>
<P>
   Thin Mints
</P>
<P>
   160 calories per serving
</P>
<P>
   (4 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   30 minutes of walking at the rate of 16-minute mile
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Butter Sandwich
</P>
<P>
   180 calories per serving
</P>
<P>
   (3 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   15 minutes of swimming the crawl-stroke fast
</P>
<P>
   Five World Cinnamons
</P>
<P>
   150 calories per serving (5 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   45 minutes of ballroom dancing
</P>
<P>
   Upside-Downs Frosted Oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   170 calories per serving
</P>
<P>
   (3 cookies)
</P>
<P>
   30 minutes of golf
</P>
<P>
   Source:
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Brown, a personal trainer at Body Business in Austin,
Texas, helped compute what it would take to work off one serving of
each of the Girl Scout cookies. The workout is based on the
American Council on Exercise's Personal Trainer Manual, using a
person weighing 150 pounds who is in average physical shape.
</P>
