<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBS-BLACKARTS04-COX     02-03 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS-BLACKARTS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBS chronicles 100 years of black arts
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Who produced the musical ``In Dahomey'' that
opened on Broadway in 1903? What became of sculptor Augusta
Savage's commissioned piece ``The Harp''?
</P>
<P>
   What question destroyed ballet dancer Raven Wilkerson's career
in America?
</P>
<P>
   Why did poet Gwendolyn Brooks stop using rhyme after 1967?
</P>
<P>
   These questions are answered during the six-hour PBS series
``I'll Make Me a World: A Century of African-American Arts'' that
captures the stories behind African Americans' artistic legacy in
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The series pays tribute to the legends, such as actor Paul
Robeson, writer Zora Neale Hurston and musician Dizzy Gillespie,
while telling what happened to those who may not be as well-known,
such as Wilkerson and Savage, whose career triumphs and tragedies
illustrate the bittersweetness of being an African American artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is particularly impressive is the variety of artists,''
Joni Jones, an Austin performance artist and an associate professor
at the University of Texas, said during a preview screening of the
series. ``They are not showing one art form; they are sharing the
complexity of the arts and the artists. That is a real strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hampton, who created and produced the three-night series,
died in November from bone marrow disease. He was the producer of
the Emmy-winning series ``Eyes on the Prize,'' which told the
stories of the not-so-famous names in the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton and his production team at Blackside Inc. organized
``I'll Make Me a World'' in hourlong segments against the backdrop
of American history, starting at the turn of the century with
vaudeville stars Bert Williams and George Walker. Instead of
relying only on old photographs and crude film footage, the lives
of these groundbreaking actors are movingly told through a
contemporary stage play. Actor Ben Vereen gives a wrenching
portrayal of Williams, who reveals the pain and humiliation of
racism and segregation experienced by the black performers of his
era. He tells his story while slowly removing the blackface makeup
he must wear if he wants to work.
</P>
<P>
   The next segment traces the rise of jazz and blues music and the
Harlem Renaissance, which was heavily financed by white patrons who
were fascinated with ``Negro'' entertainment. The literary giants,
such as Langston Hughes and Hurston, are given their due, but the
cultural critics offer perspective on the conflict that arose over
what African American art should do.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a progressive black person at the beginning of the
century was to consider the meaning of your success and its impact
on race,'' said Edmund Barry Gaiter, a museum director who talks on
the issue. ``Many people took the posture that our job was to lift
the race, to defend the race, to put forward the best view of it
and to make our lives the wedges that would open a larger space for
those who came behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second installment, the series examines African American
artists and their work at midcentury. It was a time when several
artists were breaking racial barriers in dance, acting and music.
Some moved to Europe, particularly to France, so they could have
the freedom to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes as a great shock to discover the country which is
your birthplace and to which you owe your life and your dignity has
not, in its whole system of reality, evolved any place for you,''
said writer James Baldwin, explaining why he moved to France in the
footsteps of writer Richard Wright and performer Josephine Baker.
</P>
<P>
   The midcentury is when Wilkerson and Savage built their careers.
The light-skinned dancer quietly joined a white ballet company
while Savage built a community-based art school that influenced
artists such as painters Jacob Lawrence and Gwendolyn Knight.
</P>
<P>
   The most vivid part of the series is its final two hours, which
examines the rise of the Black Arts Movement, the Motown sound and
the artistic forms _ spoken-word art and hip-hop music _ that
dominate today's post-Black Arts era.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to be told about the charismatic power of
poet-playwright Amiri Baraka, and it's another to see it for
yourself in film footage. The series shows Baraka reading a poem at
the Congress of African Peoples in Atlanta in 1970 and you
understand why a crowd went wild when he walked in during Gwendolyn
Brooks' poetry readings at Fisk University.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks explains that the young poets who gathered at home for
salon-style readings, such as Sonia Sanchez, Nikki Giovanni and
Haki Madhubuti, so changed her views on her work that she changed
publishing houses and even stopped straightening her hair. ``I
wanted to be natural,'' said Brooks. ``I love that word _
natural.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most dramatic events occurred among artists and museums,
particularly in New York. In 1968, the Whitney Museum of Art opened
an exhibit entitled ``The 1930s: Painting and Sculpture in
America.'' No African American artist's work was represented. Black
artists protested by picketing the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later painter Romare Bearden had a solo exhibit at
the Museum of Modern Art and playwright August Wilson saw it: ``It
was one of the very few times that I could see black life presented
in all this richness and fullness, and yet not be sentimental. And
I think this is one of the things that I valued and appreciated
most was the lack of sentimentality and this bold and affirmative
grace.''
</P>
<P>
   African American artists continued to move their work beyond the
expected in the 1980s and the 1990s. The series shows how visual
artist Kara Walker and dancer-choreographer Bill T. Jones
re-examine stereotypes in their art forms.
</P>
<P>
   Jones says he changed his perspective on his art after the death
of his partner from AIDS: ``Don't wait around to talk about the
stuff that's really big for you. And you have no reason to be
afraid of anything, since you may die. And you have as much freedom
as you will take.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kellie Jones, a curator and cultural critic says: ``There has
been the `Cosby Show' on television. Spike Lee has been making
movies for 10 years, so that's all in place. People can see these
images, so there's no need to always have this positivity and very
serious, somber images as the `real' us. There is freedom to poke
holes in these kind of stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   Norma Martin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
