<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BUCHMAN04-COX     02-03 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BUCHMAN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fashion: Buchman designs for daily grind, not Oscar glory
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Dana Buchman is her own best model.
</P>
<P>
   She slips easily between two mannequins at Bloomingdale's,
smiles calmly for a photo, then walks, impeccably postured, through
the maze that will be her $35-a-seat luncheon and fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   Tables of well-groomed ladies, waiting to dip into their Asian
pasta salad with soy vinaigrette, look at her approvingly as she
steps forward to deliver the pre-show remarks _ which, of course,
are off-the-cuff and warm.
</P>
<P>
   The nearby racks of her new spring designs are heavy in peach
and coral, but she wears winter's gray, light-wool pantsuit. She
designed that, also. Go ahead, feel it. She leans forward and
offers a sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   She even wins over the caterer, Jack Merklien, who stands
off-stage in shorts and a gray T-shirt, clutching an empty tray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen some designers, their clothes are too outlandish,''
he says. ``But her, each piece is so simple and plain.'' (After
catering a similar event a year ago, he says, he went home to Coral
Springs with two of Buchman's suits for his wife.)
</P>
<P>
   Buchman, a Tennessee native, doesn't quite design in the fast
lane. During Fashion Week this month in New York, she will present
her collection in her showroom instead of on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   And she doesn't bother with the wear-my-dress-for-the-Oscars
pleading with celebrities. ``I'm not into that kind of promotion,''
she says. (Her Luxe line, however, does include gowns.)
</P>
<P>
   Buchman caters to women like her, the 35-and-older crowd, the
kind now waiting for her fashion show and pecking at their salads.
(If she doesn't find time for lunch, she'll snack on the bag of
salted peanuts in her purse.)
</P>
<P>
   Ever helpful, she includes terms _ Tones of Twilight, Graphic
Seductions _ on her price tags to help shoppers know what can mix
and match.
</P>
<P>
   Buchman's fans have enough money to shop on Worth Avenue in Palm
Beach, where she just opened her latest boutique. But they're not
above seeking out the sales rack, which for Buchman's visit has
been shrunk to a row of animal-print blouses ($59.99) and stuck
behind a pillar.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, her new spring jackets run in the mid-$300s, and
one silk scarf is $98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know in Florida, spring doesn't really leave,'' Buchman
says. ``But it's so exciting when the first wave of the season
arrives _ it makes my heart pound.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't stay in town long _ just enough for the luncheon, a
stroll through Mizner Park (scouting a future boutique?) and a
visit with a local uncle.
</P>
<P>
   She came down with a single small bag. ``I travel with as little
as possible,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't pare down enough. ``The perfect way would have
been to wear these pants with a sweater set yesterday and this
jacket today,'' she muses. ``Then I wouldn't even have the hanging
bag...'
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
