<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good Stuff in Food
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Consumer Reports taste-tested typical frozen meals, the
magazine found most ``mediocre at best.'' It sampled lasagna,
chicken, Salisbury steak and fish meals. Top ratings in all
categories went to Marie Callender's and Stouffer's. The ``not so
hot'' category was filled with familiar names such as Healthy
Choice, Weight Watchers, Banquet, Lean Cuisine, Swanson and
Gorton's. The magazine's final conclusion: `` Stick with chicken or
lasagna. Think twice before grabbing frozen Salisbury steak. Just
say no to frozen fish.''
</P>
<P>
   ONE GOOD ALTERNATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Yes, cheese has lots of fat _ 9 grams in a 1-ounce cube. But
low-fat, no-fat cheeses simply have no taste. And, experts say, no
satiety. That means you're not satisfied and eat more and more. The
calories add up even if the fat doesn't. A better choice is to buy
the real thing and eat just a small amount. Pay attention to what
you're eating and savor it instead of tossing cheese cubes down by
the handful.
</P>
<P>
   A real corker of a keepsake
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's got a millennium gimmick and Dom Perignon is not
going to settle for champagne sales. The company is marketing a
cork-shaped silver box called the Keepsake Cork. Engraved with the
upcoming New Year's Eve date, it's a hinged box designed to hold
the cork you pop that night. The price is $65, plus shipping and
handling: call (800) 421-9705. Or wait until March when the silver
box and a bottle of the sought-after 1990 Dom will be packaged for
sale. Price: $200.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
