<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mr. Sports will answer all who seek his knowledge
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Mr. Sports sees all, knows all, tells all.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sports is responsible for low interest rates, the budget
surplus and the painting of the Sistine Chapel. In a fair fight,
Mr. Sports would take out Stone Cold Steve Austin in less than five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But then you knew all that. Now let Mr. Sports do his job:
Answer mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Sports: Should I go or should I stay? _ J.E.,
Denver''
</P>
<P>
   Dear John: You saw how Michael Jordan did it. He went out on top
as fans and the media threw rose petals in his path. You could do
it that way, or you could gamble on going out like Y.A. Tittle with
blood streaming down your forehead. For a good part of last season
you couldn't roll right without pulling a groin muscle. That was
your body telling you it was time. Now let your head catch up with
your body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Sports: Should I go or should I stay? _ B.E.,
Cincinnati''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Boomer: You can't be serious. You're on the ice cream
truck, man. You do one football game a week, you never get hit and
you're paid like a neurosurgeon. If you've forgotten what Monday
morning feels like after an NFL game, c'mon back. But do yourself a
favor and don't get stuck with a lousy team that can't protect you.
Hint, hint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Sports: Michael's on the golf course. Scottie's in
Houston. As usual, I don't care 'bout nuthin'. Should I go or
should I stay? _ D.R., Parts Unknown''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dennis: Give up hoops and settle down with Carmen. I see
the two of you as the new Arthur and Guinevere in Camelot. And, oh,
one other thing, Denny. Always wear pearls with your black dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Sports: Ohio State didn't want me even though I was
only tackled like maybe eight times all season. What a bummer. _
R.B., Troy''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ryan: It's hard to argue with OSU's recruiters. They are
kings of the meat market. Plus they've got 'em lined up at tailback
into the next century, so your chances there would have been
limited. I think they did you a favor. Go to South Carolina and
thrive. As Fish says on Ally McBeal: ``Bygones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Sports: I did a bad. What's my next move? _ E.R.,
Atlanta''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Eugene: Get a good lawyer and have him claim you were doing
research for your next speech. It works every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Sports: I waited forever, and finally I got a chance.
It ain't working. Any advice? _ B.G., Chapel Hill, N.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Bill: I've got more advice than Judge Judy. But you, sir,
are trapped. I can think of no man who replaced a legend and
survived. All I can think of are Gary Cunningham, Phil Bengtson,
Earle Bruce, Joe B. Hall, Frank Leahy, Ray Perkins and a dozen
others. My advice: Keep your suitcase packed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Sports: I finally did it. I got rid of Reggie
Sanders. What's your take? _ J.B., Cincinnati''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Jim: You're as predictable as Ken Starr at the barbershop.
You've rented another power guy for a year. Sometimes it's worked
(Ron Gant), sometimes it hasn't (Kevin Mitchell). Bottom line:
You'd be a credit to any Rotisserie League that would have you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Sports: Hey, have you noticed? We're doing some
damage up here. We're cookin'. _ S.P., Columbus''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Scoonie: It's nice that you guys are 16-6, but you know
what's nicer? That you haven't busted into anybody's car, shot out
any tires, punched out your girlfriends or any of that other fun
stuff your predecessors did. The punks are gone. Hallelujah.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
