<HEADER>
A9861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-BOOKBEAT04-COX     02-03 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-BOOKBEAT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Writer reworks novel to address bigger issues
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Like everyone who needs to write fiction, Frank
Dobson wanted more than to tell a tale. He sought to address the
big picture, to shed some light on the larger issues. He had a
story, born of a real incident back in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the premise from watching a PBS show on rational
suicide,'' he said, in which a woman with a terminal illness
planned her death. It was a premise on which could be draped all
sorts of issues; so Dobson started to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a young, gifted, black college graduate who planned
a rational suicide. His problems had to do with ghosts of the past,
a failed marriage, a failed career as a world-class sprinter and
problems with substance abuse in the family. He had high and lofty
goals that hadn't been met and felt that rather than deal with
disappointments, he'd commit suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished the book. He got an agent _ seen by many to be the
first, most difficult step toward being published. The book didn't
sell.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson is black, and his own lofty career goals seem to have
been attained. He grew up in Buffalo, N.Y., earned a Ph.D. at
Bowling Green University and has been teaching literature at Wright
State University since 1991. So while his outward, professional
life was going nicely, his novel _ the result of countless hours of
inner work _ was stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   So he took it upon himself, removing the manuscript from the
agent's control. His efforts at selling his story to a publisher
fared no better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to rework the book after being unable to sell it
myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Dobson received awards for his poetry and short
stories, including a Culture Works grant. Finally, in late 1996,
his reworked novel sold to Sterling House, a small publishing
company in Pittsburgh. The Race Is Not Given ($11.95, paperback)
was released this month. Borders Books &AMP; Music plans an order, as
does the Barnes &AMP; Noble near the Mall at Fairfield Commons, Dobson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson thinks part of the reason his book finally sold was the
addition of a concrete reason for his main character's suicide. He
kept the failures, and added cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the cancer helped sell the book, I really do,'' he
said, adding that rational suicide is such a hot topic that the
mainstream balked at the man's decision. A terminal illness made
his action slightly more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was working on it, my dad had cancer and was fighting
it for a while. My uncle died . . . It made it much more personal.
But I see the cancer as a metaphor for the cancers we all deal
with. He's struggling with lots of issues, issues of race, of
place, his family, his failed marriage, his failed relationships
and simply not achieving those goals he's set for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobson is pleased with his book, less happy with Sterling
House's marketing ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some struggles with the title, and the rights to some
of the songs I wanted to use. But I'm comfortable with the book. It
behooves me to do what I can to get the word out.''
</P>
<P>
   So Dobson, a full-time teacher, has become a part-time marketer.
More to the point, he's started another book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself as a fiction writer, so I've begun the second
novel. I'm 150 pages in.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Dempsey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
