 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, February 4, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Just when you think nothing is
safe from the filthy halls of commerce, you learn that, well,
nothing is safe from the filthy halls of commerce. Take my
daughter's name, for instance. A time-honored Catholic name, I
thought, even if a tad old-fashioned. My mother's name, although
everybody calls her Vera. Little did I know the name really belongs
to Archie Comics. Yep, that's right; the comic book company claims
to own the trademark. Lawyers had threatened legal action against
the father of 22-month-old Veronica Sams unless he pulled the Web
site Veronica.org. Is there anything in our society that somebody
isn't trying to own? (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Any day now I expect Texas'
jackbooted lawyer-protection police to kick in my front door and
ransack my house for my copies and upgrades of Quicken Family
Lawyer. In an touching effort to protect Texas consumers, U.S.
District Judge Barefoot Sanders has released a summary judgment to
prevent Parsons Technology Inc. from selling copies of its popular
home computer software Quicken Family Lawyer and Quicken Family
Lawyer '99 in Texas. A ban on the sale of self-help legal software
may be a defeat for the First Amendment and common sense, but it's
a slam-dunk triumph for the Unauthorized Practice of Law Committee,
which is fully funded by the State Bar of Texas and also an
extension of the Texas Supreme Court. (Nethaway, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Exterminator Mark Langford says
there's one little detail you've got to remember when you use a dog
to find termites in someone's apartment. ``One important thing is
to walk the dog before inspections,'' said Langford, an owner of
ASAP Termite Pest Control. Langford's termite-detecting beagle is
named Woody. What else are you going to name a termite dog?
Aluminum Siding? Langford has been using Woody for about a month to
sniff out the wood-eating bugs. He says Woody's the only termite
dog in Austin. ``He's got a nose on him,'' Langford said. ``I'm
going to get him his own business cards with his picture on it that
says, 'Woody, termite finder.' '' (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ One hour a week. Not
much time to educate a youngster, but when an adult spends time
one-on-one helping a child to learn, remarkable progress can occur.
The student feels valued. Learning becomes important. Someone in
authority believes he can achieve. Gov. Bush understands these
dynamics. As a candidate, he visited more than 200 schools. On
Wednesday mornings, he begins his day at Augusta Raa Middle School
a few miles from the Capitol in Tallahassee. There, in the library,
before the first class of the day, he spends an hour reviewing the
homework of a 13-year-old seventh-grader who is behind in his
studies. Since the governor has been tutoring him, the boy named
Trayvon _ whom Gov. Bush describes as ``a smart kid'' _ is already
showing signs of improvement. (Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ I was taking out a loan and trying to hedge
my bet a bit, but would you believe it? The bank balked. When the
nice lady punched in the particulars, a red band popped up across
her computer like she'd never seen before, declaring in no
uncertain terms: ``Credit Life Refused!'' (Murray, Cox News
Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
