<P>
   HIPHOP-COMEBACK _ When Tupac Shakur and Notorious B.I.G. were
murdered within six months of each other two years ago, many
predicted the gangsta rappers would take the popularity of hip-hop
music with them to the grave. Go ahead and call it a comeback,
then, that hip-hop music dominated the Billboard charts during this
past holiday rush and continues to weigh in as the most popular
music of the day. Last week, five of the 10 best-selling albums in
the country were hip-hop-oriented, including the new No. 1 album by
New Orleans rapper Silkk the Shocker. What's most surprising about
this boom, though, is that even the sterotypically rap-less Austin
is feeling its ripples. (Riemenschneider, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
