<HEADLINE>
`HOMICIDE' COPS GET HANDS-ON LESSON IN INTERNET CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MATT BEER   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A serial killer is mutilating young girls,
posting grisly video clips of his handiwork on the World Wide Web.
To catch the video producer, the police give chase on the Net,
diving into the arcane culture of the on-line world with its
confusion of addresses, chat rooms and fake e-mail drops.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens on the Feb. 5 episode of NBC's ``Homicide:
Life on the Street,'' the critically acclaimed police program that
airs 10 p.m. EST (check local listings).
</P>
<P>
   To help the show's old-school detectives navigate through the
intricacies of an on-line crime investigation, ``Homicide'' writers
turned to Alex Wellen and Luke Reiter, two young lawyers who host
the ``CyberCrime TV'' broadcast on a computer-based television
channel in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to us with the concept of a murder that would be
broadcast live on the Internet,'' said Reiter, 28, a former
district attorney in Queens, New York. ``They wanted to know
whether or not it was technologically feasible for somebody to do
what their made-up killer could do on-line.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair's answer was enough to create a multimedia extravaganza
that should satiate even the most die-hard ``Homicide'' fan.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the ``Homicide.Com'' episode airs on NBC, the Web
site for the program _ called ``Second Shift'' (www.homicide.com) _
will begin showing a pre-TV show episode. Using New York-based
actors, ``Second Shift'' will feature the preliminary investigation
of a mysterious, shocking on-line film of a murder. The Web site
detectives investigate the authenticity of the video clips.
</P>
<P>
   Then the TV show takes over, where Lt. Al Giardello (Yaphet
Kotto), Detective John Munch (Richard Belzer) and the other
fictional gumshoes from the Baltimore homicide bureau track down
the killer. ``Second Shift'' takes over after the TV episode for
some post-investigation work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show will flow back and forth between the Web and TV,''
said Ayelet Sela, a writer/producer of the Web site. ``We're going
to be laying some new ground here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they were looking to us for was to try figure out how
detectives would go about investigating this kind of a high-tech
murder,'' said Reiter, who spent his DA days chasing New York
homicide officers. ``They wanted to show how old-school detectives
would investigate a murder on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an easy gig for Reiter and Wellen, who have been
reporting on on-line crime and other stories since the ZDTV
computer channel was launched last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we helped show them how to sustain a story that had a
lot of high-tech angles,'' said Wellen, a civil lawyer from
Manhattan. ``That's because we've been into all aspects of this
stuff for quite some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiter said he and Wellen, who attended Temple Law School in
Philadelphia together, were invited to Baltimore in December to
observe the ``Homicide.Com'' episode being filmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, that was interesting,'' said Wellen, who used the chance
to create his own segment on the experience for ZDTV. The project
was mutually beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really helped make the show work,'' said Sara Charno, a
``Homicide'' writer and co-producer. ``For example, in a regular
mundane murder, you look for fingerprints, hair and witnesses,''
Charno said. ``In a cybercrime, we had to show what steps you take
to trace information. ... We had to show how a criminal could erase
his on-line traces.''
</P>
<P>
   Charno also used tips from Wellen and Reiter to avoid what the
television and movie industry calls ``Internet syndrome'' _ endless
scenes of a character parked in front of a computer screen, typing.
</P>
<P>
   According to Charno, ``Homicide'' producer Jay Tobias boosted
the episode's number of scenes to 80 from the usual 40 to 60. ``We
wanted the pace to be fast and furious,'' Charno said.
</P>
<P>
   The network experience has Wellen and Reiter thinking of further
moves into new venues, including a novel and a pilot for a
fictional crime TV series. ``It'll be the next wave in law
enforcement drama on TV,'' Reiter said. ``Its about time for a new
kind of crime show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-28-99 1405EST &QL;
</P>
