<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-TV-MEDIA-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH THE TUBE OR WATCH THE COMPUTER? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Mark Cuban, whose company sends radio and
television broadcasts over the Internet to personal computers, told
a ballroom full of television executives here that any day now
people will use their computers to watch television, buy
merchandise from their favorite shows and even send feedback to
producers or advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow panelist interrupted. ``People don't watch technology,
they watch channels,'' said Jessica Reif Cohen, a prominent
media-industry analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``Who wants to watch a
PC?''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, the co-founder and president of Broadcast.com Inc. shot
back, referring to a typical cable box: ``What's a set-top box?
It's just a stupid computer. Why not watch a smart computer?'' And
Lowell Paxson, the founder and chairman of the fledgling broadcast
network Paxnet, drew applause by telling Cuban, ``I want you to
turn every PC in the world into a conduit for my television
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Will that ever really happen? Such questions arose with new
urgency last week at the largest television trade show in the
world, called NATPE and sponsored by the National Association of
Television Executives.
</P>
<P>
   Normally at NATPE, producers and syndicators of non-network
programs meet and glad-hand their customers, the United States'
television-station executives _ people far more familiar with
``Home Improvement'' than home pages.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the Internet entrepreneurs were horning in on the
party. Both as exhibitors and as experts on NATPE's informational
panels, they clamored to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, no computer company had a booth at NATPE, and
only Microsoft made a presentation. This year, more than two dozen
new-media companies bought booths, and Microsoft's
3,200-square-foot display entwined wavy glass, sleek stainless
steel and computers with big screens featuring live video and
CD-like sound.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the convention center was still dominated by
old-fashioned NATPE pursuits. Sprawling, gaudy booths stood ready
to woo customers with free food, open bars, plush carpets and
billboard-sized blowups of the studio's stars. Conventioneers could
gawk at starlets zipped into shiny dresses, queue up to shake hands
with Pamela Anderson Lee or William Shatner, or share a cocktail
with the latest exceedingly bronzed game-show host.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the world of new media began to intrude on the
old. ``It's still a big unknown, the question of how do we make
money with it,'' said Nick Trigony, NATPE's chairman and the
president of Cox Broadcasting. ``Most guys' stations now have their
own Web sites, but frankly, they aren't too exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   New-media concepts still baffle many of the 17,000 who attended
NATPE. Many think digital television means high-definition
television, and dismiss it as a gimmick. Others understand that
digital TV simply means a digitally compressed signal that can
carry voluminous amounts of extra information with the traditional
sound and picture _ but even those people have no clue what extra
information their viewers will want.
</P>
<P>
   And so the computer mavens _ distinguishable by the sporty polo
shirts they wore instead of jackets and ties _ swooped in,
preaching the gospel of digital bits and video streaming. Steve
Klein, director of new-business development for Intervu Inc., a
company that helps people expand the reach and speed of their Web
sites, said Internet knowledge among television executives was
rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, it would have been `Streaming _ what?''' he
said. ``Last year it was `Streaming _ how?' And this year it's
`Streaming _ when?' Can you do it live? Can you do video on
demand?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, three panels during the four-day convention addressed
new-media issues. This year, 11 did, out of 31 altogether. Last
year, a seminar on how to sell ads on a Web site drew 10 people who
sat around a table together; this year, it attracted almost 100,
and aides had to drag more chairs into the room.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Molly Glover, the director of interactive marketing at Granite
Broadcasting Corp., which owns 10 television stations, helped
conduct that seminar.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 Granite stations have Web sites, and three _ in San Jose,
Calif.; Buffalo, N.Y.; and Austin, Texas _ are ``streaming'' their
news broadcasts now.
</P>
<P>
   This means people with personal computers, no matter where they
are, can watch the station's local news live, or tune in to catch
the traffic report. They do so through Cuban's company,
Broadcast.com, which announced during NATPE that it had just signed
contracts with two ABC stations _ WABC, Channel 7 in New York, and
WPVI in Philadelphia _ to stream their news.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had quite a few e-mails from servicemen or other people
overseas who have watched their local news,'' Ms. Glover said.
``And snowbirds in Florida like to watch the Buffalo weather.''
</P>
<P>
   In corporate offices, Cuban likes to point out, almost everyone
has a personal computer, or PC, but few have radios or television
sets. He sees that as a huge market to be exploited by television
and radio stations, and by corporations wishing to stream speeches,
seminars or announcements.
</P>
<P>
   To get good-quality sound and video, though, requires an
expensive computer with a high-speed connection to the Internet.
And television traditionalists insist that people will never use a
computer to watch ``E.R.'' or ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' or any
other hit show, movie or sports event, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   But some day people may well use the computer for some
televisionlike functions, and the television set for some
computerlike functions. As NATPE demonstrated, the two are
beginning to mingle, if not to meld.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-31-99 1840EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      02-03 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING MONEY BY PAYING COMPUTER USERS TO READ INTERNET ADS  
 ANGRY INTERNET JOUSTING OVER SIMULATED WARFARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The basic premise of Cybergold, an electronic commerce company
in Berkeley, Calif., is that the best way to get consumers to read
Internet advertisements is to pay them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   It finds advertisers willing to pay people who sign up at its
World Wide Web site (www.cybergold.com) and look at the ads. It
then compensates consumers who demonstrate in some way that they
have read an ad by crediting an account in the consumer's name;
amounts range from 50 cents for downloading America Online software
to $100 for referring a new paid-up subscriber to the At Home
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Once enough money accumulates in a consumer's account, it can be
put in a bank account by direct deposit, used to pay credit card
bills or sent to a favorite charity.
</P>
<P>
   Cybergold recently received its second patent covering the
concept of offering incentives to people to pay attention to ads.
But the company's patents cover two other intriguing approaches to
advertising in cyberspace. The first is a way for consumers to
store direct-marketing information about themselves on their
computers _ like their income bracket, ZIP code, hobbies and
profession _ so they can be compensated every time they decide to
release such information to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion here is that the information about you belongs to
you and doesn't belong to anybody else,'' Goldhaber said. ``And you
can decide when you release it and whether you want to be paid for
it globally or on an ad hoc basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The patents also cover a way of turning conventional
advertising-based publishing on its head. In Goldhaber's patented
Internet publishing system, which he said the company planned to
introduce in coming months, online authors or other creators of
online content would not be paid a set fee by a publisher. Instead,
they would receive a tiny commission from each new reader, who in
turn has been paid to read an accompanying advertisement. Cybergold
would act as a clearinghouse for these transactions, effectively
cutting out the role of a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``First you get paid to see the ads and then you use that to pay
for the content,'' he said. ``You change the flow of money. But you
don't change the basic setup, which is that advertising supports
publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldhaber contends that these are concepts that empower people
who want to self-publish or consumers who want to compensated for
their time. But he and Gary Fitts, co-founder of Cybergold, are
coming under fire for having patented these ways of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Love, director of the Consumer Project on Technology in
Washington, said he would press Congress to conduct hearings on
Cybergold's patents as well as other so-called business-methods
patents. Love said he disagreed with the idea that Cybergold's
system was novel enough to be patented, contending that he had
written articles on a similar concept back in the 1980s. ``And I
didn't consider myself the inventor then,'' he said. ``This is
typical of the poor quality of review they give at the Patent and
Trademark Office for this sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Love described as ``dangerous'' the legal monopoly that these
patents provide, arguing that politicians would likely use such
cash incentives to get potential voters to read their material on
line. ``Suppose one candidate in a given campaign were the only one
to be given a license to the patent,'' he said. ``He would be the
only one who could disseminate information this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldhaber conceded that politicians would probably use the
system, noting that while it was illegal to buy votes, it was not
illegal to pay voters to read political tracts. ``Instead of
offering a drink down at the bar for coming to a rally,'' he said,
``you can offer a buck and let them go down to the bar and buy
their own drink.''
</P>
<P>
   But he argued that Love's concerns were unfounded. ``The
Internet is not just about hackers anymore,'' he said. ``It's about
real business. If patents are valid in other arenas, they ought to
be valid on the Internet as well. People who globally criticize
patents on the Internet are just wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Cybergold most recently received patent 5,855,008.
</P>
<P>
   ANGRY INTERNET JOUSTING OVER SIMULATED WARFARE
</P>
<P>
   Computer programmers were busy spewing vitriol last week on
Slashdot, an Internet site (www.slashdot.org) that proclaims itself
as specializing in ``news for nerds,'' over another Internet
patent.
</P>
<P>
   The patent, assigned to Rtime, of Seattle, covers certain
aspects of playing three-dimensional games on the Internet. One
aspect is a type of real-time data filtering that insures that only
relevant data is distributed to participants. Another is a global
time base that keeps different users synchronized within
milliseconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have two or more people distributed across the
Internet that want to act in real time, you have to resolve slow
performance issues,'' said Chip Overstreet, chief executive of
Rtime, a company with eight full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
   Overstreet said the technology was developed by programmers who
helped build the U.S. military's Simnet, a virtual-reality system
used to train soldiers for combat.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those weighing in on Slashdot wondered whether Rtime
would try to extract a licensing fee each time someone tried to
play private sessions of Doom or Quake or other three-dimensional
games over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Overstreet declined to comment specifically on the remarks made
on Slashdot.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Snoswell, a founder of Cyberterm, a software company in
Adelaide, Australia, was one of those who derided the patent on
Slashdot.
</P>
<P>
   But after reading the patent carefully, he said in a telephone
interview, he was less concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The animosity over this patent arose because it was seen as
cornering the market,'' he said. ``Initially, when you read the
patent you think it covers everything. But then when you read the
fine print, it looks a lot more narrow. It's not going to become a
generic solution over time. It wouldn't surprise me that this will
fit a niche market. But eventually that niche market will get
smaller and smaller as other technologies crowd it out of the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Patent 5,841,980 was granted to Rolland Waters and John Allred
and was assigned to Rtime.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-31-99 1730EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
