<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-N     02-03 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN OF A DISK-DRIVE JOCKEY  
 MARKET CHAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If any companies in the personal-computer industry are prone to
painful cycles and oversupply problems, it is the makers of disk
drives, the unglamorous but critical components that store a
computer's data. And nobody knows this better than one of the
disk-drive pioneers, Finis Conner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite his travails, or perhaps because of them, Conner is
back, and with a new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Conner's new company, Conner Technology, based in San Jose,
Calif., plans to make drives for the budget end of the market,
selling $100 drives for PCs that would be priced around $600.
Mining this low-margin end of the market, Conner is trying some
profit shortcuts, including incorporating in Ireland to cut taxes
and subcontracting manufacturers in China to trim costs.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Conner is no stranger to risk in the drive business.
Twenty years ago, along with Al Shugart, Conner co-founded what
would become Seagate Technology, the disk-drive industry's biggest
survivor. In 1986, the partners had a bitter falling out, and
Conner struck out on his own, founding Conner Peripherals. Ten
years later, despite phenomenal growth, the company became buried
in debt, battered by increasingly heavy competition. Conner was
forced to sell out _ to Seagate.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1996, and shortly afterward Conner disappeared from the
scene, self-exiled by a noncompete agreement with Seagate that kept
him out of the drive market for two years. Within a few months
after the contract expired last year, Conner founded Conner
Technology. Shugart, incidentally, lost control of Seagate last
year and was forced by its board to sign a noncompete agreement
that will keep him on the disk-drive sidelines for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Conner said his goal is to sell 2 million drives the first year
and to make his new company grow at the same rate of Conner
Peripherals, which sold $113 million in 1986 and reached $2.7
billion 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
   But it is far from certain whether Conner's model for
outsourcing will work in the crowded drive business, which has had
its share of casualties the last few years. But Conner put a
positive spin on the skepticism that greeted word of his new
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any measure of success is how much your competitors don't
understand you, we're in good shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   An Online Chat to Invest In
</P>
<P>
   As if it wasn't enough to stare blankly into the computer screen
all day and watch the numbers in one's stock portfolio go
roller-coastering about, here now is perhaps another reason for eye
strain: 12 hours of live online chat with market experts daily.
</P>
<P>
   America Online and Sage, a financial site already carried on the
online service, plan to introduce this new offering Monday, in an
attempt to ``replicate television business programs,'' Stephen
Cohn, a Sage co-founder, said. He cited CNBC's ``Squawk Box'' and
``Power Lunch'' as two shows from which he'd like to woo viewers.
</P>
<P>
   As with the televised shows it seeks to emulate, the chat
service, called AOL's Market Watch, plans to offer a roster of
financial experts and pundits from the likes of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist,
John Hancock and Smart Money magazine, who will interact with users
as the day unfolds. The difference is you don't have to turn down
the volume when there's a particularly bombastic guest _ since the
``chatting'' will all be done through typed text.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the perfect category for the online medium,'' Tom
Ziemba, a spokesman for America Online, said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the personal-finance part of its service, the company
already provides about 100 million stock quotes each day, and it
contends that more than 9 million users actively manage their
portfolios through America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide everything television can and more,'' Ziemba
said.
</P>
<P>
   Like commercials. Asked what Sage gets out of the deal besides
more work and potential users of the site, Cohn said, ``This is an
opportunity to sell marketing programs, like sponsorships and
advertisements.''
</P>
<P>
   Scudder Funds, T. Rowe Price, Kauffman Funds and E-Annuity have
already signed up as sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-31-99 1454EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
