<HEADLINE>
TOP WEB SITES? DEPENDS ON THE CHOOSER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID HOYE   
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Well, we're a month into the new year, and the
computer press is winding up its look back on the top Web sites of
1998. &QL; 
In checking out some of the lists of top sites, I found it
interesting to note that being a top site in terms of the number of
visitors attracted doesn't necessarily make for a top site in terms
of quality.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the lists of top Web sites published by
``Yahoo! Internet Life'' and ``PC Magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Yahoo! Internet Life,'' which rated Web sites
based on number of visitors, the top three online news sites were
CNN.com (www.cnn.com), MSNBC.com (www.msnbc.com) and USA Today
(www.usatoday.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``PC Magazine,'' meanwhile, created its list of top sites based
on the expertise of its staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are our essential bookmarks,'' Don Willmott wrote in the
Feb. 9 issue of ``PC Magazine.'' They are ``sites that we find
ourselves returning to again and again for their ease of
navigation, design, content and, most important of all, their
usefulness.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came to online news sites, ``PC Magazine'' also listed
CNN.com and MSNBC.com among its top picks. But ``USA Today'' was
not on the list. Instead, ``PC Magazine'' mentioned ABCNEWS.com
(www.abcnews.com), the Associated Press news service, the Wire
(www.wire.ap.org), and the ``NewYork Times'' (www.nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   In describing the Wire, ``PC Magazine'' noted, ``No nonsense
here. The Wire is your most direct access to current news stories
and photographs coming across the Associated Press wire . . . for
some kinds of news, this is as close to the source as you can
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting top Web site category to compare was online
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo! Internet Life'' listed the top sites as Disney
(www.disney.com), Sony (www.sony.com) and the Internet Movie
Database (www.imdb.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``PC Magazine'' agreed on just one of those choices: The
Internet Movie Database. Instead of Disney and Sony, its top
entertainment sites included Broadcast.com (www.broadcast.com),
which provides live radio broadcasts, MP3.com (www.mp3.com), which
offers information and downloadable music in the new MP3 format,
Mylaunch (www.mylaunch.com), a customizable site for music lovers,
and the Onion (www.theonion.com), a bawdy adult humor site.
</P>
<P>
   Something else I noted was that ``Yahoo! Internet Life'' ranked
Yahoo! (www.yahoo.com) as the top Web site based on the number of
visits it gets.
</P>
<P>
   (I know, the magazine has a licensing agreement with the Web
site of the same name. But don't worry, I've seen Yahoo! listed as
the top Web site by other sources. And the magazine claims to be
``editorially independent'' from the Web site. For the record, both
``Yahoo! Internet Life'' and ``PC Magazine'' are owned by Ziff
Davis.)
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting is how ``PC Magazine'' listed Yahoo!.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``PC Magazine'' listed Yahoo! as one of its top portal,
or starting, pages on the Web, it didn't include Yahoo! as a top
search engine, which is how Yahoo! got its start.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``PC Magazine'' listed top search engines as AltaVista
(www.av.com), HotBot (www.hotbot.com), MetaCrawler
(www.metacrawler.com), Google! (www.google.stanford.edu.com), and
Northern Light (www.northernlight.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``PC Magazine'' did mention Yahoo! among the tops in three other
categories: Yahoo! Chat (chat.yahoo.com), Yahoo! Finance
(www.quote.yahoo.com), and the people-finder Yahoo! People
(www.people.yahoo.com).
</P>
<P>
   Although I still use Yahoo! often to find things, I have to
agree with ``PC Magazine's'' Yahoo!-less search engine list. In my
experience, I more often find what I am looking for by using either
HotBot or AltaVista.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
What's an old PC worth?
</P>
<P>
   So, you have a PC sitting in the unused bedroom. You bought it,
say, three years ago, and you spent, say, $2,800. Now you want to
sell it, figuring it's gotta still be worth about $500, maybe
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong-o, buddy boy! You'll be lucky if that old PC is still
worth $300. More likely, it's worth closer to $200!
</P>
<P>
   That's the lesson learned by anyone who has access to an Orion
Blue Book of Computers, one of 12 price manuals produced several
times a year by Orion Research Corp. in Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to computers, Orion produces Blue Books on cameras,
audio equipment, car stereos, copiers, guitars, guns, pianos, power
tools, televisions and other categories.
</P>
<P>
   Orion owner Roger Rohrs sent me the company's latest Blue Book
of Computers, which comes on a handy CD-ROM. It was both
interesting and painful to read!
</P>
<P>
   If you look at older computers, those sold in the early 1990s,
you can find many that sold for thousands of dollars but now are
worth $10, $20 or $30.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to check out Orion's Blue Books for yourself,
usually you've got to shell out a few hundred bucks to buy the
CD-ROM or a printed book.
</P>
<P>
   But for a limited time, Orion is offering a complete set of its
Blue Books _ including the computer pricing information _ on CD-ROM
for just $25. The catch: The CD-ROM and its data expire at the end
of this month.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in obtaining such a time-limited CD, or if
you want to buy a regular CD, visit Orion at www.bluebook.com. Or
you can call the company at (602) 951-1114. &QL; 
Year 2000 humor
</P>
<P>
   As a parting dose of humor, this week I offer a funny Y2K tidbit
that's been bouncing around the Internet via e-mail. I'm not sure
who wrote it, but it's worth a laugh:
</P>
<P>
   ``January 4, 2000
</P>
<P>
   Dear Valued Employee:
</P>
<P>
   Re: Vacation Pay
</P>
<P>
   Our records indicate that you have not used any vacation time
over the past 100 year(s). As I'm sure you are aware, employees are
granted 3 weeks of paid leave per year or pay in lieu of time off.
One additional week is granted for every five years of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please either take 9,400 days off work or notify our office
and your next paycheck will reflect payment of $8,277,432.22 which
will include all pay and interest for the past 1,200 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   ``Automated Payroll Processing'' &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-01-99 1319EST &QL;
</P>
