<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-ESSAY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER-EVALUATED ESSAYS: LOOKING FOR THE TIDY MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (The Week in Review) 
By JANNY SCOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So it has come to this. The essay, the great literary art form
that Montaigne conceived and Virginia Woolf carried on, that the
writer Edward Hoagland likens to jazz or a butterfly's flight, has
sunk to a state where someone thinks it is a bright idea to ask a
computer if an essay is any good.
</P>
<P>
   The new computer, which is called e-rater (sort of like
In-Sink-Erator, the company that makes machines to grind up kitchen
garbage), will be used along with a trained human to grade the two
essay questions on the Graduate Management Admission Test taken by
200,000 business school applicants each year.
</P>
<P>
   E-rater's interest is not exactly that of Addison and Steele or
E.B. White. Humor is outside its jurisdiction, as are irony and
surprise. E-rater likes subordinate and complementary clauses and
words like ``however'' and ``therefore'' that some people think
suggest a tidy mind.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when essays were thought to be more than the
sum of their therefores. They were distinguished by their
originality, insight and personal voice, by their graceful style,
lack of affectation and willingness to meander. Instead of stomping
toward a conclusion, many never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   A genuine essay is ``the movement of a free mind at play,''
writes novelist and critic Cynthia Ozick; it is ``a stroll through
someone's mazy mind.'' The essayist is free ``to hop from thought
to thought, to begin with the finish and finish with the middle, or
to eschew beginning and end and keep only a middle.''
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, Samuel Johnson and other great essayists were
used as models to teach theme writing in schools. But in the
factory of freshman composition, the meaning of ``essay'' has
eroded to a point where it is almost equivalent to any old hunk of
prose. As a result, shortly after Robert Atwan started editing his
annual book series, ``The Best American Essays'' (Houghton
Mifflin), a dentist sent along an article on root canal that he had
published in a dental journal and said was the best essay he had
ever written.
</P>
<P>
   The telltale signs of a bad essay are at least as familiar as
the virtues of the great ones. There is the obligatory ``thesis
statement,'' Atwan says. Then come three paragraphs of exposition,
then a concluding paragraph summarizing the preceding three, along
with the phrase ``Thus we see that ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to forget the school essay before they can
write,'' said Ian Frazier, the writer. ``They have to forget `not
only but also' constructions. That's dead. Nobody wants to read
that, not even teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter the e-rater.
</P>
<P>
   The impulse behind e-rater was not, of course, doing Max
Beerbohm one better. The idea was to cut costs, among other things.
Instead of two people grading each essay, the Graduate Management
Admission Council, which administers the test, could have one
trained human and one machine.
</P>
<P>
   And what a machine! E-rater is ``the most highly developed,
holistic electronic writing assessment application to date,'' said
Frederic McHale of the admission council. It is a computer bulked
up on a high-protein diet of high-scoring answers to past
admission-test essay questions.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Burstein, a scientist at Educational Testing Service in
Princeton, N.J., who led the team that invented e-rater, says the
computer looks for what she called syntactic variety, such as
different kinds of clauses. It also looks for words associated with
organization of ideas, such as ``first,'' ``second'' and ``third.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not trained to score Montaigne,'' she said. ``It's not
designed to score creative writing and irony and metaphor and
poems. It's designed for a specific purpose, to score the kinds of
essays we see on standardized tests.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible (therefore!) to say how Montaigne might have
fared. He never did have to analyze the annual report of Olympic
Foods or agree or disagree with a statement like, ``Nations should
cooperate to develop regulations that limit children's access to
adult material on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Much business writing seems to aspire to little more than
lowest-common-denominator order and clarity. And, with home
computers already editing for gender neutrality and pointing out
when sentences exceed 31 words, why not let e-rater be the enforcer
of corporatese?
</P>
<P>
   ``For business letters, I think it's OK,'' Ms. Ozick conceded in
an interview. ``On the other hand, this is no way to teach somebody
to think. If an essay represents thinking at its purest and most
original, this is a terrible template to put over the human mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, however, said he understands the impulse. Strangers
keep cranking out manuscripts on computers and shipping them off to
him. ``It would be great if one machine wrote it and another
machine read it,'' he said, ``and we would all be free to go about
our business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-01-99 1339EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9907 &Cx1f; tic-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-SCHOOL-     02-03 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-SCHOOL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PCS REVAMP WAY UNVERSITY STUDENTS PREPARE, LEARN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JONATHAN SIDENER   
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For decades, students have been penciling in little
circles on standardized tests so that electronic scoring machines
can grade those multiple-choice results.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a computer application called e-rater is ready to go beyond
the dots and take on the tricky task of grading essay questions.
</P>
<P>
   Educational Testing Service of Princeton, N.J., has developed a
system for the group that runs the Graduate Management Admission
Test.
</P>
<P>
   Some time this month, E-rater is scheduled to begin grading the
two essay questions on the GMAT, which is taken by applicants to
business graduate schools. Using expert-system technology, essays
will be graded on the basis of their vocabulary, syntax and logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a trial,'' said Frederic McHale of the Graduate
Management Admission Council, the Virginia group that sponsors the
GMAT. ``It's been thoroughly tested.''
</P>
<P>
   With college students and educators among the most computerized
demographic groups, it comes as little surprise that computers are
shaping the educational experience beyond the classroom. For a
growing number of students, the traditional wait in long lines at
the college bookstore has been replace by a process of surf and
click from the comfort of their dorm rooms. And for other students,
help cramming for exams is available online.
</P>
<P>
   Essay questions on past versions of the GMAT were graded by two
professors. If their answers were within one point of each other
then an average of the two becomes the final score. If their
answers are more than a point apart, then a third professor comes
in to be the deciding vote. The new system will use the e-rater in
place of one of the humans. If the human and computer scores are
within one point, then an average will be the final score, as it is
in the existing system. If they differ by more than a point, a
second professor will be brought in and the computer score will no
longer be considered.
</P>
<P>
   McHale said the system is designed to work in conjunction with
human check and balance. It is also designed to score answers to
specific questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about evaluating creative writing. We're not
planning to use the machines by themselves,'' he said. ``Some
individuals have a unique or creative way of writing that the
machine cannot understand.''
</P>
<P>
   E-rater begins with a sample of about 300 answers to each
question that have been previously graded by professors. The
questions include the full range of 1 to 6 possible points. E-rater
analyzes each answer on the basis of 57 features from three
categories, syntax, vocabulary and the logic or structure of its
argument and builds a sort of statistical profile of what makes up
each of the six possible scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks for syntactic structure, the structural information
about the sentence,'' ETS developmental scientist Jill Burstein
said. ``It looks for vocabulary. And it looks for discourse, cue
words and terms related to argument structure.''
</P>
<P>
   E-rater then runs the same analysis of the 57 features on each
essay answer and compares the profile of that essay against the six
profiles of possible scores from the sample essays.
</P>
<P>
   The computer score agreed with the human score from 87 to 94
percent of the time, which is identical to the agreement rate
between two people, McHale said.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are changing another facet of college life at the
University of Arizona and dozens of other large universities across
the country. Students can sign on to the Web site VarsityBooks.com,
select their school from a list, then select their major from a
second list and then select the required books for their classes
from a third list. Texts are listed by class number and
instructor's name. In a few days, the selected books will arrive in
the mail.
</P>
<P>
   VarsityBooks.com includes the University of Arizona as one of 57
major U.S. schools where required books can be selected by
professor name and class number. Company founder Eric Kuhn says
plans call for inclusion of Arizona State University book lists by
the fall semester.
</P>
<P>
   Students from schools not yet included can still shop with the
company, but will have to go through a couple of extra steps to
search for the books by title.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhn, who gave up a job as a corporate attorney to found
VarsityBooks.com in December 1997, said that inefficient industries
such as the college bookstore are fertile ground for Internet
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ideal opportunity,'' he said. ``It's a $3 billion
niche market.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the attractions is that 95 percent of college students
are online, more than any other demographic group. They're
comfortable with the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   When the e-marketer launched, it had only five featured schools
in the Washington, D.C., market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a week, we were selling to students in all 50 states.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuhn said that the reduced overhead of e-commerce allows
VarsityBooks.com to offer significant discounts over the college
book stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've operated much like a monopoly for years,'' he said.
``This has not traditionally been a competitive area.''
</P>
<P>
   He said some college bookstores have launched their own online
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their response has been interesting,'' Kuhn said. ``I think
that most view us as inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also offers several sites to help students, for a
fee.
</P>
<P>
   One such site, cram.com, offers notes, study aids called cram
sheets and cheat sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Tutor Co. announced (www.supertutor.com) offers a site
targeting high school and middle school students. The company's
final-exam prep site, the Cram Zone (www.homeworkhelp.com), was
launched in May. &QL; 
Jonathan Sidener can be reached at jon.sidener(at)pni.com via
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-01-99 1304EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
