<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spruced-up `Slap Shot' scores with Newman
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With football on the wane, why not check out a sports classic in
another field? Paul Newman's 1977 film ``Slap Shot'' does for
professional hockey _ albeit in a jokier, less daring way _ what
``North Dallas Forty'' does for football. Newman is the manager of
a hockey team made up mostly of has-beens and rookies. His solution
is to go for the opposition's throat _ and knees and jaws and
whatever _ which makes for some bone-crunching action sequences.
The DVD version offers little more than a spruced-up version of the
film, but the film bios remind you that Newman and director George
Roy Hill struck pay dirt with ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance
Kid'' and ``The Sting,'' and the theatrical trailer is, as usual,
of a certain time-capsule interest (the men's very-'70s hair alone
is worth a look).
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
