<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MARY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's something about Diaz amid `Mary's' gross-out humor
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Rude, crude and hilarious, this comedy by the ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber''
team of Peter and Bobby Farrelly definitely isn't a family film.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Stiller plays Ted, a nerdy high school senior who suffers a
very particular bathroom mishap that prevents him from making his
prom date with golden girl Mary (Cameron Diaz). Thirteen years
later, he hires a lower-rung gumshoe (Matt Dillon) to track her
down.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is liberating in its scatological, slapstick way; it
throws in gross-out humor but maintains a surprisingly sweet tone
(that's partly thanks to Diaz's substantial charm). If you're a dog
lover, you might have a hard time. Same goes if you're queasy about
body-function humor. But for the funniest American movie of '98,
it's a gotta-see. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
