<HEADER>
A9939 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-RINGEL04-COX     02-03 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These football sagas won't let you down
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling let down after the last touchdown last weekend?
Suffering from post-Super Bowl depression? Don't let the gridiron
blues get you. Instead, try some of these football-themed rentals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``North Dallas Forty'' (1979)
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the best film about pro football ever made. Except,
it's not exactly pro pro football. Based on Peter Gent's novel, a
thinly disguised account of his experiences playing for the Dallas
Cowboys, the movie stars Nick Nolte as an aging receiver who's
slowly being forced to realize that the real game isn't played on
the field; it's played in the corporate offices. As he tells the
team owner, ``We're not the team. You're the team. We're only the
equipment _ like the jockstraps and helmets.'' G.D. Spradlin is
chilling as Nolte's ruthless, Bible-quoting coach (read, Tom
Landry).
</P>
<P>
   Notable faces in the locker room: Singer Mac Davis as a showy
quarterback who knows how to play both games and John Matuszak from
the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Longest Yard'' (1974)
</P>
<P>
   Burt Reynolds sailed to the front of the early '70s box office
pack with this crowd pleaser about a former pro football player
expelled from the NFL for point shaving. He ends up serving a year
at the state penitentiary (played by Georgia's own state facility
at Reidsville) run by evil warden Eddie Albert. The finale is a
down-and-dirty game between the inmates and the guards. Director
Robert Aldrich was initially displeased with the football footage;
it looked too rehearsed. His solution was to capitalize on
Reynolds' own background as a college player. He told his star to
call a play in the huddle every other down, meaning one play would
be rehearsed, one not. Not so coincidentally, Reynolds also wears
his old Florida State University number _ No. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Notable faces in the locker room: Ray Nitschke of the Green Bay
Packers, Joe Kapp of the Minnesota Vikings and Ernie Wheelwright of
the Atlanta Falcons (look for other NFL imports, too.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``All the Right Moves'' (1983)
</P>
<P>
   Just like the supposedly ``dumb'' jocks who are its heroes, this
movie has a lot more on the ball than you might think. Tom Cruise
extended his ``Risky Business'' winning streak as a high school
hotshot whose only ticket out of a drab Rust Belt one-factory town
is a football scholarship. Most teen movies would be about the Big
Game, the one attended by all the college recruiters. But this one
is about the day after the Big Game. And the day after that. It's
about that terrible teen pressure that assumes that one wrong move
can erase all the right ones. No notable faces in the locker room;
this is, after all, about high school football. But look for Lea
Thompson (TV's ``Caroline in the City'') as Cruise's supportive
girlfriend and Craig T. Nelson as Cruise's ambitious coach. And the
cameraman is Jan De Bont, who later directed ``Speed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Paper Lion''(1968)
</P>
<P>
   A pre-Hawkeye Alan Alda made his film debut as George Plimpton,
a celebrity journalist with a career as a kind of ``professional
amateur.'' He'd fought bulls, boxed with Archie Moore, been beaten
6-love by tennis champ Pancho Gonzales. In ``Paper Lion,'' based on
Plimpton's best seller, Alda tries playing quarterback with the
Detroit Lions. Alda, who'd had polio growing up, had to work extra
hard at the part. He won over his pro-ball co-stars with his
determination and humor. Asked by one if he'd ever played football
as a kid, the actor said, ``My mother wouldn't let me, so she had
my orthodontist write a note to school saying it was bad for my
braces.''
</P>
<P>
   Notable faces in the locker room: Lots of Detroit Tigers,
including John Gordy, Roger Brown and Alex Karras.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Horse Feathers'' (1932)
</P>
<P>
   The Marx Brothers go to college. And where there's college,
there's football. Groucho plays the president of Huxley College, an
institute of higher learning that's on its last legs. Like many
college presidents, Groucho's solution is to produce a winning
football team (the film's jokes about academia cutting corners,
compromising standards and trying everything from cash to coeds to
lure top players are eerily current). The climactic game against
rival Darwin is pure Marx mania. Harpo passes a ball with a rubber
band attached to it (so it comes back to him and he can score).
Chico calls the plays: ``Hey diddle diddle, the cat and the fiddle,
this time I think we go up the middle.'' Groucho cracks wise.
</P>
<P>
   Notable faces in the locker room: Zeppo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: eringel(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
