<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERROR-TRAINING-NEWS-     02-03 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-TRAINING-NEWS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW NOT TO GET KILLED ON DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By IAN FISHER  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Among the many useful things I learned at hostile-environment
school _ a school like no other I have ever attended _ is a
technique called ``crack and thump.''
 &HT;    For this to work, you must first stay calm enough to make an
educated guess about the bullet being fired at you. If you decide
it is, say, a 7.62 high-velocity round, you must then remember that
the bullet travels at approximately half a mile per second.
 &HT;    You listen for the ``crack,'' the sound of the bullet streaking
over your head. You then listen for the ``thump,'' the sound of the
gun being fired in the first place. (The bullets are supersonic, so
they reach you before you hear the rifle go off.) By counting the
seconds between the two sounds, you can tell how far away the
maniac with the gun is.
 &HT;    Three seconds, for example, equals one and a half miles, which
may or may not be far enough away for you to run for your life.
It's like counting the seconds between a flash of lightning and the
rumble of thunder. But it's more unsettling. Lightning doesn't want
you dead.
 &HT;    I have never been shot at. If it happens, I am sure my first
instinct will not be to do math. But as a freshly minted foreign
correspondent, I like this illusion of control in the face of
danger. And that is precisely what you get for your money _ not a
little of it _ from Centurion Risk Assessment Services Ltd.,
situated in a genteel manor house an hour outside London.
 &HT;    For four days, a team of sadistic former Royal British Marines
runs you through mud and trees, explodes things, makes lots of
noise, even kidnaps you, hooded, leading you around by your thumbs.
At the end, you are supposed to understand three truths about the
world we live in and, thus, the world that reporters cover at close
range:
 &HT;    1) The number of ways to die is unlimited.
 &HT;    2) There are many bad people and bad things ready to inflict one
of those ways on you.
 &HT;    3) You can, sometimes, with proper training, even the odds.
 &HT;    This course was designed specifically for journalists in what
Centurion defines broadly as ``hostile environments'' _ war zones,
malarial jungles, cold places, crashing helicopters. (A hint: If
your helicopter goes down in water, make extra sure the rotors have
stopped before you swim to the surface.)
 &HT;    By the time I went this fall with a colleague, Nori Onishi, some
4,000 people had been through the course, including more and more
aid workers and business travelers willing to believe the worst
about the places they go.
 &HT;    And in fact, the worst is sometimes true. According to the
Committee to Protect Journalists, more than 500 reporters have been
killed on the job since 1986. Every year they are kidnapped and
shot, go down in planes, crash on bad roads, run over land mines.
In the early '90s, top editors at the BBC noticed an increase in
the number of reporters injured on assignment. They were not about
to stop covering the news, so they decided to make sure their
people were better prepared for when things went wrong.
 &HT;    They asked Paul Rees, a Falklands war veteran with two decades
in the British marines, to help them develop a course to make
reporting safer. The business turned out to be so good that Rees
founded Centurion and ended up quitting the marines.
 &HT;    His creation is a paranoiac's delight. Nori and I began the
course on a drizzly day in October. We met with Rees and nearly two
dozen reporters from the BBC and ITN at the former estate, with its
firing range and a portrait of some venerable ancestor on the wall.
 &HT;    John Seward, who served in the marines with Rees, got things
rolling by showing off an arsenal, starting with handguns, from the
9-millimeter to the .45 (``Tad bit bigger,'' Seward said crisply,
``more thump at the end of it'') to the AK-47 (``Something like 18
million of these knocking around the world'') to rocket-propelled
grenades and artillery shells.
 &HT;    At every turn, he offered exotic advice: If you find yourself
unable to escape a grenade, lie down with the soles of your feet
pointing toward the blast. Your shoes can take the shock and
shrapnel better than your head.
 &HT;    Then it was off to the range itself, where I learned that
Starsky and Hutch most definitely would have died in the first
episode. The instructors fired weapons of increasing power into a
series of objects that someone like me might cower behind in a gun
battle: brick walls, cement blocks, car doors (no more Starsky),
tree trunks. None of those help for very long.
 &HT;    The only safe place, it seems, is behind a double row of
sandbags, sadly hard to come by. The lesson was clear: If someone
really wants to kill you, there is no way to stop it.
 &HT;    Technology isn't much help either. There was a poignant moment
on the range when a sales representative for a body-armor
manufacturer _ supposedly top-rate gear _ strapped a bulletproof
vest to a mannequin. The result, after a pounding from the rifles,
was, in industry jargon, ``100 percent failure.''
 &HT;    ``This has never happened before,'' the rep said. He was
stricken, and I felt like crying too. I have worn those things.
 &HT;    Rees, Seward and the others were instructors in the military _
where they tear recruits down to rebuild them stronger _ and I
guess that was the theory behind the centerpiece of the course.
 &HT;    Out of the blue on the first day, while we were in the back of a
Range Rover going much too fast, a red car appeared and forced our
driver to pull over. From the surrounding woods came a band of
masked men with rifles. I remember thinking, ``Ah, this is the part
where we get kidnapped.'' It seemed funny.
 &HT;    Then they pushed the guy in front of me face first into the mud.
Then me. Glasses, wedding bands, watches disappeared. Stinking
burlap bags went over our heads. I knew it wasn't real, but I still
couldn't catch my breath. They shoved us down onto the wet ground,
spread-eagled. Gunfire went off.
 &HT;    Someone mysteriously tapped the tips of my fingers. I thought:
``I only met these guys three hours ago. Will someone please tell
me why I am supposed to trust them?''
 &HT;    Twenty minutes later, inside the manor house turned corporate
training center, where students in other courses sat surreally
taking computer classes, Seward and the others asked us what we
thought about what we had been through and how we thought we had
behaved.
 &HT;    Only one person had ``died,'' which I thought was pretty good;
she was shot for ripping the bag off her head _ my first instinct
exactly. That was the bottom line: Remain calm, even when every
fluid ounce of you is screaming out in panic.
 &HT;    Then they let us in on the finer points of kidnapping etiquette.
Do not speak unless spoken to. Make enough eye contact to let your
kidnappers know you are human but not so much as to seem
threatening. Neither cower nor take charge. (Kidnappers are
apparently more likely to shoot either type.) Do whatever you are
told. If your captors start executing other hostages, kick, scream,
bite, run like hell.
 &HT;    ``Not much to lose at that point, is there?'' Seward asked.
 &HT;    This was the pattern repeated over the next three days. First,
they scare you silly. But then they tell you how to live through it
or, more realistically, how to improve your chances.
 &HT;    We saw an hours-long color video presentation of corpses shot up
and exploded, narrated in good cheer by the former military surgeon
who took the pictures. Our sex lives, we learned, could be
compromised by post-traumatic stress.
 &HT;    Not much was overlooked _ they even passed around preserved
specimens of a scorpion and a tarantula (the bites of which are not
normally fatal to healthy adults, though it is still smart to carry
a special venom-sucking syringe, which I now own).
 &HT;    The training was emphatically good to have _ most of the
reporters in the course thought so too _ even if it was not always
comforting. I kept thinking that the course was the evil twin of
the happy Lotto slogan, ``Hey, You Never Know.''
 &HT;    The truth is, though, that you can only work the margins. Life
itself is risky. Tromping around anywhere called ``rebel-held
territory,'' which I am finding out makes up an alarming percentage
of my new beat, makes it more so, and no amount of training can
erase that. When I told a colleague, Frank Clines, a longtime
foreign correspondent now based in Washington, that I was going to
take a course on avoiding dangerous situations, he gave me the only
truly sensible advice: ``Stay as far away as possible.''
 &HT;    That is the advice, I know, that many people give about the
place that makes me feel most safe: New York City. Now that I have
left it, I am somewhat soothed to know all these tricks from
Centurion. For the curious, here are a few: In crossfire, simply
lie on the ground. You are probably not the target. In mortar
attacks, again lie down. If you can, crawl into one of the holes
made by a previous shell because _ back to the thunderstorm analogy
_ lightning rarely strikes twice in the same place.
 &HT;    To see if an area is mined, look for exploded wildlife or
unusual patterns of rocks or leaves that locals might have
fashioned as a warning. (Crazy as it sounds, a
hostile-environment-school graduate actually avoided a booby trap
this way in Cambodia.) Keep your feet warm and dry.
 &HT;    Maintain good water discipline. I'm not sure what that means,
and I hope I never have to find out.
 &HT;     c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
