<HEADER>
A9957 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABBY-LIFEBEAT-CORRECT     02-03 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABBY-LIFEBEAT-CORRECTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE BEFORE DEAR ABBY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: No art accompanies this feature.) 
 BY KAREN DECROW 
 800 words  
 c.1999 Karen DeCrow 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is 1906; a man writes for advice. He has lied to his wife and
wonders if he should tell her the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now I never told anyone about it, but it bothers me. I
have no secrets from my wife, and I want to know whether I should
now tell her all, or not mention it. I beg you to answer me.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer: ``This secret may be withheld from his beloved wife,
since it is clear he keeps it from her out of love.''
</P>
<P>
   And what is the secret? It's not about fooling around. The man
and wife are immigrants living from paycheck to paycheck. The wife
has fallen gravely ill, and the husband must tend her. His boss
tells him that if he doesn't appear at work he will be fired. He
fears they will slowly starve to death. He opens the gas jet, gets
into bed with his wife, and waits for death for the two of them.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly his wife cries out for water. As he goes to get it, he
closes the gas jet. Two weeks later she has recovered, but he does
not know whether to tell her the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The advice comes from the arbiter of ethics and behavior for
millions of people, for dozens of years: The Jewish Daily Forward.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1881 and 1925, about 2.5 million Jewish immigrants came
to America from Eastern Europe. Few spoke English and most were
very poor. They were all eager to integrate, to become, as my
grandmother used to say ``real Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   They needed guidance, not only in the ways of the new land but
in ways that would carry on the traditions they had left behind.
Not all of them chose to continue the Orthodox way of life, but
they did not want to throw aside the ethics of their fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus arose the readership for the daily column, A Bintel Brief
(A Bundle of Letters). It was the Dear Abby and the Ann Landers of
its day, giving advice in solving weighty problems. It eased the
transition from the old world to the new. And it dispensed wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   A man who describes himself as a ``greenhorn'' from Russia
inquires: ``Shall I send my father a few dollars for Passover, or
should I keep the little money for myself? I will do what you tell
me.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bintel Brief replies: ``He should send his father the few
dollars for Passover because, as he is young, he will find it
easier to earn a living than would hi. blind father in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Concise and to the point: It is all right to lie to your loved
ones to spare them pain. Help your parents, even if it requires
personal sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   A letter on eating habits will resonate with the parents of
today who shape tofu into the form of a turkey at Thanksgiving:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two sons, 9 and 7 years old. They are healthy, well
built and are doing well in public school and Hebrew school. So you
would think everything is fine, but I have trouble with the older
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``About nine months ago he took it into his head to become a
vegetarian and stopped eating meat...As soon as he smelled meat
cooking he wouldn't come into the kitchen. ...Not only does he
refuse meat, but he doesn't even eat fish or sardines. With thanks
for your answer, The Worried Mother.
</P>
<P>
   A Bintel Brief: ``The mother is advised to find out where her
son got the idea to become a vegetarian, and then, with the help of
a specialist, she might be able to bring him back to eating
meat...A good doctor would know how to treat her 9-year-old
vegetarian.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 92 years since the following letter was written, nothing
has changed:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a girl from Galicia and in the shop where I work I sit
near a Russian Jew with whom I was always on good terms...But once,
in a short debate, he stated that all Galicians were no good, ...
and that he wished all Galician Jews dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Editor, does he really have a right to aay this7 And,
does he, the Russian, remain fine and intelligent in spite of such
expressions?''
</P>
<P>
   A Bintel Brief: ``The Galician Jews are just as good and bad as
people from other lands. If the Galicians must be ashamed of the
foolish and evil ones among them, then the Russians, too, must hide
their heads in shame because among them there is such an idiot as
the acquaintance of our letter writer.''
</P>
<P>
   For the new year I wish every reader peace, and I heartily
recommend ``A Bintel Brief: Sixty Years of Letters From the Lower
East Side to the Jewish Daily Forward,'' compiled and edited by
Isaac Metzker (Schocken Books, $12).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Karen De Crow is an attorney in Jamesville, N.Y.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
