<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAL-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SAYS HE WON'T BOYCOTT AIR CARRIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown said he would continue using
United Airlines unless the Board of Supervisors votes for a boycott
to protest the company's opposition to San Francisco's unmarried
partners law.
</P>
<P>
   The city's three gay supervisors and other gay community leaders
have urged people to avoid using the air carrier whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   United is challenging the ordinance that requires companies
doing business with the city to provide the same benefits to
workers with unmarried partners as they give to married employees.
</P>
<P>
   United joined a federal lawsuit filed in May 1997 by the Air
Transport Association, the trade group for the nation's biggest
airlines, seeking exemption from the ordinance, contending that
only the federal government could force such a requirement on the
industry. The case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Board of Supervisors has not voted for a boycott,
Board President Tom Ammiano and board members Leslie Katz and Mark
Leno joined other supporters of the domestic partners ordinance in
urging people to avoid United.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he knew nothing of that request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about a United boycott, who sponsored the boycott
or any of those things,'' he said. He added that his use of United
should in no way be construed as a waning commitment to his support
of equal rights for gays.
</P>
<P>
   He said he flew United to New York and back from Washington,
D.C., last week because it was the most convenient. United is the
largest airline at San Francisco International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   He said that if the Board of Supervisors made a boycott official
city policy, he would comply. That is unlikely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot be in a position of penalizing United because we're
in litigation,'' Katz said. ``To have an actual boycott would
subject the city to legal liability for attempting to curtail an
entity's legal right to challenge an ordinance. However, the city
can call United to task for its failure to accord its employees
basic dignity and respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
