r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-HN     02-03 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY GROUPS SUE OVER BERKELEY ADMISSIONS POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Five civil rights groups have filed a federal
lawsuit alleging that the undergraduate admissions process at the
University of California at Berkeley illegally discriminates
against minority students.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in the U.S. District Court in San
Francisco, said the process violates civil rights laws and has
unfairly denied entrance to more than 750 well-qualified black,
Filipino-American and Hispanic students.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint was brought on behalf of minority freshman
students who, according to the lawsuit, were forced to attend other
colleges around the country because of the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new admissions policies and practices have a totally
unjustified disparate impact on African-American, Latino and
(Filipino-) American applicants,'' said Joseph Jaramillo, a lawyer
with the Mexican American Legal Defense and Education Fund, one
group representing the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Mena, a Berkeley spokesman, declined to comment on the
lawsuit, saying university lawyers had not yet reviewed it.
However, he said campus officials had been working with the civil
rights groups ``side by side to ensure there is minority access to
higher education,'' and called it unfortunate that they had chosen
to sue.
</P>
<P>
   The university began admitting freshmen under the new policy for
its fall 1998 class. The policy was prompted by a resolution passed
by the board of regents in 1995 that barred admissions officers
from considering an applicant's race, gender or ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Ward Connerly was author of the resolution and is a key
force in fighting affirmative action, which he contends is a kind
of reverse discrimination. Connerly also headed the successful
campaign in 1996 to pass Proposition 209, the California ballot
inititiave that banned affirmative action throughout state and
local government.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who is black, said he had not seen the lawsuit but
defended Berkeley's admissions policy as fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't think that the university is engaged in
discrimination towards anyone or any group, because we apply the
same standards to everybody,'' he said. ``With preferences being
outlawed now, more than ever we're applying the same standards to
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that minority students simply needed better grades
to get into the prestigious school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they need to do a little more heavy lifting academically
to me more competitive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Paterson, the executive director of the the Lawyers'
Committee for Civil Rights, which helped bring the lawsuit,
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, affirmative action policies attempted to
compensate for some of the unfair components of the admissions
process,'' she said. ``In the absence of affirmative action, we are
simply left with a discriminatory system.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, in the fall of 1998, more than 750
minority applicants with grade point averages of 4.0 or better were
denied admission to the Berkeley campus. (Students who take
advanced placement courses may earn extra points and achieve a
maximum 5.0 grade point average.)
</P>
<P>
   While white students with 4.0 GPAs or better had a 48.2 percent
chance of admission, the lawsuit said, similarly qualified minority
students had less opportunity: Hispanic students had a 39.7 percent
chance; black students, a 38.5 percent chance; and
Filipino-American students, a 31.6 percent chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
