<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CUPID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CUPID' NEEDS AN ANGEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC lied. That shouldn't be a surprise to any veteran television
viewer. But the network really redefined the art when it canceled
``Cupid.''
</P>
<P>
   First, ABC said that it liked the show quite a bit and was
moving forward. Yes, the less-than-ringing endorsement from
entertainment president Jamie Tarses and entertainment chairman Stu
Bloomberg should have set off bells, but then there was the matter
of the ABC slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, great. ``Cupid'' was a highly acclaimed romantic comedy
and there aren't many of those around. Everything about the show
reeked of success _ except the ratings. ``Cupid'' just had that
feel, that look, that sense that it could not only be a hit but,
more importantly, be one of the few really good shows on network
television. Now that doesn't always guarantee a Top 20 finish in
the Nielsens, but if your motto is ``We Love TV,'' then ``Cupid''
is a show you keep.
</P>
<P>
   What ABC really should have said was, ``We Love Ratings.''
Because, like many modern networks, it didn't have a clue how to
take a great show and make it work. In the TV business, where bland
is the norm, when you get something of quality, it's first and
foremost a shock, then a gift. What are you going to do with it?
ABC decided to put it on Saturday nights at 10.
</P>
<P>
   That makes a lot of sense. A romantic comedy for lovers or
would-be lovers on a night when most of the target audience is out
trying to live the premise of the show. Brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that ABC was the same network that put David Kelley's
``The Practice'' on Saturday nights as well, which led to Mr. Can't
Miss TV telling critics he thought the move was dumb _ which
everybody but ABC knew anyway. Finally, Tarses and company tripped
or something, hit their collective heads and moved ``The Practice''
to a better time slot and not long after it got an Emmy for best
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Building on its luck _ and forced to create new shows because
everything else it had was miserable _ ABC developed a fairly
impressive schedule for this season.
</P>
<P>
   Along with ``Sports Night,'' ``The Hughleys,'' ``Whose Line Is
It Anyway?'' and some fluff on Fridays, ``Cupid'' gave the network
a lot of options. Despite critical acclaim and an Emmy-deserving
performance from Jeremy Piven, ratings for the show on Saturday
were in the tank. The network moved it to Thursdays and put it up
against ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, not exactly brilliant. It seems that ABC, suddenly flush
with some decent shows, has become cocky, like one of its best
shows can just be shunted away or given up for dead because the
scheduling pooh-bahs couldn't find a place for it. That's pretty
bold for a third-place network.
</P>
<P>
   ABC couldn't find a place for ``Cupid,'' but it has no trouble
giving up hour slots to the news division for more ``20/20''
overkill.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ABC's second idea of moving it to Thursday because of
a perceived weakening at NBC wasn't too far-fetched. But if you
want to topple the giant, then it takes patience and programming.
Surely ABC has more good shows in the works and with a couple of
quality new shows in the fall _ Kelley's upcoming ``Snoops'' might
be one _ there could be a takeover. But it won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ABC fumbled. And here's what it said about the cancellation:
```Cupid' has been a labor of love for everyone at ABC from the
very start. The writing was phenomenal, the production first-rate,
and the tremendous talent of its stars, Jeremy Piven and Paula
Marshall, really gave the show life. Unfortunately, despite
everyone's efforts, the audience just didn't respond.''
</P>
<P>
   What a complete cop-out. And if you're going to rave so
effusively about a show, you look stupid doing it at the funeral.
If ABC really believed in ``Cupid,'' really believed in its own
``We Love TV'' slogan, it would save the show. It would admit the
patently obvious scheduling blunders of its programmers and
restart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Somebody ought to save ``Cupid.'' No network _ including ABC _
has so many good shows that it doesn't need a little more depth.
Unfortunately, lack of patience, lack of vision and the continued
pervasiveness of ``newsmagazines'' all diminish the possibility of
saving ``Cupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the show are understandably outraged. They're seeing red
_ not ABC's ubiquitous yellow. They feel cheated and upset. And
they have a right to. But TV burns everyone at some point, because
it's a numbers game and emotions get tossed in the cruncher when
the numbers don't add up. Quality doesn't always _ in fact very
rarely _ equal ratings success.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no mistaking this: ``Cupid'' didn't die because
``the audience didn't respond,'' as ABC says. It's dead because ABC
let it happen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
