A0075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-HARVARD-BOS &LR;      02-03 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-HARVARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HONG KONG, HARVARD ALUMS LAMENT A BREACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In the clubby world of Hong Kong power brokers,
where money and contacts are everything and a Harvard pedigree has
more cachet than in Cambridge, Mass., Stephen Wai-wan Chik was not
just any Harvard graduate. He was the president of the Harvard
Alumni Club.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of the dynamic young financier, the club
began to attract big money for the university from a distant locale
brimming with rich and influential graduates. But something went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Chik, a 1986 economics graduate whom former friends describe as
an ambitious comer from a modest background, allegedly abused his
position as club president by siphoning half a million dollars into
his own accounts, according to a newly released club investigation
report and an independent audit.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday (Feb. 4), a year after Harvard informed club officers
that a donation of $333,333 had never reached Cambridge and that
Chik was ignoring phone calls, members of the 300-person club will
vote whether to sue him, pursue criminal charges, or do nothing.
Chik has returned almost 80 percent of the missing funds.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has rocked the Hong Kong club, sparking accusations
that an old-boy network shielded Chik during a prolonged and
secretive investigation, and that lax oversight and cozy ties among
club leaders allowed the transgression to occur. The disgrace also
comes at an inopportune time for Harvard, just as its business
school is establishing a center here and as the university is
expanding its programs and fund-raising efforts in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the sad tale of one promising man's fall from grace are
the larger questions of how clubs based on trust can police
themselves, and how Harvard can oversee far-flung groups or stop
alumni from misusing benefits and donations that a prestige college
attracts.
</P>
<P>
   The club ``had become very much an organization that (Chik)
operated for his own advantage. At the same time, it became larger
and more effective under Steve's leadership,'' said Robert Neer, a
1986 history graduate who headed the committee that traced missing
money. ``But people have many reasons for belonging to alumni
clubs, and not all of them are altruistic.''
</P>
<P>
   For a university that doggedly raises more money than any other
in the world, the scandal damages credibilty in a rare place in
recession-hit Asia where alumni still have cash to give. Harvard is
by far the most famous and respected university in China, and
locals worry that a drop in donations _ to some extent the unspoken
quid pro quo for Harvard's expansion here _ could knock Hong Kong
and China off Harvard's priority list.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni and university officials play down that fear, saying that
one person cannot destroy Harvard's reputation. But they caution
that Hong Kong's club, like Harvard's 160 alumni clubs worldwide,
needs to install checks and balances and avoid the perception that
it coddles members who have done wrong.
</P>
<P>
   All clubs should probably consider new standards, said John P.
Reardon Jr., executive director of the Harvard Alumni Association.
The richest clubs, in New York and Boston, have audits and business
managers. But ``you can set up a lot of structures, and what if
people set out to be dishonest?''
</P>
<P>
   Reardon said he knows of no similar incidents in other clubs,
but he added that most clubs ``are not in a situation where they
have much money anyone could walk away with. . . . Hong Kong's club
_ in Steve Chik times _ had started to bring in real money.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether to sue Chik for $107,810 of
still-missing funds is also linked to concern about his ability to
pay up. Chik's company, Pacific Asia Group, is facing liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated efforts to reach Chik were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Some alumni complain that club officers fast learned that Chik
had taken sole control of bank accounts and removed money, but the
investigation dragged on and meeting minutes were kept secret.
Officers say they were treating Chik as innocent until proven
guilty and needed to collect facts. They also wanted to save the
university and club from bad publicity or a defamation suit.
</P>
<P>
   It was a delicate matter _ whether to go after a fellow alumnus.
Besides Chik had wowed people with his energy and he had formed
friendships with Hong Kong's movers and shakers.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Financial Secretary Donald Tsang and Home Affairs
Secretary Shelley Lau, both Kennedy School of Government alumni,
were godparents for Chik and his fiancee at their joint baptism,
though Lau says she is godmother to a lot of people. Futures
Exchange Commission chief Geoffrey Yeh, a member of an alumni
committee that advised on the Chik affair, spoke at Chik's
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Tan, a Graduate School of Design alumnus who was elected
president after Chik was deposed, was a junior college classmate of
Chik's in Singapore and best man at his wedding. Tan says they
``were never close,'' and he denies any conflict in his presiding
over the club while Chik was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Former treasurer Yun Ed Wong, a 1989 graduate with a doctorate
in geophysics, was an employee of Chik's when Chik asked him to
cosign a blank transfer note from club accounts. Wong says he
``trusted him too much. But it was a club, and I thought we were
supposed to trust each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of mainland Chinese parents, Chik is described by other
alumni as well-dressed, personable, and well-spoken, ``the jewel of
his family,'' and a man ``with executive polish.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabrina Fang, a 1988 graduate who was briefly club secretary
last year, complains that ``people who have been friends with Steve
for years'' are partly responsible for not checking bank statements
and for letting him hold the only key to the postal box. ``Everyone
is too concerned about protecting everyone else instead of being
concerned with the members' right to know,'' Fang said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers insist they were not protecting Chik, but rather were
trying to recover as much money as possible through the influence
of senior alumni with whom Chik considered himself close, such as
Trade Development Council chairman Victor Fung.
</P>
<P>
   Roderick MacFarqhuar, a government professor who knew Chik as
the energetic student president of the Hong Kong Club at Harvard,
acknowledges Chik may have later capitalized on Harvard's name in a
place where ``guanxi'' _ Chinese for ``connections'' _ is king. But
``the old-boy network and `guanxi' are hardly the invention of the
Harvard Club of Hong Kong,'' MacFarquhar said.
</P>
<P>
   Neer contends that the Asian ``recession will probably hurt Hong
Kong's fund-raising efforts here more than Steve Chik's
activities,'' adding that the upside is that it ``energized people
to get things done and make sure it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Popular as Chik once was, only one of the many alumni
interviewed said he still considers himself Chik's friend. ``I
would not give up on him,'' said Reuben Mondejar, a 1988 graduate
who specialized in international studies and who was club vice
president under Chik.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man has a lot of raw talent,'' Mondejar said. ``I think he
can be resurrected. But I think it would be very difficult for him
to be resurrected here in Hong Kong. Everyone knows him already. He
was very visible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
