<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0078 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-03 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY BLACK ATHLETES LACK A SOCIAL CONSCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spiked dog collar Ray Buchanan wore around his neck early
last week before the Super Bowl was meant as a cartoon joke to
symbolize the underdog status of his Atlanta Falcons against the
Denver Broncos. In the overdog's camp, Shannon Sharpe boasted that
he so thoroughly destroyed opposing teams that ``I've got a guy
suspended. I got a guy cut. One coach resigned. Another thought
about resigning. I'm pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the barking, up to the level of hiring and firing in the
National Football League, there is one subject that makes the fangs
of these and a host of African-American players drop from their
gums and clatter to the ground in a useless heap: The failure to
hire black head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   New York Times columnist Bill Rhoden brought this up at the big
game. The NFL has had 24 straight head coaching changes with no new
African-American faces. The NFL is 72 percent African-American in
players, but 90 percent white in head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   That question reduced these warriors who risk ruptured disks
into snivels and spineless sweats. Buchanan said, ``I don't want to
talk about that right now. It's too controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the players don't want to upset the coaches or the
owners because they are playing for them,'' said Ray Crockett of
the Broncos. ``If we put ourselves out there, our names on the
line, and there's still a bunch of white coaches out there, of
course you're intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to keep our comments to a minimum because _ not that
we're scared _ there's nothing we can do,'' said Cornelius Bennett
of the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the dog collar is no longer a joke. The spikes take
on the weight of the iron that bound the necks of Buchanan's
ancestors. The fear strips them naked of their championships and
their millions of dollars. As incongruous is the thought of a
millionaire slave, they are here before us, so powerful, so
flamboyant, so rich, yet so docile, so scared and so easily prone
to ``yessum, boss'' as to make one wretch.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no lack of African-American coaches if the
players threatened to walk off the field. No other group of
African-Americans is in such a position to strike for fairness.
African-American athletes in team sports earn at least $2 billion a
year, revenues that would place them near the Fortune 500. Yet,
they are a collective shame.
</P>
<P>
   While thousands of people of color with no clout risk their life
savings suing for job discrimination, black athletes so fear
offending white fans that Michael Jordan would not campaign openly
for Harvey Gantt against one of the most racist of US senators,
Jesse Helms. Jordan, also a sellout on sweatshop labor for Nike,
said he couldn't campaign because Republicans buy shoes, too.
</P>
<P>
   The cowardice is hardly new. In 1992, I watched the teeth fall
from the gums when I asked the same question of the Chicago Bulls
and Portland Trail Blazers before their National Basketball
Association finals. Several players would not comment, with one
saying he did not want to be seen as ``inciting something.''
</P>
<P>
   The only player who would speak was Craig Hodges of the Bulls.
Within weeks after uttering these remarks, Hodges was mysteriously
cut by the Bulls:
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine the instant impact we could have had if, say,
we had walked off the court and said, `We want justice for Rodney
King?' Somebody asked M.J. (Jordan) what he thought about Rodney
King. Mike said, `I need to know more about it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on. Maybe you do not have to comment on the specifics,
but at least you can say something in general about injustice to
black people. It's war out there. The owners understand only one
thing _ money. They will only change if they know we are willing to
make a sacrifice. If we did not play, the owners would raise hell,
finding black folks to hire.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of raising hell, black athletes are content on the
plantation, living proof of the observation of slavery historian
Kenneth Stampp that the mark of a broken slave was one who was
lowered to a condition of ``raw fear,'' ``unconditional
submission,'' and ``perfect dependence.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rhoden asked John Mobley of the Broncos if star players
such as Sharpe (who has a three-year, $7.5 million contract) or
Terrell Davis ($56.1 million, 9 years) would come to a meeting to
discuss the lack of African-American head coaches, Mobley said,
``They probably wouldn't even want to sit down and discuss it if
they knew what the topic was about. They'd think it was really
something silly. It probably wouldn't even get touched.''
</P>
<P>
   The ignorance of Davis was as frightful as the raw fear.
Offering no clue why black coaches were ignored, he said, ``So what
should I do, say `where are the black coaches?' without having any
earthly idea about what I'm talking about?
</P>
<P>
   With such comments, today's black athletes are millionaires as
bereft of consciousness as were their ancestors of freedom. They
are so vacant, Buchanan never knew the true meaning of his collar.
It was not a joke. It was a symbol of his enslaved mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
