<HEADER>
A0079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-03 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING, AND LOSING AT AGEMANSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently suffered a birthday, my 45th. I'm fine, thanks. God
tricked me by sending me good health (knock on wood) and much
happiness. It wasn't what I thought I wanted, but considering the
alternatives, I'm quite content.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to my birthday, I conducted a modest
research project. While scanning the newspapers, I picked out the
names of men and women my age to see where I stood relative to my
chronological peers. I enlisted my children's help, and it was with
no small amount of glee that my 12-year-old recently announced that
Oprah Winfrey, arguably the best-known journalist in the
English-speaking world, was my age.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what of it? I have no beef with Oprah, who's done even
more for literate writers in America than the Clinton-Lewinsky Walt
Whitman revival. And I maintain a stiff upper lip when reading that
my contemporary Condoleezza Rice is retiring from the third of
three successful careers, first as a Soviet expert, then a National
Security Council aide, and now as the provost at Stanford
University. (Dennis Eckersley just retired from one successful
career at 44.) Comparing lives with Rice, who is also a
concert-quality pianist, prompts me to paraphrase Tom Lehrer's
wistful observation that by the time Mozart was my age, he had been
dead for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a man thing, reading an article about some newly
minted Internet trillionaire and praying that he or she is as old
as . . . 32. Not bloody likely. Hartford talk show host Colin
McEnroe, 44, admits he reads newspapers the same way. Pundit
Michael Kinsley, 47, wrote a funny essay a few years ago upon
realizing that a man roughly his age had become president. This
wasn't a problem for me; I was only 38 when Bill Clinton took
office.
</P>
<P>
   So, on to the 44-year-olds. There's writer Jon Krakauer and
actress Kirstie Alley. The arithmetic mean of the many ages
proclaimed by actress Melanie Griffith seems to be about 44. Dennis
Quaid is 44, as is Kevin Costner. Actress Kim Zimmer and rock
musician Michael Schenker of the Scorpions are also 44, whoever and
wherever they are.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Wall Street Journal profiled a 44-year-old rock
musician named Jack Kidney, who, unlike Mr. Schenker, does not get
his name included in celebrity birthday lists. Jack and his older
brother Robert have been playing in their Numbers Band for nigh on
30 years, hoping to break through into the big time. Numbers was
hot in the 1970s; their bass player even made it into Devo.
(Remember Devo?) But, while dedicated, the Kent, Ohio-based Kidneys
are not hot. ``Kids want to buy the records of artists they
perceive as their peers,'' an industry mogul told the Journal. ``My
advice to (the Kidneys) is to get a day job.''
</P>
<P>
   I have a day job. Maybe I should stop complaining. But look at
the new chief financial officer of Boeing., Deborah Hopkins. She is
44, and Boeing's youngest senior executive. Likewise the vice
chairman of Barnes &AMP; Noble, Stephen Riggio, is 44. In Boston, the
famously press-shy husband and wife real estate developers Frank
and Jamie McCourt are 44. As is America's Internet investing
champion, David Wetherell, the chief executive of the conglomerate
CMG of Andover, Mass. An early investor in such hypergrowth
companies as Lycos and GeoCities, Wetherell and his company are
worth a great deal of money. But neither he nor the McCourts nor I
approach the net worth of Microsoft's Bill Gates, a mere stripling
at 43.
</P>
<P>
   Did you see the Atlanta Falcons' backup quarterback Steve DeBerg
prowling the sidelines at the Super Bowl? He just turned 45, and he
looked decrepit! Thirty-eight-year-old John Elway, who's thinking
of retiring, called DeBerg ``ancient.'' Do I look like that? No
doubt I look considerably worse.
</P>
<P>
   Does life begin at 45? I don't know. Happily it rarely ends at
45. I kept a weather eye on the obituary notices while preparing
this column, but spotted no contemporaries. Where's that hill they
keep talking about? Am I over it yet? Oh, never mind . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
