<HEADLINE>
FIGHT TO BOLSTER SOCIAL SECURITY GOES PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When payday rolls around, a glimpse at the pay stub
can be a painful reminder that Social Security takes a big bite out
of wages. About 145 million Americans pay the retirement tax, which
cuts 6.2 percent from most salaries, and 12.4 percent from people
who are self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   But a tiny minority of about 5 million workers pays no Social
Security taxes. Most are police officers, firefighters, teachers
and other government employees. While the rest of America takes
shelter under the broad Social Security tent, which is now sagging
from financial strains, these public employees are camped out in
retirement systems of their own, many of which are stable and
financially healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as lawmakers try to shore up Social Security, a political
battle is brewing to force all new public employees out of their
own plans and into the national retirement system. The move would
raise some much-needed cash, at least in the short term. But
neither the workers, nor their government employers, want them to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has more at stake in the debate than any state but
Ohio. At least 86 percent of Massachusetts public employees are
covered by retirement plans other than Social Security. That
amounts to more than 400,000 workers, retirees and other
beneficiaries, who belong to 106 separate public employee
retirement systems in the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   Four bills before Congress would force all new public employees
into Social Security. In each bill, the change is part of a broader
proposal to delay financial problems in Social Security, which has
promised trillions of dollars more in benefits than it can raise in
tax revenues. By one calculation, from economists Henry Aaron and
Robert Reischauer of the Brookings Institution in Washington, D.C.,
moving new public employees into the system would make up 12
percent of the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   The change is a matter of fairness, Aaron and Reischauer
contend. Public employees have had a good deal at the expense of
everyone else, they say, and the nation can no longer afford that
to continue.
</P>
<P>
   But public employees and their allies argue that the change
would cut their benefits dramatically while raising costs for local
government. Given the tight budgets in place under Proposition 2
1/2 in Massachusetts, for instance, cities and towns would have to
cut essential police and fire services to pay the higher retirement
costs, say advocates for public employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a matter of public safety,'' says Thomas
Lussier, executive director of the Massachusetts Teachers'
Retirement Board, which oversees the state's second-largest public
employee retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how a tiny portion of the work force formed its own
retirement niche started early in the century. Long before Congress
made retirement security a priority, several states took up the
idea. The Massachusetts Legislature created the system for teachers
in 1914, 21 years before President Franklin Roosevelt signed Social
Security into law.
</P>
<P>
   Public employers continued to create separate retirement plans,
as Social Security at first specifically excluded state and local
government workers. At the time, legal specialists questioned
whether the federal government could compel states to pay a federal
tax, though the presumption today is that it can.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, a series of legal changes allowed more public workers
into Social Security, but many opted to remain separate.
</P>
<P>
   The law for many years allowed public employees to draw from
both retirement systems, a feature that holds political
implications. A teacher might work 25 years and then start a new
career, or a state office worker might take a second job just to
become eligible for Social Security. On retirement, they could draw
benefits from Social Security and from their public employee
system.
</P>
<P>
   And in many cases, Aaron says, the Social Security benefit would
be far greater than the taxes the worker paid in. ``This is one
reason why we have problems today,'' he said. While the rules
tightened up on these windfalls about two decades ago, ``some of
the unfunded liablity in Social Security is directly traceable to
the employees of states who are outside of the Social Security
system,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fairness, Aaron believes, public employees should
help make up the shortfall caused by their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he notes, a key feature of Social Security is that it
redistributes money from wealthier workers to low-income earners.
Public employees tend to earn more than the average worker, he
argues, but they do not fulfill their ``responsibility'' for
covering the nation's commitment to low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be universal participation in Social Security,''
echoes Bradley Belt of the Center for Strategic and International
Studies which sponsored a panel that studied the retirement
program. ``It's a slippery slope: If you make the case for some
employees to be out of the system, why not make the case for a
broader group?''
</P>
<P>
   To many public employees, however, these arguments are far
removed from the real world of work.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, public employees pay between 5 percent and
more than 9 percent of earnings into their retirement system,
depending on when they were hired and other factors. That means
many workers pay more than the 6.2 percent Social Security tax.
</P>
<P>
   But they generally don't mind, claims Kenneth Donnelly,
secretary-treasurer of the Professional Firefighters of
Massachusetts, an organization of 185 unions. In most cases, the
benefits are far better in the public employees' systems than in
Social Security, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem is on the employers' side. Local and state
governments pay between 2 percent and 4 percent of payroll into the
employees' retirement systems. That is far below the 6.2 percent
employers must pay under Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   If required to pay 6.2 percent for each worker, Massachusetts
cities, towns and public employers would have to come up with an
additional $210 million to $500 million each year, one state
retirement agency estimates. And that money would go to a system
that offers fewer benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Donnelly says, firefighters, police officers and other
public safety workers would demand that cities and towns buy them
supplemental insurance to cover features that Social Security does
not.
</P>
<P>
   Police and firefighters in Massachusetts can retire at age 55,
partly because of their shorter life expectancies and partly due to
the physical demands of their jobs. Social Security does not pay
even partial benefits until age 62.
</P>
<P>
   Morever, disability and survivor benefits are better in many
public employee systems than in Social Security. If those benefits
were reduced, employers might have a harder time filling jobs that
put a worker in harm's way, say public employees' advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lieutenant in the Lexington Fire Department,'' Donnelly
says. ``I have a wife and three children. We go into burning
buildings and on the highways and expose ourselves to risk, but we
don't have to worry that our families will be provided for. That
shouldn't be taken away.'' Finally, say Donnelly and Lussier,
public retirement systems are counting on payments from future
workers to cover benefits for people already in the system.
Stripping out new workers would cripple the finances of these
retirement plans, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   Public employees have begun a lobbying campaign to block the
proposed changes. They fear that the pressure to repair Social
Security is so great that their concerns will be traded away during
the search to find a political compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Early lobbying targets have included Senator John Breaux,
Democrat of Louisiana, and Representative Charles Stenholm,
Democrat of Texas. Both have sponsored bills to move new public
employees into Social Security, but they are also from states where
many public workers belong to their own retirement systems.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John Kerry has sponsored briefings on Capitol Hill for
Massachusetts public workers and employers to make their case to
congressional aides. Through a spokesman, Kerry said that any
changes to Social Security law must ensure that ``the benefits of
retired and current Massachusetts public employees are fully
safeguarded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I hope they notice is that we have management and
labor together on this issue,'' says Donnelly. ``It's a funny kind
of alliance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
