<HEADLINE>
THIS JUVENILE WON'T BE THE ANSWER IN THE DERBY, EITHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the Breeders' Cup began in 1984, no winner of the $1
million Juvenile has captured the Kentucky Derby the following
year. After the way Juvenile champion Answer Lively ran Saturday,
it is highly unlikely the jinx will be broken this year.
</P>
<P>
   A son of Lively One, out of Twosies Answer, a sprinter who ran
in New England, Answer Lively won four of his seven starts as a
2-year-old. Naturally gifted with speed, Answer Lively came into
the Juvenile at Churchill Downs last Nov. 7 off a narrow loss to
Cat Thief in the Breeders' Futurity at Keeneland, in which Cat
Thief caught him in the last jump. Churchill was playing to speed
at the time, and Answer Lively became the darling of the figure
players. He was bet down to the 5-2 favorite under Robby Albarado
and did not disappoint his backers, holding on gamely to tally by a
head over Aly's Alley, with Cat Thief third.
</P>
<P>
   The Breeders' Cup Juvenile is run at 1 1/16 miles, and those who
had seen Towsie's Answer race 5 furlongs on the grass at Suffolk
Downs knew it was doubtful that Answer Lively would be successful
at the 1 1/4-mile distance of the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Answer Lively made his 3-year-old debut in the
$100,000 Lecomte Handicap at Fair Grounds, where he is based for
owner John Franks and trainer Bobby Barnett. Answer Lively was the
highweight at 122 pounds, giving away 4-11 pounds to the rest of
the field, but the Lecomte is only a mile, a distance perfectly
suited for him.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence that Answer Lively frightens no one, a full field of
14 went in the Lecomte. Even though he was stuck out in post No.
11, Answer Lively was made the 1-2 favorite. When the gates opened,
he was outrun for the lead by a group of horses inside him, and it
was basically over. He tried to rally from the outside turning for
home but had no late kick and finished seventh. The winner, Some
Actor, was 42-1, and he was followed under the wire by a 22-1 shot
and a 10-1 shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little wide, but that was no concern,'' said Albarado.
``At the three-eighths pole, I called on him for a little response
and he lacked it. He wasn't there for me. I wish I could come up
with a better excuse. He pulled up super. He hit the ground fine
and was nice and smooth the whole way. There was just nothing
there.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Eclipse Awards dinner Feb. 16, Answer Lively will be
named best 2-year-old colt of 1998, but you can bet he's not going
to win the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helping the cause
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Handicap was helped when Puerto Madero and
Behrens finished ahead of 4-5 favorite Silver Charm in the $500,000
Donn Handicap at Gulfstream Park Saturday. Trainer Richard
Mandella, who has Puerto Madero, and trainer Jim Bond, who has
Behrens, have supported the MassCap in the past. Puerto Madero ran
second to Skip Away in last year's edition, and Bond sent up Will's
Way to run third to Skip Away in 1997. Bond would have entered
Behrens last year, but the horse was not doing well at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very happy with the outcome of the race,'' said
Suffolk vice president Lou Raffetto. ``A lot of local people were
rooting for Puerto Madero because of his performance behind Skip
Away last year. Puerto Madero could easily become the next `Suffolk
horse,' popular here, as were Cigar and Skip Away. Both Richard and
Jim want a reason to come back. I'm very encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffetto is preparing to make recruiting stops in Florida and
California. He'll be in Florida for the Eclipse dinner, which is in
Coral Gables, and he'll visit Gulfstream and Payson Park, where
several of the top trainers are stabled. Then he'll head to Santa
Anita for the $1 million Big 'Cap March 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a good spot,'' said Raffetto. ``Now we just have to
work hard and hope to get lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from the Daily Racing Form and from publicity departments
at tracks was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
