<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLIER TREATMENT NEEDED FOR WOMEN, AIDS PANEL TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ American women infected with the AIDS virus are not
getting antiviral drugs early enough, a leading specialist on women
and AIDS said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Women have 20 percent less AIDS virus in their blood than men at
any given stage of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection and
the immune-system damage it causes, Dr. Katherine Anastos of
Catholic Medical Centers in New York City reported at the Sixth
Conference on Retroviruses.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of virus in patients' blood is the main signal for
doctors to begin treatment. Thus, official treatment guidelines,
which were based on the course of the disease in men, are causing
women to begin treatment later than they should, Anastos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The treatment guidelines may need to be adjusted,'' she told
colleagues, ``to lower the treatment threshold by 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Anastos' conclusion is based on the largest study thus far on
gender differences in HIV disease, based on 1,268 women and 1,604
men. Previous studies, such as one published last year, had
suggested as much as a 50 percent male-female disparity _ that is,
women showed severe immune damage at half the blood virus levels
seen in men with similar damage.
</P>
<P>
   Anastos' proposed revision would expand the numbers of women
needing antiviral treatments by only 2 to 5 percent. Even though
that's not a large fraction, she said, ``it's an important issue''
for individual women whose treatment is delayed.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 52,000 American women with diagnosed AIDS and
another 150,000 or so who are thought to carry HIV without having
progressed to AIDS. Federal estimates place the total number of
infected Americans at 650,000 to 900,000.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   One day in November, 1989, a teenager and three men ranging in
age from their 50s to their 70s got infected with the AIDS virus at
a dermatology clinic in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The virus came not from a health care worker, as in the
notorious case of a Florida dentist who apparently infected six
patients in the late 1980s, but from another patient at the clinic.
The apparent cause was a failure to sterilize equipment used in the
five surgical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, an Australian researcher presented conclusive evidence
here that all four patients got the virus from the same patient on
the same day. Nitin Saksena of the University of Sydney said the
proof came from the virus's distinctive genetic ``signature'' in
three of its genes.
</P>
<P>
   Because HIV evolves so rapidly, there was no way the four
patients' virus could have matched unless they had all become
infected on the same day, Saksena said in an interview. For legal
reasons, he said, no sample was available from the patient who
began the chain of infection, a homosexual man who subsequently
died of AIDS. One of the four accidentally infected patients has
died of AIDS and the other three remain well.
</P>
<P>
   Saksena said he knew of no other documented case of
patient-to-patient HIV infection through contaminated medical
equipment. Neither did Dr. Harold Jaffe, director of the AIDS/HIV
laboratory at the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe said patients' risk of being infected this way is
apparently tiny, ``but there's always the possibility our
surveillance could miss rare cases.'' The Australian episode, he
added, underscores the critical importance of good
infection-control techniques.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive new drug treatments against HIV often reduce the
virus in patients' blood to undetectable levels, so public health
officials have hoped that the risk of sexual transmission would be
eliminated too. But evidence is mounting that individuals whose HIV
is successfully repressed still harbor the virus in genital
secretions.
</P>
<P>
   Of 70 Brazilian patients under antiviral treatment, one-quarter
still had HIV in their semen after six months of treatment, even
when none could be detected in their blood, Dr. Paulo Barroso of
the Federal University of Rio de Janeiro reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roger Pomerantz of Thomas Jefferson University in
Philadelphia reported on Monday that he has found HIV in genital
secretions of both men and women despite apparent viral clearance
from the bloodstream. The message is, treated patients and their
sexual partners should not assume they can't pass the virus on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US blood supply is increasingly safe, with the risk of HIV
contamination now no larger than one unit of blood in every
half-million. But a new study of first-time blood donors, who make
up about 20 percent of all donors, shows their blood is 2.5 times
more likely to contain HIV than repeat donors.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing problem is that infected individuals may donate
blood before their immune systems have begun to generate
antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael P. Busch of the Blood Center of the Pacific in San
Francisco said the study found 427 HIV-infected blood donors among
1.8 million individuals giving blood for the first time. US blood
banks will soon begin using a new genetic screening test, primarily
to detect blood containing the hepatitis C virus, a leading cause
of liver failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope the new screening tests will prevent blood
transmission (of HIV) completely,'' Busch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
