<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DSS DESERVES CELLUCCI'S REPLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Change the date, and the letter to Paul Cellucci could have been
written Tuesday, not nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Child welfare and human service groups and organizations are
busy making recommendations to you about key candidates for
Commissioner of the Department of Social Services,'' Jetta Bernier,
the executive director of the Massachusetts Committee for Children
and Youth, wrote to the lieutenant governor-elect on Dec. 13, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We write to urge you to defer filling the position at this
early phase and to set a more critical priority _ that of
developing a process to define how Massachusetts will take on the
challenge to reform its child welfare and social services system.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cellucci never replied.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a decade later, Cellucci is governor and the state's
child protection agency is as adrift as ever. Once again, a
``nationwide search'' is under way for someone to lead a department
whose mission is no better defined than it was when he and Governor
William Weld took office in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It is past time to stop and take stock of DSS.
</P>
<P>
   The department has sometimes seemed like a bottomless well of
scandal and mismanagement. The so-called House of Horrors in
Everett, where five children were found living in squalor last
week, is only the most recent example.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's response to revelations that DSS had ignored repeated
reports from teachers and others about the neglect the children in
Everett were suffering is typical of the crisis-driven management
that has characterized his approach to child protection. He
suspended the social worker on the case and her supervisor, without
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Is a reactive policy of assigning blame and moving on supposed
to calm an outraged public or comfort the vulnerable families who
rely on DSS to protect children from abuse and neglect?
</P>
<P>
   Is hanging a couple of overworked social workers out to dry
supposed to exonerate the Cellucci administration for failing to
develop a substantive, coherent approach to child protection?
</P>
<P>
   Is it only those on the front lines _ caseworkers earning
starting salaries of $23,900 _ who are to be held accountable for
the failures of DSS?
</P>
<P>
   When DSS Commissioner Linda Carlisle recently announced that she
would be leaving the post she has held for six years, she actually
claimed to be resigning because she had accomplished all she had
set out to do.
</P>
<P>
   Only days later, the Committee for Children and Youth, a
private, nonprofit group that has advocated for vulnerable children
for 40 years, issued its findings that fewer than one in four
families reported for abuse or neglect are even offered support
services by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers are expected to function as one-person
interdisciplinary teams. They are not psychiatric nurses, but they
are expected to understand psychotropic drugs. They are not
substance abuse counselors, but they are expected to cope with
alcoholism. They are not experts in sexual abuse or domestic
violence but they are expected to protect children who suffer both
plagues.
</P>
<P>
   This is DSS at its peak performance?
</P>
<P>
   Social workers for the agency, long at odds with the
Weld-Cellucci administrations about the size of caseloads, the lack
of training and the need for more integrated services for children
and their families, resorted to gallows humor this week to endure
the scapegoating that, more and more, has become part of their job
description.
</P>
<P>
   In a mock employment advertisement, one social worker described
the qualities DSS looks for in a valued employee. ``Extraordinary
stamina, emotional and physical,'' she wrote. ``Ability to
withstand verbal abuse, threats of physical abuse and occasional
physical abuse, as well as disdain from the public in general, the
press, the politicians and occasionally other helping
professionals, including the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, and perhaps most importantly, she wrote, applicants for
jobs with the state's child protection agency should have ``no
expectation of loyalty from bureaucratic and political systems.''
</P>
<P>
   She got that right.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nine years since members of the child advocacy
community reached out to Paul Cellucci. It is long past time he
answered their letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
