<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0094 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-03 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROOT OF ALL EVIL AND GOOD: HORSERADISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since my grosspa taught me how to dig up the gnarled roots
and grate them till we laughed and cried _ he laughed while I cried
_ I suspected there was some earthy magic in horseradish.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the strange plants in my great-grandfather's garden, the
Meerrettich _ ``sea radish,'' which must be a cryptic Germanic
reference to sea of tears _ was the only one we dared not filch.
(Now there's a word that has atrophied into dictionary dust ...
means mini-misdemeanor level theft, such as filching an apple from
Mr. Carter's tree. I saw a man only last week take a shelled nut
from a bulk barrel in the local Safeway produce department and pop
it into his mouth. Legally, that's probably theft. But it's really
filching, which is basically what the neighborhood beat cop was
doing when he took an apple from the Grocerland's sidewalk
display.)
</P>
<P>
   Which strays somewhat from Grosspa's garden, a goodly part of
which was given over to this strange root, which resembled a
parsnip on steroids and tasted like ... well, like something you
wouldn't on a double-dog dare filch and try to nibble.
</P>
<P>
   Which no doubt has something to do with a report that
horseradish can protect you from E. coli, listeria, Staphylococcus
aureus and other nasty food pathogens. Scientists at Oklahoma State
University and the federal Agricultural Research Service discovered
what my great-grandfather already knew:
</P>
<P>
   Something in horseradish can kill bad microbes and germs. Which
seems, by extrapolation, to make sense, since any substantial
helping of horseradish is likely to kill whoever eats it. Or, at
very least, make them wish they had died suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   No telling from the news reports just how the scientists
researched this, but if they're alive to tell about it, we have to
assume they worked with samples no larger than what the average guy
puts on his corned beef sandwich or prime rib or grilled bratwurst.
Apparently, both horseradish and mustard oil contain the pungent
oil allyl isothiocyanate (which is worth italics just so's you know
I'm not simply drawing my finger across the keyboard).
</P>
<P>
   This chemical _ about 93 percent concentration in mustard oil
and 60 percent in horseradish _ helps kill, injure, maim or
otherwise render impotent those nasty germs and viruses that hide
out in our food with premeditated deadly intent to send us directly
to the bathroom or the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, as I noted, too much horseradish can do the same
thing. My father introduced me to Industrial Strength Horseradish
in a place called Slowik's, a workingman's restaurant and bar with
reception halls. The Bohemian joint at the angular junction of
Belmont and Milwaukee avenues was known for its weekday
workingman's lunch, and I followed my dad to the bar, where we each
ordered a beer and a smoked pork butt sandwich on rye.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the draft Michelob came in thick glass schooners known as
``goldfish bowls,'' which, in truth, were large enough for a great
white shark. And the smoked pork butt sandwiches were truly tasty
and huge. ``You want some of our horseradish wit dat?'' the
bartender asked me, all the while smiling at my father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure!'' says The Kid, bellying up to the bar and wanting more
than anything to eat and drink elbow-to-elbow with my dad. So the
bartender sticks a wooden paddlelike thing in the horseradish jar
and slides it down the bar so it stops about ]-inch from my
sandwich. ``You might wanna go li'l easy on dat stuff ... it's
sorta strong,'' he says, turning away as if to wash some glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``H---! I grew up eating horseradish!'' I said confidently,
filling the wooden paddle with about a teaspoon of the white stuff
and spreading it across my sandwich. I took a big bite and began
chewing.
</P>
<P>
   In the big back-bar mirror, I could see my father watching me.
And about the same time molten steel went down my throat and fire
belched out like an old Bessemer blast furnace, my dad put his arm
around me so I wouldn't collapse backward off the bar stool.
</P>
<P>
   My eyes were tearing. I couldn't breathe in, because that made
the fire go deeper into my chest and through my nose like a red-hot
rebar. If you've ever been Maced or tear-gassed, you have some idea
what Slowik's horseradish can do. ``Take some beer ... quick, but
not too much!'' said the smiling bartender.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my boy!'' my father said, almost proudly, smiling back.
The bartender wiped his hands on his white apron and extended a
beefy paw over the bar. ``Name's Matt Slowik,'' he said, crushing
my hand as I continued to gasp for air. ``Drink up and I'll buy you
a fresh one, on the house.''
</P>
<P>
   The Slowiks already knew _ 40 some years ago _ and my
great-grandfather years before that, what the Oklahoma State U. and
federal scientists just learned: This horseradish stuff is good for
what ails you, if it don't kill you first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
