<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0096 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-03 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO PUT ZEAL IN JOHNSON'S IMPEACHMENT? BUTLER DID IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One was elected governor of Massachusetts and
ran for president. Three went to the Senate. One almost became vice
president. Another would become Treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the 13 impeachment managers pursuing William Jefferson
Clinton face uncertain political futures. In 1868, the seven
managers of the impeachment of Andrew Johnson prospered at the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   History's verdict does not always validate the decisions of the
ballot box. ``Altogether the impeachment of Johnson was one of the
most disgraceful and vulgar episodes in the history of the federal
government,'' Henry Steele Commager and Samuel Eliot Morison wrote
in ``The Growth of the American Republic.'' The historians called
the impeachment managers ``unscrupulous parliamentarians who
exhausted every device, appealed to every prejudice and passion,
and rode roughshod over every legal obstacle in their ruthless
attempt to punish the president for his opposition to their
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachers thrived because editorial and emotional opinion
in the nation was proimpeachment, but most scholars today call the
major impeachment article against Johnson unconstitutional. After
Congress passed a law forbidding the president from dismissing a
Cabinet officer, Johnson fired Secretary of War Edwin Stanton.
Congress did not wait for Supreme Court clarification but impeached
Johnson, who had become president after the assassination of
Abraham Lincoln in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost from the time when the blood of Lincoln was warm on the
floor of Ford's Theatre, Andrew Johnson was contemplating
treason,'' John A. Logan of Illinois said on the House floor. Logan
later went to the Senate and was the Republican VP candidate in
1884.
</P>
<P>
   Even more extreme was Thaddeus Stevens of Pennsylvania. In his
dying months, Stevens pursued Johnson on the House floor, calling
him a ``wretched man'' and ``pettifogging political trickster.''
After the president's acquittal, he said, ``The only recourse from
intolerable tyranny is Brutus's dagger.'' In 1864, Stevens had
called Lincoln too soft on the South, rejecting ``malice toward
none'' in favor of punishing the defeated Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   In one of history's twists, in 1977, Jimmy Carter of Georgia,
the first Southern politician elected president since the Civil
War, fulfilled a campaign promise by enrolling his 9-year-old
daughter in the District of Columbia schools. Amy Carter attended
Thaddeus Stevens Elementary School, named after a man who once
demanded, ``Some proper pain must be inflicted on the people who
constituted the Confederate States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Franklin Butler of Massachusetts had a pinball career
in politics, beginning as a Jackson Democrat, bouncing across
parties and eventually becoming the Greenback presidential
candidate in 1884. In 1860 he nominated Jefferson Davis for US
president, but a few years later Davis denounced him as a felon and
an outlaw because of Butler's actions as military governor of New
Orleans. Any woman insulting a Union soldier, he ordered, was
``liable to be treated as a woman of the town plying her
avocation.'' To Southerners, he was ``Spoons'' Butler, alleging
that he swiped cutlery. They called him ``a cross-eyed beast'' to
mock his drooping eye.
</P>
<P>
   After declining Lincoln's offer of the vice presidency in 1864,
Butler brought zeal to the impeachment proceedings, hiring private
detectives and violating other rules of fair play. After several
attempts, Butler was elected governor of Massachusetts, and when he
died in 1893, mourners filled the streets of his home town, Lowell.
The kindest thing historians have called him is ``a political
general,'' but his legacy lives on in the Bay State. When an
outgoing governor hands over the symbols of office to a successor,
the trinkets include John Hancock's keys to the State House and the
Bible Ben Butler carried during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
