<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEEP-BEEP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWERS THAT BEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question from the '60s: who put the bomp in the
bomp-da-bomp-da-bomp? Question for the '90s: who puts the beep in
the cell phones?
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just the beeps. It's the chirps, the bings, and the
bongs. It's the bells and the whistles. It's the whole cacophony of
electronic burps that are imbedded in microchips inside the likes
of automobiles, cash machines, stereo gear, answering machines,
wristwatches, toys, cameras, computer hardware, fax machines,
copiers, and coffee makers. Not so long ago the alarm clock and the
telephone were pretty much the only buzzes in our lives. Now we're
surrounded by dozens of cheap trills.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid we had very few of these sounds, because we
didn't have things like microwave ovens and cell phones and ATMs,''
says 41-year-old Mark Barasch, once a jazz guitarist in Boston and
now a sound designer in New York. ``I mean, these devices didn't
replace anything. They're relatively new, and so are the sounds
they make. And there may be room for millions more.''
</P>
<P>
   Beeps and bongs are perhaps no more ubiquitous than in cars,
where sound designers have decreed that noise means status. Drivers
of upscale models tend to get audio warnings of, say, near-empty
gas tanks or unlatched trunks, while owners of more plebeian models
do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chimes in particular tend to be used more often in expensive
cars,'' says Charles Richlie, a design engineer for Visteon
Automotive Systems in Detroit, which is part of Ford Motor Co.
``Somebody here obviously decided that chimes sound expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Richlie creates hardware that alerts drivers via tones (``Those
are the beeps,'' he explains) and chimes (``Those are the bongs'').
He points out that chimes usually bong at speeds of 60, 120, or 240
times per minute, and that the fastest rate is intended to create a
sense of urgency _ warning you, for instance, that, yipes, you've
left your your key in the ignition. Richlie's current project: a
beep that will inform you that you've left your turn signal on too
long.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of our beeps and bongs vary. Many are turned out by
engineers who simply borrow them from libraries that are available
on CDs and CD-ROMS, as well as on line. But others are the
creations of specialists who often work in ``human factors''
laboratories, who expound on the importance of ``interface sound
design,'' and who sometimes speak not of bells and whistles but of
``earcons'' (as in icons for the ears).
</P>
<P>
   At Timex Corp., in Middlebury, Conn., where one particular
wristwatch is so beepy it's called Beepwear, shifting demographics
are literally changing the tune. Explains Ron Lizzi, a Timex senior
software engineer: ``As people age, they become less sensitive to
higher frequencies. That means we're now tending to favor lower
frequency tones in our watches.'' Meanwhile, Timex has discovered a
beep gender gap. ``Women don't like beeps as much as men do,'' says
Lizzi.
</P>
<P>
   Timex watches emit all sorts of small noises: alarms, hourly
chimes, timers, and so forth. The sounds are made by tiny
piezoelectric crystals that vibrate in response to current sent
from a microchip. They're not particularly sophisticated noises,
nor is the method for testing them. Their engineers most often rely
on advice from Timex marketing specialists. ``Or we might try them
out on whoever happens to be in the hallway at the time,'' Lizzi
says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But at Bell Labs, the New Jersey-based research arm of Lucent
Technologies, the testing is considerably less casual. Bell's
Integrated User Experience Group might, for example, invite a wide
range of outsiders into a conference room in order to have them
listen to and rate a gaggle of sounds given off by an assortment of
cellular telephones. Are the sounds loud enough? Are they pleasant?
Are they annoying? Are they distinct?
</P>
<P>
   The sounds a product emits can roughly be divided into two main
types _ ``confirmation'' and ``error'' _ and it's important that
the user not get these messages mixed. ``As a rule, a confirmation
tone is a higher tone that curves upward,'' explains Joanne Walsh,
a technical manager at Bell Labs. ``Error tones are lower, and they
curve down.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, we've become a culture that learns early in life when an
electronic sound is trying to tell us we've done good or done bad.
``My 5-year-old can't read, but he already knows the difference
between a `good' tone and a `bad' tone,'' says Veronica Frischman,
who tests Lucent products against competitors' units. ``And my kids
have always said `beep-beep' when they wanted their bottles,
because the oven beeped when the bottles were ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Barasch, the Hub former Hub guitarist turned New York sound
designer, considers the creation of consumer-product sounds an art
form. He thinks they should be able to elicit emotional responses
ranging from gladness to sadness. Barasch Music &AMP; Sound has
produced sounds for Bell Labs, and Barasch remembers the test he
was given first: ``A guy from Bell came in and asked me to create
the sound of a phone ringing. And the sound of the ringing had to
tell a person, before he answered it, that a baby had been born. So
I created it. It was the sound of a celeste, which is a
glockenspiel-like instrument, playing a short melody twice.'' P.S.:
Barasch got the job.
</P>
<P>
   What do folks want in their bells and whistles? Barasch thinks
they want music: ``Every message that Bell Labs has wanted me to
convey _ whether it was an urgent sound, or an error sound, or
whatever _ was created in three ways. There was a musical version,
a real-world sound-effects version, and a speech-prompt version.
And when these got tested in focus groups, they found over and over
again that the musical sounds always won in terms of preference.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Negoescu, a sound designer at Frog Design in Austin,
Texas, has created sounds for the likes of ATM machines, stereo
gear, and personal computers. He uses a computer to cut, chop, and
meld sounds that are either generated by a synthesizer or recorded
in the real world. He thinks the electronic noises that surround us
should be, as much as possible, audio versions of the messages
they're trying to convey. His favorite personal symphony is a sound
he created for Compaq Computers, which accompanied an on-screen
image of an opening control panel. ``I combined the sound of a car
door shutting with the sharp click of a Zippo lighter,'' Negoescu
says proudly.
</P>
<P>
   (There are at least two major rumors circulating in the world of
bells and whistles. The first is that popmeister Brian Eno created
the orchestral sound that bursts forth as Microsoft's Windows
operating system boots up. That's false, says Microsoft. The second
is that the sound that warns Honda drivers of a door ajar is Morse
Code for the letter H. That's true _ four beeps, or ``dots'' _ but
it's purely a coincidence, says Honda.)
</P>
<P>
   Many of us, of course, can do without all the noise. Even men.
But if electronic sounds are impossible to avoid, maybe it's at
least possible to alter them to suit our individual tastes. Indeed,
Timex produces a high-tech watch called a Data Link, which allows
users to customize its tones. ``That's something we certainly
expect to see more of in the future,'' predicts Lizzi.
</P>
<P>
   So if you don't like your beep, you can always change it to a
bong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
