<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEWE-BOS &LR;      02-03 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEWE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBONY LOVE; WHITE GUYS WHO ROCK; SAVAGED IN OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Black History Month _ all 28 days of it _ so many magazines
are giving their annual nod to the lives and contributions of
African-Americans. Ebony, which is all black, all the time,
regardless of calendar markings, does its part for the cause with
an issue focusing on ``Black Love.'' Now, anyone who has ever spent
time flipping through Ebony's glossy pages at the beauty parlor or
barber shop can pretty much guess how one of the nation's oldest
black magazines would celebrate black love _ by featuring
photographs and breathless copy about bank-breaking celebrity
weddings. Among the brides and grooms are South African President
Nelson Mandela; Erinn Cosby, daughter of Bill and Camille Cosby;
and Portland Trailblazer Rasheed Abdul Wallace. For Wallace's
marriage to Fatima Labretta Sanders, Joy Bennett Kinnon writes,
``After Wallace placed a 10-karat diamond on his bride's finger,
lovebirds took flight, confetti was sprinkled, and flower petals
dropped from the ceiling.'' Such detail! Wallace also gave his
bride a Lexus as a proposal gift. Long before celebrities regularly
hawked their lavish nuptials in InStyle and People magazines, there
was Ebony to remind us of all things we could never afford in our
ordinary little lives.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it doesn't stop there. Also submitted for our
approval are the ``10 Hottest Couples.'' By far the most intriguing
of the lot are Terry McMillan and Jonathan Plummer. Why, you ask?
Well, the 20-something Plummer was the inspiration for the Winston
Shakespeare character in ``How Stella Got her Groove Back.'' As in
the book (and the film adaptation starring Angela Bassett),
McMillan, 46, met Plummer while vacationing in Jamaica and,
shunning the advice of friends, began a relationship with him. Just
before marrying Plummer in September, McMillan, never known for
holding her tongue, said, ``Our attitude is `Yeah, we're going to
get married; however long it lasts, it lasts.' '' Ain't love grand?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whither Spin?
</P>
<P>
   Now that editor-in-chief Michael Hirschorn and executive editor
Craig Marks have been kicked to the curb by their bottom-line
owners, Miller Publishing, there's more than a little hand-wringing
concerning what will become of American's best music monthly. The
mag founded by Bob Guccione Jr. has never taken itself, or most of
the world around it, too seriously even as it has offered stellar,
in-depth reporting on a variety of subjects from AIDS to militant
animal-rights activists to the fine art of body decoration. At
Spin, cocky irreverence and social relevance have always made for a
tasty cocktail, shaken and stirred.
</P>
<P>
   What has made Spin so good is evident in the February issue,
perhaps the last with Hirschorn and Marks at the top of the
masthead. Chris Norris hangs with Offspring, the Orange County
hard-core vets who breezed into the mainstream during that neo-punk
minute of the mid-1990s, disappeared quicker than you could say
``You gotta keep 'em separated,'' and came roaring back with the
quirky, annoying dis of gangsta-trippin' wannabes, ``Pretty Fly
(For a White Guy).'' At a time when rock stalwarts from Smashing
Pumpkins to Hole have had a tough time making a dent in a world
dominated by frothy pop and hip-hop, they are, in Norris's words,
``four 30-ish guys in bowling shirts with their fingers on the
pulse of young America.'' With their songs about bad love, loony
girlfriends, lousy roommates, and the trailer-trash culture of
Jerry Springer, the Offspring voice ``the cry of the alienated
white dude and _ to a sizable demographic _ it rocks.'' Just like
the Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, great. Michelangelo Signorile is gone from the pages of Out,
but here comes Dan Savage to rant, rave, and save our gay souls.
He's on the warpath about those he tags as ``ACCs'' _ adult closet
cases _ in his essay, ``Too Chicken to Come Out.'' He takes to task
those who still aren't out to their friends, families, workers, and
have the audacity to whine about their predicament. Know this:
Savage does not feel their pain. ``If you don't have the guts to
come out, well, that's your right, cupcake. But if you're going to
be closeted and live a life devoid of integrity, shut up about how
miserable you are. Your wounds are self-inflicted, and your excuses
_ such as they are _ underwhelm.'' Ouch. A bit shrill, perhaps, but
Savage's savaging of closeted gays and lesbians does make some
salient points.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out is, of course, a gay issue, although this month's
cover girl, the inexplicably popular indie doll Parker Posey, is
not a gay actress. But she makes the obligatory ``some of my best
friends are gay'' comment to quell those who wonder why Out insists
on featuring straight folks on their covers. Says Posey, ``I just
find a lot of strength in gay people because they've had to deal
with something.'' Yeah, like not being able to get on the covers of
gay magazines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0105 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDELITY-LYNCH-2TAKES     02-03 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-LYNCH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MAGICIAN OF MAGELLAN PERSONIFIES FIDELITY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Peter Lynch was shooting Fidelity Investments' new
advertising campaign last August, a bout of back pain threatened to
wreck a scene requiring the legendary stockpicker to jog on a
treadmill. Anxious executives on a tight filming schedule wondered
if a double could be used. But replicating Lynch's trademark
cumulus of snow-white hair proved impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closest match found was from a yak,'' a person involved in
the episode says in dead seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   In pain, the mutual fund icon soldiered on.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch's uniqueness, of course, extends far beyond his Warholian
mop and avuncular investment advice, both on full display to
investors in television and print ads. In 13 years as skipper of
Fidelity's Magellan fund, Lynch racked up singularly spectacular
returns and earned a place among the capitalist gods. Now Fidelity,
the nation's largest fund firm, wants that Midas touch again, this
time to lure back fickle investors.
</P>
<P>
   As he dispenses homespun adages and puts a human face on a
byzantine institution, Lynch has become the poster boy for a
democracy of investors, the pied piper of the personal portfolio.
He is equally significant to Boston-based Fidelity, which he never
really left after quitting Magellan in 1990 at the height of his
success. Now Fidelity has embraced its favorite son as the ultimate
emblem of the firm. In the shift from star stock picker to media
star, is Fidelity remaking Lynch, or is Lynch reshaping Fidelity?
</P>
<P>
   Fifty five-year-old Lynch, of course, has long since ceased
managing mutual funds. These days, as vice chairman of Fidelity, he
functions as sage in residence to whom future fund managers can
turn for advice. Every two months, he meets individually with 10 or
so rookie research analysts and discusses matters such as how to
explain a good idea to a busy portfolio manager. He has no fund
managers under his tutelage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an important sounding board for me,'' says Fidelity
investment chief Robert C. Pozen, who sought out Lynch when he
reorganized the company's research team two years ago and drew up
new fund performance standards. Pozen says he talks to Lynch
several times a month.
</P>
<P>
   Operating out of his office at Fidelity, a semi-retired Lynch
spends as much time fundraising for 16 nonprofit organizations,
including the Archdiocese of Boston, as he does on Fidelity
business. ``Basically, I'm a beggar,'' he says. He also sits on
nine investment committees, including the Museum of Fine Arts and
Boston College, his alma mater, helping to plan their financial
futures.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch is also helping Fidelity mind its own coffers. Following a
period of spotty performance in the mid-1990s, Fidelity has
struggled to expand its market share. Sales last year slowed
considerably, due to a lingering tarnished image and the rise of
the Lynch antithesis, the no-brainer index fund. The $5.3 trillion
fund industry, pioneered in Boston in the 1920s, will only grow
more competitive, and Fidelity cannot rest on old laurels if it is
to thrive and grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign is an opportunity for Peter to espouse all the
ideas he has had over these years,'' explains Bruce Johnstone, a
managing director at Fidelity Investments and longtime Lynch
friend. ``Peter is the company in those ads.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a wintry day, Lynch is nestled in his cluttered office at 27
State Street, in a Fidelity building in Boston dubbed The Tower _ a
reference to the medieval edifice in London where the fallen from
grace were sent before exile or worse. The symbolism is ironic, of
course: Lynch, hardly out of favor, holds around 6 percent of
Fidelity, a stake worth up to $1 billion, according to insiders.
</P>
<P>
   He is, by most accounts, ignorant of corporate statecraft, a
``completely apolitical person who couldn't give a hoot about
company politics and is nothing like a bureaucrat,'' one close
associate says.
</P>
<P>
   In his cramped space, which resembles a professor's den, a black
toy cow wearing beads bestrides a bookcase. A giant yellow wooden
pencil stands in one corner. Under his desk, a white tote bag with
green piping bespeaks staid Boston, not flashy New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a dark suit and brown shoes, Lynch had stuck yellow
notes on shelves reminding himself to get vaccinations for an
African safari. Scores of pictures of Caroline, his wife of 30
years, and three grown daughters (Elizabeth bears the middle name
Peter) line the walls. A note from Pope John Paul II thanks Lynch,
a devout Roman Catholic who has been known to carry rosary beads in
his pocket, for his substantial charity work.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch doesn't like to talk about the advertising campaign, whose
artistic merits have been panned since its launch in September. But
he admits the message of the pitch, which centers on his populist
investing wisdom, was his idea. (Casting co-stars Don Rickles and
Lily Tomlin was not.) The two comedians have not struck a chord
with viewers, some of whom saw little humor when the ads aired
during last year's market meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to use Fidelity's best-known asset as spokesman _ a
radical shift for a firm that long eschewed a personality cult _
came from the company's marketing guru, Stephen Cone. While the
company credits the campaign for boosting visits to its Web site,
direct sales of mutual funds to investors have not yet taken off.
Sales via brokerages, however, have grown, Cone says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Lynch embodies Fidelity's external persona, does he occupy
center stage inside the firm, too?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he is in the inner circle, joining chairman and chief
executive Edward C. ``Ned'' Johnson 3rd and Pozen as an in-house
trustee, and sitting on Fidelity's powerful policy-setting
investment committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Lynch is not a stage director at the fund behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of overall corporate strategy,'' Pozen says, ``I
don't think Peter has played any real role in this.'' As the
family-run firm prepares eventually to pass the reins of control to
Johnson's 37-year-old daughter Abigail, Lynch is unlikely to rise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
