</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0106 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDELITY-LYNCH-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     02-03 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-LYNCH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... to rise.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That suits him just fine. Asked if he would ever have a more
senior position at Fidelity, Lynch says, ``Doubt it, doubt it,
doubt it. I think this is perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch is neither a lieutenant-in-waiting to Abigail, who
overseas Fidelity's analysts (a position Lynch held earlier this
decade), nor the power behind the throne. A minister without
portfolio, Lynch says he talks to Ned Johnson ``as much as I did
when I ran Magellan, which is not very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Others echo that degree of separation. ``You don't want Peter
Lynch trying to run Fidelity,'' one top Fidelity executive says.
``He never ran anything but funds. And that is where his magic
is.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Lynch's investing record is held in awe _ in his
hands, Magellan grew a stunning average 29.2 percent a year and
attracted a flood of new cash _ not everybody at Fidelity likes the
long shadow of the Magellan yardstick.
</P>
<P>
   Some even suggest that Lynch has become something of a dinosaur
in a dynamic industry. ``Once you stop managing money, it flips
into the world of wisdom, not application,'' says a source close to
Fidelity fund managers. ``But the money managers want application,
not wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   With his swing-for-the-fences investment bets, workaholic Lynch
helped create a risk-taking culture at Fidelity during the 1980s
that scored big for investors. His love was growth stocks, or
mostly small to mid-size companies likely to boost earnings
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine years since Lynch quit Fidelity's flagship fund, the
company and the markets have changed, with both now favoring large,
mainstream stocks, not the quirky, overlooked companies Lynch so
loved. With gigantic funds, Fidelity no longer makes huge, wild
wagers on individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is irony in Fidelity using the world's most
celebrated stock picker as its pitchman. ``Peter was a cowboy
investor, so in that sense, Fidelity has really remade themselves
from that old Peter Lynch mold,'' says Russell J. Kinnel, equity
funds editor at Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   With $753 billion in total assets, the Fidelity of today no
longer relies on a single investment genius like Lynch to set the
tone. After fund manager defections and sinking returns in the
mid-1990s, Pozen shook up part of the Lynch legacy by better
organizing and evaluating managers and then leaving them alone to
do their own thing. Since then, Fidelity's returns have improved.
Last year, they were among the best in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Sitll, Lynch is ``disgusted with the whole market trend,'' said
one Boston investor who knows him, referring to Wall Street's focus
on only the biggest of the blue chips that fill up index funds.
``He likes adventurism and people who do creative stock picking.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lynch's modus operandi _ rigorous, bottoms-up
analysis of companies, rather than top-down assessment of
macroeconomic trends _ remains deeply ingrained in Fidelity's
culture. When Pozen beefed up the research unit to intensify
company and sector analysis, he was expanding Lynch's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch won't discuss his own portfolio, his stockpicking ideas
haven't changed. ``I like the stocks that have been beaten down and
then turn. Just buying big stocks doesn't work. You have to buy big
stocks where the fundamentals are better'' than their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Would he join in Internet mania, paying sky-high prices for
shares in as yet unprofitable companies? Lynch didn't buy many
technology shares in his Magellan days. The reason, colleagues say,
is that he doesn't like to buy a stock in a company whose products
he doesn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Despite working for a firm that spends billions on technology,
Lynch is a bit of a techno-klutz, associates and friends say. Early
in his marriage, he couldn't work the microwave. Later, he was
shocked to see Fidelity staffers fax, rather than hand deliver,
materials from 82 Devonshire, the main office, to 100 Summer
Street, a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter Simon Lynch was born in 1944 in Boston and raised in
nearby suburb Newton. His father died when he was 10 and he grew up
in modest circumstances, making pocket money caddying a top
Fidelity executive's golf clubs at West Newton's Braeburn Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   He attended Boston College on a caddying scholarship, graduating
in 1965 and working at Fidelity for the summer before entering the
University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business, where in
1968 he finished near the top of his class. Then he was called to
serve in the US Army as a lieutenant, lucking out by landing in
South Korea, not Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He formally joined Fidelity as a research analyst in 1969. He
has never worked anywhere but Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Amiable but cool, Lynch can be impatient. He famously entered
analysts' meetings in the 1970s with an egg timer, giving young
staffers exactly three minutes to pitch a stock. In Korea, he
played pick-up basketball in stiff leather boots so as not to waste
time changing shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Family is important to Lynch, who quit Magellan to spend more
time with his own. Now he lives in the seaside community of
Marblehead in a Bauhaus-style residence filled with antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his vacation time (he took 98 days last year) is spent
at his 18th-century Georgian country manor in Ireland, his
ancestral land. After buying the farmhouse, Lynch suggested to the
sellers that they live in the guest quarters. At a recent gathering
of investment-world friends at the estate, Lynch invited the
previous owners to the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   While seemingly down-to-earth, Lynch is not simple.
</P>
<P>
   He is known as the world's greatest stock picker, yet his ads
(and the three books he has authored) create the impression almost
anyone could do it. A market animal who holds reams of numbers in
his head, he was a market heretic when he preached the virtues of
the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He is guarded in public but adores the limelight. Friends
describe him as a creative thinker, yet he often recites trademark
sayings (``I always say, if we didn't have the 10 Commandments,
you'd have to get the U.N. to invent them'' is one).
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is phasing out the Rickles and Tomlin ads in favor of
unscripted spots of Lynch discussing his stock-picking philosophy
with Fidelity staffers. The company says it will use the Lynch
campaign at least until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   So what is Lynch's next act?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it all,'' he says. ``I've done all I want to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
