<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-UNITED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED EUROPE VIEWED BY SOME BRITONS AS NOT QUITE THE THING  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Sitting in the bar of the venerable Oxford &AMP; Cambridge
Club on Pall Mall, surrounded by dark wood and old money, Sir Roy
Denman would appear to be the kind of Englishman who still mourns
the loss of empire.
</P>
<P>
   But Sir Roy is a rare breed: a knighted Briton who is an
unabashed, enthusiastic European.
</P>
<P>
   As the European Commission's former representative to
Washington, he has been embarrassed by the dismissive attitude
toward Europe held by many of his compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude is, `We won the war for this? What the Germans
couldn't win in the war, we're going to give away to them in the
name of European integration?' Europe is a concept that,
unfortunately, escapes most British people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The British have long been the most reluctant of Europeans.
Their opposition to monetary union is but the most recent example
of this reluctance.
</P>
<P>
   The smooth launch of the euro, the single currency used in 11 of
the European Union's 15 nations, has softened resistance to it in
Sweden and Denmark, two of the three countries that chose not to
join. (Greece wanted to join but did not qualify.) The new
willingness of Sweden and Denmark to reconsider participating in
the single currency underscores just how isolated the British are.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the euro has actually fallen in Britain, where a
skeptical public has been bombarded by relentless anti-European
rhetoric from politicians and media commentators. They warn of
massive unemployment and the inability of Britain to make economic
adjustments should it join the other 11 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Recent speeches by the Danish and Swedish prime ministers
suggesting they would join the single currency as soon as possible
were well received in those countries. But British Prime Minister
Tony Blair's attempts to do the same are often met by derision
here, especially in the newspapers and television stations owned by
media baron Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show strong support for the euro among British business
people. But fervent opposition to it and nearly every other aspect
of European integration in many of the newspapers owned by Murdoch,
who controls 40 percent of the British media market, blunts Blair's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest establishment newspapers, the Daily Mail, the
largest ``serious'' tabloid, and the Daily Telegraph, the largest
broadsheet, also oppose the euro and make no effort to keep their
editorial position from influencing news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But historians say it is simplistic to attribute most of the
current opposition to the euro to Murdoch and others who
legitimately fear it will hurt their business interests. Instead,
historians maintain that this bout of Europhobia is the latest
example of the cultural and political ambivalence among the British
about the very idea of a united Europe and their participation in
it.
</P>
<P>
   Some try to portray anti-Europeanism here along a
liberal-conservative divide. But Hugo Young, author of the recently
published book, ``This Blessed Plot: Britain and Europe from
Churchill to Blair,'' says both the Conservatives and Labor Party
have been stridently anti-Europe when it suits them.
</P>
<P>
   Half a century ago, Winston Churchill articulated the idea of a
united Europe. Today, Blair says he too wants to bring Britain
further into Europe. Both Churchill and Blair, Young contends,
``were spectators rather than actors in a continental drama from
which Britain, the island nation, chose to exclude herself.''
</P>
<P>
   The venerable island-nation theory holds that the British view
themselves apart from the continent, physically and
psychologically. As Young puts it, ``The island people were not
only different but, mercifully, separate, housed behind their moat.
They were also inestimably superior.''
</P>
<P>
   This sense of superiority was encapsulated in a British
government memorandum, published in 1949, that argued against
building a channel tunnel linking Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
   ``An important element in the character of our national life
would be altered by the creation of a land connection,'' the memo
concluded. ``One effect might for example be the weakening of that
unquestioning sense of superiority over the peoples of the
Continent which forms an essential element of British
self-confidence and which has proved its value in recent times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph recently reproduced that memo as part of its
steady diet of anti-European stories.
</P>
<P>
   Young argues that this sense of superiority remains largely
undiminished by time or the fact that Britain lags behind many
European countries in standard of living and educational
achievement levels. Young believes Britain has been unable to come
to terms with losing its empire. As he observes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanging on to the past, in the form of the post-imperial
Commonwealth, seemed for a time to be the answer. Remaining
constant to the Anglo-American relationship . . . was apparently
another necessity, which would be fatally compromised by the lure
of something called the European Community.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of the rest of Europe enthusiastically endorsed the
union concept, Young says that the idea was regarded as a blow to
the British national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Denman added that it is understandable why the British are less
prepared to sacrifice national sovereignty than the French,
Germans, Belgians and others in the name of a united Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't just because Britain is an island,'' he said.
``Indeed, Ireland is an island and the Irish are the most
enthusiastic of Europeans. The difference is we've never had a
revolution. We've never experienced occupation. We've been bombed.
But we haven't been conquered, and that's a critical difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Xenophobia also explains part of British anti-Europeanism. The
Sun, a Murdoch tabloid, recently ran a front-page picture of Oskar
Lafontaine, the German finance minister, with a headline
proclaiming him ``The Most Dangerous Man in Europe.'' Ostensibly,
the headline impugned Lafontaine's socialist agenda. But it also
articulated a subtle prejudice held by many here: that inside every
German lurks a potential extremist.
</P>
<P>
   That such animosities exist within generations that endured Nazi
bombs and lost so many people in two World Wars prosecuted by the
Germans is not unusual. But it is striking how many people who were
born after World War II hold the same views. Such dated prejudices
are less pervasive on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Other EU partners, especially the Germans and the French, who
have been the driving forces behind integration, are becoming
increasingly impatient with the British position. As the German
newspaper, Bild Zeitung, observed recently, ``While we were toiling
away on making the euro, the British in their fine pinstripes did
not want to get their hands dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Brussels, Yves-Thibault de Silguy, the European
commissioner in charge of monetary policy, said Britain is deluding
itself if it thinks that refusing to join the single currency will
protect its monetary independence.
</P>
<P>
   Denman agreed, adding that British foreign policy since World
War II has been built on two illusions: that Britain could be an
influential leader in Europe by remaining outside it, and that
Britain's interest is always best served by adopting the position
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Denman said that Blair could increase British influence by
bringing Britain further into the European Union. In doing so, he
would become the linchpin securing Washington to continental
Europe. ``Right now, Britain is seen in the rest of Europe as
America's poodle,'' said Denman. ``It's not a flattering image.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
