<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARS FACTOR MAY SERVE GLENN WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Some dream of a white Christmas. Ivan Fears
dreams of an Antonio Freeman-Terry Glenn 1-2 punch.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad dream to have. A lofty one for the Patriots' new
receivers coach? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman is the prize receiver in free agency, but it doesn't
appear that the Patriots would lay out the $6 million or so per
year it would take to get him.
</P>
<P>
   So Fears's biggest job is to find a way to keep Glenn on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   While Fears didn't mention it at his press briefing Tuesday, the
Patriots plan to restrict Glenn's in-season practice time _ mostly
his post routes _ in an effort to preserve his hamstrings, which
Glenn has injured in each of his three years in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate concern is Glenn's recovery from a broken
right ankle. He is due in town soon for a reexamination and will be
in a cast until late this month. Then he'll need some time to
recuperate. The good part is Glenn will spend a lot of time in
Foxborough to rehabilitate the ankle and therefore will take part
in the team's offseason conditioning program and likely will be
around for more than the 25 (of 40) workouts he attended last
season.
</P>
<P>
   That number is deceiving, because Glenn worked out on his own in
Columbus, Ohio, and also attended Cris Carter's receivers camp in
Orlando last spring. He came to training camp in superb shape. And
still got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to have our thumb on him the whole year long,'' said
Fears. ``But maybe it's better for him to get away for a while as
long as he's ready to come here and play and make things happen
that he makes happen. I think he's done a good job of getting that
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury thing is something that's going to happen. I don't
think there's any indication that Terry is too old or too whatever
or wore out, whatever it may be. There are things that happen to
guys. Curtis Conway has had a lot of injuries. Isaac Bruce, he's
missed a lot of playing time. Jerry Rice. It happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The most refreshing thing Fears said is that offseason
conditioning programs don't prevent players from breaking ankles.
He doesn't think they prevent recurring hamstring pulls, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many speed guys do you know that don't have hamstring
pulls?'' he said. ``You're talking about fast guys. It's one of the
things that come with being a fast guy. Terry is not just fast,
he's strong. He's 5-11, 200 pounds, and he has exceptional speed.
And those guys, when they're turning on that speed, occasionally
will have problems with their hamstrings.''
</P>
<P>
   So why does Glenn have so many problems and Shawn Jefferson,
also a fast guy, doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way,'' said Fears. ``You look at the play
between Shawn Jefferson and Terry Glenn . . . I'll let you answer
that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn is a sudden player. When you're making those sudden
moves, those things happen. I'm not going to tell him to slow down
and not make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Fears hasn't met Glenn yet. He plans to sit down with him and
ask specific questions about his goals. And then Fears will tell
him what he thinks. He's not shy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the reason the Patriots hired Fears is that he's very
direct and tough. Fears calls himself demanding. He understands
that Glenn is a special talent and calls him his No. 1 priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go all the way to the Super Bowl with Terry,'' said
Fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put him in a bubble and keep him there until
Sunday. We're going to be smart about it. We're not going to lose
him in practice, though, but we're going to make sure he's prepared
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there are things Fears can't say because he hasn't
talked to Glenn yet. But he was brought in as a motivator. He has
been known to instill, well, fear, into some players. And just how
he does that and how Glenn responds might make for the best
entertainment of next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
