<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0113 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-03 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has David D'Alessandro gone too far this time?
</P>
<P>
   Not far enough, if you listen for long to the guy who won't let
up on the International Olympic Committee and ``the code of
secrecy'' that surrounds it. ``There are a lot of guys trying to
preserve their jobs right now,'' says the president of John Hancock
Mutual Life Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The always-quotable D'Alessandro has been everywhere as the
pay-to-play scandal has built into the greatest embarrassment in
Olympic history. He's been all over the TV networks, in The Wall
Street Journal and The New York Times, and on and on. Always, he's
been the noisy and insistent voice for full disclosure of the IOC's
modus operandi.
</P>
<P>
   It only looks like a campaign, D'Alessandro tells me. He's
turned down 200 interview requests in the last few weeks, including
one from ``60 Minutes.'' ``I am not interested in a campaign. I am
interested in sending a clear message through some media that the
sponsors do have leverage here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the sponsors _ Hancock is one of 11 worldwide _ have
appreciated the messenger. Two weeks ago, for instance, anyone who
is anyone among Olympic sponsors was at the Reebok Club in
Manhattan for the premiere of a film on the Nagano Games. In
conversations with Hancock executives, McDonald's director of
global sports, Jackie Woodward, made it perfectly clear that she
didn't appreciate D'Alessandro's very public approach to the
problems. What was he trying to accomplish? she wanted to know.
Didn't he know he was making problems for the other sponsors? An
executive with United Parcel Service made similar remarks.
</P>
<P>
   A McDonald's spokeswoman, Bridget Coffing, says she was unaware
of what was said that day, but adds the company is pleased the IOC
is ``acting swiftly'' to address the problems. On Hancock's
position she adds: ``No sponsor represents the sponsor group.
Nobody represents us but McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   The only surprise here is that anyone should be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC in Lausanne, Switzerland, with its marbled walls and
fresco-lined rooms, is the ultimate club. Sponsors now pay $40
million every four years just to belong to The Club _ event
tickets, hotels rooms, media time, etc. are extra.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro was hardly born to The Club. He came to Boston and
Hancock 15 years ago as an ambitious PR man who didn't know how to
dress. He put himself on the map by rescuing the Boston Marathon
with Hancock's dough, and then put himself in position to run one
of the nation's largest insurers by slashing costs and improving
profits in one division after another.
</P>
<P>
   Shock of shocks, he has ruffled feathers getting there. He's
hardly loved among Hancock's career agents. In 1993 D'Alessandro
and his spokesman, Hancock chairman Stephen Brown, made more than a
few enemies in this town when they said making a bid to bring the
Olympics to Boston was a stupid idea. In 1996 D'Alessandro
criticized how Atlanta had commercialized the Games, and last year
he created a stir in Australia when he suggested sponsors should
sue the pants off Olympic organizers if they tried to play games
with the contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Running through all of his recent comments, D'Alessandro says,
is one goal: protecting the value of the five Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   There's evidence that he is getting results. He was the first to
publicly call for expanding the investigation beyond Salt Lake
City. His proposal for an ethics commission to oversee the process
is likely to happen. He wants a ``morals clause'' to give sponsors
an out, and financial disclosure for IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock is clearly trying to provide the leverage that
reform-minded Olympic executives like Dick Pound need to create
change. The betting here is that D'Alessandro has said nothing that
surprised these people or nothing _ almost nothing, anyway _ that
they have had a problem seeing in print.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro, after all, has bet a bundle on the Olympic rings,
in terms of Hancock's budget and his own career. He and the boys in
Lausanne are natural allies, not enemies.
</P>
<P>
   But at this point he is hedging his bets, too: He's ordered the
rings off Hancock's annual report, which comes out in April.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey's e-mail address is bailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
