<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-03 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING SHOPPING FOR HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the jobless rate lower than it has been in years and
skilled applicants hard to find, one recruiter has come up with a
novel idea: computerized ``Job Shop'' kiosks placed inside shopping
malls.
</P>
<P>
   The kiosks, much like ATM machines, link job hunters to work
currently offered by clients of Adecco, a Swiss temporary
employment agency with US headquarters in Redwood City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Adecco is hoping its kiosks, now located in malls around the
country, will provide another source of skilled labor at a time
when national unemployment rates have remained at or below 5
percent, forcing US employers to devise more innovative ways to
attract job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the current tight labor market, we had to make an effort to
be creative and attract more people,'' said Adecco spokeswoman
Bonnie Olmsted. ``We put the kiosks in high traffic areas such as
malls, junior colleges, and universities. People can step up to it,
put in the information and, within five minutes, they can find out
if there is a job for them in their region.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four months, 500,000 people have activated 50
Adecco Job Shop computers by touching the screens. Of those, 30,000
have used the kiosk's computerized touch system to tap in their
resumes and apply for work. The company has placed about 2,000
people. The names of remaining applicants are kept in a national
job bank.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to the tight labor market, US companies are either
scrambling for employees or keeping their own workers on the job
for longer hours to meet production goals and demands, say experts.
One Massachusetts economist, Barry Bluestone, believes the current
economy has led to a ``field of dreams'' labor market. In other
words, he says, employers who make their needs known shouldn't
worry because workers will come.
</P>
<P>
   But some employers say they cannot afford to wait. Faced with
vacancies they cannot fill, these companies are turning to
interactive computer, telephone, or Internet systems to attract,
prescreen, or select qualified applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In Waltham, Mass., for example, MTS Boston uses resumes gleaned
from Internet and non-Internet sources to match companies to
hard-to-find computer professionals. The company, which represents
about 200 Boston-area firms, has a spinoff called HotChili
Technology Inc. that manages resume databases for employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers receive these resumes from all kinds of sources,''
said Ian Grant, cofounder and principal at MTS Boston and HotChili.
``Some employers take an ad out in the newspaper and receive
resumes, others collect them at career fairs, or they receive
through direct mail or at open houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies pay between $6,000 to $8,500 per year to select an
unlimited number of applicants from MTS Boston over the course of a
year. ``If a company went to a headhunter, it would have to pay
between 20 or 30 percent of the first year's salary of a software
engineer,'' he said. ``That means the company would spend $10,000
to $15,000 just for that one person. If they hire a second person,
it would mean another $10,000 to $15,000. With us, they can hire an
unlimited number of people for up to $8,500.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Adecco, food service and retail firms are relying on
PC-based recruiting systems, computerized stations similar to the
new kiosks, or voice-activated telephone screening tools to capture
new applicants and slash hiring costs. Macy's, Wendy's, McDonald's,
Burger King, and Chili's Grill &AMP; Bar are all using these new hiring
and screening tools.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms have developed interactive employment centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than direct applicants to the personnel office, the
companies are sending applicants to personal computers,'' noted
Bill Parness, a spokeswoman for HREasy Inc., a North Carolina
company that designs telephone screening systems for retail
companies.
</P>
<P>
   One interactive screening program relies on timed answers to
analyze job applicants' responses to a series of questions designed
to gauge honesty, reliability, punctuality, and state of mind. The
new system screens out job applicants who respond too quickly or
too slowly to such questions as, ``I sometimes borrowed pencils,
paper, and other supplies from my prior boss,'' or ``Taking money
from the cash register is okay as long as you pay it back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this depends on the industry,'' said David Beck,
publisher of Recruiting Trends Newsletter in Fitzwilliam, N.H., a
division of Kennedy Information. ``Within the high-tech industry,
for example, there is a real scarcity of professionals and there is
greater use of the Internet as a hiring tool. Obviously, that is
becoming very big. Many of the human resources executives are on
line.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Beck said: ``These methods really supplement
traditional forms of recruiting and interviewing. They are not
replacements. On Long Island, for example, one recruiter was using
billboards because it was competing for scarce talent.
Traditionally, however, nothing replaces face-to-face contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Adecco's Olmsted agrees. ``For us, this is just one way to
attract people,'' she said. ``We also use Internet recruiting,
classified news, job fairs, and we see people face-to-face.''
</P>
<P>
   The company places 2.5 million people in jobs annually. Thus
far, its kiosks have been installed in part of the US and Europe,
and plans are under way to expand the kiosks' reach to include
Spain, Britain, Canada, and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Kiosks are in malls in Connecticut, New York, New Jersey,
California, Ohio, and several other states. Adecco franchises in
Rhode Island and New Hampshire are expected to install the machines
within the next three or four months. Kiosks will be installed in
Massachusetts some time this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments? Contact Diane Lewis at work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
