creating a tire manufacturer with annual sales of $15.5 billion.
Goodyear will control the combined operations in Europe and the
United States; Sumitomo will control the operations in Japan.
Goodyear will lay off as many as 2,800 of its workers and will pay
the Japanese company $936 million to make up for Sumitomo's
relinquishing control of some assets. The venture stops short of
being a merger, although the companies will exchange about $110
million of stock, equivalent to 10 percent of Sumitomo and 1.4
percent of Goodyear. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
