<HEADLINE>
JACOBS HAS HER EYE ON A RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last July Fourth, Regina Jacobs set an American record for 5,000
meters (14 minutes, 52.49 seconds) at the Maine Distance Festival
in Brunswick. The 35-year-old Californian must think New England
agrees with her: on Sunday, she'll be back, this time in search of
the US record indoors at 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I heard, it just rocks,'' said Jacobs of the oval at
the Reggie Lewis Track &AMP; Athletic Center, site of the New Balance
Invitational. ``I'm not discounting the record. It's definitely
strong. But it's also achievable, and I'm in the shape to break it
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The US record (8:40.45) is held by another woman who is fond of
New England: Lynn Jennings of Newmarket, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, a three-time Olympian at 1,500 meters, has had an
up-and-down career since graduating from Stanford in 1985, but the
last few years have certainly been more ``up'' than ``down,'' and
she is finally getting some of the recognition that had eluded her
for most of her career. After finishing a disappointing 10th in the
1,500-meter final in Atlanta, Jacobs ran well on the European track
circuit for the rest of that season before winning a silver medal
in the 1,500 at the 1997 World Outdoor Championships. She picked up
another another silver last summer in the mile at the Goodwill
Games in a personal best of 4:20.93, besides the 5,000 record.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a busy weekend for Jacobs, who like many of the other
athletes coming here will compete Friday in the Millrose Games in
New York City. ``My primary focus is Boston,'' said Jacobs. ``But
that certainly doesn't mean I won't be racing hard and strong'' in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   At Millrose, Jacobs will compete in the mile against longtime
rival Suzy Hamilton. It is no secret in the world of track and
field that the two women are not friends, and Jacobs' strategy
won't be made any easier by Hamilton's presence. ``When we get on
the line I want to beat her as much as she wants to beat me,'' said
Jacobs. ``It's not friends, kiss kiss, let's go out and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows we don't really like each other,'' said
Hamilton, who will run the 800 in Boston against, ironically, her
good friend and former Harvard star Meredith Rainey Valmon, who
finished second to Hamilton at the NCAA championships in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Hamilton in another race, there will be plenty at
stake for Jacobs in Boston: besides prestige, the US record will
bring a meet bonus of a 1999 Chevrolet Blazer. ``Tom could use a
car,'' Jacobs quipped of her husband and coach, Tom Craig. ``If you
see him yelling, like really screaming, you know he's thinking more
about the car than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's still more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm feeling really good,'' Jacobs said last week, ``I'm
going to go for the world record (8:33.82). I'll put that on the
line right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The meet begins at 2:30. Tickets are available by calling Global
Athletics and Marketing at 617-536-7030.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Back on the ice
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When USA Hockey announced its roster Tuesday for the 1999 US
Women's National Team that will compete in the 1999 World
Championships next month in Finland, there weren't many surprises.
But there certainly were two: Boston's Stephanie O'Sullivan, who
blasted US coach Ben Smith after he included her among the final
cuts for the 1998 Olympic roster, is among 12 forwards named to the
squad, which will again be coached by Smith. And one of the
goaltenders will be Erin Whitten, also one of Smith's last cuts.
Both have extensive international experience: this will be
Whitten's fourth world championships and O'Sullivan's third.
</P>
<P>
   Also named to the 20-player roster Tuesday were 11 Olympians:
defensemen Chris Bailey, Sue Merz, Tara Mounsey and Angela
Ruggiero, and forwards Alana Blahoski, Karyn Bye, Tricia Dunn,
Cammi Granato, Katie King, Shelley Looney and Jenny Schmidgall.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the squad are seven newcomers to the world
championships, including Laurie Belliveau of Manchester, Mass. and
Amy Coelho of North Truro, Mass., as well as Brandy Fisher, Sarah
Hood, Catherine Hanson, Natalie Darwitz and Krissy Wendell.
</P>
</TEXT>
