<SLUG> BC-SIMPSONS-CLOSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEPARTMENT STORE THAT COULDN'T FIT A NEW BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The surprise is not so much that Simpson of Piccadilly,
the most traditional of London department stores, closed for good
Saturday (Jan. 30). The real surprise is that it lasted this long.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson's, as every Londoner calls it, is known to many
Americans because it was the inspiration for the 1970s British
sitcom ``Are You Being Served?,'' which has had an inexplicably
popular run on US public television over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from its place in TV trivia, Simpson's was a place
where tweedy men and horsey women bought traditional British
clothing since it opened in 1936. While kings and queens, princes
and princesses, dukes and earls and baronesses bought cashmere
scarves and tweed jackets there for more than 60 years, Simpson's
became a casualty to Cool Britannia and modern retailing.
</P>
<P>
   The store's parent company, DAKS Simpson, said it plans to sell
its products in smaller boutique shops. As the company put it when
announcing the store's closure, Simpson's was ``economically and
logistically unsuitable to use solely for the very focused retail
style and format that has been developed.''
</P>
<P>
   In plain English, that means the store was too big, and its
customers were dying off.
</P>
<P>
   Waterstone's, the book seller, is taking over the gorgeous,
seven-story building that graces Piccadilly. Londoners are still
voracious readers, but fewer of them dress like Princess Margaret
these days. While Simpson's billed itself as the biggest menswear
store in the world when it opened, Waterstone's says its new
flagship outlet will be the biggest bookstore in the world.
</P>
<P>
   By English standards, 63 years is not a long time. But by any
standard, Simpson's was an institution in London, a store whose
mere mention conjures images that one finds either warm and fuzzy
or ludicrously outdated.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a curious lack of sentimentality attached to its
closing, a deliberate marketing strategy by DAKS. The way the
company sees it, it is merely consolidating retail space. Aside
from the sale signs that cheekily suggest a ``Good Bye'' to be had
inside, there is a remarkable absence of emotion as yet one more
institution gives way to the steamroller that is Tony Blair's New
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Londoners ventured into the store last week as some
might to a wake, giving the dearly departed one last look over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember coming here as a child, at Christmastime, and it
was magic,'' said Shirley Evans, a retired teacher. ``We'd watch
`Are You Being Served?' and compare the characters to the sales
ladies and men there. It was good fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But, perhaps explaining Simpson's demise better than any flow
chart, Evans left the store the other day empty handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are You Being Served?'' is still shown regularly on British
television. One of its creators, Jeremy Lloyd, worked as a salesman
at Simpson's some 50 years ago. By today's standards, the show's
characters are politically incorrect: a pompous World War II
veteran who insists on being called by his army rank of captain, a
lecherous manager and his bosomy secretary, a blousy loud-mouthed,
middle-aged saleslady who changes her hair color every day, a
limp-wristed lisping gay salesman.
</P>
<P>
   But Lloyd says the store and the characters it inspired were a
metaphor for Britain's quirky class system, where people are born
into social strata, where identity was formed by the harsh years of
the war.
</P>
<P>
   If the characters on ``Are You Being Served?'' are outrageous,
the real salespeople at Simpson's are polite and discreet. A
saleslady who sold an American visitor a scarf the other day talked
wistfully about the store, but politely declined to give her name,
saying, ``That wouldn't be right.''
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese company bought the store in 1991 and introduced
contemporary designer labels such as Armani in an attempt to lure a
new generation of shoppers. But like Kennedy's, the menswear shop
that died a retail death in downtown Boston years ago, Simpson's
was so inextricably linked with an older, tweedy generation that
the marketing strategy was doomed. People who can afford to shop at
Simpson's go to Harrods or Harvey Nichols instead.
</P>
<P>
   What killed Simpson's was not a lack of quality clothing. On the
contrary, its wares are among the finest in London. What killed
Simpson's is an adage older than the store itself: you don't shop
where your grandfather does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
