<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA SCHOOLS FACE TOUGH LESSON: A TEACHER SHORTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: California, Massachusetts)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A critical shortage of teachers in California
has led to the first statewide advertising campaign to recruit
qualified applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In the next 10 years, from 260,000 to 300,000 new teachers will
be needed, according to various estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a certain age to get my meaning, but we need to
treat the teacher shortage the same way we treated the need for
math and science education in the wake of Sputnik,'' said Mary
Burgan, president of the Oakland-based California Federation of
Teachers, representing about 50,000 teachers in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The tag line for the $2 million ad campaign is, ``Change their
lives. Change yours. Teach.'' Targeted at high school and college
students entering the work force, as well as professionals
considering changing careers, the campaign hopes to fill positions
created by a burst of population, teacher retirement and the
mandate for smaller classes.
</P>
<P>
   According to California Superintendent of Schools Delaine
Eastin, 37 percent of the current 250,000 public schoolteachers are
over 50 _ hired in the 1960s and early 1970s when there was another
bubble of population growth _ and are expected to retire in the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, within six years, California public schools will be
educating 6.5 million students _ 1 million more than today _ said
Nancy Brownell, interim director of the Institute for Education
Reform at the California State University system.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Beach-based institute administers the California Center
for Teaching Careers (CalTeach). CalTeach, which is sponsoring the
ad, is a one-stop teaching information, recruitment and referral
center.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second spot began airing last week and will be shown for
13 weeks on cable channels in Los Angeles, San Francisco, San
Diego, Sacramento, Fresno and Bakersfield. The state is paying for
the advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The ad features a young, energetic teacher who travels to school
by bicycle and leads a culturally diverse group of students in a
classroom science experiment. ``There's a place in California where
you can do something important with your life every day,'' a voice
says. ``The place is the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Early indications are the ad is working: Prior to its launch
last week, CalTeach was getting about 7,500 monthly visits on its
Web site (www.calteach.com) and now receives 43,000 per week,
Brownell said.
</P>
<P>
   But in California, particularly in expensive areas such as the
Silicon Valley, the rub for teachers has always been starting
salary _ $27,000 to $28,000 on average.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Pope, a former newspaper reporter and now a sixth-grade
teacher at Cabrillo Middle School in Santa Clara, said it was
difficult for schools to compete with electronics companies that
offer starting salaries greater than a 30-year veteran teacher
earns.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who opt for teaching, said Pope, do so for other
reasons. ``There are huge frustrations teaching,'' she said, ``but
huge rewards, too. You can see a lot of potential in kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortage is so acute that about 18,000 teachers lack the
credentials required but are working under emergency permits issued
by school districts _ particularly in Los Angeles and scattered
rural districts _ that do not have enough qualified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the state and the economy are requiring far higher
standards be met, said Bill Hauck, president of the
Sacramento-based California Business Roundtable, which advocates
education reform in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we have a technological society today, not
tomorrow,'' Hauck said. ``We are falling short of giving people
education to a level that is required for the work force they are
in today, much less tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Other states have teacher shortages as well, and California
increasingly must compete with them. This year, Massachusetts
officials are visiting 48 campuses across the country _ including
the University of California campuses at San Diego and Berkeley,
and Stanford University _ to interview prospective teachers. In
March, 50 will be selected and will get $20,000 signing bonuses
paid over four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the 50 best people we can get,'' said Mieka Freund,
who manages the recruiting program at the Massachusetts Department
of Education. ``We want people excited about teaching and about
teaching in Massachusetts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
