<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETTYSBURG04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUDGET PROPOSES DEMOLISHING HATED TOWER AT GETTYSBURG
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's proposed federal budget
provides funding to tear down a tower for tourists that has
outraged Civil War buffs since it was built one score and seven
years ago near the very spot where Abraham Lincoln delivered his
Gettysburg Address in 1863.
</P>
<P>
   The privately owned, 310-foot tower looms over the historic
battlefield and can be seen for miles around. Preservationists have
regarded the structure as an anachronistic eyesore since it was
erected in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no better symbol for the need to preserve the
Gettysburg battlefield than taking down this tower,'' said Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt. ``Until this initiative, the park has not
had the funding.''
</P>
<P>
   In the budget submitted to Congress this week, a $1 billion
Lands Legacy Initiative contains $5.7 million for the Gettysburg
National Military Park to purchase the tower from its private
owners.
</P>
<P>
   The tower was built as a tourist attraction next to the
federally protected parkland. However, in 1990 the federal
boundaries were expanded to include more of the actual battlefield.
Since then, removal of the tower has been a high priority for both
the National Park Service and private preservationists, who have
often differed on other issues regarding the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one thing that there's been the most agreement
on,'' said Katie Lawhon, a spokeswoman for the National Park
Service in Gettysburg. ``The tower has been controversial since its
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It never should have been built in the first place,'' agreed
Jerry Russell, chairman of the Civil War Roundtable Associates,
based in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   However, Congress must approve the budget before the tower can
be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to sit tight,'' said Lawhon. ``We are interested
in negotiating with the owners'' even before congressional approval
of the funding, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations may prove ``problematic,'' said Irwin
Aronson, the attorney for the tower's owner, Baltimore businessman
Thomas Ottenstein.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Park Service authorized an appraisal that valued
the tower at $6.6 million, Aronson recalled. By now budgeting $5.7
million to buy the tower for demolition, he said, the Park Service
appears to be ``trying to manipulate the outcome'' of any
subsequent appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a garish piece of tourist-trap junk,'' Aronson
said. ``It happens to be tall. It is a tower'' that provides ``an
educational experience'' to legions of tourists who visit it for an
overall view of the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service _ in a controversial public-private partnership
with a commercial developer _ aims to build a new, $40 million
visitor center near the land where the tower is located, Aronson
noted. That should increase the value of his client's property, not
decrease it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawhon said only that a new appraisal would have to be completed
for the tower.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the proposed new visitor center continues to divide
the historic preservation community. Rep. James Hansen, R-Utah, has
called a hearing of the House subcommittee on national parks that
he chairs for Feb. 11 to question witnesses about his concerns with
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are against commercialization inside the boundaries of the
battlefield,'' said Russell, who is a leader in the opposition
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
