<HEADLINE>
THE RULE OF LAW VS. THE WILL OF THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 7)   Commentary  
 (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a particularly frustrating juncture in the
Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton, chief House
prosecutor Henry Hyde exclaimed that ``despite all the polls and
all the hostile editorials, America is hungry for people who
believe in something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You may disagree with us,'' the Illinois Republican told the
assembled senators, ``but we believe in something.''
</P>
<P>
   With those pungent words, the eloquent congressman from the
Chicago area cut to the heart of the dilemma that is so perplexing
to millions of Americans as well as those 13 Republican prosecutors
who have laid out the evidence that they believe should result in
the conviction of Clinton for perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The ``rule of law,'' Hyde and his colleagues keep repeating,
should be the deciding factor in the case and they, of course,
believe the rule of law is on their side.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's defenders also have a potent argument. While
Clinton's behavior has been despicable, they contend, his crimes do
not constitute impeachable offenses because they have not posed a
threat to the government as did Richard Nixon's attempt to use the
CIA and FBI to cover up the Watergate break-in.
</P>
<P>
   This is a most unusual time in the life of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Should a charismatic leader who advocates popular programs and
presides over rollicking good times be ousted from office because
he has led a scandalous private life and sought through lies to
withhold details from the public?
</P>
<P>
   That is a question that ultimately must be answered by the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   We have had in this century several examples of great countries
being led to disaster by leaders who, despite their evil ways, held
the people in their thrall. Such was the case with Adolf Hitler in
Germany and Benito Mussolini in Italy, and more recently Saddam
Hussein in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, we have had presidents who lied publicly
about their activities and decisions while enjoying public
approval. Among them, in addition to Nixon, were Dwight Eisenhower,
when the Soviets shot down an American spy plane; John F. Kennedy,
when Cuban dissidents invaded the Bay of Pigs with U.S. approval;
Lyndon B. Johnson, when he committed ground troops to Vietnam; and
Ronald Reagan and George Bush in regard to the Iran-contra
shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   That some of his predecessors also lied to the people does not,
however, exonerate Clinton, who could have saved the government
millions of dollars and the country months of turmoil had he
admitted in January 1998 the true nature of his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde told the senators: ``We're not delegates who are sent here
to weigh our mail every day and then to vote accordingly. Our work
here is not an ongoing plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are elected to bring our judgment, our experiences and our
consciences with us here. I have always believed that there are
issues of transcendent importance that you have to be willing to
lose your office over.''
</P>
<P>
   Among such issues, Hyde said, are abortion, which he flatly
opposes, a strong national defense, which he supports, and equal
justice under the law.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, news reports last week from Hyde's
heavily-Republican Illinois district indicate that some of his
constituents have grown weary of the inquiry into Clinton's actions
and the attempt by Hyde and his GOP colleagues to remove the
president from office.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Chicago Tribune, Hyde is blamed by voters in
his district for prolonging the inquiry. That does not mean that
the congressman, who will be 75 in April, faces defeat if he seeks
a 14th term in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But it does mean that even many conservatives who don't support
Clinton personally are opposed to his removal from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde was right in contending that an elected official should be
prepared to sacrifice public office for issues of transcendent
importance.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people were willing to sacrifice their lives in the
wars of the 20th century for such an issue: the preservation and
protection of this magnificent nation. And many did lose their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the rule of law should govern the conduct of the man
in the White House as it governs that of every other person. But
removing a president from office through the impeachment process is
an almost revolutionary undertaking that has not happened in the
210 years since the birth of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   If the polls are to be believed, the majority of Americans do
not consider Clinton's misdeeds serious enough to oust him.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hyde believes strongly in something and so do those who
want Clinton to be censured or reprimanded but not driven from
office. That is the strange dichotomy that bestrides the nation at
the end of the 20th century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
