<P>
   GETTYSBURG _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's new budget
includes funds to tear down a controversial tower at Gettysburg
that has outraged preservationists for twoscore and seven years.
(Dart, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Spot coverage of the federal antitrust
trial of Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-COMMERCE _ Gov. George W. Bush speaks to business leaders
Wednesday at a luncheon sponsored by the Texas Association of
Business and Chambers of Commerce. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TURNER-GRANTS _ Latest grants are announced by Ted Turner's UN
Foundation. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-DIVIDE _ BRCKCO, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ An international
tribunal will meet today to settle the only piece of unfinished
business left over from the Dayton Accords: the fate of of this
most divided of cities. It's a decision that many international
observers believe, with the problems in Kosovo, could re-ignite the
war in Bosnia. Developing. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-NOOR _ AMMAN, Jordan _ Last fall, when King Hussein of
Jordan suffered a setback in his cancer treatment, Queen Noor
clasped the hands of his first son Abdullah and wept. At that
moment, she stood between the once-and-future kings of her adopted
country. The 47-year-old Noor, born and educated in the United
States and half Syrian, has been bridging cultural gaps, palace
intrigue and matters of life and death since she married into the
royal family in 1978 -- all to mixed reviews from her Jordanian
subjects. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
