<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CANNEDTOMATOES04     02-03 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CANNEDTOMATOES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fresh not always best: For authentic sauces, San Marzano is
primo
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At downtown's chic Mumbo Jumbo Cafe, chef Shaun Doty
proudly touts on the menu the San Marzano tomatoes he uses in a
pasta dish that also includes fresh sheep's-milk ricotta flown in
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that these tony tomatoes come out of a can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canned is not necessarily a bad thing,'' Doty says. ``A really
nice tuna in olive oil or a tin of foie gras can be wonderful.
Sometimes things resting in a jar can improve in flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of San Marzanos, then, as the foie gras of canned
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain flavor in the San Marzanos that says,
`That's a true tomato sauce,' '' Doty says of the unique, deep red,
pear-shaped plum tomato grown for hundreds of years in the
lava-rich soil near Mount Vesuvius south of Naples, Italy. ``It'll
take you to the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   When cooking sauces, Italian cooks have never been ashamed to
use tomatoes from a can, which frequently yield a superior product
to fresh ones that are often of less than optimal ripeness. In her
glitzy coffee-table cookbook ``Lorenza's Antipasti,'' author
Lorenza De'Medici recommends using canned tomatoes year-round when
making basic red sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, which canned tomato.
</P>
<P>
   The experts aren't the only ones who recognize there are
differences. Home cooks, too, have gotten pickier.
</P>
<P>
   Every day at E. 48th Street Market in Dunwoody (Ga.), manager
Mark Fowler knows he'll get at least three callers desperately
seeking just one thing: those canned tomatoes from San Marzano.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly popular,'' Fowler says. ``We've always had
people aware of it, but in the last year it's had a sudden rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Whole, peeled San Marzano tomatoes _ most often under brand
labels like La Bella San Marzano, La Valle and Bel Aria _ now
outsell all other canned brands at Fowler's Italian food market.
Nationally, sales of canned Bel Aria San Marzano tomatoes, packaged
for New Jersey's BelCanto Fancy Foods Ltd., jumped 60 percent in
1998, according to BelCanto sales associate Ari Ariel.
</P>
<P>
   Credit that surge to the burgeoning popularity of the
Mediterranean diet and the flood of Italian cookbooks and media
reports that have touted the virtues of Italy's various plum
tomatoes _ essential, the experts say, to replicating authentic
marinara sauce and other classic Italian fare.
</P>
<P>
   An article last year in Saveur magazine extolled the virtues of
San Marzanos in particular. Less sweet and less acidic than other
tomatoes, they have a near-perfect balance. The pulp is dense,
there are fewer seed pockets and less natural water than in
America-grown round tomatoes and its skin is easily removable.
</P>
<P>
   And famed cookbook author Marcella Hazan adds that because a San
Marzano has less liquid to boil down, it cooks faster, ``yielding
that fresh, clear flavor characteristic of so many Italian
sauces.''
</P>
<P>
   While San Marzano tomatoes can be found so far only in a few
specialty markets in larger U.S. cities, getting other first-rate,
canned Italian plum tomatoes half a world away here in America is
easier than it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to Atlanta in the '70s, I could find only one
store in Toco Hills that carried import products,'' says Camille
Sotis, owner of the Italian restaurants Camille's and San Gennaro
in Atlanta. ``That's all changed now.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite high tariffs that have doubled and even tripled the
costs of some imported Italian plum tomatoes, large supermarket
chains and outlets such as the DeKalb Farmers Market have been
selling a few brands of the canned products.
</P>
<P>
   Publix, for instance, carries whole, peeled canned Italian
tomatoes under the Cento label. Though still small, it's a brand
growing in popularity in America with more than $4.8 million in
sales in 1998 out of $468 million spent, mostly on U.S. supermarket
private labels and brands such as Hunt's and Del Monte.
</P>
<P>
   Cans aren't the only way to preserve those fresh tomato flavors.
Parmalat's imported Pomi, chopped tomatoes that are packaged in
aseptic boxes, is frequently found on shelves at A&AMP;P, Harris Teeter
and other chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're getting the purest taste of an Italian tomato you're
going to get,'' says author Carol Field, who touts Pomi tomatoes in
her cookbook ``In Nonna's Kitchen.'' ``They're just tomatoes in a
box. They also don't have the taste of the can.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you can't find imported tomatoes, some experts suggest
you try an organic domestic variety. Homestyle Italian food guru
Nancy Harmon Jenkins, author of 1998's ``Flavors of Tuscany''
cookbook, swears great Italian delicacies can be made with Muir
Glen, an organic, whole tomato grown and processed in California _
although the taste may not be exactly the same.
</P>
<P>
   Hazan advises cooks to buy whole, peeled plum tomatoes one can
at a time until they find a brand that suits their taste _ and
adheres to a few strict rules. ``There should be no pieces, no
sauce in the can, nothing but whole, firm-fleshed tomatoes, with a
little of their juice,'' she says. ``When cooked, there should be
depth to their flavor, a satisfying fruity quality that is not too
cloyingly sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   The lore of the trendy San Marzano tomato certainly fits Hazan's
description.
</P>
<P>
   In other words: It's a can-do tomato.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy canned San Marzano tomatoes at E. 48th Street
Market, 2462 Jett Ferry Road, Dunwoody , Ga.(770-392-1499) or by
mail order at Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Ave., New York, NY
10021 (212-452-0690) with a minimum order of six cans plus shipping
costs. A prepared sauce _ Rao's Homemade, from New York's renowned
Italian restaurant _ made with San Marzano tomatoes is available in
jars at Eatzi's Market &AMP; Bakery, 3221 Peachtree Road N.E., Atlanta
(404-237-2266). Both the puttanesca sauce and marinara sauce sell
for $9.99 for a 24-ounce jar.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
