<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CANNEDTOMATO-REC     02-03 2082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CANNEDTOMATO-RECIPES04-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Canned tomatoes are not only acceptable, they're preferable to
fresh
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In these recipes, canned tomatoes are not only acceptable,
they're preferable to fresh. Use Italian plum tomatoes if you can;
organic American tomatoes are a nice substitute, but realize they
tend to be more watery and have more seeds, which you may wish to
remove first.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Spareribs With Tomatoes and Vegetables for Polenta
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 1/4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Marcella Hazan's substantial concoction from her ``Essentials of
Classic Italian Cooking'' (Knopf, $30) can also be made with mashed
potatoes in lieu of polenta. But, she says, ``the juices (the
spareribs) produce are exactly the kind that yearn for a plump
dollop of soft, hot polenta to sink into.''
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 pound rack of spareribs, cut in pieces
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped carrot
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chopped canned Italian plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Polenta or pasta, optional
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Add spareribs and
brown on all sides, about 10 minutes, then drain on paper towels
and reserve. Remove all but 1 tablespoon oil from pan. Add onions,
carrots and celery and cook, stirring, until nearly tender, about 3
minutes. Add tomatoes and return spareribs to pan. Bring to a boil
and reduce heat to medium-low. Cover and cook ribs about 2 hours
until meat is tender and begins to fall off bone. Watch the cooking
liquid; when it is low, add water during cook time. Serve with
polenta or pasta if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 357 calories, 23 grams protein, 28 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 70), 4 grams carbohydrates, 91
milligrams cholesterol, 83 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Veal Scaloppine With Eggplant and Tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 25
minutes
</P>
<P>
   In her cookbook ``The Mediterranean Kitchen'' (Morrow; $16),
Joyce Goldstein offers this Sicilian recipe with a sauce made of
canned tomatoes. She says you could serve this with rigatoni for a
very inauthentic but satisfying dish (Italians eat pasta as a
course in itself and usually do not pair an entree with pasta).
</P>
<P>
   2 medium eggplants, peeled and cut in 1/2-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil, divided, plus more if needed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 to 2 pounds boneless veal loin, cut in 1/2-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup veal, beef or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons finely minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups tomato sauce (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   20 Nicoise or Kalamata olives, pitted and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup slivered fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Position oven rack 6 inches below heating element and preheat
broiler to 550 degrees. Place eggplant slices on cookie sheet and
brush both sides with about 4 tablespoons olive oil. Sprinkle with
salt and pepper. Broil for 5 minutes, then remove from oven and
keep warm. Place veal slices between sheets of plastic wrap and
pound to 1/4-inch thickness. Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Heat
remaining 4 tablespoons olive oil in large skillet over medium-high
heat. Add veal slices and brown on all sides, about 6 minutes,
working in batches and adding more oil if needed. Drain meat on
paper towels. Add stock to pan and scrape up any bits. Add garlic
and cook 1 minute. Stir in tomato sauce, olives and basil. Season
to taste with salt and pepper. Cook until heated through. Alternate
slices of veal and eggplant on dinner plates and drizzle with
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If serving pasta on the side, increase tomato sauce to
about 3 1/2 cups to have enough to cover pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 346 calories, 30 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 55), 9 grams carbohydrates, 113
milligrams cholesterol, 328 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Tomato Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 quarts
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds canned Italian plum tomatoes, chopped in food processor
</P>
<P>
   2 cups tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons unsalted butter, cut in thin slivers
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In Dutch oven, put chopped tomatoes; add tomato puree and butter
on top. Stir over medium heat until butter melts and sauce is
slightly thickened, about 10 minutes. Add salt and pepper to taste.
Can be stored in refrigerator up to 1 week or frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4 cup: 26 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 3 grams carbohydrates, 4
milligrams cholesterol, 79 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Cacciatora
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This ``in the style of the hunter'' dish from ``Rao's Cookbook''
uses canned San Marzano tomatoes with an assortment of vegetables
cooked down to a rich sauce.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 2 1/2-to-3-pound frying chicken, cut up
</P>
<P>
   2 green bell peppers, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sliced white mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   4 cups crushed canned Italian plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   Pinch red pepper flakes, optional
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Add chicken pieces
and brown on all sides, about 10 minutes. Drain chicken on paper
towels and reserve. Remove all but 1 tablespoon oil from pan. Add
peppers, mushrooms and onion. Saute about 5 minutes on medium heat;
add wine and stir for 1 minute. Stir in broth and tomatoes. Add
oregano and pepper flakes and bring to a boil. Add chicken and
simmer, uncovered, on medium-high heat about 30 minutes until
chicken is tender and sauce is slightly thickened. Add salt and
pepper to taste. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 430 calories, 33 grams protein, 24 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 19 grams carbohydrates, 45
milligrams cholesterol, 396 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Fillet of Halibut With a Savory Tomato Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Lidia Matticchio Bastianich's ``Lidia's Italian Table'' (Morrow,
$26) includes this scrumptious fish dish. While she says halibut is
not found in the Mediterranean, its Italian cousin _ the rombo
(which the French call turbot) _ is. They are in the same family of
flatfish.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 celery ribs, diced
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 28-ounce can peeled Italian plum tomatoes, crushed lightly and
passed through a food mill or coarse sieve
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup loosely packed minced fresh Italian parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds fresh spinach, tough stems removed, thoroughly
washed and drained
</P>
<P>
   Pinch crushed red pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 5-to-6-ounce pieces halibut, grouper or salmon fillet
</P>
<P>
   In a medium-size skillet, heat 5 tablespoons of the oil over
medium heat. Add the celery and 4 of the garlic cloves and cook,
stirring, until celery is wilted, about 3 minutes. Add tomatoes and
parsley. Season with salt and pepper. Cook until sauce is lightly
thickened, about 10 minutes. Keep warm. Meanwhile, in a large
skillet, heat 2 tablespoons of the remaining oil over medium heat.
Add the remaining 2 garlic cloves and cook, stirring, until golden
brown, about 3 minutes. Add about half the spinach and the red
pepper and cook, tossing, until the spinach is wilted.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining spinach a handful at a time, adding more as
each handful in the skillet wilts. Cover the skillet and cook,
stirring occasionally, until the spinach is tender but still bright
green. The whole process should take about 5 minutes. Cover, set
aside and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Pat the fillets dry with paper towels. Season generously with
salt and pepper and coat with the remaining 1/4 cup oil.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large skillet, preferably nonstick, over medium-high
heat. Add the fillets and cook, turning once, until well-browned on
both sides and barely opaque in the center, about 8 minutes. Drain
any oil from the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Drain any liquid from the spinach and divide the spinach among
six serving plates. Top with fillets. Remove the garlic cloves from
the tomato sauce and spoon the sauce over and around the fish.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 332 calories, 34 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 11 grams carbohydrates, 45
milligrams cholesterol, 396 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Minestrone
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   This dish from Frank Pellegrino's ``Rao's Cookbook: Over 100
Years of Italian Home Cooking'' (Random House, $40) is
protein-potent.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fine-quality olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped whole leeks
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peeled and diced potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced celery
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fava beans, fresh, canned or dried
</P>
<P>
   1 cup green peas, fresh or frozen
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canned Italian plum tomatoes, with juice
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken broth or water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cups cooked cannellini or kidney beans
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly grated Pecorino Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large stockpot over medium-high heat. Stir in
onions, leeks, parsley and thyme. Lower heat and saute for about 5
minutes or until onions begin to brown. Add potatoes, carrots,
celery, zucchini, fava beans and peas _ one at a time _ sauteing
each for about 3 minutes. When all the vegetables are sauteed, stir
in tomatoes, broth and salt and pepper. Bring to a boil. Lower heat
and simmer for about 1 hour, until soup is thick. Add cooked beans,
mashing some against the side of the stockpot with the back of a
spoon as you stir them in. Cook an additional 5 minutes. Remove
from heat and stir in basil. Serve sprinkled with Pecorino Romano
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 392 calories, 12 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 44 grams carbohydrates, 3
milligrams cholesterol, 276 milligrams sodium, 10 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Farfalle With Simple Tomato Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 3 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2-3 hours
</P>
<P>
   Using canned San Marzano tomatoes, we adapted our own marinara
recipe into a vibrant red sauce perfect for bow-tie pasta. The
proof came after the meal: We caught our kids in the kitchen
dunking big chunks of bread into the leftover sauce and happily
devouring it.
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 medium white onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 35- or 36-ounce can whole Italian peeled plum tomatoes with
juice
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces concentrated tomatoes (paste)
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pinch granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 or 6 big sprigs fresh basil, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried farfalle pasta
</P>
<P>
   Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Put 2 tablespoons olive oil in large saucepan and turn heat to
medium-high. Add garlic and saute. As garlic begins to turn pale
gold and garlic aroma starts to rise, put in chopped onion and
continue cooking until onion turns translucent.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-squeeze canned whole tomatoes into the saucepan or break up
tomatoes into meaty chunks with wooden spoon. Add concentrated
tomatoes and water. Stir until fully incorporated. After a minute
or so, salt and pepper to taste, then add pinch of sugar and stir
again. Then add chopped basil, at least 2 more tablespoons olive
oil and stir again until oil is fully incorporated. Reduce heat to
low and cook for at least 2 and up to 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Cook pasta in large pan according to package directions. When
pasta is al dente, drain and return to pan. Add 1 or 2 tablespoons
olive oil and toss. Add tomato sauce and stir until pasta is
well-coated. Place pasta on dinner plates or in pasta bowls,
sprinkle with fresh grated Parmigiano-Reggiano and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 438 calories, 12 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 27), 69 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 425 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
