A0188 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE04-COX     02-03 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heavenly sites abound for `food of the gods'
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mmmmmmmmmm Choooooooc-laaaaate!!!, swoons Homer Simpson _ and
everybody on the planet can relate.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteenth-century Swedish naturalist Carolus Linneaus, who
created the modern system of naming all living things on Earth,
definitely made the connection when he named the tree from which
chocolate comes ``Cacao theobroma'' _ no less than ``food of the
gods.'' Indeed, the world has had an enduring passion for this
sweet confection for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   This is the season, of course, for chocolate lovers to openly
indulge their passion, and the Internet increases the pleasure by
offering total immersion to anyone surfing the thousands of
chocolate-related sites.
</P>
<P>
   There are chat rooms, histories, scholarly treatises and
chemical analyses, Q&AMP;A's and reviews. There are companies that will
duplicate anything (and we mean anything) in chocolate, there are
ongoing chocolate soap operas, chocolate poetry, and, naturally,
most all the sites contain an abundance of luscious recipes from
brownies to bombes.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a rundown of some chocolate addresses to get you
started.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start at the beginning with one of the best histories of
chocolate we ran across. ``This delightful tale ... draws upon
botany, archaeology, socioeconomics and culinary history to clear
up the ambiguities and misconceptions, presenting ... a complete
and accurate history of chocolate.'' See
http://www.wwnorton.com/thames/501693.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  After history comes trivia. Did you know that:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nine out of 10 people like chocolate. The tenth person
always lies.'' John G. Tullius (born 1953), American artist and
cartoonist.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Americans eat about 10 pounds of chocolate a year per capita,
the Swiss about 22.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chocolate in a blue wrapper won't sell in Shanghai or Hong
Kong because the Chinese associate blue with death.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Queen Victoria was such a devotee that she sent 500,000 pounds
of chocolate to her troops one Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   For more great chocolate trivia see
http://home.earthlink.net/(tilde)wallerdesign/trivia.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For the connoisseur, here's a list of chocolate reviews rating
brands from one to five. At the top, with five-bar ratings, are
Callebaut Bittersweet and Valrhona Noir Amer. Hershey's milk
chocolate is given two bars and Dove dark a 3.5. See
http://www.hhhh.org/cloister/chocolate/reviews/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``One Passion'' at http://www.choco.com/ is on the silly side.
You'll find contests, more trivia and a humor page where there is
something called ``chocolate ritual'' that was obviously put
together by people totally over the top.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ``Chocolate Lovers' Page'' is a good example of how
chocolate has proliferated on the Internet. The site was founded in
1994 as a simple list of 20 chocolate shops, and now it claims to
be ``the most comprehensive list of chocolate Web sites in the
world.'' For links galore see
http://www.links2go.com/more/chocolate.emanon.net/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you want to get into some serious candy making in your own
kitchen, dial up ``Chocolates by You'' at
http://www.chocolatebyyou.com/ for information about lessons, molds
and the supplies you'll need to make your own chocolate
confections.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Looking for a mold for a chocolate jigsaw puzzle? See
http://www.jigsawpuzzle.com/chocjigs.htmnd.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Or perhaps a T-shirt with the chemical structure of chocolate
printed on it? Go to http://www.gaftee.com/welcome.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And finally, here are some standout chocolate recipe sites:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.kitchenlink.com/chocolate.html.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.geocities.com/NapaValley/4908/choco1.htm.
</P>
<P>
   http://ei1.ei.ele.tue.nl/(tilde)paul/recipes/alphanames.html.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.hersheys.com/cookbook/chocolate/.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.godiva.com.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.kaiwan.com/(tilde)perew/choctalk.html.
</P>
<P>
   http://chocolate.emanon.net.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.guittard.com/recipes.htm.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ajlc.waterloo.on.ca/Recipes/Chocolate/.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Valentine's Day!
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Reduced-Fat Chocolate Amaretto Mousse
</P>
<P>
   Makes 9 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation and chilling time: 2 1/4 hours
</P>
<P>
   Microwave time: 1 1/2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1package (8 ounces) Neufchatel cheese (reduced-fat cream
cheese), softened
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4to 1/2 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   1envelope unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   1cup reduced-fat semisweet baking chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup skim milk
</P>
<P>
   2cups frozen light nondairy whipped topping, thawed
</P>
<P>
   Sliced fresh peaches or strawberries
</P>
<P>
   (optional)
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor bowl, combine Neufchatel cheese,
confectioners' sugar, vanilla and almond extracts; process until
smooth. In small bowl, sprinkle gelatin over water; let stand 3
minutes to soften. In medium microwavable bowl, place chips and
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Microwave on high (100 percent) 1 1/2 minutes. Add gelatin
mixture; stir until gelatin is dissolved and mixture is smooth.
Pour chip mixture into cheese mixture; process until smooth, about
2 minutes. Add whipped topping; process until blended, about 1
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into individual dessert dishes. Cover; refrigerate about 2
hours or until set. Garnish with fruit, if desired. _ From Hershey
Kitchens
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 210 calories, 5 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 50), 23 grams carbohydrates, 25
milligrams cholesterol, 115 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
