A0191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TOMATOTIPS04-COX     02-03 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TOMATOTIPS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to choose cream of the crop
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The experts have sage advice on ways to ensure your canned
tomato is the best tomato it can be:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Why whole tomatoes over crushed or pureed ones? Whole tomatoes
guarantee higher quality, says Ari Ariel, sales associate of
BelCanto Fancy Foods Ltd. of New York. ``Chopped (and pureed) is
sometimes whatever is left over.'' Cookbook author Julia Della
Croce agrees that the quality of crushed tomatoes is sometimes
unreliable. But, she says, ``if you find a brand that is
consistently thick and chunky instead of watery and thin, with
good, sweet flavor and no sugar or other additives, stock up on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What about ``Italian Style''? Italian food maven Marcella
Hazan warns that the word ``style'' on can labels often means
Italian spices such as basil and oregano have been added to
non-Italian tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How significant is the single basil leaf added in some cans of
authentic Italian plum tomatoes? ``It's for the trash,'' Hazan
says. One basil leaf, she says, doesn't add a thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How do I judge quality in a canned tomato? ``It must, of
course, look red and healthy,'' Atlanta restaurateur Camille Sotis
says. ``If you open it up and see all this orange and yellow, the
tomatoes are less ripe.''
</P>
<P>
   Della Croce advises that the labels ``should list no additives
or sugar. Tomatoes should be meaty and whole, not flabby and
disintegrated. Fleshier tomatoes produce thicker sauces, with more
body than thin, watery ones. Nor should they be excessively seedy.
Their flavor should be full-bodied and sweet, not overly acidic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does price matter? ``You get what you pay for,'' says Mumbo
Jumbo chef Shaun Doty. ``I've seen people buy really cheap stuff
and get stems and unripe tomatoes in return.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How long can I keep an opened can of tomatoes? Tomatoes
oxidize rapidly and lose mineral value once exposed to air, Della
Croce says. So canned tomatoes should be used very soon after
opening the can.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
