<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-49ERS-STADIUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDER PROPOSES LESS-EXPENSIVE STADIUM FOR 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A builder working on the expansion of the San
Francisco International Airport says he can construct a stadium for
the 49ers football team for as much as half as the current
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan for replacing Candlestick Park was estimated
at $325 million, and later grew to more than $500 million, putting
the proposal in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Willie Brown said Tuesday that Ronald Tutor, the
chairman of Tutor-Saliba Corp., said his company could do the job
for $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tutor-Saliba tells me that, in a period of between 24 to 30
months, they can build a stadium for the city and county of San
Francisco ... and they can do it for $250 million,'' Brown said.
``That is exactly what Ron Tutor represented here in City Hall, and
that information has been passed on to the 49ers for them to take
the appropriate look.''
</P>
<P>
   The outside estimate could be one of the few pieces of good news
in a year for a project that Brown invested so much political
capital in and voters approved narrowly in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The city-backed plan called for a stadium and adjacent shopping
mall at Candlestick Point to be partly financed by taxpayers
through a $100 million bond issue.
</P>
<P>
   The project has been on hold not only because of costs, but
because the team's co-owner, Edward J. DeBartolo Jr., was indicted
in a Louisiana government corruption investigation.
</P>
<P>
   John Wasson, the 49ers stadium project director, said Tuesday
the team's owners welcomed Tutor's input and have reviewed his
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Wasson said the $250 million price tag didn't take into
account everything involved in building a stadium, including design
work, environmental review and other costs beyond construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these things, like in any budget, you have to look at what
pieces are being counted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tutor could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The team's original plans called for a 72,000-seat stadium with
the Mills Corp. of Arlington, Va., building a
1.4-million-square-foot shopping and entertainment complex next
door for an additional $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tutor's Los Angeles-area company is familiar with stadium
construction. Tutor-Saliba, through a joint venture, built Bank One
Ballpark in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Also known as ``The BOB,'' the stadium opened in April as the
home of the Arizona Diamondbacks baseball team. Wasson managed that
project, which was completed, he said, at a cost of $360 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tutor-Saliba also is involved in the expansion of the Oakland
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Serious questions about the 49ers stadium project were first
raised after DeBartolo, facing indictment, relinquished his title
of chairman of the 49ers and handed over operations to his sister,
Denise DeBartolo York.
</P>
<P>
   She heads the team's parent company, the Edward J. DeBartolo
Corp., of Youngstown, Ohio. Since then, DeBartolo has agreed to
cooperate in the case against former Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards
and pleaded guilty in October to concealing a crime.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, York issued a statement saying estimated
stadium costs had ballooned to $525 million and suggested the team
might abandon the project.
</P>
<P>
   The window of opportunity is shrinking if the stadium is to be
built in time for the 2003 Super Bowl, which was promised by the
National Football League as an inducement to voters to support the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The financing deal has been tied up in litigation alleging
irregularities in the June 1997 election in which the city bonds
were approved for the stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
