<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR BIRDS IN CATTLE COUNTRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSVILLE, Texas _ Spreading over 825,000 acres and larger than
the state of Rhode Island, the 146-year-old King Ranch is renowned
for developing two major breeds of cattle and producing the first
registered American quarter horse.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't come to admire the Santa Gertrudis or King Ranch
Santa Cruz cattle or the 29,000 white-tailed deer that roam this
vast land. Neither is the main focus the King Ranch Museum or King
Ranch Saddle Shop, both popular attractions in downtown Kingsville.
</P>
<P>
   I have another priority. The search for ``butter butt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we call the myrtle warbler, or yellow-rump
warbler,'' says Tom Langschied, who conceived and directs nature
tours at the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I need to fess up. I'm not a birder. Or wasn't. Truth is,
I'd always been rather intimidated by men and women dedicated to
recording every new species they spy. I remember how Miss Jane
Hathaway was so devoted she almost stopped chasing Jethro on ``The
Beverly Hillbillies.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd never keep a birding checklist. Would I?
</P>
<P>
   This new-found interest had begun _ and almost ended _ two days
earlier at the Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge near Port
Isabel. We stood for the better part of an hour in what is known as
a ``photography blind,'' a camouflage of sorts devised so that
humans can watch wildlife without disturbing it.
</P>
<P>
   Real birders probably would call this cheating. I didn't care. I
was mesmerized by the bright red cardinals and long-billed
thrashers and green jays. Especially the green jays, unique to this
part of the world. Two strikingly beautiful green jays. No, four.
Now 10 green jays. Each busily devouring oranges placed on a tree
trunk to attract them. More cheating, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Thrilled by this discovery, we turned to leave when a man
approached carrying a sheet of paper and enormous binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know where I can go to see the aplomado falcon?,'' he
stammered. ``I understand they've just been released here. It's so
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I said with all sincerity _ and naivete _ ``but there
are some beautiful green jays a few steps away.''
</P>
<P>
   He scowled, obviously irritated. ``Green jays? That's nothing.
There are thousands around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Deflated, my first reaction was to return to the hotel and watch
television. I couldn't distinguish a rare sighting from a common
occurrence. But, then, I thought, ``So what?'' I look at a painting
and don't know if it's worth $100 or $1 million. But I relish
sauntering through an art museum and marvel at the creativity of
even an amateur artist. I sip a glass of red wine and can't tell if
it's from Australia or California. But I know what tickles my taste
buds.
</P>
<P>
   So, undeterred, we drove for two hours on an unpaved loop within
the refuge, stopping now and then to watch the brown and white
pelicans (Brown pelicans dive awkwardly; white pelicans are more
graceful. See, I'm learning.) frolic along the Laguna Madre Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Next day, we ventured to Sabal Palm Audubon Center and Sanctuary
in Brownsville and the Santa Ana National Wildlife Refuge west of
Harlingen, where we saw the bright orange Altamira oriole and the
yellow-and-brown great kiskadee. And an enormous great blue heron
perched high atop a post.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I didn't bother keeping a list of sightings. Until today.
At the King Ranch I check off each bird that appears: the belted
kingfisher, red-tailed hawk, solitary sandpiper, golden-fronted
woodpecker. ``Wow, look, there's an olive sparrow; we're fortunate
today,'' Tom Langschied says, his enthusiasm encouraging our
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, see the bright red on the vermillion flycatcher,'' he
says. ``And over there, the ruby-crowned kinglet.''
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then, Langschied steps out of the van he drives
during these nature tours and calls to the birds, luring them
closer. ``Let's see if we can coax out the eastern screech owl,''
he says, then lets out a piercing shrill.
</P>
<P>
   But what's this? ``It's the myrtle warbler,'' Tom says. ``It's
butter butt.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 3 1/2-hour tour, we record 63 species. ``Not bad,''
Langschied says. ``We have more than 300 species on the King Ranch.
But we've got 1,300 square miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Nature tours here date only to 1994, reflecting the growing
interest in birding. Participants also are likely to see deer and
javalina, maybe even bobcats, but the emphasis is aviary.
</P>
<P>
   Beginners are welcomed. ``Birding can be whatever you want it to
be,'' Langschied says. ``There is a beauty that everyone can
enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Little, ornithologist for whooping crane excursions aboard
the Wharf Cat boat from Rockport and Port Aransas, echoes those
sentiments. ``I teach a five-day class at Elderhostels,'' he says.
``Some folks think that when you get to be 55 years old, you're not
supposed to learn anything new. But you should see how eagerly
people get into bird-watching. By the end of the class, they're
asking me what kind of binoculars and scopes to buy and the best
places to see different birds. Some of them write me with
descriptions of what they've seen, and I identify it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we'll add to our list. Maybe not. Maybe some day we'll
look for that aplomado falcon. Or just go back to that photography
blind and watch the green jays eat oranges.
</P>
<P>
   With no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--------------------------- &QL; 
 &QL; 
Note: Half-day nature tours in vans are scheduled Mondays,
Thursdays and Saturdays at 8:30 a.m. CST and 1:30 p.m. through
March 20 at the King Ranch. Cost is $17.50. Full-day birding tours
(``Real birding,'' Tom Langschied describes these) begin March 22
and cost $99; call for dates. Customized tours can be arranged.
Reservations are essential. Other tours by bus focus on the ranch's
60,000 cattle and its history. Phone: 512-592-8055. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
