A0224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-CORPUS-H     02-03 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-CORPUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELAXED ATMOSPHERE IS CORPUS CHRISTI VIRTUE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ Unwind with a leisurely jog along one of
America's loveliest urban seawalls.
</P>
<P>
   Buy shrimp fresh off a rustic trawler in the shadow of
glittering skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   Admire passing sailboats _ their designs reflecting a rainbow of
colors _ from an open-air pavilion overlooking the tranquil water
in a downtown marina. Better yet, rent a kayak and paddle away your
cares among the pleasure yachts and sightseeing boats.
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully situated along Corpus Christi Bay _ and less than an
hour's drive from the Gulf beaches on Padre and Mustang islands _
this thriving city of 350,000 residents maintains the same low-key
ambience of much smaller neighboring towns.
</P>
<P>
   Its heart is at the waterfront, where restaurants tempt with the
mouth-watering catch of the day and old-style seafood shops market
a bounty of riches.
</P>
<P>
   Romantics gravitate to the shade and solitude of the Miradores
del Mar, gazebolike pavilions where on a crystal-clear day vistas
extend seemingly forever.
</P>
<P>
   The Mirador de la Flor, on Shoreline Drive at the base of
Peoples Street downtown, includes a statue dedicated to Selena, the
late Tejano singer who lived here.
</P>
<P>
   The seawall, 2.5 miles long and 14 feet high with a sidewalk up
to 20 feet in width, was designed prior to World War II by sculptor
Gutzon Borglum of Mount Rushmore fame. It's ideal for running,
walking and roller skating, spying on shorebirds or watching the
traditional Wednesday-night sailboat regattas.
</P>
<P>
   Extending to the southeast, as Shoreline Boulevard becomes Ocean
Drive, a seven-mile scenic drive is lined with parks, walking
trails and the city's stateliest homes.
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi, which hosts 5 million tourists annually, also
boasts high-quality attractions that appeal to those with interest
in science and history.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Texas State Aquarium, located across Harbor Bridge from
the center of town. A new jellyfish exhibit is drawing acclaim. Up
to 12 educational programs are presented daily. Phone:
800-477-4853.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lexington Museum on the Bay, a World War II aircraft
carrier adjacent to the aquarium. Its flight deck includes more
than 20 historical airplanes. Phone: 800-523-9539.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Corpus Christi Museum of Science and History, at 1900 N.
Chaparral about half-a-minute from the center of town. This
facility is home to the Pinta and Santa Maria, two of three ships
in the ``Columbus fleet'' _ reproductions commissioned by Spain to
celebrate the 500th anniversary of the explorer's voyages to the
New World. Phone: 512-883-2862. (The area code changes to 361 in
mid-February.)
</P>
<P>
   A Corpus Christi ``Fun Pass'' costs $21 and allows admission to
all three attractions. It's available at each location.
</P>
<P>
   Other lures include the Corpus Christi Botanical Gardens; the
Asian Cultures Museum; Heritage Park, which features nine restored
historical homes; and the Art Museum of South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about these and other enticements or about
upcoming special events, lodging and dining alternatives, golfing,
fishing excursions and other recreation, call 800-766-2322. Access
www.cctexas. org on the Internet. Or make your first stop the new
visitor center at 1823 N. Chaparral (near the Museum of Science and
History, Asian Cultures Museum and Heritage Park).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
