<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0259 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CELL-PHONES-ART-2     02-03 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CELL-PHONES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK IS CHEAP? IT ALL DEPENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T'S announcement last week that it would offer long-distance
and wireless service at a single rate of 10 cents a minute was yet
another sign of how enmeshed wireless service is becoming in the
fabric of our daily life.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a cellular phone is just another household phone
number. Sometimes it's the only telephone. Of course, rate cuts are
nothing new; competition among the wireless service providers
constantly forces them to offer better deals.
</P>
<P>
   But now carriers like AT&AMP;T are selling not only long distance
and cellular service, but Internet connections, too, all presented
in one monthly bill. The result is that customers have new
opportunities, and a whole new set of decisions to make.
</P>
<P>
   What's a telecommunicator to do? In the most competitive
markets, like Boston, Seattle, New York and Los Angeles, five or
six carriers offer up to a hundred service plans. How to sort
through them? The new world without wires may seem daunting, but it
needn't be.
</P>
<P>
   If you are thinking of buying a cellular phone, or if you
already have one and are thinking of switching carriers or moving
up from analog to digital cellular, ask yourself a few fundamental
questions before setting foot in one of the growing number of
stores selling wireless phones and service plans, places where
salespeople will often sell first and educate later.
</P>
<P>
   Start off with these: Do you travel a lot? Do you make more
local calls than long distance ones? Will you use the phone just
occasionally or is it likely to become an extension of your ear?
Are you looking for a phone to keep in the car for emergencies? You
might think you are interested in spiffy features like voice mail
and e-mail retrieval, but will you really use them?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are carriers and plans to satisfy most every need out
there,'' said Mark Lowenstein, a senior vice president at the
Yankee Group, a technology research company in Boston. He said the
single most important thing consumers could do was to take the time
to write down their needs and research their options.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than ever, consumers need to go through this process,''
he said. ``It's easy to get under the wrong plan and get turned off
to wireless.''
</P>
<P>
   The two most recent developments in cellular phones have been
the all-you-can-eat calling plans and the rise of the digital
phone.
</P>
<P>
   New digital networks are being touted by companies like Sprint,
Omnipoint and others as a great improvement over the analog network
that has been in place since the early 1980s. That is because the
newer networks transmit information via digital signals. That gives
digital cellular phones many advantages, like greater security,
compared with analog phones.
</P>
<P>
   They are smaller and lighter, their batteries yield longer
standby and talking times, and they offer added features like
three-way calling, Caller ID and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Digital cellular service can also cost less. In fact, calls can
be 25 percent cheaper per minute than analog calls, and sometimes
even cheaper than that.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is a catch: Digital service seldom comes with a free
phone, as most analog plans still do. Although some carriers sell
discounted phones for $50, count on paying at least $100 for a
good-quality digital phone.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, digital phones outsold analog phones in the United
States for the first time, according to preliminary figures from
Dataquest, a market research company.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean you should follow the pack. Though digital
phones are billed as having clearer sound, not everyone who uses
them finds that to be true. Many people complain that receiving a
call from someone using a digital phone is like getting a call from
the bottom of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Weak signal strength, caused by spotty network coverage, is also
a problem. Experts say that the quality of the calls depend heavily
on the quality of their underlying networks and that analog calls
have long had their own sound-quality problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Digital service is now available in about 70 percent of the
United States, compared with coverage of more than 90 percent for
analog service.
</P>
<P>
   A very important way to find out if a digital phone will work
for you is to ask your neighbors about their experiences. If they
report that their digital phone works fine in the kitchen but not
upstairs in the bedroom, think twice about buying one.
</P>
<P>
   You have probably heard a lot about PCS in the last couple of
years. PCS, which stands for personal communication services, is
just digital cellular service that operates at a higher frequency.
The difference is mostly in the marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Digital networks use three different and incompatible standards.
As a result, many digital phone owners cannot use their phones
freely outside their home service areas. To solve that problem,
carriers have introduced dual-mode phones that can operate as
digital cellular or analog phones.
</P>
<P>
   If the phone is unable to detect a digital signal, it defaults
to analog and, theoretically, the call continues seamlessly. In
reality, the experts say, how well this function works can depend
where you happen to be calling from when it happens.
</P>
<P>
   The tradeoff for this feature is shortened battery life, said
Matt Hoffman, a senior analyst at Dataquest, because once the phone
defaults to an analog network, it needs more battery power.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line on digital phones is this: If you travel a lot,
especially to rural areas where digital service is not likely to be
available, then buy an analog phone and wait for the digital
networks to improve.
</P>
<P>
   As for service plans, the consumer never had it better. AT&AMP;T's
One Rate cellular service, introduced just last May, eliminates
extra charges for using its phones on other companies' networks,
known as ``roaming,'' and gives customers 600 to 1,400 minutes of
calls per month for a flat monthly rate of $90 to $150.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes AT&AMP;T's Personal Network plan, which will cost about
$30 a month plus 10 cents a minute for air time. For the first
time, the rates for calling someone across the country on a
wireless phone will cost the same as calling from a home telephone
or phone booth. Other companies have similar plans in the works.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to roll over your service from an existing contract
to a new plan, you will have to ask your carrier to do so. Most
carriers are willing to do allow that, as long as you are sticking
with them, of course.
</P>
<P>
   There are several wireless shopping sites on the Web, in
addition to the ones each carrier has. One independent Web site,
Wireless Dimension has impartial and comprehensive information
about cellular service, although it does sell service plans
directly on its site (www.wirelessdimension.com).
</P>
<P>
   Wireless Dimension helps you choose a plan by looking at your
preferences and matching a service to your needs. It includes
coverage maps, provided by the carriers, but it is working to
refine those to be more realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our intention to show consumers what the real coverage
is,'' said Leigh Barer, a spokeswoman for Wireless Dimension. ``Not
that the maps are dishonest, but they don't show every nook and
cranny on your commute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1527EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0265 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SILICON-PERKS-ART     02-03 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SILICON-PERKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NERDS IN GILDED CUBICLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The (AT) word should be replaced by the symbol)  
 (ART ADV: Photos is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By GARHY ANDREW POOLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Eric Schmidt, chief executive of Novell, joined the company
nearly two years ago, he would meet a smart employee and wonder why
the person still worked there. Not only had Novell, the world's
fifth-largest software maker, missed the Internet phenomenon and
been hampered by product delays, but it also had some of the
ugliest offices in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, where many corporate ``campuses'' resemble
destination resorts, Novell looked like an hourly motel. It was
hampering Schmidt's ability to attract and retain the brightest
programmers. Salespeople were embarrassed to bring customers to the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt made the decision to go ahead with a new $130 million
campus in San Jose, Calif., with tennis, volleyball and basketball
courts, a restaurant, a gym and an espresso bar. ``To compete in an
extremely tight labor market, our campus had to have at least the
quality of our competitors,'' Schmidt said recently as he admired
his complex, which opened in December.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly proud of the look of the campus, which was
inspired by a trip to Venice. Many of the buildings are made of
Olympia cream limestone, a light-colored stone imported from
Tunisia because Schmidt was awed by the colors of St. Mark's
Square.
</P>
<P>
   To lure talent in an industry desperate for it, Schmidt and
other Silicon Valley chief executives have become part-time
architects, restaurateurs, fitness gurus and concert promoters.
Companies are trying to out-perk one another. Some of the best gyms
and restaurants here are not open to the public. As the saying
goes: Want a good meal? Go to work.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, surly servers in hairnets do not dish out
mushy mystery meat. The best meals are served at corporate
cafeterias where technology workers choose their own pieces of fish
or meat and have the chefs grill them to order. Like hoteliers,
chief executives brag to other chief executives about their chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Cooks like Lucent Technology's executive chef, Robert Sullivan,
can write their own meal ticket. ``I come in early, I leave early,
and I don't work weekends,'' Sullivan said, taking a break from
preparing a basmati rice salad with currants and mixed nuts, to be
sold at the highly subsidized price of $4.35, for employees at
Lucent's Coyote Creek Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Why are technology companies, especially large ones, so
enraptured with creating fine eateries and other perks?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in an economy that is driven by skills, and the
skills bucket is close to empty,'' said Thornton May, vice
president for research and education at Cambridge Technology
Partners, a consulting firm. ``Companies are desperate for skilled
workers. They'll do anything to recruit and keep you.''
</P>
<P>
   This flies in the face of Silicon Valley's tradition of
frugality. After all, this is the business that popularized the
cubicle, stock options in lieu of salary, casual Fridays and
tilt-ups (a Valley term for cheap office buildings).
</P>
<P>
   But as the industry has grown, a quiet revolution has taken
place. Companies flush with money are investing not only in
in-house restaurants but also in gyms with tae kwan do; spinning
and yoga classes; pool and Ping-Pong tables; free soda, juice and
fresh popcorn; massage therapists; dry-cleaning drop-off services;
car detailers; dog walkers, and roving ergonomics experts who try
to keep nerds pain-free.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't hurt to present Bob Dylan and his son Jakob _
both Grammy winners. Applied Materials paid $500,000 so the Dylans
would help the company celebrate its 30th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dylan had never played a public show with Jakob Dylan, who
headlines the Wallflowers, which meant that the 12,000 people
attending the Applied Materials private celebration had a ``once in
a lifetime experience,'' said Richard Garwacki, vice president of
Bill Graham Special Events, which organized 60 shows last year for
companies, most of them in Silicon Valley. He said that ``there's a
lot of ego involved'' as companies tried to outdo one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Valley companies have sophisticated, young
employees,'' Garwacki said. Presenting corporate-party regulars
like the Temptations, Chicago or the Beach Boys just won't cut it.
Young, hip and perhaps spoiled, geeks want bands with current hits.
``We get more requests for new bands like the Barenaked Ladies,
Matchbox 20, Smashmouth, No Doubt and the Smashing Pumpkins,''
Garwacki added.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Valley's largest growth industries is perk
subcontractors. Bay Sport, a manager of corporate fitness centers,
was co-founded by Linda and Doug Emery in 1984. Today they have 200
employees and 100 corporate clients. Although it costs $940,000 to
build an average 7,500-square-foot club and $200,000 to stock it
with the latest exercise gadgetry, Emery said he could barely keep
up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   On Sand Hill Road, a thoroughfare famous for its collection of
venture capitalists, Fedele R. Bauccio runs Bon Appetit Management
Co., one of the largest catering companies in Silicon Valley.
Starting in 1986 with a single executive dining room, Bauccio now
has 140 locations, 50 in the Bay Area. Last year his company
generated $200 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not use the term cafeteria at this company,'' Bauccio
said. ``Green beans do not sit in water for hours at one of our
restaurants. We provide fresh food rivaling any fine restaurant.''
Every in-company restaurant worth its paprika prepares food
reflecting the work force's ethnic diversity, he said, with Indian,
Japanese and Chinese foods as musts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The Oracle Corp., based in Redwood Shores, is a Bon Appetit
client that is known to have one of the Valley's best Japanese
noodle bars, complete with a baby grand piano.
</P>
<P>
   It is not likely that a genius programmer will go to a company
just because of its tasty crab cakes, step-class guru or cool
hip-hop concerts, but if a company does not provide the standard
perks, it will not get on the brightest recruits' short lists.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, at Sun Microsystems' stately Menlo Park campus, the
4,000 workers can eat at several restaurants, including the upscale
Java Java, where you can have a generous portion of porcini
mushroom and cheese ravioli for $8.25. Sun's fitness center,
Fit(AT)Sun, has the latest crazes in fitness classes, including
kick-box aerobics. And to keep employees in good humor, Sun brought
in the comedian Dana Carvey to perform at a state-of-the-company
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   To set itself apart in the perks war, however, Sun has an
on-call lactation consultant. Furthermore, it actively helps people
interested in adoption. With a $2,500 adoption stipend, Vicky Yee,
Sun's corporate diversity manager, went to Guangzhou, China, to
adopt her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Visit Autodesk's headquarters in San Rafael and you will find
dogs _ lots of dogs. Kathy Tom-Engle, a spokeswoman, estimated that
100 people had their pooches sleeping in their cubicles. ``On
occasion you'll hear a growl when you walk around here, but for the
most part, the dogs are lazy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular, and unusual, perk at Autodesk is prepared
dinners. An employee can call Rick Gernetti, a chef lured from the
film director George Lucas, and he will prepare a gourmet meal that
employees can take home and reheat.
</P>
<P>
   The company encourages the practice because it keeps employees
at work. A recent dinner selection: blackened salmon with mango
salsa, wild rice and vegetables for $6.25 per person. Gernetti and
his staff bake cookies every day, too.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these inducements, established companies are still at a
recruitment disadvantage. Since the biggest perk in Silicon Valley
continues to be stock options, start-ups have the hiring edge.
Having a steady but anonymous job at a stable company is not as
valued as getting in on the ground floor of a startup where a
person has the chance to become a multimillionaire, even the next
Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest difficulties faced by larger companies include a
perceived, and often real, lack of willingness to offer equity
options or profit sharing,'' said Michael R. Forrest, president of
Job Options, an online recruiting company. ``As the employment
market continues to tighten, they are faced with having to offer
salaries and perks to new hires that exceed what the existing work
force receives.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said Novell's new 536,000-square-foot campus had already
bolstered morale and given him confidence that he would be able to
hire hot recruits. Almost every employee has an office because
``programmers hate cubicles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt encouraged his architect, Hellmuth, Obata &AMP; Kassabaum,
to create spaces throughout the building where people could gather
and talk _ while not creating so much space that people would never
meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The density of space in relationship to people is very
important in creating a buzz,'' said Schmidt, 43, who was an
architecture student in college before realizing that he was
``truly terrible'' at it.
</P>
<P>
   During the building of Novell's campus, Schmidt was known to
say, ``Make it so no one has a reason to leave.'' That mantra seems
to be fulfilled. Eat a plate of pasta with salmon, pesto cream and
fresh tomatoes ($4.95) at Novell's (AT)cafe.com, ride a stationary
bike, sit in one of the Herman Miller Aeron chairs and have a latte
at Java City, Novell's coffee bar, and Schmidt's intended effect
seems plausible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mind if they were working 24 hours a day, seven
days a week,'' Schmidt said, half-joking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
