<HEADER>
A0267 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PHONE-CARD-2TAKES     02-03 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PHONE-CARD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO KEEP TRACK, PREPAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ark., Mass., Fla., Ohio, Texas, Minn.)   (af)  
 By ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About three years ago, Mike Norris, a home remodeler and single
parent of three in Little Rock, Ark., decided that owning a
wireless phone was a great idea. Then his bill came.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about three times the size it should have been,'' he
said. Some of the promotions and rules were confusing and he didn't
get all the breaks he expected. ``We had the weekends free, and it
didn't happen,'' he said of the calling plan he bought.
</P>
<P>
   But Norris found a way to control his bills. He dropped his
contract service and now pays for a block of time in advance. When
that is used up, he buys more. The phone industry calls this
pay-as-you-go plan its ``prepaid service,'' and Norris says it
helps him keep track of his spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to worry about a bill,'' he says. ``I don't get
anything in the mail about it.'' His cell phone, he said, ``tells
me when it needs money.''
</P>
<P>
   Prepaid phone services nearly doubled, to 1.8 million, in 1998
from their 1997 level of 533,000, according to the Yankee Group,
Boston-based telecommunications analysts. Prepaid services are
currently the fastest growing segment of the wireless phone market,
perhaps because wireless service can start up for under $100 _ and
sometimes well under.
</P>
<P>
   For many of those people, paying in advance was the only way
they could get a wireless phone. About 30 percent of the
million-plus people a month who apply for wireless service get
turned down, usually because they have no credit record or a bad
credit record, said Richard Siber of Andersen Consulting in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are turned down have a choice _ put down a deposit of
up to $1,000 for service that is billed monthly, or buy prepaid
cards. About 5,000 a month will pay the deposit, Siber said. And
the rest? ``Suffice it to say, the preponderance of those people
are accepting service through prepay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more people are using this service to control
spending than to get around credit problems.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Silverman, 27, a recruiter in Fort Lauderdale, says he uses
prepaid cards because they help him control his phone spending.
Silverman said that going out of pocket for phone time makes him
more aware of the time he spends on the wireless.
</P>
<P>
   When an announcement comes on his phone saying he is low on
minutes, Silverman heads to his neighborhood convenience store, and
usually hands over $25 for a plastic card good for 30 minutes of
local calls. He dials an access code written on the card and then
makes his call.
</P>
<P>
   Prepaid customers can use the same phone handsets as the
contract services, but they often pay more for them. Providers
often subsidize the cost of a handset for people who sign a
long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a Motorola StarTac analog phone packaged with 10
minutes of prepaid time from Topp Telecom costs $299. To buy the
StarTac analog handset without service from Bell Atlantic Mobile
would cost $279.99. The StarTac analog phone with any one year
agreement from Bell Atlantic Mobile is $149.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases the prepaid phone services offer fewer features
than contract services. Even though the companies offering prepaid
and contract services are the same _ AirTouch, OmniPoint, Sprint
and many of the Bells are among the big players in both products _
some offer service only on analog handsets, which have connections
in more parts of the country than digital handsets, but are also
more vulnerable to eavesdroppers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, these phones have experienced problems with ``cloning,''
which allows third parties to make calls on the original phone's
bill. Contract services often offer ``dual band'' phones that
automatically switch to analog where digital is not available.
</P>
<P>
   Prepaid phone service generally costs more per minute than
contract service. The contracts lock the consumer into a year or
multi-year deal, selling a specific number of minutes each month at
a specific price, often as little as 10 cents a minute, even for
some long distance calls. The consumer pays a premium for using
more minutes than the contract allows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   According to Boston Communications Group, which runs prepaid
programs for companies like Southwest Bell and Airtouch, prepaid
calls range from 42 cents a minute to 80 cents a minute, depending
on who's selling the service and the area of the country. Some
prepaid services also charge for long distance, roaming and
directory assistance. Most have an activation charge of about $50.
</P>
<P>
   But rates have gotten progressively lower since prepaid service
was introduced in late 1996. The national average prepaid cost in
October 1998 was 58 cents per minute, down from an average of 67
cents per minute in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many carriers are finding out prepaid card buyers are not just
the credit-challenged,'' said Kevin Thigpen, Vice President and
General Manager of Boston Communications Prepaid Services Division.
``People who would like to control their budget, or who want to use
it for gift giving, or people who just want to avoid a contract buy
them too.''
</P>
<P>
   The providers haven't done much to promote prepaid service, but
that is changing. Companies are learning that having their cards in
gas stations and convenience stores helps to build brand
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Companies hope to use that visibility to graduate prepaid users
into contract users. For example, take Jody Arrowood, 22, a server
at a Middletown, Ohio, Cracker Barrel restaurant who recently
returned to her job at after having her fourth child.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Josh, decided she needed a wireless phone
to be instantly available to her babysitter. But the couple needed
to know how much they would use a wireless phone before they could
pick the most economical plan. So they are testing their use by
using a prepaid service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually we think we might go to the contract, but this is
like a trial and error,'' said Mrs. Arrowood. So far, in the first
month, each of them has used about 20 minutes of time.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Arrowood pointed out that with a contract plan, unused
minutes are forfeited at the end of a month, but the prepaid cards
typically allow 60 days to use the time, then allow consumers to
keep their leftover time if they buy another card good for another
60 days. So they may stick with prepaid.
</P>
<P>
   Parents sometimes give prepaid phones to their kids, and not
just to assure that the youngsters won't spend too much time
chatting with friends. ``As a gift you don't want to saddle the
recipient with the monthly bill,'' said Rick Borinstein, senior
vice president of merchandising for Radio Shack in Ft. Worth,
Texas, which says it is the largest retailer of wireless phones in
the country ``That's really the gift that keeps on giving.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids who want to buy their own phone usually have no choice but
to prepay. Jessica Nadeau, a 16-year student in Champlain, Minn.,
bought her phone from a convenience store in the strip mall where
she worked part time in a pizza restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of an impulse buy,'' she said. ``It just seemed
like a good deal kind of cheap. It was about $80 and there was no
monthly bill.'' She said she uses the phone sparingly, but was able
to call a friend when she was stranded at a mall.
</P>
<P>
   Because the cards can be bought with cash, people who treasure
anonymity like the prepaid system, and that group includes
criminals. Although both analog and digital phones can be tapped,
some criminals use scores of cards in a way to confound electronic
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem for law enforcement,'' conceded Edward
Allen, who is in charge of investigative technologies at the FBI in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest downside to the prepaid cards may be to the industry
itself. Once the pool of new consumers diminishes, expect a prepaid
price war, said Siber, the telecom analyst. ``It is a commodity
service at that point. Do you go to the same gas station each time,
or when you are on the highway and running low, do you stop for
gas? You go for the carrier with the most convenience or lowest
cost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
