<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     02-03 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS, SOUND, DVD: THE TEMPTATION BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In last week's thrilling episode, our hero escaped from the dank
dungeons of Divx and, accompanied by a swelling musical score
delivered in multichannel Dolby Digital surround sound, arrived in
front of a secret cave that the jini (the one in his magic
television set) said was full of sparkling cinematic treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open DVD!'' he shouted. And the cave opened to reveal ... a
confusing array of DVD video players.
</P>
<P>
   Cut! This was not in the script.
</P>
<P>
   DVD is the next step up on the evolutionary ladder from its
physical twin the CD, or compact disk. DVD players have been on the
market here for about two years, and already they have reached
critical mass confusion.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of different DVD video players to choose from,
and more are expected to arrive this spring. Prices are coming
down, and typically range from a low of $299 to well over $1,000,
depending on features.
</P>
<P>
   The disks themselves typically cost anywhere from $10 to $40 and
rentals are in the same range as videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Hooking up a DVD player to almost any TV set will result in a
better picture when playing back pre-recorded movies. The
horizontal resolution of a DVD image can be as high as 500 lines,
which is twice the resolution or sharpness of VHS video tape.
People with fancy video monitors, as high-end TV sets are called
today, get the best picture quality.
</P>
<P>
   Video is not the only advantage of DVD. All DVD players use an
audio format called Dolby Digital (also known as AC-3) and some of
the newer models can also send out a rival format called Digital
Theater Sound, or DTS. Both formats support six discrete channels
of audio: center, front right, front left, surround right, surround
left, and subwoofer.
</P>
<P>
   The poor subwoofer is not given credit for being a full channel,
so Dolby Digital is usually said to have 5.1 channels. (Not all DVD
disks carry 5.1 channels, however.) Obviously, DVD audio sounds
best when pumped through a six-speaker home theater sound system,
but it also sounds great through any stereo speaker system.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where it gets dangerous. You don't need a fancy home
theater system to take advantage of the basic features of a DVD
player, but there's no question that the most appealing features of
DVD cry out for a big video screen, a separate receiver capable of
decoding multichannel Dolby Digital and DTS audio signals, and a
six-speaker audio system. In other words, they cry out, ``This
could cost you a lot of money!''
</P>
<P>
   With a really good system, you can hear your money flying around
the room, behind you, over your head, and out the window.
</P>
<P>
   The system I used to test DVD players consisted of a 35-inch
Mitsubishi television (about $1,500), a Yamaha RX-V995 home theater
A/V amplifier and receiver (list price $999), and a set of six Bose
Lifestyle 15 Acoustimass speakers (list price $1,299).
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that even a garbage disposal could keep me entertained
if it was attached to such an impressive home theater system. Even
so, I did find a few DVD players that stood out from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   As happens all too frequently, the DVD player I liked best was
also the one that cost the most.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was the Sony DVD-S7700, based on features, quality
and performance. My friendly local high-end audio and video store
sells it for $1,199 plus $100 local sales tax, while the
impersonal, arrogant and occasionally rude online store halfway
across the country sells it for $999 with no taxes, plus $40
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was just to use the Sony S7700 as a ``reference
standard'' against which to measure other DVD players. The S7700
sets a pretty high standard, both for DVD video disks and for CD
and DVD audio, which are processed separately.
</P>
<P>
   Searching a disk for a particular scene was smooth and quick,
even in reverse, which is usually difficult for DVD players. Sony
uses many different technical tricks to give the S7700 the best
possible picture quality. Set-up and operation were relatively
painless, and the glow-in-the-dark remote control is a nice
feature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But I could also live happily ever after, or at least until the
next product generation, with the less-expensive Pioneer DVD-414
(which lists for $525 but with a street price of about $330.). The
DVD-414 was the best bargain I found, and it comes with many of the
high-end features of Sony's top machine.
</P>
<P>
   These include component-video and S-video output, both of which
yield better picture quality than the more common composite video
output. But you have to have a TV monitor that has either component
video or S-video jacks.
</P>
<P>
   While I prefer the Pioneer at about the same price, there were
quite a few write-in votes for the Panasonic DVD-A110 (about $450),
(about $400), a low-end machine that was cited positively more
often than any other player by readers who wrote in response to
last week's column on the choice between ``open'' DVD and Divx _ in
which Divx finished a distant second.
</P>
<P>
   Several letters recommended ``anything made by Toshiba'' or
``anything made by Sony.'' The advice is solid.
</P>
<P>
   The overall message from the digital mailbag was that people
seem pretty happy with their DVD players, regardless of make and
model.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some people might not want to buy a DVD player, at
least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   First, a DVD player is not a replacement for a video cassette
recorder (VCR). Today's DVD video players cannot record anything.
Given the complexity of compressing video signals on the fly _ and
there is no way to fit a movie onto a DVD disk without serious
compression _ it is likely to be years, if ever, before affordable
DVD video recorders reach the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a small risk that DVD could flop, going down the
same dead-end path as the Sony Betamax or the 8-track stereo.
However, almost all of the major motion picture, consumer
electronics and computer companies have endorsed DVD, and more than
a million DVD players have been sold so far, so it would be a
surprising flop.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear how DVD will evolve to support High
Definition Television (HDTV) standards. Most likely, today's DVD
players will work with HDTV sets, but they may not be able to play
HDTV-quality disks.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, DVD holds the potential to surpass CD audio disks
with higher-quality, multichannel sound, but not until DVD audio
standards are nailed down. Today's players may or may not be able
to play the new DVD audio disks.
</P>
<P>
   Not scared yet? Then go shopping.
</P>
<P>
   First, look for a model with 10-bit digital-to-analogue
converter (D/A converter). This is an indication of video signal
processing power. With the slower converters, movies sometimes
hiccup or exhibit the digital equivalent of dandruff. For audio, it
should say ``24 bit/96 khz.''
</P>
<P>
   If movie sound is really important to you, get a DVD player that
handles DTS sound, even though there are very few DTS-coded disks
available so far.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the salesperson to show you how easy it is to call up the
movie's menu to select video chapters and soundtracks, and then
compare how quickly each machine responds to your commands. Some
players take longer than others.
</P>
<P>
   Take plenty of time to test the remote control, because that
will be your user interface for some time to come.
</P>
<P>
   Use the remote to scan forward at various speeds _ some players
can creep ahead frame by frame _ and watch how solid the picture is
when it is paused. An even bigger test is how well the player scans
in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Movies are compressed to fit on a single DVD disk by means of a
technique called MPEG-2, which works by recording only the visual
information that changes from one frame to the next. This is swell
for people who speed through movies, but it makes it much more
difficult to go backward smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they did it that way to keep your money from flying back
into the room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
