<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-COAST-AR     02-03 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-COAST-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TREASURES: THE LOWER GULF COAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in jalapeno) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKPORT, Texas _ The whooping crane glides gracefully above the
rippling waters, its snowy white grandeur and the black-feathered
tips of its majestic 6-foot wing span silhouetted against the soft
gray clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The hauntingly beautiful crane is one of only about 365 existing
in the world _ all in North America _ and among 182 to make the
familiar journey this winter from western Canada to the Aransas
National Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Searching amid the marshes for the elusive blue crab and
oblivious to the stares of two dozen intruders aboard an excursion
boat, the whooping crane represents a symbol of peace and
contentment.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, it also represents the essence of life along the
Texas Gulf coast, from the sleepy fishing villages of the Coastal
Bend to the idyllic beaches on South Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome Winter Texans,'' billboards proclaim along highways
and side roads.
</P>
<P>
   The greetings are aimed at tens of thousands of humans who
congregate here each year to escape the bitter cold _ and the
hubbub _ surrounding their homes to the north.
</P>
<P>
   But the welcome mat is out, too, for the whooping cranes and
dozens more migratory bird species. And for the brown pelicans and
green jays and chachalacas and other species that live year-round
in a region avid birdwaters cherish as their mecca.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, this is a slice of Americana where people _
visitors and residents alike _ take the time to savor these wonders
of Mother Nature just as they linger for hours over coffee and
conversation as a breakfast ritual or appreciate the solitude of a
walk along the beach at sunrise or sunset.
</P>
<P>
   So exit the fast lane for a spell. First, the lay of the land:
Unlike much of Florida or California or Oregon, we don't merely
``drive'' the lower Texas coast. Except in dune buggies or
4-wheel-drive vehicles, that is. No roads deface the sand buildups
from just south of Corpus Christi almost to the town of South Padre
Island _ 80 miles of which is designated as the Padre Island
National Seashore.
</P>
<P>
   Most travelers congregate in one of two areas: the
Rockport-Fulton-Port Aransas-Corpus Christi corridor to the north;
or from South Padre Island and neighbor Port Isabel to Brownsville
at the Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   The inland path along U.S. Highway 77 connecting these clusters?
``Next services 50 miles,'' one sign cautions. ``Boring,'' some
would argue.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you pause at legendary Joe Cotten's barbecue
establishment in Robstown (``Here's your brisket and ribs, served
on our finest china,'' a waiter says as he spreads lunch atop a
sheet of butcher paper just as his predecessors did for former
President Lyndon Johnson, singer Willie Nelson and former pro
football player Roger Staubach.); explore the immense King Ranch
outside Kingsville; and shop for the freshest oranges and
grapefruits in Sebastian and Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Slow down, lest we violate the spirit of this Texas
treasure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`HEAVEN IS JUST LIKE ROCKPORT' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A friend in Houston tells a true story about a child who,
distraught about her elderly grandmother's death, asked, ``Where
has Grandma gone?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma is in heaven,'' the child's father replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is heaven like?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heaven,'' the father said, ``is just like Rockport.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks in Rockport _ or Fulton, Aransas Pass, Port Aransas, Port
Isabel and any number of other towns along the Texas coast _ would
readily agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this paradise,'' says Dori Sloat, a former urbanite
who moved to Rockport in 1984 and with her late husband founded a
tour boat company that offers birding and fishing excursions aboard
the 95-passenger Wharf Cat and other vessels.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just friendlier here,'' Sloat says, ``and the pace
of life is slow. And you can get anywhere in five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost.
</P>
<P>
   Only a half-hour north of Corpus Christi, Rockport is noted for
its intimate art galleries (with more than 150 artists in
residence) and the Texas Maritime Museum beside the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent Fulton is home to the ornate 125-year-old Fulton
Mansion and a shiny new 40-pound granite-and-silver Lombardi
Trophy, awarded each year by the Houston Rotary Club to the best
lineman in college football. It's showcased proudly within the
unpretentious Hu-Dat restaurant (serving ``Oriental and Cajun''
cuisine) owned and operated by Texas A&AMP;M linebacker Dat Nguyen's
parents and other relatives, all-stars themselves at preparing
sesame shrimp, orange chicken and fresh redfish with noodles.
</P>
<P>
   From November through March, one of this area's biggest lures is
being a departure point for whooping crane tours to the Aransas
National Wildlife Refuge, about a 45-minute boat ride to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Little, ornithologist aboard the Wharf Cat, has guided
birders for more than 50 years. ``Amazing, isn't it, considering
I'm only 25 years old,'' Little says. ``I like that number 25 so
much I'm on the third go-round with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Little knows precisely where to look for cranes, the world's
tallest bird at 5 feet and one of the most endangered species,
because, he explains, ``They're very territorial. Each `family'
returns to the same area of the refuge every year, and there is
never more than a male, female and one chick. Except for the
`subadults.' They tend to fly and gather in larger groups. Kind of
like human teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This territorial nature also makes it easier to count their
numbers,'' Little continues. ``That's why we know 182 are here now.
That includes 18 chicks.'' Those are encouraging numbers, too,
considering the whooping crane was on the brink of extinction half
a century ago when fewer than 30 were alive.
</P>
<P>
   Wharf Cat first mate Jay Porter's main expertise is fishing, not
birding. But he, too, is captivated by the cranes' migration.
``They're just like winter Texans,'' Porter says. ``The whooping
cranes are on vacation so they take two months to get down here,
stopping several places along the way. Then, going back they make
the trip in two or three weeks because they've got things to do at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Winter Texans'' is now the operative phrasing, having replaced
``snowbirds.'' Couples arrive by the thousands in vans and
recreational vehicles, their license plates revealing that they
hail from Michigan, Maine, Ontario, indeed almost every state and
province in North America.
</P>
<P>
   From Rockport to Brownsville, RV parks abound near the water and
miles inland. High-rise condominiums line the beaches, many
offering lodging by the month, week or night. Other visitors _
especially those from Houston and elsewhere in Texas on short-term
vacations _ choose among a plethora of chain motels and quaint
bed-and-breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty percent of our guests are here for one of three reasons:
birding, fishing or antiquing, and another 10 percent are
honeymooners,'' says Jill Jenkins, innkeeper at the exquisite
eight-room Hoopes' House overlooking Rockport Harbor and a short
walk from the Wharf Cat's dock.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour removed _ a tad longer if the lineup is long for the
free ferry that connects Aransas Pass, acclaimed as Texas'
shrimping capital, with Mustang Island _ Port Aransas offers many
of the same enticements. These include once-a-week Wharf Cat tours;
a birding center with a pier ideal for close-up viewing of
shorebirds; and an ambience that helps even a first-time visitor
feel immediately at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you blink, you might miss Port A,'' says Vickie, a waitress
at popular Pelican's Landing restaurant. ``Everyone in town goes at
a slow pace _ except us, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulars here are addicted to blue crab corn cake with jalapeo
sauce or Aransas barbecue shrimp with sausage, corn and potatoes,
described on the menu as ``finger-lickin' messy.'' Or the standing
offer is to ``bring your own fish; whether you catch it or buy it
fresh from us, we fix it your way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, people have taken to bringing in their own duck, and we
put together an appetizer,'' Vickie says. ``Before long, they'll be
bringing in shrimp and chickens and asking us to cook them.''
</P>
<P>
   Names on storefronts _ Beach Bum, Fish Tales, Moby Dick's, Salty
Dog Saloon _ attest to the character within. And for a real treat,
step inside the appropriately named Island Pepper Shack and say
hello to Fred Franklin and Pat Marsh, otherwise known as Uncle Fred
and Aunt Pat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the kind of person my dog thinks I am,'' a sign
at the counter reads. And Uncle Fred and Aunt Pat have done the
pooch, ``Little Boy,'' proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been making barbecue sauce for about 10 years, and in '94,
a friend said, `If you'd put it in a bottle, I'd buy it,'''
Franklin says. Meanwhile, Marsh was a whiz at homemade jellies.
Now, they are reigning champions at the Texas Fiery Food
competition for Uncle Fred's BBQ 'N Dippin' Sauce, South Texas
Salza, and Hot 'n Sweet Mustard, among about 15 foods they prepare
and bottle from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pushing it; I'm no salesman,'' Uncle Fred says (but
you may want to check out www.unclfred.com on the Internet before
believing him). We just make enough so that we can enjoy life and
pay for our property. We're not looking to get rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Pat affirms. ``We were going to make a batch of habanero
sauce today, but neither of us felt like it. That's the nice thing
about life here. There's no hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, nothing feels rushed or crowded _ save perhaps a
waterfront seafood restaurant in early evening or a boat jammed
with fishermen all chasing the same frisky red snapper.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever you do, leave that fancy dress and necktie at home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A RELAXING ATMOSPHERE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As former director of the Cameron County parks system,
transplanted Californian Ken Conway says he felt compelled to wear
a tie to important meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I did, the mayor had the police chief come after
me,'' says Conway, who now operates the Brown Pelican Inn B&AMP;B with
wife Vicky in the resort community of South Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wear a tie and a police officer sees you, he'll stop
you, give you a T-shirt and cite an ordinance that bans ties,''
Conway says. ``It's the same with socks; they're banned, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Get the idea that everyday life here is relaxed?
</P>
<P>
   Too relaxed, some contend, for a few weeks each spring when as
many as 125,000 students invade a town of 2,100 permanent residents
for what tourism officials tout as the ``Texas-size party of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   On summer weekends, too, the competition is intense for a prime
spot on the beach, in a fishing boat, on the golf course, or for a
table at Scampi's, Louie's Backyard, the Sea Ranch and other
popular eateries.
</P>
<P>
   But the true personality of South Padre Island _ tucked between
the Gulf of Mexico and the Laguna Madre Bay on a strip of land so
thin that only three north-south streets will fit _ runs deeper
than its 5,500 hotel rooms and condominiums, its bungee tower,
lively nightspots and Peggy's Tattoo Studio (``From mild to wild,
we do it all!!!!'').
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best place we've ever lived,'' Ken Conway says.
``It's safe; we don't have drive-by shootings here. It's soothing;
the beaches are clean and wonderful to walk, and the sunsets _
moonsets, too _ over the bay are spectacular. We have an
outstanding selection of good-quality restaurants. And there is a
warmth and hospitality in our Hispanic culture that is so
genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   This part of the lower Texas coast is a haven for winter Texans.
``A lot of people stay in RVs for two or three years, then decide
they like it so much they come back and spend the winter in a
condo,'' Conway says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some winter Texans are so happy they stay until June,'' echoes
Manuel Barroso, proprietor of Manuel's Restaurant, renowned along
with Rovans _ a larger and more eclectic eatery situated a few
blocks up Padre Boulevard _ for scrumptious breakfasts served all
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of our customers order breakfast, even in the
afternoon,'' Manuel says.
</P>
<P>
   Barroso, his sons and other family members have operated the
restaurant for 14 years. And wearing a hat as broad as his smile,
Manuel greets most customers by name. Acknowledging a visitor from
the big city, he points proudly to the Houston Rockets memorabilia
_ and countless other sports-related artifacts _ on the restaurant
walls and initiates a discussion of the team's potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say you like your chilaquiles spicy? Here, try this,''
Manuel says, a twinkle in his eye as he places on the table a
bottle of Dave's Insanity Hot Sauce whose label cautions, ``Shake
well and good luck. Use this product one drop at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooooh, Dad usually only gives this sauce to the customers he
doesn't like,'' jokes one son. (It was a joke, wasn't it?)
</P>
<P>
   Just as innovative cuisine is a trademark of South Padre Island
_ and don't pass up Scampi's peanut butter shrimp with garlic,
ginger, soy sauce, sugar, peanut butter and a touch of jalapeno _
this part of the Texas coast, and extending well inland, beckons
birders and other naturalists from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caution when flashing. Slow to 45 mph. Pelicans on road,'' a
huge sign greets motorists as they start across the Queen Isabella
Causeway _ at 2.5 miles, the longest bridge in Texas _ from Port
Isabel to South Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   Heed the warning, Ken Conway advises. Brown pelicans often
become exhausted in flight and pause to rest on the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,500-foot Laguna Madre Nature Walk near the South Padre
Island Convention Center affords viewing of brown and white
pelicans, egrets, herons and other shorebirds. Or check into the
Conways' eight-room Brown Pelican Inn and admire the pelicans from
an armchair on a porch overlooking the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour away by car is the 45,000-acre Laguna Atascosa
National Wildlife Refuge where more than 300 bird species have been
recorded. Alligators swim in ponds and white-tail deer roam
throughout. Negotiating a 16-mile driving loop (mostly unpaved, and
take it slow or risk damaging your car) can introduce a wide range
of wildlife. Or choose among several walking trails. A visitor
center provides a good introduction.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-minute drive southwest from South Padre Island leads to
Sabal Palm Audubon Center and Sanctuary in Brownsville. Another 45
minutes westward is Santa Ana Wildlife Refuge. Beyond is
Bentsen-Rio Grande Valley State Park. Each has its unique
attributes, and serious birders know them well.
</P>
<P>
   South Padre Island has long been home, too, to its ``Turtle
Lady,'' Ila Loetscher who founded Sea Turtle Inc. in 1977 to
provide education about _ and help save _ the five species of sea
turtles found in the Gulf of Mexico, all threatened or endangered.
Loetscher is now retired, but associates maintain her legacy by
conducting educational presentations on Saturday and Tuesday
mornings, with special emphasis on protection of the Kemp's ridley
turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Another focus is on the dolphins that swim in the bay and ocean,
and several companies offer boat tours to watch them frolic in
their natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the high-rise hotels and condominiums _ and, yes, soon the
spring breakers _ this concentration on nature seems especially
remarkable. But Vicky Conway says, ``There has always been an
appreciation for the beach and the bay, and now there is an
appreciation for the birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Husband Ken elaborates, ``There has been an evolution since I've
been here. People who said, `Don't get in the way of my
bulldozers,' have started realizing the economic value of
eco-tourism. More important, they recognize it as being ethically
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CORPUS CHRISTI: A PROUD CITY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All along the lower Texas coast _ even in Corpus Christi, among
the most laid-back of modern cities _ these defining
characteristics remain constant: a love of nature and the sea, of
fine food and good conversation and a relaxed lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   And pride. Pride in a hometown, a beach, a fishing boat, an
avocation, a son or daughter, an ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Step inside a museum _ perhaps the new and lovingly arranged
Port Isabel Historical Museum or Rockport's Texas Maritime Museum
or the Museum of Science and History in Corpus Christi _ and gain
rich insight into how this part of our state derived its
personality and appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a question of a ranger at a wildlife refuge and chances are
he or she will chat for as long as time allows about whatever
beautiful birds have captivated us that day.
</P>
<P>
   Pause at Gonzalez Fruit Market in Sebastian _ among about two
dozen family-run stands along Highway 77 _ and owner Jesus Gonzalez
will point eagerly to the freshest and prettiest Texas grapefruit
and oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Every town has its fascinating characters _ a Manuel Barroso, an
Uncle Fred and Aunt Pat, a Ray Little.
</P>
<P>
   Its typically tall Texas tales, some even true: ``People say we
serve just about the biggest chicken fried steak in the world,''
says a waitress at the Barn Door in Riviera as she delivers a
portion so heaping _ and costing only $7.25 _ that it barely fits
on a plate.`` (A letter from President George Bush framed on a wall
attests to his satisfaction.)
</P>
<P>
   And its keen sense of humor: ``A Dilly of a Deli; Eat Like a
Pig, Look Like a Fox,`` reads a sign outside Simon's on historic
Jackson Street in downtown Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of all this is an overwhelming sense of
contentment. We feel it during a quiet walk along a sandy South
Padre Island beach at daybreak. Savoring sunset over the marsh in
Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge. Reflecting within a
mirador, or open-air turret, along the seawall overlooking Corpus
Christi Bay. Munching on a fortune cookie and chatting with Dat
Nguyen's cousin beside the Lombardi Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Admiring the whooping crane in its graceful flight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
