<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0344 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0204-COX     02-03 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0204-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OLYMPICS OFFICIALS BALK AT GIVING UP RIGHT TO VOTE ON HOST
CITIES
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Threatened with the loss of their
cherished right to vote on Olympic host cities, International
Olympic Committee members on Wednesday expressed deep resistance to
sweeping reforms to the bidding process proposed by IOC President
Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   During a hastily organized private breakfast attended by 41 IOC
members, here for a world summit on drugs and sports, many
complained to top Olympics officials that the reforms sought by
Samaranch were indiscriminate and unnecessarily harsh.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of emotional and sometimes bitter exchanges between
IOC members and the committee's executive board, the members argued
that innocent members were being unfairly punished for the abuses
of their colleagues, said IOC members who attended the closed-door
breakfast at the Lausanne Palace hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have some bad apples, they should be thrown out, but
don't tell us the whole general assembly is corrupt,'' said Italian
IOC member Mario Pescante. ``If 20 members are guilty, then 20
members should be expelled, but we can't change the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   An overwhelming majority of the members said they opposed the
proposal, he added. ``For the first time in the history of the
Olympic movement, the voice of the members is very, very loud,''
Pescante said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Easton, a U.S. member, said he was surprised by the tone of
the meeting. ``There were some hurt feelings that we were being
classed in that group of guilty IOC members,'' Easton said.
</P>
<P>
   IOC members are fiercely protective of their right to pick host
cities, perhaps the most important function they perform.
</P>
<P>
   However, Samaranch and other top IOC officials are equally
determined to make changes in response to the Salt Lake City
bidding scandal. Fourteen members have been implicated in the
scandal. Four resigned; one was issued a warning, and the executive
board has recommended that five be expelled. The cases of three
members are still under investigation. One of those implicated died
before the allegations came to light.
</P>
<P>
   In a move to act decisively late last month, the embattled
president called for sweeping changes in the bidding process to
minimize the opportunities for corruption. The plan, endorsed by
the IOC's powerful executive board, would place the selection in
the hands of a 15-member committee, eight of whom would be from the
IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch proposed testing the system in this summer's selection
of a city to host the 2006 Winter Games, adding that it could be a
model for permanent reform. The expulsions as well as the reforms
are scheduled to go before the full IOC in a special session here
in March.
</P>
<P>
   For Samaranch, who was not present at the breakfast, the
opposition complicates his effort to steer the IOC through this
scandal. The number of members expressing resistance puts in
question whether he can muster enough votes from the full
105-member session to pass the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is under considerable pressure to contain the scandal
before it inflicts long-term damage on the image of the Games.
Olympics sponsors, who pay tens of millions of dollars to be
associated with the Games, have made it clear that they remain
committed but are worried about the impact of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rebellion in the ranks over the bidding reforms, the
IOC members expressed strong support for Samaranch personally even
as they demanded that the president reconsider his proposal, IOC
members said.
</P>
<P>
   Some members are circulating a plan to create a 15-member
committee to cull the list of bidding cities to two and then let
the full membership chose between the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Easton said the plan makes some sense because it places the
decision in the full IOC's hands at the end of the process,
minimizing the opportunities for candidate cities to lobby
individual members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if there weren't some small
adjustments,'' Easton said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said he leans toward enacting the reforms at
least for the selection of the 2006 city. ``It's certainly worth
trying as a public relations gesture to indicate to people that we
are serious about making a change,'' he said. ``Even if it hurts a
few feelings maybe that's something they must do at this point in
time.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Members also complained that the IOC's lingering corruption
inquiry is damaging the reputations of members Kim Un-Yong, Vitaly
Smirnov and Louis Guirandou.
</P>
<P>
   Smirnov says he has responded to the question raised by the
inquiry panel and is frustrated that his case hasn't been resolved.
``I'm president of the Olympic committee of a huge country,'' he
said. ``We are a country with many criminals, and sport is under
very big danger. The prolongation of this uncertain situation will
harm not only myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The special investigative commission is still reviewing the
cases of these members. However, the three have said that they have
responded to the questions raised by the inquiry and should either
be absolved or recommended for expulsion instead of being left
exposed to public contempt while the investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   Before it makes its final decision, the commission wants to
review an investigation report by the Salt Lake City organizing
committee to make sure there are no surprises, IOC members said.
The report is expected to be completed next week.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the inquiry, IOC vice president Dick Pound, said he
didn't know when his panel would rule. ``We have to proceed with
this in the normal way . . . that is, not to act without proper
evidence, nor to fail to take all the steps we can to obtain the
evidence,'' he said. ``It's going to take time and are all going to
have to live with that delay.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
