<HEADER>
A0350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     02-03 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASIC TOOLS, 2 PEOPLE NEEDED TO PUT UP A TIN CEILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only skills required to install a tin ceiling are the
ability to drive screws and nails and cut sheet metal.
Nevertheless, the job can be tedious because you have to bend over
backward to nail the panels in place. This is definitely a
two-person job.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few basic tools are required: a hammer, chalk line, a
variable-speed drill or electric screwdriver (for driving drywall
screws), aviation or tin snips, a circular saw (for cutting plywood
panels) a hacksaw with a fine-tooth blade and heavy-duty work
gloves (the edges of cut metal pieces are razor sharp).
</P>
<P>
   Even though the individual panels are lightweight, they must be
nailed to a substantial substrate or they will eventually pull
loose from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   A layer of half-inch CDX (construction grade, exterior) plywood
provides the best base for the tin ceiling because it is easy to
install, and it offers a broad nailing surface. A network of 1 by 2
wood furring strips is another alternative, but the strips must be
placed precisely so they line up with the nail holes in the tin
panels.
</P>
<P>
   Before attempting to mount the plywood, locate all the ceiling
joists and the wall studs. When you have located the joists, snap
chalk lines across the ceiling to mark their position.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the plywood panels should run perpendicular to the
joists with the edges ending on a joist. Leave about an eighth-inch
between panels to allow for expansion during humid weather. Stagger
the sheets so the ends do not meet at the same place. Use
one-and-a-quarter-inch drywall screws to attach the plywood to the
joists.
</P>
<P>
   When the entire ceiling is covered with plywood, transfer your
layout to the ceiling. Mark off the border where the cornice will
project onto the ceiling and along the walls. Then snap chalk lines
to indicate the position of the field panels. The layout is
important so double-check your work.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can nail the field panels in place, using special,
decorative ''cone-head'' nails or common one-inch flat-head nails.
Start by nailing around the edges, then work your way across the
panel. Do not set the nails around the perimeter; instead leave
them protruding out about a quarter inch so you can pull them later
to slide the filler strips in place. Install an entire row of
panels before starting the next one.
</P>
<P>
   Be especially careful when driving the nails. Dents are
impossible to remove, so you will have to fill them with auto-body
filler. To do that, first roughen the area with medium-grit
sandpaper. Apply the filler, then try to mold it (it may be easier
if you let the filler dry, then shape it with sandpaper) to match
the surrounding pattern.
</P>
<P>
   When all the field panels are in place, install the cornice
pieces. Use one- inch flat-head nails to fasten the top of the
cornice to the ceiling and longer, one-and-a-half-inch flat-head
nails to secure the bottom edge of the cornice to the wall studs.
The hardest part of installing the cornice is mitering the ends to
fit within corners. One way to cut acceptable miters is by making
an oversized miter box. Place the cornice in the box and cut the
ends with a hacksaw. Place wood blocks behind the cornice to keep
the metal from buckling as you push the saw.
</P>
<P>
   With the field and cornice pieces in place, the next step is to
place the filler panels. One edge of the filler panel slips under
the field panels; the other overlaps the bead along the top of the
cornice. At the corners, cut the ends of the filler panel at a
45-degree angle so it butts neatly with the filler panel.
</P>
<P>
   After the installation, some of the seams between the field
panels may not be tight. Inject latex caulk into these openings,
then tap the seam together with a hammer and wood block.
</P>
<P>
   Before painting the ceiling, prime it with an oil-based primer.
(A latex primer will rust the metal.) You can paint the ceiling
with either latex or oil paint. Latex is easier to apply, but brush
marks are less likely to show if you use oil-based paint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
