<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GODZILLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE GUIDE TO TRASHY FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just about everyone has a guilty pleasure tucked away, whether
it is a fondness for pork rinds or an obsession with Olympic
synchronized swimming. The glorification of truly bad films is
another popular one, judging by the enthusiasm of the readers and
writers at Stomp Tokyo (www.stomptokyo.com), a Web site celebrating
the art of the B movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stomp Tokyo is an effort dedicated to reviewing the kinds of
movies you see on cable or in the video store, but you're just too
afraid to see for fear that you might waste two hours of your
life,'' the site's mission statement says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sympathize, and so we screen these potential movie duds and
rate them on our exclusive lava lamp scale.'' The lava lamp rating
system ranges from the painfully awful (one lava lamp) to the
superior (five lava lamps). The site's links to both the exhaustive
Internet movie Database (us.imdb.com) and to Reel (reel.com), an
online video peddler, can help interested surfers further explore
the bad movies.
</P>
<P>
   The site is overflowing with detailed video reviews, news and
message boards devoted to cinematic kitsch, including hyperactive
Hong Kong action flicks and cheesy horror films. Created by Scott
Hamilton and Chris Holland, Stomp Tokyo, as the name implies, has
reviewed a large number of Japanese monster movies. More than a
dozen different Godzilla masterpieces are discussed here, as are
the exploits of some lesser-known reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gamera, Guardian of the Universe,'' which stars a giant turtle
with overgrown lower bicuspids and the ability to blast himself
into space with a set of turtle turbothrusters concealed under his
shell, earns a lava lamp rating of three on the Stomp Tokyo scale.
The film, first released in Japan in 1995, has many scenes of
Gamera battling large space-pterodactyl creatures as scientists and
the Japanese military chase them all around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``If monsters were duking it out in Tokyo, we'd be as far from
Tokyo as humanly possible,'' the whimsically deadpan review reads.
``Barcelona sounds good. Monsters never attack Barcelona.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviews of the movies are grouped by genre, with grammatically
creative category names like Comedical and Dramatical. There is
also a category called Bleeping Things, Killer Androids and Little
Green Men that contains reviews of several of the ``Planet of the
Apes'' films.
</P>
<P>
   Some current television shows are also critiqued in the site's
Diary of a Tuber section. Lisa McInnis, the writer, discusses plot
and character motivation while picking up on some of the more
superficial aspects of a show. As she observed in her review titled
``Dawson's Creek: Oy! The Pain!'' the actors had a few problems
with continuity in the wig department. ``As bad as it was, the hair
catastrophe of the premiere is a surmountable obstacle,'' she
noted.
</P>
<P>
   The site also has a letters page for its readers, an area called
Bad Movie Report and links to other places on the Web that share
Stomp Tokyo's distinctive sense of humor and video preferences. The
Stomp Tokyo is obviously not for everybody, but the site's creators
sum it up nicely: ``There's no accounting for taste, ours or
yours.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1613EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0194 </DOCNO>
