<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERS-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDOW OF SLAIN CIVIL RIGHTS LEADER TELLS STORY OF STRUGGLE IN NEW
BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if she does sound a bit overwhelmed, the quiet grace that
Myrlie Evers-Williams wears so well comes through the moment she
speaks.
</P>
<P>
   She has been in three cities in as many days for lectures, and
now the former chairman of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People is in New York to promote her new
autobiography, ``Watch Me Fly: What I Learned on the Way to
Becoming the Woman I Was Meant to Be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see it now,'' she begins, imagining what an impending
news story might say about her life full of tragedy and struggle.
`` `I spoke to her and she immediately broke into tears.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That may be what people expect, but it's simply not true. At 65,
Myrlie Evers-Williams, one of the most beloved and respected widows
of the civil rights movement, isn't crying. In fact, she is having
the time of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that when she lectures and shares her joy,
people want to know just how she kept going back in 1963 after her
husband, Medgar Evers, an NAACP field secretary, was ambushed and
shot in the back in the driveway of their home in Jackson, Miss.
How she found the strength to go back to college to get a degree
while raising three children alone. And how, in the wake of losing
a second husband, to prostate cancer in 1995, she could take over
the reins of the NAACP and in three years not only wipe out its
debt but also increase its membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young men and women ask me those questions repeatedly when I'm
on the lecture circuit,'' Evers-Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   The short answer, she says, is that she was determined to
preserve Medgar Evers' memory. The long answer is in ``Watch Me
Fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Evers-Williams is in New York when she answers the telephone at
the Michelangelo Hotel on West 57th Street, the second stop on a
13-city book tour begun last month in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The book, which Evers-Williams describes as an ``instructive
autobiography,'' reveals a religious faith that pulled her through
the severe financial worries she faced after Medgar Evers' death,
two hung-jury trials, the pain of knowing that her husband's
murderer was still at large. She admits that her grief led to
depression and self-doubt, causing her to ``take crazy risks,''
such as taking too many prescription drugs and contemplating
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   But after nearly a year, she says, she reached a point when: ``I
said, `Tighten your grip, girl, and go on with your life.' I got up
and started going, and I've never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   And so began Evers-Williams' transformation. Over the next 30
years she would go from small-town Mississippi girl to accomplished
businesswoman to national civic and political leader. Thanks
largely to her determination to see the case through, she would
eventually see Medgar Evers' killer come to trial and be convicted.
She would also find love again.
</P>
<P>
   Although written against the backdrop of the civil rights
movement, ``Watch Me Fly'' contains two beautiful love stories. One
with Medgar Evers. And the other with Walter Williams, a
longshoreman and union activist whom Evers-Williams married in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to her story than even that: ``Watch Me Fly''
is a work of self-revelation about a woman who, despite her
successes, continued to feel that she had to prove herself.
</P>
<P>
   She writes at length, for example, about the ambivalence among
members of the NAACP when she became a contender for chairman. Many
members questioned her ability to lead, saying that she wasn't
tough enough, that she'd never even been a branch president, and
that she was ``just'' Medgar Evers' widow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't even take the time to look at my
accomplishments,'' she says. ``Medgar opened the doors that me and
others could walk through, but if you're not tough enough to learn
the game and play the game, you don't stay there. I think of my
life in corporate America, in politics. I've been a trailblazer.''
</P>
<P>
   Evers-Williams admits that, because she is naturally shy, she
came to leadership reluctantly. Medgar Evers pushed her to work
with him in the NAACP field office in Mississippi. And later,
Walter Williams pushed her to run for chairman of the NAACP board.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `This is the last thing I will ever ask you to do for
me,' '' Evers-Williams recalls. `` `You run and win.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And she did. By a 30-29 vote, Evers-Williams was elected to
replace William Gibson, who was ousted after allegations of
financial impropriety. Two days later, Walter Williams died of
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In no time, Evers-Williams was crisscrossing the country,
seeking new members and money for the organization that Medgar
Evers had given his life for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were bankrupt,'' she says of the NAACP. ``We just didn't
use the term. But I, with the help of others, was able to get the
organization out of debt. In terms of policies and practices, I was
also able to clean that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Having accomplished her mission, Evers-Williams stepped down
last year from her position to begin taking care of herself. And
she does so with a mind and heart open to the same God who has
brought her this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray that as I keep still for a moment, God will guide me,''
she says. ``That's where I am right now, and it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
