<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SYMBOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGE DEVICE? `SYMBOLS' CAN HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HUBERT B. HERRING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You see a circled ``P'' with a line through it, and you know you
had better keep looking for a parking spot. You see a skull and
crossbones on a jar, and you figure you'd better not add what's in
it to your morning coffee. You even remember the peace symbol from
the flower-child days.
</P>
<P>
   But you think such meager knowledge means you have a clue about
the world of graphic symbols? Ha! You don't know the half of it _
no, not even the (italics)hundredth(end italics) of it.
</P>
<P>
   What if you saw, say, a circle abutting a square, each with a
dot in it, on the door of a house? If you took it as a child's
harmless doodling and barged in, you might be sorry. For what it
means, in ``the American system of hobo signs,'' is ``Here lives a
man with a bad temper.''
</P>
<P>
   And how about a scarecrow-like figure with its arms curled
inward? In Ghana, at least, it means ``Come back and fetch it.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be able to sketch some of these obscure symbols
on a napkin as a graphic icebreaker at the next party, head for
symbols.com, the online version of the book ``Thought Signs,'' by
Carl G. Liungman.
</P>
<P>
   A triangle with a couple of cartoonish arms emerging from the
sides, by the way, might not be the best one to start with. It is
the hobo symbol for ``man in this house is armed with a gun.'' And
if you're looking for that skull and crossbones, you won't find it
here. These are ``nonpictorial ideograms.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you want ice, you can choose among graphic
representations of ``ice grains, small, frozen raindrops,'' ``ice
granules,'' ``ice needles'' and ``ice, many signs for assembled.''
</P>
<P>
   The site includes more than 2,500 Western signs, from Cro-Magnon
carvings in mammoths' teeth to subway graffiti. Browsing is richly
rewarded, as you find two dozen types of crosses, from the cross of
the robbers to the Maltese cross to the cross of infinity, not to
mention different signs for a barking dog or a merely angry one.
There is even a British meteorological sign for dust devils.
</P>
<P>
   With each symbol comes a history of its origins, with links to
other relevant signs. The question mark, for instance, is likened
to a ``soothsayers' staff'' with ``the ideogram for a complete
wave, stood up in a vertical position, which symbolizes the contact
between the material actuality down here and the spiritual
possibilities up there.'' Thus the words preceding it ``have no
one-ness or truth'' but ``oscillate between possibilities.'' Any
questions?
</P>
<P>
   What of the word ``symbol'' itself? ``In ancient Greece,'' the
reader learns, ``it was a custom to break a slate of burned clay
into several pieces and distribute them within the group. When the
group reunited, the pieces were fitted together (Greek
symbollein).''
</P>
<P>
   But the value added _ what can't be found browsing in a book _
is that the symbols are arranged into 54 groups by graphic
characteristics. If you come across a symbol and hunger for its
meaning, you can do either an ``easy graphic search'' or, if you're
feeling like the king of your mouse, an ``advanced graphic
search.''
</P>
<P>
   Here you can try to define your symbol as ``single-axis
symmetric'' or ``multi-axes symmetric'' and sort the various lines
into permutations of ``soft,'' ``straight,'' ``crossing,'' ``not
crossing,'' ``open,'' and ``closed.'' Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   If you get frustrated, follow a link to something called ``The
Alphabet's Bastard Children'' to find ``ambigrams,'' which are
similar to palindromes but the letters themselves are played with
graphically so that a word, when flipped or seen in a mirror, comes
out identical.
</P>
<P>
   Or, when your head starts spinning with graphic possibilities
and you want to get back to basics, follow another link to
``typewriters.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, typewriters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
