<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Speed Check: Baud vs. Bps &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the baud rate the same thing as the bits-per-second speed
on a modem?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. A baud rate is the number of frequency or voltage signals
per second on a communications line (most often a telephone line).
It is also sometimes referred to as the switching speed. The word
comes from the name of J.M. Emile Baudot, the 19th-century French
scientist who invented the Baudot telegraph code.
</P>
<P>
   Bits per second, or bps, is a measure of data transmission speed
and refers to the number of bits that can pass a specific point per
second. A bit, in case you have ever wondered, is the smallest unit
of computer information storage, and its name is short for binary
digit. On most computers, eight bits add up to one byte, and one
byte equals one alphanumeric character, like a B or a 2.
</P>
<P>
   On early modems, the baud rate was the same as the bps rate,
which may be why the two terms are mistakenly used synonymously
today. An old 300-baud modem did transmit 300 bits per second. With
higher baud rates, more than one bit per second can be encoded in
each of the frequency or voltage changes. With higher baud rates,
the speed of the data transmission tends to be given in the greater
number, which is in bits per second. For example, you can have a
modem that operates at 2,400 baud but transmits data at a speed of
9,600 bits per second.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1617EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
