<HEADER>
A0380 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARIBBEANDISHES-2ndTa     02-03 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARIBBEANDISHES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Speed, $16.96) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   JERKED CORNISH GAME HENS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   Dry jerk seasonings:
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons habanero chile powder, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freeze-dried chives
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons onion powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   4 Cornish game hens, cut in half, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Combine all spices in a spice mill or blender and grind to a
fine powder. Be careful not to inhale dust.
</P>
<P>
   Rub spice blend into the chicken skin, as well as inside the
cavities. Cook on gas or charcoal grill until juices run clear _
about 30-45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 403 calories, 23 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 42 grams protein, 129 milligrams cholesterol,
128 milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``The Caribbean Pantry Cookbook'' by Steven
Raichlen (Artisan, $25)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SOUSED MANGOES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 large semiripe mangoes, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dark Caribbean rum
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup triple sec
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Heavy cream, for topping
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs mint, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Cut mangoes into thin slices, leaving skin on. In large dessert
bowl, arrange a layer of mango and sprinkle some sugar over it.
Continue this process until all the mango has been used. Carefully
pour rum and then triple sec all over the slices of mango and
garnish with grated nutmeg. Cover and place dish in refrigerator
overnight. Serve chilled with heavy cream as topping or by itself,
garnishing each serving with a sprig of mint.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving without heavy cream: 407
calories, 1 gram fat, 63 grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0
cholesterol, 10 milligrams sodium, 2 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Dorinda's Taste of the Caribbean''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   COCONUT FLAN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   Caramel:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar and water in saucepan. Cover pan and cook over
high heat for 2 minutes. Uncover pan and continue cooking until
sugar mixture caramelizes (turns a deep golden brown), 3-4 minutes.
Pour a little caramel into each of eight 1/2-cup ramekins or one
8-inch-round cake pan and tilt to coat bottom and sides with
caramel. Take care not to drip any caramel on your fingers _ it's
dangerously hot. Bring 1 quart of water to a boil. Preheat oven to
350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Custard:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   14-ounce can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark rum
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Combine coconut milk, canned milk, eggs, rum, vanilla, cinnamon
and nutmeg in mixing bowl and whisk until smooth. Strain this
mixture into the ramekins or cake pan. Place ramekins or pan in a
roasting pan. Fill the roasting pan with boiling water (1/2-inch
high). You're creating your own ``bain Marie.'' Place pan in oven.
</P>
<P>
   Bake flans until set, about 30 minutes. When cooked, an inserted
toothpick or skewer will come out clean. Transfer to a cake rack
and cool to room temperature. Refrigerate flans for at least 6
hours, preferably overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, run tip of paring knife around inside edge
of each ramekin or cake pan. Place a dessert plate over each and
invert flan onto plate. (You may need to give the flans a little
shake.) Spoon any caramel that remains in the ramekin over and
around the flan.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 501 calories, 23 grams fat, 55
grams carbohydrates, 17 grams protein, 415 milligrams cholesterol,
188 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Caribbean Pantry Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Glossary:
</P>
<P>
   Star fruit: Also called carambola, this sweet-to-tart fruit is
especially fragrant when ripe. Fruit with green-tipped ribs can be
left at room temperature to ripen. Slice crosswise, without
peeling, to use in salads, desserts or as a garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Mango: Ripe mangoes are yellow-skinned with a red blush. The
skin is a rich yellow with a musky, exotic flavor. Mangoes can be a
chore to prepare because of their large, slippery seeds. Luckily,
sliced mangoes in jars are available in many produce sections.
</P>
<P>
   Papaya: A large tropical fruit with a smooth, green skin that is
bright orange-yellow when ripe.
</P>
<P>
   Plantain: A member of the banana family that is more starchy
than sweet. Must be cooked to be edible.
</P>
<P>
   Scotch bonnet chiles: These top-shape chiles aren't widely
available here, but their taste can be approximated by using
habanero chiles.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
