<HEADLINE>
A WORLD OF FLAVORS STIRS THE SENSES IN `MELTING POT' CUISINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For wage slaves, these are the darkest days of the year.
</P>
<P>
   We're tied to our desks, caught between Christmas bills and the
tax man. There might be a vacation somewhere down the calendar, but
it's dismally far away.
</P>
<P>
   Cheer up: Culinary Zoloft is as near as your local supermarket.
Bring a taste of the Caribbean, and the sense of a holiday, to your
dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   North America uses the term ``melting pot'' to describe its
food. But with the exception of Louisiana, which melds
French-African-Spanish into Cajun/creole, we are a nation of many
separate cuisines. We have German, we have Greek, we have Italian,
we have Mexican, each standing on its own. It's our island
neighbors to the south who integrate many cultures into a culinary
whole.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that New England was being settled by
Europeans, so were the islands that stretch from southern Florida
and the Yucatan Peninsula to the coast of Venezuela. Over the next
500 years, waves of immigrants included the Spanish, the British,
the Dutch and the French. From the 1600s until the 1850s, millions
of African slaves were imported to work the sugar plantations. When
slavery was abolished, many of those jobs were filled by workers
from India and elsewhere in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   All those cultures brought elements to the communal dining
table, making Caribbean fare a cohesive cuisine, although with some
variations. The Spanish influence is seen in the ``Christians and
Moors'' (black beans and rice); the British come through with
ginger beer; and the African use of yams and okra is widely
evident. And through all of this runs a river of almighty rum.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the input of man, it's the weather that most affects the
food of the islands. Hot, hot days and a lack of refrigeration led
to a cuisine that is heavily preserved with methods such as spice
mixtures and drying. The cooking method of choice is outdoors over
island-produced charcoal. Abundant tropical fruits show up in
chutneys, marinades, jams and beverages. The incendiary scotch
bonnet pepper and its relatives promote perspiration _ a health
benefit in hot climates.
</P>
<P>
   We can't duplicate the jeweled seas or the heady aromas, but we
can appease at least one of our appetites.
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN CURRY
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons curry powder, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   Seeds from 2 cardamom pods
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, peeled and chopped; or 1 cup canned plum
tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds winter squash, peeled, seeded and cut into 1-inch
cubes
</P>
<P>
   About 1 cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   In large nonreactive heavy skillet, heat oil over medium heat.
Add onion, garlic and curry powder and cook, stirring, until onion
is wilted and translucent, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add cardamom, allspice, bell pepper and bay leaf and cook for 2
more minutes. Add tomatoes, squash, stock, and salt and pepper to
taste. Cover and cook over very low heat for 25 minutes, or until
squash is tender. Add a little more stock if mixture begins to
thicken.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 119 calories, 8 grams fat, 12
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, trace cholesterol, 16
milligrams sodium, 59 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Cooking Caribe'' by Christopher Idone and Helen McEachrane
(Potter, $25)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PLANTAIN FRIED RICE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as side dish
</P>
<P>
   4 firm, ripe plantains, fried, see Note
</P>
<P>
   3 cups hot, cooked long-grain rice or brown rice
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig parsley, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Note: Peel off skins of plantains. Cut each plantain into thirds
horizontally. Then stand each section up and cut in half
vertically. With small knife, score down either side of central
column of seeds and remove long dark strip of seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle salt and pepper over plantain sections. Pour oil for
deep-frying into a saucepan and heat until very hot but not
smoking. Quickly deep-fry plantains in oil until golden, about
30-45 seconds. Remove from oil and drain on absorbent paper.
</P>
<P>
   Divide fried plantains into 2 portions. Save 1 portion for
garnish, and cut up other portion into tiny pieces. Mix plantain
pieces with the hot rice and place in serving dish. Garnish with
remaining plantains and parsley. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 425 calories, 8 grams fat, 86
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 7 milligrams
sodium, 16 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Dorinda's Taste of the Caribbean'' by Dorinda Hafner (Ten
Speed, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
