<HEADER>
A0390 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WORDS-ONLINE-2TAK     02-03 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WORDS-ONLINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'LL TAKE HIS WEB PAGES STRAIGHT, WITH NO JAVA JIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Kan.)   (af)  
 By BENJAMIN CHEEVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everywhere I turn, there's another story or advertisement about
the Net. The copy is frequently illustrated with an enviably
attractive person sitting in front of a screen from which she has
just received masses of intensely satisfying information.
</P>
<P>
   The impression given, if never fully stated, is that most of
this red-hot stuff does not arrive in text but in pictures,
numbers, sound effects _ a new Ur data for which the tiresome old
ABC's are never or rarely employed.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived by President Dwight D. Eisenhower's Pentagon as a
system for linking government computers, the Internet (nee Arpanet)
has been called the most significant federal investment since the
Louisiana Purchase, but I'm still from Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   All this hoopla reminds me of the A.A. Milne story in ``Winnie
the Pooh'': ``In Which Eeyore Has a Birthday and Gets Two
Presents.'' Eeyore is thrilled with the empty honey jar Pooh gives
him. ``I believe my balloon will just go into that pot,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The news bulges with stories about dispensing therapy on the
Net, doing business on the Net, trolling for unsuspecting sexual
prey on the Net. Not on this computer. Most of what I do on the
electronic superhighway is write and read letters, and if it did
not involve the elimination of envelopes and a certain parallel
loosening of style, the process would be similar to the one that
once involved lambskins and sharpened feathers.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the fabulous Net to such base service may be the
equivalent of dropping a burst balloon into an empty honey jar, but
like Milne's old donkey, I am delighted.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, if it weren't for graphical user interfaces (GUIs),
I probably wouldn't be able to figure out how to get my e-mail. I
know this and am thankful. But when it comes to streaming video,
downloading music and all the other ways the Web is supposed to
deliver images glorious to behold, I'm not all that interested.
</P>
<P>
   What's wonderful to me is the happy marriage of hard science and
self-expression. And it happened so fast.
</P>
<P>
   That the Web would enhance communication _ via text _ was
apparent early on to some people, like James P. Girard, a novelist
who is a friend and e-mail correspondent. He worked at newspapers
as a reporter and later as a computer guru. ``Like most people,''
he told me in an e-mail message, ``I thought of computers as number
machines, right up until the day I applied for a job on the Wichita
Eagle in late 1977 and discovered that the copy editors were
working at computer terminals. These are word machines, I thought.
I gotta have one of these. I think I was the third person in
Newton, Kan., to own one, and I had to go all the way to Kansas
City to buy it. The guy I bought it from threw in a membership to
The Source and a modem _ 300 baud. I think there were maybe a
couple of hundred people on The Source.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the early Source correspondents had handles, Jim
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Insane Chicken,' he wrote, ``was a very bright 9-year-old
girl from Boston, using her father's account (he never used it
himself), who pretended for a while _ quite successfully _ to be a
woman of 25. There was a highly respected programmer, named John
something-or-other, who everyone spoke of with a kind of reverence
and deferred to on software issues. (The Source had a built-in
programming language, which actually allowed users, if they knew
how, to modify the environment and introduce new capabilities; John
was one of the most active, and, as far as I know, invented a
number of things that are standard now.) It turned out he was a
15-year-old kid from Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't really know any of the usual things you know about
people _ age, gender, race, etc. You were really just dealing with
another human intelligence, through language, and the rest of that
stuff, when you did learn it, often turned out to be a kind of
disappointment. People were trying to make for themselves an online
persona that they liked better. I think that impulse, if nothing
else, is likely to boost linguistic skills tremendously over the
next couple of generations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Katherine McNamara is another e-mail friend and the widow of Lee
Goerner, the editor Jim and I shared at Atheneum. In 1997, she
started Archipelago, a serious literary journal on the Net. In an
interview for the 1997 Dictionary of Literary Biography, she spoke
of the Web as providing a publishing opportunity for people with
limited capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though what's called literature or writing on the Web has
incited a great deal of self-indulgence and youthful
experimentation,'' she was quoted as saying, ``it has also made it
possible, I find, to distribute the best work you can find.''
</P>
<P>
   Archipelago is one of the sites I visit. Sometimes I do shop, at
other sites, but even then it's usually at Amazon.com, and what I
buy is books. I turn off the graphics.
</P>
<P>
   In my thirst for pure text, I seem not to be alone. ``Readers
admire our graphics,'' said Cyrus Krohn, managing editor of Slate
magazine (www.slate.com), ``but what they really admire is fine
writing. A month ago, we began delivering articles via e-mail
several times a day. We're delivering to In boxes around the world
with no art. The readers appreciate not having to wade through the
pulp to get to the juice.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of text on the Net. I found a Blake Web site. He
was described as a multimedia poet, which I think is a stretch, but
it is Blake nevertheless, annotated.
</P>
<P>
   If one characteristic of the Net is a flood of sites that are
chiefly cherished by this writer for their texts, another is that
the Net is wildly democratic. Amazon.com has reviews by
professional critics, but it also has reviews written by anybody.
``Contact Congress'' was one of the buttons on America Online's
welcome page as the House debated Clinton's impeachment. ``Talk
about it.'' By which it meant: Write about it.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview conducted by Jacob Weisberg for Slate, the
novelist Tom Wolfe described the online community as ``a virtual
Haight-Ashbury.'' He added, ``The users are kind of virtual
hippies; they sense they're discovering a wonderful community and
they feel high.''
</P>
<P>
   Which does not always make for a clear head. I visited a virtual
writer's club once and found many virtual writers. Many of them
were poets, blank verse having become the medium that requires an
awe-inspiring proficiency, or none at all.
</P>
<P>
   Never, or rarely, has the artist's feeling of stark and dismal
alienation been so widely shared. For his AOL screen name, my son,
now 12, chose ``stranger.'' Dozens of others had already picked it,
so he had to add a number to the end _ a very high one.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to be alienated, though, isn't it better not to
be alone? I have electronic friends now, just down the road and in
Santa Monica and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   I used to spend a half-hour every morning writing in my journal.
``I'm depressed,'' I'd write. Now I send e-mail to a half-dozen
close and articulate friends. ``I'm depressed,'' I write. ``Me,
too,'' they holler back, and we all feel better. Or at least I do.
</P>
<P>
   Once or twice, I've been betrayed when somebody sent me a
picture, but I'm the forgiving sort. Mostly they send me words.
Sometimes happy, sometimes despairing, often precise. It's
astonishing what you can do with those little things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
