<HEADER>
A0397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-DIVIDE-0204-CO     02-03 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-DIVIDE-0204-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THREAT OF VIOLENCE LOOMS, AS OFFICIALS ONCE AGAIN DECIDE FATE OF
BOSNIAN CITY
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRCKO, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ International officials here like to
tell each other that this small town is a microcosm of the whole
country -- and that for peace to last in Bosnia, the problem of
Brcko must first be solved.
</P>
<P>
   Next week(CQ), an international arbitrator will try for the
third time in three years to decide the fate of the one town left
out of the Dayton Peace Accords.
</P>
<P>
   What has many here worried, however, is whether that decision
will spark renewed violence. In addition, Serbs and Muslims -- the
two factions with the most interest in the city's fate -- don't
trust one another, and the threat of NATO airstrikes against Serbs
in neighboring Kosovo looms.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Peace Accords, signed in December 1995, divided
Bosnia into two states: the Serb Republic and the Muslim/Croat
Federation. After three years of ethnic war and three weeks of
tense negotiations, the leaders of Bosnia's warring Serb, Croat and
Muslim factions were able to agree on where the line between the
two states should lie, except in Brcko -- a strategic deepwater
port and rail line where thousands of Serbs and Muslims died
fighting for control of it.
</P>
<P>
   An international arbitrator was appointed to resolve the issue
and pending the decision, a line was drawn through the middle of
the pre-war Brcko area, separating the urban area from the outlying
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator, Roberts Owen(CQ), a U.S. attorney involved in
the peace negotiations, has postponed the decision twice. On
Monday(2/8), he will begin to hear evidence from all sides and this
time, most here hope a final solution will be found for this
community of about 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very bad here right now,'' explained Miroslav Ristic, a
Serbian businessman living in downtown Brcko. ``The war has been
over for three years, but here it's still a situation where it's
not war but it's not peace yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ristic's driving school was bombed early last year when he
organized a car rally with a driving school in the Federation.
</P>
<P>
   There are several possible solutions for Brcko, a predominantly
Muslim town before the war when it was ``cleansed'' by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The downtown area could be left in Serb hands.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The whole town could be reunited and turned over to the
Muslim/Croat Federation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A special district could be created out of either the downtown
or the whole town, a neutral city outside of both states.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Owen could even decide to postpone the decision again.
</P>
<P>
   Each possibility has its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim officials argue that giving Brcko to the Serbs rewards
ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a city is decimated by genocide, if its citizens are
expelled under threat of death, then later, that town belongs to
the perpetrators of that crime, I leave it to you to call it
names,'' said Bosnian prime minister Haris Silajdzic(CQ). ``What we
have now in Brcko is the rule of those people who perpetrated this
crime in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the Serbs say taking Brcko away from them
would violate the Dayton Peace Accords, because the town is part of
the 49 percent of the country Serbs were promised in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   But more important to the Serbs is Brcko's strategic position as
a corridor between the eastern and western halves of the Serb
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a corridor that can be defended,'' explained Nikola
Kostich(CQ), a Serbian American attorney from Milwaukee
representing the Serb Republic in the arbitration. ``If you take
that away, then you are ethnically cleansing the Serbs here, and in
other areas. They're not going to stay. They're not going to feel
safe if Brcko isn't in the (Republic).''
</P>
<P>
   Muslim officials have said they will not be able to control the
reactions of people if the Serbs get Brcko. Serb officials have
responded with the same sort of inflammatory rhetoric. And Brcko
has had problems with violence, even after the war ended. In August
1997, 14 United Nations trucks were destroyed in a riot.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Though neither side thinks it's a good idea, the special
district option may be the easiest diplomatically. But without
support from either of the two states, international officials
would have to step in with money to prop up Brcko's government, at
least in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the situation in Kosovo may cause Owen to postpone the
decision again. Some in the international community here think Owen
won't make any decision that would inflame Serb feelings while NATO
is threatening to bomb Serbs in neighboring Yugoslavia. The
potential for a snow-ball effect riot is too great.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Farrand(CQ), the international supervisor for Brcko says
he doesn't know what the decision will be. No matter what the
decision, however, he doesn't think there will be riots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that Brcko is a tender box I think is outdated,'' he
said. ``I think Brcko is in fact becoming a more stable community
than perhaps others in the Serb Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   But his office is preparing for violence, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the $64,000 question.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
