<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GUEST-ROOM-ART-2TA     02-03 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUEST-ROOM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUND IN SPACE: ROOMS FOR SHORT GUESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Naomi Donne thinks back on all the visitors she
accommodated in her old Perry Street apartment _ suitcases stashed
in the corner of the living room, bulging with socks and underwear,
pillows and blankets hogging the couch, towels dripping from
doorknobs _ the memory makes her cringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were always sacked out on the couch,'' she said,
wrapping a tiger-print bathrobe even tighter. ``It almost drove me
mad.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Ms. Donne, a makeup artist who relocated from London to
New York eight years ago, went shopping for a new place with enough
room for her migrating friends and relatives, she found that two-
and three-bedroom apartments in the West Village were well out of
her reach. Still, Ms. Donne wasn't about to leave the Village,
which felt like home, for a neighborhood that had only buildings
with doormen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too invasive,'' said Ms. Donne, 42, who is known for her light
touch as a make-up artist. She has worked with actresses like
Winona Ryder and Kristin Scott Thomas, whose face she is currently
making up to make out with Harrison Ford, her co-star in ``Random
Hearts,'' a romantic drama now being filmed in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, two- and three-bedroom apartments are as hard to find
in the Village as imperfections in a leading lady. Chris Peters,
the sales manager at the Village office of the Corcoran Group,
could count the number of intact three-bedroom apartments he knows
on one hand. And Robert Eychner of Eychner Associates, a
real-estate agency that focuses on downtown, noted that ``the
demand for multi-bedroom, family-sized apartments has been wild for
the past few years.'' And they are priced accordingly. Corcoran's
forthcoming year-end residential sales report shows that in 1998,
the average price of two-bedroom apartments in the West Village was
$567,000, while three-bedroom apartments cost $1.4 million and up.
</P>
<P>
   But three years ago, with the can-do spirit of someone who
wielded the green eyeliner in ``Aliens IV'' and made Daniel Day
Lewis look haggard _ well, almost _ in ``The Crucible,'' Ms. Donne
sank $200,000 into a one-bedroom wreck with ceilings that reached
nearly 14 feet, because she dreamed that there would be just enough
space up there to create room for guests. ``It was inevitable that
people were going to visit,'' she said nonchalantly. ``I just
wanted them out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you improve on a dream? Robert Kahn, her architect, did,
suggesting he could add a mezzanine floor with two sleeping alcoves
_ and a library, with a view, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment Ms. Donne bought was part of a row of 19th-century
town houses off lower Fifth Avenue. The building had been a hotel
before being converted in 1980 into a 13-unit residential co-op.
Her 1,100-square-foot space had been stripped of its history: the
front parlor had been turned into the bedroom, and the kitchen was
crammed into a small rear addition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a set from `Boogie Nights,' said Kahn, a
Manhattan architect whom Ms. Donne had met at a party and asked, on
the spot, to inspect the place before she bought it. ``There were
shag carpets, angled walls and a deejay booth,'' recalled Kahn, 48.
``The only thing missing was a disco ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Donne was interested only in knowing whether or not the
ceilings were high enough to fit in another floor. Pulling  &UR; that &LR; 
off, Kahn had thought, would be an interesting prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ms. Donne is adept at summing up esthetic potential (``May
I pluck your eyebrows?'' she asked shortly after she first met a
reporter), she was confident that she could ``fix up the dump,''
she said. Architect and owner agreed that the first step was to
bring back its historical detail, adding period mantels, restoring
the moldings and putting the bedroom in the back. Any additions
would be both assertively and subtly modern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to treat the second level like an intervention of
a different style, with different materials that would still be
compatible,'' Kahn said. He added _ for good measure _ that he was
inspired by McKim, Mead &AMP; White's library at the University Club on
Fifth Avenue, where an industrial-style balcony runs steel rings
around the ornate space.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Donne's new floor is reached by a stair in the hall that
leads up to the addition, a catwalk suspended less than 6 feet from
the ceiling. It runs the length of the hall and opens up into a
balcony overlooking the living room. The catwalk is made of narrow
fir planks, 3/4 of an inch thick, fitted into a steel frame that's
hung from beams embedded in the walls and ceiling. It is suspended
from above rather than supported from below because city
regulations would not allow supports to go directly to the floor,
which was not designed to carry that much weight (true of most
residential construction). Rigging, like that of a suspension
bridge, allowed the catwalk to float, a bonus that the architect
religiously accentuated by keeping the planks 1 inch away from all
walls.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the catwalk, there are two berths, each about 12
feet long, 4 feet high and 8 feet deep. The berths are raised 12
inches off the floor because the architect wanted to recreate the
feeling of stepping up into Pullman-style sleeping bunks, complete
with curtains for privacy. ``I chose a fabric with stars to remind
people of the sky,'' he said, recalling how magical it had seemed
as a child to take the overnight train from St. Louis, where he
grew up, to visit his grandparents in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   High enough to kneel in, but not to stand, the two cubbyholes
each hold a double futon with room to spare for a few suitcases. A
bookshelf with a reading lamp is built in at the head of the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it should be noted that neither the architect nor the
homeowner is particularly tall, although Ms. Donne was quick to
point out that people well over 6 feet have visited for weeks on
end. And Ms. Donne herself likes to crawl into one and sleep there
when she's upset. ``It just feels so womblike and comforting,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly claustrophobic closeness of the catwalk, where the
ceiling is dropped about half a foot, suddenly evaporates when it
widens into a curved balcony overlooking the living room. The
balcony is spacious enough to pass for a small library, complete
with bookshelves, a desk and an armchair. Here, where the ceiling
is at its full height, it is finally possible to stand at full
height.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the balcony, Kahn tucked a dining table and highly
efficient kitchen. Ms. Donne recalled that when she said she wanted
a big American-style refrigerator with a water dispenser on the
door, the architect was quick to brand that ``tacky'' and insist on
a German AEG refrigerator that fits behind the maple cabinetry. The
kitchen's painted-glass backsplash suggests sophisticated subway
tiles. The zinc counter was the serendipitous result of a few
happy-hour meetings at the bar of Cafe Luxembourg. ``We even
imitated the rough welded seams,'' Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, as Ms. Donne picked up phone messages
(``Can you show  &UR; me &LR;  how to do what you did to my eyes,'' went one
from a cast member on ``Random Hearts''), she contemplated the sure
signs of a successful renovation. With an investment of about
$200,000 _ including the architect's 20 percent fee _ the
apartment's value, at least in today's frenzied market, has
probably climbed as high as $800,000, real-estate agents have told
Ms. Donne.
</P>
<P>
   And the stream of visitors has been not only constant but
unobtrusive. Few of them will ever realize that the last thing the
architect did was to soundproof her bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Specs
</P>
<P>
   When space is tight and ceilings are high, the temptation to
build up is strong. Here are the steps that Robert Kahn took before
adding a floor to Naomi Donne's 1,100-square-foot apartment.
</P>
<P>
   First, he made sure that the ceilings, at 13 feet 6 inches, were
indeed high enough to allow the renovation, which added
approximately 150 square feet. (Had the ceiling been only a foot
lower, he would not have advised proceeding, he said.)
</P>
<P>
   Renovations require government approval and a building permit.
In this case, Kahn submitted his plans for the new mezzanine as a
storage addition to New York City's Buildings Department. And he
got the approval of the co-op board.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the addition and the two sleeping berths are
constructed of drywall panels and metal studs.
</P>
<P>
   A caveat: Real-estate agents say that mezzanine additions to
prewar apartments increase the value of the apartment only when
they are done extremely well. A bad job will lower the value, and
there's no guarantee that the next buyer won't prefer the original
floor plan. At the Donne apartment, the mezzanine can be removed
easily, if not cheaply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
