<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-CONINI-BOS &LR;      02-03 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-CONINI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH ART MEETS WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manhattan is an island of islands, a patchy mosaic of
cliques and neighborhoods, overlapping yet often unaware of one
another _ and thrown into shock, or delight, when they converge.
</P>
<P>
   The World Financial Center is among the largest _ and, one would
think, least porous _ of these patches. The marble-and-glass
behemoth, headquarters to some of the planet's mightiest
money-houses, practically forms its own city, sprawled out across 6
million square feet and serving as the workplace for 39,000 people
_ with another 50,000, from the twin-towered World Trade Center
across the street, joining them for lunch or shopping in its
built-in mall.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, often, when these brokers, bankers, bookkeepers, and
secretaries zip down to the mall, they smack right into one of
those parallel universes. There's a show going on, with musicians,
poets, dancers, or installation-artists. Some of the performers are
famous, but most are more apt to be found in cramped nightclubs,
sidestreet galleries, or converted warehouses. Few have ever
performed for so many three-piece suits.
</P>
<P>
   These encounters have been going on for 10 years now and,
judging from the crowds they draw (on average, 1,200 per event) and
the corporate subsidies they consume ($21 million, to date),
everyone seems to like them.
</P>
<P>
   This culture-convergence is the brainchild of Anita Contini,
who, despite her title _ vice president of the World Financial
Center arts and events program _ seems as improbably suited to the
corporate realm as her arts-happenings are to this stone-cold
corporate complex.
</P>
<P>
   Her main funders are American Express, Merrill Lynch, and World
Financial Properties Inc., the center's original property owners,
but every firm in the building ponies up a mandatory fee to keep
the show going.
</P>
<P>
   Contini sold the idea to the companies as something ``important
for the quality of life of their employees who work here, and for
the image of the World Financial Center as a world-class public
space.'' She added, ``They get great PR out of this _ they look
fresh, they look smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the events take place at the Winter Garden, a vast,
glass-and-steel atrium that comes inescapably into view when one
steps out onto the center's 300,000 square feet of public space.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Druckman of the Battery Park City Authority, the agency
that owns the center's land, has spent many hours watching office
workers come upon these events.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see people walking through who think they're not
interested in, say, modern dance _ and then something strikes
them,'' Druckman said. ``They stop and they stay, and they stay a
little longer. That's the magical thing about this program.''
</P>
<P>
   It works for the artists, too. John Schaefer, who hosts a local
public radio show called ``New Sounds,'' has booked musicians for
Contini. Last November, Robert Fripp, leader of King Crimson,
played four sets of his out-there electric solo piece, ``Guitar
Soundscapes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I interviewed Fripp afterwards,'' Schaefer recalled, ``and he
said he loved playing there, for the privilege. . . of offering his
music to people who didn't know him and didn't know what he was
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Contini, a wire of energy in her early 50s, is well versed in
mixing downtown business and downtown art. Over 25 years ago, she
helped start a nonprofit arts group called Creative Time. Downtown
property was cheap, so communities of artists sprang up, putting on
concerts and exhibitions in lofts or some nearby hole-in-the-wall _
right in the shadow of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed there were these existing communities _ business and
artists _ that didn't mingle at all,'' Contini recalled. ``So I
thought maybe there's a way to extend what we were doing to a
different kind of public art. I was new to this. I didn't know that
it wasn't easy to go ask business people for money or for space. So
I went and asked them. Turned out, it was easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The recession had hit New York hard, and there were plenty of
vacant buildings. Morley Cho ran a shipping company with 6,400
square feet of empty space at 88 Pine Street, a building designed
by I. M. Pei, and was eager to turn it over to Contini.
</P>
<P>
   ``His motive,'' Contini said, ``was that it was lifeless on the
street down there _ all these office towers, people coming to work
with their heads down. He thought the artists could enliven the
area.''
</P>
<P>
   A celebrated result, in 1975, was ``Ruckus Manhattan,'' in which
19 downtown artists created colorful, cartoonish models of the
city's skyscrapers and pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate developers were then just starting work on Battery
Park City, a vast mile-long project of parks, offices, and
apartment towers that would stretch along the Hudson River from the
lower tip of Manhattan _ which, today, includes the World Financial
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The whole area was a sandy landfill, so Contini persuaded the
city to let artists, engineers, and architects use it for
experimental projects. She called it Art on the Beach, and it kept
moving north as the development progressed, finally ending in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Contini had a reputation for making bleak settings
fresh. So, the following year, when the World Financial Center was
finished, she was recruited to bring artists to the center.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years and 650 performances later, Contini sometimes misses
her old makeshift quarters. ``But unfortunately, or fortunately,''
she said, ``you've got to move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
