<HEADER>
A0420 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLOOPER-BOOSTS-CAREER     02-03 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOPER-BOOSTS-CAREER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV BLOOPER LED TO TV CAREER FOR EX-MISS AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a child, she dreamed of playing the violin at Carnegie Hall
and sometimes practiced five hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   But by age 16, Gretchen Carlson says, she knew that the world
was so much bigger than music. She could become a lawyer, for
instance. And so with the same fervor with which she pursued her
musical aspiration, she went off to Stanford University to pursue
that dream.
</P>
<P>
   But then her mother decided that Carlson could also be Miss
America. Carlson soon warmed to the idea, dropped out of college
for a year to prepare, and, in 1989, became the first classical
violinist to win the coveted title.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, how the Minnesota native ended up moving to
Fort-Worth Dallas last December to anchor the weekend news at
KXAS/Channel 5 is a whole other story.
</P>
<P>
   It all began during her reign as Miss America. Carlson thought
she was doing a live video conference with 5,000 engineers who were
going to explain the workings of a satellite named for Miss
America.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, actor Gary Collins and his wife, former Miss America
Mary Ann Mobley, were called off the set, leaving Carlson to do all
the talking with the help of cue cards, some of which were out of
order, upside down or missing words.
</P>
<P>
   The producers ``were pretending to try to help me, but it was
all a joke,'' she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   There was no video conference with engineers, Carlson later
found out. Instead, she was the target of TV's ``Bloopers and
Practical Jokes.'' But, she apparently pulled off the situation
with finesse.
</P>
<P>
   An agent who saw the segment called her and asked if she was
interested in a TV career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one experience,'' she says, ``scooted me over here
instead of law school.''
</P>
<P>
   But though the 32-year-old Carlson's route to television news
was admittedly circuitous, she says there's a connection between
her early years in music, her reign as Miss America and her news
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that red light goes on,'' she says, referring to the TV
camera's on-air cue, ``it's the same exact feeling I got when I
walked on stage: You're on.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson now has 10 years of television news experience, having
worked at stations in the Twin Cities; Richmond, Va.; and most
recently, as an anchor at WOIO in Cleveland. At the urging of her
former Cleveland boss, KXAS news director Kimberly Godwin-Webb,
Carlson joined Channel 5 as a reporter and weekend news anchor
opposite Calvin Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Godwin-Webb describes Carlson as a ``true professional who comes
to work to win. She is a real go-getter who believes in teamwork
and works hard to get great stories on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson says her typical day at Channel 5 begins around 2:30
p.m. and ends sometime after 10. The day always begins with making
a list of things to do, including finding time to work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm highly organized. It's one of my better traits,'' she
says. ``Actually, I'm probably overly organized. The first thing I
do when I wake up is write a list. As a reporter, I need to be on
top of things. I keep a list beside my bed.''
</P>
<P>
   TV news reporting, she says, is about communicating with people
and getting them to tell their story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I report three days a week,'' Carlson says. ``That's why I
took this job. As the main anchor, my reporting was not utilized in
Cleveland, but I have the best of both worlds here. I get to report
and anchor the news.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carlson, who recently married Casey Close, a baseball agent
with International Management Group, says she isn't in Texas just
for the work. She wants to become part of the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, I wake up and I try to do the best job I can,'' she
says. ``But I also want to be involved in the community. I want to
work with kids, talk to them about the importance of education and
introduce them to music.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a beauty queen.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
