<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALMBEACH-ANTIQUE-FAI     02-03 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALMBEACH-ANTIQUE-FAIR-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNING A HOLE IN DEEP POCKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Kristy French was having trouble
deciding between a pink and black Picasso and a very blue,
sun-dappled Monet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. French, a young collector from Dallas, was at the
International Art and Antique Fair here _ which closes on Sunday _
hoping to expand her collection of 20th-century art.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Picasso. ``It's just a little picture,'' she
explained. ``Cubist, from 1922. But I just bought a Lichtenstein _
1992 _ and it's very similar in style. That's something I like to
do _ weave a thread between them.'' Both paintings, she said, have
the same color scheme and similar zigzagging lines. The Picasso,
about the size of, say, a Town &AMP; Country magazine, was marked
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. French, 35, and Barry Williams, her interior designer friend
(her husband, Jim, was back in Dallas putting together land deals
around a new sports arena), were among the hundreds of antiques
lovers who gathered in a tent here last Thursday night for the
``vernissage'' _ Eurospeak for opening _ of the city's
three-year-old antiques fair. As the evening wore on, the ratio of
young collectors to old collectors tipped as the price of admission
dropped from $1,000 to $125 after 8:30. And what had been a
smattering of relative youth became, if not a solid bloc, a notable
presence.
</P>
<P>
   The younger patrons _ defined by David Lester, the show's
organizer, as ``men and women in their late 40s, people we were not
getting at this fair before'' _ contributed to this year's success.
Last year, Lester said, the opening raised $100,000 for the Norton
Gallery of Art here; this year, the museum reaped almost twice as
much.
</P>
<P>
   And while almost everyone at the vernissage was dressed divinely
_ lace the color of Ceylon tea was voguish for the older women,
silvery satin for the younger _ it was the under-40 crowd that lent
panache to the event, smiling sunny 90-degree smiles for paparazzi
and consulting with spouses, decorators and friends on cellular
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sands, 36, and Samantha Maltezos, 28, dropped in at
about 7:30. A collector of 20th-century furniture and American
Indian crafts, Sands compared the January Winter Antiques Show at
the Seventh Regiment Armory in Manhattan with the Palm Beach fair.
At the armory, he said, ``you walk in and feel like all your
clothes just received a starching.'' The New York show, he added,
is a furniture show, with some old masters paintings, ``fit for
Fifth Avenue mansions.''
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach, ``what happens is they pick all the colorful
things for the seashore,'' he said, as he studied a $2.7 million
Fernand Leger painting, which would be bought the next day _ but
not by him. Sands, who said he was ``into telecommunications'' in
Sun Valley, Idaho, has homes in New York, Sun Valley and Palm
Beach, where he now spends four or five months a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. French was among the first of the younger patrons. ``I never
miss these openings, because one time I missed a painting by Bo
Bartlett,'' she said, referring to the figurative artist born in
Georgia. ``By the time I saw it, it had one of those terrible red
dots on it. Since then, I've bought every painting by him I
liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Just around the corner, Ruth and Christopher H.A. Cecil were
admiring a $2.5-million unfinished Renoir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like it,'' said Cecil, 33, adding that he had been
raised at Biltmore, the Vanderbilt summer retreat in Asheville,
N.C., now a house museum. ``My parents were the last to live in
it.'' He also mentioned his great-great-great-grandfather Cornelius
Vanderbilt, ``who built Grand Central Station,'' and ``Grandfather
Cecil'' from Britain, whose family treasures from Burghley House _
15th- and 16th-century Italian paintings _ will be exhibited at the
Society of the Four Arts here this month. (In Palm Beach, there
seems to be a great divide between those who have ancestors and
those who do not _ or do not mention them when meeting strangers.)
</P>
<P>
   Cecil and his wife appraised the Renoir, ``Mother and
Children.'' ``You can see the canvas showing through,'' he said.
``It's a sketch, a classic Renoir face, but he hasn't quite
completed it. The colors are there _ it's really quite unique.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cecils, who have lived here for six years, bought a 1930s
house by the Palm Beach architect Marion Sims Wyeth and are still
decorating it. ``There's so many decisions,'' Mrs. Cecil, 34, said,
glancing toward the Renoir as the dealer hovered.
</P>
<P>
   In another corner of the tent, a young couple, dressed to kill,
chatted near Picasso's $2.4 million ``Jacqueline at a Window.''
Jill Hepworth Crompton, 31, an interior designer and Palm Beach
socialite, whose photograph appears prominently in the current Palm
Beach Illustrated, laughingly denied she had come to buy. She was
at the fair ``because of the remarkable scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle, two stylish young women, Tuty Mena, 31, and
Cathy Vedori, 34, who wore diamond earrings with black pearls the
size of bubble-gum balls, were admiring a $900,000 Jean-Michel
Basquiat. Ms. Mena showed off a ring she had just bought from Fred
Leighton, the Madison Avenue jeweler, who has a booth here: a tiny
ebony elephant that she said was used to weigh opium.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the younger collectors, at least on opening night,
gravitated toward modern works. At Landau Fine Art, the booth with
the $2.7 million Leger, Robert Landau said on Sunday that he had
just that hour sold two pictures to young collectors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several dealers pointed to the nearly empty Art Deco booths.
``The dealers have to learn to accommodate themselves to the
market,'' Lester said, a tactful way of questioning whether the
Palm Beach crowd's appetite for shagreen and highly polished
rosewood had been overestimated. (By Tuesday, he reported, the Art
Deco dealers ``had started doing business,'' and he gave the
example of the Philippe Denys booth, where a 1930 Gio Ponti cabinet
of rosewood, silvered gilt and brass, marked at $45,000, had been
sold. Nevertheless, Denys later termed his business at the fair
``interesting, but quite slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one younger man interviewed at the opening, Christopher
Fillichio, 36, described himself as a furniture collector. Spotted
peering over a combination bench and bookcase, a 1952 Charlotte
Perriand design, Fillichio, who builds prefabricated houses, said
he collected Carlo Mollino, Gerrit Rietveld and plywood by Marcel
Breuer. Before the night was over, he bought the Perriand piece,
priced at $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   After days of hard bargaining, Ms. French, the collector from
Dallas, bought neither the Picasso nor the Monet. She chose a
Matisse aquatint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer to do things in a more relaxed manner _ have the
dealer ship it to me for approval, for instance,'' she said. ``But
everything at the show was so rushed _ so many people were
interested in it _ that I just went ahead and took it.'' And the
price? ``My husband said I can't say,'' Ms. French said primly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
