<HEADER>
A0434 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-JOYSTICKS-700&AMP;ADD     02-03 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-JOYSTICKS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW, IMPROVED FORCE-FEEDBACK JOYSTICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're flying a World War II prop fighter. An enemy plane floats
across your sights. You squeeze the trigger on your joystick and it
rat-tat-tats vigorously in your grip. An instant later, a weighty
lunge nearly rips the joystick right out of your hand. It's enemy
fire, from behind. Your engine sputters. Nose takes a dive. A fast
free-fall with no sensation at all, then one final shudder from the
stick when plane meets ground.
</P>
<P>
   This scene could be played out with any number of video games,
but players who take their fun very seriously are no longer content
with better-looking on-screen cockpits and dashboards. They want a
more realistic ``feel'' from a new crop of add-on gaming devices,
with a feature known as ``force feedback,'' which react and respond
in the player's hands to what is happening on screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have taken an interest in realism, which has driven
technology forward,'' says Mark Szabo, editor in chief of Force
One, a Web site dedicated to force feedback (www.force-1.com).
``Game developers have finally started to take advantage of the
hardware.''
</P>
<P>
   While force-feedback joysticks have been around for a couple of
years, the latest devices promise more realistic response,
better-built designs and, most important, better support for the
kinds of games that take advantage of them _ flying and driving
games. The force feedback effects are created by high-torque motors
that respond to instructions from game programs. Hit a bump in the
road or fire a machine gun and the device responds accordingly,
with a staccato vibration of the joystick or a weighty jolt in the
steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   In such a situation, a force feedback wheel challenges the
player's grip with a harder-to-hold tug that feels familiarly
unnerving _ and exhilarating _ to anyone who has ever experienced
the anxious few seconds of a real-life blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Just like being there? Not quite. But as feedback effects edge
closer to imitating the real thing, enthusiastic gamers are willing
to shell out cash to get their hands on the goods. The new devices
cost between $100 and $250.
</P>
<P>
   The first mass market force-feedback joystick, the Force FX, was
introduced in November 1996 by CH Products, which uses a technology
called I-Force, created by Immersion Corp. Immersion's designs were
inspired by highly specialized force feedback devices used for such
applications as military training and steering robotic hands to add
and remove volatile core reactor rods in nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Several manufacturers have licensed I-Force technology for their
products. But not Microsoft, maker of the very popular Flight
Simulator game. Wanting in on the fun, the company went shopping
for a force feedback technology to call its own. They found it at a
design firm called EXOS, absorbing its people and technology into
its ever-growing hardware division, which also produces mice,
ergonomic keyboards and even cordless phones.
</P>
<P>
   Where the devices vary are in price, esthetic design, special
features and how they connect to the computer. Microsoft's
Sidewinder Force Feedback Pro has an angular, split-level design
that is lighter and takes less space than Logitech's smooth and
curvy Wingman Extreme. The Sidewinder, which in its second
generation has lost the noisy cooling fan that gamers had
complained about, connects to a computer's game controller port.
The Wingman connects to a serial port, although it also accepts
optional snap-in cartridges to enable a variety other connection
options, including Universal Serial Bus ports. USB ports offer the
potential for more responsive feedback because they operate at
higher speeds than serial or game controller ports.
</P>
<P>
   In the force feedback wheel lineup, Act Labs' Force RS wheel is
wrapped in soft rubber and feels nice in the hands _ especially
comforting when the action turns white-knuckled. Optional
connectors make it work with not only PCs but also video game
systems like Nintendo 64 and Sony Playstation. Microsoft's
Sidewinder Force Feedback Wheel, which is cushioned in the 3 and 9
o'clock positions, works only with PC's running Windows.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most significant difference in both kinds of devices is
what's inside them. The Microsoft products use gears to activate
and agitate their force feedback wheel and joystick devices.
Skipping gears altogether, the Logitech Wingman Force uses a series
of cables for tugging its stick to and fro. Players on several
newsgroups and Web sites dedicated to computer games report that
feedback effects produced with the cable-based stick feel better
and less harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Szabo at Force One attributed the difference to the space
between the gear teeth in the Microsoft Sidewinder. ``The cable
system in the Logitech Wingman alleviates this space,'' he said.
``There's no gear backlash, and response is smoother and more
immediate.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitive advantages and arguments aside, is force feedback a
geeky gimmick, or does it give gamers more than just throbbing,
sweaty palms? Szabo thinks so. ``There are many games out there
where force feedback improves player performance by providing
physical cues as to what's happening in the virtual world,'' he
said. He sited, for instance, ``the feeling when the tires are
breaking loose'' in a racing game. ``This indicates how close to
the edge of the envelope they're pushing the virtual race car.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest application of force feedback is finding its way to
the computer mouse. Dubbed Feelit technology by Immersion, the
device will respond tactilely to clicks and drags on screen.
</P>
<P>
   This is interesting to the players of first-person 3-D shooter
games like Quake and Half-Life, whose preferred method of play is a
combination of keyboard and mouse. (The keyboard is used for basic
character movement: forward, backward, jumping, crouching. The
mouse is used to ``free look''in the 3-D environment _ a nudge left
or right or up or down follows the player's virtual line of sight
in the same direction, providing a full 360 degrees of freedom.) A
force feedback mouse could be used to convey the rumble of firing a
canon, or the agony of being hit by enemy fire or falling from a
high terrace to a hard dungeon floor.
</P>
<P>
   In the console video game world, Nintendo made news in 1997 when
it introduced the Rumble Pack, a small cartridge that snaps into
the Nintendo 64 controller. The cartridge, which operates on two AA
batteries, houses a small motor that responds to on-screen action
cues. Sony has since come out with a batteryless controller for the
Playstation. Both represent force feedback at its most limited.
</P>
<P>
   But Shigeru Miyamoto, the Nintendo game designer who invented
Super Mario, hopes his latest best-selling game changes that
impression. ``We've made the N64 Rumble Pak a part of the Legend of
Zelda: Ocarina of Time in a new way, never seen before in video
games,'' Miyamoto said. ``For the first time, a video game
accessory will work on a proactive basis _ shaking to clue players
into action _ as well as on a reactive basis, shaking in response
to something that has already happened.'' It's the golden fleece of
feedback: the sensation that helps you win. But, of course, there's
a catch. ``In order for the Rumble Pak to work at all, players will
need to search for and find an item that will enable it,'' Miyamoto
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
