<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: AMERICAN SONG SERIES; BECKMANN AND PARIS EXHIBIT;
SWING NIGHT; SOYINKA HEADED TO NYU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New York, St. Louis )  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The genius of Harold Arlen, whose songs range from
``Ac-centchu-ate the Positive'' and ``I've Got the World on a
String'' to ``One for My Baby'' and ``Over the Rainbow,'' will be
celebrated Friday and Saturday at Alice Tully Hall when Lincoln
Center for the Performing Arts begins ``Lincoln Center's American
Songbook,'' a new series on American songs and songwriters. This
weekend's semi-staged performance, ``I've Got a Right to Sing the
Blues,'' with full orchestral accompaniment, theatrical lighting
and slide projections, will feature Barbara Cook, Diana Krall, Jay
Leonhart, Audra McDonald, Maureen McGovern, Richard Muenz, Ken Page
and Mike Renzi. The next installment in the series is ``Richard
Rodgers: With a Song in My Heart,'' on March 5 and 6. It continues
with four more programs, scheduled for this fall and the spring of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Side by Side
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1920s, when Max Beckmann had achieved stature as a
German artist, he moved to Paris to compete with contemporaries
like Matisse, Picasso and Braque and seek international fame. ``If
one could only once hang our pictures together so that the people
could judge for themselves,'' Beckmann said. Now the opportunity is
at hand in ``Beckmann and Paris,'' an exhibition opening on
Saturday at the Saint Louis Art Museum. The show, which was
organized with the Kunsthaus Zurich and runs through May 9,
assembles for the first time nearly 100 paintings by Beckmann,
Picasso, Matisse, Braque, Leger, Georges Rouault and Robert
Delaunay and illustrates how Beckmann's themes and esthetic
approaches often paralleled those of his contemporaries in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Airs
</P>
<P>
   New York _ Swing will definitely be in the air Friday night when
Pace University sets the Roy Gerson Swing Orchestra to playing
music for dancers who favor the Lindy and the like. The event,
called ``Winterfest: Celebration of Swing Dancing,'' starts to
bounce at 8 p.m. at the Pace University Student Union Building at 1
Pace Plaza opposite City Hall Park in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Another Role
</P>
<P>
   New York _ Wole Soyinka, who in 1986 became the first African to
receive the Nobel Prize in literature, has been named the first
Distinguished Scholar-in-Residence by New York University's
Africana Studies Program and the Institute of African-American
Affairs. The appointment will bring Nigerian-born Soyinka to NYU
for lectures on democracy and democracy in the arts in Africa on
Feb. 17 and 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
