<HEADER>
A0448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METALLIC-PLASTIC-NYT &LR;      02-03 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METALLIC-PLASTIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THAT GLITTERS IS PLASTIC AND VINYL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Accent on Design exhibition at this week's New
York gift show, where manufacturers show off products for the
coming year, was awash with items for the home in metallic plastic.
These are not plastic glasses and garbage cans spray-painted copper
or silver, understand, but objects molded of a polypropylene or
vinyl where the metal color is part of the material. Their flowing
shapes, loose and liquid as some special effect from ``Terminator
2,'' flaunt their plasticity. They seem to inhabit some alchemical
middle state between plastic and metal.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Umbra stand, at Authentics and Interdesign and Totem,
last year's frosty pastels have been superseded by hues that carry
names like silver, copper, titanium, metallic oxide and metallic
iris. One reason for the shift lies in the relentless march of
fashion in home furnishings. Another is the continuing redemption,
even glorification, of plastic, now presented as a precious
material. Thus the titanium waste can and the pearlescent
toothbrush holder. (This pearlescent is not to be confused with
pearl or even mother-of-pearl; think of it, maybe, as mother-in-law
of pearl.) There was the gold laundry bin and the silver flatware
tray. There were coppery greens and metallic blues, too, like
``blued'' or hardened steel.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the next thing,'' Mary Handeland, national sales manager
for Authentics, said brightly. At her booth, silver and deep cobalt
blue glowed and glinted on the shelves. David Savchuk, national
sales manager for Interdesign, was similarly smitten: ``We expect
this will be really big for back-to-school,'' he said. He was
already looking down the road to students outfitting rooms with the
company's storage boxes and cans, which wore cuprous and argentine
hues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Interdesign, Umbra and other companies, metallics are a way
to fight cheap knockoffs. For not only do they change the fashion
ground rules, but also metallics are trickier to mold and allow
high-end plastic manufacturers to showcase their expertise.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Metallics,'' Savchuk said, ``are harder to produce in ways
that don't show the join lines. They also tend to clump in the mold
if not carefully fabricated.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is buying. At Heller plastics, where there was an
abundance of creams and yellows and a few silvery-grays, Alan
Heller sniffed at metallic as novel. ``We've had metallic cans and
other items for years now,'' he said. But elsewhere, plastics
wearing the look of precious materials were present in force.
</P>
<P>
   At the Totem stand was a new crop of products from Inflate, the
London company best known for its plastic bowls and vases filled
with air. Now, Inflate has turned to a sometimes metallic,
sometimes pearlescent sort of vinyl, out of which it makes
backpacks and cell-phone cases. For David Shearer, one of the
owners of Totem, in TriBeCa, these metallics, flecked with tiny
micalike bits of brightness, echo old bicycles and hot rods. ``I
can still remember those Schwinn bikes with metal fenders and
banana seats,'' he said. Some wore the candy-apple metallic red of
hot rods of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But if the metallic look harkens back to the past, it also looks
forward to a future of space-suit fabrics and pliable robots. A
Garbo garbage can from Umbra in silver would be at home with the
Jetsons. To Steven Holt of Frogdesign, the industrial design firm,
who teaches the history of industrial design at California College
of Arts and Crafts in San Francisco, the metal look ``is visual
future-speak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Metal is the apotheosis of the machine,'' Holt said. ``It's
about a still inchoate sense that the future is now part of our
present. It's a consumerized vision of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   We've already seen the return of metal to stereo components,
where brushed steel, dusted with irony, perhaps as a reprise of
'70s equipment, has taken over from professional black. Digital and
Advanced Photo System cameras have also given up the black look.
The metallic-looking materials of which they are made are only
occasionally actual metal; mostly, they are high-impact plastic.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as they imply the future, metallic plastics may be a
fitting material for the present, the right stuff for the times.
Their appeal lies in the subtle and elusive play of surface and
ambiguity about substance. Once, we had a president who was
described as Teflon. Now, we have one whose moral pliability
coexists paradoxically with glitteringly high popularity and golden
poll ratings. Each day brings new gloss to a stock market drunk on
a high-tech future, while Wall Street veterans warn that beneath
the glistening valuations lies stuff less sterling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-FURNITURE-FAI     02-03 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-FURNITURE-FAIR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWEAKING THE TRIED AND TRUE AT THE COLOGNE FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: optional sidebar appears in 2nd take)  
 (bl)  
 By ARLENE HIRST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Material was the message at the International
Furniture Fair, where retailers find the broadest range of
contemporary furniture available. Exhibitors in January, some 1,600
from 46 countries, were out of new ideas about form, stuck as they
were in the minimal, spare look of the 1970s. So they turned to
substances for inspiration. The materials of the moment are neither
cutting edge nor high tech. Instead, designers experimented with
the tried and true _ wood, glass, stainless steel and porcelain _
with surprising results. Here's a preview of the designs likely to
cause the biggest ripples when they arrive in America.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the bathtub by Giampaolo Benedini for Agape. Made of
teak, it has a simple rectangular shape with a luxurious, chaise
longuelike interior. Agape president Emanuele Benedini promised
dubious viewers that cleaning it would be a breeze. ``Just don't
use abrasives or ammonia,'' he advised. The collection will be at
Moss, a store in New York's Soho, this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Claudio Silvestrin, former partner of the minimalist architect
John Pawson, chose pietra lecce _ a humble, soft-to-the-touch stone
_ for his king-size, egg-shaped tub for Boffi. You may need a
special house to install it in; it weighs 1,100 pounds. The tub
will be at Boffi's New York showroom this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Norbert Wangen, a Munich designer, covered chests in
stainless-steel mesh, tempering the hard rectangular forms with the
sensuousness of the fabric. They're available through Petersburg
Press in New York. Kurt Erni's sheer, all-glass storage units,
designed for Wellis in a range of shapes and sizes, resemble mini
glass-and-steel skyscrapers. The transparency makes it easy to find
things. The line is at Luminaire in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   At the new lighting hall, porcelain shades gave a softer, warmer
look to lamps. From German designer Ingo Maurer to Babylon Design,
a hip young English company, many were taken with this ancient
material. Maurer's lamps took the form of porcelain vessels,
although he also experimented with light-emitting diodes. His new
lamp, the Bellisima Brutta _ a gangly bouquet of LED flowers with
illumination that, for now, is more striking than effective _ is
just his first step: he expects to introduce an energy-efficient
LED collection in Milan in April.
</P>
<P>
   Designers also played with sophisticated technology for
Palluccoitalia, sealing an electro-luminescent fiber inside clear
plastic for light screens. The ghostly effect, which provides
atmosphere rather than real light, is available through Current, a
Seattle store, in two sizes. The Short Wave screen is $1,425; the
Long Wave, $1,520.
</P>
<P>
   No self-respecting contemporary furniture fair would be complete
without plastic seating. Best-in-show honors went to Matthew Hilton
for his Wait chair, with its sophisticated lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the shape first, before you even see the color,'' said
Murray Moss, owner of the store Moss, who quickly snatched it up.
Authentics, the German company that helped rehabilitate plastic's
image with its beautifully simple housewares, produced Hilton's
design, which draws on the technology used in the ubiquitous resin
garden chair. The Wait chair, at $50, appeals to anyone looking for
comfort and style, indoors or out.
</P>
<P>
   Revivals have become an essential part of any '90s fair.
Cassina's reissue of Le Corbusier's LC5 daybed, out of production
for at least 15 years, was probably the most universally acclaimed
item in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you want to hear about great new designs,'' said Dan
Friedlander, owner of Limn, a store in San Francisco, ``but the
Corbusier is the best thing we've seen.'' The sofa has a polished
chrome, plated-steel frame and black leather cushions. The ones on
the back are hinged onto the rear frame so that they can easily be
flipped over, increasing the depth of the seat to the size of a
single bed. It will sell for about $5,000 at the Cassina store in
New York this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The German manufacturer Thonet presented a virtual history of
its contribution to 20th-century design, some items brand new,
others from the company archives, dating back to 1926. They
included Mart Stam's, Mies van der Rohe's and Marcel Breuer's
tubular steel-frame seating of the 1920s and '30s; a 1934 bar cart
by A. Bamberg, never in production, and new tubular steel bookcases
by Haeberli and Marchand that looked as if they came straight from
Thonet's archives. ICF will distribute the line in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of multipurpose, space-saving furniture:
while American manufacturers focus on producing giant armoires for
the ever-larger suburban home _ items that most city dwellers
couldn't fit through their front doors _ Europeans obsess over
small spaces and the storage needs of the urbanite. Ligne Roset's
Yo-Yo table not only adjusts from cocktail to dining table height,
but also doubles its size.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, young American designers have been
attending the Cologne and Milan fairs _ not to get ideas but to get
work. ``Manufacturers here will talk to me, and possibly make
things,'' said Harry Allen, who had to resort to making his own
ceramic foam lamps, which are in the permanent collection at New
York's Museum of Modern Art. ``In Europe, there's a tradition of
design. The same environment doesn't exist in the United States.
Design has scared American industry for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS IN 2nd TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When John Hutton resigned from Donghia last November, after 20
years as its acclaimed design director, it was the design-world
equivalent of the breakup of the Beatles _ and it might prove as
fractious. Buyers at the Paris furniture fair in January came
expecting to see Hutton's first solo collection. Instead, they
found an empty booth.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the trade show opened, Donghia was granted an
injunction that stopped Hutton from showing or selling his new
line. (The injunction meant that the line could not be shown the
following week in Cologne, either.)
</P>
<P>
   When the designer, known for his glamorous but comfortable
style, announced his resignation last fall, jaws dropped in the
design community. ``For an entire generation of designers,'' said
Mayer Rus, editor in chief of Interior Design magazine, ``the
Donghia name has been synonymous with John Hutton's vision, rather
than the late Angelo Donghia, as great as he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Of that accomplishment, he said, ``It's a remarkable feat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutton left to create his own company with a group of small
European manufacturers and David Sutherland, a Dallas businessman.
Discussions with Donghia for a settlement began this week, but for
now no one can see _ or buy _ the designs, as their ownership is in
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Jerrold Sonet, Donghia's chairman and the executor of the estate
of Angelo Donghia, who died in 1985, said, ``We took him to court
because we felt that the product belonged to Donghia.'' Sonet
insisted that Hutton could not have completed a new collection in
the two months since he resigned; he believes Hutton must have been
working on it while still in Donghia's employment.
</P>
<P>
   Hutton countered that in the company's early years, he often
created new product lines just as quickly. He added that he had had
only five days to answer the suit, and that the court based its
decision on oral arguments, not the visual evidence that he brought
into court _ sketches and drawings that he said were dated after he
left Donghia.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ruling, only a handful of people have actually
seen the new work _ mostly exhibitors at the Paris show who had
watched Hutton's booth being set up and taken down. Asked whether
the collection looked like Donghia, one manufacturer responded,
``It looked like John Hutton.''
</P>
<P>
   The pieces _ occasional tables, side chairs, lighting, fabric
and upholstery _ were said to have the fluid lines and striking
proportions for which Hutton is known.
</P>
<P>
   Hutton, ever the optimist, is already at work on another
furniture line. ``I'm drawing the collection this weekend,'' he
said, adding he hoped to show it in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
