<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEENEY-HOUSE-NYT &LR;      02-03 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEENEY-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR OF THE CIRCLING WAGONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Washington)   By JAMES RYAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Julia Sweeney's parents, Bob and Jeri, have moved
out. Her boyfriend no longer has to crash in the office out back.
The guest room is empty, save for a few artifacts left behind when
her brother Mike died. The pullout bed in the living room remains
tucked under its corduroy cushions.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this comedian and ``Saturday Night Live'' alumna
has her Hollywood dream bungalow back to herself.
</P>
<P>
   To those who saw her one-woman show, ``Julia Sweeney's God Said,
`Ha!''' about living with cancer in a suddenly reconstituted
nuclear family, or read it in book form (Bantam, 1997), Ms.
Sweeney's parents and her brother are familiar characters. (The
film opens on Feb. 12.)
</P>
<P>
   What is absent from each of these versions is the central
battlefield in her story: her 1,200-square-foot home, which was
host to a nine-month family reunion in 1995 when her parents helped
care for Mike, who had non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, and for the actress
herself, who learned she had cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweeney was reduced to smuggling her boyfriend in and
sneaking the occasional cigarette. ``It was sort of like being back
in high school, only this time I was paying the mortgage,'' she
recalled as she sat at her round dining room table in her home,
which she bought for $320,000 in 1993 during her last season of
``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   The time-warp is heightened by the fact that the small house is
crammed with items from her childhood home in Spokane, Wash., and
her grandmother's home, plus a comprehensive collection of Roman
Catholic artifacts _ plaster nuns, saints, cherubs and Madonnas.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of blocks from Paramount Studios, the home ties
together the two constant threads in her life: religion and show
business. She can hear the bells from a Roman Catholic church a few
blocks away and see the Hollywood sign from her front yard. An
antique Mexican rosary (her grandmother's) is affixed to the wall
above her bed. On the mantel is a painting of Madonna and Child
that has been in her family for 100 years. A kitchy statue of the
Virgin Mary prays beside a small, cobalt-blue tiled swimming pool
with hot tub she built out back.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweeney admits to being a lifelong collector. ``It all
started in 1974, when my parents' house burned down,'' she said.
``You know how people hoard food? I feel that way about stimulating
objects.''
</P>
<P>
   The cozy bungalow proved a fitting hospice as Mike declined
toward death. ``I felt like the spirit of the family was in the
house, like my grandmother Henrietta was there, because so many of
her things were there,'' she said. ``It was a healing
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   One floor-to-ceiling bookcase in her living room is devoted to
religion and philosophy. ``It's not an obsession,'' Ms. Sweeney
insisted. She said she couldn't understand why everyone didn't have
six shelves of religion books: ``It's the most interesting topic
there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweeney, who was raised Catholic, disagrees with much of the
dogma but adores the culture. ``I rejected the church but kept the
art,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the actress seems smaller, prettier than she does on
camera and far younger than her 39 years. Like its owner, the
unimposing facade of the single-story 1923 Mission-style home gives
few hints at the treasures within. ``It's very humble on the
outside and then when you come inside it's really much more than
you think,'' she said. ``This is my style. Because I think that's
how people should be. There isn't much to them until you get to
know them.''
</P>
<P>
   She knits sweaters, sitting in her L.&AMP; J.G. Stickley chair. Her
kitchen spices are hand labeled by purchase date. The 1,500 compact
discs in a Mission-style hutch are logged into the computer and
coded with colored dots. Books are cataloged by author. Bibles are
under G for God.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the accountant in me coming out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweeney grew up in Spokane, one of five children of a U. S.
Attorney and his wife. After Catholic schools, she majored in
accounting at the University of Washington and went to work in the
accounting department of Columbia Pictures. Her turn to comedy, she
believes, was divinely inspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would drive to work and hear this voice saying, `You're a
performer,''' she recalled. ``I didn't want to hear it. I was 25
and not particularly good looking and I didn't have a great
figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she signed up for a course called the Business of
Acting, offered by the Groundlings, an improvisational theater
group. Five years later, in 1989, she landed a slot on ``Saturday
Night Live,'' along with Mike Meyers, Dana Carvey and Phil Hartman.
That's when she began playing her androgynous character, Pat.
Feeling out of place after four years because of cast changes (some
critics said the show's glory days were over), Ms. Sweeney left.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1994, she was decorating her Los Angeles bungalow in a
style she calls ``really girlie,'' _ picking out fabric for
curtains, rearranging the nun figurines and planning the rest of
her life when, as she puts it, God said, ``Ha!''
</P>
<P>
   Her first movie, ``It's Pat,'' was savaged by the critics. Then
she received a call from her brother Mike, who was 30 and working
as a box office manager for the Groundlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie bombed on Friday and on Sunday Mike called saying he
was very sick and didn't have insurance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike moved into her bedroom; their parents moved into the guest
bedroom. She began sleeping on a sofa bed in her office, out back.
As she told audiences, ``I found myself walking around thinking
things like, `When I go to college I'm going to get my own dorm
room.'''
</P>
<P>
   While they were all taking care of Michael, God said another
``Ha!'' Ms. Sweeney developed a rare form of cervical cancer, which
required a hysterectomy and a course of chemotherapy. (She says she
seems to be fine now.)
</P>
<P>
   During this period, to let off steam, she would tell funny
stories about her family at the West Hollywood club Luna Park. Her
friends urged her to do a one-woman show. Thus, out of the dark
circumstances of her life was born ``Julia Sweeney's God Said,
`Ha!'''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing it on Broadway for The New York Times, Peter Marks,
praised the author's ``powerful emotional current that has carried
her through the terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Ms. Sweeney's big fears was her parents' reaction. In the
show, she talked about her father's devotion to Cokie Roberts on
National Public Radio _ ``Do you know Cokie broadcast in her
pajamas today?'' She also does wicked impressions of her mother's
stream-of-consciousness way of speaking: ``Oh, I think that
cantaloupe would work, the blouse you want altered is on the bed,
have you seen the car keys?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' they finally said. ``We can handle a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweeney believes her retelling of that time in their lives
helps keep Mike alive for them. ``It was a terrible year, but you
would give everything for one of those days with Mike again,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Memories dispel the loneliness, too.``I think of Mike on the
sofa, in the Jacuzzi, how many fires we had in that fireplace or
the meals we cooked in the kitchen,'' she said. ``Those memories
make me feel less alone. I see the house as a stage where these
incredible events in your life are going to play out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
