<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-PLANTS-775(2TAK     02-03 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-PLANTS-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVELING IN EXOTIC BLOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036.) 
(dal) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``We are as we as,'' Colman Rutkin said, meaning that
he and Sage Reynolds were not about to rush around straightening up
their rambling, 12-room house on Staten Island just because a
photographer was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness. In the bleak midwinter, I was looking for people
who didn't need spring to have green, living things keeping them
company. And I didn't want them tidying up seedlings on the kitchen
sink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plants in the bathroom,'' Rutkin said, ``plants in the
attic, plants in the cellar.'' I went right over. His first words
were, ``Sage, do you think she'll fit in the greenhouse?''
</P>
<P>
   Rutkin is 5 feet 4 inches tall, so he doesn't have to hunch down
like Reynolds, who is a half foot taller, to avoid banging his head
against 20 hanging pots of cattleya orchids, while stepping over
the 100 or so clivias that take up most of the floor of the
11-by-18-foot greenhouse the two men put up in their backyard five
years ago. By now, it's packed to the roof with their obsessions:
the orchids, the clivias, echeverias, gasterias, euphorbias, an
azalea or two. And dozens of lithops, which look like the soft pads
of little animals turned upside down in the desert. Tiny little
flowers open in between its two lobes, which vary in color from
gray to rose to magenta, or a chartreuse that seems to glow from
the inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of my favorites,'' Reynolds said, holding up a
little pot with an olive-green pair of toes. ``Lithops otzeniana,''
he said, his mop of brown curls bobbing over the plant. ``It
reminds me of a big mouth of teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   These succulents from South Africa are also known as flowering
stones, and Reynolds has started to hybridize them,
cross-pollinating his favorites with his finger or a Q-Tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were my first love,'' he said. `'When I was a kid, I'd
look through cactus and succulent books, and I couldn't believe all
the colors and textures.'' The lithops weren't widely available
until about 10 years ago, but now you can buy them at Home Depot
for $2 a piece. ``I went crazy when I found out I could actually
grow them and produce crosses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rutkin showed off the striated leaves of Clivia miniata, whose
cream-white stripes (``like old piano keys,'' he said), shade to
gray-green and then a dark green veering toward black.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese think they're native to Japan, and the Chinese
think they're native to China,'' Rutkin said, ``but they really
come from the Natal province on the east coast of South Africa.''
C. miniata grows on rocks and trees along the coast, and it can
survive dry periods by drawing moisture out of the air. Sometimes,
a clivia with all green leaves will send up a striped one, which
pleases the Japanese no end, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more noble, the sign of a real aristocrat,'' he went
on. ``Like a lady in a very sober kimono, with something really
flashy inside the sleeves.'' To get out the door, we had to squeeze
by a camellia called Yamato Nishiki (Brocade of Old Tokyo), which
was loaded with pink and white blossoms, and a rhododendron with
long tubular white flowers that smelled of jasmine.
</P>
<P>
   We pictured the yard in spring, when there's a sea of blue and
white crocuses against the south fence. The rhododendrons are a big
event, with Percy Wiseman rhododendron turning from apricot-pink to
peach, and Dreamland opening its neon-pink buds, which slowly fade
to pure white. Reynolds stared down at the white leaves of a
dianthus and described how it would look come May: ``It has 2-inch
flowers with pale pink fringed edges and dark maroon spots in the
center,'' he said. ``It looks like saddle oxfords.'' He laughed
irrepressibly, which seems to happen whenever he thinks of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The two designers met at Florida State University close to 30
years ago, when Rutkin had abandoned a doctoral program in
humanities for a master's in fine arts. Reynolds was an
undergraduate, studying graphics and dance. He started growing
sarracenia, or pitcher plants, in buckets on his patio.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they came to Manhattan and formed the Four Hands
Design Studio and Colman Sage, to produce and market their designs,
which range from gift-wrapping paper and fabric to murals and
folding screens. Reynolds also designs stained-glass lamps and
torcheres, and his luminous paper tapestries _ from the blues and
greens of a Persian paradise garden to the golds of a ginkgo forest
_ line the walls of their sunny, 1920s neo-colonial house. Their
studios are on the third floor: Reynolds paints in the east room;
Rutkin in the west room, a table full of sansevieria keeping him
company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Where aren't there plants? (In the kitchen closet; it's full of
fertilizer.) Abutilons fill the east windows in the kitchen, a
pisonia lounges on the white enamel sink, its big leaves brushed
with cream and green; a blue dish piled with the cuttings of a jade
plant sits by the faucet. Bottles of plant food share the same
table as a jar of canned peaches and the mixing bowls. Rutkin's
cymbidiums are stashed by the stove, by the closet, by the sliding
door. But only a few ceropegias survived the disaster that struck
Reynolds' collection one night last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went down to 23, and the heat didn't go on,'' Reynolds
said. ``Something like black death attacked the plants. They
probably could have survived the cold, but the cold-and-wet was the
problem.'' These rubbery vines, with hardly a leaf, hark from the
Canary Islands, South Africa and Madagascar, but they don't look
like much on Staten Island, until they cover themselves with their
waxy, intricate flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had about 40 different species,'' Reynolds said, ``but I
lost half my collection that night.'' He preserved color
photographs of their flowers, though, on a disk, and they sprang to
life on the computer: Ceropegia arabica has little minarets; C.
africana has twisted green cages; C. hybrida hort. has a black
velvet top, like a bishop's miter, and C. distincta var.
hayagarthii appears to be waving purple antennae in the air. They
can be viewed on his Web site at
www.users.interport.net/(tilde)colsage/.
</P>
<P>
   Up on the third floor, Rutkin has found the perfect place for
coaxing his clivias into bloom: the trunk room. He has the windows
cracked to keep the room chilly, which is what clivias need to send
up the flower buds hidden inside the axils on their sturdy, long
stalks.
</P>
<P>
   The young seedlings, though, thrive in the warmer temperatures
of the greenhouse and under lights in the cellar, along with
Reynolds' various succulents and cuttings and stacks of pots and
old storm windows (they make such good windbreaks for the rhodies)
and the wheelbarrow.
</P>
<P>
   What they really need, these collectors grumble, is another
greenhouse. ``Something the size of our house,'' Reynolds had said
earlier, hunched like Quasimodo over his lithops. ``We're thinking
of tearing this one down and putting one clear across the back,
with a 20-foot ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, in the dining room that has been given over to
etching presses and plant tables under lights, Reynolds held up
Ceropegia fusca, which looked like a bunch of gray sticks to me
(organ pipes to Reynolds). ``This is one that nobody has gotten to
bloom outside the Canary Islands,'' he said. ``Except maybe in the
Netherlands.''
</P>
<P>
   He fell in love with ceropegias just looking in books on
succulents. ``I was just taken with the flowers,'' he said.
``They're really spectacular.'' Over the years, he has ordered the
plants from catalogs, and traded seeds and cuttings with friends,
so it was hard to lose half of them in one fell swoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, on the Internet, I've got some people in Holland
who I hope will get me some more,'' he said. ``But I've been so
beaten down. I lost so many last year.'' Rutkin calls this ``the
voice of the plant-collector martyr.''
</P>
<P>
   Order of the Lost Ceropegias? How do I join up?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
