<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0475 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SAD-WINTER-NYT &LR;      02-03 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SAD-WINTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUICK FIX FOR THE BLAHS OF WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the end note instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If I were a truly honest person, I would admit that my motive
for hanging an intricately sequined Haitian voodoo flag over the
fireplace last Sunday was to add some color to a room that, like
the sky outside, was looking a little, well, gray.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unlikely that a truly honest person _ even one
suffering a bad case of seasonal blues _ could persuade my husband
to spend a good part of the afternoon teetering on a stepstool,
hammering nails into the wall. So instead I argued that the flag's
design, which depicted three solemn, dark-haired girls standing
shoulder to shoulder, would bring good luck to a household with
three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I added, although we technically were not practitioners
of a pantheistic religion, it would be foolish to pass up any
opportunity to summon helpful gods _ especially in the winter. (Did
I mention the hard, cold pellets of hail pummeling the
windowpanes?)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I will go to great lengths to combat the winter doldrums, a
malady that besets me in the late afternoons, when it gets dark
before dinner. As the sun sets, so do my spirits. I have tried many
treatments in addition to the sequin cure.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, I devised a simple, three-part strategy for enduring
the worst stretch _ that solitary, single-parenting portion of the
day that lasts from dusk until my husband gets home at 8 p.m. I
would turn up the heat, blast an old Bruce Springsteen album on the
stereo and saute as many onions as necessary to make the house
smell like my grandmother's. That trick worked for a while, but
this winter, instead of feeling cozy, I began to feel trapped, not
so much by my children as by the belief that winter will never end.
</P>
<P>
   I needed to escape. So after my daughters got home from school
the other day, had a snack and settled in with their homework, I
told them I had to go upstairs to my office for a second to check
for phone messages from work.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I sneaked off to my secret computer life. It's perhaps
a sign of just how dreary these days can be that a machine can
manage to reaffirm my humanity, doling out small, incremental doses
of comfort disguised as amusing e-mail or ritual tours of my
favorite Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, I begin my computer treatment with a cleansing whine. I
typed a message to an old friend from college: ``Thin layer of ice
(deadly?) on brick path could lead to lawsuit if Fed Ex driver
trips next time ... would ice pick help?'' The topic was
technically a breach of the unspoken contract that requires our
e-mail to focus exclusively on annoying people we knew in college
but have not seen or heard from since 1984. But venting about
winter did perk me up slightly.
</P>
<P>
   I felt invigorated enough, in fact, to take a quick look at
Ebay.com to see if any particularly irresistible items of
Depression glass were being auctioned. But at $9.99 (plus
shipping), the Floragold `Louisa' Cup and Saucer _nice! _ was
slightly beyond the budget of someone who earns a living as a
writer. That reminded me that I hadn't yet read the latest
installment from one of my favorite writers, Anne Lamott. So I
zipped over to Salon magazine to learn how Ms. Lamott recently
achieved a modicum of spiritual comfort by wrapping herself in her
9-year-old son's still-warm blanket after he went off to school.
</P>
<P>
   This made me remember that I had a lot of pending spiritual
questions of my own, even beyond ``Are trees unhappy in the
winter?'' For instance, I started to wonder what powers those
Haitian gods shimmering on the wall downstairs might actually
possess. And since I was already online, it would take only a few
seconds to go to Hotbot to conduct a search on Haitian flags to do
some research. At gallery-guide.com/museum/noma/archive and
egallery.com/flags.html, I found out that the figures on my flag
probably represented lwas, or spirits invoked during a voodoo
religious ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   This led me to Amazon.com, where I found ``Haitian Vodou
Flags,'' a book by Patrick Arthur Polk that discussed the banners'
religious and cultural implications. The book was published by the
University Press of Mississippi, and after I read the description
of the book at www.upress.state.ms.us, I phoned to ask how to reach
the author.
</P>
<P>
   That's how, about 10 minutes later, I found myself eagerly
describing my flag over the phone to Polk, a museum scientist at
the University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your flag depicts the three twins, or the holy triplets, of
the vodou religion,'' he said. ``Twins have a sacred power in West
African belief. In fact, this is interesting _ a child born after
twins is considered to have even more spiritual force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So the third girl is the most powerful?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all child protectors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good,'' I said, ``because I have three daughters and
_''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, then this flag is absolutely the thing you've got
to have,'' Polk said excitedly. ``It's perfect. Make nice herbal
baths for the children on Christmas and invoke the holy triplets.''
</P>
<P>
   After I hung up, I realized my secret computer life had consumed
more than an hour of the time that could have been allotted to more
practical pursuits. I couldn't really remember where I had been; I
just knew that I had been away. But now I needed to come back home
to cook dinner. Check over homework. Read the baby's favorite puppy
book to her 40 times in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Did I feel guilty about sneaking off? Maybe I should have. But
instead, when I went downstairs to examine the Haitian voodoo flag
again, I was pleased. Then I sat with my children while they
practiced their piano lessons. The music sounded like spring.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Slatalla's e-mail address is Slatalla(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
