<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0503 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      02-03 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNT THE WAYS   HOW, NOT WHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, one can surely buy the poems of Emily Dickinson and
Shakespeare's sonnets this Valentine's Day from any bookstore or
online bookseller, but publishing has nonetheless turned the
holiday of a thousand and one romances into an exercise in the
utilitarian. The fuzzy and lyrical, the twisted skeins of lies and
sighs that make up so much of the romantic novel are not as popular
as the real and practical. How to make love, rather than why.
</P>
<P>
   Has it always been thus? Not really. Book publishers, who one
supposes are as sentimental and dreamy as anyone else in the
faraway spaces of their imaginations, seemingly have gotten caught
up this year in the increasingly popular self-help genre. So for
Valentine's Day it's refining sex and defining relationships,
without the flowers and chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be a bit of a risk since Valentine's Day and Mother's
Day are generally the only times of the year in which ``women's
fiction,'' as publishers loosely call it, can find its away to the
front of the bookstores (with the exception, of course, of the
mega-selling female authors). This is either because book makers
feel these are the two special days worth spending the money to buy
such positioning or the sellers themselves feel it might be good
business. Publishers, like other retailers, are driven by their
ambits of opportunity, like Christmas, Thanksgiving, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Typically this year, for instance, Amazon, the online
bookseller, has on its Valentine's Day gift list ``The Kissing
Companion: Secret Technique of Over 500 Exotic Kisses,'' by Stephen
Jarvis and Elaine Edwards, and ``10,000 Ways to Say I Love You,''
by Gregory J.P. Godek. For the outwardly rigid but secretly
incontestably romantic buyer there is ``Recruiting Love: Using the
Business Skills You Have to Find the Love You Want,'' by Jessica B.
Freeman. Barnes &AMP; Noble's online service is touting, among many
others, ``The Art of Spooning: A Cuddler's Handbook,'' by Jim
Grace, and ``101 Nights of Great Sex,'' by Laura Corn.
</P>
<P>
   And since the celebration is surely about nostalgia,
HarperCollins has issued what it calls the ``all new''
30th-anniversary edition of ``Everything You Always Wanted to Know
About Sex (but Were Afraid to Ask),'' by Dr. David Reuben, and
Pantheon has reissued ``The Technique of the Love Affair,'' by
Doris Langley Moore, originally published in 1928 but updated this
year by Norris Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   That book is almost high art in the lineage of such work, far
beyond the liaisons hinted at in the greeting cards, a work of such
apparent transcendental importance in the genre that Dorothy Parker
said of it that if only she had been privy to its secrets ``maybe I
could have been successful rather than successive.'' Probably the
most graphic book to capture the quality of this year's celebration
is ``Sex Tips for Straight Women From a Gay Man,'' by Dan Anderson
and Maggie Berman on Regan Books.
</P>
<P>
   Now none of the above is entirely fair to book publishers. There
are in fact plenty of lusty romantic fictions in the stores aimed
to flutter the hearts of the Valentine's Day buyer, although Irwyn
Applebaum, president and publisher of Bantam Books, said: ``Many
booksellers have the old Erich Segal syndrome: `Madison County,'
`Message in a Bottle.' They are more into those romances than ones
written by women.'' (Nicholas Sparks' ``Message in a Bottle'' was
published in hardcover last summer, but Warner Books has gotten a
huge gushy best-selling paperback pop out of advertising for the
movie, which opens two days before Valentine's Day.)
</P>
<P>
   But no such manly hangup for Applebaum. He hopes to make
Valentine's Day a bank day for two novelists who are women. In the
alchemy that is book publishing, Bantam is printing nearly 500,000
copies of a paperback original by Jane Feather _ her 12th book _
cleverly, if not obviously, titled ``A Valentine Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It combines two certain attention getters _ the word
`valentine' and the word `wedding' _ and we get a one-two punch,''
he said, sounding about as happy as a candy maker this time of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bantam also hopes to surf the high emotional tide of the
Valentine celebration with Luanne Rice's ``Cloud Nine.'' Applebaum
describes this as ``adult fiction in its best sense'' by which he
means it combines the complex themes of love, remission from cancer
and a surprise romance with an unexpected man. He is betting 50,000
copies, hardcover, for a first printing. ``There are many meanings
to the title,'' Applebaum said rhapsodically. ``It's the name of
the shop the character runs, in which she sells comforters, and of
course, dare I say it, she's on cloud nine with pleasure.'' You
see, titles are all important.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Warner Books, along with ``Message in a Bottle,'' the
publisher has great hopes for Katherine Stone's ``Thief of
Hearts,'' a novel of ``heart-wrenching betrayals and unforgivable
pain.'' Still John Aherne, the associate editor, said, ``It's
interesting to see how more and more the prescriptive books are
breaking out, along with the fuzzies that come out on the 14th.''
</P>
<P>
   He has high hopes for Joyce Marlow's ``Country Ways: Secrets for
Finding and Keeping a Country Man,'' aimed at those women who, as
with Lady Chatterley, are apparently searching for a gamekeeper.
``We've found that the books that tend to work for us are practical
advice,'' Aherne said, adding that he was particularly prideful
about what he called an anti-Valentine Day book, ``The Breakup
Book,'' by Monica Sheehan. ``It's for people who could use all the
advice they could get after the bitter reminder that it doesn't
always work out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So what about Mother's Day, the next great celebration of love?
Bantam is gearing up ``Hot Sex: How to Do It,'' by Tracey Cox,
advice for Mom and Dad on the hot tin roof.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
