<HEADER>
A0506 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOTIVATORS-PRODUCTS     02-03 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOTIVATORS-PRODUCTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK ON THE DARK SIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're having a lousy day, filled with disappointments and
clouded by self-doubt. The Smashing Pumpkins' ``Cherub Rock'' _ the
song with the refrain ``Let me out!'' _ is blasting from the car CD
player, sounding strangely appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Days like this, some people tell you to buck up; there's even a
whole industry of motivational products telling you to look on the
bright side. But sometimes, instead of optimism, you want empathy,
best served with a dash of cynical humor. That's where Despair Inc.
and its Demotivators products come in.
</P>
<P>
   Walk into the hallway at the Dallas-based company's
``fulfillment center'' in an Irving industrial park, and you find
that cynical humor immediately. Posters brandish platitudes _
anti-platitudes, really _ about ``Ineptitude,'' ``Failure'' and
``Procrastination.'' Example: ``Pessimism _ Every dark cloud has a
silver lining, but lightning kills hundreds of people each year who
are trying to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   E.L. Kersten, founder of Despair Inc., doesn't look like an
unhappy guy. He looks, well, businesslike, with his easy smile and
smart suit (''I get my clothes from Wal-Mart,'' he says). But
behind the smile lurks a cynical heart _ or maybe just a realistic
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at something like our `Mediocrity' poster, and I think
it's true,'' he says. ``I look at the `Stupidity' poster, I think
it's true. I look at the `Failure' poster, and I think it's true. I
think the difference is that I personally would rather deal with
reality than paint a nice, happy veneer over it to make myself good
until reality comes crushing in.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kersten's cynicism, Despair Inc. is all in good fun.
It's a parody of the Successories line of motivational posters that
adorn some corporate conference rooms. Kersten says he has yet to
hear any complaints from Successories. (Several calls to
Successories' headquarters weren't returned _ or maybe we should
say that we failed to get them to talk to us.)
</P>
<P>
   Kersten and his associates, brothers Justin and Jef Sewell, were
working for a start-up company in Dallas when the idea was born.
Things weren't going well, and one of them _ they're coy about who
_ began thumbing through a catalog for motivational products and
making up more pessimistic sayings. Then they began attaching the
one-liners to stock images and hanging them in their cubicles. The
sayings drew so much attention that the trio decided that, should
the start-up fail, they should market the sayings.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, the start-up stopped. The three took the money
they got from the sellout and started Despair Inc., with a Web
site, www.despair.com, to market their Demotivators posters,
calendars, T-shirts and note cards (''Ineptitude,'' for instance,
is illustrated with a shot of a skier wiping out). About a dozen
sayings are in circulation, and they're working on a dozen more
designs. They are also considering adding screen savers and coffee
mugs.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Web site didn't engender much response; five
orders was considered a good day. Then someone _ they don't know
who _ downloaded the images but didn't include the company's URL,
the despair.com address. Whoever downloaded the images began
forwarding them, and the images eventually turned up on the home
page of a computer-science professor at Washington University in
St. Louis. USA Today wrote about his page and the Demotivators
images, and Yahoo! named his page Cool Site of the Day. But the
images weren't his, and when he tracked down where they came from,
he gave credit where credit was due.
</P>
<P>
   The second the computer-science professor added the link to
www.despair.com, life changed for the guys at Despair Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had acclimatized ourselves to two or three orders a day,''
Justin Sewell says in a rare nonreticent moment (Kersten usually
does the talking). ``At 11 a.m. on _ I guess it was Oct. 23 _
suddenly, in the course of literally an hour, the fax machine would
go off every time we moved. Literally, after 100 consecutive
orders, it was like, `Hey, this thing is not stopping!' We struck
some sort of loser reservoir.''
</P>
<P>
   A big reservoir. The Sewell brothers work for Despair full time,
but they recently hired a full-time operations director to allow
them to step into the background and work on other projects.
</P>
<P>
   Despair Inc. accepts orders only through its Web site, although
Kersten and associates are working on adding a toll-free number. On
peak days _ usually just after a story in the media _ orders can
hit 250. The Wall Street Journal, the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
and the Los Angeles Times have written about the company, and a
People magazine story is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The products' popularity says something about
turn-of-the-millennium malaise. Or does it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many people who tell us they are sick and tired of
motivational posters,'' Kersten says. ``I think it suggests that
there's a large group of people out there that want something that
is more honest, more refreshing, more in keeping with their
experience, rather than `Life is just this wonderful journey of
overcoming hardships.' Sometimes it's making peace with your
weaknesses and cutting your losses and moving on. Especially if it
includes purchasing a poster, which can be seen as an outward
indication of your healing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
