<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-VITAMINS-TEX </SLUG>
 
THE ABCs OF CHILDREN'S VITAMINS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Healthy children who eat whole-grain breads, cereals and pasta,
meat, milk, fruits and vegetables probably don't need extra
vitamins and minerals. But what about the 8-year-old who spurns
anything that might contain meat or eggs, or the 5-year-old who
will eat nothing but hot dogs, or the child who absolutely refuses
all vegetables?
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are frantic that their children aren't getting what
they need from their diets, but in most cases they are,'' says Dr.
Loraine Stern, associate clinical professor in the Department of
Pediatrics at the UCLA School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a child won't eat meat, offer him peanut butter on a
whole-wheat cracker. It has the same complete protein,'' Stern
says. ``If young children will eat only white bread, plain noodles
and corn kernels, it's because that's what their parents offer
them.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's any doubt about whether kids are getting all the
vitamins and minerals they need for good growth and development,
talk to your pediatrician, she advises.
</P>
<P>
   Stern and Dr. William Dietz, director of the Division of
Nutrition and Physical Activity at the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention, are co-authors of a guide to children's nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Published last month, ``The American Academy of Pediatrics Guide
to Your Child's Nutrition'' (Villard Books, $23) is an
authoritative, easy-to-use guide to children's diet and eating
habits.
</P>
<P>
   The book has a section on nutrition basics, with vitamin and
mineral tables listing all the essentials including effects, signs
of deficiency, signs of overdose and good sources for various
vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on Page 97, you learn that vitamin A keeps skin,
hair and nails healthy, helps maintain gums, glands, bones and
teeth, helps prevent infection and promotes eye function. Good
sources include milk and dairy foods, fortified cereals, green and
yellow vegetables, deep-yellow or orange fruits and organ meats.
</P>
<P>
   It is always better to get vitamins from food than in pill form,
Stern says. First, the vitamin supplements available in pills are
incomplete, and second, a pill results in a high concentration of a
particular vitamin that may interfere with the absorption of other
nutrients from food.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary for children, vitamin and mineral supplements are
available in liquid drops and colorful chewable tablets. Most
provide vitamins A, D and C, with or without iron, and some also
contain vitamin E and the B vitamins thiamin, riboflavin, niacin
and B-6.
</P>
<P>
   One supplement that could be a must-buy is fluoride. If drinking
water does not have fluoride added or a child drinks only bottled
water, parents should put fluoride on the list of supplements that
children definitely need, Stern says.
</P>
<P>
   Fluoride is crucial to the formation of teeth, and is the main
reason pediatricians recommend mixing powdered formula with regular
tap water rather than bottled water. In most areas of this country,
the municipal water supply is fortified with fluoride..MDBR/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
