</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITTSBURGH-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PITTSBURGH SYMPHONY: PITTSBURGH PRESENTS ITS NEW VOICE  
(DW) 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa.)  By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Pittsburgh Symphony, like most good orchestras,
has the knack of taking on the voice of its music director. This is
a benign form of ventriloquism, though one not practiced
everywhere. A few ``personality'' orchestras do in fact survive
(though some only as recent memories): the Vienna Philharmonic
(gemuetlich), the Philadelphia Orchestra (luxurious), the Chicago
Symphony (loud). On the other hand, most operatives on the world
stage are less shapers of style than they are the ones being
shaped.
</P>
<P>
   After profitable years under Lorin Maazel, the Pittsburgh
visited Carnegie Hall on Tuesday night with his successor, Mariss
Jansons. Much has changed, as this program of Dvorak, Berlioz and
Christopher Rouse showed. Maazel gave these players a combination
of power and elegance that made it sound like one of the country's
truly undervalued ensembles. Jansons brings a personal touch and
with it a looser sound.
</P>
<P>
   The string playing is together and in tune, though not so
sharply edged. The conductor's emotionalism also extends to a love
of the big noise, and when Berlioz's ``Symphonie Fantastique''
invited such displays, Jansons seemed happy to have his brass and
timpani players explore their outer limits.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, Jansons is also somewhat of a micromanager, a man
who likes to map out phrases according to his own careful
itineraries. Phrase marks, hesitations, ritards, crescendos and
decrescendos are meticulously planned; though his players followed
him with skill, there was an apprehension and self-consciousness in
their responses.
</P>
<P>
   This was the kind of conducting that works wonders when
conductor and orchestra spend a lot of time together, so one hopes
that in seasons to come Jansons will not follow the path of
absentee music director but give this worthy ensemble a suitable
gift of his presence.
</P>
<P>
   Midori was the soloist in the Dvorak A minor Violin Concerto,
and it was heartening, and a little chastening, to see how she has
survived the predictions of doom and destruction (some from this
writer) uttered during her years as a child prodigy. The sound is
fine and lean and the technique as impregnable as ever.
</P>
<P>
   More important is the soundness and seriousness of the
musicianship. First is the choice of repertory. The Dvorak is
neither a showpiece nor a career maker. Difficult without being
spectacular, its music has half hidden values, and Midori met them
with respect.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing at all is hidden in Rouse's ``Infernal Machine,'' an
exercise in gee-whiz orchestration hellbent on demonstrating its
powers to amaze. The many effects are smoothly handled; the
entertainment value is high. The work behaves like a stand-up
comedian: glib, wise of mouth, inventive and relentlessly
self-referential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1723EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVIL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-03 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVIL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE EVIL THAT MEN DO': LEARNING WHAT IS STANDARD ABOUT DEVIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the opening pages of ``The Evil That Men Do,'' Stephen G.
Michaud drops several intriguing comments like these:
</P>
<P>
   _ When rape victims struggle, rapists tend to remain with them
twice as long as when there is no resistance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deviant sexual crimes were ``both curbed and concealed in
America at mid-century by a moral climate hostile to sexual
extremes or erotic experimentation of almost any sort.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Aberrant offenders use pornography to validate their
deviance. ... The more they see of it, and masturbate to it, the
more their behavior is reinforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Since these are all controversial observations, the reader is
drawn to learn what more Michaud has to say on these subjects. But
this turns out to be not so easy to do in a book that is partly a
biography, partly an examination of methodology and partly a
collection of case studies.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud first met Roy Hazelwood, his subject and collaborator,
in 1984, when Hazelwood was a member of the FBI's Behavioral
Science Unit, based at the FBI Academy at Quantico, Va. This is the
team that was made famous in the 1980s by the Atlanta child murders
case, which Hazelwood and other members of the unit helped solve,
and by Thomas Harris' novel ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' which was
based on the unit's specialized work.
</P>
<P>
   Michaud writes of Hazelwood, ``Roy's domain is the sexual
criminal's mental and emotional planes, the deviant mind's hot
zones where lust and rage are fused and deadly fantasies flower.''
After their first meeting, Michaud decided to do a book about
Hazelwood's work, but several factors impeded him. His subject had
much of his career still ahead of him. He found it difficult to
adapt the formula of previous books on which he had collaborated,
like ``The Only Living Witness,'' a portrait of Ted Bundy, and
``Ted Bundy: Conversations with a Killer.'' Hazelwood's story had
too many focal points.
</P>
<P>
   Describing his eventual solution, he writes, ``The search for a
narrative thread through such diverse material led me at last to
settle on a thematic organization for the book, a chapter by
chapter exploration of sexual criminals and their victims, divided
according to offender types, their motives and their modus
operandi.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the resulting tangle doesn't have threads worth
following. Hazelwood is a fascinating figure who started out as a
career Army officer working with criminals, switched to the FBI in
1971, joined the behavioral unit in 1978, when sex crimes were
largely ignored because the bureau had little jurisdiction over
such matters, and helped transform the investigation of sexual
deviance into a scientific discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Among his major contributions were the realization that sex
crimes could usefully be classified as organized, disorganized and
mixed, and that rapists could be divided into six groups, according
to their motives and behavior. By such systematic analysis, he
developed the ability to read crime scenes analytically and to
profile deviant criminals with uncanny accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   As for the cases Hazelwood has helped solve with the behavioral
unit or as a member of the consulting group he joined in his
retirement, some, like the deadly explosion aboard the battleship
Iowa in 1989 or the hoax that a grand jury found was perpetrated by
Tawana Brawley in claiming falsely to have been raped in 1987, are
too familiar to be of much interest in their retelling. Others seem
to have attracted Michaud by their sheer weirdness, particularly
autoerotic fatalities from accidental strangulation, which
Hazelwood happens to be an expert on, and the case of a man who ate
parts of two victims in a macaroni casserole.
</P>
<P>
   The most instructive ones to read are those illustrating four of
Hazelwood's six basic types of rapist. These are what he terms the
common ``power reassurance rapist,'' who wants only to prove his
masculinity to himself; the ``power assertive rapist,'' less common
but more violent; the ``anger retaliatory rapist,'' who works out
his rage against women by using excessive force, and the ``anger
excitation rapist,'' a sadist who is sexually stimulated by his
victim's suffering. (The other two categories, which interest
Hazelwood somewhat less, are the so-called ``opportunistic
rapist,'' who is often drunk or high on drugs, and the ``gang
rapist,'' who succumbs to pathological group behavior.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you learn so much from cases like these that by the
end, in a chapter called ``You Be the Analyst,'' you find you are
able to put together many of the clues in the 1986 rape-murder of a
young typist in the FBI's San Antonio office. (Although one clue
that the author himself seems to have disregarded is the peculiar
sense of humor of the victim's parents, a German-American couple
named Vetter who called their daughter Donna, Donnerwetter being
German both for thunderstorm and an interjection translated in my
dictionary as ``damn it all!'' and ``blast!'')
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that in a survey of some 41 convicted serial
rapists undertaken by Hazelwood, he could find no comprehensive
reason, as he puts it, ``why some people act out and others
don't,'' although he still believes the answer has to do with
self-perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons that we all don't act out is that we have
inhibitors, or brakes, to control desires,'' he says. ``They can be
social status, religion, personal values or fear of jail. Those who
do act out are losers. They are convinced they are losers, so they
don't see how they have anything more to lose by yielding to their
desires.''
</P>
<P>
   He quotes one serial rapist as saying: ``Regardless of how
successful I may appear to be, I know I'm going to screw up. So why
not go ahead and do it and enjoy it? I'm going to give in to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood concludes: ``I frequently run into this theme with
offenders. Sexual sadists. Serial rapists. It is a common theme.''
</P>
<P>
   Depressing.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE EVIL THAT MEN DO'
</P>
<P>
   FBI Profiler Roy Hazelwood's Journey Into the Minds of Sexual
Predators
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen G. Michaud with Roy Hazelwood
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 262 pages. St. Martin's Press. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
