<P>
   AIRLINES _ ATLANTA _ The planned introduction of flights to
Atlanta by several niche airline services is gradually changing the
complexion of competition. The service is being introduced by major
carriers, not startups. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   AIRTRAN-ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ AirTran Airways has found a way to
get more of its planes into Hartsfield International Airport. The
airport will reconfigure parking spaces for larger planes to
accommodate AirTran's smaller 737s. The company already uses 18
gates for its 131 daily Atlanta flights. Hartsfield Airport will
allow it to double-park its airplanes. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LEVIN-ARENA _ ATLANTA _ A day after Turner Broadcasting System
and Philips Electronics signed a deal to name the new arena Philips
Arena, Time Warner Charmain Gerald Levin praised the deal as very
significant for Atlanta's downtown renewal. Levin also said Atlanta
remains important to Time Warner's . 8'' (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT _ ATLANTA _Lucent's Norcross plant has scored a large
contract with Pathnet for the production of fiber-optic cable, a
deal potentially worth $2.1 billion. It's apparently the largest
fiber-optics deal ever. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-Y2K-MEDICAD _ Checking out a tip that medicaid is way behind
on its Y2K readiness. That could throw a real snag into the system.
It processes 50 million claims in Georgia a year. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELCO _GM founder Billy Durant bought AC Spark Plug in 1909 and
four years later Dayton Engineering Laboratories (Delco). Soon, he
acquired companies owned by Charles Kettering, inventor of the
self-starter. It was the start of an auto parts empire that would
eventually become Delphi Automotive Systems, the world's largest
auto parts maker. A historical review. (Kliner, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DELPHI-HACHEY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Guy C. Hachey, the new president
of Delphi Chassis Systems, agreed to be the subject of a newspaper
profile on one condition: no photographs of him sitting in his
Kettering office, please. ``He's hardly ever in his office,''
explained Delphi spokesman Michael McCurdy. ``More than any GM
executive I've known since I've been here, he spends an enormous
amount of time on the (factory) floor. He's trying to understand
the plants.'' He has good reason to take a close look. Those plants
are key to Delphi's future. We profile the new president.
(DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
