A0534 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     02-03 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY ARE YOU SMILING? 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If things are going well but you're still feeling blue, it could
be because you're suffering from ``happiness anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 125 million Americans suffer from happiness anxiety,
according to an article in the prestigious supermarket tabloid
medical journal Weekly World News, a publication that is to the
advancement of psychiatric understanding what ``Biker Chick''
magazine is to the advancement of women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   If I understand the article correctly (no sure thing; my
attention often wandered to the photo of the Page Five Girl),
happiness anxiety is when you feel bad when you should be feeling
good, as opposed to unhappiness anxiety, which is when you feel
good when you should be feeling bad.
</P>
<P>
   From what I read in the newspaper (certainly not from what I
read in my bank statement), the United States is enjoying a period
of unprecedented economic prosperity. The stock market is up and
unemployment is down. Dan Quayle says he's going to run for
president and scientists say fiber may not be that great for your
colon after all.
</P>
<P>
   With news this good, it's no wonder so many people are ready to
tie cinder blocks around their necks and jump off a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   People who suffer from happiness anxiety either feel guilty when
they are happy or else worry that the bubble will burst as soon as
they crack a smile. While some might say that the happiness anxiety
phenomenon is just another example of how America is populated by a
bunch of pathetic whiners who not only don't appreciate their good
fortune but wouldn't recognize it if it bit them on the neck, I,
personally, am taking the matter quite seriously.
</P>
<P>
   We in the media, of course, do everything we can to promote
happiness anxiety. (People who don't know from one minute to the
next whether they should be happy or sad are apparently more apt to
buy a paper than those who do. They also tend to be big fans of the
comic strip ``Cathy,'' but that is another story.)
</P>
<P>
   Next to the front-page story of President Clinton's impeachment
trial we will run the results of a public opinion poll showing that
72 percent of the American people think that Clinton is doing a
great job even though he is a lowlife who deserves a good paddling.
(By Hillary, not Monica.) A TV network the other day announced that
Joe DiMaggio had died but then retracted the story about 20 minutes
later. (Joe, who is of an earlier generation, did not suffer
happiness anxiety upon hearing the premature news of his death, but
did, reportedly, very much want to strangle someone at the
network.)
</P>
<P>
   On the business page, we run stories about how great technology
stocks are doing next to a story about how the Y2K computer bug is
going to cause all the world's computers to short-circuit at
midnight, Dec. 31, 1999, sending us all scurrying into caves in the
Wyoming foothills where we will spend the rest of our lives
defending our cache of Spam and powdered milk from those who did
not have the foresight to prepare. The coming of the millennium, of
course, is the ultimate happiness anxiety story. On the one hand,
we love watching all those zeros roll up on our historical
odometer, but how can we really enjoy the moment when we know (or
fear) the world is going to come to an end at the stroke of
midnight?
</P>
<P>
   The real mystery here is why a full 50 percent of Americans are
not suffering from happiness anxiety. Are their powers of
self-delusion greater than the rest of us? Are they taking Prozac
or some other anti-depressant? Are they too cheap to buy a
newspaper? The next time I encounter a person who is suffering from
happiness anxiety, I'm going to ask him how he can smile at a time
like this.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
