<HEADER>
A0537 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     02-03 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING AIM AT THE HEART OF THIS PROFESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HARRAL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a decade or more, we have been reading surveys that say
public confidence in the news media is dropping.
</P>
<P>
   This is frightening information, because it strikes at the very
heart of what journalists do for a living. In its most simple
definition, journalism is relating information to people.
</P>
<P>
   It works when people believe that the information is credible.
When they do not believe that, it becomes an exercise in futility.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Newspaper Editors recently concluded a
three-year research project to study this issue, specifically
related to newspapers. There'll be more later about how that was
done.
</P>
<P>
   As a working journalist for 35 years, I dislike being lumped
into a category _ ``media'' _ that includes everything from
Internet sites to supermarket tabloids to shock television to talk
radio to highly niched magazines.
</P>
<P>
   I've argued that the standards are higher in newspapers than in
many other forms of journalism. I believe that, partly because I
have experience in different forms of media and partly because of
observation of the handling of stories about which I possessed a
great deal of information.
</P>
<P>
   But this study didn't deal with the ``media.'' This study dealt
specifically with newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The ASNE report grouped the results into six major findings:
</P>
<P>
   (1) The public sees too many factual errors and spelling or
grammar mistakes in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   (2) The public perceives that newspapers don't consistently
demonstrate respect for, and knowledge of, their readers and their
communities.
</P>
<P>
   (3) The public suspects that the viewpoints and biases of
journalists influence what stories are covered and how they are
covered.
</P>
<P>
   (4) The public believes that newspapers chase and overcover
sensational stories because they are exciting and they sell papers.
Readers don't believe that these stories deserve the attention and
the play that they get.
</P>
<P>
   (5) The public feels that newsroom values and practices
sometimes conflict with their own priorities for their newspapers
(for example, trading speed for accuracy).
</P>
<P>
   (6) Members of the public who have had experience with the news
process are the most critical of media credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The research was conducted in 3,000 telephone interviews
completed in April and May 1998, supposedly projectable to 197
million U.S. adults, and in 16 focus groups completed in August
1998. Also, a questionnaire was sent to 1,714 newspaper
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   To those of you who believe we rig the polls: I assure you that
we wouldn't have rigged this one to report these findings.
</P>
<P>
   The results are not surprising to anyone who is in daily contact
with newspaper readers.
</P>
<P>
   What I don't know is whether the issues they address have
changed over the years. My memory tells me that newspapers are more
accurate and more concerned with fairness and balance than they
were when I first broke into the trade, but maybe my memory is
faulty.
</P>
<P>
   I do know that the research findings are consistent with what I
see and hear from the readers.
</P>
<P>
   As an ombudsman, I handled perhaps 6,500 telephone calls and
several thousand e-mails and letters in 1998, and most of them
would have fit in one of the six categories above.
</P>
<P>
   The ASNE study broke out each of those findings in a separate
and more complete report. During the next month or two, I'll
occasionally deal with one of the findings in more detail.
</P>
<P>
   I promise not to blow it out of proportion. I don't, however,
promise to make no typographical errors. I always have been a lousy
typist.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is ombudsman for the Star-Telegram. His e-mail
address is harral &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1734EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETTY-RETURN-NYT &LR;      02-03 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETTY-RETURN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTY TO GIVE   3 ARTIFACTS   BACK TO ITALY
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Agreeing that the works were stolen, the J. Paul Getty
Museum will turn over three important pieces from its antiquities
collection to the Italian government this week.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time the Getty has returned ancient
artifacts that were discovered to have been stolen. But the return
of a 480 B.C. Greek terra-cotta drinking cup, a torso of the god
Mithras from the second century and a second-century Roman copy of
a sculpture by Polyclitus, the head of a young athlete known as
Diadumenos, is one of the most significant archeological
restitutions to Italy in many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent them to Italy because that is where they belong,''
Marion True, curator of antiquities at the Getty, explained. ``Our
own examination confirmed the claims of the Italian government.''
</P>
<P>
   The Getty's decision, which was not prompted by legal action in
Italy, was a boon to Italian officials, who have waged a long,
complicated and often fruitless battle to retrieve artworks and
ancient artifacts stolen from archeological sites and museums and
sold on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   There are still many artworks on display in American museums
that are claimed by Italy, Greece and Turkey. The Metropolitan
Museum of Art in New York City has a longstanding dispute with
Italian government officials over its collection of third-century
B.C. Hellenistic silver, which Italian and American archeologists
say were illegally removed from a site that Americans were
excavating.
</P>
<P>
   Italian officials say they see this week's restitution as a
hopeful sign. ``There is greater openness,'' said Gen. Roberto
Conforti, who heads the special police task force on art theft.
``We have had a lot of dialogue about this issue, and it is
beginning to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Getty's decision to return works that it thinks have been
proved stolen from a clearly identified site comes after years of
dispute between the Italian authorities and American museums and
private collectors. But there have been growing signs of
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Italy gave in to pressure from foreign museums
and loosened its loan policy, extending the time artworks could be
shown abroad from six months to a year. That display of flexibility
seems to have eased the Getty's decision. ``It can only help,'' Ms.
True said. ``We don't have to own everything if material is made
available for exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Getty made its decision on its own but acknowledged
that it might have repercussions for other museums and collectors.
``There is great fear among many museums; they are already getting
defensive,'' Ms. True said. ``But we have drawn a clear ethical
line: Once we have demonstrated that a documented piece was stolen,
it has to be returned.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981 and 1982 the Metropolitan Museum, with great fanfare,
acquired 15 silver artifacts from a private art dealer in
Switzerland. A Sicilian magistrate, Silvio Raffiota, conducted a
long investigation and concluded that the silver had been stolen by
local thieves from the site at Morgantina. Malcolm Bell, an
American archeologist who oversaw the dig at Morgantina, agrees.
When Bell asked the Metropolitan Museum for permission to study the
silver to try to prove its provenance, it refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Getty has done is admirable and important,'' Bell
said on Wednesday night. ``The Met and other collectors have taken
a very hard line that they can buy what they please, and I think
this weakens their position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan on Wednesday declined to comment. A spokesman
said the museum staff had not had an opportunity to study the Getty
decision.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. courts have also started setting precedents for art
collectors. In 1997 a federal judge upheld the seizure of a gold
platter dating from 450 B.C. that had been bought by Michael H.
Steinhardt, a former hedge-fund manager, and that the Italian
government said had been smuggled out of Italy. That case is now
under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian authorities say they hope that court decision and
the Getty's decision will influence private collectors. Maurice
Tempelsman, a wealthy diamond merchant who was close to Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis, bought pieces of sculptures of two goddesses that
are over 2,000 years old from a London dealer. The Italian
authorities say they were stolen from a grave near Morgantina.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government has not sued for their recovery, relying
mostly on diplomatic contacts and appeals to Tempelsman.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Tempelsman, Gus Weill, said that Tempelsman
``has not been presented with one iota of evidence that the works
were in any fashion inappropriately acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Mario Bondioli Osio, president of the Interministerial
Commission for Artworks, which seeks to recover lost patrimony,
said, ``I am convinced the goddesses were stolen from that site,
but I do not know if I can prove it in a court of law.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
