<HEADER>
A0563 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEESE04-COX     02-03 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEESE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warming up to raclette cheese
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The night was cold. The fire was hot. The cheese
he brought was raclette.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect! That's the cheese the Swiss love to heat in front of a
fire, scraping the slowly melting cheese off to eat with warm
vegetables or bread.
</P>
<P>
   It was an impromptu event, so I put the cheese in front of the
fire and set out a plate of crackers. The warm cheese oozed. I
scraped off a soft layer. It was good. I stretched out.
</P>
<P>
   And kicked over his glass of red wine. On the Oriental rug.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is clear. Do your cooking in the kitchen, not the
living room.
</P>
<P>
   And there is always cheese in my kitchen. Even if the blizzard
comes, and I haven't been to the store in a week, there will always
be cheese, enough Parmesan for pasta and blue for a salad, and
inevitably some good-eating cheese.
</P>
<P>
   With a little luck the refrigerator might even hold a big wedge
of a raclette cheese, which, with the proper accompaniments, can
become a meal. The preparation is an old standby, like Swiss
fondue, but it never caught on over here the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Eating raclette, like fondue, is a ritual. Melt and scrape. Melt
again and scrape. But there is more to be done with this cheese
than that. Because of its wonderful melting qualities _ it oozes
into a velvety consistency instead of running _ raclette has
multiple uses.
</P>
<P>
   These raclette crisps are easy snacks to serve with cocktails.
Simply slice the cheese, put the slices on a cookie sheet, sprinkle
with chopped pecans and bake for 12 to 15 minutes. That's it. No
mixing, no flour, no fuss. The crisps cool for a moment on the
cookie sheet, then are lifted to a paper towel-lined plate. When
cool they can keep for a few days in a well-sealed tin.
</P>
<P>
   For added interest, sprinkle with some fresh basil the last
minute they are in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   For this recipe the cheese needs to be very cold to slice
easily. Tuck it into the freezer for an hour ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   RACLETTE CRISPS WITH PECANS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 to 30
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound raclette cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons snipped fresh basil, optional
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Trim rind from the cheese. Slice the cheese 1/4-inch thick. Cut
each slice in half; you should have two square pieces, about 1 1/2
to 2 inches square.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pieces 2 inches apart on a nonstick cookie sheet (the
cheese will spread). Sprinkle each piece with some of the pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 12 to 15 minutes, until the oil bubbles from the
cheese. Do not allow the crisps to brown or they will become
bitter. If using the basil, sprinkle over the crisps for the last
minute of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Cool the crisps on the cookie sheet for about 10 seconds and
remove with a spatula to a paper towel-lined plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serve at room temperature. They can be stored for a day or two
in a tightly sealed tin.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, there is no nutritional analysis for this recipe.
The fat bubbles up and separates from the cheese, with much of the
fat remaining behind on the cookie sheet. How much is a scientist's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipe adapted from Hors d' Oeuvres by Gillian Duffy (Morrow
$23).
</P>
<P>
   Another appetizer that makes good use of raclette's superior
melting ability is cheese toasts. These are also good served with
soup.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the cheese must be very cold to slice.
</P>
<P>
   RACLETTE CHEESE TOASTS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 toasts
</P>
<P>
   One whole-grain baguette or country-style loaf
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cold raclette cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons whole-grain mustard
</P>
<P>
   Cut the bread on the diagonal into eight half-inch slices,
discarding the ends.
</P>
<P>
   On a baking sheet, toast one side of the slices under broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the cheese into thin pieces, using a cheese plane if you
have one.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the bread over and spread teaspoon mustard on the untoasted
side of each slice. Top toast with the cheese, dividing equally.
Broil until the cheese is just melted, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipe from Gourmet magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 181 calories, 9.7
g fat, 33 mg cholesterol, 410 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional way to serve raclette is from a wheel softened
in front of an open fire. That can be a fireplace inside or a
charcoal fire outside. A contemporary method is to use a raclette
pan with its own little broiler to warm the cheese. Those with
neither a fireplace or a raclette pan can do a makeshift version in
the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
