<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN04-CO     02-03 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: When downtown wasn't run-down
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share their memories of growing up in small-town
America. Back then, or at least the way we remember it, life was
like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Mattie Trantham
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   MEXIA, Texas _ Every trip I make through downtown Mexia leaves
me saddened and misty-eyed. Nostalgia overtakes me as I view the
vacant buildings and caved-in structures.
</P>
<P>
   During my growing-up years in the 1940s and '50s, there were no
vacant buildings, and faces everywhere were familiar.
</P>
<P>
   So many wonderful memories of so many wonderful people!
</P>
<P>
   Aubrey Franklin was always on hand to welcome shoppers to Duke &AMP;
Ayers, and he never seemed to mind that the new toys were tested
along the floor of the aisles ... Pearson Saltsman was the affable
butcher at Hitt Grocery ... Mrs. Wortham, Mrs. Spencer and Josie
Chandler were the helpful ladies at the Sears catalog store.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday nights found no empty parking places when the stores
stayed open late and families and friends gathered to shop and
visit. The stores were packed, people visited from car to car, and
the National and Palace theaters were full.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 9 or 10, Mother began sending me to town to run
errands, pay bills, etc. My bicycle would remain parked by the City
Hall, and there was never a concern that it would not be there when
I returned.
</P>
<P>
   Funny smells came from the Bill Moss Shoe Shop.
</P>
<P>
   Cox &AMP; Forrest Drugstore was a child's delight with its
marble-top soda fountain, tall leather bar stools, slow-moving
ceiling fans and ice cream tables and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Karner-Phillips was a ``grown-up'' store, and there was a cage
at the back where the cashier, Mrs. Ione Busby, sat.
</P>
<P>
   Gafford's Furniture had hope chests to die for.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Noles' J.C. Penney store was equipped with those
fascinating change cups which were zoomed by cable to the cashier,
Mrs. May, upstairs. How funny it was when the cup was not properly
secured and money rained down everywhere!
</P>
<P>
   Christmas toyland in Penney's basement was a magical wonderland
that seemed as large as a football field.
</P>
<P>
   The J&AMP;V Cafe was a popular gathering place, and Eubanks Hardware
was an institution with its wonderful creaking wooden floors and
leathery smells.
</P>
<P>
   On Main Street was the International Harvester dealership where
my dad worked for Ralph and Mabel Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Boss McKenzie was THE law in town, trains stopped regularly at
the depot and the textile mill whistle awakened the whole town each
morning. In summer the aroma from the cotton gin was delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Later, growing up, I worked summers and weekends at the dime
store making 30 cents an hour. My only worry back then was whether
I'd have a Saturday night date.
</P>
<P>
   I was blessed with loving Christian parents and a delightfully
happy childhood that was touched by the lives of so many who helped
mold me during my young years.
</P>
<P>
   Our downtown may be crumbling, but memories are forever!
</P>
<P>
   (Mattie Trantham, who is retired, has lived in Mexia for almost
60 years.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
