<HEADER>
A0585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MINDSPRING02-COX     02-03 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MINDSPRING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring finds the way to San Jose
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ According to the guidebooks, U.S. 101,
California's Bayshore Highway, is not the way to San Jose. At least
not the right way. Interstate 280 is far prettier, going through
mountains, past lakes and other scenic vistas. But for the plugged
in and wired crowd, U.S. 101 is the only way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Every exit _ Cupertino, Palo Alto, Mountain View and Santa Clara
_ is another off-ramp on the real-life information superhighway.
Apple Computer, Sun Microsystems, Netscape, Intel, USWeb, Informix,
Yahoo! and Netcom, the Internet service provider being acquired by
Atlanta's MindSpring, all call this little corner of the world
home.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling down U.S. 101 makes the so-called parking lot deal
between cable modem provider At Home and Web portal Excite in
nearby Redwood City not only plausible but downright inevitable.
You can't swing a cat without hitting some 24-year-old techie who
is making more money than his parents by spending 18 hours in front
of a state-of-the-art computer working on what nearly everyone,
even pinstriped analysts way back in New York, is convinced is the
Next Big Thing.
</P>
<P>
   You've really got to love a place where ComputerWorld is
considered recreational reading, where the Technology Museum is
bigger than the Art Museum _ and has longer lines. And, in this
world, having three jobs in three years is seen as visionary
instead of aimless.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of this high-tech wonderland is Netcom, which
MindSpring snapped up for $245 million last month. Netcom operates
out of sleek Italian-modern offices in the heart of San Jose. It's
a good bet the chief executive officer does not have lawn furniture
in his office, as does MindSpring Chairman Charles Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring is pretty much an unknown quantity in California.
Brewer bought his way into technology's most exclusive neighborhood
_ a place most of his neighbors grew up in. Back home in Atlanta,
Brewer is king of the world. His company's every move is chronicled
and applauded in a city desperately trying to draw attention to its
growing high-tech community.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Silicon Valley, MindSpring is just another
technology company in a region dominated by technology companies.
Brewer is just another quirky company chairman in a sea of quirky
company chairmen, including Apple's Steve Jobs, Sun's Scott
McNealy, Intel's Andy Grove, and ``chief Yahoos'' Dave Filo and
Jerry Yang.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring is working hard to get noticed out here. Business and
tech types know MindSpring by reputation and by its stock price,
but California consumers still need convincing. The ``road
warriors'' who man MindSpring's psychedelic interactive traveling
bus say the puzzled looks began somewhere around Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the psychedelic bus. MindSpring's mini-media blitz through
the Valley and San Francisco was planned long before the Netcom
acquisition. The appearances and special events aren't about Netcom
or about connecting the two companies in consumers' minds.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring has been sponsoring ice skating events at San
Francisco's Embarcadero Center business/shopping complex since
early December. Thursday night the company pulled out all the stops
and sponsored ``singles skating night'' in conjunction with a local
radio station.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter with virtual computer games and a similarly
outfitted (and loud) monster truck were also there with balloon
banners and bright neon green MindSpring stickers for all skaters
to wear. The rink wasn't packed, but MindSpring banners were
everywhere _ even visible from the top floors of the nearby Hyatt
Regency hotel.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring says events like this aren't about signing up
subscribers, but creating a personal connection between potential
customers and the company.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of touchy-feely customer contact that is
supposed to go over well in California. But most of the skaters
were more interested in skating than MindSpring. Several skaters
got their kicks by telling MindSpring staffers what other (and
better) ISP they used, and no, not even the best customer service
in the world will make them switch. The MindSpring staff doesn't go
for the hard sell. They truly believe these misbegotten souls will
eventually see the light.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Netcom, already a venerable presence in the
Valley. One of the first companies to provide Web access to
consumers nationwide went public long before it became trendy.
</P>
<P>
   Its presence in the Valley consists of high-profile sponsorships
and community involvement. It is a charter sponsor of the pro
hockey team, the San Jose Sharks, and a major sponsor of the flashy
purple and orange San Jose Museum of Technology and Innovation.
Many of its 400,000 subscribers were online long before the
Internet was the rage du jour. In fact, Brewer was a Netcom
subscriber before the Internet became a major commercial enterprise
but canceled after a brief, frustrating experience in the early
'90s. He went on to become an excellent example of the adage, if
you want something done right, do it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of MindSpring's core values and beliefs now hang in
Netcom's offices, but otherwise it's business as usual. The
MindSpring team has been racking up frequent flier miles going to
San Jose to teach and to learn. Netcom employees say they are happy
to be part of MindSpring _ its stellar customer service will soon
be serving Netcom subscribers who've been moaning about lousy
service for years. Netcom wants the good MindSpring stuff, but not
at the price of its own identity and reputation in San Jose and
nationwide as an Internet pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Will MindSpring sponsor the beloved San Jose Sharks? Will it be
a good steward of the Netcom legacy? Nobody knows yet, but if the
fabulous California roadshow is any indication, watch for a
MindSpring banner at next season's Sharks games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
