<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Feb. 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Winds roaring down the east slopes of the Colorado Rockies
gusted to 100 mph or more across the northeast corner of the state
early Wednesday. The fierce winds were fed by momentum from fast
jet stream winds associated with a disturbance moving across the
upper Middle West. On Thursday, the jet stream disturbance will
arrive in the Northeast, paving the way for rain and snow across
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will develop during the day over much of New England as the
jet stream disturbance helps to spawn a surface low pressure system
along the northern Middle Atlantic Seaboard. Snow will be confined
to high elevations in the Adirondacks of upstate New York to the
Green Mountains of Vermont, with snow eventually spreading to the
White Mountains of New Hampshire and the Longfellow Mountains of
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night and early Friday, however, rain will change to
snow over much of interior New England as the jet stream
disturbance, which marks the center of a pool of cold air aloft,
moves east toward the coast. Meanwhile, the surface low will
rapidly deepen in the Gulf of Maine, and, in the process, sending a
stream of Atlantic moisture inland. The end result will be a swath
of moderate to locally heavy snow over parts of northern New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, showers will dampen western Oregon and Washington as
moist Pacific winds persist. Snow will fall in the Cascades.
Farther inland, snow will fall on west-facing slopes of the Rockies
in the wake of a cold front slicing across the Great Basin. Showers
will fall in some of the valleys.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Downslope Windstorm
</P>
<P>
   Fierce winds gusted to 119 mph at Wondervu, Colorado, marking
ground zero of a windstorm that lashed the northeast corner of the
state. Ferocious winds that careen down the Front Range are a
cold-season feature of the regional climate. When fast winds
blowing from the west-northwest near mountain summits rise up the
terrain, they sometimes, in roller coaster fashion, descend rapidly
down east slopes. Rapid descent is favored when a narrow swath of
speedy jet stream winds pass just north and east of a location, as
happened Wednesday near northeast Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
