<HEADER>
A0593 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AARP04-COX     02-03 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AARP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON BOOSTS MEDICARE, CRITICIZES GOP TAX PLAN
 &HT;    400&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Raising the bar for Congress, President Clinton
challenged Republicans on Wednesday to forgo tax cuts in order to
save the projected federal budget surplus to strengthen Medicare,
as well as Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the AARP (formerly the American Association of
Retired Persons) legislative council, Clinton criticized a plan
unveiled Tuesday by House Republicans to use $743 billion of the
projected $2.4 trillion surplus over the next decade for a 10
percent across-the-board income tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the GOP tax cut would benefit the wealthy while not
providing support for the financially troubled Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the latest in a rather long series of large and risky
tax proposals that we have heard over the years,'' Clinton said.
``If we had adopted even one of the large ones, we wouldn't have
the surplus we enjoy today. We cannot return to the old policies of
deficit and debt.''
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address last month and his budget
proposal Monday, Clinton outlined plans to use 62 percent of the
projected budget surplus over the next 15 years to shore up the
Social Security system by reducing the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed using 15 percent of the surplus to bolster the
flagging Medicare system, which is projected to run into a deficit
by 2008 unless changes are made.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech marked the latest rhetorical skirmish over how
to use the federal surplus. Last year, the president prevailed with
his call for using the surplus for Social Security over GOP efforts
to offer a tax cut. Wednesday, he raised the stakes to include
Medicare as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who hopes to invest the surplus, or to spend it on
other programs, or to spend it with a tax cut must first tell
America's families, 'What is your plan to preserve and strengthen
Medicare in the 21st century?' `` Clinton said. ``I
</P>
<P>
   was always taught ... that you may want to do a lot of things,
but you have to do first things first. To me, Social Security and
Medicare, with their looming financial challenges, are the first
things and we have to take care of them first.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Corry, AARP director of federal affairs, said that while
there is general agreement with Clinton's plan to use 62 percent of
the surplus for Social Security, ``he is now upping the ante on the
use of the other 38 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested that his plan, to use 12 percent of the budget
surplus _ after Social Security and Medicare _ to provide tax
credits for private investment accounts for retirement would be a
better way to provide tax relief to working families than the GOP
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Such relief would be targeted to help low-income families by
providing a higher federal match on voluntary investments in the
private accounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his plan to invest about $700 billion over 15 years
in Medicare should not be seen as a way of avoiding major reforms
in the federal health care program for the elderly and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Without any changes, Medicare's hospital trust fund will be
depleted by 2008. By shifting money from the surplus into the
program, Clinton would extend the fund's life to 2020.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan commission is expected to issue its recommendations
for reforming Medicare on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing those reforms, Clinton listed four guidelines he
wants included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Using the surplus to extend the life of the trust fund.
Without that money, he predicted benefits would have to be severely
curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   _ A modern, competitive system that ``maintains high-quality
care and top-notch service by drawing on the best private-sector
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A defined set a benefits for services that Medicare will cover
without excessive costs to the beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   _ A prescription drug benefit, which Medicare does not now
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested the drug benefit, which would cost more
initially, would ultimately save Medicare money by keeping people
healthier and reducing the use of hospital services.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
