<HEADER>
A0594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-BOOK04-COX     02-03 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-BOOK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BANTAM BOOKS TO PUBLISH GLENN MEMOIR
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John Glenn, America's resurrected space hero, has
signed a deal with Bantam Books to publish his memoir in the fall,
the publishing house announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, 77, recently returned from nine history-making days in
orbit aboard the space shuttle Discovery, a journey that made him
the oldest man ever in space. His late October flight marked a
dramatic return to glory for Glenn, who at the age of 40 was
crowned the original space pioneer for making America's first
orbital flight in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's deal with Bantam was struck for an undisclosed sum, but
it had been expected throughout last year as he trained for the
flight. Glenn signed with a New York literary agent shortly after
NASA agreed to let him join a shuttle mission as the test subject
of experiments on how weightlessness affects elderly humans.
</P>
<P>
   During the flight, Glenn kept a tape recorder near the
pillow-end of his bunk to remind him to make entries in his oral
diary about the experience. He also had kept it close by during the
nine months he spent training for the flight at the Johnson Space
Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to gaining renown as an astronaut, Glenn was a
decorated combat pilot who flew in World War II and Korea, and in
1957 set a record as pilot of the first transcontinental flight to
average supersonic speed from L.A. to New York.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bantam announcement, Glenn's book also will
deal heavily with his ``55-year partnership with his wife Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn retired after 24 years in the U.S. Senate representing
Ohio, and now is working on the creation of the John Glenn
Institute of Public Service and Public Policy at Ohio State
University. He also has been traveling around the world with his
six crewmates from the Discovery flight, providing briefings on the
shuttle flight to such groups as the European Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
   He's working with coauthor Nick Taylor on the still-untitled
John Glenn story.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got deadlines,'' joked Barb Burg, a spokeswoman for
Random House, Inc. which owns Bantam.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
