<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMSONOV LOOKS FOR WAYS TOP END SCORING SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's no question it's a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Samsonov hasn't scored a goal in 11 games since Jan. 15.
He hasn't had an assist since Jan. 21, a span of five games. And
hasn't compensated on defense, compiling a minus-10 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov, the NHL's rookie of the year last season, wants to do
something to get the Bruins and himself going. It's what the team
needs now. It's what he needs now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's been happening to me,'' said Samsonov, who has 15
goals and 35 points this season. ``We need some confidence. Just
one win. We come out there against Colorado (a 3-2 setback
Tuesday), but it just didn't happen. We got a lot of chances to
score, but we'll find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov is frustrated. ``I guess I'm getting my chances, but
the puck just isn't going in for me,'' he said. ``I'm getting three
or four shots per game, and it's not going in. If I keep on
working, if I keep working hard, good things are going to happen
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents aren't doing anything special to stop Samsonov. ``It's
the system,'' he said. ``Most teams are playing a trap, and it's
not a big scoring game or anything like that. You have to be
patient and wait for your chances. You can't really do anything
about it. You've just got to continue to work hard and stick to the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns took Samsonov off the first line with Jason
Allison and Dmitri Khristich against Colorado, replacing him with
Steve Heinze. Samsonov, who was with the top unit on power plays,
said he understood completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing very well together, so we needed some changes,
and obviously, it worked out well, with Jason scoring two goals,''
he said. ``I was happy for Jason. Since that line was getting good
chances, one of the goals on a power play, things got back to
normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov feels he's shooting the puck enough, something just
about everyone has stressed to him since his NHL first game. ``I
have been shooting more; I'm trying to do that,'' he said. ``But if
I see someone open, I'm going to pass to him because he has a
better opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The goals and points seemed to come easily in the early part of
the season. Samsonov's longest drought before the All-Star Game was
four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying earlier this season that a lot of those goals
were lucky goals, lucky bounces,'' he said. ``I guess it's how fast
you're going to get out of the slump. The only thing that you can
do is try for more simple plays, where you don't have to make a
great play. You've got to put the puck on the net and go hard to
the net, looking for the bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   His defense is another source of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I can't be too happy with that,'' Samsonov said.
``When you're on the ice, the puck goes into the net. Sometimes
it's frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, though. At minus-10, it wouldn't bother me as much
if the team were winning games. You start thinking you might be the
problem because your team isn't playing well. We've got to start
winning games. We've got to concentrate on our game.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Samsonov knows, means scoring more goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
