A0599 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MITCH-RELIEF04-COX     02-03 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-RELIEF04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS INTRODUCE BILL TO AID HURRICANE MITCH VICTIMS
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A plan to spend more than $800 million to speed the
economic recovery of hurricane-devastated countries in Central
America and the Caribbean was introduced in the Senate on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga. was joined by Sens. Bob Graham,
D-Fla., Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, and Mary Landrieu, D-La., to introduce
the Central American and Caribbean Relief Act of 1999, which would
enhance trade and provide emergency U.S. assistance and financial
aid to Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Last October and early November, Hurricanes Georges and Mitch
caused extensive damage in the Dominican Republic, Nicaragua,
Honduras and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic stability of the Western Hemisphere depends upon
the United States' ability and willingness to help its neighbors,''
said DeWine, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee's
subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation includes the expansion of the Caribbean
Basin Initiative (CBI), originally passed by Congress in 1983,
which would give Caribbean Basin nations the same trade benefits
afforded to Mexico in the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBI expansion is a step forward,'' Graham said. ``Without it,
the region's manufacturing base, its main source of economic
activity in the wake of Hurricane Mitch, will not have the
incentives it needs to grow during this period of reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also calls for U.S. assistance to Central America.
It would provide $16 million for debt forgiveness to Honduras _ 67
percent of its debt to the United States _ $557 million in
humanitarian aid, and $150 million to replenish money spent by the
Pentagon to offer emergency assistance after the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would spend $70 million to expand the New Horizons
Program, a project that provides health care and builds roads and
schools through the U.S. military. This legislation also would
earmark $1 million to assist U.S. businesses in the region and
develop low-income housing.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also proposed assistance of $25 million for the
Central American Emergency Trust Fund, to be applied to the
countries' international debts.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is expected to announce its plans for
relief to Central America next week. Graham said he expects to see
similarities between the two proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
