<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZMAGS04-COX     02-03 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Problems relegate Asia to back seat
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not too long ago, everybody thought the 21st century
belonged to Asia, given the rise of Japan, China and Southeast
Asia. Not any more, Business Week (Feb. 8) suggests in its cover
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the U.S. and Europe are steadily converging to form a new
Atlantic economy _ with vast impact on global growth and
business,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   If Asia's economic problems are taking that part of the world
out of the race, the rise of the Atlantic economy is being driven
by a combination of the euro (the new European common currency),
deregulation, pension investing, a software and telecom boom, and
new styles of business management. ``Europe is in fact looking more
and more like America's twin,'' says Business Week. ``The two blocs
are bursting with market opportunities, with or without Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta in the spotlight
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta pops up more than usual in the latest batch of
national business magazines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta-based Miller Industries, North America's largest maker
of wreckers and other towing equipment, makes this year's list of
top stock picks assembled for Worth (February).
</P>
<P>
   Miller Industries gets high praise for entering the towing
business in addition to making tow trucks, a move ``to create the
FedEx of towing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Inc. (February) spotlights suburban Chamblee as ``the promised
land for Latino, African and Asian immigrants'' and home of some
100 immigrant-owned businesses just seven years after projecting an
image of ``xenophobia and economic backwardness.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Fast Company (February/ March) says Atlanta-based MindSpring
Enterprises proves that ``you can forget everything you thought you
knew about Internet companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's one that's growing responsibly, serving customers well
_ and making money ... it's worth $1.5 billion,'' the magazine
says.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Oil prices have slipped to levels not seen in more than a
decade _ $11 per barrel in 1998. But Ticker (February) says the
time may be right to buy energy stocks _ providing investors
``don't expect big gains anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Financial planning is important for everybody, but especially
for women, says Working-
</P>
<P>
   Mother (March). That's because ``about half of all women who are
over 65 are widows and nearly 52 percent of all marriages end in
divorce,'' making it ``imperative that women become financially
savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ America is on the brink of a trade war with Europe over
bananas. That may be unusual, but in fact it's just one of the
signs that protectionist pressure is rising in the United States,
with ``little hint of the determined political leadership needed to
resist it,'' says The Economist (Feb. 5).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
