<SLUG> BC-KINGSBURY-SMITH-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH KINGSBURY-SMITH, PULITZER PRIZE WINNER, DEAD AT 90 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Joseph Kingsbury-Smith, a Pulitzer-prize winning
journalist and former national editor of the Hearst Newspapers,
died Wednesday at his home in suburban Virginia. He was 90 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   During more than 60 years of service with The Hearst
Corporation, Mr. Kingsbury-Smith held a variety of posts, including
publisher of the New York Journal-American and chief foreign
correspondent for the Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   He retired as a vice president and director of The Hearst
Corporation. He also was a former trustee of the estate of William
Randolph Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   As a journalist, Mr. Kingsbury-Smith interviewed most of the
contemporary world's great leaders and was widely acclaimed for his
achievements in the field of diplomacy. His exchange of
correspondence with Soviet Premier Joseph Stalin in 1949, which
became headline news around the world, was widely acknowledged to
have been a factor in the lifting of the Berlin Blockade.
</P>
<P>
   The exclusive stories of this exchange won him the George Polk
Memorial Award for Outstanding Journalism, the National Headliners
Club Award for Exclusive Foreign Correspondence, the Sigma Delta
Chi Award and, for a second time, the George R. Holmes Memorial
Award.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kingsbury-Smith won the 1956 Pulitzer prize for
Distinguished Reporting of International Affairs as a member of a
three-man team that included William Randolph Hearst Jr. and Frank
Conniff and which conducted a series of interviews in 1955 with
Nikita Khrushchev and other top Soviet leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Frank A. Bennack Jr., president and chief executive officer of
The Hearst Corporation, said: ``Joe's passing is a great loss to
the international journalistic community as well as to The Hearst
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the most distinguished individuals in our field
during the 20th century. He was, however, unbelievably modest when
it came to his many accomplishments; when he was inducted into the
Hall of Fame of the Society of Professional Journalists in 1992,
his speech attributed most of his achievements to chance. He will
be greatly missed.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of New York City, Mr. Kingsbury-Smith attended public
and private schools in New York and later the University of London.
In 1924 at age 16, he was hired as a copy boy by Hearst's
International News Service (INS). Soon after, the New York World
asked him to write a copy boy's impression of the 1924 Democratic
National Convention at Madison Square Garden. The newspaper
published the story on page 1.
</P>
<P>
   In 1927, Mr. Kingsbury-Smith was assigned to the INS bureau in
London. He was transferred to the Washington bureau in 1931 and
later became chief INS diplomatic correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, he was named INS vice president and general manager.
Three years later, when INS and United Press consolidated to form
United Press International (UPI), he assumed the temporary post of
UPI vice president and associate general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kingsbury-Smith later returned to general management duties
with The Hearst Corporation before becoming publisher of the New
York Journal-American in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, he was appointed European director of The Hearst
Corporation and chief foreign writer for the Hearst Newspapers,
with headquarters in Paris and later in Rome. He was named national
editor of the Hearst Newspapers in 1976 and later was appointed
director of corporate activities in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kingsbury-Smith was a Knight of Malta and a member of the
Brook Club of New York and the Metropolitan Club of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Eileen; two daughters, Eileen
Pulling and Diane Keesee; two grandchildren, Eric Odelfelt and
Helen Youngman; and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
