<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PRISONERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI PRESIDENT COMMUTES SENTENCES FOR JEWS, ANGERING
PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ President Ezer Weizman of Israel has commuted the
sentences of five Jews serving long prison terms for murder or
attempted murder of Arabs, an aide to Weizman announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The president, whose post is ceremonial, signed recommendations
submitted by Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, a political ally of
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The move drew harsh criticism from Palestinian officials and
lawmakers from the Israeli opposition, who accused the government
of a double standard.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has refused to release Arab prisoners ``with blood on
their hands'' as part of interim peace accords with the
Palestinians. He has routinely accused the Palestinian Authority of
freeing Arab terrorists through a ``revolving door'' in its
prisons, and this week he asserted that 21 Muslim militants were
recently released.
</P>
<P>
   To deflect accusations of leniency toward Jewish killers,
Hanegbi and an aide to Weizman portrayed the reduction of their
sentences as a demonstration of even-handedness after previous
Israeli releases of Arab convicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have released thousands'' of Palestinian prisoners under
the peace accords, Hanegbi said, ``and I thought that a similar
custom should be followed when it comes to Jewish prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   Aryeh Shumer, an aide to Weizman, said the president had
previously commuted the sentences of five Israeli Arabs convicted
of killing suspected informers or planting bombs. One was freed two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Jewish and Arab prisoners had expressed regret for
their actions, and the reduction of their sentences ``should be
received in the spirit of general reconciliation'' that should
accompany peace efforts, Shumer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ahmad Abdel Rahman, the secretary-general of the Palestinian
Cabinet, called the move a provocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel should have released those mentioned in the peace
accords instead of freeing Jews who killed Palestinians in cold
blood,'' he told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Asfour, a senior Palestinian negotiator, said, ``This
shows the true face of this government, which protects terrorists
and murderers.''
</P>
<P>
   One Jew whose sentence was reduced is Ami Popper, who killed
seven Palestinians in 1990 when he sprayed gunfire at a group of
laborers in the Israeli town of Rishon Letzion. Popper was given
seven life sentences, and his term has now been commuted to 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   Another Jewish prisoner, Yoram Skolnick, killed a
grenade-carrying Palestinian in 1993 after he had been caught,
partly stripped and tied up near the West Bank settlement of Susia.
Skolnick was given a life sentence for the execution-style slaying,
but the term was later reduced to 15 years. It has now been cut to
11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nehemia Mashbaum was convicted as a teen-ager of throwing a
grenade in an Arab market in Jerusalem's Old City that killed an
elderly Palestinian in 1992. His sentence, previously cut from 15
to 12 years, was reduced to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Two more prisoners, Yehoyada and Eitan Kahalani, who were
sentenced to 12 years each for trying to kill a Palestinian, had
four years taken off their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television reports said the sentences of the Israeli
Arab convicts were reduced far less, to an average of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The early release of the Jewish killers ``violates the basic
principle, touted so proudly by this government, that terrorists
with blood on their hands must not be freed,'' said Yossi Sarid, a
lawmaker from the leftist Meretz Party. ``Does a murderer deserve
to be freed just because he is a Jew?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
