<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER DIGITAL CAMERA BREAKS THE PIXEL BARRIER  
 IN THE HOME OR OUT OF IT, WOMEN HAVE A NEW WEB SITE  
TECHNOLOGY FOR BLIND USERS EVEN READS THE INTERNET ADS  
HELP WITH MATH HOMEWORK? A SEARCH ENGINE CAN HELP  
WEB SURFERS STARTING TO LOOK LIKE JUST ABOUT EVERYONE ELSE  
NOTEBOOK WITH CONSUMER FEEL WILL BE AIMED AT COMPANIES  
FREE E-MAIL SITE CUTS BACK ON SERVICES FOR SOME USERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumer Digital Camera Breaks the Pixel Barrier  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Breaking another barrier for consumer digital cameras, Fuji
Photo Film USA on Wednesday introduced the first pocket-size camera
that captures more than two million picture elements, or two
megapixels, per image. The Fuji MX-2700 will cost ``well under
$1,000'' when it becomes available in April or May, a Fuji
spokesman said, and will have a maximum resolution of 1,800 pixels
by 1,200 pixels. Until now, only professional digital cameras
costing thousands of dollars each had similar resolution. Other
digital camera makers are expected to introduce two-megapixel
cameras later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Higher resolution improves the picture quality, and Fuji asserts
that its MX-2700 rivals traditional film cameras in color and
sharpness. Higher resolution also allows consumers to print bigger
enlargements of their digital images with relatively inexpensive
ink-jet color printers and photographic paper. Fuji says that
glossy color prints as large as 8 by 10 inches are now possible and
that 4 by 6 prints are ``stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Pepper, editor and publisher of the newsletter Digital Focus
(www.digfocus.com), said that while crossing the two-megapixel
threshold was significant for consumer cameras, it also means a
leap up in image storage requirements because file sizes will be
bigger. The MX-2700 will come with an 8-megabyte Smart Media card,
the Fuji spokesman said, capable of holding eight images at the
highest resolution and more than 100 at the lowest. An optional 32
MB version of the storage card will be available later this year.
Many other digital cameras use a rival storage system called
Compact Flash, which has a higher maximum capacity, 80 MB.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER H. LEWIS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Home or Out of It, Women Have a New Web Site
</P>
<P>
   If Cosmopolitan and Ms. magazine came together under one roof,
it might be seen as culture clash. But the operators of two
disparate Web sites for women recently announced a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com is a Web site (www.women.com) &UR;  &LR; that focuses on issues
facing professional women, entrepreneurs and mothers who both drive
the children to soccer practice and coach the team. Homearts.com,
owned by the Hearst Corp., has a softer editorial side, offering
features like how to plan a wedding around one's astrological needs
(www.homearts.com).
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. recently purchased a 50-percent stake in
Women.com. As part of the deal, Hearst is giving Women.com control
over Homearts.com. The idea behind the merged company, called
Women.com Networks, is to create a company whose combined Web sites
will be a formidable force in attracting women and advertisers who
want to cater to them. The company points to figures from Media
Metrix, a market research company, showing that the two Web sites
will reach a combined audience larger than that of any other single
women's site.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Meier, senior vice president of Women.com, based in San
Mateo, Calif., said the newly merged sites would have no trouble
co-existing. ``Woman have many different parts of themselves,'' she
said. ``They can have their cake and make it, too.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Technology for Blind Users Even Reads the Internet Ads
</P>
<P>
   This week IBM started selling technology that allows blind users
to hear the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Called Home Page Reader, the software, which costs $149, uses a
speech synthesizer not just to read the text on a given Web page
but also to describe the graphics and even advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Other screen readers are capable of reading Web-page text. But
Paul Luther, a manager with IBM's special-needs unit, said the Home
Page Reader was designed specifically with the Web in mind and
tailored to reading pages built in HTML.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a picture of a person on bicycle, the Home Page
Reader will say, `There's a picture of a person on a bicycle,''' he
said. ``Then the blind user can say, `I'm not interested in this,'
and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   (And when there's a banner advertisement, it will probably say:
``Loading, loading, still loading. Go take a nap; I'll call you in
20 minutes.'')
</P>
<P>
   Help With Math Homework? A Search Engine Can Help
</P>
<P>
   A new search engine is tailored to help students from
kindergarten through high school do their homework. The site,
www.searchopolis.com, includes databases of sites in various
school-related categories, like history, math, science and social
studies.
</P>
<P>
   The site, created by two Internet content developers, Look
Smart, of San Francisco, and N2H2, of Seattle, also includes a
reward for homework well done: television listings.
</P>
<P>
   Web Surfers Starting to Look Like Just About Everyone Else
</P>
<P>
   The universe of Web users might need a group therapy session to
come to terms with the latest assessment of their state:
collectively, they have grown average.
</P>
<P>
   That is the essence of a new survey from the Pew Research Center
for the People and the Press, based in Washington. The study found
that the demographics of Web surfers, and their interests, had
evolved strikingly in the last two years and now more closely
resembled those of the general public.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the single most-sought-after news item on the Net
is the weather; today, 64 percent of users log on to learn about
the weather, up from 46 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center, said the
changes reflected the changing demographics of the Web. ``The ways
the Internet is being used are more ordinary,'' he said. ``The
kinds of people who are using it are more typical and ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Notebook With Consumer Feel Will Be Aimed at Companies
</P>
<P>
   After years of making industrial-strength notebook computers
designed for corporate use, the Hewlett Packard Co. this week
announced its first laptop with a true consumer feel. The trouble
is that it won't be intended for consumers. The low-end of the HP
Omnibook XE includes a 266-megahertz Intel Pentium II processor, a
4.1-gigabyte hard drive and 32 megabytes of RAM. It's not a bad
package for $1,499, the expected retail price.
</P>
<P>
   But Hewlett Packard won't initially be selling it in any
consumer retail stores. Rather, the company, which markets itself
as a maker of laptops for use in large internal networks and
corporations, will continue to sell it through existing corporate
channels and on the Web. The company hopes to position the laptop
as a freestanding notebook for small- and medium-size businesses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Free e-mail site cuts back on services for some users
</P>
<P>
   Juno, a New York company that pioneered the concept of free
e-mail, recently announced that thousands of its users would be
able to check their e-mail only once a day. The reason, the company
said, is that those users live in regions of the country where
telecommunications costs are more expensive. Users affected by the
change who still want to check e-mail more often must pay $2.95 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ardai, the company's president, said that ``fewer than 1
percent'' of the company's 6.5 million subscribers were affected.
But he was less than reassuring when asked whether he might expand
the geographic area falling under the once-a-day for checking
e-mail. ``I have no opinion about that,'' he said. While the Juno
service is free, users view banner advertisements that appear at
the top of messages. The idea of advertising-supported e-mail, and
the related concept of advertising-supported Internet access, have
attracted many entrepreneurs. But analysts contend that the
business model presents difficulties because millions must be spent
on marketing and technology to build a subscriber base to attract
ads.
</P>
<P>
   Ardai wrote to the subscribers affected by the latest Juno
limitation and suggested his motive was not profits, but keeping
the service widely available. He asked those subscribers who could
afford it to pay $2.95 a month to upgrade their service so they
would be helping to subsidize the accounts of members who cannot
afford service. ``You will be helping us to move closer to this
important goal,'' he wrote, of providing ``free e-mail services to
all Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
