<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      02-03 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PREPARES FOR BATTLE OVER LEWINSKY TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican Senate braced for a struggle
Thursday over whether to have former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky testify at the impeachment trial of President Clinton _ in
person or on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The White House tried to forestall personal testimony by the
25-year-old former presidential paramour by embracing admission of
Lewinsky's entire videotaped testimony rather than having House
prosecutors present excerpts to the 100 senators.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart also sought to allay
Republican concerns that Clinton might claim vindication if the
Senate fell short of the two-thirds majority needed to convict and
remove the chief executive from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now declare in a post-impeachment era, this is a gloat-free
zone,'' Lockhart said. Clinton is accused of perjury and
obstruction of justice in trying to conceal his affair with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Senate prepared to vote Thursday on
the request by House prosecutors to admit videotaped testimony from
Lewinsky, presidential confidant Vernon Jordan and White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans theoretically have enough votes to admit witnesses'
testimony on videotape or in person because the party holds 55 of
the Senate's 100 seats. A majority of 51 votes is all that would be
needed to admit videotaped testimony or live witnesses in the first
presidential impeachment trial since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   But key Republican senators said the outcome was too close to
call on the question of admitting the taped statements.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, said: ``It's too early to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch of Utah, and Sens.
Larry E. Craig of Idaho and Olympia Snowe of Maine echoed the
caution, saying they couldn't predict the vote.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., said the Senate would vote Friday on whether to
invite one or more of the three witnesses to testify before the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But again, Republican senators voiced doubts about actually
calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he favored calling witnesses, but added: ``I
seriously doubt that there will be the votes to have any live
witnesses in this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowe said she could not ``personally foresee circumstances
under which we would call Monica Lewinsky'' to the floor of the
Senate to provide testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said she had learned so
``few new things'' from viewing videotapes of Lewinsky and Jordan
that ``I would not say that we need to have them on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard C. Shelby, R-Ala., a former Democrat, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of the same, nothing explosive, no dynamite,''
Shelby said.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors completed three days of videotaped depositions
Wednesday, questioning Blumenthal on allegations that Clinton
coached his subordinate in a scheme to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, leader of the
13-member prosecution team seeking the conviction and removal of
Clinton, said prosecutors ``always prefer live witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be open to questions from senators (and)
cross-examination in a setting conducive to truth telling,'' said
Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., who questioned Blumenthal, said the
prosecutors had a ``constitutional duty'' to make a case before the
Senate with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., who questioned Jordan on Tuesday,
said senators deserve to have the witnesses present for
questioning. Hutchinson, a former federal prosecutor during the
Reagan presidency, said ``live testimony's better than video and
video is better than written statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, reversing iron-clad White House opposition to
testimony on the floor of the Senate, announced that the
president's team could accept the presentation of videotaped
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said ``there's no need to release these videotapes,''
but added: ``If the Senate majority decides that there is some
compelling reason that they have to release them, this shouldn't be
done in snippets.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., echoed the White
House position. ``We should take it all or we should not take any
of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's spokesman said if the Senate voted to admit videotaped
testimony, he expected the entire depositions to be admitted as
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any groundswell to only put out snippets,''
Czwartacki said.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News/New York Times survey released Wednesday showed that
more than two-thirds of the people questioned said the Senate does
not need to call witnesses to help senators decide on the two
articles of impeachment adopted by the House on Dec. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six percent disapproved of the way the Senate was handling
the trial; 37 percent approved.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said the Republicans would pay a political price if they
agreed to summon witnesses. ``Live witnesses will do nothing but
perpetuate a trial that now nobody wants,'' Daschle said. ``The
more the Republicans demand an extension, the more it becomes a
Republican trial.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The jockeying over witnesses took place amid equally frenetic
maneuvering over a Republican-backed proposal for the Senate to
endorse a so-called ``finding of fact'' that would declare Clinton
guilty of perjury and obstruction of justice without taking the
next step of removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is a middle-ground approach. The Constitution
requires the Senate to come up with a two-thirds vote, or 67
senators, to vote for conviction and removal of a president.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of votes last week showed that the White House has
at least 44 Democrats _ 10 more than the 34 required _ to block any
Senate effort to remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's spokesman said the Senate would debate various proposals
over a possible statement of wrongdoing next week before a final
vote on the two articles of impeachment on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., rejected the
``convict-but-don't-evict'' scenario as an end run around the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Offering senators a ``way to convict the president without
having to accept responsibility for removing him from office would,
in effect, bastardize the impeachment process,'' Byrd said in an
opinion piece published Wednesday in the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   But the approach was finding favor among some Republicans.
Craig, the No. 4 Republican in the Senate leadership, said a
finding of fact met the requirements of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constitution does not say we can not make expressions of
the finding of the court,'' Craig said, dismissing a
post-impeachment vote on censure ``a wet noodle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., said a finding of fact was ``certainly
worth discussing,'' adding: ``It's not a verdict, not a
condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, in a bid to shift the Senate focus to an effort to
censure the president, set up a task force to develop a censure
resolution. Daschle said he hoped Sens. Dianne Feinstein of
California and Patrick Moynihan of New York could work out a
censure resolution with the Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
