<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA, PAKISTAN LEADERS PLAN NEW ROUTE TO PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee of India
accepted a warmly worded invitation Wednesday from Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan to ride the first bus to roll from India
to Pakistan in half a century and to search for a breakthrough to
peace between the hostile nations.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the two leaders, probably in a month, would be
their third since India and Pakistan conducted underground nuclear
tests in May. The idea for the Delhi-Lahore bus service emerged at
a meeting in September when they were in New York for a U.N.
session. In recent months the leaders have developed a closer
rapport during regular telephone conversations, Sharif and Indian
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif invited Vajpayee, whom he described as ``an extremely
decent man'' in an interview with Shekhar Gupta, editor in chief of
The Indian Express, an English-language daily here, which was
published Wednesday. By Wednesday afternoon the Indian prime
minister had accepted.
</P>
<P>
   In a transcript of the interview provided by Gupta, an effusive
Sharif promised that Vajpayee, arriving on the luxurious
air-conditioned bus that India is outfitting , would be received
with a hospitality ``so great that people will not forget it for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will even be happy to go back with him,'' Sharif added. ``We
will solve 50 percent of our problems, make 50 percent progress on
all issues, on our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, who was in Lucknow Wednesday, said, ``I would like to
have a bus ride to Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, a spokesman for the External Affairs Ministry, K.C.
Singh, said, ``His visit will be one more manifestation of India's
abiding desire to build peaceful, friendly and cooperative
relations with Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee has recently gone out of his way to ensure that the
first cricket series between India and Pakistan in a decade was
peaceful. He publicly accused Hindu militants who had dug up a
cricket field in New Delhi of being cowards, though they are active
in the Shiv Sena, a party that his Bharatiya Janata Party is in a
coalition with in the state of Maharashtra.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee also sent the home minister to press the Shiv Sena
chief to withdraw his threats to disrupt the games. The series
ended peacefully on Sunday, with a victory for Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Sharif proposed that the countries go beyond
setting up bus service and competing in sports to discuss with ``an
open mind'' the core issue that has poisoned their relations since
they became independent in 1947, their rival claims to Kashmir. He
also said the countries should talk directly about nuclear weapons,
missiles and conventional forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian and Pakistani foreign secretaries have been holding
talks since October on peace and security problems. But they have
generally repeated their unyielding positions, including on
Kashmir. Some experts fear that the region could become a nuclear
flash point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say, Vajpayee Sahib, let's solve the Kashmir
problem, let's solve the other problems, so that we can also move
on like the rest of the world,'' Sharif said. ``See, there are such
great prospects for our cooperation in business and investment. You
are busy making weapons, and so are we, because we are competing
against India. Some rivalry this is!''
</P>
<P>
   Sharif said he believed that the people of Pakistan were ready
to normalize relations with India. Both nations are scarred by the
violent division of the subcontinent in 1947 into predominantly
Hindu India and majority Muslim Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years have already gone by,'' Sharif said. ``How many
more decades are we going to waste? Are we going to waste all our
resources in the arms race?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been wishing for a long time to come to India and see
the Red Fort, Agra or those parts of Delhi that represent its rich
culture and history,'' he said. ``Similarly, I believe that the
people of India are fervently hoping to visit Pakistan, see Lahore
or visit the houses and villages they have left behind. They don't
get a visa, nor do our people. Nobody comes, nobody goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
