<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFE NOT WORTH LIVING IS WORTH SHARING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As Johnny Muhammad tells me about his
childhood, I am thinking I know this story, know the loneliness in
his words. It's like crying under a driving rain. No one can see
the tears, but they're there.
</P>
<P>
   He is a little boy, he recalls, no more than 8 or 9. But as
always, the adult world beckons him to be a man. He washes the
dishes, makes sure his little sister's hair gets combed and the
homework gets done.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, to help make ends meet, there is an odd job for him
to do. And if he manages to go to school at all, learning is out of
the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't focus on studying, because I was focused on making
sure the door was locked,'' he says. ``Did I make sure I locked the
front door?''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, 33, repeats his story often these days for seventh-
and eighth-grade students at Dunbar Middle School in Fort Worth. He
hopes he can have a positive effect on kids whose lives have not
been much different from his.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, one of four behavior-modification instructors in the
Fort Worth school district, works with students at risk of being
suspended or expelled because of discipline problems. Under the
program, which began this school year, members of the local
nonprofit African-American mentoring group Umoja offer guidance,
anti-drug messages and other instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad shares his story so students will know that they, too,
can overcome even the worst neglect, the worst odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at them and I see me,'' he says. ``I came from the same
kind of environment _ trying to make money to help out. I want them
to know that if Mr. Muhammad can get through it, they can, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He sits now just inside the door of the school auditorium. He is
a survivor who has gone from desperation to redemption, from
homeless crack addict to custodian to teacher. He has been clean
for five years.
</P>
<P>
   It would not have been possible, he says, had it not been for
the teachings of the Honorable Elijah Muhammad and Minister Louis
Farrakhan, teachings that a friend shared with him.
</P>
<P>
   The most important teaching, he says, is to love yourself. He
also says it's the one he tries hardest to impart to his students
who ``don't just have low self-esteem. They have no self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time most students meet Muhammad _ if they are lucky
enough to meet him _ abuse and neglect have taken their toll and
have resulted in academic failure, mischievous behavior, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, he gets discouraged. He has four or five hours a day
to reach students, and it often seems too little. But while he has
them, he tries to get the students to see why they are worth
loving, to show them that one mistake doesn't define who they are.
</P>
<P>
   What is troubling to him is that he knows his story may not make
a difference. The reservoir of bitterness can be a powerful one,
even deadly; the community's apathy can be too entrenched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have men tell me all the time `Brother Johnny, you're
getting too close,' '' he says. `` `Brother, you're just wasting
your time. That's a lost cause. The only way they're going to get
it right is when Jesus returns.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I say, `Well, don't you have Jesus in you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad maintains that whether one believes in the teachings of
Jesus or in those of some other God, it is time for adults to put
aside religious differences, to put aside titles and to work
together to make a difference in the lives of children.
</P>
<P>
   He says he feels blessed to be able to share his story, to do
his part.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
