<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0642 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT     02-03 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE PHANTOM ALLIANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: boldfaced words should be italicized) 
(bl) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ A specter is haunting the Middle East _ the
specter of a Phantom Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, Israel and the United States firmly deny its existence.
The Turks assure fellow Muslim nations that its new military and
economic ties to the Israelis don't threaten them. The Americans
say the U.S. tilt toward Turkey should be of no concern to Arab
monarchs. The Israelis say: Alliance? What alliance? No one of the
three is committed to go to war if another is attacked.
</P>
<P>
   The more vociferous the denials, the more other nations become
convinced that the Phantom Alliance is now a Middle Eastern fact of
life. And they're right.
</P>
<P>
   Turks, unfairly kept out of the European Union by Germany and
Greece, see America as making the world go round and Israelis as a
key to American support.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis need a powerful friend in the Muslim world and the
large Turkish land mass over which to train their air force.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans need Turkey as a base to strike Iraq, and
recognize that keeping sanctions on Saddam Hussein also hurts the
Turks.
</P>
<P>
   Now follow the three-way backscratching. The Turks sell textiles
and other commodities duty-free to Israel, which adds its labor to
the product and sells it to the United States duty-free. This
boosts the Turkish economy, which hires Israeli companies to
construct power plants and develop irrigation projects. Meanwhile,
the United States leans on oil companies to build a pipeline from
the Caspian Sea through Turkey rather than Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis side with the Turks against the Greeks on Cyprus. A
couple of Israelis were just jailed by the Greeks for snooping
where Russian S-300 SAMs aimed at the Turks were scheduled to be
installed. The United States, not wanting to block a Russian sale,
got the Greeks to put the weapons on Crete rather than Cyprus, and
to reduce charges against the Israelis from espionage to
``possessing scanning equipment without a license.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel urges the United States to sell Turkey our Apache
helicopters, to use in the battle against the ``bad'' Kurds seeking
to break off a piece of Turkey. Meanwhile, U.S. and Israeli
intelligence and diplomats help track down the Turks' most wanted
Kurd, Abdullah Ocalan, forced out of Damascus by a threat by Turkey
to invade Syria and now seeking refuge everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Turks quietly help the United States support the
``good'' Kurds in northern Iraq who may cause Saddam trouble,
despite Turkish worries about autonomous regions becoming
independent Kurdistan. And we need Turkey to lead the Turkic
peoples of Southwest Asia away from fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   But never say ``the allies.'' It's just the Three Musketeers
marching along together, sometimes all for one and occasionally one
for all.
</P>
<P>
   Others want to join the informal club. These range from Muslim
separatists in Chechnya to a much more significant player _ Egypt _
of late stridently anti-Israel. President Hosni Mubarak visited
Turkey three times in the past two months. He apparently sees his
economic lifeline from the U.S. endangered by the Phantom Alliance
and may want the largest Arab nation to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan seemed to be in, but King Hussein's firing of his brother
as successor throws that into doubt. If Palestinians seize his
Hashemite throne, Jordan could line up with a grouping of enemies
of enemies.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, when almost any  &UR; entente &LR;  becomes  &UR; cordiale &LR; , it
invites a counter-grouping. Although Russia is temporarily impotent
and the Saudis permanently feckless, Iran, Iraq, Syria and its
captive, Lebanon, and the emerging Palestinian state may be
strange-bedfellowing. We can hope that Greek-Americans can prevail
on Athens to avoid such an unpromising alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean that any war will immediately spread through the
region? No; this is not NATO vs. the Warsaw Pact. In a local fight,
there would be much holding of coats.
</P>
<P>
   But the untreatied association is good for the three democracies
of Turkey, Israel and America. People in Istanbul remind me that in
the year 1492, when Ferdinand and Isabella cruelly banished all
Jews from Spain, the Ottoman Empire's Sultan Beyazid II welcomed
the refugee Israelites to what is now Turkey. Another event of the
same year paved the way for what has become the Phantom Alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
