<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-microsoft0204-cox     02-03 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-microsoft0204-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT FACES FRESH CREDIBILITY GAP
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government sought to poke a hole in the
credibility of Microsoft Corp. Wednesday by showing in court that
the software giant used a flawed videotape to mount its antitrust
defense.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in as many days that Microsoft was unable
to drive home its charge that the government's prototype program
for separating Windows 98 from its built-in Internet Explorer
browser broke the operating system. The issue is important because
if the government can show that Microsoft tied the browser to
Windows as a marketing move to harm rival Netscape Communications
Corp., the judge in the case _ after it's proven such a solution is
technically feasible _ could order the company to ship Internet
Explorer as a separate application.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's four-minute tape purported to show that the removal
program, devised by Princeton professor Edward Felten, caused
Windows to behave as if it had fallen victim to a digital lobotomy.
</P>
<P>
   But that effort broke down when Microsoft Senior Vice President
James Allchin was forced to admit under cross-examination on the
witness stand that the demo was taped on multiple computers,
running various applications, rather than, as originally claimed
simply on a virgin machine that had been simply ``Feltenized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly has not been a good demonstration,'' Allchin
allowed, offering to bring his own laptop to court Thursday in
another bid to prove that, contrary to the government's claim in
the antitrust case, Windows and its browsing tool are inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   Such a live demo would violate court rules. But the episode
clearly exasperated U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson who
told Allchin: ``It certainly casts doubt on the reliability _ the
entire reliability _ of your video demonstration.''
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was an agreement, reached at a hastily convened bench
conference, that Microsoft would try once more Wednesday night to
test its Felten-destruction thesis and show the results in the
courtroom on a new video Thursday. Both Allchin and a host of
government experts were to be present at Microsoft's Pennsylvania
Avenue law offices to referee the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go about it the right way and get to the bottom of
this,'' promised Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Allchin said earlier discrepancies in the
video, uncovered Tuesday by David Boies, the government's lead
lawyer, arose from inadvertently filming a computer that had once
had the Prodigy Internet service on it.
</P>
<P>
   The original Microsoft tape sought to show how, even after the
Felten program had run, users could still get out to the Internet
via the Windows help utility system, as well as through the
remaining vestigial stub of the browser, which ran far more slowly
than the full-fledged product.
</P>
<P>
   But the demo flopped because instead of the title ``Windows
98,'' which appears at the top of the Felten version of Windows,
were the words: ``Internet Explorer.'' David Boies seized on the
shift, asking Allchin how he could claim the Felten program made
Windows run more slowly when the screen suggested it wasn't even
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I'm seeing here,'' Allchin replied, ``they filmed
the wrong system.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, the three technicians who performed the lab
tests had arrived here on a commercial flight from Seattle with the
computer they used for their tests. Overnight, they showed Allchin
how they had installed and then uninstalled a copy of the Prodigy
Internet service. After they removed Prodigy, the title bar that
once read ``Windows 98'' again read ``Internet Explorer.''
</P>
<P>
   This patch job held for a few hours until Boies blew his
multiple-machine hole in Microsoft's defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence that they have put forth to the court is simply
unreliable,'' Boies said on the courthouse plaza. ``This is not
public relations. This is not sales _ you've got to come up with
something that is accurate and something that someone can be
cross-examined on.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
