</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH FIND $2.9 MILLION IN ASSETS SEIZED DURING THE HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A government-appointed panel examining the seizure of
assets from Jews in France during World War II has reported finding
$2.9 million taken from deportees to Nazi death camps that was
never claimed and remains in a government bank.
</P>
<P>
   In the second interim report since it was set up in 1997, the
nine-member panel, headed by the prominent banker and Resistance
veteran Jean Matteoli, recommended on Tuesday that if the money
remains unclaimed, it should go to a government fund to expand the
Memorial to the Unknown Jewish Martyr in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also recommended that thousands of seized paintings
and other art works now in museums and French diplomatic and
government buildings here and abroad should be assembled and
publicly exhibited so that rightful owners or their heirs get
another chance to make claims.
</P>
<P>
   At least two-thirds of the roughly $1 billion of Jewish property
that was seized in France was reclaimed and restored to its
original owners in the first five years after the war, the panel
reported.
</P>
<P>
   But after 1948, postwar French society turned to other things,
and the issue of remaining unclaimed Jewish assets sank into the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Renewed public outrage half a century later was prompted by the
discovery that French museums were exhibiting works of art whose
rightful owners they had done little to try to find, and by claims
from Jewish groups that banks had profited from deposits of gold
bullion and cash that belonged to people killed in concentration
camps.
</P>
<P>
   After President Jacques Chirac did what none of his predecessors
had dared to do and publicly acknowledged that France, not just the
collaborationist authorities based in Vichy, had been guilty of
crimes against humanity in helping the Nazis persecute Jews on
French soil, the government decided to find out how much injustice
still remained 50 years after the incomplete restitutions it made
just after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 75,721 Jews the French authorities deported to Auschwitz
from camps at Drancy, north of Paris in the German-occupied zone,
and elsewhere between 1941 and 1944, only 2,564 came back. The
total population of Jews in France during the war was estimated at
330,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who disappeared were people who had fled the Nazis
from Poland and other countries in Central Europe. They left behind
orphans who had no way of claiming the often meager assets that had
been taken from their parents, and the commission has recommended
lifetime government pensions for Jewish survivors previously denied
them because they were not considered French.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report said it had found a total of 9,733,308
wartime francs _ the equivalent of $2.9 million today _ still in
the state national deposit bank. Maurice Kiffer, a French
functionary scandalized by what he and other French administrators
of the camp at Drancy were being made to do by the Germans, had
deposited the money in escrow accounts there for the people who had
been forced to surrender it.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Lebegue, the head of the bank, the Caisse des Depots et
Consignations, said it would cooperate fully in efforts to return
funds to their rightful owners.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 168 banks and other financial institutions listed as
having blocked tens of thousands of accounts by Jewish depositors
following Nazi orders in the occupied zone between 1940 and 1942,
the commission said, were a few American ones which have said they
would cooperate to return themoney in the accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It listed them as Morgan &AMP; Co., now part of the J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co., Guaranty Trust Co. of New York, now also part of J.P. Morgan,
and Chase Bank, now part of Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth institution, American Express, was also named in the
report, but a spokeswoman said that it was not aware of any
accounts that were turned over to Nazi authorities but that it is
reviewing its archive. Its offices in occupied France were closed
in early 1941, the spokeswoman said. The report estimated that
altogether, these American banking operations had about 60 such
accounts, their total value unknown.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by a group of six large French banks and the
French Bankers Association said they welcomed the recommendations
of the commission, which reflect many of the recommendations the
banks themselves have made in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1854EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
