<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYEAR-JAPAN-NYT     02-03 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYEAR-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN UNLIKELY TO EXPERIENCE NEW WAVE OF FOREIGN TAKEOVERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ohio)  (sidebar with GOODYEAR-SUMITOMO) 
(bl) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co.'s deal for control of most
operations of Sumitomo Rubber Industries Ltd. echoes faintly an
earlier U.S.-Japanese marriage in tires. In 1988, amid a wave of
high-profile Japanese acquisitions in the United States,
Bridgestone bought Firestone of Ohio for $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's agreement comes as Japan undergoes a surge of
mergers and acquisitions _ including some involving U.S. companies.
But a reversal of the 1980s trend is unlikely, and few here expect
the Goodyear deal to herald a new flood of foreign takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't see it,'' said Clifford Shaw, head of Merrill
Lynch Mercury Asset Management Japan Ltd. ``I don't think this is
the beginning of a major trend.''
</P>
<P>
   For one, investment bankers said, the Goodyear-Sumitomo deal was
spurred by competitive pressures specific to the tire industry.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the lingering recession that is forcing Japanese
companies to seek out deals also means that many assets up for sale
may not be at the top of international shopping lists. How many
auto companies want to buy a plant and increase capacity? How many
foreign companies want to pay for expensive headquarters here? Or
the real estate under a department store when renting is markedly
cheaper?
</P>
<P>
   Recent purchases by foreigners have largely been in financial
services _ deals that are also being driven by the deregulation of
Japanese markets. Companies like GE Capital, Citigroup and Merrill
Lynch have been picking off struggling operations while others are
forming joint ventures and other alliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reactive M&AMP;A rather than pro-active on the part of the
Japanese companies,'' said Craig Chudler, a strategist with Salomon
Smith Barney in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, deals between Japanese companies are breaking fast and
furiously. Toshiba Corp. has been paring its exposure to affiliates
and subsidiaries, as has its rival, Hitachi Ltd. Nippon Oil Co.,
Japan's largest refiner, is buying Mitsubishi Oil Co. in an effort
to consolidate, and Asahi Chemical Industry Co. has agreed to sell
its processed foods subsidiary to Japan Tobacco Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the number of mergers and acquisitions involving
Japanese companies rose 35 percent last year, to 908 deals,
according to Nikko Securities Co. Foreign buyers were responsible
for 121 deals.
</P>
<P>
   More foreign deals may soon be on the way. Nissan Motor Co. has
been talking with foreign automakers about buying a stake.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers and alliances among Japanese companies have always been
fairly common, even in good times. But the recession has clearly
driven many deals as companies restructure and sell assets not
integral to a core business.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Sumitomo, it is a second-tier tire company
staring rapid consolidation in the auto industry in the face and
contemplating its prospects, one of its bankers said.
</P>
<P>
   With $2.76 billion of debt, more than three times its equity,
striking a deal with Goodyear _ with which is already had a
substantial relationship _ was a stroke of good fortune. Goodyear
is providing $1 billion in cash, which will go a long way toward
cleaning up Sumitomo's balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo's operations in the United States and Europe are
profitable, but marginally so. And an alliance with Goodyear
promises to catapult it almost overnight into the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Wednesday's deal is merely part of a global
consolidation sweeping the auto business, which can produce 20
million to 23 million more cars annually than anyone wants to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, home to 11 vehicle manufacturers, numerous auto parts
companies and thousands of dealers, can produce four million more
cars than it can sell, so it is a natural market for such
consolidation. Nissan is seeking the same sort of deal that
Sumitomo made with Goodyear, and Mitsubishi Motors Corp. is
shopping bits of itself around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the auto industry _ and the tire business is part
of the auto industry _ there are quite specific reasons why deals
are being brokered,'' said Chudler of Salomon Smith Barney. ``The
same could be said for financial services here. But those specific
reasons don't imply a broader trend for M&AMP;A in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the deal with Goodyear is not a straightforward
merger or acquisition in the way Daimler melded with Chrysler, and
that is largely, bankers say, a function of Sumitomo's Japanese
character.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese companies prefer the safety of a joint venture, capital
participation or other types of corporate links that allow them to
hold hands without quite getting into bed, precisely what the six
ventures between Goodyear and Sumitomo are.
</P>
<P>
   They let Sumitomo maintain a vestige of control and
independence, which its bankers say was critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of M&AMP;A you're most likely to see here,'' an
investment banker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
