A0651 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURTHOUSE-CAFE-TEX     02-03 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTHOUSE-CAFE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS AMERICANA THAT WORKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECATUR, Texas _ Fellow travelers, there is a Zen way for food
to evolve, and Sarah Chapman has found the path.
</P>
<P>
   It's not through the pleasure palaces of Chicago, where Svengali
Charlie Trotter assembles towers with 75-year-old balsamic vinegar
and golden raspberries. Nor is it through the glass-encased towers
of Dallas, where chefs marry Morocco with Macao in a journey of
experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   But Chapman, in her little Courthouse Cafe &AMP; Restaurant in
Decatur, succeeds in advancing our natural cuisine without taking
her customers on a roller-coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman's stage is as unpretentious as her food. The restaurant
is tucked into a corner of the Wise County Courthouse square, amid
stores that can't decide whether they want to be gentrified.
Wanda's Frames &AMP; Thangs is decidely rural, while across the square
Harris Family Center (vacuums, music and Metabolife representation)
is a store in transition. But also on the square is Memory Lane,
Est. 1988, a sign that the bed-and-breakfast boomers are looming.
</P>
<P>
   Like her town, Chapman has a foot in two worlds. Her food is the
classics of Texas: meatloaf and fried chicken and pimiento cheese
sandwiches. But unlike most such restaurants, which freeze their
food in a time capsule of how grandmother would have cooked it,
Courthouse Cafe incorporates the progress that time brings.
</P>
<P>
   Daily plate lunches are served, just as they are in every
courthouse square in Texas. But the salad with the meal is made
with a lettuce mixture that includes frisee, arugula and radicchio,
and is topped with a house-made Thousand Island dressing miles
ahead of any bottled version.
</P>
<P>
   And the salad is just the beginning of the $5.99 daily special _
roast beef on a recent Monday. Thinly sliced pieces of roast are
fanned on the plate, sided with still-crunchy carrots and mashed
potatoes so rich with cream and butter that they slide across the
tongue. The all-hallowed biscuit, part of any Texas communion, is
presented with a sprinkling of rosemary in the dough.
</P>
<P>
   Soup of the day, cream of broccoli for $1.25, is more French
than is fashionable in a Texas cafe, a light potage of pureed
vegetables that is more soothing than solid.
</P>
<P>
   Apple cobbler, included in the daily special, is so beyond the
saccharine norm that it should be renamed. The crust, flaky with
unsalted butter, tops a savory combination of the fruit punctuated
with cinnamon, nutmeg and cardamom _ an imagination celebration
that Grandma would have never dreamed up.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe is a core sample of this century's dining. The original
hulking bar, a remnant of the cafe's pharmacy days, looms on one
wall. Chicken-wire tile is visible here and there on the floor. And
the booths, hideous green pressed-plastic jobs, are certainly from
some equally hideous fast-food joint of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Evolution, this cafe says in a calm voice, is a wondrous thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Courthouse Cafe &AMP; Restaurant
</P>
<P>
   Food: 1990s American
</P>
<P>
   Service: Small-town friendly
</P>
<P>
   Atmosphere: A chronology of American restaurants
</P>
<P>
   113 N. State St. on the courthouse square, Decatur; 6:30
a.m.-2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Monday-Saturday; cash and checks; (940) 627-1777.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
