<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SAYS HE ACTED `HASTILY' IN ACCEPTING RESIGNATION; JOB OFFER
EXPECTED 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to end the first major flap of his young
administration, Mayor Anthony A. Williams conceded Wednesday that
he acted hastily in asking a white aide who used the word
``niggardly'' in conversation with a black colleague to resign from
his job.
</P>
<P>
   While not apologizing to the aide, David Howard, 44, who stepped
down last month, Williams said in a statement that he has asked him
to return to his job as head of the District of Columbia's office
of the public advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, who had worked on Williams' election campaign, met with
the mayor for 20 minutes Wednesday and told him he would like to
return to city government but in a different job. Williams said he
would try to accommodate him, saying in a statement, ``I believe I
acted too hastily in accepting David's resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Howard said he was satisfied with resolution of
the matter but that it was ``really not about me or the use of the
word niggardly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about feelings underneath the surface that a lot of
people in Washington and the whole naion wanted to talk about.''
he said. ``This was just the flashpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he believed the city would benefit from the
incident. ``A lot of good came of this,'' he said. ``It has
fostered a discussion, not about racial tensions but about racial
perceptions. It can only help us to understand each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' decision to invite Howard back follows a swirl of
events that began on Jan. 15, the day Howard used a synonym for
miserly in a budget discussion with two co-workers, one of whom
said later he thought he heard Howard use a racial epithet. Howard
said at the time: ``I will have to be niggardly with this fund
because it's not going to be a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   After rumors of the misunderstanding and news of hurt feelings
reached Howard, he acknowledged he had used ``bad judgment'' in
selecting such a word and offered his resignation on Jan. 26. It
was immediately accepted by Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But that only led to a bad situation turning worse, prompting
waves of protest around the city _ from language purists, arguing
that niggardly is a perfectly acceptable word; from gays, defending
Howard as the mayor's first openly-gay appointee; and from many
blacks who already have questioned Williams' loyalties to the black
community.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the incident became the latest example of the
difficulties District leaders have navigating issues of race in a
majority black city that has no voting representation in the
majority white Congress that, ultimately, runs the city. Williams,
the city's former chief financial officer who was educated at Yale
and Harvard, is black, but he is perceived by many in the city as
``less black'' than his predecessor, Marion S. Barry Jr., a veteran
of the Civil Rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Williams initiated an investigation of the matter
after Howard resigned. He said in his statement that he concluded
that `` Howard did use the word `niggardly' but did not use a
racial epithet. The review also showed that an employee of the
Office of the Public Advocate did misunderstand Howard to have used
a racial epithet.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was inaugurated on Jan. 2, also said that he has
learned a lot through this incident. ``While it is important for a
mayor, or any leader, to act decisively, make bold decisions and
create a sense of urgency,'' he said, ``it is not always necessary
to act hastily.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
