<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRON-SPECIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DECLARES WAR AGAINST UNWANTED INVADERS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration on Wednesday declared
the ecological equivalent of war against an invasion of unwanted
and mostly foreign species that are steadily infiltrating the
American landscape.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed an executive order to establish a
council of scientists and bureaucrats to combat zebra mussels,
leafy spurge, long-horned beetles and hundreds of other invasive
pests.
</P>
<P>
   And the White House urged Congress to increase spending by $12.8
million, nearly doubling the current amount spent by the government
on a problem that scientists have estimated costs the nation $123
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alien species are the stealth destroyers of the American
environment,'' said noted biologist Edward O. Wilson, who joined
administration officials at the presentation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said that competition from invasive species is the main cause
of decline in 18 percent of endangered species, and contributes to
the loss of 24 percent of them. Only the outright destruction of
habitat is a more important cause, said Wilson, a leading authority
on biological diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Officials presenting the plan to a crowd of hundreds at the
National Geographic Society used rhetoric that was one part Winston
Churchill and one part H.G. Wells. They vowed in patriotic tones to
fight on beaches, fields, hills and city streets, but also threw in
many alarming references to hordes of invading aliens. One official
dubbed Clinton's call to arms ``the X-files executive order.''
</P>
<P>
   But the plan they are putting in motion has been urged on the
White House for years, gaining momentum after 500 scientists,
agriculture officials, conservationists and land managers sent a
letter to Vice President Al Gore demanding concentrated action.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said that the government can
really only envision ``modest goals of containment.'' Still,
officials said that the executive order, which requires all federal
agencies to design their policies with the war against alien
species in mind, is an important step.
</P>
<P>
   Measures would be taken by agencies as diverse as the
Transportation Department, the Commerce Department, the Defense
Department and the Customs Service to control the influx of pests,
as well as by the agencies with chief responsibility for protecting
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   One problem facing the administration is that international
trade rules can defeat import barriers imposed to control invasive
species. Asked about this by a member of the audience, Babbitt said
that in his view the world's nations need to do a better job at
reconciling trade and environmental statutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
