<HEADER>
A0676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-LEGISLATORS-ART     02-03 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-LEGISLATORS-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE AND MORE WOMEN ARE AT HOME IN STATEHOUSES, AND THEIR IMPACT IS
FELT 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ariz., Colo., Kan,, Nev., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK     
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
     OLYMPIA, Wash. _ In the Democratic caucus of the Washington
state Senate, male legislators, already outnumbered by their female
counterparts 18-9, have formed a Last Man's Club _ betting among
themselves, with a touch of nervous bonhomie, on who will be the
final one left before all the caucus members are women.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The men also shrug good-naturedly when asked whatever happened
to their posh, marble-lined bathroom in the state Capitol. The
women took it over last year, and the male legislators were
re-assigned to a decidedly less ornate lavatory, with fewer stalls,
that had been the ladies' room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy in action,'' explained Sen. Harriet Spanel, smiling
sweetly.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, women have not yet taken over the Legislature
here, but they do constitute 40.8 percent of the membership _ the
highest percentage of women in any state legislature in the
nation's history. The women of Olympia are a powerful symbol of an
electoral tide that has brought record numbers of women into public
office this year, notably in the increasingly important state
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is hardly alone. Women make up 36.5 percent of the
Nevada Legislature; 35.6 percent of Arizona's; 33 percent of
Colorado's, and 32.7 percent of Kansas'.
</P>
<P>
   No legislature anywhere yet mirrors the proportion of women in
the general population, 51 percent. And wide disparities exist
among the states. The national average of female state legislators
is 22.3 percent, and in the state at the other end of the spectrum,
Alabama, only 7.9 percent of state lawmakers are women.
</P>
<P>
   But enough states have a critical mass of women that an old
debate has fresh currency: What difference does it make when women
are in charge? And this debate has added meaning as states assume
more and more power over issues like welfare and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Some academic studies indicate that legislatures with greater
numbers of women are more favorably inclined toward measures
involving care for children and the elderly and toward women's
health issues, a view with which many lawmakers here and elsewhere
heartily concur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, generally, men like tax-type issues; they like
criminal-justice issues,'' said Sen. Shirley Winsley, a Republican
from the Tacoma area, who has served in the Legislature for 22 of
the last 26 years. ``When you get down to the nitty-gritty issues
of dealing with children, aging, long-term care, all those are
things that are a natural for women. They're wives, they're
mothers, they've been much more active in the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But even many female legislators, noting that women are hardly
monolithic in their views, question whether there is a women's
agenda to be advanced with their rising numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally sometimes kind of bristle at the idea that there
are `women's issues' for us to carry,'' said Rep. Cheryl Pflug, a
Republican who was recently elected to serve a district outside
Seattle and who ran on a platform of lowering taxes and tackling
traffic congestion and suburban sprawl. ``All issues are women's
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the mechanics of political power, some experts note that
women have not yet captured their share of the most powerful
positions in the legislatures, like House speaker, which have the
most impact in setting the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Washington, for instance, the picture is mixed. Women do
head 12 of the 15 standing committees in the Senate, and they hold
five of the top six Democratic leadership positions in the Senate.
On the other hand, the four pre-eminent leadership positions in the
Senate and the House are held by men, and no woman has ever served
as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trends here and around the nation are striking. In
1969, women held just 4 percent of all state legislative seats in
the country, according to statistics compiled by the Center for the
American Woman and Politics at Rutgers University's Eagleton
Institute. In every two-year election cycle since then, that
percentage has risen _ to 10.3 percent in 1979, 20.5 percent in
1993 and 22.3 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, in the U.S. Congress, nine women serve in the
100-member Senate and 56 in the 435-member House of Representatives
(12.9 percent of the membership there), both all-time highs,
according to the Rutgers center. The number of women in statewide
elective posts is 89, also a record number, representing 27.6
percent of the available positions. Female legislators are
disproportionately Democratic, while women in executive positions
are more evenly divided between the two major parties.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state has long drawn attention for the high numbers
of women who hold public office. Even so, the inroads in the state
Legislature stand out. Twenty-three of the 49 state senators are
women, as are 37 of the 98 state representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've traveled around the country and spoken with a lot of
lawmakers in other states,'' said Sen. Pat Thibaudeau, a Seattle
Democrat. ``And I've never seen a woman yet, be she Republican or
Democrat, who doesn't get this big smile on her face when I tell
her that we're almost half the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   One question that has been widely explored is just why women
seem to hold much larger percentages of legislative seats in
Western states than they do in many other parts of the country,
especially the South. (By comparison, New York's legislature is
20.9 percent female, Connecticut's 29.4 percent, and New Jersey's
16.7 percent.) The most widely advanced theory seems to be that the
Western states' pioneering traditions created a culture in which it
was acceptable and even necessary for women to exert strong
leadership roles. Many of these states were also among the first to
give women the right to vote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman had to be able to shoot dinner, chop the wood, harness
the horses,'' said Sen. Valoria Loveland, a Democrat from
southeastern Washington. ``And I think that's carried over in our
history. I was basically raised never to use the word `can't.'''
</P>
<P>
   But other factors also play a role in women's political
participation, experts say; for example, women sometimes do better
in states with weaker party structures, which tend to be more open
to candidates entering politics through untraditional routes.
</P>
<P>
   A larger question is just what difference women make in the way
government functions and in what kinds of bills get passed. Debbie
Walsh, associate director of the Center for the American Woman and
Politics, has studied that issue closely. In particular, she said,
women are generally more likely than men to cite child care
(especially as a component of job-training programs), affordable
health insurance and long-term care for the elderly as their
top-priority issues, as well as a range of issues dealing with
women's rights, including divorce and spousal-abuse laws.
</P>
<P>
   A study by political scientists at the University of Florida,
``Impacts of Female Legislators on Policy Making,'' based on
surveys of legislators around the country and released last summer,
also found an interesting difference between the sexes: although
Republican women in office express more conservative views than
male Democrats on several issues dealing with taxes, finance and
business matters, they are still more likely than those Democratic
men to sponsor bills in ``women's policy'' areas, even ones that
require additional government or industry financing.
</P>
<P>
   And although both male and female legislators listed education
as their top priority, they split on their second issue. Women
listed health care; the men chose taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the female legislators here, many seemed leery of the
notion that their priorities might be different from men's, a view
echoed by Gov. Gary Locke, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the Legislature, we had women who were heads of
the environment committee, economic development, education, natural
resources, the budget, local government,'' Locke said in an
interview in his Capitol office. ``They were experts in a wide
variety of issues. I didn't see the women in our Legislature just
focusing on particular issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But many other female lawmakers said it was only natural for
their priorities to be somewhat different.
</P>
<P>
   ``When more women come into the process,'' said Sen. Pat Hale, a
Republican from eastern Washington, ``I think the debate changes,
and that's healthy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
