<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0684 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREST-SERVICE-630&AMP;AD     02-03 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREST-SERVICE-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS MINING BAN TO PROTECT LAND IN MONTANA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont.)  (dal) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, determined to emphasize
conservation over development on public lands, called on Wednesday
for a mining ban in a vast section of federal land in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   The move would significantly expand protections along the Rocky
Mountain Front, at the edge of one of the richest wilderness zones
in the lower 48 states.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly undeveloped, the front has become a tempting zone for
exploration by mineral companies. In 1997, the Forest Service moved
to restrict oil and gas leasing there, and on Wednesday the agency
moved to prohibit mining for metals and ores as well.
</P>
<P>
   A rugged cascade of limestone and shale that tilts eastward to
the plains, the Rocky Mountain Front is home to elk, mountain goat
and grizzly bear and is the doorstep to millions of acres of
mountain wilderness. Although it bears no physical resemblance to
the savannahs of Africa, conservationists sometimes call it
America's Serengeti because of its spectacular wildlife habitat.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech prepared for delivery Wednesday night in Missoula,
Mike Dombeck, the chief of the Forest Service, said he has
petitioned the interior secretary to immediately impose a
moratorium on new mining claims in 400,000 acres of the Lewis and
Clark National Forest and on 29,000 acres of the adjacent Helena
National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The region is full of some of the nation's finest trout streams,
such as the Blackfoot River made famous in Norman MacLean's book
``A River Runs Through It.'' Runoff from the cyanide used in mining
can endanger these streams.
</P>
<P>
   Although the petition just begins a long process of public
comment and hearings that is to result in a final decision in two
years, the move means there will be no mining in the meantime. The
larger administration goal appears to be to eventually block mining
in the area for at least the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the move means all the public land along the Rocky
Mountain Front, from the Glacier National Park on the Canadian
border south for 100 miles through the wilderness areas and the
national forests, will be off-limits to mining.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest round in a long-running fight between the
administration and the mining industry. The administration has
sought for years to get the nation's mining law rewritten, raising
the price industry would pay for access to minerals on public land,
and to toughen mining regulations administratively, but has been
blocked in Congress so far. The administration did foil plans to
build a gold mine on the edge of Yellowstone National Park, buying
the land last year. And it set aside millions of acres in Utah as a
national monument to limit coal mining there.
</P>
<P>
   Even if pro-mining forces in Congress try to reverse the latest
proposal, it would be difficult because Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont.,
strongly favors the plan. (Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., was said to
be upset when informed of the decision Wednesday morning.)
</P>
<P>
   There is little or no mining along the Rockies Front now, but in
recent years a few clusters of mining claims have been staked under
the 19th-century law that allows prospectors to move onto public
lands.
</P>
<P>
   That alarmed conservationists, who began to lobby the
administration to withdraw the land from eligibility for mining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only place in the lower 48 where grizzlies roam
out on the plain,'' said Bob Ekey of the Wilderness Society's
Bozeman office. ``It is largely intact right now, and we would like
to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Grasser of the National Mining Association said that
``this is of great concern to us,'' especially coming on the heels
of other measures to restrict development on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are apparently marching in a particular direction,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, the move to protect the Rockies Front was just the
boldest announcement in a wide-ranging speech that Dombeck's aides
described as a comprehensive explanation of the Forest Service's
new vision of its mission. He discussed several important shifts in
how the agency intends to balance national forests' many uses:
logging, mining, grazing, recreation and conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiple use does not mean we should do everything on every
acre simply because we can,'' Dombeck said. ``Many areas are simply
not appropriate for certain activities, such as hard rock mining.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke at a time when plans for 65 percent of the national
forests are under revision, bringing changes to federal management
of more than 150 million acres of land, and when the agency is
about to issue new scientific guidelines for forestry and to
develop a new policy on building logging roads in the remotest
parts of the forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my expectation that in the future, we will rarely build
new roads into roadless areas, and if we do, it will be in order to
accomplish broader ecological objectives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the emphasis will be on maintaining existing
roads or, in many cases, obliterating them. The agency, he said,
has a road maintenance backlog of $8.5 billion and a budget for
that purpose of less than $600 million a year. Only 18 percent of
its roads are maintained up to existing standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unacceptable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dombeck appeared to be signaling a thorough overhaul of the
Forest Service's priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consider, we are spending about $2 billion per year managing
191 million acres of forest, yet contributing only about $200
million toward the 500 million acres of state-managed and
privately-owned forests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the policies he endorsed was a new definition of
``salvage'' timber sales, in which dead and dying trees are cut in
an effort to improve the forest's health. He said the new
definition should ``reduce if not eliminate'' the current practice
of cutting healthy green trees on the same tracts.
</P>
<P>
   And for the second year, he said, the administration would try
to end the practice of passing on revenues from timber sales to pay
for local roads and schools, finding other sources of money
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should the richest country in the world finance the
education of rural schoolchildren on the back of a controversial
federal timber program?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of measuring the Forest Service's success, and
determining its budget, based on how much timber it sells, Dombeck
called for new measures that would evaluate water quality, wildlife
habitat and soil condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
