<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-UMASS-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR THREATENS TO CUT UMASS BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY AND KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Governor Paul Cellucci Tuesday threatened to strip $4.6
million from the University of Massachusetts' budget in retribution
for the UMass board of trustee's surprise move to raise tuition and
fees.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also filed legislation to take away the UMass
trustees' power to set tuition costs and fees, transferring it to
the state Board of Higher Education, whose chairman, James F.
Carlin, has steadily crusaded against increasing costs at UMass and
the state colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very upset that the board apparently has decided to raise
the fees,'' an agitated Cellucci told reporters outside his State
House office Tuesday. ``We've been trying to get college and state
universities to be more affordable, more accessible to the citizens
of this state. Now all of a sudden the University of Massachusetts
wants to increase the costs of going to that university for the
students and I don't think it's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the governor appoints the UMass trustees as well as the
board of higher education members, who all serve for five years, he
said he feels the trustees are not heeding his call to make the
university more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it very clear what I think should be happening,''
Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the UMass board of trustees reversed four years of
tuition expense cuts at its meeting Tuesday, unanimously approving
an average increase of 1.4 percent in tuition costs and fees at the
four undergraduate campuses of the state's public university. For
students who live on campus, costs will rise an average of 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts in tuition costs, along with increases in fundraising
and standards, have helped raise the esteem of the university, and
attract top notch students. But the trustees defended Tuesday's
move as necessary, and well-reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am astounded at the level of anger this has caused,''
chairman Robert Karam said. ``It's not like we shoved this down or
did the Marie Antoinette bit, `Let them eat cake.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the governor is in favor of tuition and fee cuts, and
Carlin is in favor of tuition and fee cuts. We'd all like to agree
to that, but when we're sitting there every day, we have to make
some tough decisions. If they're the wrong decisions, we'll find
out. But we're doing the best we can to protect the public
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he was not upset by UMass President William M.
Bulger's gradual 49 percent pay increase _ approved in October but
not detailed until Tuesday _ which will bring the former Senate
President's salary to nearly $300,000 within 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of the salary, I think, is a decision for the
board of trustees,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he does not understand why the trustees raised
tuition costs and fees.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the board of higher education has final approval over
tuition costs, but not fees. Carlin, the chairman, has already
threatened to veto the tuition recommendation unless the trustees
cut it by five percent. But the UMass board has power to set the
fees, so Cellucci was left with few options but to cut the public
university's state funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to ask them to reconsider this and if they persist,
I will veto $4.6 million, which represents the (student cost)
increase'' from the upcoming budget, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, the Legislature has increased funding
for UMass by 13 percent, Cellucci said. In his fiscal 2000 budget
proposal, Cellucci recommends a 5 percent funding jump of $20.4
million for UMass.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 80s and 90s, UMass tuition costs more than doubled
as the state funding was cut 22 percent. Since 1996, however, the
board has cut tuitions and fees each year. But Karam said the
trustees had no choice but to increase them this year, given
technological updates and building repairs needed on the four
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not take increases lightly,'' Karam said. ``The simple
fact of the matter is, we cannot operate effective with the amount
we receive from the state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has been very generous, we're not complaining,''
added. But UMass, he said, had already done all it could to raise
money from donors, alumni, and research grants.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting Tuesday, the trustees insisted the increase was
only a slight one, and emphasized that they had kept their promise
to keep any increases below the rate of inflation, which is 1.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``An increase less than inflation is helping to keep (the
governor's) commitment,'' Karam said. The university president's
office also pointed out that tuition and fees at other public
universities rose an average of 4 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people are going right by us, all over the country,''
Karam said. ``To have an average increase of one and a half
percent, I think is a very reasonable and very measured response
from the board. It is measured, it is minor. I understand that
money means a lot to a lot of people, but for a university
education, when we're dealing with (private) campuses in the state
that charge 30,000 a year, and we're expected to be as good as some
of those campuses, to be at under $10,000 is pretty reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Karam said he would ask the governor to meet with him, to try to
persuade him with the logic behind the board's decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
