<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-U.S.-205&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TELLS TALIBAN THAT BIN LADEN MUST BE BROUGHT TO JUSTICE
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A senior U.S. official met Wednesday in Pakistan
with leaders of the Taliban, the armed religious group that rules
most of Afghanistan and shelters Osama bin Laden, the world's most
wanted terrorist suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The assistant secretary of state for South Asian affairs, Rick
Inderfurth, told the Taliban's deputy foreign minister, Jalil
Akhund, that bin Laden must be ``expelled from Afghanistan and
brought to justice for his crimes,'' said State Department
spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, a wealthy Saudi exile whom the United States calls an
international financier of terrorism, has been indicted in the
bombings of two U.S. embassies in Africa, which killed 224 people,
including 12 Americans, six months ago. The director of Central
Intelligence, George Tenet, told Congress on Tuesday that bin Laden
could strike again at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban have never shown any inclination to turn him over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to really make clear to them the risk they are
taking by harboring Osama bin Laden,'' a senior State Department
official said. ``We believe there are real threats against us
coming from Osama bin Laden. This is an extremely serious matter
and we going to hold them responsible for his behavior.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Taliban preside over one of the world's poorest and most
war-ravaged nations. Afghanistan spent the 1980s under Soviet
occupation, enduring a war that killed perhaps a million people and
sent perhaps 6 million into exile.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets withdrew 10 years ago this month. But then the
Afghan rebels, which were backed some $3 billion of military aid
from the CIA, and, separately, supported by bin Laden in their
struggle, spent much of the 1990s fighting one another over their
nation's broken remains.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Afghanistan is a refuge for stateless outlaws, its
economy largely a bazaar of guns and drugs. The United States
estimates that Afghanistan is the source for as much as 40 percent
of the world's supply of heroin. The United Nations and
international aid groups have almost entirely withdrawn from
Afghanistan after violence against their personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, an armed religious group organized with assistance
from Pakistan's intelligence service, wrested power from the
feuding rebel groups in 1996. They have been shunned by most of the
world for their intolerance, their violence and their embrace of
bin Laden. Only Pakistan, the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia
recognize the group as the legitimate government of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Taliban want from the outside world is acceptance and
recognition,'' a State Department official said. ``We can't promise
we will recognize them, but we're telling them: if you want to be
seen as a government, you have to act like a government. If you go
along with international norms, you will receive wider acceptance
and probably greater assistance.'' The United States has held
periodic meetings with the Taliban over the past year, sometimes at
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott met with
Pakistani officials Wednesday to tell them that since ``they have
used their influence to assist the Taliban in their rise to power,
we expect them to use their influence to stop them'' from harboring
bin Laden, a State Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech delivered in Islamabad, Talbott called Afghanistan
the site of ``the last battle of the Cold War'' and ``one of the
first, most severe and most ominous battles of the post-Cold War
world: the battle against the forces of terrorism, extremism and
intolerance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
