<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ELDERLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES DEBATE ON SURPLUS, CRITICIZES GOP TAX CUT PROPOSALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ohio)  (dal) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton called on Wednesday for a ``great
national debate'' about how to spend the growing federal budget
surplus as he promoted his plans to shore up Social Security and
Medicare at the expense of Republican tax cut proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to work together across party lines to make these
decisions,'' Clinton said even as he warned of the dangers of
Republican ideas in a speech here to a powerful lobbying group for
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   As he sketched out his broad goals for strengthening the
Medicare system, Clinton was clearly trying to box in the
Republican Congress. He accused Republicans of proposing tax cuts
without first addressing the elderly's health care needs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that before spending any of the surplus on new
programs or tax cuts, policymakers ``must first tell America's
families: `What is your plan to preserve and strengthen Medicare in
the 21st century?'''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans fired back that Clinton was offering a false choice
between cutting taxes and saving the surplus until popular programs
are fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't make Americans pay higher taxes because the
politicians haven't finished their work,'' said Ari Fleischer, the
spokesman for the House Ways and Means Committee. ``Let's work hard
and work together to get it all done.''
</P>
<P>
   The aging of the population is increasingly straining the
Medicare and Social Security systems. A bipartisan commission on
Medicare is scheduled to report its recommendations by March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Steering clear of any specific proposals for a radical overhaul
of Medicare, Clinton reiterated earlier ideas as he presented four
guideposts for strengthening the system.
</P>
<P>
   He called for committing 15 percent of surpluses to Medicare;
assuring ``a modern, competitive system'' for high-quality care,
and guaranteeing Americans specific benefits without ``excessive
new costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last, he urged the creation of a prescription drugs program that
he said would be paid for with savings from changing the system.
Clinton's proposal for that new benefit drew applause from the
audience, the national legislative council of the American
Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John B. Breaux, D-La., who heads the advisory commission
studying Medicare, welcomed Clinton's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased that the president is forcefully focusing on
Medicare as a prime part of his legislative package this year,''
Breaux said in an interview. ``His call for modernizing Medicare
and making it more competitive is consistent with what we're trying
to do at the commission. I look forward to producing something that
can meet his standards and get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux added: ``Just adding money to an antiquated system that
provides inadequate benefits isn't the answer. I'm pleased that the
president has recognized that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly said he also favored tax relief. But he
derided Republican ideas _ what he called ``a rather long series of
large and risky tax proposals'' _ as short-sighted.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that it would ``benefit clearly the wealthiest
Americans,'' the president criticized a plan put forward on Tuesday
by Rep. John R. Kasich, R-Ohio, for a $1 trillion cut over the next
15 years. ``It would do this before Medicare has been secured,''
Clinton warned.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cuthbertson, a spokesman for Kasich, said of the surplus:
``We view this as the people's money; it's not our money and the
government's. Mr. Clinton believes just the opposite, that it's the
government's money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
