<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEHOVAHS-BLOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT WEIGH JEHOVAH'S WITNESS TRANSFUSION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL LANGNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three justices of the Massachusetts Appeals Court were
asked Tuesday to make a precedent-setting decision on whether a
17-year-old girl, a Jehovah's Witness, may refuse a blood
transfusion even if doing so would mean her certain death.
</P>
<P>
   In a hastily convened session, Kent B. Smith, George Jacobs, and
Elizabeth Porada heard arguments in the case of Alexis Demos, of
Lenox, who ruptured her spleen in a snowboarding accident Jan. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Richard Simons told the justices that Alexis is a
``mature minor'' who has often stated her belief that the taking of
blood violates biblical tenets and who had made a written
declaration only 10 days before the accident saying she did not
wish to have a blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the justices to consider that the law does not fix a
single age to define maturity or juvenile status. The test he asked
them to apply is the balancing of a child's paramount interest
versus the interests of the state.
</P>
<P>
   For Alexis, he said, the paramount interest is that she be
allowed to follow her religious convictions.
</P>
<P>
   However, Benjamin Smith, attorney for the Berkshire Medical
Center in Pittsfield, where Alexis is now apparently recovering
from her injuries, said the position of the hospital and of
physicians working there is that a situtation could easily arise
where the girl would die without a transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   That concern had prompted the hospital to obtain an order from
Superior Court Judge Judd Carhart that allows the doctors to
administer a transfusion. The Demos family is appealing that
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Jehovah's witnesses consider transfusions to be covered by the
prohibition against eating blood which may be found in at least
three places in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alexis now seems on the way to recovery, Benjamin Smith
said, the healing process of the spleen could be interrupted by a
sudden movement by the patient and that heavy bleeding could be
started, with a blood clot coming loose. Without a timely
transfusion, the brain would be deprived of oxygen with resulting
permanent damage, if not death.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Alexis's father Alec Demos declined to answer
when asked whether he was prepared to let his child die rather than
violate the biblical injunctions. He said that he knew of many
physicians across the country who would be prepared to try
alternative treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's questions by the justices probed at the point that
Alexis is now out of the intensive-care unit, off intravenous
tubes, is eating a regular diet, and is showing a rising
red-blood-cell count, suggesting that their decision may not be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But the hospital's attorney emphasized that ``The hospital's
position is that this court shouldn't allow the avoidable death of
a child.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still the danger of a sudden bleeding, Smith said, and
``Alexis Demos would not have any opportunity to change her mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The jduges did not make an immediate ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
