<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time Warner chairman `proud' of arena naming
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time Warner Chairman Gerald Levin praised the city of
Atlanta and the management of his Turner Broadcasting System unit
for a deal naming the new downtown arena Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of Atlanta,'' said Levin during a briefing
Wednesday about the company's quarterly financial performance.
``The arena deal is significant for Atlanta and its downtown
renewal.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin said the deal, in which Philips Electronics North America
will pay his company $180 million over the next 20 years, cements
his company's presence in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta has become important intellectual and physical
presence for us,'' said Levin. ``(In) no other location do we have
such an integration of facilities and businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Atlanta, Time Warner has its corporate offices in
New York. The company's movie and television production is based in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Levin has signed off on a major renovation of CNN Center, the
downtown headquarters for Turner Broadcasting. The center is adding
an atrium that will tie in with the adjacent Olympic Park. Philips
Arena will sit beyond the CNN Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my idols is William Paley (the deceased founder of
CBS),'' said Levin. ``He had his company as a whole, from the
architecture of its buildings to the way he did business, project a
certain grace. I think what we are doing in Atlanta shows a certain
elegance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
