<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lucent's deal to make fiber optics for Pathnet may be biggest of
its kind
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lucent Technologies has landed a $440 million
agreement to make fiber optics for Pathnet Inc. _ a deal that could
grow to $2.1 billion over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, a sign of continued boom in high-speed
telecommunications, is also confirmation of Lucent's decision to
expand the 170-acre, 3,000-worker surburban Atlanta factory known
as the Atlanta Works, which makes fiber-optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Works, which is already undergoing expansion, will
not grow any faster because of the Pathnet deal, said Bob Mohalley,
chief strategy officer for Lucent's Network Products Group. ``This
is a good match with our capital investment. We expect that this
will make us even more competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the deal grow to its full potential, it would represent
the largest fiber-optics purchase thus far in the United States,
the companies said. The network group already accounts for more
than $3 billion of the $30 billion in revenue that New Jersey-based
Lucent Technologies reported last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pathnet, a 2-year-old company based in Washington, D.C., is
buying Lucent's cutting-edge fiber. That cable, called TrueWave,
can potentially handle up to 40 billion bits of data per second,
Mohalley said. ``You have to build the right photonic highway for
the speeds that are coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent beat out rival Corning for the contract, according to
Dick Jalkut, president and chief executive officer of Pathnet.
Jalkut, CEO of Nynex until its purchase by Bell Atlantic, sits on
the board of directors of Home Wireless Networks _ which has
received a hefty capital investment from Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Lucent's attitude about working with an ``early stage
company'' like Pathnet that convinced Pathnet to make the deal,
Jalkut said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber optic cables, which use pulses of light to convey
information, are capable of transmitting data far more quickly than
traditional analog phone lines. Although expensive, fiber is also
capable of carrying far heavier data loads than analog. But because
of its price, many smaller cities have been bypassed by the
companies installing high speed national networks.
</P>
<P>
   Pathnet started as a microwave company, carrying data
wirelessly. But company strategy now is to construct a fiber
network that connects the ``second- and third-tier cities'' to the
larger centers, president and chief executive officer of the
company. ``There is a significant part of the network that is
siginificantly underserved. Qwest is connecting to National
Football League cities, not downmarket to cities of 100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pathnet does not carry its own traffic, instead leasing the
use of its lines to long-distance companies, Internet service
providers and others. Jalkut said the eventual entry into
long-distance of the regional Bells such as BellSouth will likely
add to demand for such high-speed service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
