<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-GRANTS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner adds $31.5 million to grant total
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ted Turner's money continues to flow around the world,
largely to projects designed to help women, protect children and
clean the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Foundation, set up a year ago to administer the Atlanta
businessman's gift of $1 billion to the United Nations over 10
years, announced Wednesday its third round of grants.
</P>
<P>
   The new grants total more than $31.5 million, bringing the total
disbursed since the foundation was created 13 months ago to about
$86.5 million. Grants are awarded only to projects proposed by one
or more U.N. agencies, and only to projects approved by both the
U.N. leadership and the foundation board, which has set its
emphasis on women, children and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Of the money awarded in this round, 36 percent went to women's
issues and population control, 34 percent went to environmental
programs and 10 percent went to children's health programs. The
remainder went to other U.N. projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely pleased with the high-quality projects
proposed by the U.N. and with the increasing focus on the board's
major priorities,'' said Tim Wirth, foundation president.
</P>
<P>
   The grants are as follows:
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.5 million to help establish a ``distance training'' system
intended to enable thousands of health professionals in other
countries to be trained less expensively than with face-to-face
programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.7 million to encourage women in Zambia, Cambodia and Nepal
to participate in irrigation development projects.
</P>
<P>
   _ $300,000 to involve Kenyan girls and their parents in
identifying rites of passage that would serve as alternatives to
female genital mutilation.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1 million for AIDS prevention and health in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   _ $700,000 to encourage responsible fatherhood in Guatemala, El
Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   _ $3 million to expand the U.N.'s microcredit project into new
countries.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.2 million to reduce violence against women.
</P>
<P>
   _ $512,000 to enhance the status of women in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.4 million to create a Forum of South Caucasus States to
encourage conflict resolution in Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   _ $313,000 to strengthen the participation of nongovernmental
organizations in U.N. conferences.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.5 million to develop a plan to address coral reef
degradation around the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.2 million to produce an assessment, timed to the new
millennium, of the condition of the world's ecosystems _ including
the world's fisheries, freshwater ecosystems, savannahs, forests
and urban ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.7 million to help establish, in collaboration with the
Brazilian government and a Brazilian bank, an Amazon Biodiversity
Permanent Fund.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.2 million over three years to demonstrate in northeast
China the usefulness of biomass energy to farmers in hopes of
taking the concept worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   _ Up to $2 million to enhance energy efficiency and
infrastructure in Belarus, Bulgaria, Kazakhstan, Russian Federation
and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   _ $500,000 to develop a CD-ROM and Web-based U.N. Atlas of the
Oceans.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.5 million over three years to help develop a World Energy
Assessment for the ninth session of the Commission on Sustainable
Development, which will meet in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1 million to help develop in one Nicaraguan community
sustainable environmental programs that can serve as a model for
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   _ $200,000 to help develop in Brazil methods for conserving
eco-systems by surrounding them with buffer areas which allow some
development.
</P>
<P>
   _ $2.2 million for preventative health care for children in
Ghana, Mali, Niger and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1 million to help eliminate iodine deficiency, which can lead
to mental retardation, among young people in Angola, Central
African Republic, Chad, Democratic Republic of Congo and Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   _ $3.79 million to set priorities so land mine fields that cause
the greatest social and economic damage to communities can be
cleared first.
</P>
<P>
   _ $210,000 to help create the ability locally to deal with land
mines in Angola and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   _ $440,000 to produce 25,000 copies of a handbook to educate
civilian field workers about how to avoid being injured by land
mines.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.5 million over three years to help indigenous peoples
defend their legal rights on Costa Rica, El Salvador, Honduras,
Guatemala, Belize, Nicaragua and Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
