<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TBWA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SHAKE-UP AT TBWA/CHIAT/DAY'S NEW YORK OFFICE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: England, Cal., Minn.)  By STUART ELLIOT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A shake-up in top management is under way at the New
York office of TBWA/Chiat/Day.
</P>
<P>
   Again? Yes, again.
</P>
<P>
   Senior executives have come and gone frequently at the
problematic office since the merger that combined the New York
operations of TBWA Advertising with Chiat/Day in 1995. For example,
three executive creative directors have departed in less than three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for all the turmoil? Culture clashes between
executives who had worked for the two predecessor agencies, along
with widespread perceptions _ fed by the popularity of campaigns
for products like Energizer batteries and Taco Bell fast food _
that the TBWA/Chiat/Day California office, now based in Playa del
Rey, has long been superior.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the annual Best Agencies issue of the trade
publication Advertising Age, published last month, declared that
the TBWA/Chiat/Day New York office ``remains below the standards of
the California agency.''
</P>
<P>
   But the importance of New York as the largest market in the
world's leading country for advertising requires another effort at
de-worming the Big Apple office of TBWA/Chiat/Day, the North
American unit of the TBWA Worldwide division of Omnicom Group. This
time around, the changing of the guard is taking place on both
sides of the agency _ administrative and creative _ at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're really going to be what we want to be, the best
worldwide network there is, the New York office needs to be a
strong, shining light,'' Bob Kuperman, president and chief
executives for the Americas at TBWA Worldwide, said in an interview
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do now is not to fix an old office that
was broken,'' he added, ``but to construct a new office and bring
in the best talent to run it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the administrative side, the new top manager, with the title
of president and chief executive, is arriving at the TBWA/Chiat/Day
office on Madison Avenue from a sibling agency overseas.
</P>
<P>
   He is Carl Johnson, 40, who for the last two years has been
chief executive at what is now TBWA GGT Simons Palmer in London,
which handles accounts like National Westminster Bank PLC; the
Virgin Direct unit of Virgin Group PLC French Connection U.K., an
apparel retailer making a foray into the United States; Sony
Playstation video games, and the Holsten Pils beer sold by Scottish
&AMP; Newcastle PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Total billings at TBWA GGT Simons Palmer are estimated at $400
million, compared with the estimated $250 million handled by
TBWA/Chiat/Day in New York; the California office handles $1.4
billion, including the agency's crucial Nissan Motor Corp. account.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Johnson helped found Simons Palmer Denton Clemmow &AMP;
Johnson, one of five shops that contributed to TBWA GGT Simons
Palmer. It was runner-up for the 1998 Agency of the Year honor from
the British trade publication Campaign; the article included praise
for ``how nimble the new management is on its feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will need to be nimble to help restore the reputation of
TBWA/Chiat/Day in New York, particularly as competitors like Fallon
McElligott and Wieden &AMP; Kennedy are making ambitious attempts to
bolster their Gotham operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in playing second fiddle to anyone in New
York,'' said Johnson, who joined Kuperman for the interview, ``or
anyone in our network.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The London office is the third or fourth biggest TBWA
office,'' said Johnson, whose resemblance to the British actor Tim
Roth of ``Reservoir Dogs'' was heightened by the black sports coat
he wore. ``When you think about what I'm leaving behind, I wouldn't
have come from that to run an ordinary office.''
</P>
<P>
   On the creative side, the new top manager, with the title of
executive creative director, is arriving from crosstown.
</P>
<P>
   He is David Page, who since October has been senior partner and
executive creative director at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather New York, part of
the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP Group PLC. Page, 43, an
art director, has been working on such accounts at Ogilvy New York
as the Eastman Kodak Co. and the Hershey Foods Corp..
</P>
<P>
   Page, a particularly peripatetic creative executive, also has
worked at agencies like Ammirati &AMP; Puris in New York, later the
Ammirati Puris Lintas unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies;
Goodby, Berlin &AMP; Silverstein in San Francisco, now the Goodby,
Silverstein &AMP; Partners unit of Omnicom, and Carmichael Lynch in
Minneapolis, now also part of Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   An ad created by Page for Harley-Davidson ``is one of Lee's
all-time favorites,'' said Kuperman, referring to Lee Clow, chief
creative officer at TBWA Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ad shows a man with the Harley logo tattooed on his arm,''
Kuperman recalled, ``and the headline `When was the last time you
felt this strongly about something?'''
</P>
<P>
   The appointments of Page and Johnson were reported this week by
the trade publication Adweek. Page will succeed Eric McClellan, who
left in September. Though Johnson's position is new, Mary Maroun
has served as managing director _ the top administrative title
until now _ since February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maroun, 42, has been asked to ``continue on as managing
director,'' Kuperman said, ``and she is considering that.''
</P>
<P>
   Page, who is to begin on Feb. 15, and Johnson, who is to begin
in April, will be responsible for all accounts at the
TBWA/Chiat/Day New York office, which include Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc.;
the Nivea skin care line sold by Beiersdorf AG ; the New York Life
Insurance Co., and such liquor brands sold by the Seagram Americas
unit of the Seagram Co. as Absolut vodka, the Glenlivet Scotch
whisky and Seagram's Gin.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the New York office of what was then
Chiat/Day had matched if not surpassed its West Coast sibling, with
acclaimed campaigns for clients like the Nynex Yellow Pages and
Arrow shirts. But constant churn, as the office won and lost
accounts like Reebok International Ltd. and American Express, took
its toll.
</P>
<P>
   The office has been doing better recently, landing accounts like
Barnes &AMP; Noble, Outback Steakhouse and the Promus Hotels Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to the experience of sitting in an office with no
clients, just some partners, owing money to the banks and saying,
`OK, boys, here we go,''' Johnson said. ``That you never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether being English would hinder his efforts to
understand the New York and American markets, Johnson said, ``I can
feel as foreign walking across the road in London to an agency that
does things I don't believe in as I can anywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's hiring is the second time in a week that a president
and chief executive has been named at a TBWA/Chiat/Day office. Tom
Carroll is joining Playa del Rey with those titles from Messner
Vetere Berger McNamee Schmetterer/Euro RSCG in New York, a unit of
Havas Advertising, where he had been a partner and managing
director.
</P>
<P>
   At Ogilvy New York, said Toni Lee, a spokeswoman, a successor to
Page is being sought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
