<HEADLINE>
MAIER TO COMPETE AT VAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hermann ``The Hermannator'' Maier will take on the tough Vail
downhill course on Saturday, an odds on favorite to take the gold
in this year's World Alpine Championships taking place at the
Colorado resort over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the overall World Cup standings, Maier will take on
Norway's Lasse Kjus, who has been chasing him all season, and is
about 200 points behind the Austrian.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, the ski racer best known for his spectacular
flying crash at last year's Olympic downhill, was tied in the Vail
Super-G.
</P>
<P>
   True to the growing rivalry, Norway's Kjus was just as fast as
Maier and in a rare tie for first, shared the first-place podium
with a time of 1-minute 14.53 seconds. At the Nagano games, two
days after his downhill crash, Maier rallied to win the Super-G.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in women's action Wednesday, Alexandra Meissintzer
led an Austrian sweep of the Super-G, showing why she is often
called the female Maier. Over a rolling bumpy course, Meissintzer
nailed the Vail course to beat her teammate Renate Goetschl by .03
seconds. Another teammate, Michaela Dorfmeister, placed third ahead
of a German star, Hilde Gerg.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Gerety, skiing before the watchful eye of boyfriend, Tommy
Moe, had a decent run going before she crashed off the course,
leaving on her own power, unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   The best US finish went to Kate Monahan, who skied with a bad
back, but placed 23d.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
