<SLUG> BC-NEWT-IRS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS CLEARS FOUNDATION IN GINGRICH ETHICS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case involving the ethics violations that led
the House of Representatives to reprimand former Speaker Newt
Gingrich in 1997, the Internal Revenue Service has cleared a
private foundation close to Gingrich of breaking tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS ruling, involving the Progress and Freedom Foundation,
does not directly exonerate Gingrich. But it suggests that he did
not illegally use tax-exempt money for political purposes, one of
the main accusations against him.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich could not be reached for comment Wednesday. His closest
associate in Washington, Joe Gaylord, did not return a telephone
call about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Galen, executive director of Gopac, a political action
committee that Gingrich headed for eight years, said the finding by
the IRS showed that the House ethics investigation of Gingrich had
been ``way off base.''
</P>
<P>
   James M. Cole, a Washington lawyer who served as special counsel
to the House Ethics Committee and brought the case against
Gingrich, said Wednesday that despite the ruling he had not changed
his opinion that Gingrich had broken the tax law.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich stepped down as speaker last year after Republicans
lost five House seats in the November election. In December, he
paid the last installment of a $300,000 fine imposed by the House
for ethics violations. He resigned from Congress last month.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS' ruling, after an audit that took three and a half
years, cleared the foundation of any violation of tax laws in
connection with its sponsorship of a college course Gingrich
taught. The foundation is a conservative research institute whose
president, Jeffrey Eisenach, was once on Gingrich's staff.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation released the ruling Wednesday. Officials at two
schools in Georgia where Gingrich taught the course, Kennesaw State
University and Reinhardt College, said in interviews Wednesday that
they had received letters from the IRS last month also clearing
them of any violation of tax law in the Gingrich case. Galen said
Gopac had not been audited.
</P>
<P>
   The facts of the case go back to 1993, when Gingrich was the
inspirational leader of Republicans in the House, who had been
mired in the minority for a generation. He was determined to put an
end to that status.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who has a doctorate in history, began teaching a
course that year, Renewing American Civilization, at Kennesaw State
College. The theme of the course was the central message at the
time of conservative Republicans: that the ``welfare state'' should
be replaced by an ``opportunity society.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 and 1995, the course moved to Reinhardt College. It was
also broadcast around the country on cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of satellite uplinks and other expenses were covered by
tax-deductible donations to the colleges and by the Progress and
Freedom Foundation, which also is tax exempt. Gingrich was not
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, tax-deductible contributions like those given to
the colleges and the foundation cannot be used for partisan
political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   After a long investigation, a subcommittee of the Ethics
Committee reached an agreement with Gingrich in late 1996. In the
agreement, which was essentially a plea bargain, Gingrich did not
admit to the direct tax law violation he was accused of by Cole,
the special counsel. But he did admit that he had failed to obtain
the necessary legal advice that the financing of his course was
within the law.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also admitted to providing the Ethics Committee with
false information when he told the panel in writing that Gopac, the
political committee he headed from 1986 until 1994, had nothing to
do with his course. In fact, Gopac paid at one point for satellite
broadcasts of the course material.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats saw this as a more serious violation than the tax
matter. Gingrich said one of his lawyers had been responsible for
the erroneous information.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the agency called it a ``close case'' but
concluded that the private interests of Gingrich and the Republican
Party were served only incidentally by the use of tax-exempt money
to pay the expenses of the course.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were set forth in what the agency calls a
``technical advice memorandum.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery L. Yablon, the Washington tax lawyer who represented the
Progress and Freedom Foundation, said the 74-page memorandum was by
far the longest and most detailed finding he had ever seen
involving the question of whether activities were tax exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion that no tax law was violated, the agency said,
was based on many factors, including ``the nonpartisan content'' of
the course, the favorable mention in the curriculum of
officeholders who were not Republicans and the fact that the
colleges at which the course was taught were well established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
