<HEADLINE>
PRAYER BREAKFAST INVITATION TO ARAFAT MEETS CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The invitation of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
to Thursday's annual National Prayer Breakfast has transformed the
event designed to symbolize global peace and reconciliation into a
hotbed of angry protest and finger-pointing.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to Arafat's attendance has been building over the
last week, as conservative religious groups, including the
Christian Coalition and the National Jewish Coalition, charge
President Clinton with exploiting a spiritual event for political
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Mike Forbes, Republican of New York, is one of at
least two members of Congress who have announced they would boycott
the breakfast following a flurry of calls and letters sent to
members of Congress from conservative religious groups asking that
they refuse to join the hundreds of foreign dignitaries, heads of
states, and other political luminaries attending the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply wrong for Congress to treat this unrepentant
terrorist with the respect due a legitimate world leader,'' said
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   A group called The Committee for a Secure Peace, chaired by
former Senator Rudy Boschwitz of Minnesota, also took out a
full-page ad in Wednesday's Washington Times that said,
``Congressman and Senators: Don't Go.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad accused Arafat of breaking his commitment enshrined in
the Oslo and Wye accords to combat terrorism, and noted that Arafat
last week released five terrorists who killed Americans, and listed
the victims by name.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to meet with Arafat some time before or after the
breakfast. State Department spokesman James Rubin said there was no
evidence yet to support these claims by the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
   While some members of Congress may boycott the event, attempts
by religious groups to have Arafat disinvited, however, were
rebuffed by Representative Steve Largent, an Oklahoma Republican
and chairman of this year's National Prayer Breakfast committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly the type of event people like Arafat ought to
be invited to,'' said Largent. ``The idea of a prayer breakfast is
to bring people together for reconciliation and healing and
forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   But the spirit of goodwill is unlikely to prevail as the
Christian Defense Coaltion holds a demonstration and a prayer vigil
outside the breakfast. Inside, relatives of the victims of
terrorist violence conducted by the Palestinian Liberation
Organization intend to approach Arafat at the breakfast, according
to the religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yasser Arafat is an unrepentant murderer and terrorist with
blood on his hands,'' said Adrea Sheldon, executive director of the
Traditional Values Coalition. ``It's Jewish blood, it's Christian
blood, it's American blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat arrived in Washington Tuesday for a three-day visit to
discuss the breakdown of the peace agreement with Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1937EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
