<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Lottery $60 million winner `taking a few days off'
 &HT;    By Doug Payne and Clint Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was easy to spot the winner of Tuesday's $60
million Big Game drawing _ he was the big guy with the huge grin as
he walked into the Georgia Lottery Corp.'s news conference
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sheets, 42, looked like a man who's suddenly many millions
of dollars richer than he was the day before _ $33 million before
taxes, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   You don't often hear of that happening to someone who owns a
bait shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what to say,'' Sheets, of the Chattanooga
suburb of Harrison, Tenn., said at the start of the news conference
in his honor. ``It's all so unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the big question out of the way quickly, Sheets said he
doesn't know what he'll do with the money. Maybe take a long family
vacation with his parents and three children. Certainly there'll be
more time for golf, he said. Beyond that, he said he hasn't really
been able to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   As for the bait shop, it was just a sideline anyway. Sheets is a
property assessor in Hamilton County, Tenn. Before driving to
Atlanta to claim his prize, he gave the shop to his son and
``called my boss (in the tax assessor's office) to say I'd be
taking a few days off.''
</P>
<P>
   No comment on whether he'll continue working there after a few
days off.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets and a friend drove to Ringgold on Monday for the express
purpose of buying tickets for Tuesday's Big Game drawing. They
bought their tickets at Favorite Market No. 79 on U.S. 41, just
north of Ringgold.
</P>
<P>
   The friend, Kevin Bartenfield, asked the clerk for three Quik
Pik numbers. Then Sheets stepped up and said, ``Give me five of
what he got'' _ he, too, going the Quik Pik route instead of
thinking up his own numbers.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second time Sheets had ever bought lottery
tickets. The last time was a couple of years ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the first of Sheets's five number series was
the winner: 6-14-23-31-33, with the Big Money Ball 13. Had
Bartenfield asked for four number sequences instead of three, maybe
he'd have been the guest of honor at Wednesday's press conference.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Sheets bought his tickets at that market means a
big bonus for the employees who work there. The Georgia Lottery
gives a $25,000 bonus to the retailer who sells a jackpot-winning
number. The company policy of the Dalton-based Favorite Market
chain is to share that bonus with store employees. The company will
keep half and give the rest to the staff at Favorite Market No. 79.
</P>
<P>
   As manager of the store, which is two miles from the Chattanooga
city limits, Angie Bryson will get a $6,250 bonus. The six other
employees of the store will get bonuses of slightly more than
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sheets' winnings, he chose the lump-sum payout option,
which meant he got a big presentation check for $33,277,860 from
Georgia Lottery President Rebecca Paul. It was the biggest single
payout in the Lottery's 5 1/2 year history, Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the real check that was cut by the lottery corporation
for Sheets withheld state and federal taxes. The check that he
drove back to Harrison with was for $21,963,387.60.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
