<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPSTAKES-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PROPOSAL WOULD CRACK DOWN ON SWEEPSTAKE OPERATORS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Ill., Miss., Mich.)  By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Legislation was introduced in the Senate Wednesday
to strengthen regulations prohibiting sweepstakes mailings that
mimic government documents and increase civil penalties for
companies that send out fraudulent or deceptive sweepstakes entry
forms.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was described by one of its sponsors, Sen. Susan M.
Collins, R-Maine, as a means of increasing protection for senior
citizens and other consumers who are vulnerable to sophisticated
mass-marketing techniques and pitches by celebrities used by
sweepstakes companies and similar mass mailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen countless examples of mailings that deceptively
promise extravagant prizes in order to entice consumers to make
unnecessary purchases, said Collins, who introduced the legislation
along with Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., and two Democrats, Sens.
Carl Levin of Michigan and Dick Durbin of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Collins cited as examples of deceptive practices two recent
mailings to constituents in Maine. One of them, she said, appeared
to be a government document and said, ``Urgent Delivery, A Special
Notification of Cash currently being held by the U.S. Government is
ready for shipment to you.'' The mailing asked recipients to send
$9.97 to learn how to get the cash. A sweepstakes entry package
said, ``You Were Declared One of Our Latest Sweepstakes Winners And
You're About to Be Paid $833,337 in Cash!''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would establish new standards requiring sweepstakes
companies and other mass mailers to disclose that no purchase is
necessary to win a prize and strengthen laws against mailings that
appear to be official documents. It also would streamline Postal
Service procedures for stopping fraudulent mailings and increase
penalties for civil violations from the current $10,000 to up to $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations opened an
investigation into the extent of sweepstakes fraud late last year
and public hearings are expected in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Cerasale, senior vice president for government affairs at
the Direct Marketing Association, the industry trade group in
Washington, said the organization had been working with Collins and
her staff to develop new laws aimed at eliminating fraudulent
sweepstakes operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our push is that we want to get rid of fraud in the
sweepstakes areas because that makes it better for legitimate
sweepstakes companies,'' he said. ``We do agree that there are
clearly people out there that are fraudulent and we've got to go
after them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerasale said that the vast majority of sweepstakes companies
comply with the law and most people who enter the contests
understand what they are doing and are satisfied with the products
that they receive.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for senior citizens have contended that they are
particularly vulnerable to the sophisticated mailings and lookalike
documents used by the sweepstakes indus4ry. Senior citizens have
spent thousands of dollars entering contests after receiving
mailings promising that they were finalists or winners, though the
fine print disclosed that no purchase was necessary to enter and
that the odds of actually winning were often greater than those of
winning a state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Most actions against sweepstakes companies have come from state
attorneys general, who use consumer protection laws to go after
allegedly fraudulent mailings. The proposed legislation would not
preempt existing state laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
