<HEADER>
A0734 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMA-EDITOR-BOS &LR;      02-03 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMA-EDITOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMA AND FIRED EDITOR STRIKE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Medical Association has announced a cease-fire with
the top-ranking editor it fired last month, but the announcement
left many questions unanswered about the fate of Dr. George D.
Lundberg and the AMA itself.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the nation's largest doctors' group and
Lundberg said Wednesday they had ``reached agreement on the terms
of Dr. Lundberg's departure,'' but they would not discuss the
provisions, which are believed to include a sizeable financial
settlement. The statement also said Lundberg would continue
contributing to ``scientific medical research and journalism,
including JAMA,'' but it added that such contributions would be
``subject to editorial discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   AMA officials declined to amplify on the terse statement and
Lundberg was unavailable. But others close to the controversy said
the announcement does not settle the issues of journalistic
independence raised by Lundberg's firing, nor does it erase the
black eye the incident gave the AMA, whose membership was already
down to less than 40 percent of US physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we need to do as a committee is address the
issue of creating some kind of firewall'' between the AMA
leadership and JAMA, said Dr. Michael M.E. Johns of Emory
University in Atlanta, a member of the AMA committee charged with
finding a new JAMA editor. ``Any candidates are going to ask about
this, and I think we need to find something that provides better
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Raymond Scalettar of Washington, D.C., who chaired the AMA
board in 1992-93 and has led unsuccessful bids to shake up the
organization, went a step further. ``This sad chapter at the AMA
will not end by just `making nice' '' with Lundberg, he said.
``Fundamentally, a scientific and medical journal has to have
complete independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about that independence were raised last month when
the AMA abruptly terminated Lundberg after a 17-year tenure, during
which he transformed the journal from a mouthpiece of the AMA to
one of the world's most esteemed medical publications. But the
feisty and blunt-spoken Lundberg also had raised the ire of many
AMA trustees, some staffers and Dr. E. Ratcliffe Anderson, the
retired Air Force general the AMA brought in last year to rescue it
from earlier scandals and boost its sagging membership.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and his supporters apparently were distressed when
Lundberg published a special issue last year on alternative
medicine, and when he appeared the CBS-TV ``60 Minutes'' show
arguing that hospitals should do more autopsies when patients die.
The episode that led to his firing came last month when he
published a survey study in which a majority of college students
had agreed with President Clinton's controversial contention that
oral-genital contact does not constitute ``having sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Running the study just as Clinton's Senate impeachment trial was
getting underway, Anderson said, amounted to ``inappropriately and
inexcusably interjecting JAMA into a major political debate.'' But
leading medical editors from around the world, and even Lundberg's
interim replacements at JAMA, railed against the firing, saying it
called into question JAMA's editorial integrity and raised the
spectre of the journal once again becoming an AMA house organ.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's statement by the AMA and its ex-editor sought to put
the controversy behind them, saying that ``neither Dr. Lundberg nor
the AMA wishes to add to the confusion and uncertainty surrounding
this event.'' It went on to point out areas where both agree,
including ``their absolute commitment to JAMA's editorial
integrity, independence and excellence.'' And it called Lundberg's
career ``distinguished and invaluable,'' adding that ``the AMA and
Dr. Lundberg have now resolved their substantive differences.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a dramatic change in tone from the AMA's statements
last month, when Anderson said Lundberg had ``threatened the
historic tradition and integrity'' of JAMA.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's statement was just one in a series of steps the
association has taken to end the controversy. Last week it named a
committee of health leaders who will help choose a new JAMA editor,
although that announcement was somewhat overshadowed when a member
of JAMA's editorial board _ Dr. Donald Lindberg, director of the
National Library of Medicine _ resigned in protest over Lundberg's
firing. Thursday Anderson is due to address the controversy in a
special meeting of the AMA staff at a Chicago hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It will take more than that, however, to win back many of those
alienated by the AMA's interference with its respected medical
journal, said one well known Boston physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fan of the AMA, but I have been a fan of JAMA and I
have felt there was a nonpermeable wall between the two,'' said Dr.
Thomas Delbanco, head of general medicine and primary care at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston and editor of a monthly
column in JAMA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a wall between the two, and it was called editoral
independence. Unless that were restored beyond just nice words, I
don't see how anyone in good conscience could serve on a search
committee for the successor to Dr. Lundberg.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
