A0737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTOS-PRIVACY-NYT     02-03 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTOS-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 STATES CANCEL PLANS TO SELL DRIVERS LICENSE PHOTOGRAPHS TO
DATABASE CONCERN 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: S.C., N.H., Colo., Fla.)  By LISA NAPOLI   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A private company's effort to buy driver's license photographs
and place them in an electronic database has raised privacy
concerns, prompting three states to backtrack on their decision to
sell the data.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Image Data of Nashua, N.H., manufactures a
fraud-protection device that allows store clerks to verify the
identity of a consumer using a driver's license number or Social
Security number to call up a digital photograph. The device is
currently being tested in 10 stores in South Carolina, which sold
Image Data digital records of 3.5 million drivers licenses last
year for $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   But after news reports of the sales, officials in South
Carolina, along with those in Colorado and Florida, moved to halt
the transfer of data to the company.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, the attorney general, Charlie Condon, will
appear in court Thursday morning to ask for a temporary injunction
to halt the use of the photos. Ten stores across the state have
been wired with Image Data's True ID security device since last
August.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Condon's office explained that state officials
only recently became aware of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lawsuit asks for the photos back because the budget
proviso that allowed the sale was unconstitutional,'' said Robb
McBurney, Condons spokesman. ``At the last minute you can stick in
a lot of things with a budget proviso, and this got in in 1998 with
no public scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado and Florida had signed contracts with the company, but
Colorado has not yet delivered data. On Monday, Gov. Jeb Bush of
Florida terminated the states contract with Image Data, after a
temporary injunction blocking the transfer of images was issued by
a Seminole County judge. Prior to the injunction, Florida had
released 35,000 of the states 14 million drivers license records to
the company, and had been paid $140,000 by Image Data for all of
the records.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Colorado State Sen. Tony Grampsas introduced
legislation to repeal a bill he had introduced in the Colorado
House of Representatives two years ago to allow the sale of the
states drivers license records to Image Data. Gov. Bill Owens
lobbied for the repeal on Tuesday after the sale of the photographs
became public last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became apparent the public wasn't going to buy off on it,''
said Dick Wadhams, press secretary for the governor. ``Even though
it was Super Bowl weekend, a lot of legislators got hammered pretty
hard by their constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Christie, vice president of public affairs for Image Data,
called the public outcry surrounding True ID a
``misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   When a digital image is called up by a store clerk, it only
stays visible ``for seconds,'' Ms. Christie said. No other personal
information is displayed on the LCD screen, she said, nor can the
clerk operating the device capture any of the data. Transmissions
between Image Data's computers and the retail store are encrypted,
she said, to inhibit wiretapping of private information.
</P>
<P>
   Though the device is built for check identification purposes,
Ms. Christie said it could be expanded to verify credit card
purchases as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a misperception that we were selling our database to
retailers,'' said Ms. Christie. ``We are using technology to
protect customers. Our use of the information is only for identity
purposes, not for marketing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1944EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
