A0741 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BAXTER04-COX     02-03 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BAXTER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate trial needs a deft Dickens wrap-up
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Since White House lawyer David Kendall evoked his
name last week on the Senate floor, it has been impossible to
dislodge the image of Mr. Micawber, hat askew, looking down grandly
from the gallery on the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   This story has had Charles Dickens' touch all along. Only he
would have been brash enough to name a deceitful friend Tripp and a
lowlife reporter Drudge. Kendall himself, reed-thin and acerbic,
could be one of those Chancery lawyers in ``Bleak House,'' droning
away endlessly over Jarndyce vs. Jarndyce.
</P>
<P>
   The story badly needs the author's services now. Dickens wrote
his novels, just as the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal has unfolded, in
weekly magazine installments that twisted plots this way and that,
accumulating characters by the dozens. The more bankable side of
Dickens' genius was his ability to sense when his public had read
enough, knit all the plot threads back together and account for all
the characters in a grand concluding chapter.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has set itself on schedule to bring the trial to a
close by Feb. 12, but wrapping up the loose ends will be, well, a
Dickens of a job.
</P>
<P>
   Neither ``adjournment-plus,'' Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch's
suggestion, nor the ``finding of fact'' idea offered by Maine's
senators, Susan Collins and Olympia Snowe, is likely to leave all
the sides in this serial with an agreeable sense of closure.
</P>
<P>
   Even before they vote, the senators, who include several genuine
war heros in their number, have had their courage questioned by the
increasingly entrenched House Republicans. House Judiciary Chairman
Henry Hyde last week said he was glad the senators who wanted a
short list of witnesses weren't at Valley Forge or the Alamo, and
Rep. Jack Kingston of Georgia this week branded them a ``Senate of
cowards'' for hurrying to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   It seems very shrill for Republican House members, who only had
to vote on impeachment and often run in safely drawn districts, to
speak this way of the senators, who face a far more difficult vote
on removal from office and the much more daunting challenge of
running statewide, in races more likely to reflect the national
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican senators are trying to find a twist that will
reconcile the demands of their House colleagues with the demands of
a public that overwhelmingly wants this story to conclude _ a hard
job for the best novelist.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall brought up Micawber, who was ``always waiting for
something to turn up,'' simply to draw scathing comparison to the
House managers' strategy in calling for witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Like all great characters, however, the debt-ridden but
bombastic gentleman from ``David Copperfield'' finds his own seat
in the imagination, and seems no more out of place at this trial
than Paul Coverdell or Max Cleland.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, re-reading ``David Copperfield,'' might see a lot
of Bill Clinton in the duplicitous James Steerforth, the charming
climber whose real ambition is to ``ride over all obstacles and win
the race.''
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat would be more likely to see the president in the
book's title character, who grows into an able man with the
``undisciplined heart'' of a fatherless child. But Micawber _ the
well-meaning but ineffectual family man, who composes messages to
Parliament from debtor's prison, a credit risk who becomes a
magistrate in the end _ is the type of fellow who could be sitting
on either side of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
