<HEADLINE>
GM DISAPPOINTED BY JANUARY SALES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
(dal) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ As many of its competitors reported double-digit sales
increases, the General Motors Corp. said Wednesday that January
sales rose a scant 4 percent compared with exceptionally weak sales
in the month a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed in the January results,'' said Michael
DiGiovanni, GM's chief forecaster. ``But we're optimistic going
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   GM reported sales of 308,880 cars and light trucks in January, a
4 percent increase compared with sales in the month a year earlier,
which were off 6 percent from January 1997 and thus not especially
tough to beat. Sales industrywide were up nearly 12 percent last
month.
</P>
<P>
   GM's car sales rose 11.4 percent, to 166,970 vehicles. Gains
came largely from GM's newer midsized cars. In other market
segments, sales of Cadillac's flagship Seville, which hit the
market in January 1998, climbed 21 percent, and Saab, buoyed by its
new top-of-the-line 9-5, had its best January in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   However, GM's truck sales dropped 3.7 percent, to 141,910. Ford
far outsold GM, and DaimlerChrysler nearly matched it in truck
sales. GM continues to be plagued by inventory shortages,
particularly of its new full-size Chevrolet Silverado and GMC
Sierra full-size pickup trucks, in the aftermath of last summer's
two-month strike, which shut down almost all of GM's North American
assembly plants. Sales of the two trucks combined rose 3 percent in
January, but their inventory levels remain 44 percent below last
year's level.
</P>
<P>
   Shortages of the Sierra were compounded in November when a die
for the hood broke, halting production and costing about 4,000
Sierra sales in January alone, GM officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Silverado and Sierra sales could be better with more
availability,'' said Donald R. DeVeaux, GM director for North
American market analysis. ``They are turning well at dealerships.
It's a matter of how fast we can get them out there and sell
them.''
</P>
<P>
   GM plans to add 250,000 units of truck production this year,
including new full-size sport-utility vehicles to replace the
Chevrolet Tahoe, GMC Yukon and Chevrolet and GMC Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of GM were unchanged yesterday at $89.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors worked against GM last month. On Jan. 1, GM began
revamping its field organization, which assists dealers. Some
personnel were not in place by Jan. 1. In conjunction with the
reorganization, GM installed a new computer system for dealers
ordering vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Also in January, Cadillac paid for its December sales surge,
with sales off 38 percent compared with those in the month a year
earlier. Cadillac offered a lot of incentives in December to
maintain luxury car leadership over the Ford Motor Co.'s Lincoln
division. Heading into December, Cadillac risked losing its 60-year
sales reign over Lincoln, but ended the year just ahead of its
rival.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sales of the Catera were off 88 percent in January
because Cadillac had been unable to sell the 1999 German-built
cars. The car's engine-management system had been changed for the
1999 model year but had quality problems. The 1999 Catera began
arriving at dealerships at the end of January. Production of
Cadillac's new full-size sport utility vehicle, the Escalade, which
just went on sale last fall, also was halted because of a tooling
change at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its problems, GM missed out on a blistering sales
pace for the industry, which spilled over into the new year from
1998. U.S. vehicle sales for January totaled 1,090,950 cars and
light trucks, an 11.6 percent increase compared with sales in the
month a year earlier. Car sales totaled 546,030 units, up 8
percent, and truck sales increased 15.4 percent, to 544,920
vehicles. That put the seasonally adjusted annual selling rate for
light vehicles at 15.6 million cars and light trucks for January.
</P>
<P>
   GM's forecasters agree with many analysts who see a continued
strong automotive market. GM is considering increasing its industry
sales forecast for 1999. GM opened the year expecting 1999 sales of
all trucks and cars to total between 15 million and 15.5 million in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously moving to the upper end of that range,''
DiGiovanni said.
</P>
</TEXT>
