<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PREMIER BEGINS CRACKDOWN ON CORRUPTION IN GOVERNMENT AND
BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's top prosecutor suddenly resigns, officially
for health reasons, although no one believes that. A former justice
minister, out of office for two years, is arrested on charges of
fraud and embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
   Then police on Wednesday night confirmed that they had found
evidence of illegal wiretapping during a city-wide raid of offices
and apartments linked to Boris A. Berezovsky, Russia's best-known
businessman, ace political intriguer and the most public target of
what seems to be Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's opening shot in
a crackdown on economic crime and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov had already sent out a warning signal last week when he
said that an amnesty of 94,000 Russian prisoners would free up the
cells needed to house an incoming wave of corrupt officials and
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   But as Berezovsky noted in a public response, economic crimes
are a malleable offense that can be easily twisted to political
purpose. Berezovsky, who has openly boasted about his role in
making and breaking successive Russian political fortunes, has
already seen the Primakov government methodically chip away at his
power base, starting with an attempt to push him out of Russia's
largest television station, now virtually bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did he call on Primakov to cool his threats than armed
federal agents in black ski masks this week swooped through the
offices of Sibneft, a Berezovsky-controlled oil company, and Atoll,
a Berezovsky-controlled security company. Atoll has been accused of
serving as Berezovsky's private intelligence agency, secretly
spying on top Russian officials and even members of Russian
President Boris Yeltsin's own family.
</P>
<P>
   The raids _ widely seen as the final blow to Berezovsky's
dwindling prestige and influence _ took place Tuesday, the day that
Yeltsin accepted the resignation of chief prosecutor Yuri Skuratov.
It was also the same day that Yeltsin, still convalescing from a
bleeding ulcer, unexpectedly made a brief appearance in the Kremlin
_ his first this year _ where, in keeping with past practice, he
promptly fired four of his own aides.
</P>
<P>
   If, as some believe, the events are linked, then they suggest
that Russia is again undergoing another bout of old-style political
intrigue, which, as one Soviet expert once said, is as difficult to
decipher as a wrestling match under a rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``To outside observers, all this smells of deep medieval
political barbarity, thickly mixed with an uncivilized reckoning of
accounts between opponents,'' noted a political commentator for
Nezavisimaya Gazeta, a newspaper with close ties to Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   In private conservations, Kremlin aides acknowledged that there
was more to Skuratov's abrupt exit than a bad heart, the ailment
with which he was admitted Monday night to the Kremlin hospital.
They said Yeltsin's displeasure had been a long time building,
first over Skuratov's failure to bring Russia's most publicized
crimes to trial and, more recently, over his failure to move
against Russia's outspoken neo-fascist and anti-Semitic
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a sudden phenomenon,'' said one Kremlin aide. ``It
was a sum of all the cases, several of them important, that were
not solved.'' The prosecutor's foot-dragging in bringing a case
against Albert Makashov, the Communist lawmaker who last October
publicly called for Jews to be driven from Russia, was linked to
the resurgence last weekend of a small splinter neo-fascist group
in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Although Skuratov has not solved any of Russia's more notorious
murders _ including the killing of Galina Staravoitova, a widely
respected liberal legislator from St. Petersburg _ he did recently
launch well-publicized investigations into the former leadership at
Russia's Central Bank and into some of Russia's biggest privatized
companies, earning himself enemies among liberal reformers and
friends among Russia's Communists.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow or other, the most prevalent theories about his
resignation seem to revolve around Berezovsky, whose political
influence stems in large part from the fact _ or the illusion _
that he has close ties to Yeltsin's family, in particular Tatiana
Dyachenko, the president's daughter and political adviser.
</P>
<P>
   According to one version, Skuratov, fearing Berezovsky's
influence, had dawdled over the investigation into Berezovsky's
wire-tapping operations, even after they were publicly revealed in
a newspaper article. According to another, contradictory version,
his attempts to investigate Berezovsky alarmed Yeltsin, who has
reasons to want to stop any leaks about evidence of his family's
financial dealings that might be in Berezovsky's possession.
</P>
<P>
   But others believe that the real driving force behind Skuratov's
ouster may have been Primakov, who, after four months in office,
wants to make headway on his threats to crack down on corruption.
As if to illustrate the government's new vigor, the interior
ministry on Wednesday night announced that it had arrested former
Justice Minister Valentin Kovalyov on charges of embezzlement, two
years after he resigned from office under the cloud of a sex
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   At an assembly of law enforcement officials that was to have
been addressed by Skuratov on Wednesday, the acting prosecutor
general Yuri Chaika said that the scale of corruption among Russian
bureaucrats had reached unprecedented levels, with Russia now
ranked as the fifth most corrupt country on earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
