<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-AMERICANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN ORDERS AMERICAN, BRITISH WORKERS TO LEAVE IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Buckling under pressure from Baghdad, the
United Nations ordered a pullout Wednesday of all American and
British UN employees in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, approved by Secretary General Kofi Annan, brings
an end to Iraq's yearlong campaign to expel citizens from Western
nations seeking to topple Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as the Pentagon has expanded attacks against Iraqi
antiaircraft systems.
</P>
<P>
   UN officials said Wednesday that the two remaining American
citizens _ Darlene Bisson, the deputy director for the World Food
Program in Iraq, and the secretary of the chief UN envoy to Iraq,
Prakash Shah, are expected to leave the country in the coming days.
All of Britain's nationals have left.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Eckhard, Annan's chief spokesman, said UN security chief
Benon Sevan ordered the evacuation after Iraq ignored a series of
appeals to allow all UN staffers to carry out the UN's efforts to
provide humanitarian relief to the country's poor. He added that
Iraq also issued unspecified ``threats'' against the two Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The specific threats were to these two nationalities so it was
the security coordinator's call,'' Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has long charged Washington and London with planting
intelligence agents in the UN mission in Iraq to spy on the
government. The accusation has been given weight by recent
revelations that the United States used the UN weapons inspectors
to spy on Iraqi security agencies in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi leadership first demanded the expulsion of American
and British weapons experts seeking to rid Iraq of chemical and
biological weapons in the fall of 1997. But the executive chairman,
Richard Butler of Australia, refused, insisting that Iraq did not
have the right to single out nationals. The United States and
Britain vigorously backed that stance.
</P>
<P>
   Butler finally withdrew the whole team of inspectors on the eve
of US airstrikes in December.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart insisted that the decision to
pull out the Americans was not a prelude to a fresh bombing
campaign in Baghdad. And he expressed sympathy with the UN's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   UN officials said Americans have been singled out in other
countries, including North Korea, where the World Food Program only
recently was allowed to post its first senior American official,
Douglas Broderick. They said that the relief effort in Iraq would
continue despite the expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has more than 400 relief workers in Iraq
providing food and medicines to the countries poorest. The
operation is financed by the oil-for-food deal, which allows
Baghdad to sell more than $10 billion in oil over one year to buy
humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has withdrawn more than a dozen American and
British nationals serving with the United Nations. UN sources
insist that the British and departed American employees left on
vacation and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we need to stay to save lives,'' said
Abby Spring, a spokeswoman for the World Food Program. ``Otherwise,
250,000 children with malnutrition would probably have to die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 1951EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0748 &Cx1f; taf-z
