A0752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-FILM-DOCUMENTAR     02-03 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FILM-DOCUMENTARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A FILM ABOUT WINNING A TRUCK? YES, BUT MORE.
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounds like a terrible idea for a documentary: film two dozen
people in East Texas standing around a brand-new pickup truck,
trying to win it by keeping one hand on the truck and doing almost
nothing else for 70 hours or more. The rules promise no big-screen
excitement: ``5-minute breaks every hour, 15-minute breaks every
six hours, no leaning, the last person left with a hand on the
truck owns it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when aspiring filmmaker S.R. Bindler walked out of a bar in
his hometown of Longview, Texas, in 1992 and saw the final,
grueling hours of the contest in the parking lot of a local auto
dealership, he could not shake the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was truly surreal,'' he recalled recently. ``It was the
middle of the night, and these bright tungsten lights made it look
like daytime. It looked like a movie set. At the time, I didn't
know what to think about it, but I couldn't quit thinking about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And as it turned out, Bindler never did. He returned to Longview
in 1995 with two young friends who had studied filmmaking with him
at New York University. With little more than local high-school
volunteers, borrowed video equipment, a vague idea and a free place
to stay _ with Bindler's parents _ they made a crude, funny and
sometimes harrowing 97-minute documentary about the contest. The
film has been quietly building a following and received glowing
reviews around the country over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Without the help of a major Hollywood distributor, the film,
``Hands on a Hard Body,'' which Bindler directed, has opened in
several cities and has picked up a handful of audience awards and
other prizes at small film festivals. (It opens Friday in Chicago
and New York.)
</P>
<P>
   A critic for Philadelphia Weekly recently wrote that the film
has done ``for Longview, Texas, what the Coen Brothers did for
Fargo, N.D.'' In Fort Lauderdale, Fla., a reviewer said it managed
to drape the mind- and body-numbing quest for a $15,000 Nissan
Hardbody truck with all the ``moral trappings of Greek drama.'' In
Austin, Texas, the film has filled a theater for 30 weeks and shows
no signs of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   Bindler, 28, now lives in Los Angeles, where he has received
offers to direct small feature films as a result of the
documentary's success. But over breakfast last week in New York's
Soho, near where he is staying with a friend while in town
promoting the movie, he said he was still a little stunned by the
response. After all, the film's budget was only slightly more than
the cost of the new truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it takes people into a mind-set and to a place that
they normally couldn't go,'' he said. ``We always thought that
people in Texas would watch it and go: `I know this. I know people
like this. It's fun.' But we didn't know how people from the rest
of the country would react.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, for some, inevitably conjures up ``They Shoot Horses,
Don't They?,'' the 1969 movie by Sydney Pollack that used a
seemingly endless dance marathon as a metaphor for greed and
sensationalism during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   In Longview, a blue-collar oil town with 70,000 people, many of
the hopeful men and women who were chosen in a drawing to
participate in the 1995 competition did not simply want the truck.
They needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Welch, a rancher, had been forced to sell his only good
truck after a bad winter. Kerri Parker, who was then a bartender,
was unable to afford a car and rode her bicycle 12 miles a day to
put her name repeatedly into the drawing. Another contestant, Kelli
Mangrum, who loaded trucks for the United Parcel Service, explained
how she would ready herself to remain on her feet for days for the
contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm going to have to do,'' she told herself, ``is realize
that if I don't get it, I'm going to have to get another job. And I
don't want another job.''
</P>
<P>
   But the movie _ shot in a shaky freehand that gets shakier as
both contestants and filmmakers crumble from lack of sleep _ tends
to concentrate more on the funny and quietly heroic moments, as
homespun philosophies get tested and unlikely friendships form
across the pickup bed.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Valverde, a fervently religious homemaker who sold her
pickup before the contest because, she said, she believed it was
God's will that she would win a new one, kept herself motivated by
listening to Christian music. She often broke out in spasms of
laughter and whooping.
</P>
<P>
   Across the truck, a gangly, frenetic young man who wanted to
replace his old Volkswagen Beetle so he could stop feeling ``like
an oddball'' told the filmmakers that he admired Ms. Valverde.
``She started to laugh a while ago, and she said it was the Holy
Ghost,'' he said, swaying on his feet. ``I thought that was pretty
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie also spends a lot of time examining, through the eyes
of the contestants, the exalted position of the pickup truck in the
Texas value system. Ronald McCowan, a maintenance man, said: ``A
truck makes money. A car don't make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Benny Perkins, a swaggering, wisecracking mechanic who emerged
as a kind of star of the movie, added that in Texas ``you just grow
up saying: `Eventually, you're going to own a truck. Eventually,
you're going to need a truck.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, who had won the competition in 1992, proved to be what
Bindler called ``a moviemaker's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins provided a virtual voice-over for the movie, dispensing
discount wisdom in his cigarette-scarred baritone, warning against
eating hamburger during breaks: ``Eat something heavy like that,
and it's going to take you down.'' He explored the more profound
implications of the competition: ``It's a human drama thing. It's
more than just a contest. It's more than just winning the truck.''
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of the movie, in fact, the dramatic tension came
not from the question ``Who will make it to the end?'' but ``Can
they beat Benny?''
</P>
<P>
   Bindler _ whose parents grew up in Texas and met at the
University of Texas in Austin, where they both studied art and
became interior designers _ admitted that he had never owned a
truck.
</P>
<P>
   When he and his friends, Michael Nickles and Chapin Wilson,
finished shooting the documentary, Bindler returned to Los Angeles,
where he had worked as what he called an office boy for another
friend, Kevin Morris, a successful entertainment lawyer who is one
of the film's producers.
</P>
<P>
   Morris and Bindler at first made a short trailer of their film.
``People saw it, and they didn't know what to make of it,'' Bindler
said.
</P>
<P>
   So Bindler went back to Longview and moved in with his parents
to try to edit the movie. In Longview, he borrowed an old editing
machine in the back room of a church. When that broke down, he
bartered to get the use of another machine at night, and finished
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The only real Hollywood help the filmmakers received was at the
end of the project, when they needed money to transfer the edited
video to film in order to enter film festivals. It was at this
point that Longview's most prominent native son, actor Matthew
McConaughey, a childhood friend of Bindler's, came through with a
check.
</P>
<P>
   Bindler said he had made little money so far from the movie. But
he spent what he has made to replace his worn-out car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what I got because it's too embarrassing,''
he said. ``Kind of a wimp car. I went to go buy a truck, is what I
did. But I couldn't find one for under $10,000 that was worth a
damn. I guess I should have known that, right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
