<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT &LR;      02-03 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE FORK IN THE ROAD OF IMPEACHMENT  
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-OPEN, IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL,
IMPEACH-BORK) 
(dal) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There is a whiff of bipartisanship in their
exasperation, at least, as the Republicans and Democrats of the
Senate impeachment court wend their way to their fifth week of
judgment, stolid as parents peppered endlessly at the wheel by the
waif-like plea of constituents: Are we there yet?
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the answer to that question was, well not yet, but
we'll finally be getting really close once we make a choice at this
fork in the road that points to either ``Findings of Fact'' or
``Censure.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators in both parties labored to polish comprehensible
sound-bites to explain this latest confusing fork in their trial
meanderings to cranky back-seat constituents who long ago gave up
counting brindled cows and other ballyhooed phenomena on their way
to the widely anticipated destination of Acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking it's Ground Hog Day,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa, sympathizing with puzzled constituents. ``I feel like Bill
Murray,'' he said of the actor in the movie about endless
repetitions of predictable events. ``I just keep doing this over
and over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   In the corridor outside the Senate, Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill.,
struggled with the problem of explaining to the people why
Democrats prefer condemning the president's misbehavior by
legislative censure after the trial, while Republicans hope to vote
a finding of facts to condemn him as a court during the trial
despite the expected acquittal. ``It's tough to explain to the
American people why we're even in trial, let alone why we're
considering `findings of fact,' '' he said somewhat dispiritedly.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were similarly caught up in the need to explain such
arcane disputes within a trying ordeal to constituents impatient
for a plain ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an overwhelming feeling of sadness that we've got
ourselves in this mess,'' said Sen. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt.,
striking a bipartisan note of melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as the last deposition witness emerged from the
security-tight testimony room in the Capitol attic, some senators
sampled the two earlier videotaped depositions. But most gravitated
to separate party caucuses intent on seeking workable if not
elegant endgame strategems. The trial was in recess until Thursday.
The corridor crossfire was muted, with ``cockamamie'' the most
interesting partisan epithet of the day, used by a smiling
Democrat, then a mildly amused Republican in rebuttal, as they
paused at the trial fork to either Censure or Findings of Fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of hearing myself answering questions,'' Sen. John
B. Breaux, D-La., said apologetically after delivering a riff of
anti-Republican sound bites on the issue. ``I can't make them sound
different, more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   He let out a low yowling sound in the corridor when asked if he
sensed some tedium in the trial. ``Aaargh! A sense of weariness, a
sense of exhaustion!'' he corrected as he offered a crazed grin in
moving on.
</P>
<P>
   There was naked delight from some Democrats that the Republican
majority must gingerly try to manage an end to the trial that
serves history, soothes the zealous Republican prosecutors, and
entices enough Democrats aboard to seem a bipartisan deliverance to
the public. ``They must reach across the aisle,'' said Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., straight-faced as a cat waiting outside a
mousehole. ``This is more of us trying to save them from
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   One genuine bipartisan note was general agreement in the
corridors that Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., had bombed Tuesday
night in attempting political humor at a showcase dinner of
Congress and the news media. Republicans sat steaming as he tried
to needle them with a bludgeon. But on Wednesday Schumer seemed
invincible as ever as he estimated the chances of the trial ending
on some sort of a bipartisan note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been almost a Cassandra saying in the caucus that this
always unravels out of control,'' said the freshman senator who
fought in the House impeachment trenches last year. ``Now, I'm more
optimistic than I've ever been that this could end by the 12th,''
he said of the Senate's target date for deciding whether to remove
President Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   For that schedule, the journey must move beyond what is being
called its ``bolt-of-lightning'' phase, by which a fresh round of
witnesses or evidence could be sought, but only if the two party
leaders concurred. This seems unlikely, but only as unlikely as a
bolt of lightning hitting the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Before that juncture, there remains the turn to either Findings
of Fact or Censure, and the senators' continuing struggle to draw a
meaningful distinction between the two for constituents wondering
where the end is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't finding-of-fact, it's finding-of-fiction,'' Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy declared spur of the moment Wednesday morning in
dismissing the Republicans' preferred route to a small group of
news workers who cornered him by an elevator. The senator himself
brightened at the simple coinage he had just wrought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you say it around the corner at the television mikes?''
he was asked by a producer who thought the line had legs, at least
for a news cycle that needed fresh traction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' said the senator, trying out the line one more time in
the corridor, then opening with it on camera as the impeachment
trial moved along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
