<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ The Senate braces for a struggle
over whether to have former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
testify at the impeachment trial of President Clinton _ in person
or on videotape. The White House, meanwhile, tries to forestall
personal testimony by the former White House intern by embracing
admission of her entire videotaped testimony rather than having
House prosecutors present excerpts to the 100 senators. By STEWART
M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND And DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ White House aide Sidney
Blumenthal completes his testimony before congressional
investigators in the Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton.
Blumenthal is the third and final witness to go before House
prosecutors in the private interviews. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON-TROOPS (Washington) _ Defense Secretary William Cohen
tells the Senate Armed Services Committee that the United States
could send up to 4,000 troops into the Serbian province of Kosovo
to help keep peace. But the deployment is contingent upon European
efforts to seal a peace agreement into the tense region. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KINGSBURY-SMITH-OBIT (Washington) _ Joseph Kingsbury-Smith, a
Pulitzer-prize winning journalist and former national editor of the
Hearst Newspapers, died Wednesday at his Virginia home. He was 90
years old. As a journalist, he interviewed most of the contemporary
world's great leaders and was widely acclaimed for his achievements
in the field of diplomacy. By The Hearst Newspapers. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ELUSIVE-SHERIFF (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Tarrant County Sheriff
David Williams' routine absence is not cause for alarm. Few
officials here have had more than a moment's contact with the
sheriff in more than six months. Nor does anyone seem to have a
clear answer to the question of why the sheriff of the Texas'
fourth largest county would become one of the state's most elusive
public officials. By EVAN MOORE.
</P>
<P>
   FREEZER-MURDER (San Augustine, Texas) _ Testimony begins in the
murder trial of Bernie Tiede, who is accused of shooting an
81-year-old woman to death and hiding her body in a freezer. By
ALLAN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   49ERS-STADIUM (San Francisco) _ A builder working on the
expansion of the San Francisco International Airport says he can
construct a stadium for the 49ers football team for $250 million _
as much as half as the current proposal. The stadium project, a
partnership between the team and the city, has been on hold because
of the cost and other problems. By CHUCK FINNIE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Henry Hyde and his colleagues
keep repeating that the ``rule of law'' should be the deciding
factor in the Clinton impeachment case. But the president's
defenders also have a potent argument, that while his behavior was
despicable, his crimes never threatened the government. This is the
strange dichotomy that bestrides our nation. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
(Already filed.)
</P>
