   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Top center: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOREST-SERVICE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration,
determined to emphasize conservation over development on public
lands, called Wednesday for a mining ban in a vast section of
federal land in Montana. The move would significantly expand
protections along the Rocky Mountain Front, at the edge of one of
the richest wilderness zones in the lower 48 states. It also is the
latest round in a long-running fight between the administration and
the mining industry, as well as between the administration and
Congress, which has blocked attempts to toughen mining regulations
administratively. By John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARAFAT (Gaza City, Gaza Strip) _ Suha Arafat, the first lady of
the Palestinian territories, would seem an unlikely partner for the
69-year-old revolutionary, who remains forever wedded to his cause.
She was raised in a well-off home in the West Bank, educated by
nuns and refined at the Sorbonne. And her deep-seated Christian
faith and Western assertiveness seem at odds with his world:
desperate Gaza with its veiled Muslim women. But in ideology Mrs.
Arafat, whose husband is to meet on Thursday with President Clinton
in Washington, is every bit the fiery Palestinian freedom fighter.
By Deborah Sontag. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
