   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-OPEN (Washington) _ Momentum is building in the Senate
to change its 19th-century impeachment rules and allow public
viewing of the final deliberations on whether to remove President
Clinton from office. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-TV-INTERNET (Washington) _ As AT&AMP;T completes two large
business deals _ a merger with one large cable company and a joint
venture with another _ that will give it access to the cable lines
into almost half of the nation's homes, a ferocious
multi-million-dollar legal and lobbying battle is taking shape in
Washington and in cities around the nation over the future of the
Internet. The fight, which is being led by America Online, the
nation's largest internet service provider with 15 million
customers, has drawn many of Washington's most prominent former
officials who are now lobbyists. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 8:30 p.m. ET in `f' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS (Undated) _ Angry about declining incomes and being
dictated to by managed-care organizations, doctors are joining
labor unions in record numbers, hoping for a more powerful voice to
counter what many call the corporatization of medicine. By Steven
Greenhouse. With photo.
</P>
