</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-IRS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Organization with close links to Gingrich did not violate tax
laws, IRS finds
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Washington-based think tank with close ties to
former House Speaker Newt Gingrich did not violate its tax-exempt
status by helping him finance a college course at two Georgia
schools, the Internal Revenue Service has concluded in an audit.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year investigation of the Progress and Freedom
Foundation was ``a close case'' because of Gingrich's involvement
in Renewing American Civilization, the college course he taught at
Kennesaw State University and Reinhardt College, according to the
IRS' audit letter, formally known as a technical advice memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency eventually concluded that the foundation ``did
not serve the private interests of Mr. Gingrich, GOPAC (his
one-time political organization), and Republican entities.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax-exempt charitable organizations like Progress and Freedom
may not take part in partisan political activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about as utter, complete and comprehensive a vindication
as I could hope for,'' said Jeffrey Eisenach, the foundation's
president and a longtime Gingrich adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation made a copy of the audit letter available
Wednesday via the Internet. IRS spokesman Dan Roberts would not
confirm or deny the existence of the audit or its outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But Roberts said that a technical advice memorandum is issued by
IRS headquarters when an auditor in a field office requests an
``authoritative interpretation'' of tax law.
</P>
<P>
   The audit resulted from a 14-month House ethics committee
investigation of the links between the college course and GOPAC.
</P>
<P>
   James Cole, the special counsel appointed to direct the
investigation, concluded that Gingrich's use of charitable
organizations to finance his political activities violated federal
tax law.
</P>
<P>
   Cole concluded that donors who wanted to support GOPAC made
charitable contributions to ALOF, which then funneled the money to
GOPAC. In this way, the donors could claim tax deductions.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics committee was less certain and referred Cole's
findings to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The committee determined that Gingrich had violated House ethics
rules for other reasons, and the House eventually imposed a
$300,000 sanction on the speaker and reprimanded him.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS apparently is continuing to investigate the Abraham
Lincoln Opportunity Foundation, another charitable organization
implicated by Cole. Howard ``Bo'' Calloway, the former Georgia
congressman and ALOF director, said he has not received a similar
clearance letter from the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
