<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NHAMP-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE URGES CONGRESS TO LISTEN TO PUBLIC ON IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ It's time for Congress to take its cue from the
America public on the impeachment trial of President Clinton, Vice
President Al Gore said Wednesday during a trip to New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to a new New York Times/CBS News poll showing an
impeachment-weary majority of Americans wants the trial to conclude
swiftly, and without the removal of the president, Gore issued one
of his strongest statements yet on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the country has long since come to the conclusion that
all of those in Washington who have been concentrating on partisan
political agendas should instead concentrate on the people's
business,'' the vice president said in an interview with the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I sense that we are nearing an end to the long
ordeal, and I certainly hope the Republican leadership in the
Congress will start listening to the desires of the American people
and shift their focus to what really matters most to the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked whether he thought the Senate should take any
disciplinary action at all against Clinton, Gore declined to
specify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to leave that for the Senate,'' Gore said. ``I have
had confidence they will end up doing the right thing, because in
my view none of the offenses that are alleged rise to the level of
offense justifying removal from office.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was clear, however, on those issues he
thought Congress should focus on rather than impeachment, including
making college more affordable the improving the quality of
education at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   And on a trip billed as official government business, but with
campaign themes, Gore took his own advice for much of the day,
engaging in detailed policy discussion while dancing delicately
around most political queries.
</P>
<P>
   He had little to say of the House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt's decision not to run for president, saying he wanted to
defer to Gephardt, who didn't make his plans official until later
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gore did vow that he and Gephardt ``will work closely
together in whatever capacity to win back Democratic control of the
House of Representatives next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Gore supporters and aides were more optimistic, saying they
hoped to gain Gephardt's support and were confident that, at the
least, the minority leader would not support another candidate over
the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   So far Gore has only one other rival for the Democratic
nomination: former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley, who has formed
an exploratory presidential campaign committee. Wednesday, Gore
refused to speculate about a possible presidential candidacy by
Massachusetts Senator John F. Kerry, who has long been mulling a
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is an extremely able public servant with an expansive
vision of this country's future,'' Gore said. ``Whatever decision
he makes, he will make a strong contribution to the future of this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   He was similarly circumspect about Boston's chances of beating
Denver and Los Angeles in the competition to host the 2000
Democratic National Convention. Boston had ``made a wonderful and
strong bid,'' Gore said, but offered no further hints about which
city he favored or felt would be chosen.
</P>
<P>
   In his public events, Gore, making his 14th trip to New
Hampshire since 1994, repeatedly underscored how much the Granite
State economy has improved since the Clinton administration came to
office.
</P>
<P>
   A state that had been losing 10,000 jobs a year in 1992 is now
adding 12,000 each year, said Gore, who claimed New Hampshire now
has ``the highest concentration of high-tech jobs in the entire
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   That boom in high-tech jobs, with their demand for skilled
workers, is one reason why lifelong learning opportunities are so
important, Gore stressed in stops at New Hampshire Community
Technical College in Nashua and PC Connection, a skyrocketing
computer company in Merrimack.
</P>
<P>
   So do the issues the vice president touted in Wednesday's
tightly focused trip offer an intellectual framework for a Gore
2000 campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Aides said yes. But Gore was characteristically cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past is always prologue, so in that sense whatever we are
doing that is succesful in New Hampshire should be taken as a
framework for future progress in New Hampshire,'' he told the
Globe. ``But I don't want to put it in a political context because
it is still 1999 and the election is in 2000.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
