</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYEAR-SUMITOMO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODYEAR AND SUMITOMO PLAN HUGE JOINT VENTURE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ohio, Ala.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Also see sidebar, GOODYEAR-JAPAN) 
(bl) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. and Sumitomo Rubber Industries Ltd.
said Wednesday they would combine many of their plants and sales
operations into a huge joint venture with annual sales of about
$15.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, which will be the controlling partner, will pay
Sumitomo about $936 million for the assets it contributes. And, the
two companies will swap about $110 million in stock, giving
Goodyear 10 percent of Sumitomo, and giving Sumitomo a 1.4 percent
stake in Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which had been expected, gives Goodyear access to
Sumitomo's Dunlop brand and a toehold in Japan. It also catapults
Goodyear to the No. 1 spot in the world tire market in terms of
sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal is eliciting big yawns from Michelin Group of
France and Bridgestone Corp. of Japan, the two companies the new
venture will jump over. Executives at those companies noted that
Goodyear and Sumitomo have cooperated in manufacturing and sales
ventures for two years now. And, with the consolidation in the tire
industry, it was only a question of what order the smaller players
like Sumitomo, Continental General and Perelli would get snapped
up, not whether any of them would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was predictable and logical, and it doesn't change the
balance of power at all,'' said Etienne Mercier, a spokesman for
Michelin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not adding capacity, they're changing the name on the
door,'' said John Lampe, the president of Bridgestone's U.S. unit.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the joint venture may not change the competitive
landscape much in the short term. Sumitomo ranks fifth in worldwide
tire sales. Bridgestone, Michelin and Goodyear together command
more than half of worldwide tire sales, but they have always been
within a percentage point or two of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear is the dominant player in the United States, and
attaining 75 percent ownership of Sumitomo's U.S. plants will not
change that. In Europe, where Sumitomo and Goodyear each do about
$2 billion in annual tire sales, the venture will push past
Bridgestone in share, but Michelin still reins supreme.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, though, a bigger, more powerful Goodyear may
have a larger impact. Despite the careful use of words like joint
ventures, Goodyear has in fact acquired controlling interest in
Sumitomo's operations in Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
   For now, both companies' plants are operating at capacity. But
Goodyear has more advanced manufacturing technology. Goodyear chief
executive Samir Gibara said Goodyear could use its technology to
increase Sumitomo's production by a third, without adding capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Bozarth, executive director of the International Tire &AMP;
Rubber Association, noted that Goodyear could well use that
capacity to make truck tires, which are in short supply. Goodyear
could also help turn Dunlop, a big seller in Japan, into a
powerhouse brand in North America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of cost-cutting is also expected. The joint venture will
likely close the oldest plants, executives said. And Goodyear and
Sumitomo said they would realize as much as $360 million in savings
from combining their purchases and eliminating duplicate functions.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, Goodyear's role is smaller and more subtle. Sumitomo
is the controlling partner there and is holding onto its own
manufacturing plants, though Goodyear said they would eventually
incorporate its advanced tire-making technologies.
</P>
<P>
   But the venture gives Goodyear inexpensive access to a market
that it has had little luck penetrating. ``The only way to compete
against Bridgestone in Japan is through Sumitomo,'' Gibara said.
</P>
<P>
   The full impact on Goodyear shareholders is still to be seen.
The deal involves a combination of taxable and tax-free events
around the world, and Goodyear's lawyers are ``working to see how
to best minimize the tax implications for shareholders,'' a
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Goodyear, which ended 1998 with about $2 billion in debt
and a debt-to-equity ratio of about 30 percent, will have to borrow
heavily to come up with the $936 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Goodyear's investors seemed pleased with the move. Shares
of Goodyear, which is based in Akron, Ohio, rose $1.625, to $52,
Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear reported its fourth-quarter earnings Wednesday; the
posting of 78 cents a share met analyst expectations, when one-time
gains of about 4 cents a share were factored out.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear earned $121.5 million, or 78 cents per share, in the
final three months of 1998, compared with $2 million, or 1 cent per
share, a year earlier. Sales fell to $3.2 billion from $3.3 billion
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Goodyear earned $682.3 million, or $4.31 per
share, on sales of $12.6 billion, up from 1997 profits of $558.7
million, or $3.53 per share, on sales of $13.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear said it would close an old plant in Gadsden, Ala., and
that it would ``rationalize'' operations in Latin America and Asia.
The moves will mean the end of as many as 2,800 jobs, Goodyear
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
