<SLUG> BC-MINORITIES-LOANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DETAILS MINORITY DIFFICULTIES IN OBTAINING LOANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minority entrepreneurs have difficulty obtaining bank credit to
start or expand their businesses even when annual revenues exceed
$1 million and the firms have been operating for a minimum of three
years, according to a study scheduled for release Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared by the Organization for a New Equality, the study of
200 minority firms in cities around the country contends that
access to capital remains a serious problem for an estimated 3.7
million minority firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``ONE's analysis reveals that even viable businesses owned by
minority entrepreneurs have difficulty obtaining the financing they
need to grow,'' said the Rev. Joseph E. Washington, ONE chairman
and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The survey indicated 89 percent of the companies had applied for
a particular bank credit product or program, but fewer than half,
or 43 percent, received it. Fifty-seven percent were turned down.
ONE also found fewer than half of the credit applications submitted
by companies with yearly revenues of more than $1 million were
approved.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 26.5 percent of the companies surveyed had annual
revenues of more than $1 million, and 22 percent had more than 20
employees.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal statistics, 51 percent of all white
business owners are approved for credit, compared with 41 percent
of all minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, of 116 businesses in the ONE study whose first credit
applications were denied, 65 applied for bank credit a second time,
but only 8 percent were approved on the second try. Fifty percent
of the companies turned down a second time reapplied three or more
times. Of those, 20 percent eventually received credit. ONE
suggests these business owners had not received information that
would have improved their chances of getting a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Washington said minority firms often turn to alternative sources
of funding because they have difficulty gaining access to bank
loans. Of the 200 companies surveyed, for example, 69 percent
applied for alternative methods of funding and paid interest rates
that were, on average, 59 percent higher than rates paid for bank
credit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2000EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
