A0765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT &LR;      02-03 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE AHEAD FOR CARDOSO AS DEPUTIES SWITCH PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil _ A raft of newly elected members of Congress
switched parties just before taking office here this week, in a
move that appears to signal a more fractious second term for
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso as he forges ahead with
unfinished changes.
</P>
<P>
   Some deputies, belonging to the evangelical Christian movement,
dropped the powerful conservative party that had delivered the
votes for their elections, joining a smaller party in which they
could hold more sway. They promised a more critical stance toward
Cardoso's proposals for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's against the people and against the nation, we're going
to fight head on,'' vowed Marcos Jesus, who as with many candidates
who ran on evangelical platforms, switched from the small Liberal
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Several legislators from Minas Gerais dropped Cardoso's party
for the party of Gov. Itamar Franco of Minas Gerais. Franco is in
the middle of a battle of nerves with Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
   Franco declared a moratorium on his state's debt to the federal
government, shattering Brazil's already fragile credibility in
world markets and unleashing the latest round of economic
turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso is waging an all-out campaign to return the faltering
economy on course, bolstered by a $41.5 billion standby loan from
the United States, the group of seven industrialized nations, the
International Monetary Fund and other lending agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Having experienced 39 percent annual interest rates,
unemployment at a 15-year high and soaring, and a currency that has
been devalued more than 30 percent in the last month, Cardoso's
popularity has fallen to an all-time low, with 27 percent of 2,000
Brazilians questioned in a survey saying they supported him.
</P>
<P>
   The first deputy managing director of the IMF, Stanley Fischer,
postponed his return to the United States Wednesday night. Fischer,
along with technical and negotiating teams from the fund, have been
combing through accounts and reworking the targets and conditions
for aid.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is eager to speed delivery of the second part of $9
billion in aid.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cardoso's six-party coalition enjoys a comfortable
majority of about 380 among the 513 deputies in the House, some
important parties in the coalition have disparate factions.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian Democratic Movement Party of Franco, for example,
is split between those who support him and those who back Cardoso.
Because of defections this week, Franco's party swelled, from 83 to
95 seats, the total that Cardoso's party has in the lower chamber.
Franco is widely seen as a highly likely presidential contender
four years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cardoso's party shows signs that the ready Congressional
support for most of his proposals would not last into his next
term. Aecio Neves, leader of Cardoso's Brazilian Social Democracy
Party in the House, told a newspaper that the party ``had to act
with more liberty, without making so many concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Carlos Rodrigues of Rio de Janeiro, another member of the
evangelical block, dropped the government-allied conservative party
that helped him win office in October to switch to an opposition
party.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Rodrigues criticized the government for raising taxes,
saying spending had to be cut. But he said laying off public
workers and cutting pension benefits were not the answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't solve anything,'' the bishop said. ``It's only a
palliative.''
</P>
<P>
   To balance its books, he added, the government ought to simplify
taxes to reduce opportunities for evasion and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Rodrigues said he switched parties because of a Cardoso
administration plan to push for laws that would require members of
Congress to vote along party lines, removing their independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wants party loyalty not for political reasons,
but to put a muzzle on the deputies, and I won't accept that,''
Bishop Rodrigues said. ``For that, you don't even need to be here.
You could just sit in your house and have the party leader vote for
you. Why even be a deputy at all?''
</P>
<P>
   The administration sees a law on party loyalty as a way to cut
down on pork barrel projects and other concessions that each
victory in Congress demands
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
