<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHIATRY-CONDUCT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENTAL HEALTH RESEARCH CHIEF WANTS REVIEW OF PSYCHIATRIC
EXPERIMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PHILLIP HILTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chief of the nation's mental health research agency says he
will propose the establishment of a new federal committee to review
all human experiments in psychiatry that might be considered ``high
risk'' for the subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven E. Hyman, director of the National Institute of
Mental Health, says he plans to announce the proposal Thursday at a
meeting of the NIMH Advisory Council.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman's proposal is an attempt to walk a narrow line between
factions in the rancorous debate that has split research
psychiatry. Some scientists say that the idea of a review committee
is long overdue while others argue that it could snarl research in
more red tape and bureaucracy. Meanwhile, patient advocates suggest
that it is too small a step.
</P>
<P>
   The debate centers on the subject of whether, when and how
experiments that offer no hope of treatment benefits to the
experiment's subjects should be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   NIMH funds more than $470 million worth of studies annually,
including more than 1,700 grants for clinical studies carried out
at universities, medical centers and clinics around the nation.
NIMH is one of the federal research institutes that make up the
National Institutes of Health, and other institutes have already
cut back their internal research as well, and shifting the funds to
pay for more grants.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past eight years, patient advocates have charged
researchers with ethics abuses in studies that were done at both
the NIMH headquarters and in universities and clinics around the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies have been criticized for ethical lapses, and
government agencies have found federal ethics violations in a few
of the cases, including two at major universities.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman recently suspended a number of studies carried out at NIMH
headquarters itself, after an internal review indicated scientific
or ethical problems. Of the 108 in-house clinical studies, 29 were
suspended and more than 50 others were ordered changed in some way.
</P>
<P>
   In the most typical cases, the patients have been taken off
their medicines while scientists observe their return of psychotic
symptoms. The risk for patients in such studies is in dispute, but
may include suffering extra bouts of symptoms briefly, to permanent
deterioration of the patients' mental state. At least four
instances in which such subjects have committed suicide have been
reported in the press in the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   In the riskiest subset of the cases, patients have not only been
taken off of their medicines, but have also been given drugs to
intentionally provoke psychotic symptoms while the scientists
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that too often patients are not clearly told and do
not understand that when they enter such an experiment, the study
offers them no hope of benefit or treatment, and at the same time
subjects them to serious risks.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the research say that while some experiments may
not be up to ethical standards, the great majority are. As for the
subjects, the defenders say the suffering caused in the experiments
is probably not permanent, and the brief suffering is necessary to
help learn how to best treat illness.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said he is taking steps to assure that the riskiest of the
human experiments are scrutinized more closely. Although the number
of such experiments is not known, it is likely to be in the range
of a few dozen or fewer experiments per year, researchers estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Under his proposal, experiments in which mental patients with
the most serious disorders are taken off their medication, and
those experiments in which drugs are used to provoke illness, will
be reviewed by a committee of eight to ten scientists and patient
advocates just before final approval of the each grant.
</P>
<P>
   The group will review each study to determine whether the study
includes proper plans to get informed consent from patients, as
well as plans to closely follow patients in case trouble should
arise.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald Klein, a professor at Columbia University and
researcher at the New York State Psychiatric Institute, said he
thought the proposal was ``jumping the gun. As far as I know, the
studies going on out there have had no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there should be very firm evidence of a systematic
problem before establishing a new bureaucratic organization. ``What
we need is a study, to find out whether there is a problem, not
another bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Kupfer, chairman of Psychiatry at the University of
Pittsburgh, one of the largest psychiatric research centers in the
nation, and former president of the American College of
Neuropharmacology, said he thought the proposal is a reasonable
step forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned so much, are so much farther along, we can
afford to standards a little bit higher. We do not have to do as
many fishing expeditions as we did 25 years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Klein worried that science would be slowed and some
experiments prohibited, Kupfer disagreed. ``I don't think this will
stop any good things from happening and it need not lead to more
bureaucracy,'' Kupfer said.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Hassner Sharav, head of the New York-based activist group
called Citizens for Responsible Care in Psychiatry and Research,
said of Hyman's actions, ``What he is doing is a start.''She called
for further investigation of the issue. ``What we need is an
independent investigation of all risky human experiments funded by
NIMH across the country,'' she said. ``We believe thousands of
patients are being harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said ``we must keep the public's trust that we are doing
the right thing. If there are deficiencies we need to care of them
ahead of time, not wait till they become horror stories.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the new panel review was simply a proposal to reaffirm
faith in methods while moving ahead with the research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
