A0768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAIRBANKS-CULTURE-2TA     02-03 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRBANKS-CULTURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A CITY OF FROZEN DUSK, GALLERIES AND THEATERS ARE TRUE
LIFESAVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRBANKS, Alaska _ The ice was too cold. When the temperature
sank under 30 degrees below zero here last week and bottomed out at
47 below zero through the weekend, an icy fog swaddled this city in
a glowing soup. And the local sculptors who have dotted the city
with angels and polar bears and other crystalline icons had to put
away their sanders and their chisels and the water _ ``Arctic
superglue'' in local parlance _ they use to fuse ice limbs to ice
torsos and to make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   It was cold even for Fairbanks, where residents routinely use
the frozen Chena River for a road; cold enough for a cup of coffee
tossed in the air to freeze before the droplets hit the snow; cold
enough for automobile tires to square against the ground, and cold
enough for heating oil to begin thickening. At such temperatures,
blocks of ice simply become too brittle and prone to shatter for
the delicate shaving and whittling that a sculptor's work requires.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kathleen Carlo-Kendall gave it a shot. With Anita Tabor,
a wood sculptor who moved here from Arkansas 13 years ago, Ms.
Carlo-Kendall, an Athabascan Indian and mask maker, spent an hour
or so on Saturday in front of the Westmark Hotel downtown, working
on two large native-style masks, one traditional, one contemporary.
They did not make much progress, but it was a good workout; the two
women are half of the first all-female team to enter the
International Ice Art Championships (``Frigid Women,'' they
jokingly call themselves) held here each March.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a good excuse to battle the cabin fever that many
people say is a winter burden, brought on more by lingering
darkness than by the cold. There are but seven hours of dim
sunlight a day right now, up from little more than three hours at
the winter solstice six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get out of the house,'' Ms. Carlo-Kendall said.
``I haven't been out in three days.''
</P>
<P>
   The arts have a tough row to hoe in this part of the world, a
place where man's creations pale beside Mother Nature's, and
particularly at this time of year when the world is dark, and for
many, the spirit is, too. Yet there may be no other place in the
country where the arts serve such a practical function as they do
in this surprisingly diverse (ethnically and artistically),
brutally winterbound and isolated environment.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this not a pretty town _ the blocky, economical
architecture is often lamented, with good reason, by the locals _
Fairbanks manifests a persistent and enduring interest in the arts.
They not only bring people out into the cold and cheer the bleak
landscape, but they are cited by many here, not outlandishly, as a
reason to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suicide during this time of year runs a little high, and the
arts have been a comforter,'' said Mayor James Hayes. ``They play
an integral role in this city. Without them, I don't know what we'd
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The state, with its notorious small-government bias, has cut
back on arts subsidies in recent years; its support to the
Fairbanks Arts Association diminished to just $11,000 this year
from more than $65,000 in the early '90s. But the political isn't
personal, says June Rogers, the executive director of the
association, who notes that many of the budget-slashing legislators
contribute generously to the arts from their own pockets. The city
supports the arts with a hotel bed tax; its contribution to the
association this year was $77,000, 90 percent of which was
channeled to local nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks maintains two dance companies, two art galleries, two
community theaters (one performs original work, the other
Shakespeare), a chorale and a light opera company that often sells
out a 1,400-seat hall.
</P>
<P>
   The city also has an ambitious amateur symphony whose
co-principal violinist also plays the tuba. On Saturday night the
symphony's Arctic Chamber Orchestra lured about 300 people out in
30-degrees-below-zero weather for a program that included Bartok's
difficult ``Divertimento for Strings'' and the world premiere of
``Sculptured Memories,'' a dissonant tone poem by Gregory Mertl,
29, of Rochester, his first commissioned work.
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks has a fair amount of public art, supported by a state
levy on builders of 1 percent of the cost of all new buildings. And
the city is rife with painters, musicians, writers and
photographers, as well as decorative weavers like Marnie Cornwall,
who specializes in the delicate wool of the qiviut, or Alaskan musk
ox; artists using natural materials (aside from ice) like Penny
Wakefield, who works in dried and painted fish skins, and
Athabascan skin sewers and beadworkers like Dixie Alexander, whose
variations on tribal clothing are in the collections of the
Smithsonian Institution and other museums in ``the lower 48.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a gem of a museum here, on the main campus of the
University of Alaska, tiny and crammed with the natural history of
the state, along with native artifacts and art objects ranging from
1,500-year-old Eskimo carvings of wood and ivory to contemporary
paintings. The university is a focus for the regeneration of native
arts, whose connection to tribal life had long been attenuated by
the encroachment of modern times.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alexander (who also runs an annual fiddling festival where
Athabascan elders gather to play the twangy, countrified music
brought here by Scottish and French-Canadian traders in the 19th
century) spends part of the year in villages around the state,
reintroducing the traditional art forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people still have their elders sewing for them,'' she
said. ``What happened to the younger generation? The Alaska Cable
Network. Computers. Snowmobiles.'' She added, ``We get a lot of our
funding from suicide prevention groups.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
