<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES DEAL VAUGHN, SWEENEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So Greg Vaughn and his 50 homers have relocated from
San Diego to Cincinnati. So why didn't the Red Sox, desperately in
need of power after the loss of Mo Vaughn, come up with an offer to
bring Mo's cousin to Fenway Park?
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the way the ball bounces in baseball these
days. Economic considerations more often than not outweigh
outstanding individual numbers as well as common sense.
</P>
<P>
   In helping the Padres to the World Series, Greg Vaughn posted
career highs in home runs and runs batted in (119). He had a great
season. But it produced mixed results. And cost-conscious San
Diego, in the process of overhauling its roster and payroll,
wondered whether it could afford him after 1999.
</P>
<P>
   So Vaughn's immediate reward was to be traded Tuesday along with
first baseman-outfielder Mark Sweeney to Cincinnati in a
five-player deal that sent outfielder Reggie Sanders, infielder
Damian Harris, and minor league righthander Josh Harris to the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn might have joined the Red Sox if the price had been
right. Instead, Boston was apparently one of four teams that put in
bids and didn't get him. Boston, Arizona, and Anaheim didn't offer
the help in specific areas the Padres were seeking. Toronto offered
prospects and never really was in the running.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, according to sources, initially offered veteran
infielders John Valentin and Tim Naehring. The Padres weren't
interested and Boston since has let Naehring go. Recently, the Sox
tried to sweeten the offer by including some prospects but were
again rejected. Several Red Sox regulars have multiyear contracts
which San Diego apparently wasn't eager to assume.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been the irony of the offseason if Boston had
wound up with one Vaughn to replace another. The price was right,
at least from a contract perspective. Greg Vaughn, 33, will make
$5.75 million in 1999, then become a free agent. Mo Vaughn joined
the Angels for a six-year, $80 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres also turned down the Diamondbacks, who offered
lefthanded pitcher Brian Anderson (12-13, 4.33 ERA) and outfielder
Bernard Gilkey (.233, 5 HRs, 33 RBIs), and the Angels, who dangled
outfielder Jim Edmonds (.307, 25 HRs, 91 RBIs) along with a couple
of prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best offer we had,'' said Padres general manager
Kevin Towers Wednesday when asked why he chose the Reds package.
``It was certainly better than Arizona. I'm not as worried about
the rotation as I am about defense, speed, and scoring runs.''
</P>
<P>
   So why a trade?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the makeup of this team reminds me of the 1996 team
that won the division,'' said Towers at a press conference
following the announcement of the deal. ``That team had pitching,
speed, and defense.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes he got that with the addition of Sanders and
Jackson. So, Towers reasoned, he could part with Vaughn, who joins
an exodus of headliners who have left San Diego since the Padres
lost the World Series to the New York Yankees _ pitchers Kevin
Brown and Joey Hamilton, third baseman Ken Caminiti, and outfielder
Steve Finley, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Unless he hits 50 home runs again, Greg Vaughn won't get the
kind of free agent deal cousin Mo did. And his stay in Cincinnati
may be short-lived, especially if the Reds are lagging around the
All-Star break and other contenders come calling.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call, Vaughn said, ``I have some friends who
said, `Don't unpack.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the rejected suitors will have another crack at him
after all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
