<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAIRBANKS-CULTURE-2ND     02-03 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRBANKS-CULTURE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
FAIRBANKS: prevention groups.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On campus there are signs of renewal. Alvin Amanson, who directs
the native arts program at the university, is an Aleut painter from
Kodiak known for modern expressionist portraits of Alaskan
wildlife. (De Kooning is his acknowledged influence.)
</P>
<P>
   He has been encouraged, he said, by the skill of his young
students, who are beginning to meld the rhythms and skills of their
villages with contemporary imagery. One young woodcarver, he said,
a Yupik from southeastern Alaska, dazzled him with the masks he
made for a university dance troupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one was of Bart Simpson,'' he said, laughing
uproariously.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in a broad valley cut by the Tanana River, between the
towering Alaska Range to the south and the Brooks Range to the
north, Fairbanks is home to 31,000 people, with another 50,000 in
the surrounding North Star Borough. It is a small place, but it is
nonetheless the state's second-largest city (behind Anchorage, 400
miles south), and the only urban center serving Alaska's interior,
a region the size of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It is a place that must be all things to many people. ``We've
got more variety of arts per capita than most places our size,''
said Matt Reckard, a retired civil engineer and part-time actor.
``But I don't know that that makes us an arts town. We've got more
car dealerships than you'd expect, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1902, Fairbanks has been an important mining center
through most of the century. In recent decades, however, its
population and urbanity have been augmented by the presence of Air
Force and Army bases and the growth of the state university, whose
main campus serves 9,000 students. Construction of the Alaska
pipeline brought thousands of laborers in the 1970s; many stayed on
after the wild times of the period settled down.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the outdoors attracted individualists from all over
the United States, many of whom decided that the glories of summer
(not only hiking and rafting and midnight softball but a two-week
summer arts festival) were worth enduring the hostile winters.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoors is alluring to artists as well, of course. They
include both lifelong Alaskans like Lisa Rogers, a self-taught
painter, sculptor and crafts artist whose work includes imagery
from her years of a subsistence life style in Lime Village, a
remote northern town with a population of 40; and others, like
David Mollett, a landscape painter who was born in Oregon but has
lived most of his life here.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a landscape painter it's nice that nobody's painted it
much,'' said Mollett, who has lived and exhibited in New York and
Paris. He was among the very first painters to venture into the
Brooks Range. In his studio, he keeps a canvas that was shredded by
a bear on one of his sojourns there.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of all these influences, the population of Fairbanks
is idiosyncratic and tends to be self-selecting. By their own
assessment, the city's residents tend to be curious people and
readers, even though Alaska is, in the words of Greg Hill, the
director of the local library, ``book poor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the libraries in the state put together don't have the
volumes they have at the University of Washington,'' Hill said.
``But Alaska has 10 percent higher usage rate than the rest of the
country, and Fairbanks has a 10 percent higher rate than the rest
of Alaska. We have our kooks and cranks, but they tend to be
intelligent here.''
</P>
<P>
   The population is also increasingly diverse. This is a city
whose best restaurant is arguably a Thai luncheonette, and where
last week at the Arctic Bar, a local watering hole, Marc Brown, an
Athabascan guitarist, introduced the members of his band, the Blues
Crew, by saying, ``You probably won't see another blues band with
an Indian, an Eskimo, a black guy and a white guy.''
</P>
<P>
   And although country music is prevalent in most of the
roadhouses, there are places that occasionally feature Celtic
music, jazz and even rap. Fifteen percent of Fairbanks residents
are black, including Hayes, who is also the pastor at the Lily of
the Valley Church of God in Christ, one of several black churches
in the city that nurture a tradition of gospel singing. On Sunday
morning the church choir, 20 strong, accompanied by an organist and
drummer and singing in a distinctively pop style, stirred a full
house of congregants to the extent that the ushers were passing out
fans, making it the only overheated place in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The arts are warm, but in Fairbanks in winter, maybe a lonely
flame. Drive a short way out of town, and the snowfields and
snow-sugared black spruce seem to stretch on forever, an endless
abstract in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at all this grayness, and I think about depression and
loneliness and all the things grayness can contribute to,'' said
Ms. Rogers of the arts association. ``But you know, it is
beautiful. I don't find it depressing. And I think that's what art
can do for people here, give them another way to look at things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
