<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING GRAHAM IN WORDS AND ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The gala opening of the Martha Graham Dance Company's
three-week season at the Joyce Theater on Tuesday night was strong
on the stark and the spare. With one exception, all the dances were
choreographed by Graham in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   If the evening did not offer a complete picture of Graham's
theatrical range, her radical vision of an ecstatic theater could
be seen in the company's performance of her 1931 masterpiece
``Primitive Mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, no dance was like another, even within this
selective sampling. Graham, who died in 1991, divulged a secret
when she was heard suddenly on tape at the beginning of the
performance: ``I take the puppet, which is myself, and I fling him
against the sky.'' In this extravagant and perfect metaphor for the
unbridled creative act, Graham defined herself. Certainly she went
her own way, as a group of well known former Graham students
reminded us in their onstage remarks. The choreographer Twyla Tharp
led the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who am I to introduce Martha Graham?'' she asked, adding that
Graham's works required no validation. She wished, she said, to
address Graham as a teacher, as a creator of a dance technique and
as a woman. ``Without these my career would be severely less than
what it is,'' Ms. Tharp said, and asked for 15 seconds of silence
``to give the stage back to Martha and for what Martha Graham, her
works and her company mean to all of dance worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tharp thanked all for their support, which includes a
$110,000 grant that Schuyler G. Chapin, the New York City cultural
affairs commissioner, said would be made to the Graham
organization. Speaking before the performance, Chapin said the
grant, from the mayor's office and the City Council, was part of
``continuing city support of this extraordinary organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The Graham legacy was extolled with conviction by Pearl Lang, a
luminous dancer in the troupe's earlier days, and with a mix of
seriousness and humor by three actors who studied with Graham at
the Neighborhood Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Randall's dry wit reached back to his first day at the
playhouse school in 1938 when he met ``a boy'' who became his best
friend, Eli Wallach. ``This is a week of high culture for me,''
Randall said. ``Sunday I was at the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallach and his wife, Anne Jackson, joined Randall in
reminiscences about Graham's courses. Wallach said that Graham,
exasperated with the way he walked across the stage one day,
exclaimed, ``Eli, for God's sake, walk as if you carry the seed.''
Wallach lifted his chest and walked across the stage at the Joyce.
 &UR;  &LR; Graham is at her purest in ``Primitive Mysteries,'' inspired by
Spanish-Indian ceremonies she saw in the Southwest. The ceremony
onstage is nonetheless not a literal ritual but a highly abstract
rendering of an image: a community celebrates the Virgin by
celebrating the coming of age of a young girl.
</P>
<P>
   As the Madonna figure, Rika Okamoto, in Graham's famous white
dress, is surrounded by 13 women in blue who enter three times with
her in silence. Hands cupped to their hips, their bodies often held
in a contraction of the lower torso, the women step in, holding one
foot to ankle before placing it on the floor. This unison footfall
in the entrances and exits of each section creates an aura of
anticipation and suspense.
</P>
<P>
   The Virgin relives Jesus' passion. The deliberately flattened
style of Mexican altar sculpture is dominant. Steven Spielberg
chose Ms. Okamoto for the title role of a future film of Arthur
Golden's ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' and certainly she has no trouble
holding center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Horst's deceptively simple and dolorous score, played by
Alison Potter, Ariana Ghez and Alan Moverman with Alan Sherber
conducting, propels the drama onstage. In the first section, ``Hymn
to the Virgin,'' the central figure blesses the women who support
her in adoration. In ``Crucifixus,'' she cups her hands to her
cheeks, inching forward with two acolytes. When she attains her
religious vision, she throws her arms out in an ecstatic release,
which spreads to the women who circle like a band of furies.
</P>
<P>
   A slip to the floor by one dancer did not obviate the meticulous
detail that the ensemble, under Yuriko's coaching, incorporated
into the difficult movement. Graham did not distort for
distortion's sake but to express the essence of emotion, as visible
in the final ``Hosanna'' section.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's first principles of movement are based on the
contraction and release of the pelvis; the release is as important
as the first part, as the program's solos demonstrated. In
``Frontier'' (1935), Denise Vale, advancing three times from Isamu
Noguchi's fragment of a fence, exulted as an American pioneer
contemplating the future. ``Deep Song'' (1937), created during the
Spanish Civil War, had a spellbinding Christine Dakin as the
anguished wife in all wars. Her dancing was unusually tight, and
the final release in despair all the more dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation was the young Fang Yi Sheu in the recent
reconstruction of ``Satyric Festival Song'' (1932). She captured
the spring and freshness of the Indian clowns who were Graham's
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The 1981 ``Ritual to the Sun,'' with a male and female ensemble,
has been danced more solidly in the past. But compelling is the
word for Terese Capucilli's agitator in red, seconded by Miki
Orihara, and a fabulously swift and forceful young female group in
``Prelude to Action'' (1936). The musical ensemble was completed by
Laura Koepke, Hiro Noguchi and Peter Wilson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
