<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS SEEN IN BREAKTHROUGH RECRUITING EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call them exit polls. Not a slam-dunk predictor of how things
will turn out, but a pretty good indicator.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the pronouncements from recruiting services
around the country, the overwhelming winner in Wednesday's annual
national letter of intent signing day festivities was . . . the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting guru Tom Lemming, who has been charting the progress
of high school and prep football talent for 20 years, calls it a
breakthrough year for the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it's hard to argue. In only his second season,
coach Mack Brown landed the USA Today Offensive Player of the Year
(quarterback Chris Simms) and the USA Today Defensive Player of the
Year (linebacker Corey Redding).
</P>
<P>
   ``We only called 35 guys and we got 28 of them,'' said Brown as
he sweated out the final few hours of recruiting while the official
faxes and commitments came into the football offices in Austin. ``A
lot of guys said they wanted to go to Texas. That made it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Or easier.
</P>
<P>
   In an enterprise that is considered a major crap shoot, just
like the NFL draft, Texas was the consensus No. 1. Following in
varying order were Notre Dame, Ohio State, UCLA, Texas A&AMP;M, Miami,
Alabama, and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   In a banner year for the Big East, the conference had three
teams in the Top 25, topped by Miami, which harvested the talented
fields of south Florida for a new power base, followed by Syracuse
and, if you can believe it . . . Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   BC's ranking, according to the people who study such things, is
unusual. Rarely do teams with losing records climb into the Top 25
in recruiting. But this year California and LSU also fit that
description.
</P>
<P>
   BC made its hit by taking talented players out of New Jersey,
another fertile recruiting field. The biggest catch was running
back William Green from Absecon, projected as the successor to
All-American Mike Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was crucial because verbal commitments mean nothing
until the letter of intent is signed. The national champion
Volunteers learned that a few weeks ago when Simms switched from a
verbal at UT to a verbal at UT, which startled the people at
Tennessee and pleased the people at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols got singed again when running back Santonio Beard, a
6-foot, 185-pound prospect from Nashville, opted for Alabama
instead of the home state university.
</P>
<P>
   Another shocked and disconsolate suitor was Notre Dame, which
shored up its offensive line in anticipation of landing quarterback
C.J. Leak of Independence, N.C. Instead, Leak signed with Wake
Forest, a school he did not even visit officially.
</P>
<P>
   Such things are common. And so is a recruiting class labeled as
the best turning into something less than that.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to keep score, using a Top 100 consensus list of
high school prospects as a guide, Texas was the clear-cut winner
with eight such signings, while Texas A&AMP;M, Michigan, LSU, and UCLA
tied for second with five.
</P>
<P>
   All those schools have been mentioned constantly in the Top 20
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   BC, a newcomer in the ``also receiving votes'' list, would seem
to have hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's simple. All Eagle coach Tom O'Brien has to do is keep
them in school, keep them healthy, and hope they are as productive
as their reputations would seem to indicate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
