<HEADER>
A0776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PREVIEW-2TAKES-NY     02-03 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PREVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SEEKS TO SALVAGE A TARNISHED SEASON  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's now up to Larry Bird's team and Shaquille O'Neal's smile.
Maybe Grant Hill's daring and Kobe Bryant's ``do'' can pick up the
slack. Karl Malone and John Stockton better have a few
pick-and-rolls left in them, too.
</P>
<P>
   The job of resurrecting the National Basketball Association's
image _ and of purging the taint of a destructive lockout from the
public's consciousness _ is no longer Michael Jordan's
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the league works to regain its identity,
Jordan will be busy planning a golf outing this June. The
retirement three weeks ago of the game's best player and premier
attraction not only ended the championship run of the Chicago
Bulls. It sent aftershocks through NBC and every luxury box,
producing a genuine feeling of trepidation about where the NBA goes
from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to sell basketball,'' said Lenny Wilkens, the Atlanta
coach who has won more games than any NBA coach. ``Michael was
great for our league, but the league will survive and it will
survive when all of us are gone. Whomever emerges as the torch
bearers, let them emerge on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens echoes the general perception among players, coaches and
league officials, who believe there is no one player waiting to
take Jordan's place. Instead, a handful of young stars and a return
to team rivalries are seen as important toward renewing fan
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The first gauge may be this unpredictable, seat-of-the-pants
season beginning Friday. Like a lot of desperate teams after the
lockout ended, it was thrown together in three weeks. Fifty games
will be played over 90 days, a grind that raises concern over
injuries and quality of play.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Jordan was kind enough to depart with a going-away
present: Twenty-eight other franchises now have a chance to win a
title, which only accelerates the healing process in runner-up
cities like Indianapolis and Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers and the Jazz, on talent and experience alone, seemed
headed for a finals showdown. Bird, in his second year, is relying
on the same core group _ Reggie Miller, Rik Smits and Mark Jackson
_ that came within a game of knocking off the Bulls last season.
The same goes for Jerry Sloan in Utah, where Malone and Stockton
are still shaking their heads over the last 40 seconds of Game 6,
when Jordan stole Utah's soul and led Chicago to its sixth title in
eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Since that summer night in Salt Lake City last June, the league
has undergone a striking transformation:
</P>
<P>
   _ Scottie Pippen left Chicago to team with Hakeem Olajuwon and
Charles Barkley in Houston to form a legends-in-their-own-time
frontline
</P>
<P>
   _ Latrell Sprewell went from a suspended, troubled Golden State
Warrior to a rejuvenated Knick, expected to help Patrick Ewing get
a championship ring before the 36-year-old center's knees crumble
to dust.
</P>
<P>
   _ Indicative of tough times, Dennis Rodman is still looking for
a job, although Miami, Orlando and the Lakers have shown interest.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere will the changes be more evident than on Friday night at
the Delta Center in Utah, where the where Jazz host the Bulls on
opening night in what hardly amounts to a rematch between last
season's conference champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael and Scottie aren't in those uniforms anymore,'' said
Tim Floyd, who takes over for Phil Jackson in Chicago and is one
seven new coaches along with Paul Westphal in Seattle and George
Karl in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd is not presiding over the defending champions as much as
he is figuring out how to stay out of the Central Division basement
along with Toronto. With Jordan, Pippen, Steve Kerr, Luc Longley
and Rodman gone, the forecast is grim in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper and Toni Kukoc are the only returning starters, and
Bill Wennington was the lone free agent offered a contract. Though
they acquired Brent Barry, the Bulls' banner days are far behind.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers seemed poised to take over. Yet with so many Eastern
Conference teams undergoing facelifts, parity might kill the
Indiana's chances of securing the best record in the league, and
thus, homecourt advantage throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Save Ewing, the Knicks finally gave up on the old guard of
Charles Oakley and John Starks and wagered on the talent and
baggage of Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, who has yet to play a regular season game in 14 months
because of his suspension for choking P.J. Carlesimo in December of
1997, became the most controversial acquisition of the off-season.
Other than adding depth, Indiana and Miami decided to pass and let
the Knicks gamble on the three-time All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets were beset with preseason injuries to Kerry Kittles and
Rony Seikaly, but still have enough talent to contend for the
Atlantic Division title.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta still has its nucleus in tact, and the Hawks acquired
the former Nugget LaPhonso Ellis through free agency. Anfernee
Hardaway is finally healthy again in Orlando, where the Magic
acquired Isaac Austin and still remain in the hunt for Rodman.
Young legs in Cleveland give the Cavaliers hope. And now that
Washington has re-signed Rod Strickland, the Wizards appear
playoff-bound.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Out West the competition is not as keen. The Lakers, who are
still searching for a complement to O'Neal in the post (Rodman is
still a possibility), appear all grown up. But then, that's what
everyone said last year before the Jazz swept them away in the
conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, Seattle and San Antonio represent the only other great
threats to Utah's chances of a third straight trip to the finals.
So-so backcourts hurt the Spurs and Rockets, while the soft Sonics
are in desperate need of a rebounder with a nasty disposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are predicting Utah and Indiana because of
their experience and being there in the past, but I honestly think
Los Angeles, San Antonio and maybe Miami have as good a chance as
anybody,'' said Karl, who has resurfaced in Milwaukee after being
fired by Seattle. ``When May comes around I think we are going to
have at least one surprise hanging around in the playoffs and I
think it is going to be a toss-up more than a favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, there is mystery over who will win the title
again. And that in itself is almost as tantalizing as, well,
watching Jordan play.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the league pine for the days of Bird's Celtics and Magic
Johnson's Lakers, the last NBA team rivalry that captured the
country's imagination. The personality-driven league that has
emerged over the last decade make those halcyon times seem all but
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, the pressure is on players like Hill,
Bryant, Tim Duncan, Keith Van Horn, Stephon Marbury, Kevin Garnett,
Allen Iverson and especially O'Neal to take the league into the
next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   It is an arduous task. You not only have to lead your team to a
title, but you have smile wide for the cameras and be amenable to
the marketing possibilities. You not only have to perform mid-air
artistry with the basketball, you need to care enough about the
sport to work out during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we should drop the burden on them that they
have to carry the NBA because they don't,'' Wilkens said. ``People
forget when Michael came in his first couple of years, no one
dubbed him as a torch bearer, but he emerged into it, based on what
he did. I think we need to let Kobe and we need to let Grant mature
into those positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Commissioner David Stern, ``The challenge is each for them
to push their team to victory, that's the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   As to what kind of season to expect, no one is sure. For the
first time in 10 years, teams will occasionally be playing three
games on three consecutive nights _ a fact that eliminates many
practice sessions. Worse, players like Shawn Kemp ate too much in
the extended off-season. He is one of several players trying to
frantically shed pounds before the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Overweight All-Stars. Conditioning and chemistry kinks. And,
finally, no Jordan to bail out his team, the networks and,
basically, the league.
</P>
<P>
   Some new era.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do win a championship, I don't think anyone should put
an asterisk on the side and say it was not a full season and
Michael wasn't playing,'' Karl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a great opportunity for every team now to say,
`Michael's not in there now. It's wide open.' ``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2007EST &QL; 
