<HEADER>
A0779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTT-PREVIN &LR; - &UR; MUSIC-R     02-03 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTT-PREVIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FELICITY LOTT: OPERATIC ARTISTRY FROM A BRITISH SOPRANO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT 
(ATTN: Great Britain)  By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The British soprano Felicity Lott never has quite won
the visibility and renown in the United States that she has long
enjoyed in Europe. Her Metropolitan Opera debut in 1990, as the
Marschallin in Strauss' ``Rosenkavalier,'' under the conductor
Carlos Kleiber, was a remarkable achievement. Last fall she was a
vocally refined Countess in several performances of the Met's new
production of Mozart's ``Nozze di Figaro.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night with the New York Philharmonic, the third of
four performances of an all-Richard Strauss program that mark Ms.
Lott's debut with the orchestra, it was clearer than ever what a
superior artist she is and what American audiences have been
missing.
</P>
<P>
   With the conductor Andre Previn providing musically supple
support, Ms. Lott sang the final scenes of ``Arabella'' and
``Capriccio,'' two Strauss operas she has long been identified
with. Though she may not have a deluxe soprano sound, her voice is
attractive, warm and vibrant. But it's what she does with it that
makes her artistry special. Her singing here had arching lyricism,
technical finesse, musical grace and alive, idiomatic diction.
</P>
<P>
   In the floating high phrases of the Countess' soliloquy in
``Capriccio,'' her almost seamless breath control was a marvel. As
the worldly-beyond-her-years Arabella, she produced a fullness of
sound with seeming effortlessness, serving as a bit of a
chastisement to the talented young American bass-baritone Richard
Bernstein, who sang the few lines for Mandryka, Arabella's wealthy
suitor, in this final scene. Bernstein has a naturally robust
voice, but, perhaps trying to make an impact with not much to sing,
he pushed his voice ineffectively.
</P>
<P>
   It was an interesting idea to begin the program with the
introduction to ``Capriccio,'' a string sextet, played winningly by
six members of the orchestra. This led effectively to the next
work, Strauss' delicately scored, genial Duet-Concertino for
Clarinet and Bassoon, with String Orchestra, a late work composed
in 1948. Two principals from the orchestra, the clarinetist Stanley
Drucker and the bassoonist Judith LeClair, were the marvelous
soloists.
</P>
<P>
   The concert concluded with the orchestra suite from ``Der
Rosenkavalier,'' and for the first time in my experience, this work
did not seem just the composer's shameless concoction of the
opera's hit tunes thrown together to provide a moment-making
concert piece. Previn's spacious and unmannered performance made
the difference. There was no attempt to sell the work, to milk it;
the orchestra's playing was vital, but in a refreshingly relaxed
way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2007EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
