<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harrelson, Knievel help kick off sweeps
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pop some fresh batteries into the remote, 'cause you're going to
need that little device during the next four weeks. It's sweeps
time again, when Nielsen measures local stations' demographics so
they can set their ad rates worth millions.
</P>
<P>
   And that means all new episodes of most shows, miniseries and
splashy guest stars. ``Stunting,'' they call it in the TV business,
and tonight it gets literal, as Robbie Knievel, Evel's son, jumps a
motorcycle between two buildings on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Big deals: ``The '60s'' (9 p.m. Sunday and Monday on NBC) is a
four-hour fictional re-creation of the decade we still love to
debate, with hippies and hard hats and Panthers, oh my! . .
.``Stephen King's Storm of the Century'' (9 p.m. Feb. 14, 15 and 18
on ABC) was written by King directly for TV; it's less about snow
than about pure evil. . . . ``Too Rich: The Secret Life of Doris
Duke'' (9 p.m. Feb. 21 and 23 on CBS) stars Lauren Bacall in a rare
TV appearance as the eccentric heiress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Turning points: The mysterious Cigarette Smoking Man's secrets
are finally exposed on a two-part ``The X-Files'' (9 p.m. Sunday
and Feb. 14 on Fox). . . . George Clooney hangs up his scrubs as
Dr. Ross on ``ER'' (10 p.m. Feb. 18 on NBC), but reportedly may do
some guest spots next season. . . . Monica and Chandler's secret
affair finally becomes known to all the ``Friends'' (8 p.m. Feb. 11
on NBC).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Guest stars: Elton John plays himself on the Feb. 14 ``The
Simpsons'' (8 p.m. on Fox). . . . Home run king Mark McGwire finds
more perks to his achievement than he imagined, as he gets romantic
in a fantasy with Helen Hunt on ``Mad About You'' (8:30 p.m. Feb.
22 on NBC). . . . Woody Harrelson is back playing ``Cheers''
bartender Woody Boyd on a visit to ``Frasier'' (9 tonight on NBC).
. . . Brian Dennehy returns as Finch's dad in a two-part ``Just
Shoot Me'' (9 p.m. Tuesday and 16 on NBC).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Only during sweeps: ``Robbie Knievel Building-to-Building
Death Jump Live'' (8 tonight on Fox). A live death jump: only on
Fox. . . . ``And the Beat Goes On: The Sonny and Cher Story'' (9
p.m. Feb. 27 on ABC). . . . ``The Grammy Awards'' (8 p.m. Feb. 24
on CBS) will be hosted by Rosie O'Donnell. . . . ``Opening the Lost
Tombs: Live From Egypt'' (8 p.m. March 2 on Fox) features the
opening of the pyramid of Queen Khamerenebty. Will it be Geraldo
and Al Capone's vault all over again?
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy it while it lasts, because come March 4, the networks will
have exhausted their supplies and it'll be reruns of reruns.
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow on `SNL'
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Live'' kicks off sweeps (11:30 p.m. Saturday on
NBC ) with Gwyneth Paltrow, a probable Oscar nominee for
``Shakespeare in Love,'' as host. The musical guest: Barenaked
Ladies.
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming guest hosts include Brendan Fraser on Feb. 13 (musical
guest: Busta Rhymes) and Bill Murray on Feb. 20 (musical guest:
Lucinda Williams).
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
