A0791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-DAVOS-BOS &LR;      02-03 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DAVOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISDOM IN A GLOBALIZED WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By H.D.S. GREENWAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVOS, Switzerland _ As they have for 30 years, heads of state,
finance ministers, politicians, and business leaders _ with a
sprinkling of scientists, musicians, artists, and writers _ have
been meeting in this Alpine resort made famous by Thomas Mann as
the magic mountain of his novel. Then it was for tuberculosis that
people came. Now it is for economic ills that people come to the
World Economic Forum _ ills that Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
calls ``the most serious financial crisis of the last 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the matter is ``globalization,'' which has the
capacity to lift countless millions out of poverty and backwardness
but can also do harm, as the crises in Asia, Russia, and Brazil
have so amply demonstrated. How to reap the benefits of
globalization while limiting the damage has dominated the
conversation here. Reforming the global architecture has been on
the books for years, but no one can agree on the blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the answer is to devise a world system of safeguards.
Britain's finance minister, Gordon Brown, spoke of a ``global
standing committee of international and national regulators to
conduct the regular and systematic surveillance of our world
financial system.'' He talked of an ``early-warning system'' that
could prevent financial meltdowns before they happened.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, however, warned that there are ``no easy answers or magic
wands'' and said an early-warning system could provoke what it
sought to prevent. The answer, he said, lies less in unwieldy
control machinery than in adherence to sound business practices by
both borrowers and lenders.
</P>
<P>
   The knowledge-based society of the next century will founder if
knowledge runs too far ahead of wisdom. Societies with banking
systems that are open and aboveboard and that have the
self-discipline to put their houses in order _ to stamp out
corruption, cronyism, and unproductive and inefficient state
controls _ are likely to prosper. Those that do not will not, and
no international regulatory system is likely to save them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
