<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POLICY-NYT     02-03 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAY SEND UP TO 4,000 TROOPS TO KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
 (with KOSOVO-TALKS) 
 (bl)  
By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen told a Senate
committee Wednesday that President Clinton does not need
congressional approval to send U.S. troops as peacekeepers to
Kosovo, and Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said that preliminary Pentagon plans call for a force of
2,000 to 4,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals, which are being refined in advance of this
Saturday's peace talks in France, envision U.S. troops serving as
the smaller part of a contingent that would include about 8,000
British soldiers and as many as 5,000 French soldiers. Germany,
Italy and other nations are also expected to commit troops,
according to administration and diplomatic officials.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials emphasized that the president has not
made a final decision on committing troops. U.S. representatives to
the peace talks expect to leverage that fact to extract the best
agreement possible from both parties, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's senior national security advisers returned
Wednesday to Congress for consultation with key senators. The
administration officials, including Cohen, Shelton, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and National Security Adviser Samuel
Berger, appeared at two confidential briefings. They described the
stakes the United States had in preserving peace in Kosovo and the
Balkans, and the dire consequences if the United States did not
take part in preserving any peace attained at the upcoming
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Several participants said they were left with the ``clear
impression'' that the United States intended to make available
2,000 to 4,000 troops for the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen told the Senate Armed Services Committee on Wednesday that
several aspects of the Kosovo crisis are propelling a U.S. role in
a peacekeeping operation, and cited the long history of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic refusing to end conflicts without
threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear from the past that Milosevic will not respond
unless he understands there is a very real threat to him and to his
forces, `` Cohen said. ``In order for there to be a credible NATO
threat, the NATO countries have indicated they won't participate in
that military operation unless the United States also participates.
``
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, whose
autonomous status within Yugoslavia was revoked by Milosevic 10
years ago, and who have been victims of Serbian repression and
massacres in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said these Kosovo Albanians `` would not feel confident of
having a NATO force that doesn't have some representation by the
United States,'' believing that U.S. troops would insulate them
from attacks by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   The administration continued drawing up details for a possible
air campaign should the warring parties fail to reach a ceasefire
agreement, and for Americans to join a peacekeeping force should a
ceasefire be negotiated and Clinton orders in troops.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the Kosovo Albanians agreed to take part in the peace
talks while the United States and its NATO allies continued to
pressure Serbia to join the talks. Already NATO has threatened to
use airstrike against Serbia if an agreement is not achieved by
Feb. 19 at the talks sponsored by the United States and five
European nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would have to be a real agreement, not something that is
illusory,'' Cohen said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is to make an address Thursday outlining the diplomatic
and military strategy underway.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the president must see the final agreement
and then is expected to consult Congress again before he would send
in ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   During consultations and in testimony Wednesday, administration
officials emphasized how Europe is taking the larger role in the
proposed Kosovo settlement. In this regard, Cohen said, ``more
responsibility should be shifted to the Europeans to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever contribution we make to NATO in this regard should be
relatively small by comparison because we have been carrying a very
large load as far as the Air Force components. And should there be
any airstrikes ordered, we would be the ones carrying the load on
that,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said that instead of having an American
lead the peacekeeping force, he would recommend that a British
officer head it. ``This will send a signal that Europe and Great
Britain are beginning to assume a greater role and responsibility
for this regional conflict in the Balkans,'' he said in a later
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Congress will eventually support the president in this
conflict. We're not there yet, but I think we're getting there,''
Warner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
