<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0794 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARK-LOWERY-INTERVIEW     02-03 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARK-LOWERY-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS GUY IS FUNNY, MARK MY WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This interview had to happen. I needed to prove to my co-workers
that Mark Lowry, the Baptist storyteller/singer, is indeed NOT the
same human being as Mark Lowry _ that would be me _ the Pentecostal
preacher's kid who often tells stories and thinks he can sing.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry, who will appear this weekend at gospel singer Bill
Gaither's Homecoming Texas Style at the Fort Worth Convention
Center, has been mixing comedy and the faith for nearly 20 years.
His shtick: telling stories sated with nudge-nudge, wink-wink
in-jokes. He performs about 80 times in any given year, won a Dove
Award for his long-form video ``Mouth in Motion,'' and has written
several books, including a children's series called ``The
Adventures of Piper the Hyper Mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   His latest album, ``But Seriously,'' is indeed a serious piece,
so to speak, but count on him to sprinkle his comical parables
throughout his concert of original and standard gospel tunes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mark Lowry Web site (www.marklowry.com) is filled with
irreverent bits such as ``classic church bulletin bloopers'' and
``you might be a Southern Baptist ...'' (No.4: if the first
complete sentence you uttered was ``We've never done it this way
before.'')
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``fun things to do during boring sermons'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Slap your neighbor. See if they turn the other cheek. If not,
raise your hand and tell the preacher'' and ``Start from the back
of the church and try to crawl all the way to the front, under the
pews, without being noticed'' are two that have come to my mind
many times _ especially when visiting churches whose services are
less, um, hyper, than those he, Lowry, and I, Lowry, were raised
with (for example, those that actually list the order of the
service on a program, as if they already know that the spirit is
not going to move.)
</P>
<P>
   I should probably also mention Lowry's favorite Bible verse,
just because. It's 1 Chronicles 26:18: ``At Parbar, westward four
at the causeway, and two at Parbar.''
</P>
<P>
   But enough about him. To prove that Lowry and I are not one and
the same, I picked up the phone and called him, and I offer this
question-and-answer session as irrefutable proof.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I guess the most obvious question is, Mark, what's your
middle name?
</P>
<P>
   A: Alan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You didn't get a double dose of New Testament names like I
did _ Mark Timothy.
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I guess I didn't. Do you have a brother, Mark?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Yes: David Joseph. My sisters didn't get biblical names at
all, though. But enough about me. How did you get involved with
Christian comedy?
</P>
<P>
   A: I started out just singing. And I'd talk about things that
had happened to me and my family, and the people would just laugh.
I never set out to be a comedian. I don't like that word. I'm a
storyteller. Like Bill Cosby; he's a storyteller. People like Jay
Leno are comedians. You don't get to know anything about them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you just talk about my, I mean, your life.
</P>
<P>
   A: If I haven't lived it, I don't tell it. To me it isn't funny
if it isn't true.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of things do you talk about?
</P>
<P>
   A: For one, I like to shoot down those sacred cows. I don't deal
in politics, or in pulling down other individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you don't pick on fallen Christian icons?
</P>
<P>
   A: Once I used the phrase ``cried like Tammy Faye at a yard
sale.'' But that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your most recent story?
</P>
<P>
   A: One I'm calling ``From Toilet Plungers to the Resurrection,''
which is about when I recently bought a new house and discovered
Home Depot. I went looking for picture hangers and left with a
Jacuzzi. Later I had a party and ended up talking to an atheist who
was so interesting.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting atheist? Wait. Is that a punch line?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
