<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-RUSHMORE-TEX     02-03 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RUSHMORE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S COMING-OF-AGE FILM, BUT NO ONE GROW UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Take dead aim on the rich boys, get them in the cross hairs
and take them down,'' bored, out-of-it millionaire Herman Blume
(Bill Murray) lectures the benign, indifferent students of
``Rushmore,'' the elite boys' school that is the setting for Wes
Anderson's new comedy. (The picture had its debut at last season's
inaugural Fort Worth Film Festival.) One of the students, Max
Fischer (Jason Schwartzman) takes particular notice of Blume's
speech. Max, the protagonist of ``Rushmore,'' is a nervy, ambitious
nerd who sports his Rushmore blazer as if he spends his entire life
in it. He recognizes a kindred spirit in Herman and attaches
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Max has shoehorned himself into every after-school club and
extracurricular activity available and has created a few activities
that Rushmore didn't have before he got there. He writes
grandiloquent plays about big events from a perspective that he
must've gleaned from movies, dramas complete with onstage special
effects, like explosions. He has thrown himself into every aspect
of Rushmore, except his studies. ``He's the worst student we've
got,'' drawls Dr. Guggenheim (Brian Cox), the headmaster.
</P>
<P>
   When Max develops a crush on one of his teachers, Rosemary
Cross, (Olivia Williams, who seems far more human here than she did
in ``The Postman),'' his life goes off track. In his attempts to
impress, he gets himself expelled. And his mentor, Herman, becomes
his rival for Rosemary. Murray, with his contemplative shrewdness,
takes over the movie. For years, he has done startlingly good work
in pictures that have no place for him, going all the way back to
the restive spirit he brought to his portrayal of Hunter S.
Thompson in ``Where the Buffalo Roam.'' In ``Rushmore,'' Murray
finds just the place for his insinuating corrosiveness, sporting
pinstripe suits and matching shirt-and-tie ensembles that make him
look as if he aspires to be Matt Lauer or Johnny Cochran. In this
boys-will-be-boys tableau of Olympian pettiness, Max and Herman are
pitted against each other, with Max's aggressiveness impressing
even Herman.
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that Max is an aspiring actor-writer-director,
because he has a capacity for turning everything into melodrama,
and his cheesy self-dramatizing arrogance is funny. He has to make
himself the constant center of attention. He's a spoiled brat of
his own making, and the expectation that Anderson and co-writer
Owen Wilson set up is that Max will come to some realization about
himself. Or that Herman will grow up. Neither happens, so
``Rushmore'' is like an overly vivid cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson turns ``Rushmore'' into a handsomely mounted, grasping
pastiche that is part ``The Graduate,'' part Charles Schultz's
``Peanuts,'' with a liberal dollop of British popular culture from
Lindsay Anderson to ``Quadrophenia.'' It has a rangy, scavenger's
spirit, right down to rescuing Williams and Dirk Calloway (who
plays Max's best friend Mason Gamble and made his debut as the star
of ``Dennis the Menace)'' from their history of misuse in other
movies. It's as if the movie was written by Max, whose brain is
constantly ticking off opportunities to seize. (In interviews,
Anderson has the ingratiating, slightly untrustworthy quality of a
grown-up Max.)
</P>
<P>
   Every frame is presented like a painting, with burnished reds
and golds and yellows; the colors seem heartfelt. And the picture
has an autumnal melancholy, the understated yearning quality of the
'60s and '70's British pop music that fills the soundtrack.
``Rushmore'' has the sprawling ambition of British pop, a coil of
displaced anger, that makes the picture feel as if it is all over
the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rushmore'' also has the excitement of Brit-pop, brooding
smarts that churn things up, even when not much is going on in the
movie. The music generates energy, maybe doing some of the work
that we'd expect the movie to accomplish. ``Bottle Rocket,'' the
previous picture by Anderson and his co-writer, Owen Wilson, has a
loose, scattered feel that holds together because of the peculiar
ambitions of the wannabe petty hood Dignan (Wilson). There's also a
warmth in the midst of all of the bizarre enthusiasms in
``Rocket,'' brought to the picture by brother Luke Wilson (who has
a cameo in ``Rushmore).'' Even when ``Rushmore'' is clicking, it
has an anecdotal feel, and all the anecdotes don't mesh into a
whole as they did in ``Bottle Rocket.'' Eventually, the movie just
rolls to an end. But Anderson creates such an endearing mess that
you find yourself pulling for the movie. Part of that desire to see
the picture succeed is that Anderson has found a way get a major
studio _ Touchstone, the home of ``Armageddon'' _ to underwrite his
specific vision.
</P>
<P>
   The film often has a magnificent silliness that makes you laugh
right out loud, such as when ``Rushmore'' makes one of its direct
quotes from some other movie, like ``Heat.'' But that's also what
hampers ``Rushmore;'' after a while, it begins to feel as if it has
no life of its own, as if it's all quotes and homages. That is,
with the exception of Murray's courageous honesty. His performance
has a life, a reality, all its own. He brings the floating whimsy
down to Earth and gives it flesh and blood. He also helps you
forgive a lot of ``Rushmore's'' scattered feel. He definitely knows
what he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rushmore'' is rated PG-13 for adult language and mild
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rushmore:'' Four stars on a scale of one to five
</P>
<P>
   Director: Wes Anderson
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Jason Schwartzman, Bill Murray
</P>
<P>
   Length: 93 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/
</P>
</TEXT>
