<SLUG> BC-LYNX-RELEASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID CONTROVERSY, LYNX REINTRODUCED IN COLORADO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   (dal) 
 By MINDY SINK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH FORK, Colo. _ After a few minutes of terrified hesitation,
a lynx, a cat not seen in Colorado in over 25 years, was
reintroduced here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-pound, 3-year-old female was the first of two lynx
released on private property in the Weminuche Wilderness area of
the San Juan Mountains, and the first of about 50 lynx to be
reintroduced this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're back,'' hollered Gene Byrne, a wildlife biologist with
the Colorado Division of Wildlife, as a second tuft-eared cat
darted across the sunlit snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never left,'' another wildlife official, Bill Andree, said
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these elusive cats were ever really gone from Colorado
has been a subject of much speculation in recent years. The Earth
Liberation Front, for example, a radical animal-rights group, was
so certain of the Lynx's presence in Colorado that last October it
claimed responsibility for a major fire at a ski resort the group
believed was threatening a habitat for the animals.
</P>
<P>
   The last known sighting of a lynx in Colorado was near Vail in
1973. But there is no doubt that the lynx once roamed this state
freely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a relatively common species in Colorado before the
20th century,'' said Todd Malmsbury, a spokesman for the Colorado
Division of Wildlife. ``We can't say if their decline was caused by
human settlement and all its impacts _ mining, pollution,
agriculture, recreation _ or something else.'' The Lynx's
disappearance may also have been the result of a decline in their
primary prey, the snowshoe hare, or of trapping.
</P>
<P>
   The spread of development in the Vail area prevented officials
from releasing the mountain cats there. Instead, they settled on
this site next to San Juan-Rio Grande National Forest, about 200
miles from the popular ski resort area.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many people, too many dogs, too many everything
up there,'' said Malmsbury. ``It doesn't mean they can't repopulate
there though.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their entryway into 6,500 square miles of
wilderness,'' said Cal Joyner, a supervisor for the U.S. Forest
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The lynx released Wednesday, which were brought 1,700 miles from
British Columbia last week, are part of a $2 million, 5-year
program by the Colorado Division of Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The reintroduction sparked a lawsuit by local cattlemen and
back-country tour groups anticipating that the animal would bring
about restrictions on land use. Their primary concern is not the
lynx, itself, which is not a natural predator of livestock, but the
restrictions that may result if the cats are later declared to be a
``threatened'' or ``endangered'' species.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on whether to include the lynx, which is thriving in
Canada and Alaska, on the federal Endangered Species List is
expected by summer. A handful of states _ Montana, Idaho, Maine and
Washington _ are believed to have lynx populations. It is currently
on the Colorado Endangered Species List.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just assumed they were here before, but once they're
legally listed, we don't know what falls after that,'' said Freeman
Lester, a 63-year old rancher and president of the Colorado
Cattlemen's Association. ``Recreational people might be affected,
and some grazing.''
</P>
<P>
   But others note that there are already restrictions since it was
assumed the lynx still existed here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every action we take _ whether it's grazing allotment or
recreational use _ we plan as if they were present,'' said Joyner.
``To have the animals suddenly here shouldn't change our management
style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
