A0802 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PAYBACK-TEX     02-03 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PAYBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULP FICTION, FOR REAL THIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by the goofy trailers for ``Payback.'' This is
one tough movie. It signals the return of Mel Gibson's ``Mad Max''
meanness, which appeared to have vanished after his increasingly
clownish turns in the ``Lethal Weapon'' series and an over-the-top
sputter-fest in 1997's ``Conspiracy Theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson and director Brian Helgeland reportedly clashed during
``Payback's'' filming. If so, the end product is a sign of the
rookie director's confidence, because it's more his movie than
Gibson's. This is real pulp fiction, devoid of Tarantino-influenced
pop-culture references and giddy ironies. Instead, its ironies and
gallows humor are its own, rooted in detective magazines and
especially the fiction of Donald E. Westlake, who wrote the source
novel ``The Hunter'' under the pseudonym Richard Stark.
</P>
<P>
   From the first scene, which shows a back-alley doctor removing
bullets from the barely alive, single-named Porter (Gibson),
Helgeland shows that he's in touch with Westlake/Stark's darker
side. Porter caught the bullets when his faithless wife and his
scheming partner set him up after a heist. They didn't make sure
they finished the job, though, and Porter wants his $70,000 share
of the take.
</P>
<P>
   Getting it won't be easy. Porter not only has to track down the
wife and partner, he has to deal with corrupt cops, Asian gangsters
and a syndicate called the Outfit, which is so
close.MDBU/d.MDNM/-ranked that it houses its thugs in its own
hotel. Mean isn't necessarily lean, and the movie's nefarious
characters also include Ally McBeal's Lucy Liu in a scene-stealing
turn as a sado.MDNM/masochistic hooker and former ``ER'' player
Maria Bello as a more benevolent hooker. The movie's portrayal of
women isn't enlightened, but then, no character here is on a guest
list for lunch with the pope.
</P>
<P>
   The overpopulation is a switch from 1967's ``Point Blank,'' John
Boorman's stripped-down, martinis-meet-acid adaptation of the same
material. But the added characters help ``Payback'' feel like its
own movie instead of another pointless remake. A recent article
referred to Gibson as a 43-year-old kid, which was cause for
concern for those familiar with ``Payback's'' story. Its vengeful
protagonist needs to be played by a determined man, not an
overgrown boy (Lee Marvin, steely and obsessed, was perfectly cast
in the '67 version).
</P>
<P>
   Gibson pulls it off, though, with a gravel-voiced intensity he
seems to have borrowed from Nick Nolte; it's easy to imagine that
Gibson screamed himself hoarse before every take to get that rasp
in his throat. One story going around is that Gibson came to
Helgeland worried that his character wasn't ``heroic''
enough..MDNM/ Helgeland .MDBR/either .MDNM/set Gibson straight or
wisely stood his ground, because Gibson shows a no-nonsense
maturity that he seldom shows in his crime-drama roles, and he
gives the movie a gutsy center. He may not be heroic enough, but
he's antiheroic enough.
</P>
<P>
   Helgeland, who wrote the screenplays for the dazzling ``L.A.
Confidential'' and the whacked-out ``Conspiracy Theory,'' makes a
sharp directorial debut here. He smartly has Gibson underplay his
role, surrounding the star with scenery-chewing turns by Gregg
Henry, David Paymer and William Devane. They fuel Porter's
off-kilter universe, as does the timeless retro look that Helgeland
and cinematographer Ericson Core give the movie. The filmmakers
leach out the color, so that even the daffodils look gray, adding
to the cold-blooded feel.
</P>
<P>
   The director's only missteps are keeping a few lines of
'90s-esque dialogue. which vitiate the movie's pulpy veneer, and
wasting the deliciously watchable John Glover in a small part as a
henchman. Why isn't Glover, instead of a dubious actor like Kris
Kristofferson, playing the baddest bad guy? Although Kristofferson
ekes out something resembling a performance, Glover would have
relished such a role, giving the movie more gritty panache.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a nice movie, and the easily offended should take
heed: The violence is brutal, the characters unpleasant. If its
treatment of women is disturbing _ Bello and Liu'.MDBR/s.MDNM/
characters take some vicious shots, but they give as good as they
get _ then it's even more unsettling to hear scattered audience
laughter during these scenes, which aren't played for comedy. But
as a genre piece, it works. Maybe it's not in a league with the
assured sexiness of last year's ``Out of Sight,'' but it has a
personality of its own _ or at least that of a growling, volatile
pit bull. It's a relief knowing that Gibson can still star in
something with this much teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback'' is rated R for harsh violence, strong language and
sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
