<SLUG> BC-BRADLEES-RECOVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLESS COMES OUT OF BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will Bradlees Inc. be like Ames Department Stores, a retail
phoenix that now flourishes, or like Caldor, which recently
announced plans to close all its stores and go out of business?
</P>
<P>
   After 3 1/2 years of doing business under Bankruptcy Court
protection, Bradlees emerged Wednesday from Chapter 11, but the
future of a chain of discount-department stores that sell
everything from clothing to kitchen gear and consumer electronics
may still be up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   With a new three-year financing facility of $270 million from
BankBoston Corp., Bradlees chairman and chief executive Peter
Thorner is optimistic even as Target, a much larger national
discount chain, prepares to invade New England.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years Bradlees has managed to ``carve out its
own niche'' with ``contemporary'' apparel, a niche less ``upscale''
than Target's and different from Ames', he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enormously upbeat,'' said Thorner, who noted that Bradlees
has been holding its own at 17 locations, many in New Jersey, where
the two chains go head to head.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston is not only upbeat about Bradlees, but ``delighted''
to ``assist in the preservation of this leading New England
retailer,'' said Ward K. Mooney, president of the bank's retail
division.
</P>
<P>
   Under its reorganization plan, about $165 million will be
distributed among Bradlees' creditors; that includes the issuance
of new common stock with an estimated value of $85 million,
Bradlees said. Those new shares began trading Wednesday on Nasdaq,
opening at 10 and closing at 9 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   While in bankruptcy, Bradlees, based in Braintree, Mass., was
delisted from the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization plan provides ``no consideration for old
shareholders,'' said one of Bradlees' attorneys, Stuart Hirshfield
of Dewey Ballantine LLP, a New York law firm. The old shares have
been ``rendered valueless,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thorner has been part of remarkable retail turnarounds before,
most notably in helping Connecticut-based Ames get out of
bankruptcy in the early 1990s. Today Ames is enjoying great success
under chief executive Joseph Ettore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Thorner is widely respected in the retail industry,
especially among vendors,'' said Stewart L. Cohen, chief executive
of Paragon Capital LLC, a Needham company that lends to retailers
but has had no business with Bradlees.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy offers a struggling retailer a chance to get out of
expensive leases and close unprofitable stores. And that's pretty
much what Bradlees did as it slashed expenses.
</P>
<P>
   While in bankruptcy, Bradlees closed about 33 stores and shed
6,000 jobs in a bid to become lean and mean. Other cost-cutting
measures initiated by Thorner allowed Bradlees to reduce losses.
</P>
<P>
   Bradlees now operates 103 stores, including 36 in Massachusetts,
and projects annual sales of $1.4 billion, down from $1.9 billion
in 1994. It now employs about 10,000 in seven Northeastern states
from Maine to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Bradlees exiting Chapter 11 while Caldor is liquidating?
The answer may hinge as much on the realities of filing for
bankruptcy in the 1990s as on retail acumen.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, creditors of a bankrupt retailer were its
vendors and lenders, and they often had a vested interest in the
retailer's long-term survival.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays a retailer's debt can be sold to Wall Street
investment firms. Sometimes these firms conclude that the
retailer's liquidation is the best way to maximize their
investment. As a result, a retailer's fate may depend as much on
having patient creditors as on having a sound business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Tough competiton was one factor that forced Bradlees to take
refuge in Chapter 11, and tough competition hasn't gone away.
</P>
<P>
   With its recent acquisition of Hills Stores Inc. of
Canton, &UR;  &LR; Mass., Ames has gotten stronger. Target is moving into New
England, and some Wall Street analysts are predicting Target will
take over some of Caldor's best store locations. Wednesday a Target
spokeswoman declined to comment on the company's plans.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, Bradlees could also be hurt by Caldor's
going-out-of-business sales, which in theory could siphon away many
of its customers over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bradlees found it difficult to compete against a rapidly
sinking rival like Caldor, can you imagine the outlook once the
(Caldor) stores are bought by Target or Kmart?'' asked Kurt
Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1958, the first Bradlees opened its doors in New
London, Conn., in an era when discount department stores flourished
by providing consumers with one-stop shopping.
</P>
<P>
   But by the 1980s, superstore chains such as Staples and Home
Depot began to emerge. With a larger size and a narrower focus,
they gave shoppers one less reason to visit regional discounters.
Then rapid expansion by national giants such as Wal-Mart and Kmart
offered more discount shopping choices.
</P>
<P>
   All this competition would seem to make an endangered species
out of the regional discount chain. But the success of Ames proves
that a smaller player can still thrive among giants.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a ``somewhat sluggish third quarter,'' Thorner is upbeat
about Bradlees, noting that a sharp increase in January sales was
only one of many recent improvements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
