<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA THINKS HARKES IS WORTH THE RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution have acquired the Major
League Soccer rights to John Harkes, but his concerns are elsewhere
for now.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes will join the Revolution by mid-March if his current
club, Nottingham Forest, fails to exercise an option to buy his
contract from MLS. And Harkes has understandably placed his English
Premier League career above other priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Nottingham Forest is preparing for Saturday's match against
Manchester United, and Harkes was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Revolution player-coach Walter Zenga is apparently satisfied
with the possibility of Harkes joining other newcomers such as Dan
Calichman, Kris Kelderman, and Giovanni Savarese, also acquired
from MLS teams, and free agents Brian Bliss, Unisa Conteh, Paulo
Dos Santos, and Ze Rodrigues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter is getting the players he wants,'' assistant coach Sid
Mazzola said. ``They fit the criteria of having leadership
qualities, they are strong players, and they will give the team a
lot on and off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, who is in Italy preparing for the team's preseason
training, is comfortable with players whom others consider castoffs
and players who have clashed with coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``These problems can happen with anybody, any player,'' Mazzola
said. ``It's a matter of managing the situation. You can't get
along with everybody, but these are all good guys and they all want
to be winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach has to be in charge,'' Mazzola added. ``Everyone
says Walter did whatever he wanted as a player, but he did whatever
he wanted within parameters. He is a professional. He has a strong
personality and he voices his opinion. But he was not a rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes, 32, has a reputation for being outspoken and potentially
disruptive. But Revolution defender Richard Goulooze, a former
Harkes teammate at Derby County in England, is surprised at the
label.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over there, he was one of the guys, he did the job, and he
played well,'' Goulooze said. ``A lot of things get blown out of
proportion. He was kicked out of the national team and replaced as
captain at D.C., but those are choices a coach makes. Walter
doesn't worry about someone's reputation as long as you do the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes has mostly been able to produce. He joined Sheffield
Wednesday in 1990 and became the first US player to have success in
the Premier League, scoring a goal in the 1993 League Cup final at
Wembley. In MLS, he helped D.C. United win the 1996 and '97 MLS Cup
championships.
</P>
<P>
   But his reputation suffered when former US national coach Steve
Sampson left him off the team after qualifying for the World Cup
finals last year. Sampson, who had once promoted Harkes as the
team's ``captain for life,'' cited Harkes's hesitancy in changing
positions and accused him of being insubordinate. Harkes, who had
played in two World Cup finals and had a six-year career in Europe,
clashed with Sampson, who had not played professionally and was in
his first major coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different attitude in Europe,'' Goulooze said. ``There
are not a lot of outspoken people in this league, but there are in
Europe. It can bounce back on you if you don't play well. John is
outspoken, but that's not a problem. We all know John and he's won
two championships in D.C.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
