<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER PROFIT DROPS   BY MORE THAN HALF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time Warner Inc. said Wednesday that improvements in its
publishing, cable network, entertainment and music divisions during
the fourth quarter helped offset a loss from its satellite
broadcasting business.
</P>
<P>
   The media giant reported a fourth-quarter profit of $90 million,
down from $216 million in the period a year earlier. Per share
earnings were a loss of 17 cents a diluted share after preferred
dividends, better than analysts' expectations. Wall Street had
expected a loss of 19 cents a share. In the fourth quarter of 1997,
Time Warner had an 11 cent profit.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the quarter rose to $4.2 billion from $3.84 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the quarter had been depressed by two unusual
events: the redemption of preferred stock at a premium and
writedowns related to the sale of PrimeStar, its satellite
business, to DirectTV. At the same time the 1997 quarter was
inflated by a one-time sale of assets: Time Warner's investments in
Hasbro and E: Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner chairman Gerald Levin continued to emphasize the
company's growth in all its divisions, its ability to generate
cash, to pay down debt and to keep key ratios of debt to cash flow
at low levels. (Cash flow is earnings before interest, taxes and
amortization.)
</P>
<P>
   ``By growing its cash flow and shrinking the amount of capital
invested, Time Warner can generate higher returns on investments,''
said Christopher Dixon, an analyst at Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Levin was careful to promise analysts Wednesday that the
company's capital spending would grow only in line with inflation,
so that key ratios would continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has been pleased with the company's performance.
Shares of Time Warner rose $2.8125, to $64.0625. The stock has
risen from a 52-week low of $31.59375 on Feb. 6 to a Jan. 20 high
of $67.0625.
</P>
<P>
   The stock's performance has also been helped by Monday's news
that Time Warner had completed a long-rumored joint venture with
AT&AMP;T Corp. They will jointly sell local telephone service over Time
Warner's cable television lines.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that cash flow at its music business, which had
been having severe problems, rose 34 percent, to $205 million for
the quarter. Warner Music had 23 of the year's top 100 best-selling
albums, including releases from Madonna and Alanis Morissette.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing division's cash flow rose 18 percent, to $234
million. Time Warner said the results were bolstered by gains at In
Style, People and Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Levin also noted that the new Teen People magazine had an
extremely successful debut.
</P>
<P>
   At the Entertainment Group, which is 75 percent owned by Time
Warner and 25 percent owned by Media One, cash flow rose 20
percent, to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Turner cable networks reported a 21 percent increase in cash
flow, to $201 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
