<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-BIRDS-OF-PREY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDS   OF   PREY COURSE IS NOT FOR SHRINKING VIOLETS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., France, Norway, Japan)  By BARBARA LLOYD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAVER CREEK, Colo. _ It has been in use for only a year. But
already the Birds of Prey downhill course in this resort town has
gained a worldwide reputation. Not unlike facing a grizzly bear in
the West, to have skied Birds of Prey is to regale others with a
tale of encounter.
</P>
<P>
   David Kelly, a bartender here, speaks with a certain reverence
about the time last March when he and a buddy sneaked up a side
trail early one morning, then snowboarded down the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were mischievous,'' Kelly said. ``But we agreed, come on,
let's do it. So we hiked up, climbed under the ropes that blocked
it off, and went down in knee-deep powder. Our legs were burning at
the end, but we were just glad we had all that powder to help us
get down the steeps.''
</P>
<P>
   For the men competing here in the downhill and super-G
competitions this week in the world Alpine ski championships, Birds
of Prey is a sheet of near-vertical ice sprayed down with hoses
before race time.
</P>
<P>
   For the likes of Hermann Maier and Lasse Kjus, the two skiers
who tied for gold medals here Tuesday in the super-G, Birds of Prey
is a run to be conquered. But to Bernhard Russi, a gold medalist in
the 1971 and 1972 Olympic downhills who designed the course, it is
a personal triumph. The Birds of Prey course for the two men's
events here is essentially the same, with the downhill starting at
the top of 11,427-foot Beaver Creek mountain and the super-G a
little lower at 10,948.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw Birds of Prey,'' Russi said during an
interview here, ``I told others, I don't want to change the
mountain. But I want to listen to the mountain and see what it
tells me. I could see this was a well-balanced mountain with all
the features you need to ski it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than many of the other famous ski runs Russi has designed _
at Calgary, Alberta, for the 1988 Olympics; Albertville, France,
for the 1992 Games; Lillehammer, Norway, in 1994, and Nagano,
Japan, in 1998 _ Birds of Prey already had a strong personality.
</P>
<P>
   When Vail Resorts, which owns Beaver Creek, received the
go-ahead to stage the 1999 world championships here, Russi walked
the mountain with personnel from the U. S. Forest Service, which
leases the land to Vail. Along the way, he tagged trees with
different colored ribbons to see where the main trail might follow
the fall-line best. Then he watched to see where the snow fell.
</P>
<P>
   Not much more had to be done when he designed the course.
</P>
<P>
   At Screech Owl Jump, a point two-thirds of the way down the
1.6-mile downhill course, Russi thought the runoff was too short
for a decent landing. ``I like to have the possibility of letting
people fly at least 180 feet, and still land on a steep hill and
not on a flat,'' Russi said.
</P>
<P>
   Racers know that their speed is likely to start building at the
Brink, three sharp turns over a natural step in the mountain near
its peak. With a 65 percent incline _ 90 percent is straight up and
down _ the area is steep.
</P>
<P>
   Near Russi's Ride, a spate of open terrain just below the
halfway mark, a racer is likely to reach a speed of 90 miles an
hour. Around the bend at Golden Eagle, about three-quarters of the
way down, a skier is swept into the air for at least 200 feet. He
then heads into the Abyss, a left-hand turn that hurtles him into a
final jump before the finish.
</P>
<P>
   After the races here are over next week, Birds of Prey will be
open to the public, albeit, for experts only. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
