<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SURVEY04-COX     02-03 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SURVEY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public `disgusted' with Olympics, survey shows
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With one-third of Americans claiming that their
impression of the Olympics has been damaged, the International
Olympic Committee is moving swiftly to regain the confidence of the
deep pockets that are affected most by what the public thinks about
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of dollars are at stake. Corporate support has become
the lifeblood of the Games, and organizers of the upcoming Sydney
and Salt Lake City Olympics are worried that the widening scandal
will staunch their corporate fund-raising and force them into
staging cut-rate Games.
</P>
<P>
   They have reason to worry. Roughly one-third of the public is
``totally disgusted'' by the worst corruption scandal in the IOC's
105-year history, according to a new study conducted by Performance
Research, an independent market-research firm in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the respondents to the survey conducted Feb. 1-5 said
they were aware of allegations that Salt Lake City Olympic
officials gave lavish gifts, scholarships and cash to IOC members
in exchange for favorable votes the bid process that decided where
the Games will be held.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the Americans surveyed blame the IOC, rather
than the Salt Lake organization or corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   But while approximately one-third of the 200 respondents say
their overall impressions of the Olympic sponsors have been hurt,
relatively few indicated they are less likely to support those
companies.
</P>
<P>
   That finding could create some cautious optimism among sponsors
who say they are holding on to their checkbooks until the IOC
repairs its reputation and produces credible evidence that the
Olympic brand is not permanently damaged.
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC is to allay the concerns of its corporate
benefactors, it will have to do it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is still $130 million short of the $455 million it need
from sponsors. Salt Lake City needs $245 million more to meet its
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be a big challenge for both Sydney and Salt
Lake to reach their financial goals,'' said Bob Heisner, senior
vice president for strategic planning at Advantage International, a
Washington, D.C., marketing consultant that represents Olympic
sponsors. ``And if they don't, the IOC bears some responsibility
for making them whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more important to the Olympic movement, NBC is in
the market now to sell commercial time for its broadcast next fall
of the Sydney Games. NBC is halfway to its estimated $900 million
break-even goal. But even in the best of times, the last half is
twice as hard to get.
</P>
<P>
   The Games' biggest sponsors _ multinational companies such as
Coca-Cola and Eastman Kodak, which are investing as much as $500
million _ have pressed the IOC to conduct its own research to
determine what, if any, damage the scandal has wreaked on the
Olympic image.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the IOC's marketing agency, Meridian Management, is
planning a survey that it hopes will reassure sponsors and
encourage them to sign on for the 2002 and 2004 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure consumers are still excited about the
Olympic Games and they draw a distinction between all this other
stuff and the Games,'' said Terence Burns, senior vice president at
Meridian in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the 11 companies paying an average $50 million each
to sponsor the current 1998-2000 Olympiad have renewed their
sponsorships for the Salt Lake City Winter Games and the Athens
Summer Games: Coca-Cola and Time/Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the IOC and Meridian we wanted that research,'' said
Susan Rosenberg, Olympic spokeswoman for Atlanta-based United
Parcel Service, which has yet to renew its sponsorship. ``We still
are not (subscribing) to the theory that the product is tainted.
We're not going to do a knee-jerk, but we will take a hard look at
what the research tells us.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the U.S. Olympic Committee released the
results of its own national market survey, which it says shows
support for Olympic athletes and the corporations that pay their
way.
</P>
<P>
   But the USOC's survey also showed that the public wants major
changes in the way Olympic host cities are selected and greater
oversight of organizers. The survey found that 73 percent said
``significant changes'' were needed in the host-city selection
process and that 83 percent said Olympic organizing committees
should be watched more closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is legitimately concerned,'' said Stephen Disson,
whose Washington, D.C., consulting firm represents several Olympic
sponsors. ``No one is talking about bolting, but they want to get
the thing resolved and behind them as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies will use the current scandal to negotiate lower
prices for sponsorships and seek escape clauses in contracts if the
near-daily embarassing revelations don't stop, Olympic sponsor
consultants say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect sponsors to try to use it to their advantage,''
Heisner said. ``This will potentially affect the price... . My
sense is it will delay things, and that always works ... to the
sponsor's advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Ebersol, president of NBC Sports, which has invested $3.5
billion in the next five Olympics, said Wednesday he hasn't felt
the pinch yet. He's made nine Olympic presentations in the last
seven days to potential advertisers for his network's 161-hour
broadcast of the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All nine expressed sentiment they want to enter into
negotiations,'' Ebersol said. ``The Olympics, in terms of viewers
and advertisers, are the athletes and competition. At no reasonable
level does anyone think that has been impacted.''
</P>
<P>
   However, all but two of NBC's signed advertisers are current IOC
and USOC sponsors _ companies that have already paid the
multimillion-dollar entry fee for the Sydney Games. They have to
advertise to protect their investment.
</P>
<P>
   And some media buyers contend their clients who have not yet
bought sponsorships are balking at buying commercial time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this scandal has a long way to go, I would think a
number of advertisers are at the very least going to hold back
now,'' said Gene DeWitt, whose media-buying firm counts several
sponsors among its clients. ``Nobody wants to go to their board of
directors and say they have put $100 million into something that is
embarrassing the company.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWitt and others say there's no doubt the Olympic brand is
tainted _ at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question there is a value assigned in an Olympic
sponsorship to the wholesomeness and completely uncontroversial
positive quality of what an Olympics has stood for and what an
advertiser stands for,'' DeWitt said. ``And this has been
lessened.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Payne, the IOC's director of marketing in Lausanne, said
this week he too expects sponsors to use the controversy to their
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When advertising agencies negotiate the prices... they look
for every opportunity to argue that the price should be lower,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Payne contends the public differentiates between ``the backhouse
problems they've been reading about and the Games themselves.
Normally, the IOC doesn't even register on their radar screens, but
now it's out there, and people are aware that there are some
problems. But they're also seeing that steps are being taken to
respond to the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Four IOC members have resigned in disgrace, five others face
expulsion and revelations continue to pour in about questionable
activities.
</P>
<P>
   However, the IOC cleared Sydney of any wrongdoing in connection
with $70,000 in inducements offered to two African IOC members in
1993, on the eve of the Australian capital's selection as host of
the 2000 Summer Games. Initially, the IOC said it would launch a
full investigation, but after reviewing documents of Sydney's bid
with Australian Olympics chief John Coates, it determined the
organizers did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``That potential fog had to be lifted in a hurry; they've got to
move,'' observed A.D. Frazier Jr., the former No. 2 official at the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games. He is spending next week
in Sydney advising organizers on Games operations.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier said he will suggest areas where Sydney can cut back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have the opportunity,'' he said, ``to reset the
expectations for hospitality surrounding an Olympic Games, which
might be a very good thing driven by these financial challenges _
to set a standard that is appropriate for the Games for the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
