<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0816 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-TV-INTERNET-2ND     02-03 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-TV-INTERNET-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: on Congress. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On one side in the fight are the formidable lobbying forces of
AT&AMP;T and Tele-Communications Inc., two of the most powerful players
in Washington. The companies have an impressive roster of lobbyists
and lawyers who once worked in the federal government and Congress.
They include Cicconi, a former top White House official in Reagan
and Bush administrations and now the general counsel of AT&AMP;T;
Philip L. Verveer, a leading telecommunications lawyer and close
friend of Bill Clinton since their days together at Georgetown
University, whose wife is the chief of staff to Hillary Rodham
Clinton; and Kevin Joseph, who recently stepped down as senior
counsel to Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, the ranking Democrat on the
Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and Tansportation.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition on the other side is being led by Greg Simon, the
former domestic policy adviser to Vice President Gore, and Richard
Bond, former chairman of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing what Microsoft is accused of doing - building a
system where they say you can't separate the transmission from the
actual content,'' said Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the
Washington office of Consumers Union, referring to the government's
antitrust suit filed against the software company. ``They're saying
if you want AOL, we'll let you have it but you have to pay At Home
first. This is precisely what telephone companies can't do. The
request from our side is, Let's open up access to cable wire the
same way we require them to open up for programming.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the Federal Communications Commission has
declined to step into the fight but has said it will watch the
situation closely. Officials there say they do not want to do
anything that might impede the progress of upgrading the cable
lines.
</P>
<P>
   But cable regulators in a growing number of cities, including
San Francisco, Los Angeles and Seattle, have held hearings and
vowed to consider the issue as franchise licenses are renewed this
year. And one city, Portland, Ore., has blocked AT&AMP;T's cable
venture from moving in without first opening its proposed new
broadband pipeline to rival gateways like America Online. The move
by the city's cable regulators recently prompted the telephone
company to file a lawsuit in federal court there.
</P>
</TEXT>
