<HEADLINE>
DOW UP 92.69 AFTER FED OPTS NOT TO CHANGE RATES
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paced by renewed vigor in technology companies, stock
prices marched higher Wednesday as Federal Reserve policy-makers
left interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed's decision was widely expected, analysts said the
meeting created some early nervousness and then touched off some
late-session profit taking.
</P>
<P>
   In between, however, most major gauges moved steadily higher,
despite the close balance between the number of advances and
declines, 1,645 to 1,391, respectively, on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gains have been concentrated, but while we're very narrow, I
still think there is a bias to the upside,'' said Steven Goldman, a
market strategist at Weeden &AMP; Co. And he said there was little
chance of a significant skid. Except for 1981-82, he said, the
market has never in modern times dropped more than 7 percent within
six months of two cuts in the Fed's discount rate, which happened
late last year.
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 92.69
points, or 1 percent, to 9,366.81. The technology-laden Nasdaq
composite index rose even more, 29.99 points, or 1.22 percent, to
2,493.41, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index edged up
10.08 points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,272.07.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics and computer-component stocks were among the day's
standouts, along with oil drilling and some financials, notably
Chase Manhattan and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which were rumored
to be merger partners. Morgan Stanley rose 2], to 91}, after
trading as high as 95, while Chase rose 2 9/16, to 79].
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, upgraded to ``outperform'' by Morgan Stanley, jumped 2|,
to 36 13/16. It was the second-biggest contributor to the Dow after
AT&AMP;T, which climbed 3 1/16, to 95.
</P>
<P>
   But while hefty gains were posted by an assortment of technology
stocks _ Intel, up 4 1/16; Micron Technology, up 6~; Texas
Instruments, up 4 11/16; Ebay, up 24, and Amazon.com, up 15{ _
others faltered. These included Cisco Systems, which disappointed
some investors with its announcement late Tuesday of earnings just
a penny better than the consensus forecast with no stock split. It
fell 1 17/64, to 111[. Another casualty was 3Com, which fell 6}, to
37].
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking profits in some of the blue-chip technologies,''
said Alan Hoffman, a senior portfolio manager at Value Line Asset
Management. ``It's mixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber, which announced a complex alliance with
Japan's Sumitomo Rubber Industries, gained 1|, to 52. Gains for oil
service companies included Schlumberger, up 2 13/16, to 52 7/16,
and Halliburton, up 2, to 30}, with Exxon, Texaco and Chevron all
gaining more than a point.
</P>
<P>
   Perot Systems, which went public Tuesday at 16, surged 18], to
61~. Berkshire Hathaway A shares rose 2,700 to 76,500, bringing its
gain to 16.5 percent over the last five sessions; Paine Webber
circulated a bullish report on the holding company last week.
</P>
<P>
   Among the analysts pointing to lack of breadth and liquidity in
the market was Kenneth Safian of Safian Investment Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very leveraged economy,'' he said, one implication
being that ``people have to sell stock A to buy stock B.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
