A0818 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEZER-MURDER-HNS &LR;      02-03 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEZER-MURDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESSES TELL JURY OF MURDER DEFENDANT'S TROUBLING EXPLANATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN AUGUSTINE, Texas _ For years, Marjorie Nugent, an aged,
wealthy widow from Carthage, was virtually inseparable from her
unlikely best friend, one-time mortician Bernie Tiede, a man half
her age.
</P>
<P>
   Ever solicitous, he squired her about town, hired limousines on
her birthday and _ at her expense _ traveled the world.
</P>
<P>
   But after mid-November 1996 a strange thing happened. Nugent
vanished. Prosecutors say that's because Tiede had blasted Nugent
four times in the back with a .22-caliber rifle and stashed her
body in a freezer.
</P>
<P>
   For the next nine months, friends and relatives who asked about
her welfare, were offered Tiede's believable, but vaguely troubling
explanations.
</P>
<P>
   As testimony in Tiede's trial on murder charges entered its
second day Wednesday, witnesses told jurors that a variety of clues
led them to believe something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One of Nugent's neighbors, Sherry McNeely, testified unusual
events took place at Nugent's showplace home during the winter of
1996. The once-fastidiously maintained lawn grew weedy and wild;
the back yard wasn't mowed at all. For the first time, ``there was
a lot of coming and going.''
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably, Nugent's pet dog, a black chow, appeared outside
in the dead of winter with all its hair shaved.
</P>
<P>
   But strangest of all were the Christmas decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Nugent publicly celebrated the season by placing
``a couple of soldiers'' on her front porch. At Christmas 1996, the
neighbor testified, the Nugent house was ablaze with lights and a
giant Christmas tree was visible through the windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very out of character,'' she said. ``And the tree was
up until the last of March.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Pollard, who was active in the Methodist church at which
Tiede was a lay preacher and sang in the choir, testified she asked
Tiede about Nugent's welfare on a number of occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Once, he told her Nugent was visiting a sister who lived out of
state. Another time he said Louisiana friends had taken her to
their home for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people asked,'' Pollard said, ``and I understood that
she was very ill. This probably was in the spring of '97. Once he
said she was very ill and he was afraid he was losing her.''
</P>
<P>
   Nugent's sister Merrill Rhodes testified that Tiede told her the
older woman had suffered a stroke and been hospitalized at the
Scott and White Hospital in Temple in Bell County. ``He said she
was doing fine and he would bring her home as soon as he
established a staff,'' she said. ``He said he was tired of driving
back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you comfortable with that explanation?'' asked Panola
County District Attorney Danny Buck Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Rhodes said. ``I didn't know what else to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Nugent's cousin, Ruth Cockrell, said she often spent sleepless
nights worrying about Tiede's truthfulness. Her cousin's friend,
she said, had offered a variety of explanations for her absence.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the spring of 1997, Tiede told her Nugent had been
admitted to the Temple hospital for surgery. ``I'll be right with
her,'' Cockrell testified he told her. ``The next day he called
with all the details. He said she was out of surgery and in
recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he asked Cockrell for a favor. He asked her to meet
repairmen who were scheduled to repair a gate at Nugent's house. He
would remain with Nugent.
</P>
<P>
   Cockrell readily agreed, but later realized she didn't have a
key to the gate. She called the Temple hospital to ask Tiede about
the key's whereabouts, but was told Nugent wasn't registered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sleep a wink that night,'' she recalled from the
witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   When she queried Tiede about the discrepancy, he replied that
Nugent had been lodged in an old part of the hospital and didn't
have a telephone in her room.
</P>
<P>
   Cockrell said she often felt uneasy about Tiede's stories, but
when she questioned him further, he always allayed her fears. ``He
could give such detail,'' she said. ``Oh, he was convincing, yes,
sir. But too many things just didn't add up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid to go to anyone. If I was wrong, I would be
laughed out of Carthage. ... (Still) I just had the feeling that
something was not right.''
</P>
<P>
   About four months later, in mid-August 1997, a Carthage banker
notified Nugent's son, Rod, an Amarillo medical examiner, about the
woman's absence. He authorized law officers to enter the family
home, where they found Nugent's sheet-wrapped body beneath the
vegetables in a chest-style freezer.
</P>
<P>
   If Tiede, 40, is convicted of the 81-year-old woman's slaying,
he could be sentenced to as much as 99 years in prison and fined
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
