<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: OBSERVERS INVITED
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch have been invited
to send observers to assess the paramilitary violence that is
impeding the Ulster peace effort. The invitation, by David Trimble,
the Protestant first minister of the new Assembly, was welcomed by
Roman Catholic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET'S IMMUNITY QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   An expert in international law said Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the
former Chilean dictator, might not be able to claim immunity from
prosecution for crimes committed by his forces outside Chile. The
expert, David Lloyd Jones, was appearing as a neutral ``friend of
the court'' before Britain's highest court on whether Pinochet has
immunity from arrest and extradition to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: EARLY PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Bartlett Diaz, a conservative former governor of Puebla
state, opened his campaign to win nomination as the candidate of
the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party for elections next
year. The announcement of his intent to succeed President Ernesto
Zedillo broke taboos, because candidates have traditionally
maintained a respectful silence until the sitting president
designates his successor.
</P>
</TEXT>
