<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NENEGLAND-GOVERNMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER N.H. GOVERNOR HOPEFUL WINS TOP MOCK REGIONAL POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She was never able to make it to Congress. She couldn't
get herself elected governor of the Granite State. But former New
Hampshire state representative Deborah ``Arnie'' Arnesen won a much
higher _ albeit hypothetical _ office Wednesday: She was elected
Governor of the State of New England.
</P>
<P>
   The mock election was part of a conference in Boston to explore
ways for New Englanders to cooperate on common issues, like
education, transportation, and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It coincided with the release of a survey by the New England
Board of Higher Education and the McCormack Institute showing that
New Englanders are eager for more regional cooperation on common
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's candidates for super-governor were eager to give
cooperation a try.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Arnesen, candidates for the fictitious office were
former Massachusetts state senator and gubernatorial candidate
Patricia McGovern, Maine Senate majority leader Chellie Pingree,
former Rhode Island governor Bruce Sundlun, Vermont State Treasurer
James Douglas, and Connecticut Senate President Kevin Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   They had some novel ideas for a new New England.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern argued for pooling all six states' pension funds for
higher returns. Sundlun said the states should remain separate
entities, but join with Quebec and secede from the union.
</P>
<P>
   And New Hampshire's Arnesen came up with a new slogan for a new
state of New England: ``Think Regionally or Die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-MILLENNIUM-BUG-BOS     02-03 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MILLENNIUM-BUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE LAGGING IN PREPARING FOR `MILLENNIUM BUG' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State government is slightly behind schedule in
preparing its computer systems for the year 2000 bug, and
Massachusetts as a whole does not have a plan to deal with a
worst-case, crippling loss of power and services.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message delivered Wednesday to a joint legislative
committee gauging where the state stood 238 days before the dawn of
a new millennium that could confound computers from Massachusetts
to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Calling increasing uneasiness over the Y2K problem an issue of
great public concern, David P. Magnani, a Democrat from Framingham,
asked the Cellucci administration to set a deadline for a
contingency plan to deal with a statewide disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people would feel comfortable knowing that if there were
no heat, no light, they could go to the local armory,'' Magnani
said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator told Administration and Finance Secretary Frederick
Laskey that the state's residents deserve an emergency plan that is
``thorough, well-organized, fully ready'' and includes the National
Guard and the Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Although Magnani, cochairman of the Science and Technology
Committee, acknowledged that the chance of disaster might be as
slim as .001 percent, he added that one way to quell panic is to
``get the message out'' that the state is prepared for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts residents need to know, Magnani said, that ``if
the .001 percent happens, we'll have trucks available to pick you
up and take you to a local armory or school, and that we'll clothe
and feed you.''
</P>
<P>
   Laskey, flanked by state officials working on the Y2K bug, said
no serious problems are expected, and the state is engaged in
aggressive outreach to offer help to smaller communities that do
not have the resources and expertise to prepare themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In simple terms, the Y2K problem centers on the confusion that
many computers could experience on Jan. 1, 2000. Instead of
correctly recognizing the year _ identified by most systems by the
last two digits _ many computers, if unaltered, could read the date
as 1900 and break down or malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to agreeing to develop an emergency plan, Laskey
told legislators that 57 percent of state government's
``mission-critical'' computer systems have been made ``Y2K
compliant.'' The goal had been 65 to 70 percent, said Val Asbedian,
director of a strategic planning group that has been dealing with
the problem since summer 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Still to be made Y2K compliant, Asbedian said, are such critical
agencies as the State Police and the departments of Transitional
Assistance, Corrections, and Revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the slight lag in overall compliance, Laskey said the
``backbone'' of state government is prepared for 2000, including
systems that deal with payroll, the Registry of Motor Vehicles, the
Lottery, and the Department of Social Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to panic,'' Laskey said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the fiscal year on June 30, Laskey continued, 95
percent of state government computer systems are expected to be
compliant. However, the Department of Public Health and the
Massachusetts Water Resources Authority, which supplies water to
2.5 million residents, are not expected to be ready until late
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Any agency whose ``mission-critical'' systems are not compliant
by the end of the fiscal year will be required to draft worst-case
contingency plans, Laskey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they'll make it, but we want to prepare for the
worst,'' the secretary said. ``But the fact that we're building
contingency plans doesn't mean people should start stockpiling food
and candles.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's major utilities appear ready, officials said.
However, many municipal electric companies do not appear to have
taken the warnings seriously, which could result in isolated power
outages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to turn up the heat on them,'' Laskey said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire safety systems across the state, including call boxes and
alarms, appear to be fine, officials said. And of 10,000 traffic
lights in Massachusetts, 97 percent appear immune to the Y2K bug.
The remaining lights will be fixed or removed before the new year,
lawmakers were told.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci filed a $15 million supplemental budget
last week to help meet Y2K needs. Laskey said the state probably
will need more funds, and that access to the money is needed soon.
</P>
<P>
   Magnani said the Ways and Means chairmen will be approached soon
to determine if the money can be separated from the overall budget
and approved for use quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds, if not thousands, of state employees are grinding
away at this thing,'' Laskey said. ``It's really a full-scale
assault.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no less partisan issue than this one,'' Magnani said,
noting that a lawyers' group has estimated that $1.6 trillion will
be spent nationally on Y2K legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to putting on a full-court press for the next
11 months,'' Magnani said with a smile, ``so we can all enjoy next
New Year's Eve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
