<SLUG> BC-SBC-LOCAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBC TO OPEN ASSAULT ON BOSTON MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bell Atlantic Corp.'s monopoly on local phone service
is coming under fresh assault on two fronts.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications Corp., the nation's second-largest regional
phone carrier, is expected to announce Friday plans to enter the
Boston market, initially offering business customers local and
long-distance service. It would mark the first time a Bell company
is invading the turf of another regional Bell company in local and
long-distance services.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MCI Worldcom Inc. said Wednesday it will immediately
begin offering residential local phone service throughout New York
state by leasing phone lines from Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Baby Bells, Bell Atlantic, the New York-based carrier
that serves the East Coast, faces increasing competition from
rivals eager to offer local and long-distance phone service.
Competition has been unleashed following passage of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Both MCI Worldcom and SBC are among a growing number of
telecommunications companies pursuing Bell Atlantic's most
lucrative customers. Each plans to offer a combination of local,
long-distance and high-speed Internet services that will be
packaged in a single customer bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic wants to grow by offering long-distance service in
the 13 states its serves, but cannot do so until it demonstrates to
federal and state regulators that it has opened up its local phone
market to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In a new sign that local competition is emerging, San Antonio,
Tex.-based SBC _ the most acquisitive of the Baby Bells _ says it
plans to enter the Boston, Miami and Seattle markets. SBC could
begin offering a combination of local, long distance and high speed
Internet service over phone lines as early as year-end, said David
R. Lopez, vice president of regulatory affairs for SBC's ``national
group'', which plans to enter a total of 15 new markets around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   SBC is the only Baby Bell pursuing a national strategy for
conventional local and local distance calling.
</P>
<P>
   The company is hedging its plans to enter Boston, Miami and
Seattle by saying the expansion depends on gaining federal and
state regulatory approvals by the summer for its proposed
acquistion of Ameritech, the Midwest regional Bell company
headquartered in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   If the SBC-Ameritech deal fails to gain regulatory approvals,
SBC would halt its expansion plans, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   SBC, once known as Southwestern Bell Co., has grown by acquiring
Pacific Telesis Group, which serves California and Nevada, and
Connecticut-based Southern New England Telephone Co. SBC's
immediate goal is to sign up 174 large corporate customers _ all
Fortune 500 companies _ headquartered in either SBC or Ameritech
states that collectively have 2,267 locations in greater Boston. It
also is targeting another 50 big companies with operations in Miami
and Seattle. Together, the 224 corporations spend nearly $125
million annually with SBC and Ameritech in local and long-distance
telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   After establishing itself with business customers outside its
home territory, SBC plans to pursue residential customers, Lopez
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we have our network aligned and completed, we could,
perhaps, provide service to a Fortune 500 client and a few miles
away to Aunt June and her family,'' said Lopez, adding that the
recently formed SBC national group, expects to expand to 8,000
employees within three years from a dozen now.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, MCI Worldcom is focused on selling to residential
customers in New York immediately. It expects to sign up a maximum
of 200 Bell Atlantic customers per day. The limit is based on Bell
Atlantic's ability to process the large volumes of customer service
orders it receives from competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Atlantic is confident that the long distance giant's
decision to work with us rather than against us will produce new
growth opporunities for both companies,'' said James G. Cullen,
Bell Atlantic's president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think MCI's entry into the New York market should go a long
way to give us a good idea of exactly where we are and what we
still need to do to get competition really cranking.,'' said Jeff
Kagan, an Atlanta-based telecommunications analyst.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
