<SLUG> BC-MA-HOME-HEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
  
 PATIENT HOME CARE INADEQUATE, STUDY SAYS
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BOSTON _ Many Massachusetts doctors say their chronically ill
patients aren't getting the home care they need because of
insurance and government cutbacks, and they complain that
communicating with home service providers is often frustrating and
bogged down in paperwork, a pioneering survey has found.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, commissioned by the Massachusetts Medical Society,
painted a picture of an increasingly crucial system of medical care
_ centered in the home, not the hospital _ that needs significant
improvement, officials said in releasing the results Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurers are using it more often, in part because of the
pressure to get patients out of the hospital sooner,'' said Dr. B.
Dale Magee, chairman of a society committee that carried out the
study. ``But one of our concerns is that in trying to get control
of budgets, some cuts have been made across the line'' _ both in
hospital and in home care services, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-thirds of the physicians felt that on occasion they
thought their patients didn't have enough home health coverage,''
he added. The survey sought opinions of from 6,500 physicians in 21
specialties. Ninety percent said they prescribed home health care
services.
</P>
<P>
   Federal budget cuts have slowed a move to have Medicare cover
more home care for the aging population, said Patricia Kelleher,
executive director of the Home Health Care Association of
Massachusetts, which she said represents 85 to 90 percent of the
approximately 150 home health agencies in the state.
</P>
<P>
   She said in an interview that the survey will be nationally
important because Massachusetts physicians ``have made a statement
that the availability and quality of home health care is an
essential part of their ability to practice medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Home care includes everything from nursing visits to infusing
drugs to wound care to meals, homemaking and social work. Insurers
like Medicare may cover home care if it is to help acutely ill
patients recover, but are less likely to cover care for people who
are simply ``aging in place,'' said Kelleher.
</P>
<P>
   The medical society survey showed that many physicians were
frustrated by the difficulty of getting information about the
condition of patients receiving home care, said Magee. Some of that
information is contained in paperwork that doesn't reach the doctor
until it's well out of date, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be connected more, to work with the home health
care agencies to improve timely communications,'' said Magee.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher said her association and the medical society have
agreed to work together to ``streamline paperwork.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed that doctors usually choose a home health
agency because of its affiliation with a hospital. They said they
were, in general, ``less than moderately involved'' with the choice
of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new federal mandate, home health care agencies must
report the success of their handling of various types of medical
problems, to be compiled into a database. Ultimately, that
information will be available to individual consumers, said
Kelleher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
