A0831 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      02-03 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE FACES CRITICAL IMPEACHMENT VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The impeachment storm intensified Wednesday as the
Senate braced for a series of pivotal votes Thursday, and Democrats
vowed to wage a potentially protracted war next week on a
Republican plan to formally cite President Clinton for wrongdoing
before his trial ends.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their cry for an immediate end to the saga, Senate
Democrats threatened to stall the trial with a blizzard of
parliamentary maneuvers if GOP leaders pursue their plan to
sanction Clinton during the proceeding rather than convicting him.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, which dashed Republican hopes of crafting a
bipartisan punishment, came as House impeachment managers completed
questioning White House adviser Sidney Blumenthal in their third
and final deposition. The managers plan to ask the Senate Thursday
to call all three witnesses, including Monica S. Lewinsky, to
testify in person, as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The request for witnesses, which faces opposition in both
parties, was considered as endangered as the Republican bid for a
bipartisan ``finding of fact'' of Clinton's wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats assailed the finding of fact plan in a dawn-to-dusk
barrage of news conferences, press releases, and a scathing opinion
piece in The Washington Post by the dean of Senate Democrats,
Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-backed findings would state that Clinton falsely
testfied before a federal grand jury and wrongfully impeded a
sexual harassment lawsuit that Paula Corbin Jones filed against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are findings of fiction,'' said Senator Edward M.
Kennedy. ``This is really a desperate attempt by the Republicans to
save face. It's a desperate attempt to further embarrass the
president of the United States. And it's an attempt to save their
own political positions in preparation for the final votes on the
articles of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Senate Republicans, who met Wednesday night in their
ongoing struggle to unify their members behind the alternative
sanction, conceded the ``finding of fact'' plan could wither in the
heat of Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Without Democratic backing, ``it's not worth it,'' said Senator
Olympia J. Snowe, a Maine Republican and key proponent of the plan.
``It's not what we are trying to achieve _ another party-line
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans also made a formal request Wednesday night
for Clinton to testify voluntarily at the trial, which the White
House has rejected. ``Your knowledge, intent, actions and omissions
are central to the charges,'' the GOP senators wrote in a letter to
Clinton. ``Personal answers from you should prove beneficial in our
efforts to reconcile conflicting testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ``finding of fact'' showdown, several key Republicans
Wednesday voiced opposition to the plan, further threatening its
chances of reaching the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Judd Gregg, a New Hampshire Republican, said the
``finding of fact'' proposal ``may not be unconstitutional,'' as
Democrats have charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a mistake,'' Gregg said. ``It creates a new path
where the legislative branch can discipline the executive branch
inappropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, said the plan
remained viable, and he disputed the assertion by Senator Thomas A.
Daschle, the minority leader, that no Democrats would supprt it.
Lott also downplayed GOP concerns about the apparent lack of
bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it has to be'' bipartisan, he said. ``You need
over 50 votes for it to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The slowing momentum for the Republican plan gave some impetus
to a Democratic-sponsored proposal to censure Clinton after the
trial. Daschle appointed Senators Dianne Feinstein of California
and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York Wednesday to develop
language for a censure resolution that could appeal to both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared to have a `finding' after we finish the
constitutional process,'' said Senator John F. Kerry. ``But don't
bastardize ... the constitutional process itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The skirmish over how to sanction Clinton unfolded as the 13
House Republican impeachment managers ended the deposition phase of
their search for new evidence against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A source said Blumenthal did not stray from his previous sworn
testimony that Clinton had lied to him about the president's sexual
affair with Lewinsky, telling Blumenthal that Lewinsky stalked him
and he rebuffed her.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lewinsky and Clinton's friend Vernon E. Jordan Jr. also
gave the House team little more to go on in their depositions the
previous two days, the managers vowed to ask senators to call the
three witnesses to testify before the Senate _ and the network
television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to have a verdict that will withstand the
test of history, these witnesses should come forward, and they
should be put under oath live on the Senate floor,'' said
Representative James F. Rogan of California, who led the
questioning of Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   But the House managers, sensing their request could be rejected,
also were crafting a ``fall-back'' request to show portions of the
videotaped depositions on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough to make that case'' for witnesses
testifying in person, said Representative Asa Hutchinson of
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe, for example, Wednesday joined several other Republicans
who have expressed opposition to calling the witnesses.
``Personally, I am not going to support appearances of witnesses
before the US Senate,'' Snowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the trial rules, which the Senate's Republican majority
pushed through last week on a party-line vote, the proceedings will
resume Thursday, with a series of motions, including the witness
question.
</P>
<P>
   The session is scheduled to begin with the Senate taking up any
objections that were left unresolved during the depositions. A
source said the only objection that was not resolved arose
Wednesday, when a House manager, Representative Lindsey O. Graham
of South Carolina, asked Blumenthal whether he had made statements
about Kathleen E. Willey, a former White House volunteer who
claimed Clinton groped her in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A White House lawyer objected on the grounds that the Willey
case is not under consideration by the Senate. However, Clinton's
lawyers, who posed no questions in Blumenthal's deposition, are not
expected to press the objection on the Senate floor because they do
want to attract additional attention to the Willey allegation.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, House managers are expected to file the first
motion Thursday, asking the Senate to make public the videotapes
and transcripts of the depositions. Lott's spokesman, John
Czwartacki, said the motion could call for keeping the material
under seal for a brief ``cooling off'' period.
</P>
<P>
   Releasing the videotapes would likely produce a new chapter of
Lewinsky lore and drive up some television ratings. Lewinsky has
never been seen publicly discussing the circumstances stemming from
her affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said Democrats will fight releasing the videotape until
the trial is over. ``I don't think it would serve Ms. Lewinsky or
the Senate or the trial to release it to the public until after the
trial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote on releasing the material, the witness question
is likely to be debated. If the Senate rejects witnesses and the
videotaped alternative, closing arguments could begin by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The ``finding of fact'' motion would follow the closing
arguments and precede the final deliberations on the two articles
of impeachment. With Clinton expected to be acquitted, members of
both parties said they want an alternative sanction to condemn
Clinton for his actions and dampen the president's enthusiasm for
reacting gleefully to an acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   The White House addressed part of the concern. ``In a
post-impeachment era, this is a gloat-free zone,'' said White House
spokesman Joseph Lockhart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
