u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-EXECUTION-NYT &LR;      02-03 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EXECUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR WEIGHS DEATH-ROW INMATE'S APPEAL FOR CLEMENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Those who want to see the life of Jaturun
Siripongs spared include his former prison warden, the Roman
Catholic Bishop of Sacramento, a juror who voted to convict him and
the husband of one of the two people Siripongs was sentenced to
death for murdering 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of how long or influential the list of people
asking for mercy for Siripongs, a former Buddhist monk, it will
make little difference if the name of Gov. Gray Davis is not on it.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there is a stay, the last thing standing between
Siripongs and execution is the word of Davis, and that has put the
new governor and his administration under tremendous pressure from
both sides of the emotionally and politically charged debate over
capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Siripongs, who is 43, is scheduled to be executed next Tuesday.
He has asked California's first Democratic governor in 16 years for
mercy, or at least for time for his lawyers to pursue evidence of
innocence. Davis' Republican predecessor, Pete Wilson, last year
denied a request for clemency from Siripongs, whose life was saved
by a stay. But experts in the politics of capital punishment say
that Davis also seems likely to deny clemency. no matter the merits
of Siripongs plea or the recent actions of Missouri governor, Mel
Carnahan, a supporter of capital punishment, who granted clemency
to a condemned triple murderer after a request from Pope John Paul
II. Davis is a practicing Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the political cost to Gray Davis would be enormous if
he grants clemency,'' said Gerald Uelman, a law professor at Santa
Clara University. ``We're in a state where death penalty politics
has a heavy hand in gubernatorial politics, and we've seen
Democratic candidates, again and again, become vulnerable to the
issue. But Davis got past it by taking a very strong position in
favor of the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to help stave off his Republican opponent in last year's
campaign, the staunch death penalty proponent and state attorney
general, Dan Lungren, then lieutenant governor. Davis frequently
stated his support for capital punishment and his willingness to
carry it out. To do otherwise now, the experts say, appears to be
too great of a political risk for the famously cautious politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' said Franklin Zimring, a law professor at the
University of California at Berkeley, ``no one has ever been
defeated for election by allowing an execution to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Siripongs is Davis' first life-and-death decision as
governor and it probably will not be his last. With more than 500
men and women on its death row, California has more condemned
inmates than any other state. And although just five inmates have
been executed in California since the nation resumed executions 23
years ago, the frequency of executions here appears to be on the
verge of speeding up. The case of the Buddhist and the governor is
being watched closely for any clues into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the pipeline is loosening up,'' said Michael
Rushford, the president of the Criminal Justice Legal Foundation, a
California group that advocates enforcement of the death penalty,
``and this governor is probably going to have more opportunities to
review more capital cases than any governor since the '60s and
probably more than any governor in the history of California.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rushford calls Siripongs ``a poster boy for capital
punishment,'' because ``he killed two people without giving it a
second thought,'' Siripongs' supporters say that he is an ideal
candidate for clemency. He has been on death row since 1983 and has
a spotless prison record. According to his clemency petition,
several prison guards and a former warden support mercy for the
soft spoken native of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   And from the day he was locked up shortly after the murders in
1981, his supporters say that Siripongs has been filled with
remorse about the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his supporters say there is another important reason why
he should be granted clemency. Siripongs, they say, has never
killed anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In recent court filings, Siripongs' lawyers, Linda Schilling and
Michael Laurence, contend that Siripongs had an accomplice who
committed the murders in Garden Grove, Calif. In fact, the lawyers
say, Siripongs was cut on his arm and hands trying to stop the
killing, a contention he has held since the beginning of the case.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers want Siripongs' execution to be at least postponed
so blood found at the scene can be tested to determine if it
matches a second possible suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Rushford said the case has been reargued for years and
Siripongs' sentence should be carried out without further delay.
Lance Lindsey, of Death Penalty Focus of California, a group
opposed to capital punishment, said that there are still too many
unanswered questions and that ``the case of clemency is
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of people most deeply affected by the killings, the
family members of the dead, are divided. At Siripongs' clemency
hearing on Tuesday, Vitoon Harusadangkul, the son of one of the
victims, Packovan Wattanaporn, said he wanted the execution to go
forward. But his stepfather, Mrs. Wattanaporn's husband, Surachai
Wattanaporn, supports clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Buddhist,'' he wrote in a letter last year to Wilson, ``I
do not seek revenge for my wife's death and ask you to please
consider exercising mercy in this case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
