A0833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-DRUG04-COX     02-03 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUG04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposal for anti-doping agency eludes officials
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Olympic guardians conceded Wednesday
that they won't be able to push through a proposal to create an
international anti-doping agency and impose uniform penalties for
drug use when the World Conference on Doping in Sport ends today.
</P>
<P>
   What they will produce probably will be called the Lausanne
Declaration on Doping in Sport, little more than a written
consensus from the invited delegates to seek formation of the
agency. Everything else is open to debate over the next several
months _ from control and directorship of the agency to funding and
location.
</P>
<P>
   The only likelihood is, IOC vice president Dick Pound said, ``We
want this up before the Sydney Games (in 2000).''
</P>
<P>
   The action will fall short of the pre-conference proposal,
written by the International Olympic Committee, which called for
the IOC to assume almost total control and put president Juan
Antonio Samaranch at the head of the agency. But the IOC has been
caught in a scandal over the selection of cities that has led to
the resignation of four members, with expulsions likely to come. So
the idea of it overseeing such an ethically touchy issue as doping
in sport stirred vigorous opposition from national leaders,
athletes and the scientific community during the first two days of
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Pound refused to answer whether plans were scrapped because of
the lack of confidence demonstrated in the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he expressed surprise at the level of interest voiced
by public authorities in the proposed agency, saying it moved the
IOC to play a lesser role while broadening the influence of
governments and outside groups. The involvement of the United
Nations might be sought, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became increasingly clear that the public authorities
really wanted to be involved,'' Pound said. ``That was the element
of surprise. I thought it might be one of these arrangements where
we would do our thing with an agency, then hope the public
authorities would either work with the agency or come along
later.''
</P>
<P>
   The original proposal called for a one-sixth role on the
agency's council by international governments. Pound suggested that
it could end up a 50-50 split with the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's level of control will hold great sway over the
agency's credibility. Because the IOC initially planned to pay the
$25 million start-up cost, Samaranch wasn't eager to put it outside
his domain, and he endorsed Prince Alexandre de Merode, head of the
IOC medical commission, to run the agency. The proposal met with
considerable opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Another unsettled issue is the minimum penalty for a doping
offense. While most individual sports federations generally back a
strict two-year ban, leaders of soccer, cycling and tennis have
resisted. Under consideration is a proposal requiring a two-year
ban for an athlete caught using steroids, although officials
acknowledge that special circumstances with selected federations
and national laws might take precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the Olympic movement stridently oppose a
watered-down proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (soccer) can't accept the rules of the IOC, then they can't
be part of the IOC,'' said Roland Baar of Germany, silver-medalist
in rowing at the Atlanta Games and an elected member of the IOC
Athletes' Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
