<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0843 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      02-03 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEMOCRATS THREATEN PARTISAN FIGHT OVER IMPEACHMENT
DECLARATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Democrats warned Wednesday that President
Clinton's impeachment trial will be turned into a partisan fight if
Republicans go through with plans to push through a declaration of
wrongdoing by the president.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican-controlled Senate reconvening Thursday as a
court of impeachment, House prosecutors finished closed-door
depositions of three witnesses and prepared to argue for summoning
them to testify during Clinton's trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Republicans persist in demanding live witnesses and
demanding more depositions, and demanding extra legal devices like
findings of fact, the more it becomes a Republican trial,'' said
Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 28 Republican senators sent a letter to the president
urging him to voluntarily answer questions under oath to resolve
discrepancies in evidence supporting the two articles of
impeachment charging him with lying to a grand jury and obstructing
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your knowledge, intent, actions and omissions are central to
the charges the House of Representatives have made against you,''
said the letter to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who cannot be compelled to testify, declined last
week to answer written questions posed by the GOP-controlled Senate
and was expected to turn down the request for him to submit to live
questioning by House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by polls showing the public growing more weary of the
trial and more angry with Republicans, Daschle renewed calls for a
quick end to only the second impeachment trial of a president in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, D-S.D., said his Democratic colleagues are opposed to
live testimony during the trial and want the videotaped depositions
kept secret for now. However, what rankles Democrats most, Daschle
said, is the Republican plan for pushing through a finding of fact
that would declare Clinton a liar.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said Democratic senators are prepared to ``offer an
array of amendments'' to the GOP proposal ``as long as it appears
that a finding of fact resolutions could pass.''
</P>
<P>
   With 45 of the 100 votes in the Senate, the Democrats can block
conviction and removal of Clinton, which requires a two-thirds
vote. However, unless a half-dozen of the 55 Republicans switched
sides, the Democrats would be unable to stop passage of a so-called
``finding of fact'' pushed by several GOP senators.
</P>
<P>
   A draft of the GOP resolution would formally declare that
Clinton ``willfully provided false and misleading testimony'' to
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury. The document also
would say that the president engaged in a course of conduct
designed to ``alter, delay, impede, cover up and conceal the
existence of evidence and testimony,'' in Paula Jones' sexual
harassment lawsuit against him.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the likelihood they will not muster the two-thirds
vote to terminate Clinton's presidency, Republicans are pushing the
``finding of fact'' to keep him from claiming a total vindication
when the final votes are cast, as currently scheduled, on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do this, then history will have the wrong
interpretation'' of Clinton's effort to cover up his affair with
Monica Lewinsky, said Sen. Pete Domenici, a New Mexico Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a partisan fight, which could tie up the Senate
past the Feb. 12 target date for ending the trial, shook some
Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what we're trying to achieve, another party-line
vote,'' said Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, one of the advocates for
pushing through the finding-of-fact resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Even within the Senate's Republican ranks, a finding of facts
was viewed skeptically. Among the GOP senators who have raised
questions about the resolution's constitutionality are Mike DeWine
of Ohio, Phil Gramm of Texas, Richard Shelby of Alabama and Gordon
Smith of Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   After a closed-door meeting of Republican senators late
Wednesday, Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, indicated the popularity of
the proposal might have peaked. ``It's still up in the air. It's
not soaring, but it's not falling either. It's up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews throughout the day, Democrats argued
that the Constitution gives the Senate only one option _ guilt or
innocence _ on articles of impeachment. At the same time, several
Democrats said it was possible to censure the president's behavior,
but not in the context of an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Constitutional scholars on the left and right think it's
wrong. That should tell you something,'' said Sen. Max Baucus,
D-Mont.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unconstitutional. You can't have it both ways. Either you
convict or don't convict,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle on Wednesday named Sens. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and
Pat Moynihan, D-N.Y., to head a group to draft a resolution
condemning Clinton's behavior and cover-up attempts in the White
House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, House prosecutors interrogated White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal, the last of three witnesses, as more senators
said they have seen enough of the prosecutors' witnesses and want
no more.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal repeated Wednesday his grand jury accounts of Clinton
telling him that Lewinsky, a former White House intern, was known
as a ``stalker'' and ``threatened'' him unless he agreed to a
sexual relationship. Blumenthal also repeated that first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton told him that her husband was merely
``ministering'' to Lewinsky, according to sources familiar with his
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Like the depositions of Lewinsky on Monday and presidential
confidant Vernon Jordan on Tuesday, sources said, Blumenthal's
closed-door session provided little new grist to support the GOP
contention that live witnesses are critical to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, a Chicago-area Republican and lead prosecutor
for the House, said he would continue pushing to bring Lewinsky,
Jordan and Blumenthal to the Senate floor to testify. However, he
conceded, ``I haven't received a world of encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a strategy session with his fellow prosecutors,
Hyde said the course seems set for the Clinton case. ``There's a
general feeling that it's too late to pursue other avenues in this
proceeding,'' Hyde said. ``The time has come to pull our case
together and argue it'' before the Senate votes.
</P>
<P>
   After viewing videotapes of the Lewinsky deposition Tuesday,
five Republican senators said they see no reason to summon her to
testify on the Senate floor. On Wednesday, after viewing the
Lewinsky and Jordan depositions, two others agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I am not going to support appearances of witnesses
before the U.S. Senate,'' Snowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said she had learned so
``few new things'' from viewing the videotapes that ``I would not
say that we need to have them on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelby, a former Democrat who switched to the GOP in 1993,
dismissed the Lewinsky and Jordan depositions as ``more of the
same, nothing explosive, no dynamite.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
