<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SEAVER FOR McCARVER: IS IT WORTH IT? 
 (sw) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you were a baseball general manager during the
late 1960s or early 1970s, you would surely consider swapping Tim
McCarver to get Tom Seaver in return.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to shed McCarver as your team's television analyst,
only peers like Joe Morgan and Jim Kaat would be worthy
replacements. But would you fire McCarver and hire Seaver as your
top analyst?
</P>
<P>
   That was precisely what the Mets did on Wednesday, choosing the
rah-rah glory of bringing a prodigal son back over keeping one of
baseball's best and most outspoken analysts who had called Mets
games for 16 years on WWOR-TV in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time moves on,'' said McCarver, who will keep calling network
games at Fox Sports. ``I'm not shocked. It was already February, so
there was cause for concern. But if I were to say this wasn't
emotional, I wouldn't be telling you the truth. I saw them through
the great times of the 1986 World Series and the tough times in the
early '90s. I always tried to give fans the honest truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver's hiring is the only personnel change expected in the
Mets' local broadcast booth with the team's games moving to WPIX-TV
(which bought the rights to 50 games this year and 40 next year
from Madison Square Garden, which bought them from the Mets). The
team wants to rehire Gary Thorne and Ralph Kiner, who would
continue on the Mets' cable games on Fox Sports New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets must anticipate that the long hoped-for return of a
Hall of Fame pitcher to the Mets' organization will make fans
forget that he is replacing a future Hall of Fame broadcaster.
Remember, Seaver never distinguished himself as one of WPIX's
Yankee announcers from 1989 to 1993, although there were lots of
chuckles in the booth when he worked with Phil Rizzuto.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objective is to do the best job I can possibly do,'' Seaver
said. But, he added, ``I'm not going to be as good as the person
I'm replacing.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, critics can get caught up in the Seaver-McCarver
comparison and underestimate how important Seaver is to Mets fans.
And if Seaver is merely OK, but doesn't dazzle with the kind of
intricate analyses McCarver is known for, well, maybe that will be
enough for the hard-core viewer.
</P>
<P>
   But Seaver will step into the job with a full set of baggage,
which he seems gladly to schlep. He was hired to be more than a
broadcaster; he will also be a pitching adviser, team marketer and
promoter. It is common for an announcer to be a club employee, as
McCarver was, and for announcers to make appearances for the club.
But the formal list of club roles is unusual.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to see how a person would not find conflict in these
multiple roles, although such a combination was the only way to
bring Seaver back. But if he's helping Al Leiter with his leg kick
or Paul Wilson with his fastball, how candid will he be if they
don't follow his advice during a game?
</P>
<P>
   If Seaver is the Mets' supreme icon, he should feel great leeway
to speak freely without fretting about upsetting anyone in the
Mets' hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job is to to be critical when it's time to criticize
players and applaud players when it's time to applaud players,''
Seaver said. ``In their heart, the home broadcaster roots for the
home team.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said: ``I think he's
a strong enough guy that he'll be able to say what he wants without
looking over his shoulder.'' But viewers and critics will wait to
see if he is a homer, to see if, as he said, ``the old homer
broadcaster is a reality and inescapable.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's acknowledge that the home announcer feels a tug for the
home team. But pure homers like Rizzuto, Harry Caray and Bob Prince
were idiosyncratic enough for their excesses to be forgiven because
they defined the viewing or listening experience. Seaver never
showed a predilection for such outrageousness.
</P>
<P>
   One can only surmise that McCarver's departure will please the
touchy Mets Manager Bobby Valentine, assuming that the type of
critiques that came naturally from McCarver will be tempered
because of Seaver's range of roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I get along with Valentine?'' McCarver said. ``I tried to
do my job. I wouldn't say we were cordial, but he never said, `Be a
fan.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bingham, the club's senior vice president for marketing and
broadcasting, said the Mets contemplated teaming McCarver and
Seaver. But both are analysts, and Seaver wanted the platform that
came with broadcasting. ``Once Tom was a given, we looked at what
constituted the best team,'' Bingham said. Which would be Seaver
and Thorne.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets pushed hard for Seaver, hiring him even though the WPIX
deal has not been signed. It's hard to believe that MSG, which will
likely produce the games for WPIX, wanted Seaver over McCarver. In
a statement, Mike McCarthy, MSG's executive producer, said, ``It's
easy to see the value the Mets identified in bringing Tom Seaver to
the broadcast booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, McCarver will most likely work only the national telecasts
for Fox Sports, in a schedule that begins in June, and hook up with
another team next season. He voiced some interest in the 50-game
Yankee package at Fox-owned WNYW, but there may be too many
conflicts with his Fox schedule. ``Who knows what may happen?''
said Michael Wach, general manager of WNYW, which has been eyeing
Kenny Albert and Rick Cerone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
