A0848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-TEST04-COX     02-03 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TEST04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. taken to task for own doping troubles
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ In a solemn, statesman-like tone,
two-time Olympic gold medalist Sebastian Coe of Great Britain
challenged American sports leaders to deal with their own doping
problems at home before lecturing the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   His piercing speech registered with many delegates Wednesday
attending the World Conference on Doping, a day after Barry
McCaffrey, the White House drug czar called on international sports
to reform its drug policies.
</P>
<P>
   Although not identifying sprinter Dennis Mitchell by name, Coe
upbraided the U.S. track-and-field federation for recently clearing
a high-profile American athlete on the defense that he consumed
alcohol and engaged in sex the night before an unannounced drug
test. Mitchell failed the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ban that is overturned because somebody is able to say that
elevated levels of testosterone are due to sex and beer the night
before is a decision that does lack credibility,'' said Coe, a
former member of the British Parliament and chief of staff to
Conservative Party leader William Hague. ``You know it, and I know
it, and more importantly the competitors that are out there _ that
you need on board for this whole process to work _ lack confidence
(in the process).''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, bronze medalist in the 100 meters at the 1992
Barcelona Olympics and leader of his sport's athlete advisory
committee, tested positive for high levels of testosterone last
spring. He argued successfully before a U.S. Track and Field panel
that his elevated testosterone was the result of having consumed
five beers and having sex four times the previous night.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he found the panel's acceptance of such a defense
comical, Coe said: ``Well, it's not the touchstone of grace and
elegance, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Alexandre de Merode, head of the International Olympic
Committee medical commission, characterized the Americans as
laggards in the fight against doping and said he, thus, was amused
by the get-tough tone of McCaffrey and his delegation.
</P>
<P>
   De Merode said he found it absurd that a U.S. federation could
have accepted the defense offered by Mitchell, which he said has no
basis in science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't say drinking a beer and (having sex with) a girl changes
the level of testosterone,'' de Merode said. ``I can understand
when people try to escape. That's the game. But, please, do it
seriously.'' Coe is a respected spokesman against the use of
performance-enhancing drugs. A former world-record holder in the
1,500 meters, he is the only man to win successive Olympic titles
at the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm genuinely not unloading on the Americans,'' Coe said
later. ``It is the (Mitchell) case which has caused as much anxiety
among the athletic fraternity that I speak to regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to all countries, you have a contribution to make to
this debate, but it is a better contribution when you have actually
cleared up your own back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   The international track federation is investigating the Mitchell
case and will hold a hearing before ruling on his reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Schultz, head of the U.S. Olympic Committee, took no public
offense to Coe's comments, although he denied that the United
States is trying to dictate a drug policy for world sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that is a bizarre case,'' Schultz said, referring to
Mitchell. ``But if you do some research, you can probably find
something like that in almost every country.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
