<HEADER>
A0850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL-NY     02-03 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUMENTHAL'S DEPORTMENT DISARMS HIS INTERROGATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.C., Calif., S.C., Ill.)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-OPEN, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-BORK) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He was supposed to have been the most hostile
witness of all, the one who wouldn't check his grudges at the door,
despite the setting.
</P>
<P>
   But Sidney Blumenthal, the opinionated journalist-turned-White
House adviser who is reviled by Republicans, walked into the
Senate's national security briefing room to be deposed Wednesday
and immediately blunted those sharp edges, prompting one House
prosecutor to go so far as to call him a ``gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, both sides agreed that no new ground was
broken, but the House managers of the impeachment case called
Blumenthal's testimony ``productive'' and said it would help them
to bolster the official record on their accusations that Clinton
obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers did try to raise issues outside the articles
of impeachment, beginning to question Blumenthal about Kathleen
Willey, congressional officials said. Ms. Willey has accused
Clinton of groping her, an allegation he denies. The incident and
allegations that she was subsequently harassed by an unidentified
person after her testimony in the Paula Jones case are under
investigation by the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers, led by Lanny Breuer, objected to the
questions delving into the Willey matter. Blumenthal was permitted
to answer, but said he knew nothing about Ms. Willey.
</P>
<P>
   During one objection on an undisclosed issue, the five presiding
senators in the room, led by Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and John
Edwards, D-N.C., asked that the room be cleared as the senators
decided what to do.
</P>
<P>
   During the one hour and 15 minutes of the deposition, Blumenthal
testified, as he had before the grand jury on three different
occasions, that in a conversation with President Clinton on Jan.
21, 1998, Clinton described Monica Lewinsky as a mendacious
``stalker'' who sought an intimate relationship with him. But
Blumenthal said he never repeated it to reporters, congressional
officials said. And he added that Clinton never instructed him to
spread the story or perpetuate the lie, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never leaked any conversations,'' Blumenthal is reported to
have said to prosecutors. ``I never spoke to any reporters about
any personal conversations with the president about Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Clinton lied about his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, Blumenthal replied, ``Yes,'' the officials said. And he
noted that Clinton never apologized to him for the lie.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., the leading questioner for the House
on Wednesday, asked sharp, precise questions that required short
answers, the officials said. He was joined by Rep. Lindsey Graham,
R-S.C., who inquired mostly about the ``politics of personal
destruction'' that he believes dominates White House strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Through their questions, the two House prosecutors hoped to
illustrate that Clinton had used Blumenthal to try to destroy Ms.
Lewinsky's reputation by engaging in a smear campaign. The term
``stalker'' later showed up in some news reports. They also
maintain that Clinton intentionally gave false information to
Blumenthal so that it would be passed on to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the president was talking about preparing, if
necessary, to disparage her reputation,'' said Rep. Ed Bryant,
R-Tenn., one of the House managers.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal is long despised by Republicans as the man behind
Hillary Rodham Clinton's accusation that a ``vast right-wing
conspiracy'' was out to get the president. Blumenthal has also been
accused of masterminding the disclosure last year that Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., had a long adulterous affair nearly 30 years ago.
Blumenthal has denied that accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said, ``I found him to be a gentleman, and I hope he felt
the same way about us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
