</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOUCHERS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES OF SCHOOL VOUCHERS TAKE CASE TO TEXAS LEGISLATURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Munoz) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The superintendent of Edgewood schools _ where a
privately funded school voucher program has lured away 700
schoolchildren and $4 million in tax dollars _ said Wednesday that
Texas already has all the school choice experiments it needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important for legislators, as well as the whole
state of Texas, to know that vouchers are not the answer,'' said
Dolores Munoz, superintendent of the low-income, mostly Hispanic
district in San Antonio. ``Edgewood is a pilot voucher program, not
by choice, but we are. So we right now are experiencing the
problems that go with vouchers. So let's not go on a bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz and several dozen Edgewood parents briefed a handful of
lawmakers on the impact that a controversial $50 million voucher
program funded by the private Children's Education Opportunity
(CEO) Foundation, a pro-voucher group based in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   About 700 students left Edgewood schools this year on a CEO
scholarship, resulting in a loss of $4 million in state funding,
Munoz said, and another 500 children left the district after a
public housing development was closed. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Additionally, Munoz and several mothers said, many of those who
left were among the best students academically, while the program
turned away disabled special education students. And some of those
students who left for private schools are facing kindergarten and
first-grade class sizes of 30 to 35 students.
</P>
<P>
   She said the proof that ``public schools are doing an excellent
job'' is reflected in the recent national recognition Texas got
from a education goals panel as one of the top two states in terms
of improvements in student academic achievement. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Many would argue whether Edgewood is doing an excellent job.
While the district's passing rate on the state's basic skills test
has improved, it still lags behind the state average, despite above
average spending per student.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about one-third of Edgewood's eighth-graders passed
the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills test, compared with a
statewide average passing rate of nearly twice that. And barely
half the district's 10th-graders passed the mandatory high school
exit test.
</P>
<P>
   Voucher proponents have argued that the competition will force
public schools to improve, but Munoz said the improved student
scores occurred before the CEO voucher program was begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have first-hand experie &QL; n~?7c &LR; Q!Q
</P>
