<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES04-COX     02-03 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low-fare MetroJet flies into the fray
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Quick. Name the most prominent new airlines of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   If you said AirTran, Frontier and Kiwi you'd be right. But the
list also includes Delta Express, MetroJet and United Shuttle _ all
offshoots of major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   They operate as separate ``airlines within airlines'' and are
designed to counteract low-fare competition in different areas of
the country. They're structured for lower costs that enable lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
   And they're growing into competitive forces in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of that came Wednesday at Hartsfield International
Airport, where MetroJet, a US Airways unit, began new service
between Atlanta and Dulles International Airport outside
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   MetroJet will fly the route seven times daily at initial fares
of $154 round-trip, its planes bearing a modified US Airways paint
scheme with MetroJet in big type and the parent carrier's name in
small print.
</P>
<P>
   The new route is part of an expansion by MetroJet, begun last
year in an attempt to protect US Airways' market share along the
Eastern seaboard against low-fare competitors.
</P>
<P>
   MetroJet now flies to 22 cities, with primary operations at
Dulles and Baltimore-Washington Airport and other destinations from
Florida to New England.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and AirTran have 18 daily Atlanta-Dulles flights between
them, but Michael Scheeringa, a US Airways vice president who
oversees MetroJet, sees room for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very large market with heavy ridership and great
demand for high-quality, low-fare service,'' Scheeringa said,
adding MetroJet could eventually make up 25 percent of US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   MetroJet's buildup prompted United to announce plans for its own
expansion this spring at Dulles, and it may put operations there
under the Shuttle banner. United will boost its Atlanta-Dulles
flights from two to seven on May 1, bringing total flights on the
route to 32. And that doesn't count the 15 daily flights Delta
offers between Hartsfield and Reagan National Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to look like the Schweinfurt raids, the sky black
with airplanes'' said aviation consultant Michael Boyd, referring
to an epic air battle of World War II. ``Somebody's going to wind
up carrying sailboat fuel instead of passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not those flights prove too many for the
Dulles-Hartsfield market, the surge reflects a building dogfight
for low-fare travelers in the East.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran's predecessor, ValuJet, started the fight with its
out-of-nowhere emergence from Atlanta in 1994 and 1995. Meanwhile,
Texas-based discounter Southwest Airlines was dominating the Far
West and laying plans to enter Florida and the Northeast, which it
has since done.
</P>
<P>
   Continental was the first major carrier to counter with a
low-cost division, but the so-called Continental Lite flopped
because of poor routes and a confused market identity.
</P>
<P>
   United started its Shuttle division in 1995, using it mainly to
fight Southwest in California. The unit now has 462 daily
departures and 59 planes.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Delta started Delta Express, based in Orlando,
Fla., and flying between several cities in Florida and the
Northeast. It has grown to 37 planes, adding 12 in the past year.
It serves 22 cities with 170 daily flights.
</P>
<P>
   It does not fly to Atlanta, because its goal is to serve
point-to-point routes rather than feed Delta's mainline hub
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Paulette Corbin, managing director of Delta Express, views
MetroJet's creation and the possible eastward expansion of United
Shuttle as the sincerest form of flattery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition is heating up, and we take it as a compliment
because we've shown this concept can operate very successfully,''
Corbin said. ``We feel we have the upper hand in the low-fare
industry right now.''
</P>
<P>
   MetroJet and Delta Express are both structured on the Southwest
model, using all-coach Boeing 737s. Thanks to tight scheduling and
rapid turnarounds, Delta Express planes fly an average 11.6 hours a
day vs. nine for Delta as a whole. In-flight service is limited,
and pilots are paid less under a negotiated agreement with their
union.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, that means lower costs and higher profits despite
reduced fares. Delta, US Airways and United, however, all decline
to release specific financial information for the units.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been profitable since we started,'' Corbin said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd believes Delta Express is the most successful of the lot at
this point because its strategy is the simplest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta Express is a nice clean concept. They take Florida
passengers who used to connect in Atlanta and fly them straight to
Florida. That's not high-fare traffic to begin with, so with a
lower-cost operation you make more off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheeringa said that reality was one of the factors driving
MetroJet's creation as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``US Airways lost millions flying low-fare traffic to Florida,
and with MetroJet we've created the ability to do that
profitably,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, a potential obstacle to the continued growth of any of
the major airline offshoots is labor contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's pilot union contract, for instance, limits the airline
to using one type of older jet, the 737-200. Most of Delta's
already have been dedicated to the Express unit.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the reduced pay scales that contribute to lower costs
must be renegotiated with each new contract. Delta and its pilots
start talks later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reduced pay scales were agreed to during concessionary
times,'' union spokeswoman Karen McGuffey said Wednesday. ``Times
are now different, and it will be up to the pilots whether they
want to keep contributing to Delta Express.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
