<HEADLINE>
DARK, STORMY SWEEPS PERIOD UPON US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By KEITH MARDER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Television's February sweeps begin today and run through March
3. And dead in the middle of this month of hype, you'll find one of
the biggest events of the period, ``Stephen King's Storm of the
Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC's three-part scare-a-thon (Feb. 14, 15 and 18) comes from
the mighty pen of the king of horror himself, his first stab at
writing specifically for television. Viewers soon discover that the
worst snowstorm of the century has fallen upon a small Maine town,
bringing with it an evil stranger and murders galore.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just part of the havoc bad weather will wreak on ABC
shows during this sweeps period, one of the four times per year
that television viewership is measured and used to set advertising
rates.
</P>
<P>
   During the two days between ``The Storm's'' Monday and Thursday
airings, ABC will include stormy story lines on sitcoms ``Home
Improvement,'' ``The Hughleys,'' ``Spin City,'' ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,''
``Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place'' and ``The Drew Carey Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ABC's daytime dramas ``Port Charles,'' ``All My Children,''
``One Life to Live'' and ``General Hospital'' get hit with the
nasty storm.
</P>
<P>
   The network leaps from fictional storm to real-life weather
disasters with ``World's Deadliest Storms: Caught on Tape'' on Feb.
18 as a lead-in to the third stanza of the King thriller. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOX &QL; 
That kind of sensationalistic reality programming is proof positive
that the Fox network's success with cops on the beat, dangerous car
chases and attacking animals is enough to get other networks to
come up with their own facsimiles. Three of the Big Four networks
are borrowing that format this February.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is still the leader in this type of programming; Thursdays
during sweeps &UR;  &LR; will be shock night. It kicks off at 8 tonight with
``Robbie Knievel Building-to-Building Death Jump Live,''
chronicling the daredevil's attempt to jump 180 feet from one Las
Vegas building to another _ without a net. Knievel's stunt will be
followed by ``The World's Most Shocking Moments 2: Caught on
Tape.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 11, the network will air ``World's Wildest Police
Videos,'' on Feb. 18 it will be ``The World's Most Shocking Medical
Videos,'' and, on Feb. 25, Fox will show ``Surviving the Moment of
Impact 3'' and ``Busted Everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's big-name guest stars will include Matthew McConaughey as
Luanne's new boyfriend on ``King of the Hill'' (Tuesday) and Sir
Elton John as a cartoon version of himself on ``The Simpsons''
(Feb. 14). Ed Begley Jr. will also play his own voice Sunday on
``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox wraps up its sweeps month with a two-hour special, ``Opening
the Lost Tombs: Live From Egypt'' (March 2), television's first
live archeological excavation. The network will take viewers to the
previously unopened pyramid of Queen Khamerernebty II. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NBC
</P>
<P>
   NBC is joining the reality TV bandwagon, despite West Coast
president Don Ohlmeyer's previous criticism of the same. They're
marching out ``Confirmation: Hard Evidence of Aliens Among Us?''
(Feb. 17) and ``Dave Barlia: Extreme Stuntman'' (Feb. 24).
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger draw may be the return of many familiar faces to
the Peacock network.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Harrelson will reprise his ``Cheers'' character on
tonight's episode of ``Frasier''; another ``Cheers'' alum, Rhea
Perlman, will appear on ``Mad About You'' (Monday). ``Mad About
You'' also will get a visit from home run king Mark McGwire, who
will play himself on the Feb. 22 episode.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Reynolds will play Grace's mother on ``Will &AMP; Grace''
(Tuesday), Cheryl Ladd will appear on ``Jesse'' as a former
classmate of the lead character's father (Feb. 11), and
Tiffani-Amber Thiessen will play office assistant Foxy Jones on
``NewsRadio'' (Feb. 16).
</P>
<P>
   Other NBC series events include the rest of the gang finding out
about Monica and Chandler's trysts on ``Friends'' (Feb. 11), and
George Clooney's final episode as a series regular on ``ER'' (Feb.
18).
</P>
<P>
   NBC's big miniseries will be ``The '60s'' (Sunday and Monday)
and ``To Serve and Protect,'' starring Craig T. Nelson, which will
head into the eye of ABC's ``Storm'' on Feb. 14 and 15. Producer
Robert Halmi Sr., the energy behind such gems as ``Gulliver's
Travels'' and ``Merlin,'' will add ``Alice in Wonderland'' to his
list of hits on Feb. 28. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CBS &QL; 
Stunt-casting, of course, is a staple of sweeps, so get ready to
watch some special guests on your favorite shows.
</P>
<P>
   Skating sensation Tara Lipinski will make three appearances on
CBS, including on daytime's ``The Young and the Restless'' (Feb.
9), prime time's ``Touched by an Angel'' (Feb. 14) and her own
special, ``Tara Lipinski: From This Moment'' (Feb. 17).
</P>
<P>
   On the network's ``The King of Queens,'' Jerry Stiller's comedy
teammate and real-life wife, Anne Meara, will guest star on ``The
King of Queens'' (Monday) as an intoxicating stranger who Arthur
(Stiller) meets at a single's dance. Their daughter, and Ben
Stiller's sister, Amy Stiller also appears.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Van Dyke will play ``Becker's'' father (Feb. 15) and Trisha
Yearwood will play a Navy reserve pathologist on ``JAG'' (Feb. 16).
</P>
<P>
   CBS will add to the miniseries game with a two-parter, ``Too
Rich: The Secret Life of Doris Duke'' (Feb. 21 and 23), and to the
award-show glut with ``The 41st Annual Grammy Awards'' (Feb. 24).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ABC &QL; 
Besides the storm of the century, ABC's got some other typical
sweeps-period stunts up its sleeve. Bringing on name brands to get
viewers to tune in, for one. Singing sensations 'N Sync will appear
on ``Sabrina the Teenage Witch'' (Friday), and World Figure Skating
Champion and Olympic silver medalist Michelle Kwan makes her acting
debut on the same show Feb. 26; Johnnie Cochran will play himself
on ``The Hughleys (Tuesday); Thiessen will play a single mother on
``Cupid'' (Feb. 11); and Christopher Lloyd will be Michael
Flaherty's (Michael J. Fox) political mentor and Priscilla Presley,
back as Aunt Marie, will guest star on ``Spin City'' Feb. 23.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WB &QL; 
Begley, who once played a doctor on TV (``St. Elsewhere''), will do
it again on the WB's ``7th Heaven,'' delivering twins on a special
Valentine's episode (Monday). The WB is packing its month with
two-part episodes of its hit teen dramas, ``Felicity'' (Tuesday and
Feb. 16) and ``Dawson's Creek'' (Wednesday and Feb. 17). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UPN &QL; 
UPN will pitch in with guest stars such as Jerry Springer on both
``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' and ``Between Brothers'' (both Feb. 23). It
will also air a couple of original science-fiction movies,
``Roswell: The Aliens Attack'' (tonight) and ``Escape From Mars''
(Feb. 25).
</P>
</TEXT>
