<SLUG> BC-TIMES-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4TH-QUARTER EARNINGS ROSE 5.7 PERCENT AT NEW YORK TIMES CO. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Times Co. reported a 5.7 percent rise in
fourth-quarter earnings Wednesday on steady increases in newspaper
advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The results matched analyst estimates. But the initial reaction
from investors was negative; company shares fell $1.50, to $32.50,
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding non-recurring items, the company earned $87.4 million
in the fourth quarter, compared with $82.7 million in the
corresponding quarter a year earlier. The results translated to 47
cents a diluted share, up 11.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1998, the company posted net income of $282.6
million, up 13.5 percent from $249.1 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue at The New York Times newspaper rose 7
percent to $1.06 billion, the first time revenue surpassed the
billion-dollar level. The rate of increase, though, declined from
more than 9 percent in the first half of the year, compared with
the corresponding period in the previous year, to about 4.6 percent
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Circulation revenue at the company's flagship newspaper _ which
represents about 25 percent of total revenue _ moved in the
opposite direction. The fourth quarter's gain of 4.5 percent was
the strongest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Barlow, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston, noted
that several other newspaper companies, including Gannett Co., had
reported earnings in line with Wall Street forecasts recently only
to see their share prices dip on the day of their announcements.
Most of these stock prices recovered soon after, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But two analysts _ Lauren Rich Fine of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and
Douglas Arthur of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter _ said the company's
revenue did not match their projections, though the slight 2.7
percent rise in costs kept overall results in line with
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in on track for the bottom line, but the revenue was
lighter than we were looking for,'' Ms. Fine said. At The Times
newspaper, Arthur said, ``There seems to be somewhat of a
disconnect between the size of the paper, the number of new color
ads and advertisers and the revenue numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   When non-recurring items are included, the company's net income
for the quarter and the full year both rose 6.3 percent, yielding
45 cents a diluted share for the quarter and $1.45 a diluted share
for the year. Including these charges, quarterly net income was
$84.3 million, up from $79.3 million, and annual net income was
$278.9 million, up from $262.3 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
