A0869 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-Y2K-MEDICAID-COX     02-03 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-Y2K-MEDICAID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State computers behind federal schedule
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's Medicaid program is behind the federal
government's schedule to ready its computer system for the year
2000, state officials acknowledged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the state maintained that the Department of Medical
Assistance was on track to meet the the state's own timetable for
Y2K compliance by May 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration, which oversees the
federal-state Medicaid programs for the poor, raised questions
about the Georgia program's preparedness in a recent visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some concerns,'' said Mike Hale, project manager for
Year 2000 project for the state of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA's concerns, he said, include Georgia Medicaid's having no
plan for independent verification of the computer testing program,
and no contingency plan if the corrected system doesn't perform as
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The state does not require independent testing, but Hale insists
the state's testing policy is very rigorous. Medicaid's contingency
plan is being formulated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have a new set of eyes, you learn something,''
Hale said, but added: ``I don't see anything now that will cause us
to change our schedule.'' Hale said HCFA's timetable to be ready
was March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid's computer system is a leading priority for the state.
The program covers about 1 million Georgians. It processes more
than 40 million medical claims a year for more than 25,000 doctors,
hospitals and other health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been actively testing codes,'' said Dr. William
Taylor, commissioner of DMA. Even under a worst-case scenario,
Taylor said, the computer system ``should not interfere with the
actual care people get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem threatens because computer programmers as a
shortcut used a two-digit code to represent the year. Thus, unless
software is adjusted, a OO date could mean 1900, not 2000. If not
corrected, experts say, those computers could shut down or produce
incorrect information.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA, which is assessing states' Medicaid programs, has not
issued a report on the Georgia system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gov. Roy Barnes said that he would hold state
department heads personally responsible for the success or failure
of their agencies to make their computer systems ready.
</P>
<P>
   The state has spent $152 million on fixing the computer bug,
with a bill pending to spend $170 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
