A0873 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-2TAKE     02-03 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-2TAKES(1,035)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TRIAL RECONVENES, REPUBLICANS APPEAR RELUCTANT TO CALL
WITNESSES
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos (NYT13-15,17,18) are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also IMPEACH-OPEN, IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-BORK) 
(fe) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the impeachment trial of President Clinton set
to reconvene on Thursday for what is likely to be its final phase,
House prosecutors favor bringing Monica Lewinsky to the Senate
floor, even though their chances of prevailing look dim.
</P>
<P>
   But several influential Republicans made it clear on Wednesday
that they were reluctant to call witnesses to appear in person in
the well of the Senate, amid signs that a number of Senate
Republicans were no longer rallying around the House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors interviewed the last of three witnesses behind
closed doors on Wednesday, questioning Sidney Blumenthal, a senior
White House aide, for about an hour and fifteen minutes, excluding
breaks. They questioned Ms. Lewinsky for several hours on Monday
and Clinton's close friend Vernon Jordan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The way is now clear for several decisive votes, confronting
Senators with decisions as early as Thursday on whether to make the
videotapes of the depositions public and whether to allow the three
witnesses to be questioned once again, this time in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to have a verdict that will withstand the
test of history, these witnesses should come forward,'' said Rep.
James E. Rogan, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But even Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., head of the House
prosecution team, sounded pessimistic about the chances that the
Senate would approve the request to question Ms. Lewinsky,
Blumenthal and Jordan in the well of the Senate. ``I haven't
received a world of encouragement, but I'm ever hopeful,'' Hyde
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there were strong signs that a number of Senate
Republicans would oppose witnesses. Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
said: ``I'm not really for live witnesses. I think we took the
depositions for discovery, and I don't think anything's been
added.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said, ``I lean very very strongly
against any appearance by Monica Lewinsky.'' And Sen. Olympia J.
Snowe, R-Maine, said, ``I cannot personally forsee circumstances in
which we would call Monica Lewinsky or the other witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said: ``My inclination is to
support what the House finally requests. But I think the votes are
probably not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night 28 Republican senators wrote to Clinton to ask
him to voluntarily testify in the trial. ``Your knowledge, intent,
actions and omissions are central to the charges the House of
Representatives have made against you,'' the letter said.
``Personal answers from you should prove beneficial in our effort
to reconcile conflicting testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has steadfastly said Clinton would not take such
a step.
</P>
<P>
   Already looking toward the trial's conclusion, Senate Democrats
and the White House began a concerted campaign against a Republican
proposal to approve ``findings of fact'' accusing Clinton of
misconduct before taking the final vote on the two articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic efforts last week to end the trial showed that there
are not the 67 votes needed to convict Clinton on the charges of
perjury and obstruction of justice. But the statement of facts
could be approved with as few as 51 votes. Democrats contend that
the idea is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution gives the United States Senate the
opportunity to convict, remove or to acquit,'' said Sen. Robert G.
Torricelli, D-N.J., after a closed-door party caucus. ``The Senate
is not free to rewrite the Constitution and draw its own
conclusions because Republicans need to choose between an element
of their constituency that wants conviction and an American public
which wants acquittal.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader from South Dakota,
threatened that the Democrats would use the right of ``unlimited
amendment'' to keep the proposal from ever coming to a vote. ``If
Republicans persist in demanding live witnesses and demanding more
depositions and demanding extra legal devices like findings of
fact, the more it becomes a Republican trial,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House echoed the theme. Joe Lockhart, the White House
press secretary, said of the senators, ``As they move toward the
exits, they shouldn't try to trample on the Constitution in the
process.'' He also tried to allay the fears of Senate Republicans
that Clinton will celebrate his acquittal as a political victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a certain sense of relief here at the White
House if this process were to end quickly and go away,'' Lockhart
said. ``But I don't think that there's anybody here who thinks
anything out of this process constitutes a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowe, who is a proponent of the fact finding, said the
procedures do pass constitutional muster. ``The significance of
finding of facts is it would be part of the permanent record of the
court of impeachment,'' she said. ``That would be, in my opinion,
indelibly etched in that record, and it could not be be erased and
it could not be revoked.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I think we do owe it to the American people to
inform them of the facts as we know them to be with respect to
misconduct or wrongdoing on the part of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not clear that Republicans would coalesce around the
plan. Republicans said there was vigorous debate about it in a
closed door caucus Wednesday night, and they plan another meeting
Thursday morning. Some Republicans, too, have constitutional
concerns about the proposal, and some say they are worried that
such a finding would create a precedent that would encourage the
use of impeachment trials as political weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point at least, Republicans are not unified in favor
of that,'' said one Republican senator, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity. ``If that is still the case tomorrow, we probably
will not offer it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats favor a censure of the president after the trial
is concluded, and Daschle named Sens. Dianne Feinstein of
California and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York to develop the
language. Some Republicans are open to the idea, but other
Republicans have said they consider censure meaningless or
constitutionally suspect.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's questioning of Blumenthal, a communications aide who
is a bete noire of conservatives, took place in a secure room on
the fourth floor of the Capitol and was videotaped. Officials said
Blumenthal repeated his prior testimony to a grand jury that the
president had described Ms. Lewinsky to him as a ``stalker.'' Only
this time he had to concede that the president had lied to him.
</P>
<P>
   Officials familiar with the session said Blumenthal stated that
he had never spread that description of Ms. Lewinsky to reporters
and that the president had not instructed him to do so. Blumenthal
was the last of three witnesses whom the House Republicans had
questioned in hopes of bolstering the article of impeachment
charging Clinton with obstruction of justice in his effort to cover
up his affair with Ms. Lewinsky. A second article accuses him of
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things the Senate will consider when the trial
resumes on Thursday is whether to put all or part of the three
witness depositions, on paper or on videotape, into the Senate's
public trial record. Hyde said the managers would ask that the
videotapes be publicized in a ``presentation'' to the Senate rather
than used in snippets on closing arguments. ``I think for
continuity's sake, we would like to have a presentation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Release of the videotapes would probably result in another media
blitz about the case since Ms. Lewinsky has never told her story in
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I think that it would be better left not
released to the public,'' said Daschle, questioning what the
release would add to the trial. But he said that if any part of the
tapes were to be made public, then the entire tapes should be
released. ``Our view is that if you're going to air a deposition,
you better air the whole thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the vote count was uncertain, the Senate seems more likely
to approve public release of the videotapes than to approve calling
witnesses to the Senate. John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, suggested that the
Senate could approve the public release of the depositions but keep
them under seal for a period of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
