<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0878 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO:TELECOM-LATINT     02-03 2421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO:TELECOM-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONING HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By BRENDAN M. CASE 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ Jose Cespedes has a telephone line, the lucky one
of every 11 Mexicans who have a phone. But he wants more. After
all, this is the age of the Internet, and the 29-year-old junior
marketing exec is online. Trouble is, he can't surf the World Wide
Web very long before everyone else in his house complains about the
phone line being blocked. ``It's easy at work, but at night there
are still a lot of sites on the Internet I want to look at,'' says
Cespedes. ``We're going to get a new line as soon as we can afford
it.''
 &HT;    New lines can be had from Telefonos de Mexico (Telmex), the
former state monopoly provider, but only at a price: they go for
between US$180 and $210 apiece, and can take months to install,
especially in rural areas.
 &HT;    But there is hope for people like Cespedes. By early this year,
several companies will be offering basic telephone services,
meaning Telmex will not be the only choicefor consumers eager to
have their own dial tone.
 &HT;    Mexico's second wave of telecom liberalization has begun, and a
host of companies are at the starting gate. After spending a total
of $1 billion on local service licenses for frequencies to offer
services using cutting-edge technologies, they are poised to
pioneer a huge advance in the telecommunications industry. ``It's a
privilege to be in this business at this time,'' says Rodrigo
Sandoval, the marketing director of Amaritel, one of the most
ambitious of the new local service companies. ``It means building a
business from scratch, we have the opportunity to do it well and to
create a good service. And we think this market has tremendous
potential.''
 &HT;    Mexico now has about nine lines per 100 people, a low
penetration even compared with other Latin American countries.
Chile and Argentina have almost 20, for example, and Brazil has 10.
The U.S. and Canada have about 55 lines per 100 people, according
to U.S. consultancy Booz, Allen &AMP; Hamilton. Even so, the local
service market, is already worth about $4 billion per year, about
the same size as the long-distance market, which was deregulated in
1997. But unlike long distance, Telmex controls nearly the entire
market.
 &HT;    The long-distance opening is already a success for customers.
Real prices have fallen since early 1997, by as much as 40 percent.
But the benefits of competition have been weighted towards
corporate clients and relatively well-off residential customers, in
short, to those who already had a phone. New local lines are the
key to the industry's development beyond the elite customers who
have enjoyed telephone service for most of Mexico's history.
 &HT;    While prices for basic telephone service are unlikely to fall as
drastically, service availability should become more democratic.
Industry analysts forecast that penetration will grow quickly in
the next five years, fueled by pent-up demand for telephone lines,
the growth of the Internet, as well as business demand for
value-added services such as video conferencing and high-speed data
transmission. Government officials hope that local service
competition will boost teledensity to 20 lines per 100 people by
the year 2000. Private sector analysts say that goal is probably
overly optimistic. But they stress that in this day and age,
telecom growth is crucial to the overall economy's development.
 &HT;    With investments ranging from $70 million to $600 million over
the next five years, the upstarts expect to find a huge unserved
market of customers who either do not have telephone lines or want
more. To play for a piece of the pie, they have pledged total
investments of $8 billion between now and 2003.
 &HT;    To be sure, there are obstacles. Telmex has become a very tough
competitor since being privatized back in 1990. Then, it was one of
Mexico's most-hated companies, generating more complaints than any
other firm at the offices of the Attorney General for Consumer
Protection.
 &HT;    Times have changed. Line installations can still take up to six
months in some parts of the country, but company technicians have
cut the wait to just a couple weeks in much of Mexico City. Telmex
has started to treat telephone users like valued customers and
consumer complaints involving its service have fallen drastically
during the last few years. ``Telmex has made a lot of progress in
the customer care area, with their service, their quality, (and)
the diversification of their services,'' says Santiago Gutierrez,
vice president and telecom specialist at Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton.
``Competitors will need a lot of creativity to compete successfully
with Telmex.''
 &HT;    The new telecom players will also have trouble getting past a
regulatory environment that became much more complicated at the end
of 1998. Facing a slump in the price of oil, the Mexican government
slapped a 15 percent tax on local and long-distance telephone
service on top of the 15 percent value-added tax customers already
pay.
 &HT;    After spending millions of dollars on their concessions in last
spring's frequency auction, executives at the new telecom companies
were beside themselves with anger. Officials at the Federal
Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel) were unhappy as well, since
expanding Mexicans' access to local service is one of their key
goals. ``This tax goes against the spirit of openness in the
telecommunications sector, and is incongruent with the promotion of
investment in the industry,'' says Carlos de la Isla, the finance
director at Grupo Hermes, which won a local service license in last
spring's auction. ``The tax will cut telephone use, with all its
consequences.''
 &HT;    Another big question telecom companies face is what kind of
treatment they will get from regulators. Cofetel's only track
record comes from the long-distance market, where the Mexican
affiliates of the U.S. telecom giants _ AT&AMP;T's Alestra and MCI's
Avantel _ have wrested 30 percent of the roughly $4 billion in
total long-distance revenues from Telmex since launching their
operations. But they also complain of high interconnection fees and
international settlement rates, and charge that Telmex still
behaves like a monopoly. Whatever the reason, Telmex has defied
original expectations that it would fold against the foreign
competition, and proven it will remain the industry giant in both
long-distance and local service for the foreseeable future.
 &HT;    Local-service providers face their own challenges: finding
market niches they can serve better than Telmex. Low-income
customers are one possibility, particularly if companies can offer
a phone line more cheaply than Telmex. Other niches could involve
particular regions of the country or services aimed at business
clients. The new companies are all planning a mix of these,
although their exact strategies won't be entirely clear until they
launch. ``The broader the market these companies consider, the less
chance they have of succeeding,'' says Gutierrez. ``The key thing
is that they need to differentiate themselves from the competition:
from Telmex and from each other.''
 &HT;    But given Telmex's dominance in the local market, companies will
have to design their strategies very carefully. Analysts say there
is no room for a direct competitor to Telmex, since the cost of
duplicating the company's national network would be exorbitant.
 &HT;    Technology is one area that sets the newcomers apart, as they
seek to skirt the heavy investments associated with traditional
landline basic telephony. Executives at Amaritel, Telinor and
Miditel say they will use a mixture of microwave, fiber-optic and
wireless local-loop technology to provide service in different
regions of the country, while Unefon will rely mostly on wireless
local-loop. MCNI Telecom, a subsidiary of Guadalajara-based cable
television company Megacable, is completing a fiber-optic ring
around Mexico City, and plans to do the same in Guadalajara and
Monterrey. And Pegaso PCS and Grupo Hermes will use personal
communications services (PCS) wireless technology.
 &HT;    One of the grandest plans belongs to Amaritel. Backed by U.S.
investors, Amaritel is putting the finishing touches on a $120
million microwave and fiber-optic network between Mexico City and
Puebla.
 &HT;    In early 1999, the company plans to extend the network to Vera
cruz and the rest of the Gulf Coast, a total five-year investment
of $560 million between mid-1998 and the 2003. By that time, the
company's service should be available to a quarter of Mexico's
population. ``Our objective is not to fight Telmex toe-to-toe, but
to grow by serving markets it hasn't served sufficiently,'' says
Sandoval. ``There are many people who don't have telephone lines
and want one. There are also many people and companies that have
service but want more capacity, for the Internet, for more calls,
whatever. Telmex can't serve them fast enough.''
 &HT;    The key to Amaritel's success will be finding business customers
who need more capacity or want better service, although they will
actively court residential customers as well, Sandoval says.
 &HT;    Amaritel's small size in relation to Telmex could actually help
with many business customers. Except for the biggest corporate
clients, Telmex tends to treat all customers the same, offering the
same services and the same level of attention. By contrast,
Amaritel plans to provide to coddle its clients. ``Our very size
will allow us to get out of the office, meet with customers, design
custom solutions and install them rapidly,'' says Sandoval, adding
that Amaritel expects to have 40,000 lines installed by the end of
1999.
 &HT;    Another company that could do a lot to boost teledensity is
Unefon, an affiliate of electronics retailer Grupo Elektra. But
Unefon is also experiencing the most problems in getting off the
ground.
 &HT;    As a subsidiary of Elektra, Unefon has a built-in customer base
among the working-class consumers who frequent Elektra's 550 stores
around the country. Even better, Elektra already has a detailed
database of credit histories and long years of profitable
experience selling goods on credit to people ignored by commercial
banks. ``We already have a lot of synergies to work with,'' says
Javier Sarro, Unefon's director general. ``If you want to be in
this business, you need distribution, promotion, credit and
collection. And we know that Elektra has more than a million credit
customers who want a phone, don't have one, but who are able to pay
for one.''
 &HT;    But Unefon is having trouble finding financing. Last year's
market turbulence spoiled Unefon's plans to place high-yield bonds
abroad. It now plans to use a mix of debt and equity financing, but
unlike most of the other local service companies, its needs are not
yet fully financed. Miditel, another local hopeful, is in the same
boat as Unefon, and for similar reasons. One of its main backers,
Korea Telecom, pulled out of Mexico last July because of the severe
problems in Korea due to the Asian economic crisis. Miditel is now
looking for a new equity partner.
 &HT;    The early PCS leader seems to be Grupo Pegaso, a start-up
telecom company that belongs in part to Alejandro Burillo
Azcarraga, one of media conglomerate Grupo Televisa's principal
shareholders, and Qualcomm, the U.S. communications equipment
company. With its coffers full and a PCS license in hand, the
company is one of the favorites to grab a share of the higher end
of the market. Pegaso PCS, as the joint-venture is known, will
start by offering mobile PCS service, which would sound and feel to
customers like a sort of deluxe cellular service.
 &HT;    But it would take only a bit more investment to provide fixed
PCS service, which would compare to land-line service in quality
without the infrastructure investment costs. Analysts expect the
company to branch out into fixed service soon after launching.
``Pegaso is very well-positioned. The company has an interesting
technology and seems to be committed to the market,'' says Booz,
Allen's Gutierrez. ``Of course, Telmex and Grupo Hermes also have
PCS licenses, so there will be competition.''
 &HT;    As the local service companies fight to establish themselves
over the next few years, some predictions can safely be made.
 &HT;    One is that not all will survive. Ten companies originally
planned to offer long distance service, but that number that has
been cut to four, including Telmex. A similar shakeout is expected
among local service companies. Since their initial investments are
so high, so is the pressure to meet with early success _ those that
don't might quickly disappear.
 &HT;    Moreover, successful local companies could band together with a
long-distance partner. Rumors of such a deal are flying throughout
the country. Such common U.S. practices as reselling _ in which a
company without a telecom network buys time at wholesale rates on
another company's network, then markets its own service to retail
customers _ are also expected to take shape in Mexico as the market
develops.
 &HT;    All of which points to a promising, and much more complicated,
future. Gone are the days when Telmex was the only game in town. It
will now be merely the biggest in what is already one of Latin
America's most competitive telecom markets.
 &HT;    Which is all to the good for people like Cespedes, the marketing
exec who likes to surf the Internet. ``To be honest, I want to get
a new line as quickly as possible,'' he says. ``But I don't care if
it's from Telmex or another company, as long as it works.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
