<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-IRAQ-NYT     02-03 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LOSING GUARANTEE OF SAFETY, U.N. ORDERS AMERICANS TO LEAVE
IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
 (dal) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United Nations ordered its remaining
American staff in Iraq to leave Wednesday after Baghdad warned that
it could not guarantee their safety.
</P>
<P>
   The order, in practice, affects only two Americans among 420
non-Iraqis working in the country to provide food and medicine.
Another 12 to 15 British and American employees working for the
program already had left the country.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Eckhard, the U.N. spokesman, said he could recall no
precedent for such a move in the relief program. He said the
decision was made by Benon Sevan, the U.N. undersecretary-general
who oversees security and coordinates the Iraq ``oil for food''
program.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in the wake of sustained U.S. air strikes on
Iraq and after a month-long effort by U.N. officials failed to
elicit a pledge from Baghdad to honor its obligation to protect all
U.N. personnel, irrespective of nationality.
</P>
<P>
   Sevan recommended the ban to Kofi Annan, the secretary-general,
after Baghdad did not provide written assurances that U.N.
employees would be protected.
</P>
<P>
   Sevan's decision contrasts with that of Richard Butler, the
beleaguered chairman of the U.N. Special Commission charged with
disarming Iraq of weapons of mass destruction. When Iraq threatened
to bar entry to U.S. inspectors on teams in 1997, Butler decided to
stop inspections rather than permit Iraq to dictate the composition
of U.N. inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Sevan did not make a similar decision, Eckhard said:
``I don't want to compare Benon Sevan's judgment with Richard
Butler's judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Several U.N. officials said that the organization sometimes
informally refrained from sending staff of certain nationalities to
places where they might be in particular harm's way, but that they
were unhappy about Sevan's decision, calling it troubling.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they added, Sevan was primarily motivated to
provide assistance to the people of Iraq, one million of whom are
said to be suffering from the effects of food shortages and other
results of economic sanctions and Saddam Hussein's reluctance to
buy the vital food and medicine he is permitted to import through
oil sales.
</P>
<P>
   The two Americans who have been ordered to leave Iraq are the
secretary to Prakash Shah, Annan's special envoy in Iraq, and the
deputy director of the World Food Program, which on Wednesday
announced a $21 million appeal to help the hungry in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad had offered to make an exemption for these two
Americans, plus a third who was working in Baghdad, but Sevan did
not think that any Americans and British should be singled out to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Both the British Foreign Office and U.S. officials in Washington
expressed ``regret'' about the decision, but added that the safety
and security of its citizens required such a move. They blamed the
government of Iraq, saying that its unwillingness to guarantee the
employees' safety had ``forced'' the United Nations to take the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the U.N. employees in its ``oil for food'' program are
in northern Iraq, in three Kurdish provinces not directly under
Baghdad's control.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations distributes food in the north and monitors
its distribution by the Iraqi government in the rest of the
country. The program permits Iraq to sell almost $5.3 billion worth
of oil every six months to buy food, medicine and basic goods.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been slowly building. Iraq warned in early January
that it might expel U.S. and British relief workers, saying in an
unsigned diplomatic note that their safety could not be assured
given public anger over air strikes which, Iraq charged and the
United States and Britain denied, had targeted ``schools,
universities, hospitals, grain depots, means of communications and
factories.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, U.N. officials have tried unsuccessfully to secure
safety guarantees from Baghdad. While all U.N. members are required
to assure such protection, there is no automatic penalty in the
group's charter for failing to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is likely to be raised when the Security Council,
deeply divided over the 8-year-old economic sanctions on Iraq,
discusses policy towards Iraq at future meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
