<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-MAYOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABOUT-FACE IN WASHINGTON IN FUROR ON MISUNDERSTOOD WORD
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: LEDES with 3 grafs to recast, remove quotes.) 
 (DW) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY 
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bringing an end to the latest incident exposing
racial tensions in the nation's capital, Mayor Anthony A. Williams
on Wednesday asked a white aide who resigned last week for using
the word niggardly in a conversation with a black colleague to
return to his post.
</P>
<P>
   While he did not apologize to the aide, David Howard, Williams
conceded that he should not have accepted the resignation without
knowing what was said and how it was heard. Williams said in a
statement, ``I believe I acted too hastily in accepting David's
resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard, 44, who had worked on the mayor's election campaign, met
with him for 20 minutes Wednesday and told him he would like to
return to a city government job, but not the one he left, director
of the Office of the Public Advocate.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Howard said that he was satisfied with the
resolution of the matter but that it was ``really not about me or
the use of the word niggardly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about feelings underneath the surface that a lot of
people in Washington and the whole nation wanted to talk about.''
he said. ``This was just the flashpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he believed the city would benefit from the
incident. ``A lot of good came of this,'' Howard said. ``It has
fostered a discussion, not about racial tensions but about racial
perceptions. It can only help us to understand each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' decision follows a swirl of events that began on Jan.
15, when Howard used the word, a synonym for miserly with
Scandinavian origins centuries older than the similar-sounding
racial slur, in a budget discussion with two co-workers. One of the
co-workers said later that he thought he heard Howard use the
racial epithet. Howard had said, ``I will have to be niggardly with
this fund because it's not going to be a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   After rumors of the misunderstanding and news of hurt feelings
reached Howard, he acknowledged that he had used ``bad judgment''
in selecting such a word and offered his resignation on Jan. 26. It
was immediately accepted by Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But that only led to a bad situation's turning worse, prompting
waves of protest around the city _ from language purists, arguing
that niggardly is a perfectly acceptable word; from homosexuals,
defending Howard as the mayor's first openly-gay appointee, and
from many blacks who already have questioned Williams' loyalties to
fellow blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the incident became the latest example of the
difficulties District leaders have in navigating issues of race in
a city that, despite its black majority, has no voting
representative in an overwhelmingly white Congress that ultimately
runs Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the city's former chief financial officer, who was
educated at Yale and Harvard, is perceived by many in the city as a
less forceful representative of his fellow blacks than his
predecessor, Marion S. Barry Jr., a veteran of the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who initiated an investigation of the matter after
Howard resigned, said in his statement that he had concluded that
Howard did use the word niggardly and had not used a racial
epithet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The review also showed that an employee of the Office of the
Public Advocate did misunderstand Howard to have used a racial
epithet,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was inaugurated on Jan. 2, also said that he had
learned a lot through this incident. ``While it is important for a
mayor, or any leader, to act decisively, make bold decisions and
create a sense of urgency,'' he said, ``it is not always necessary
to act hastily.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
