<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NONBANKS-BANKS-ART-11     02-03 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NONBANKS-BANKS-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLERLESS WONDERS ARE REINVENTING SMALL-BUSINESS LENDING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the future of small-business banking? At least one person
had answers a full decade ago, and he wore T-shirts, not pin
stripes.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the actor-comic-director Robert Townsend
financed part of his independent film ``Hollywood Shuffle'' with a
fistful of credit cards. Despite punitive interest rates, the
gamble paid off when the movie became a hit. These days, some
small-business people never set foot in their local banks.
</P>
<P>
   By last year, the two top bankers for small businesses were not
banks at all, but the credit card issuers Mountain West Financial
and American Express. A third, the Advanta Corp., which provides
credit cards and other forms of business financing, was in the top
five. Together, the three accounted for a third of all corporate
loans up to $100,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Falling regulatory barriers have prompted a free-for-all among
companies that want to provide small and not-so-small businesses
with loans and other services that were once the province of
traditional banks. Many new nonbank contenders say they have caught
the big banks napping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banking is essential, banks are not,'' said Richard
Kovacevich, chief executive of Wells Fargo &AMP; Co., one of the
bluntest bankers in assessing the plight of big banks.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the country's largest brokerage house, as
well as American Express and Boston Financial Network, an Internet
upstart, are just a few of the nonbanks that see themselves as the
business bankers of the future. They and many others say they have
links to business people through brokers, credit cards and
accounting software that offer as much of a draw for customers as
bricks-and-mortar branch offices.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way the nonbanks are making their own rules and
ignoring some old ones. Most have scrapped separate savings and
checking accounts, a tradition they call anachronistic. The
nonbanks boast of lending policies that are friendlier to
entrepreneurs who often don't have large inventories or other
assets to use as collateral. And with the help of the Internet,
some finance companies offer such banking-related services as
issuing paychecks, paying bills, preparing accounts and taxes and
juggling credit lines, all with a single online account.
</P>
<P>
   The competition brings to business banking the simplicity and
lower costs that banks and nonbanks alike have begun offering
individual consumers. But the struggle to win loyalty from business
has higher stakes, because banks earn far more profits from small
and medium-size businesses than from individuals, and little
businesses sometimes become large ones, with still bigger profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks have not been well focused'' in creating products for
small businesses, said Nick Winter, a financial services specialist
with Mercer Management Consulting. ``The banks have left themselves
open to being cherry-picked by people who don't have to carry the
costs of a branch network.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, even some sizable young companies are declaring
themselves bank-free. Take Professional Modification Services, an
aircraft repair and conversion company based in Miami. With 500
employees and $40 million in sales, it is an obvious target for
Florida's leading banks. But it turned instead to Merrill, which
also serves as the personal broker of several company executives.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's opportunity came when the company had trouble
borrowing enough to pay salaries during fallow periods between
aircraft overhauls. Local bankers extended credit only when it had
a full order book. But Merrill came through with a $750,000 credit
line that was not directly tied to accounts receivable or
inventory, said Aviv Tzur, chief financial officer at Professional
Modification Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regular banks only want to lend money when you least need
it,'' Tzur said, echoing an old complaint. He spoke over the whine
of drills boring into metal at the company's hangar at Miami
International Airport as workers were pulling apart a Boeing 727
passenger plane to turn it into a cargo transporter. ``Our business
is a good one,'' he said, ``but it's not always steady. We have to
pay these people even when there are no aircraft here.''
</P>
<P>
   The credit line gave Merrill an opening to provide other
services as well. Tzur said the firm beat out First Union, the
banking powerhouse, to set up an employee stock-ownership plan.
Merrill also manages Professional Modification Service's working
capital. The Merrill checking account pays interest at rates pegged
to Treasury bonds, and it has automatic links with the company's
credit line. Local banks, Tzur said, did not offer a
cash-management package with as many features.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship is a good illustration of the threat to
traditional banks that was envisioned at least two decades ago with
the first hint that Depression-era laws separating banks from
brokerage and insurance companies might be relaxed. Merrill has
been at the forefront of nonbank financial companies that see those
boundaries as minor hurdles now, though it and other companies are
still lobbying hard to repeal the Glass-Steagall Act, which
separates commercial and investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, of course, are leaping into previously forbidden
territory, too. Citigroup, for example, which was born of the $70
billion union of Travelers Group and Citicorp, obliterates the old
walls dividing banking, brokerage and insurance. But nonbanks
appear to be making headway on banking turf faster than banks are
gaining ground elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Banks face challenges in nearly every area of their business.
Twenty years ago, the typical American household stashed more than
a third of its money in a local bank. Now the average is close to a
sixth. Businesses have also reduced their reliance on commercial
bank loans, turning regularly to the bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo, for one, is not passively accepting its fate. The
bank, newly merged with Norwest, calls its branches ``stores.'' It
also pioneered Internet banking and has aimed an array of new
products at small businesses. Its response is not surprising, for
it has the most to lose. With $16 billion in loans outstanding,
Wells Fargo ranks as the largest national lender to companies with
less than $20 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Michael James, who heads the Wells Fargo small-business team,
argues that a vast majority of business people still have bank
accounts, giving banks a leg up in offering true one-stop shopping.
But he acknowledges having to scramble to fend off nonbanks. ``A
decade ago no one was paying attention,'' he said. ``Now it's
becoming extremely competitive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Merrill has plotted how to break into banking since the late
1970s, when it was run by Donald Regan, who went on to become
Treasury secretary and White House chief of staff for President
Reagan. In the 1980s it developed its ``working capital management
account,'' which pays money market interest rates and offers some
services that are still novelties for banks, like having extra cash
swept periodically into customized interest-bearing securities. But
only recently has Merrill, which faces a slew of new online
competitors in its own core brokerage business, tried to become a
full-service banker.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill executives now say they plan to challenge Wells Fargo
and other banks that focus on the small-business market. Merrill
has hired 100 commercial bankers and plans to add 25 more this
year. Stationed at regional offices around the country, the bankers
work closely with the firm's 14,000 brokers. Last year its loans to
companies with less than $100 million in sales doubled, to roughly
$4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a great deal larger than people realize,'' said John C.
Qua, a Merrill senior vice president and director of the firm's
business financial services division. ``When you consider all the
services we provide, no one is close to us nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill has also challenged banks' dominance of the lucrative
trust business. With little public attention, it bought a failed
Florida savings and loan, giving it a license to offer trust
services in all 50 states. The operation, which manages custody
accounts as well as personal and charitable trust assets, is not
yet profitable, in part because Merrill is still poaching scores of
trust officers from commercial banks. The trust subsidiary now has
$80 billion in assets, including $8.4 billion that generate
management fees.
</P>
<P>
   David Chambers, chief executive of Merrill's trust subsidiary,
said many traditional banks had squandered their lead in trust
services by rushing to merge and distancing themselves from
customers. ``We are moving in the opposite direction,'' he said.
``They are consolidating their operations. We are moving people
into the local market.''
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders are building a business on the once
quirky-sounding notion that it was possible to make movies with
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, for example, has set its sights on luring
businesses with fewer than 100 employees away from banks. Some 2
million small businesses use the company's corporate cards, and
that gives American Express a target list for direct-mail
campaigns. It has recently pushed a range of banking services like
equipment financing, tax and accounting help, and short-term credit
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest rates are high, and you have to pay it back
fast,'' said David Reisner, who owns a household appliance store,
Allwell Supplies in Brooklyn, and borrowed from American Express
four or five times in the last year when his store's revenue
sagged. ``I would describe it as a quick fix, not a long-term
solution. But it's done instantly and no hassles.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers like that show that American Express can leverage its
brand name into a range of banklike services, said Steve Alesio,
president of the company's small-business services division.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years ago these kinds of people were getting
services from traditional community banks,'' he said. ``They had
too much paperwork, and some had cash-flow problems. We are
offering a simpler service that's national in scope.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has also taken away one of the traditional banks'
key advantages: geography. Boston Financial Network, the new online
banking service, has no branches or tellers. But it says it can act
as banker, broker, bookkeeper and bill payer for small businesses
anywhere in the country _ through a single Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Like some other new banking companies, Boston Financial Network
is just the middleman. Electronic bill payments are contracted out
to the Checkfree Corp. Computing Resources Inc. handles payroll
services. The mutual fund company Scudder Kemper manages cash in
money-market funds. And if negotiations are successful, credit
lines will come from American Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran a small business for a while, and I could not get
support from banks and brokerage firms,'' said Barry Star, chairman
of Boston Financial Network and a former Fidelity Investments
executive. ``I built this service for myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
