<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIEBERT-MARKETPLACE-A     02-03 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIEBERT-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE :  VAST RICHES AND RUDE VAGARIES OF INTERNET TRADING
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: (STAR) in the company name E(STAR)Trade, which appears
throughout the story, should be changed to the typographical
symbol.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is perhaps one good thing to say about the exuberant
frenzy in Internet stocks: It is opening up the Silicon riches
beyond the young boys' club that has hoarded it until now.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Internet billionaire, for example, is not some lucky
Stanford grad student or nocturnal Seattle programmer barely past
shaving age.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's billion-dollar lottery ticket was in the hands of
Muriel Siebert, a veteran of breaking through glass ceilings for
four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Siebert, as she is known to those old enough to remember
when electronic trading meant calling your broker on the telephone,
caused quite a few waves in 1967 as the first woman to buy a seat
on the New York Stock Exchange. Later, she was the first woman
banking superintendent of New York state.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the shares of the Siebert Financial Corp., the
holding company for Ms. Siebert's brokerage firm, soared $23.50, or
90.4 percent, to $49.50. A week ago, the shares traded at $11. The
stock's ascent places Ms. Siebert's paper wealth slightly over $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert Financial has benefited from investors' interest in
online trading, which has turned out to be the hottest business on
the Internet. In the fourth quarter of 1998, one in every seven
stock trades in this country was entered over the Internet,
according to Bill Burnham, electronic commerce analyst and trading
guru at Credit Suisse First Boston. And in January, he estimates,
online volume rose by a third.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the shares of any company that offers stock trading
on a World Wide Web site has been surging. Even shares of JB Oxford
Holdings, a Beverly Hills brokerage firm being investigated on
charges of market manipulation, rose 153 percent Wednesday, to $12.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the electronic trading business is hardly easy.
E(STAR)Trade Group Inc., despite a $100 million investment in
technology, suffered significant system problems Wednesday and was
unable to accept trades in two periods during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say E(STAR)Trade will suffer no long-term damage from
the incidents because most of the other online firms have also had
occasional computer glitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like handing out speeding tickets at the Indy 500,''
Burnham said. ``You can pull over whoever you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   In this fast field, Siebert Financial had been something of an
also-ran. The brokerage firm has offered online trading for the
last several years. But Burnham says it is a minor player in this
market, with no more than a few thousand online trades a day.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the firm hardly has a blue-chip pedigree. It went
public in 1996, not through a traditional offering, but by buying a
defunct Brooklyn furniture company, a tactic looked down upon by
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped stock traders from seizing on Siebert as
potentially a cheaper way to bet on electronic brokerage than by
buying the already expensive leaders: E(STAR)Trade, Ameritrade and
Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that many people actually believe that Siebert will be
the next E(STAR)Trade, but that enough people are willing to bet
that someone else will think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a group of marauding traders who are doing this with
their eyes wide open,'' Burnham said. ``There is talk in the chat
rooms; then there is takeover speculation, and finally the stock
starts to move, bringing in the momentum players.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are only 710,000 shares of Siebert Financial that the
public can trade, as Ms. Siebert owns 92 percent of the company.
Since 10.4 million shares of Siebert Financial traded on the Nasdaq
stock market Wednesday, the average share changed hands seven times
during the day. (Nasdaq counts each trade twice).
</P>
<P>
   What that means, of course, is that the real price of Siebert
Financial, should Ms. Siebert choose to sell it, will likely be far
less than the value ascribed to it by the market Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of selling any of my stock,'' Ms. Siebert
said in a terse telephone interview. ``We've been in business for a
long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
