<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-WITCH-COX     02-03 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-WITCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witch denied chance to sponsor baseball team
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE _ A local witch could have a legal battle brewing
after a youth baseball league turned down her offer of $250 to
sponsor a team this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Ygraine, who calls herself a witch and owns a store that
peddles items linked to the occult, didn't get it when the
president of the Babe Ruth Bambino Baseball League returned her
money. She was especially perplexed since league representatives
sought her out as a donor, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept saying, `Is this going to be a problem?' and I was
assured that all they wanted to do was help the kids,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ygraine says her religion doesn't involve animal sacrifices, nor
does it promote hate. In fact, she says, the Church of Satan
stresses responsibility, self-empowerment, and self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   But after visiting Pandora's Box, Ygraine's shop on Port St.
Lucie Boulevard, league president Dave Bowman cited league
guidelines that forbid sponsorship by groups whose practices are
``inimical to the welfare of youth'' and backed away from the
arrangement. The new league, which has its first games Feb. 20,
serves children ages 5 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most disturbing thing,'' Bowman said, is that the shop was
selling daggers without keeping them under lock and key. The
religion had nothing to do with his decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that we felt we don't need,'' he said. ``I
don't know what she is. I don't know if she's a Baptist or
Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Ygraine could face a legal battle. Sieg Christman, president
of the Treasure Coast chapter of the American Civil Liberties
Union, plans on calling the organization's attorneys today, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little league, being a private organization . . .
basically has the right to discriminate,'' Christman said.
``However, the problem you run into is that they use public lands
to be able to have their baseball leagues on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman seemed unfazed by the ACLU interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be bullied,'' he said. ``I'm going to stick
up for this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone share's Bowman's concern.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Pierce Central High School baseball program on
Wednesday happily accepted $170 from Ygraine, who when she was 17
named herself after King Arthur's mother, a figure in Celtic
mythology.
</P>
<P>
   And last week Port St. Lucie High School's baseball program
accepted $220 from Ygraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's money they're giving, it's no problem,'' Port St.
Lucie High School athletic director Danny Ninestine said. ``That's
different from them donating Budweiser shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
