<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     02-03 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IOC ARROGANCE IS OUR OWN FAULT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (Eds: See also OLY-DRUGS) 
(mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is out in the open now. We are back to 1776 and 1789 and all
those memorable years. In the foolish little world of sport, the
lords are trying to tell the rabble what is good for them, and they
are answering back.
</P>
<P>
   The lords of sport ride in limousines instead of liveried
coaches, and the monarch of the ``Olympic family'' prefers a
private railroad train when he travels in Japan. When they hold
their sporting events, they reside behind barbed wire and armed
guards, while the people mill in the tawdry streets.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday in Lausanne, Switzerland, the United States and 15
members of the European Union demanded that the International
Olympic Committee not even try to manage a proposed agency to
monitor drugs. And in the face of a mushrooming bribery scandal,
some IOC delegates even balked at giving up their rights to vote
for host cities.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly leaders of the IOC responded by taking off their
polite masks and snarling at the plebians. Of course, we contribute
to this by fluttering over soppy Olympic sagas, creating our own
soap-opera royals.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, we take all sports too seriously, giving platforms to
blithering jocks like Glenn Hoddle, who was sacked on Tuesday as
coach of the English national soccer team. Hoddle's loopy blend of
Christianity and Hindu reincarnation says that disabled people are
victims of bad karma in a previous life.
</P>
<P>
   It's our fault for letting sports figures think they can babble
like this. Eugene Robinson, the self-styled prophet of the Atlanta
Falcons, ran around a victorious locker room a few weeks ago saying
God had favored his team over Minnesota. On the night before the
Super Bowl, the prophet was arrested for allegedly propositioning a
plainclothes police officer for sex. I suspect that people would
feel far less vindictive about one man's disgrace if we had not
been subject to his ranting about divine intervention in a stupid
football game.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, we invest too much moral authority in Juan Antonio
Samaranch, who is essentially an autocratic deliverer of expensive
sporting events. Last week Samaranch made an apology for the
corruption in the bidding process for Olympic host cities.
</P>
<P>
   This week the IOC grappled with another scandal _ the
sophisticated use of performance-enhancing drugs by athletes.
During a summit on drugs in Lausanne, much of the public criticism
of the IOC has come from the Colonies. Hey, it's in our rebellious
genes.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, director of the U.S. Office of National Drug
Control Policy, called for an independent drug agency that was not
tied into the IOC. He also called for a 365-day-a-year drug-testing
policy rather than the current slapdash system.
</P>
<P>
   The lords of the IOC did not like being told what to do. Jacques
Rogge, an IOC executive board member from Belgium, criticized all
American professional sports because Mark McGwire had hit 70 home
runs last year while admittedly taking a body-building substance,
androstenedione, that is forbidden under Olympic rules but not by
baseball rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go on the moralizing and lecturing tone, you must be
sure your own house is in order,'' Rogge said. Rogge may not be
aware that McGwire was indeed criticized in the news media and by
some medical authorities who feared he might be harming himself,
and surely setting a bad example to younger athletes. Besides, who
is Jacques Rogge to criticize poor schnooky baseball? That's our
job.
</P>
<P>
   Another candid exposure of arrogance came from Prince Alexandre
de Merode, the IOC official overseeing the drug epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take offense that politicians don't trust me to chair this
agency,'' de Merode said. ``Why should I trust politicians?''
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that the prince must be sneaking looks at the
congressional impeachment process on CNN. Nevertheless, I would
trust our buffoons more than just about anybody with the word
``prince'' in front of his name. At least politicians have to run
for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The arrogant patricians and corrupt delegates of the IOC
obviously cannot keep their castle in order. This would all be a
comic opera except that communities around the world must scurry to
buy favor with the IOC. Salt Lake City will be forever tarnished by
reasonable suspicions that every friend of the Olympics _ every
sponsor, every municipality, every advertiser, every network _
diverted company and public resources and our tax dollars to
purchase the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Well, we've been through that before _ No Taxation Without
Representation. Samaranch and his henchmen are not amused at the
criticism. We share the blame for treating these people like
athletic royalty in the first place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
