<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARLINDO-AZR &LR;      02-03 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARLINDO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM TRASH TO TREASURE: MEXICAN SEA WASTE BECOMES U.S. FERTILIZER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fish guts.
</P>
<P>
   GOODYEAR, Ariz. _ Shrimp heads.
</P>
<P>
   Crab shells.
</P>
<P>
   What for generations has been trash to Mexico's fishermen has
turned to treasure for Hector Tirado.
</P>
<P>
   ``He found a niche nobody else wants,'' said Roger Blotsky,
founder of BioFlora Systems in Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   BioFlora, the largest maker of organic fertilizer in the United
States, buys much of the fish-based ingredients for its products
from Tirado's company.
</P>
<P>
   As owner of Phoenix-based Marlindo Products, Tirado brokers fish
products from five Mexican suppliers to U.S. feed and fertilizer
manufacturers like BioFlora. He also buys them outright and resells
them in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Marlindo's products include a thick brown liquid called
condensed fish solubles, made of fish guts and waste but nearly
one-third protein.
</P>
<P>
   It was Tirado's cousin, manager of a fish-meal processing plant
in Guaymas, who turned him on to the strong-smelling, neglected
items. Processors had previously thrown the waste back into the
ocean, but as Mexico's environmental rules tightened, the cousin
asked Tirado to find a market for the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Tirado, an agronomist who worked in sales and marketing at
Ralston Purina Co. for 17 years, realized that the high-protein
content meant it could be mixed with hay to enrich animal feed.
</P>
<P>
   After two misadventures getting railroad tanker cars out of
Mexico to feed lots in Iowa, Tirado found a new market in companies
that make feed for farms growing trout, salmon, shrimp and catfish.
The fish like the solubles' powerful taste, but again Tirado ran
into problems.
</P>
<P>
   The buyers wanted a consistently high level of protein in the
feed, but the Mexican processors didn't particularly care.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make their money on fish meal, and this was a nuisance to
them,'' Tirado said.
</P>
<P>
   Re-analyzing the solubles, ``I realized all that a plant needs
is in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he started calling manufacturers of organic fertilizers,
sending them samples and soon he began receiving orders for a
barrel here and a tanker load there.
</P>
<P>
   Today, BioFlora buys more than half a million gallons of fish
solubles from Marlindo and uses its products in all of its 500
formulations, Blotsky said. Smaller makers of products for home
gardeners also buy Marlindo ingredients, Tirado said.
</P>
<P>
   Blotsky said he first began working with Tirado about eight
years ago, when BioFlora needed a licensed broker to buy fish
products in Ensenada. Tirado's family background in the fishing
industry and his language skills make him unique in the business,
Blotsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a passion for stewardship. Most people wouldn't
monkey with that kind of material,'' he said of Tirado.
</P>
<P>
   BioFlora also has started buying another Marlindo product _ crab
meal, made from the shells discarded by crab processing plants. The
meal will go into organic fertilizers, but Tirado thinks it also
has possibilities among health-food manufacturers who believe the
chitin in the shells absorbs fat and carries it out of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Tirado and Blotsky also have gone into partnership in a venture
to dry shrimp heads into an intense smelling, high-protein meal to
be used in feed and fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   From his family's years in the Guaymas shrimp business, Tirado
knew sailors were selling the shrimp tails but throwing away
thousands of tons of heads a year. Getting the product is a
challenge, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel it's not worth the time to save them and bring them
to port,'' he said. The next move may be hiring a boat to ferry the
product from ship to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Large commodity companies are starting to get involved in fish
byproducts, but Tirado says his small firm has a couple of
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest, he says, is that he knows every processing
plant manager in Guaymas so well that he can walk in without an
appointment. Also in his favor is the fact that large companies
aren't innovators willing to spend the time he does developing new
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Hispanic Chamber of Commerce in December gave
Marlindo its 1998 Hispanic Business Award for Innovation, citing
Tirado's unique products and constant font of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlindo name, which means ``pretty sea'' in Spanish, was
one of the brand names Tirado's father used in his shrimp business.
</P>
<P>
   The son's namesake grew slowly at first.
</P>
<P>
   Annual sales totaled a meager $11,000 eight years ago, topped
$70,000 four years ago, ``then all of a sudden took off,'' Tirado
said. Last year the five-employee company generated nearly $4
million in sales, the bulk of it from fish meal, and Tirado says $6
million is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   He attributes the rapid gain to customers finally getting
comfortable with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot had been buying tentatively, trying me out,'' he said.
``When they saw I could deliver when they wanted it and at the
quality, word started spreading around.''
</P>
<P>
   Tirado's long road to success did take a personal toll.
</P>
<P>
   When he quit Ralston Purina after various jobs in sales and
marketing, he started a company where he acted as the American
sales force for midsize Mexican companies with high-quality
products.
</P>
<P>
   He took on products ranging from shoes to flowers, leather goods
to glass chandeliers, things he knew little about. The two or three
tough years he expected stretched to 12. His wife divorced him,
friends and family thought he was crazy, and there were times he
doubted he'd have money to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had to keep on going,'' he said. ``I never wanted to be
subject to a steady income. I wanted to not have limits.'' &QL; 
Maybe now, Tirado says, they don't think he's crazy after all. &QL; 
Jane Larson can be reached at 444-8280 or jane.larson(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
