<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTREDAME-BIGTEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH STRUGGLING WITH BIG TEN DECISION
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie knows he has a reliable spiel when he
sits in living rooms across the nation with potential recruits and
their parents. He tells them about his program's national
television contract and how, through 111 years of winning football,
the Catholic university has been one of the few and certainly the
most famous independent team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Davie, along with the rest of the Notre Dame
community, will find out how much longer that might be true. The
university president, the Rev. Edward A. Malloy, will present a
recommendation to the Board of Trustees on whether or not Notre
Dame should seek an affiliation with the Big Ten Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win situation, though I'm glad I'm not making the
decision,'' Davie said. ``There is a concern about the unknown.
Would Notre Dame remain as unique as Notre Dame is, if it were
aligned with a conference? We're in an enviable position as an
independent.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to join Michigan, Ohio State and Penn State, as
well as eight Midwestern institutions, is as much about academics
and the fate of its less-famous sports teams, which are now
affiliated with the Big East, as it is about football. The Big Ten
has not invited Notre Dame to join, but the conference has engaged
in months of what its commissioner, Jim Delany, calls
``comprehensive information exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that they would be a great addition to our
conference,'' Delany said, acknowledging that the Big Ten had
previously approached the Fighting Irish. ``But that's far short of
offering an invitation or coming to a membership agreement. We have
some heavy lifting to do if they are interested in moving
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Notre Dame community appears split on the decision. Its
Faculty Senate has endorsed the alliance because it would allow
Notre Dame to share information and research materials with
conference schools, and the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But students appear less eager, as demonstrated by the chants of
``No Big Ten'' at basketball games as the Board of Trustees'
meeting draws near. Alumni are concerned that the university might
lose its identity as an independent Catholic university.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Notre Dame keeps its gate receipts from football, its
bowl payouts and the $7 million a year from its television contract
with NBC, a contract that will reap $8 million annually in the
years 2000 to 2005.
</P>
<P>
   If it joined the Big Ten, however, Notre Dame would have to
share its gate receipts, television revenue and other earnings with
member schools.
</P>
<P>
   This past bowl season, according to Delany, the conference
grossed about $25 million, with $19 million divided among 11
members.The other $6 million was shared by the five schools that
played in bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our revenues have grown from $18 million 10 years ago to over
$70 million today,'' said Delany, who expects to reach $100 million
in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's biggest concession would be giving up the
independent television contract that has helped spread its mystique
and has aided Davie's recruiting pitch. Instead, the team would be
included in the Big Ten contract with ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wadsworth, the Notre Dame athletic director, has said a
deal with the Big Ten would be a wash economically because of
factors like reduced travel time. The nearest rival for its teams
playing in the Big East Conference is more than 350 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Michael A. Tranghese, the Big East commissioner, said his office
has not been privy to Notre Dame's negotiations, but says his
conference would survive if the Fighting Irish defected. ``If they
think they should go, then they should go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Davie said talk of joining the Big Ten did not come up among
players in the recently concluded recruiting period, but it wasn't
far from his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to sit in a young man's home and sell them on the
uniqueness we have,'' he said. ``But I understand, it's just not a
football question.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
