<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BURRELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE OF JORDAN GOES WITH BURRELL
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The first question that John Calipari
posed to Scott Burrell on Wednesday had nothing to do with his jump
shot or his conditioning. It was about Michael Jordan. While
Burrell, the newly acquired small forward, warmed up for his first
practice with the New Jersey Nets, Calipari asked loudly and in
earshot of his entire team, ``How hard did Michael practice?''
</P>
<P>
   When Burrell began speaking reverently about how Jordan never
coasted through a workout and challenged teammates who did to
fistfights, Calipari perused the gymnasium and was pleased to find
his players listening intently.
</P>
<P>
   Experiences like that, lessons learned from playing for the
National Basketball Association champion Chicago Bulls last season,
are part of the reason the Nets signed Burrell to a one-year, $1
million contract Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that guys started huddling around him to hear about
how hard Michael Jordan practiced,'' Calipari said. ``It's nice to
have a guy who knows how hard they've worked and what they've done
there to get to where we're trying to go here.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Burrell can do more for the Nets than share inspiring
tales of Jordan and the Bulls. The 6-foot-7-inch small forward
known for his long-range shooting and chest-to-chest defense fills
one of the biggest voids on this young Nets squad: he is a true
small forward, not a shooting guard with strength or a power
forward with quickness.
</P>
<P>
   As has been Calipari's custom, he would prefer not to work
Burrell in slowly. Last year, he signed Sherman Douglas on the
first day of the season and played him 19 minutes that evening
against Indiana. With Kerry Kittles due to miss the first two weeks
of the season with a bruised right knee, Calipari would like to
move Kendall Gill to shooting guard and start Burrell at small
forward in Saturday's opener at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But Burrell is not ready. Afraid of injuring himself during the
lockout, he played little five-on-five and took part in a training
regimen that consisted mainly of shooting jumpers, riding a
stationary bike and working on a stairmaster. Ten pounds heavier
than his playing weight of 225 pounds and visibly worn down after
Wednesday's practice, Burrell estimated that he is playing at only
30 percent of his capacity. Calipari concurred and, and although he
said he was not disappointed, said he would not start Burrell on
Saturday. Instead, shooting guard Lucious Harris will take Kittles'
spot in the first five.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind I'm ready to start, but not physically,'' Burrell
said. ``If that's on their mind, tell them to hold up a little bit
longer. Out of my whole game, confidence and everything, I'm not
even close to halfway there. yet. But if I stay within myself, I
can definitely contribute right away. But I'm not going to try to
dunk on anyone because I know I can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rust will be evident early on, Burrell should become a
key contributor. His defense is his biggest strength, and with
Calipari emphasizing better play on that side of the court, he is
sure to get major minutes. And while he rarely got to showcase his
offensive skills as a Bulls reserve _ he averaged just 5.2 points
in 12 minutes a game last season _ Burrell is capable of putting up
points in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   As a starter for Charlotte in the 1995-1996 season, he averaged
a career-high 13.2 points before injuries cut his season to 20
games. And in Game 3 of last year's first-round Bulls sweep of the
Nets, he scored 23 points on 9 of 11 shooting, including 3 of 5
from 3-point range. One of the reasons Burrell chose the Nets over
Houston, Miami, Phoenix and Portland (which offered him $750,000
more than the Nets) was because he felt he would get more of an
opportunity to have nights like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've started before in this league and I know I can start
again,'' Burrell said.
</P>
<P>
   There are already rumblings that, when Kittles returns and
Burrell gets into shape, Gill, always the subject of trade rumors,
will be moved to the bench or traded. Calipari disputed that today,
saying that in a 50-game season, you can never have enough quality
players. But he did leave room for competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Scott is better? Obviously,'' Calipari said, referring to a
lineup change. ``But Kendall is absolutely secure in how he plays
and what he'll do for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Burrell showed Wednesday that he already thinks the way his new
teammates do. Joining the chorus of Nets players that has declared
the team an Eastern Conference contender, he said: ``New Jersey has
a great basketball team. I don't see why we can't be one of the two
or three best teams in the East this year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
