<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MCCARVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAVER TO REPLACE MCCARVER IN METS' TV BOOTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball history books do not readily show that during their
playing careers Tim McCarver ever knocked Tom Seaver out of a game.
But Wednesday Seaver knocked McCarver out of the Mets' broadcast
booth.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that Seaver said was long overdue, the Mets brought
back their Hall of Fame pitcher to serve in a variety of roles,
most visibly as one of their announcers for the 50 games this
coming season and the 40 games next year that will be televised by
WPIX-New York. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under a two-year contract, Seaver will also work for the Mets in
uniform, beginning with a 10-day period in spring training and
continuing throughout the season as an organization-wide pitching
guru.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be the general manager, the manager or the
pitching coach,'' Seaver cautioned during a conference call with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I wonder why it didn't happen five or six years ago.
I'm just glad we've been able to get me back and get me involved. I
feel I can help the organization in many aspects. I think I'm
capable of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   But in bringing back the greatest player in their 37-year
history, the Mets dumped perhaps the best television analyst they
have ever had. McCarver said only last week that he was prepared to
return for his 17th season with the Mets ``f I'm wanted,'' but he
found out Wednesday that he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to do your job from a journalistic standpoint,''
McCarver said, ``and I can walk away knowing that I exercised every
bit of my journalistic integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The news that Seaver was replacing McCarver instantly prompted
speculation that manager Bobby Valentine had a hand in the change.
McCarver is rarely shy about offering on-air opinions and has been
critical of Valentine at times. In turn, the manager hasn't been
fond of the comments. But the Mets denied any link.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a front-office decision,'' General Manager Steve Phillips
said. ``Bobby didn't do anything to push this one way or the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bingham, the club's senior vice president for marketing and
broadcasting, said: ``This didn't start as Tim. It started as Tom.
It started as a desire to bring Tom in. Tim was here for many, many
years. He had a long and very good career here. It was not a desire
to get Tim out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingham said the Mets considered having Seaver and McCarver work
together but decided both did their best work as analysts, not as
play-by-play broadcasters. He said the Mets hoped to keep Gary
Thorne and Ralph Kiner, the other two members of the over-the-air
crew.
</P>
<P>
   Seaver's path of return to Shea Stadium, where he has not been
since August 1992, began last summer when his agent, Matt Merola,
called Nelson Doubleday, the Mets' co-owner, and, according to
Seaver, asked, ``Why isn't Tom involved in your ball club one way
or another?''
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, Seaver said, talked to Phillips, and Phillips
contacted the former pitcher. (The Mets' acquisition of Mike Piazza
last season came about in the same way.) The broadcasting element
of his employment, Seaver said, ``came from both sides talking
about how to best utilize Tom Seaver working for the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   His dual role as club employee and broadcaster raised the
objectivity issue, but both Seaver and club officials asserted he
could comment and analyze with integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue we thought about and discussed,'' Bingham said.
``We addressed this issue with Tom. I think anyone who knows Tom
knows he's going to be honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver said he didn't want to be just a broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would find it somewhat hollow,'' he said, ``if I wasn't
allowed to use my expertise, what I know about pitching, in helping
this organization. I insisted that be part of the deal. It would be
silly not to have me do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his role in the organization will develop ``as we go
along, as we find out what is needed and what they feel I have to
offer. I don't think they know, and I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he felt he could help pitchers with ``the mental
part, the physical part, the mechanical part, all the nuances that
pitching is about. I feel I can help the whole spectrum of
pitchers, from the rookie coming into camp to the veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Seaver back is part of the Mets' attempt to correct an
oversight. They basically have ignored their past. Former Met
Mookie Wilson, one of their coaches, is a rarity in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we do need to connect more with our history,'' Bingham
said. ``We wanted to reconnect with Tom. He's an icon of our
club.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
