</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-AARON-BIRTHDAY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President to honor Aaron, his feat
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's hard to imagine now how little that Hank Aaron
liked to talk or think about The Record in the years after he
surpassed Babe Ruth as baseball's home-run king.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had 755 reasons to feel he was on top of the world, he
often just wanted to get away from the world and the racial hatred
that marred his climb to break Ruth's career mark of 714 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things went on back then you want to erase,'' Aaron
said. ``That's one of the reasons I don't talk about it as much as
I should. But it's over with, done with. Now maybe some good things
can come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, Aaron is ready to embrace that time,
place and accomplishment and the sport that allowed him to achieve
it. And the feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a 65th birthday gala on Friday night in Atlanta,
Major League Baseball will pay tribute to Aaron this season and to
the 25th anniversary of the year he broke Ruth's career record.
Friday's expected guests at the Hyatt Regency Hotel include
President Clinton, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Gov. Roy Barnes, former
Gov. Zell Miller, Mayor Bill Campbell, former Mayor and U.N.
Ambassador Andrew Young, Larry King, Bob Costas, Frank Robinson,
Ernie Banks, Al Downing, Sammy Sosa and baseball commissioner Bud
Selig.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably going to be the happiest moment of my life,''
Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, it will help make up for what should have been one of
the happiest times of his life, when he hit his 715th home run off
Downing on April 8, 1974.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of nearly 54,000 in Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium and
countless fans watching on TV saw the two fans jog alongside Aaron
on his home-run trot, the embrace between Aaron and his mother at
home plate and the joy of his Braves teammates. But what they
couldn't see was Aaron's overwhelming sense of relief and the
lingering pain, pounded into his memory by a barrage of racially
charged hate mail and threats.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Billye, knew it well. She knew that her husband felt
the rejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to be the ultimate in their field,'' Billye
Aaron said, ``and once you get it, it's downgraded, no longer
important, based on reaction and remarks from a society that wasn't
ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron watched Pete Rose break Ty Cobb's hit record in 1985. Last
season, he followed Mark McGwire's and Sammy Sosa's chase of Roger
Maris. He watched how much they enjoyed what they were going
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just the opposite of what I had gone through when I was
chasing the record,'' Aaron said. ``That's the reason I'm looking
forward to (the tribute this season). When you think what might
have been, what could have been, if things had been a lot different
25 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said it was 10 years before he could begin to put it in
proper perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the longer it stayed, the more people started saying,
'Hey, that's something to be reckoned with,' `` Aaron said. ``The
record was talked about more. And it was talked about not
negatively, (but) more in terms of saying, 'You know, I never was
given my just (reward).'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I guess people say it's time for us to realize that this
was something very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron concedes that, at the time he broke the record, he had a
hard time grasping how and what it meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had an agenda,'' Aaron said. ``I always had something
I wanted to try to do. In baseball, I always wanted to do the very
best I could do, regardless of whether I was playing with a team
that was on top or whether we were on the bottom. I always thought
my job was to be the very best I could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's goals now center on numbers like 1 million. That's the
number of dollars he hopes to raise for the Hank Aaron Chasing the
Dream Foundation at his birthday gala Friday night. Since he and
his wife established the foundation in 1994, the Aarons have raised
nearly $500,000. Aaron hopes to quadruple it when he travels to 20
ballparks and the All-Star Game this summer to be honored.
</P>
<P>
   By April, 44 children will have benefited from Aaron foundation
awards. He'd like to get that number up to 755.
</P>
<P>
   His also remains a strong voice for minorities in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, Aaron was pegged as quiet and withdrawn,
but as he got older he became more outspoken. He's been that way
since, never shying away from voicing his opinion on baseball's
problems through his years in the Braves front office and now in
his position on the board of directors of TBS and the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've made some progress, but we were so far behind,''
Aaron said. ``Is there ever going to be (a minority) that owns a
franchise? When you talk about minority participation, does each
team have minority doctors? Do we go to black banks? Does baseball
itself address the issue of minority participation as far as Little
League? Does baseball address the fact that we have an economic
crunch in this country that has certainly hurt minorities? Do black
kids come out to baseball games?''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said he's tried to put his own racial hardships behind
him. He said his bitterness is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd asked me (if I felt bitterness) three years after I
had retired from baseball, I would have said yes,'' Aaron said.
``(But now) I don't have any. That's all history.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his own place in history, there are a few more numbers
Aaron would like to be remembered for, in addition to 715, 755 and
44, his jersey number: They are 2,297, his RBI total, first
all-time; 3,771, his career hit total, third all-time behind Rose
and Cobb; and 2,174 runs scored, tied for second with Ruth behind
Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be remembered as someone who was not only able to
hit home runs but was able to do all of the things that (earned)
the label 'superstar,''' Aaron said. ``I ran the bases, stole
bases, hit home runs, all these things that are necessary _ rather
than, 'Ol' Hank hit 755 home runs, and that was it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he and his wife Billye welcome the home-run
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lived through so many trying times,'' Billye Aaron
said. ``We fortunately didn't let it get us down. We're happy Henry
is finally getting the respect for his accomplishments. ... I'm
very thankful he's lived long enough to be recognized for some of
his accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
