<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Change comes easy for Blaylock
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mookie Blaylock has always been able to change for the
better _ in his personal life, in his ability to deal with people
in a public forum, in his offseason training regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a little older, you've got to change,'' Blaylock said
Wednesday. ``Let's face it _ I'm not a young guy anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the only Hawks player to precede coach Lenny Wilkens to
Atlanta _ by one year _ Blaylock turns 32 on March 20. His body
feels it, and his brain tells him he must deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   If anything makes Blaylock think young, it's his teammates _
more good ones, he says, than he has ever seen under one roof in a
Hawks uniform. They will allow him to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play a different game now with these guys,'' Blaylock
said, glancing at a dozen players shooting free throws. ``It's
probably the best team I've ever played with in the NBA, and that's
including the team we had with Dominique (Wilkins) and (Kevin)
Willis, Lenny's first year.''
</P>
<P>
   That team equaled the franchise record for victories, 57, but
went out in the second round of the playoffs. That's as far as
Lenny Wilkens' teams have gone in five years here _ three of them
winning a round, the others crashing in four games or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to question us until we get past that,''
Blaylock said. ``I can say we're a better team, and we might be a
better team, but we've got to win in the playoffs to make people
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Blaylock believes it and because old point guard Wilkens
has a profound impact on the way Blaylock approaches the game, this
aging dog plans to come back with new tricks this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done being a scorer. We don't need me to score (a lot)
anymore. With the talent we have on this team now, with LaPhonso
(Ellis) and Grant (Long) on our front line and with the young guys,
I can be a true point guard, play my usual defensive game,'' said
Blaylock, three-time defending steals champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then (I can) look for guys when we have the ball. I can
distribute the shots; I don't have to take 'em. And I can play hard
because I know I got a legitimate guy (Anthony Johnson) behind me
for the first time since I came here. ``
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the Hawks have come out of training camp thinking
run, run, run. Each year, they've allowed their offense to grind
down into a half-court game. The same thing happened last season
after they started 11-0.
</P>
<P>
   But the way they have worked in training camp this time, they
have reason to believe they won't revert.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team likes to practice hard, and I believe it will want
to play hard,'' Blaylock said. ``It's a lot more fun when you're
getting up and down the floor, instead of standing around. A couple
years ago, (Steve Smith) and I were saying we played better when we
played (an up-tempo) Western Conference style _ heck, we beat all
the Western teams _ and we want to get back to that, because we've
got the depth to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
