</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crowd control plagues Phoenix Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For years the Phoenix Open has boasted of its giant
crowds, challenging other PGA Tour events to jam 125,000 people per
day through their turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a downside. Create an Animal House atmosphere, and
you can expect a few Blutos to slip through security.
</P>
<P>
   A scary one appeared Sunday at the TPC at Scottsdale. A
spectator identified as Brian K. Murphy of Phoenix, heckling Tiger
Woods, was wrestled to the ground after bragging that he also
carried a gun in his fanny pack. Woods, once robbed and mugged at
knifepoint in college, was unaware.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' he asked. ``I didn't know it was that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the Phoenix Open has revealed its
rowdiness. Beer sales were cut off this year at the par-3 16th,
where some 60,000 went wacko in 1997 after Woods' ace there. So
much booze filled the area that John Daly, the recovering
alcoholic, said he could smell it from the teebox.
</P>
<P>
   When you hear about things like that at a golf tournament, you
realize that BellSouth Classic officials might be wise in limiting
crowds to 45,000 or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely some crazy people out there,'' Payne
Stewart said. ``And there is a black-and-white issue out there.
It's sad, but it's the way it is. As I understand it, Tiger has had
some death threats before, which is why he has so many security
guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the incident this week while preparing at Pebble
Beach, David Duval said, ``It wouldn't necessarily make me remove
(Phoenix) from my schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara cautioned against overreactions. ``I don't think
that there's any need to be overly concerned with the types of fans
that are coming to golf tournaments,'' O'Meara said. ``I still
think it's pretty (high) quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Feds not faked out
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents culminated a two-year investigation Monday by
arresting six golf-club distributors _ two in Atlanta, two in
Savannah and two in Houston _ and four manufacturers who were
illegally selling millions of dollars in counterfeit golf
equipment. Those arrested in Georgia were identified as Albert and
Angie Chung in Atlanta and Mike Cohen and Rob Isola in Savannah.
The PGA Merchandise Show, which concluded Monday in Orlando,
featured 1,401 companies and 603,000 square feet of exhibit space _
an increase of 10 percent over 1998. With industry profits down,
companies are pushing to spread their word. Taylor Made, for
example, brought 110 salespeople to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling a rock
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Open's other bizarre situation involved the
1,000-pound boulder Woods was allowed to have moved by about a
dozen men under the ``loose impediment'' rule. Nick Faldo joked
that he was putting his caddie, Fanny Sunneson, ``on a new steroids
program. ... I think that was stretching the loose impediment rule
a little bit.'' O'Meara said, ``You can't blame Tiger; you can't
blame the rules. You have to look at the (USGA) people who make the
rules.'' ... Tom Lehman, who is recovering from shoulder surgery
and should be playing in about a month, is also working on his
back. He signed a deal with the Select Comfort Corp., which makes
high-tech air beds. ... As things stand now with golf's
much-maligned Official World Golf Rankings, Faldo, No. 64, would
play No. 1 Woods in a first-round match in the $5 million Andersen
Consulting World Match play Feb. 22-28 at LaCosta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
