<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Richardson claims top prize in Wal-Mart
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde and Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Joel Richardson failed to land a big bass early in the
morning during the final round of the Wal-Mart FLW Tour bass
tournament last weekend on Lake Okeechobee, Fla., and it took him
the rest of the day to get over it. But he did.
</P>
<P>
   The Kernersville, N.C., angler kept his mind on the task at hand
enough to win the $100,000 first prize, beating second-place Curt
Lytle of Suffolk, Va., by only 9 ounces. Richardson caught five
fish weighing 17 pounds, 12 ounces on the final day to win the
first of seven events on the 1999 tour.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who qualified for the Wal-Mart FLW Tour Championship
this summer as well as for the Ranger Millennium Tournament next
fall, qualified for the semifinal round of 10 with a weight of 30-8
the first two days, and for the final round of five with a 20-1 on
the third day.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's top finishers were Mickey Bruce of Buford, who was
15th with a two-day total of 28-1, and Mark Hardin of Canton, who
was 16th with a 27-9 total. Bruce won $5,000; Hardin took home
$4,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Wal-Mart FLW Tour hosts its third tournament of the season
on Lake Lanier March 17-20. The second event will be Feb. 24-27 on
Lake Murray near Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Two for the show
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Wildlife Federation Fisharama and Duckarama and Bass
Madness will help make metro Atlanta a mecca for outdoors
enthusiasts through the weekend. The Fisharama, at 16 years old the
oldest fishing trade show of its kind in the state, combines with
the Duckarama and runs Friday-Sunday at the Atlanta Expo Center, on
Jonesboro Road, just inside I-285, Exit 40. More than 40,000 are
expected to attend. Cost is $6 for adults and $3 for seniors and
children 6-12. For information, call 770-929-3350. Bass Madness,
Bass Pro Shop's annual spring promotion _ take I-85 north to Steve
Reynolds Boulevard _ will have hourlong seminars throughout the day
today through Sunday, featuring some of fishing's brightest stars
like Denny Brauer, David Fritts, Jimmy Houston, Mark Davis and Shaw
Grigsby. Admission is free. For more information, call 770-931-1550
or visit the Web site (http://www.outdoorworld.com).
</P>
<P>
   On the tube
</P>
<P>
   LeRoy Powell and Robin Russell will go hunting for trophy buck
in Muscogee and Burke counties on Saturday's Georgia Outdoors show,
GPTV, 9:30 a.m. and 6 p.m. ... This week's episode of ``The Reel
Guys'' television show will feature largemouth bass and bream fly
fishing from float tubes in the small lakes at Callaway Gardens.
The show was taped last April with hosts Ken Ford and Tommy Nelms.
The show airs today on ESPN2 at 6:30 a.m. and 6 p.m. and Sunday at
6:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Open house
</P>
<P>
   The Charlie Elliott Wildlife Center near Mansfield will host a
volunteer open house, 1-3 p.m. Saturday. For information, call
770-784-3059.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
