<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING THE GOOD GERM WARFARE FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists at Wilkes University in Wilkes-Barre, Pa., have
concluded _ after research that must have been fun _ that having
sex can reduce one's risk of catching cold.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``The Effect of Sexual Behavior on Immune System
Function,'' which will be presented at a psychologists convention
in April, ``Individuals engaging in sexual activity once or twice a
week have substantially higher levels of the antibody
Immunoglobulin A than individuals reporting no sexual activity or
less than one occurrence a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the maximum benefit was reaped from
sex once or twice a week; levels of the antibody were lower in
people who went at it more often. Psychologist Francis Brennan also
said there was no link between the antibody and either ``length of
relationship or sexual satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The man's got amazing powers of recovery.  &UR; Alice Barnes &LR; 
forwards a Denver Post review of  &UR; Mick Jagger &LR; 's performance on
Tuesday night, describing him as ``at the top of his game'' as he
``pranced, danced and strutted. ... Jagger showed no sign of being
slowed by his recent bout with the flu, which forced the
cancellation of two shows in San Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OF RHYME AND REASON AND POETIC LICENSE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gordon Burns &LR; , a student of modern events and of poetry,
forwards a poem by the British wit  &UR; Hilaire Belloc &LR; , ``Franklin
Hyde Who Caroused in the Dirt and Was Corrected By His Uncle.'' If
you're wondering what this has to do with anything, substitute
``Henry'' for ``Franklin,'' as we have done in this quoted verse:
</P>
<P>
   ``From  &UR; Henry Hyde &LR; 's adventure, learn /To pass your Leisure
Time/ In Cleanly Merriment, and turn/ From Mud and Ooze and Slime/
And every form of Nastiness ...''
</P>
<P>
   _ Opening boxes of donations in preparation for this month's
silent auction at the Friends' Library Store,  &UR; Rod Lowe  &LR; came upon
two books nestled together as their authors largely weren't: ``The
Earth-Owl and Other Moon People'' by  &UR; Ted Hughes  &LR; and ``Ariel'' by
 &UR; Sylvia Plath. &LR;  The volumes will be sold together.
</P>
<P>
   _ And keeping in mind  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR; 's ``thing with the cup,''
 &UR; Kerry McDermott &LR;  quotes the mystic Persian poet  &UR; Rumi &LR; : ``Agnostic
says little but inside he is full of mysteries, and crowded with
voices. Whoever is served that cup keeps quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore,  &UR; Bob Wieder  &LR; says his Sunday Bible study suddenly
became exciting when he got to that part about ``my cup runneth
over.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr.  &UR; Fay Boozman &LR; , an ophthalmologist, has been appointed
director of the Arkansas State Department of Health. Boozman, an
anti-abortion activist who lost in a bid for the Senate last fall,
said during the campaign that women don't become pregnant as a
result of rape because fear releases a hormone that prevents
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   _ A string of pearls that  &UR; Marilyn Monroe &LR;  received from
 &UR; Emperor &LR; 
 &UR; Hirohito &LR;  when she was honeymooning with  &UR; Joe DiMaggio  &LR; in Japan
wound up in the possession of  &UR; Susan Strasberg &LR; , who died recently
at 60. The link between Monroe and Strasberg was the Actor's
Studio, which was run by Strasberg's parents and was where Monroe
studied.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before her death, Strasberg had sold the necklace back
to Mikimoto, the pearl company that (along with the oysters) had
made it. A check from that company for $110,000 was supposed to be
handed over to Strasberg on the day she died, January 21. It went
to her lawyer instead, says New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Post says that  &UR; Katie Couric  &LR; is worried about
glowing reviews and high ratings for  &UR; Diane Sawyer  &LR; on ``Good
Morning America,'' especially since some praise for Sawyer has been
at the expense of ``Today.'' ``They've become awfully
self-congratulatory over there,'' the Washington Post's  &UR; Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Shales &LR;  wrote of the ``Today'' crew, ``and every day they seem to
be celebrating their success rather than doing a show.''
</P>
<P>
   During a chat on Monday's show with TV's Judge  &UR; Judy &LR; 
 &UR; Sheindlin &LR; , who has a new self-help book out, Couric admitted that
low self-esteem resulted in her tendency to try to seem nice by
suppressing aggressive aspects of her personality.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``All professions look bad in the movies. Lawyers are all
unscrupulous and doctors are all uncaring. Psychiatrists are all
crazy and politicians are all corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Creighton, defending himself against charges, at last
week's meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science, that ``Jurassic Park'' had made scientists look bad.
</P>
