<P>
   (NYT27) BOSTON -- Feb. 3, 1999 -- FIDELITY-LYNCH-BOS, 2-03 --
Peter Lynch in his office in December. In 13 years as skipper of
Fidelity's Magellan fund, Lynch racked up singularly spectacular
returns and earned a place among the capitalist gods. Now Fidelity,
the nation's largest fund firm, wants that Midas touch again, this
time to lure back fickle investors. (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) MIAMI -- Feb. 3, 1999 -- NONBANKS-BANKS, 2-03 -- Philip
Caso, vice president and senior financial consultant for Merrill
Lynch, left, talks with Aviv Tzur, the chief financial officer for
Professional Modification Services Inc. at the latter's offices at
Miami International Airport. Merrill Lynch, the country's largest
brokerage house, as well as American Express and Boston Financial
Network, an Internet upstart, are just a few of the nonbanks that
see themselves as the business bankers of the future. (Susan
Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) GAZA CITY, Gaza -- Feb. 3, 1999 -- ARAFAT-1, 2-03 --
Suha Arafat helps her daughter Zahwa to read a book at their home
