<HEADER>
A0941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      02-03 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GM SALES WEAKER THAN THOSE OF RIVALS
</P>
<P>
   As many of its competitors reported double-digit sales
increases, General Motors said its sales rose a scant 4 percent in
January compared with exceptionally weak sales in the month a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   GM's car sales rose 11.4 percent, largely on gains from its
newer midsized cars. However, the auto maker's truck sales dropped
3.7 percent. GM continues to be plagued by inventory shortages,
particularly of its new full-size Chevrolet Silverado and GMC
Sierra pickup trucks, in the aftermath of last summer's two-month
strike, which shut down almost all of its North American assembly
plants.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM URGED FOR MEXICAN UTILITIES
</P>
<P>
   Warning his compatriots that Mexico's energy needs are fast
overwhelming its state-run power plants, President Ernesto Zedillo
urged the nation's Congress to approve an extensive reorganization
of the country's electric power industry, opening it to private
investment. Zedillo proposed two constitutional reforms that would
reverse Mexico's 1960 nationalization of the industry and allow
private companies to invest in the leasing and construction of
power plants and regional transmission lines.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T PRESSED TO OPEN ITS SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   As AT&AMP;T aggressively enters the cable business, with plans to
offer high-speed Internet connections, a growing group of rivals
and consumer groups has begun a nationwide lobbying effort to force
the telephone giant to open its system to Internet competitors.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY SHARES LIFT MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Paced by renewed vigor in technology companies, stock prices
marched higher as Federal Reserve policy-makers left interest rates
unchanged. The Dow industrials rose 92.69 points, or 1 percent, to
9,366.81. Nasdaq rose even more, 29.99 points, or 1.22 percent, to
2,493.41, while the S&AMP;P 500 edged up 10.08 points, or eight-tenths
of 1 percent, to 1,272.07.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN PREPARES OFFERING IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   Because China has lost much of its luster for investors, rivals
of Goldman, Sachs are watching with keen interest _ and no little
relish _ as the investment firm prepares to sell shares in a
Chinese power company.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE DEAL PART OF ACQUISITION SPREE
</P>
<P>
   Few in Japan expect Goodyear Tire and Rubber Co.'s deal for
control of most operations of Sumitomo Rubber Industries to herald
a new flood of foreign takeovers, but the agreement comes as Japan
undergoes a surge of mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   TIME WARNER BEATS ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Financial improvements in the publishing, cable network,
entertainment and music divisions of Time Warner helped the media
giant report a less-than-expected loss of 17 cents a share in the
fourth quarter. Wall Street had forecast a loss of 19 cents a
share. The company's stock rose $2.8125, to $64.0625 a share.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVE CHANGES AT TBWA
</P>
<P>
   TBWA/Chiat/Day named a new top administrator and a new creative
director for its New York office. The moves are aimed at halting
the culture clashes between executives since the merger of the New
York operations of TBWA Advertising with Chiat/Day in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET'S SCATTERSHOT APPROACH
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's proposed budget sprinkles new spending
across a huge array of programs, hardly missing a constituency or
congressional district. Rather than concentrating the scarce money
and doing a few things well, the administration has chosen instead
to do dozens of things on a small scale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
