<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0942 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELUSIVE-SHERIFF-HNS &LR;      02-03 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELUSIVE-SHERIFF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH SHERIFF KEEPS PROFILE SO LOW HE'S INVISIBLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ On Monday, Tarrant County Sheriff David
Williams was not taking calls.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he on Tuesday, Wednesday or any of the other days of the
week. His receptionist said he had ``stepped out.'' His parking
space behind the county's Criminal Justice Center sat empty and the
sheriff was not to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being cause for alarm, however, Williams' absence is
taken in stride by officials in Fort Worth and Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   None of them have had more than a moment's contact with the
sheriff in more than six months and none expect much more in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't imagine I'll be hearing from him,'' said Fort Worth
Police Chief Thomas Windham. The chief, who was unable to reach the
sheriff to discuss jail booking procedures in November, finally
resorted to making a plea on television for Williams to call him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard from him yet,'' Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does anyone seem to have a clear answer to the question of
why the sheriff of the state's fourth-largest county would become
one of Texas' most elusive public officials.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past year Williams, a 45-year-old born-again
Christian and second-term Republican sheriff, has retreated from
contact with most of the public, other elected officials and the
news media. He has become so regularly absent from the courthouse
that brief sightings of him are cause for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' reclusion and reluctance to return phone calls,
however, are only the latest in a string of irregularities in his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in 1992 Williams has:
</P>
<P>
   _ Attempted to buy an entire fleet of Chevrolet Tahoes, sport
utility vehicles that sell for $29,000 each, while two new trucks,
an automobile and five patrol cars gathered dust in a county
garage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Designed a logo for his patrol cars that omitted the words
``Tarrant County.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Approved a countywide raid of topless bars and adult
bookstores, all of which proved to have valid permits and a number
of whose owners have since sued the county.
</P>
<P>
   _ Filed a $65 million budget, increasing his predecessor's
budget by $33 million and sparking a standoff with county
commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   _ Demanded ``sovereignty'' from commissioners' authority under
the 1836 law of the Republic of Texas and claimed common law powers
as the political descendant of the old English ``shire reeve.''
</P>
<P>
   From the first, however, Williams was an uncommon sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   He had never been a political figure. Instead, he had been a
small-town policeman in his native Oklahoma, a drug-enforcement
officer in a suburb of Fort Worth and a worker in the mail room at
evangelist Kenneth Copeland's ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, however, the sheriff at the time was indicted in
connection with several alleged misdeeds. Ed Max, a self-made
millionaire who owns a string of auto parts stores in North Texas
and whose father had been a U.S. marshal, decided to back a reform
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   That candidate turned out to be Williams, whose earnest demeanor
appealed to Max. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I sank a lot of money into it and I made him sheriff,'' Max
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Max put $44,000 into Williams' campaign. Rumors abound
that Max paid for Williams' car and living expenses while the
then-unemployed Williams campaigned. Max's only comment: ``What I
give somebody is my business.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams attended a two-day school for candidates that was run
by the Texas Christian Coalition and ran on a platform promising
not to hire homosexual deputies and to oppose abortion, though his
office has little to do with the latter.
</P>
<P>
   And, during the campaign, he was a reluctant speaker at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a painfully shy man and every time he made a mistake,
they beat him up over it,'' said Max. ``He just got to where he
didn't want to make an appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with Max's money and support from Copeland and the
Christian right, Williams was elected. He made Max his confidant
and gave him a sheriff's badge, a commission as a reserve deputy, a
portable sheriff's radio, shotgun and bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   He also stepped into his new position with some obvious ideas
for change. One of his first acts was to revise the logo for the
patrol cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have spent 50 or 60 hours working on that himself,''
Max said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the revision failed to include the words
``Tarrant County,'' and was ultimately rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Though previous sheriffs had dressed in business suits, and wore
uniforms only for specific functions, Williams preferred a uniform
and he came up with a new design for his own. It included an
additional number of gold stars.
</P>
<P>
   He sought little advice. His round-table included a small circle
of sheriff's officers, contacts in the Christian Coalition and
County Commissioner J.D. Johnson, the court liaison to the sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' penchant for privacy included dealings with his
subordinates. It manifested itself in a reluctance to make eye
contact with ranking officers in the department and a habit of
entering his offices through the back door to avoid seeing anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Former sheriff's Capt. Pat Howell said he mentioned to Max that
Williams' refusal to speak with his administrators was causing low
morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just looked at me and I knew I'd made a mistake,'' Howell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams then began entering the building through a back
stairwell. Next, he had an elevator programmed so it could be set
to go from the ground floor to his office without stopping on other
floors.
</P>
<P>
   His administrative meetings began with a lengthy prayer, then,
inexplicably, the sheriff would often show old war movies, several
of them featuring scenes of cavalry skirmishes in the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't sure what the purpose was,'' Howell said.
</P>
<P>
   He brought in various speakers, including Craig Roberts, author
of a number of books on Kennedy assassination conspiracy theories
and on police snipers, again without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of interesting, but we couldn't figure out what it
had to do with the sheriff's office in Tarrant County,'' said a
former deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there were the sheriff's helicopters. Williams secured two
military-surplus Bell Ranger helicopters for his drug task force,
making the Tarrant County Sheriff's Department the only such office
in the state with aerial capability.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, one of those aircraft crashed at an airstrip on
the Kenneth Copeland Ministry grounds, killing two deputies and
adding fuel to already spreading rumors that the aircraft were
being used to film commercials for Copeland.
</P>
<P>
   Williams did not arrive at the scene of the crash for more than
four hours, then didn't explain his delay, prompting even more bad
feelings within the department.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there were Williams' ties to the Christian right and his
belief in conversion. Former deputies cite an instance in which he
brought 600 lay ministers into the jail to proselytize to
prisoners, causing massive security problems. He created a special
office for jail chaplain, with its own budget, further angering
commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   When he felt beleaguered by commissioners, Williams sent letters
to area churches, beginning with the greeting, ``True Believers,''
and summoning them to rally behind him.
</P>
<P>
   He created a Christian education unit, nicknamed the ``God
Pod,'' an area of the jail reserved for prisoners who have joined a
Christian group. That prompted a lawsuit by two non-Christian
prisoners. An appeals court recently ruled the case should go to
trial. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; At the same time, Williams' disagreements with county
commissioners were roiling. His $65 million budget proposal was cut
to $52 million and Williams responded by suing the commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Williams cut staffing at the jail, blaming his smaller budget
and creating long delays at the booking desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began keeping a log of the hours officers spent sitting
around, waiting to book in a prisoner,'' said Fort Worth Police
Chief Windham. ``One weekend it would be 33 hours. The next it was
55 hours, and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   Windham finally made his televised plea in November, asking that
Williams discuss the delays with him, but he got no response.
</P>
<P>
   And, as his relations with other departments deteriorated,
Williams began to withdraw. He was often absent from his main
office and said to be at a satellite jail office, behind locked
doors.
</P>
<P>
   He began skipping scheduled appointments at commissioners'
meetings. He stopped speaking with Commissioner Johnson, a former
supporter. He stopped holding administrative meetings and he
finally stopped speaking to Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard from him since July,'' Max said. ``He was at
my mother's funeral then and offered condolences. Other than that,
nothing. He doesn't return my calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, it seems does he return any others. Williams has repeatedly
refused to speak to Johnson and other commissioners as well as
representatives from the district attorney's office or a number of
his deputies.
</P>
<P>
   In kind, he did not answer requests for an interview from the
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it appears that Williams could well be sheriff again
after the 2000 election, even though he is already drawing
opponents. But Williams has name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``His name is in the news constantly, and he doesn't even have
to speak to anyone to get it there,'' Max said. ``It will take a
lot of money to beat him, and I don't know if anyone is willing to
spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, on the other hand, won't have Max's money behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who I'm going to support next time, if anybody,''
said the parts dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can tell you one thing. It won't be David Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
