<SLUG> BC-GREEK-ORTHODOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEK ORTHODOX BISHOPS SEEK OUSTER OF ARCHBISHOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The five presiding American bishops of the Greek Orthodox church
of America are calling for the ouster of Archbishop Spyridon, its
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying a level of public discord virtually unheard of in
religious denominations, the five clerics who head local dioceses
across the United States accuse Spyridon of plunging the Greek
Orthodox Church, which has 1.5 million members, into a crisis that
threatens to tear it apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Archdiocese is presently suffocating in an atmosphere of
fear, suspicion, insecurity, lack of trust and vindictiveness,''
states a report by the bishops submitted last month to Ecumenical
Patriarch Bartholomew, who appointed Spyridon in 1996 and is the
spiritual leader of the world's 300 million Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of the clergy and laity have lost their trust in
their ecclesiastical leadership, which during the last two and a
half years has not been able to create and promote new visions and
new dreams for the future,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Mark Arey, a spokesman for Spyridon, said the
archdiocese did not have an official response to the report but
added that the issues raised by the prelates were being addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That report is no longer relevant,'' Arey said. ``The
archbishop and the metropolitans may not agree on everything but
they have agreed to work together, and that's what they're doing
even as we speak.'' In the Greek Orthodox Church bishops are
referred to as metropolitans.
</P>
<P>
   Last month in a showdown at the Phanar, the compound in Istanbul
that is home to Bartholomew, the patriarch rebuffed the five
bishops' repeated calls for Spyridon's removal. Bartholomew,
according to reports in the Greek press, expressed his confidence
in his embattled Spyridon.
</P>
<P>
   The report was first published in The National Herald, a Greek
language newspaper in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Almost since the day Spyridon arrived in New York to assume his
post, he has been consumed by the allegations of many in his flock
who say he he is an autocrat who does not work well with the clergy
or lay people in this country. The Greek Orthodox Church in the
United States is historically more independent-minded and
democratic than the mother church.
</P>
<P>
   His crtics say Spyridon, who was born in Ohio but spent more
than five decades in Europe, is out of touch with the American
church. Spyridon's conservative views about hierarchical authority,
for instance, are typical of many Orthodox churhes abroad, but have
led to clashes with Greek Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop's defenders say his detractors represent a small
number of disgruntled clergy and laity who are upset about having
lost power and influence after Spyridon arrived. Opposition to the
archbishop has continued to pick up momentum with at least one
major lay group calling for the creation of a separate Greek
Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Chicago, and Astoria, N.Y., a Greek enclave, bumper
stickers have started to appear with the Greek word ``Anaxios,''
which means unworthy. In Greek liturgical tradition, when a priest
is ordained it's customary for people in the pews to shout
``Axios,'' which means worthy.
</P>
<P>
   The report to Bartholomew also reveals that the five presiding
bishops disagreed with Spyridon's 1997 decision to fire the
president and three professors at the church's flagship
institution, Hellenic College and Holy Cross School of Theology in
Brookline, Mass. _ a move that launched the firestorm engulfing the
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general state of affairs and the atmosphere in the
archdiocese have created such a spirit of unbearableness and
disillusionment that especially our young people no longer feel
proud of their faith, the church and the archdiocese,'' the report
states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
