<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogs close fast to join elite
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's football recruiting closed with a flurry
Wednesday, as the Bulldogs landed two of the nation's top
wide-receiver prospects on college football's National Signing Day.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech, which defeated Georgia en route to a 10-2 record
last season, signed a group of 26 players, which ranks among the
nation's top 20 classes, according to at least one recruiting
service.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's recruiting class, which was ranked second in the
nation behind Texas according to the Prep Football Report, was
strengthened Wednesday by the addition of wide receivers Reggie
Brown of Carrollton, the Atlanta Journal-Constitution state player
of the year, and Durrell Robinson of Duncan, S.C. The pair capped
off Donnan's class of 25 players, which added highly regarded
running back Bruce Thornton of LaGrange and offensive lineman Kevin
Breedlove of Clemson, S.C., on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia was one of the fastest-closing classes in the
country,'' recruiting analyst Allen Wallace of California-based
SuperPrep Magazine said. ``I thought they'd get Brown, but I didn't
think they'd get Robinson and Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a Parade Magazine All-American, was one of the nation's
most coveted players, despite missing four games of his senior
season with a broken leg. Brown still finished with 62 catches for
1,146 yards and 11 touchdowns last year, leading Carrollton to the
Class AA state title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty close,'' Brown said. ``I just made my decision
(on Tuesday). I had it down to two teams _ Georgia and Ohio State.
It was just about my family being able to see me play.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace ranked Georgia Tech's class 16th nationally and second
in the ACC, behind FSU. The Yellow Jackets' class is highlighted by
defensive back Cory Collins of Egg Harbor Township, N.J.,
linebacker Recardo Wembush of Blakely, wideout Anthony Lawston of
Baltimore and running back William Glover of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Tech coach George O'Leary's group featured 12 defensive players
and recruits from seven states other than Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filled our needs with our first 16 verbal commitments,
which allowed us to go out and recruit the best available
athletes,'' O'Leary said. ``We haven't been able to do that before.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
