A0946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-RECRUIT-GIRL04-CO     02-03 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUIT-GIRL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Butler signs for Middle Georgia
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three-inch heels, a black miniskirt, earrings and a
white satin blouse aren't typical attire for an athlete signing a
college football scholarship. Then again, Riverdale High's Tonya
Butler isn't your typical signee.
</P>
<P>
   The female placekicker was one of six Riverdale players to sign
a national letter of intent Wednesday morning. Butler, headed to
Middle Georgia Junior College, is the first female to earn a
football scholarship at a state college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered if this day would ever come for me,'' Butler
said. ``I'm just so thankful that Middle Georgia gave me this
opportunity. And it was so surprising to have so many people here
to see all of us sign.''
</P>
<P>
   A large crowd at the Riverdale Media Center applauded as she
began to write her name on the official papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonya has become a celebrity,'' said Jane Bain, who teaches
English at Riverdale. ``She has broken down a lot of barriers for
girls. She is an inspiration to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler's parents, Chris and Polly Butler, and her younger
sister, Haley, watched proudly and posed for photographs with their
famous family member after the ceremony. Older brother Tony, a
rising junior linebacker at Georgia Southern, had college classes
and could not attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good thing for Sissie,'' said Haley, 6. ``Tonya
can score points next year. It's a good thing.'' Other than Butler,
no one was more emotional about the day than technology teacher
Steve Price. As football coach at Pointe South Middle School
several years ago, he encouraged Butler _ then a team manager _ to
try kicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Tonya was the real thing the first time we put her in a
game,'' Price said. ``It was to kick an extra point. Three players
from the other team drilled Tonya in an attempt to show her this
was a male-only sport. We thought Tonya was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she came off the field, she was mad as a hornet. Tonya
said the referee had said she could kick again. But a
(roughing-the-kicker penalty) had been called, and we had decided
instead to go for the two-point conversion.''
</P>
<P>
   At Riverdale, Butler was a three-year starter on the varsity.
This season, when the Raiders were 13-1 and appeared in the Class
AAA semifinals at the Georgia Dome, she converted 64 of 65
point-after attempts and seven of 12 field goals, with a long of 39
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-6, 125-pound Butler became so skilled that coaches
and teammates played down the gender difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought of Tonya as nothing else but an outstanding
kicker,'' Riverdale football coach George Spencer said. ``I was
excited to see her sign _ not because she's a girl, but because she
is another one of our players that has the chance to play in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   Said quarterback Andreco Hines: ``Tonya is the Ms. Michael
Jordan of college kickers.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle Georgia expected to sign 30 players for this year's
recruiting class by late Wednesday, but no other signee in the
program's history has generated as much interest as Butler. She
will be honored today as The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's Female
Athlete of the Year, as part of National Women in Sports Day. The
Cochran school has been in the national spotlight since Jan. 20,
when Butler committed in hopes of eventually moving on to a major
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got 12 kids that I coached and recruited that are now in
the NFL, and none of them ever received as much attention coming
out of high school as Tonya is getting,'' Middle Georgia coach
Randy Pippin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go anywhere without being asked about Tonya,'' Pippin
said. ``I got a call earlier this week from a lady in California
who had read articles about Tonya in the paper out there. This
lady's goal in life is to be a college football coach. She wanted
my advice on how to do it. I told the lady to work hard and, as a
result, good things will happen. It worked for Tonya.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
