<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-RECRUIT-GASOUTH04     02-03 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUIT-GASOUTH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rich returning talent means wait for signees
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Georgia Southern coach Paul Johnson, the most best
aspect of Wednesday's signings of future Eagles was that the 14
high school seniors signed for a future probably two or three years
away.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has won 24 games in the last two years, returns 13
starters and almost as many other veterans from the team that
advanced to the I-AA national championship game. As a result,
Georgia Southern does not have to look to 18-year-old freshmen for
immediate help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The group we signed came highly recommended, and we're excited
about it,'' Johnson said. ``But we won't be able to tell a lot
about it until a couple of years from now. I think we've got a
pretty good group here already.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the returning players who went 14-1, the Eagles
will have 11 players for 1999 who redshirted last season.
</P>
<P>
   Among the group signing letters of intent with Georgia Southern
were eight linemen, including North Cobb High standout Freddy
Pesqueira (6 feet 2, 240); Brian Young (6-2, 265) of Washington
County High; Colby Brown (6-4, 230) of Jesup; Travis Hames, a 6-4,
320-pounder from Madison, Fla.; and Taylor Wheelis (6-0, 245) from
Pelham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't signed very many linemen the past two years, so we
went a little heavy that way,'' Johnson said. ``Some of those guys
played both ways (in high school).''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern's most glaring weakness in 1998 was at
linebacker. The Eagles had so many injuries that freshman Michael
Youngblood of Waynesboro was forced to pass on a redshirt year. The
top linebacker prospect among Wednesday's signees was Parkview High
star Justin Godsey (6-1, 218).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got all of those (linebackers from last year's team)
back. Right now, I don't know whether that's good or bad,'' Johnson
said, laughing. ``But it's going to help to get Daryl Morrell back.
He's a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrell, a 5-9, 185-pound sophomore who broke into the starting
lineup as a freshman in '97, sat out most of last season with a
neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   Because starter Greg Hill will be a senior next season, Johnson
expects to a sign another quarterback in addition to Teddie
Cummings (6-0, 180) of Lake Butler, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   None of his signees were fullbacks, however. Georgia Southern
has upcoming sophomore All-American Adrian Peterson, who rushed for
2,606 yards and 34 touchdowns and set or tied nine I-AA national
records. Former Chattahoochee High star Mike Ballisty (6-2, 212),
redshirted last season, is expected to compete for the backup spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed one kid (5-11, 185-pound Phillip Mouzou of
Clearwater, Fla.) who could probably play there if he had to,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   GA. SOUTHERN SIGNEES
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Boate, OL/DL, 6-2, 260, Jacksonville, Fla. (The Bolles
School).
</P>
<P>
   Colby Brown, DL, 6-4, 230, Jesup, Ga. (Wayne County HS).
</P>
<P>
   Charles Clarke, OT, 6-2, 262, Pace, Fla. (Pace HS).
</P>
<P>
   Teddie Cummings, QB, 6-0, 180, Lake Butler, Fla. (Union County
HS).
</P>
<P>
   Justin Godsey, LB, 6-1, 218, Lilburn, Ga. (Parkview HS).
</P>
<P>
   Travis Hames, OL, 6-4, 320, Madison, Fla. (Madison HS).
</P>
<P>
   Robert Locke, DE, 6-3, 230, Savannah, Ga. (Benedictine Military
School).
</P>
<P>
   Jesse McMillan, RB/DB, 6-3, 205, Kingsport, Tenn.
(Dobyns-Bennett HS).
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Mouzon, DB/RB, 5-11, 185, Clearwater, Fla. (Dunedin HS).
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Pesqueira, DE, 6-2, 240, Acworth, Ga. (North Cobb HS).
</P>
