<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Leary: `Our best class'
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech coaches, saying they have their best
football signing class in a decade or more, got what they wanted
and filled the holes they needed to fill.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, coach George O'Leary was able to get the
players he wanted early and then have the luxury of signing the
best available athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The 26 Yellow Jacket signees are two quarterbacks, four running
backs, three wide receivers, three offensive linemen, four
defensive linemen, three linebackers, five defensive backs and two
placekickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletically and academically, it's a top-10 class,'' O'Leary
said. ``Basically, our goal was to help out the defensive side of
the ball. I think we helped the defense, and we helped our kicking
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also recruited well on the offensive line to replace the
offensive linemen that will be graduating after next season,'' he
said. ``We've now got five quarterbacks on scholarship, and we
signed some great running backs. You can never have enough running
backs. The only area maybe we would have liked more help was at
tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I took over, this is the most quality players we've
signed,'' O'Leary said. ``Judging by the people we were recruiting
against, this is definitely our best class. It's also the most
we've signed from the state of Georgia in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Four of the top prospects are wide receiver Anthony Lawston of
Baltimore, linebacker Ricardo Wimbush of Blakely, defensive back
Cory Collins of Egg Harbor, N.J., and wide receiver/running back
William Glover of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a half-step behind them are defensive lineman Greg Gathers
of Reserve, La., quarterback Brian Camp of Dulbin, Ohio, and
offensive lineman Raymond Blake of Hinesville.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jermaine Hatch of Baton Rouge, La., might be the
sleeper of the group. Hatch, a 6-foot-2, 200-pounder, injured his
knee during his junior year, and many of the schools that were
recruiting him backed away. He turned down Miami, Arkansas and LSU
to go to Tech, and Tech coaches compare him to senior tailback
Charles Wiley.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 26 signees, 14 came from Georgia, four from Florida, two
each from Louisiana and South Carolina and one each from Maryland,
New Jersey, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   BIOS ON THE GEORGIA TECH SIGNEES
</P>
<P>
   John Bennett, OL, 6-5, 275, Etowah, Woodstock _ Chosen one of
the top 50 prep prospects in Georgia by the AJC. Excellent
strength, with a 400-pound bench press and 285-pound power clean.
Defensively, had 47 tackles, including two sacks and three caused
fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Blake, OL, 6-3, 270, Bradwell Institute, Walthourville _
Named honorable mention prep All-American by USA Today. One of the
top 50 prospects in Georgia by the AJC. Bench presses 475 pounds.
Named AAAA All-State honorable mention. Named the 3-AAAA lineman of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Ather Brown, LB, 6-3, 210, Jones County, Macon _ One of the top
50 prospects in Georgia according to the AJC. Earned honorable
mention All-State honors. Lettered four times in football, three in
basketball and three in track.
</P>
<P>
   Winfred Brown, CB, 5-9, 170, Harrison, Marietta _ Earned
all-county and all-metro honors. Has excellent speed with a 4.42
clocking in the 40-yard dash. This past season returned kickoffs 97
and 99 yards for touchdowns and made 58 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Camp, QB, 6-2, 220, Coffman, Dublin, Ohio _ Strong-armed
quarterback who also runs a 4.6 40. Named the Ohio prep player of
the year by both Gatorade and AP. Completed 89 of 156 passes for
1,400 yards, 12 touchdowns and five interceptions as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Cory Collins, DB, 6-0, 175, Egg Harbor, Egg Harbor Township,
N.J. _ Had 70 tackles and five interceptions and returned a kickoff
for a 97-yard touchdown. Also rushed for 1,080 yards and 16 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Ford, RB, 5-9, 195, Pepperell, Lindale _ Honorable
mention USA Today All-American. Powerful runner who had 2,595 yards
rushing and 33 touchdowns as a senior and 1,996 yards and 34 TDs as
a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Gathers, DE, 6-3, 255, East St. John's, LaPlace, La. _
Named an honorable mention all-American by USA Today. A two-time
all-state defensive lineman. Had 20 sacks as a senior, 42 career
sacks.
</P>
<P>
   William Glover, RB, 5-10, 185, Jesuit, Tampa _ As a senior, had
1,585 yards rushing with 20 touchdowns and 38 receptions for 520
yards and seven more touchdowns. Averaged 33 yards a kick return
and 16 yards per punt return. Totaled 3,865 career yards and 51 TDs
rushing, with 70 pass receptions and 1,245 yards and 10 TD catches.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Hall, QB, 6-3, 190, Cheraw, S.C. _ Ranked the No. 9
prospect in South Carolina by Superprep. Completed 46 of 96 passes
for 692 yards and six touchdowns and rushed 85 times for 499 yards
and eight TDs as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Jamey Hamilton, DL, 6-3, 245, McEachern, Powder Springs _ Ranked
the No. 65 prep prospect in Dixie by Superprep. Honorable-mention
all-state. Good speed with a 4.7 in the 40. Had 84 tackles and
eight sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Hartley, OL/DL, 6-5, 284, West Nassau, Bryceville, Fla. _
Ranked the No. 61 prospect in Dixie by Superprep and the No. 50
prospect in Florida. Excellent speed for size with a 4.95 40.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Hatch, RB, 6-2, 205, Catholic, Baton Rouge _ Named the
No. 25 prep prospect in Louisiana this year by Superprep. Rushed
for 954 yards and 15 touchdowns, caught 30 passes for 461 yards and
six TDs. Has 4.5 speed.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Johnson, LB, 6-1, 240, Troup County, LaGrange _ Excellent
run-stopper has 4.63 40. No. 71 prep prospect in Dixie by
Superprep. Named Top 50 prospect in Georgia by the AJC. First-team
all-state. Had 151 tackles, five sacks and 10 tackles for losses.
Has good strength.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kitchen, RB, 5-10, 190, Lebanon, Pa. _ A member of
Superprep All-America team. Ranked the No. 20 running back in the
nation by Superprep. Named to the Pennsylvania Super 30 List and
will play in the Ohio-Pennsylvania high school all-star game this
summer. Rushed for 1,410 yards on 225 carries and 14 touchdowns as
a senior in eight games. Had 112 career tackles and five
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lavette, DB, 5-10, 185, McEachern, Powder Springs _
All-region pick by Prep Stars. Helped lead McEachern to the state
AAAA championship game. Honorable mention all-state. Regarded as an
excellent cover corner. Son of Tech all-time leading rusher Robert
Lavette.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lawston, WR, 6-4, 215, Eastern Tech, Baltimore _ Also
could play tight end, linebacker or defensive back. Caught 49
passes for 819 yards and nine touchdowns last year. Intercepted six
passes, returning two for TDs. For his career, caught 156 passes
for 2,988 yards and 25 TDs and intercepted 19 passes.
</P>
<P>
   Luke Manget, K, 5-11, 180, Rockdale County, Conyers _ Named a
Parade prep All-America. Ranked No. 1 placekicker in Georgia by
several magazines. Hit 19-of-29 career FGs and 34-of-36 extra
points.
</P>
<P>
   Roderick Middleton, WR, 6-2, 182, Timberland, Bonneau, S.C. _
Rated the No. 21 prospect in South Carolina in Superprep. Excellent
receiver and defensive back. Cousin of Tech quarterback Joe
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Muyres, DB, 6-3, 195, Parkview, Stone Mountain _ Had two
interceptions, made 65 tackles and had 41 receptions for 683 yards
as a senior. Joins older brother Jon, who will be a junior wide
receiver for Tech. Oldest brother, Jeffrey, started the past two
years for Wake Forest as defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Newman, K/P, 6-1, 180, Walton, Marietta _ One of top
combination kickers in the Southeast. Averaged 44 yards a punt as a
senior with 14 punts over 50 yards and a long of 72 yards. Made
6-of-11 field goals, with three of more than 50 yards. Twenty-eight
of 35 kickoffs were for touchbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Reilly, DE, 6-4, 245, Marist School, Roswell _ Chosen one
of the top 50 prep prospects in Georgia by the AJC. Named
all-State. Had 10 sacks, five fumbles caused, five recovered
fumbles and two blocked kicks as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Rhino, RB/DB, 5-8, 175, Marist School, Smyrna _ Rushed
for 875 yards and caught passes for 150 more as a senior and rushed
for 851 yards with 200 yards of receptions as a junior. Has the
speed and quickness to be a threat on offense or defense.
</P>
<P>
   Selwyn Scott, CB, 5-10, 170, Leonard, Boynton Beach, Fla. _
Track star with 4.4 speed. The all-time leader in Florida for
kickoff return yardage, with five career touchdowns. As a senior,
had 43 tackles and five interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Recardo Wimbush, LB, 6-2, 215, Early County, Blakely _ Named to
AJC's Super Southern 100 and top 50 prospects in Georgia. Had
outstanding senior season with 155 tackles, three pass
interceptions, one fumble recovery and one sack.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wright, DE, 6-4, 250, Lehigh, Lehigh Acres, Fla. _ Has 4.7
speed. Made 58 tackles and two fumble recoveries with six sacks as
a senior.
</P>
