<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong finish for Bulldogs
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ While Georgia's 1999 recruiting effort may have
started slowly, it finished fast in what has become a typical
scenario under third-year coach Jim Donnan.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan went into the recruiting season with the express purpose
of finding some wide receivers to become quarterback Quincy
Carter's targets next season. He hit the bull's-eye in the form of
four top-notch pass catchers, including two consensus All-Americans
in Reggie Brown of Carrollton and Durell Robinson of Duncan, S.C.
Georgia also signed wideouts Michael Johnson of Tulsa, Okla., and
Damien Gary of Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Brown nor Robinson made their decisions public until
Wednesday, the first day of the national signing period. The
last-day suspense has become a hallmark of Donnan's recruiting
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens when you're recruiting guys who are making
a lot of national visits,'' Donnan said late Wednesday afternoon.
``When your going after that caliber of players, you don't get as
many early commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   Kannapolis, N.C., running back Nick Maddox was the coaching
staff's only question heading into signing day as they had not
heard from him since his apparent verbal commitment to Georgia last
week. Maddox, considered the No. 1 tailback in the South, signed
with Florida State on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox was one of two high-profile, big-time tailbacks that the
Bulldogs vigorously pursued, and both had the Bulldogs as one of
their final two choices. Cedric Cobbs of Little Rock, Ark., signed
with Arkansas on Wednesday. Still, Donnan insists even that need
went fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed DeJuan Green, who's the fastest guy in Florida. We
feel like he's got that home-run ability that not many do,'' Donnan
said. ``And Bruce Thornton was the highest priority (running back)
for us in the state. He has the ability to make big plays. We think
these guys give us instant help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs are expecting to get more help at running back in
the form of Kenny Bailey, a cousin of the three Bailey brothers who
have played for Bulldogs _ Ronald, Champ and Boss. But Georgia had
not received the signed paperwork on Bailey, a non-qualifier from
the 1998 class who has spent the last year at Hargrave Military
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs also addressed their needs on the offensive line,
in the defensive backfield, at tight end and on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Georgia signed 25 prospects to letters-of-intent on
Wednesday and that number could climb to 26 or 27. The Bulldogs
also will add three players from their 1998 signing class who are
already enrolled in school _ Terrence Edwards, Jamie Henderson and
Regan Torbert. How they will get them all on scholarship remains
unclear. The Bulldogs currently have 47 returning lettermen on the
roster and can carry a total of only 82 scholarships next season
because of NCAA sanctions for rules violations under former coach
Ray Goff. At least four of Wednesday's signees have not yet
qualified academically.
</P>
<P>
   BIOS ON GEORGIA'S SIGNEES
</P>
<P>
   Kendrell Bell, LB, 6-2, 240, Middle Georgia J.C., Augusta _ A
consensus junior-college All-American who finished with 132 tackles
and six sacks. ``Best junior-college player we saw anywhere,'' Jim
Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Billue, OL, 6-6, 300, Guntersville, Ala. _ First-team,
all-classification all-state and lineman of the year in Alabama and
Prepstar All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Brannon, TE, 6-4, 225, Independence, Charlotte _ This
SuperPrep All-American is quick and agile for his size. Also played
defensive back in school. Had 12 touchdowns and six interceptions
his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Breedlove, OL, 6-5, 295, Daniel, Clemson, S.C. _ All-USA
Today and Parade Magazine first-team All-American. National Honor
Society member.Potential first-year starter.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Brown, WR, 6-2, 185, Carrollton _ AJC Super 11 selection
and all-classification player of the year. Parade All-American. Had
62 catches for 1,046 yards and 10 TDs despite missing three games
with injuries. Led Carrollton to Class AA state title.
</P>
<P>
   Decory Bryant, DB, 5-11, 185, Lake Highland Prep, Orlando _
All-State cornerback who had 55 tackles, 10 pass break-ups and
seven interceptions as a senior. Averaged 32 yards on kickoffs and
scored 11 touchdowns as a wide receiver and running back.
</P>
<P>
   Dantra Clements, DB, 5-11, 175, DB, East Coweta, Sharpsburg _
Class AAAA All-State as all-purpose player and SuperPrep
All-American. As quarterback last two seasons, completed 101-of-214
of 2,246 yards and 25 TDs and rushed for 1,295 yards 19 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Kentrell Curry, DB, 6-3, 186, Stephens County, Toccoa _ USA
Today honorable mention. Had 63 tackles, two interceptions and ran
for 172 yards on 11 carries as a junior. Injured for part of senior
season but had 29 carries for 230 yards and six TDs and two
interceptions on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Faison, Ath., 5-11, 192, Toombs County, Lyons _ Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Class AA all-state at defensive back. Rushed
for more than 500 yards and 11 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Damien Gary, WR, 5-10, 160, Clarke Central, Athens _ Class AAAA
all-state in 1996 and 1997. Injury-filled high school career.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Grant, LB, FB, 6-4, 228, Miller County, Colquitt _
Non-qualifier from 1998 class who has yet to meet entrance
requirements. Tied Herschel Walker's high school record for TDs in
a single season with 45 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   DeJuan Green, RB, 6-0, 190, Raines, Jacksonville, Fla. _
SuperPrep preseason All-American who rushed for 1,818 yards and 22
TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hewitt, DL, 6-6, 250, Rome _ USA Today All-USA honorable
mention. Member of AJC Super 11 team. Recorded 169 tackles and 19
sacks in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Jackson, OL, 6-5, 310, Shanks, Quincy, Fla. _ SuperPrep
All-American and first-team All-State. Graded 93 percent as a
senior and allowed just one sack in more than 260 pass attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson, WR, 6-4, 205, Union, Tulsa _ SuperPrep
All-American and all-state in Oklahoma. Big receiver who caught 54
passes for 916 yards and 13 TDs last season.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathon Kilgo, K, 6-2, 200, Pepperell, Silver Creek _ Averaged
42 yards a punt as a senior and was successful on all 49
point-after attempts. Set a school record with a 50-yard field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Kirouac, K, 6-1, 200, Duluth _- Class AAAA All-State. Was
7-of-13 on field-goal attempts and set state record for FGs over 50
yards in a season with four. Averaged 41.7 yards a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Miller, LB, FB, 6-1, 225, Washington County, Tennille _
Non-qualifier from last season who still needs SAT score to meet
entrance requirements. Class AA All-State in 1997 when he rushed
for 1,668 yards, scored 42 TDs and had 151 tackles his senior
season.
</P>
<P>
   Tavarus Morgan, Ath., 5-11, 185, Jackson _ First-team Class AA
all-state at defensive back. Passed for 4,264 yards and rushed for
1,437 yards as a three-year starter at QB.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Rader, TE, 6-5, 225, St. Albans, West. Va. _ SuperPrep and
Scholastic Coach All-American. Had 14 receptions for 223 yards and
a touchdown this year. Had 256 career tackles and seven sacks as
DL.
</P>
<P>
   Durell Robinson, WR, 6-2, 200, Byrnes, Duncan, S.C. _ A Parade
Magazine first-team All-American and South Carolina player of the
year. Had 73 catches for 1,386 yards and 28 TDs as senior.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Thornton, RB, 6-0, 180, LaGrange _ AJC Super 11 selection
who rushed for 1,920 yards as a senior and 4,541 yards as a
three-year starter. Also had 932 return yards and blocked 12 kicks
as a special-teams player.
</P>
<P>
   Johnathan Sullivan, DL, 6-3, 265, Griffin _ Had 130 tackles and
19for losses last season. Played over 90 snaps per game on the
offensive and defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Shedrick Wynn, DE, 6-3, 230, Lincoln County, Lincolnton _ Class
A All-State and USA Today honorable mention. He and Garrison Hearst
are only players to start four years at Lincoln County. Also was
place kicker and played tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Veal, DL, 6-3, 290, Cedartown _ Non-qualifier from 1998
class who still needs to meet entrance requirements. Class AA
first-team All-State in 1997 with 104 tackles and seven sacks.
</P>
