<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT STRIVES TO COMPLETE PATRIOTS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Desperate to close the deal to bring the New England
Patriots to Hartford, Connecticut officials worked feverishly
Wednesday to convince the team that problems with the proposed site
of a downtown stadium would not delay construction of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals involved in the negotiations said the Patriots
organization was increasingly confident that the state will find a
way to move a steam plant that now sits on what would be the
50-yard line, and will handle any environmental contamination left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   However, Connecticut Governor John G. Rowland told the
Associated Press Wednesday there could be a delay of the scheduled
signing Friday of a development agreement that would legally bind
the team to play there for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signing could be Friday, it could be Saturday,'' Rowland
said. ``We will have agreement on all the issues by Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   A Patriots spokesman said Friday was not a deadline but ``a
goal'' to have all the guarantees in place and problems resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week a breakdown in talks on moving the steam plant
unnerved many involved in the $350 million stadium project, part of
a larger $1 billion downtown revitalization effort. Some team
officials worried that the plant could stand in the way of stadium
construction, the start of which already may be delayed until the
summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Rowland took immediate action, naming a special adviser to
solve the steam plant problem, a move that has contributed to some
newfound confidence on the part of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, we are still working towards a Friday
timetable and there are still some unknowns,'' said team vice
president Andy Wasynczuk. ``But there's more and more information
being put together and everyone is working in good faith to make it
happen. And we believe it will happen on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers continued work around the clock to complete
language in the final development agreement, a document that is
more than 200 pages long and lays out just how the stadium will be
built and when.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from putting the finishing touches on that pact, Rowland's
office pressed forward to assuage the team's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The governor hired Richard D. Gray, executive director of the
Connecticut Health and Educational Facilities Authority, to work as
a third-party deal-broker between CTG Resources Inc., owner of the
steam plant, and the Connecticut Resources Recovery Authority, a
quasi-public agency that could provide the energy to the stadium
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anyone that can get the job done it's Rich Gray,''
said one Connecticut lobbyist. ``He is very bright, very skilled in
government, very skilled in politics, a tough negotiator.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the team was encouraged by Gray's help and, even if
there is no resolution Friday on how and when to move the steam
plant, the likelihood of signing the development agreement is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of different facets to this parcel that are
being dealt with,'' one person close to the talks said. ``And
between Wednesday's meeting, last night's meeting, and continued
conversations today, it is imminently clear that the state is
moving as aggressively as possible to try to straighten these
issues out.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue: CTG is considering buying steam from the nearby CRRA
plant and running pipes to the stadium site so there would be no
service disruption downtown. If no deal is struck between the two
power producers, however, CTG could face having the state take the
land by eminent domain and reimburse the company for its value.
</P>
<P>
   That is the option of last resort because it could be the most
time consuming, those involved in the negotiations say.
</P>
<P>
   No one could be reached for comment at CTG or CRRA Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As for the cost of cleaning up the dozens of potentially toxic
chemicals that now contaminate the site, John DeVillars, regional
administrator for the Environmental Protection Agency, Wednesday
said no one knows for sure how much that would cost because the
last study done on the site occurred years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But, DeVillars added, ``There are ways in which the stadium can
be sited and constructed that can minimize the cost associated with
the environmental cleanup and we've begun those discussions'' with
site consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if the Connecticut deal falls through, Governor Paul
Cellucci would be waiting with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will very happily go back to the table,'' Cellucci said.
``It's a pretty big project. There's always hurdles when you have
big project. The question is, can they overcome the hurdles. We're
obviously watching to see if they do or if they don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
