<HEADLINE>
CHRIS SIMMS, NATION'S BEST HIGH SCHOOL QUARTERBACK, WILL PLAY FOR 
 TEXAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Tenn., N.J., N.Y., Ohio, Ind., Ill., Conn., Mass.,
Fla.)  By RON DICKER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Simms of Ramapo High School, considered the best schoolboy
quarterback in the nation, Wednesday signed a letter of intent to
attend the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5-inch, 218-pound Simms, the son of the former Giants
quarterback Phil Simms, threw for 7,055 yards and 63 touchdowns in
his career.
</P>
<P>
   His signing, after he verbally committed to Tennessee last fall,
bolstered Texas' incoming class. The Longhorns landed eight players
among the top 100 prep athletes and another 12 in the top 250,
according to Jeff Duva, publisher of PrepStar magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at sheer numbers, they're the best,'' said Duva,
who ranked UCLA, Tennessee, Notre Dame and Ohio State behind the
Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State does not announce signees, but, according to
Blue-White Illustrated, a magazine devoted to the school's athletic
program, the Nittany Lions did not use one of their 13 scholarships
to grab a quarterback, perceived as a positional weakness. Penn
State still got its share of skill players, led by running back
Horace Dodd (6-2, 205), the Connecticut player of the year from
Hamden High School.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers signed wide receiver Ryshaun Conover (6-3, 200) of
Lakewood High and linebacker Raheem Orr (6-4, 230) of Elizabeth
High. Both were rated among the top five players in New Jersey by
the McCarthy Report, a scouting service used by major colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed is probably the biggest equalizer in college football
today,'' Coach Terry Shea said. `'I wanted to generate that type of
quality with this class. That's something we didn't have enough of
but we are constantly building toward.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse found Donovan McNabb's heir apparent in R.J. Anderson
(6-1, 215), who threw 45 touchdown passes at Milford (Conn.)
Academy despite not starting at the beginning of the season. The
Orangemen also plucked linebacker Clifton Smith (6-2, 240) of
Freeport High on New York's Long Island and shored up the defensive
end position with Josh Thomas (6-7, 230) of Orchard Park High, also
in New York state, and Joe Donnelly (6-3, 208) of Kent High School
in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College received commitments from several prominent New
Jersey players, including running back William Green (6-1, 220) of
Holy Spirit in Absecon and linemen Augie Hoffman (6-4, 315) of St.
Joseph's in Montvale and Tom Martin (6-5, 245) of Howell.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College lured from New York City defensive back Will
Poole (6-0, 170) of Christ the King and running back Brian Flores
of Poly Prep. Another Poly star, wide receiver Kunle Patrick (6-1,
205), opted for Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   In other prominent signings nationwide, Notre Dame plucked
safety Jerome Sapp (6-0, 210) from Lamar High in Houston; Ohio
State lured PrepStar's highest-rated lineman, Bryce Bishop (6-5,
310) of Killian, Fla., and Temple recruited Dan Klecko, (6-1, 260),
a defensive lineman from Marlboro High in New Jersey, who is the
son of Joe Klecko, the former Temple and New York Jets star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
