<HEADLINE>
INTERNET BROKERAGE FIRM CLOSES BRIEFLY FOR SOME REPAIRS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: (STAR) in the company name E(STAR)Trade should be changed to
the typographical symbol.) 
(DW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   E(STAR)Trade, an Internet brokerage firm, had computer problems
twice Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Its World Wide Web site would not accept trades from customers
for more than an hour in the morning, and sporadically in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   E(STAR)Trade, which handled an average of 42,000 trades a day in
the last quarter, said that its business hardly had been affected.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Levinson, the company's president, asserted that online
trading companies are being held to a higher standard than
brokerage firms have been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the traditional way that people invested,'' she said, ``it
didn't matter if their broker was out to lunch. No one cared if
their trade was placed at 10 a.m. or 11. There is a new breed of
online trader, and higher expectations have been set.''
</P>
</TEXT>
