A0954 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON &LR;      02-03 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Finding a Computer School  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'm a computer illiterate who has a 9-to-5 job. I would
like to take some night classes to learn how to navigate Windows,
Microsoft Word, etc. Are there any computer schools you can
recommend?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Lots of private schools specialize in computing
classes, but I wouldn't look at those until I'd exhausted some
other alternatives. First, contact your local community college to
see if it has the classes you want at the times you need. Most JCs
now offer training in basic computing, including Windows, word
processing, spreadsheets and such. College courses usually are a
better bang for your buck than private classes, which typically
last just a few hours and cost up to $50.
</P>
<P>
   You also might try to track down a local computer users' group,
which may be able to steer you to some good classes. One group, the
Golden Gate Computer Society, offers a free Introduction to
Computing course in San Rafael. You can call them at (415)
454-5556.
</P>
<P>
   The Ideas Man
</P>
<P>
   Q: I keep track of my investments using Excel 97 for Windows. Is
there a way to import the total value of each stock to a summary
worksheet showing all my investments? Currently, I copy and paste
the value. I wonder if there's an easier way by setting some sort
of automatic function. Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Ideas is my middle name. You should be able to accomplish
your goal by linking the cells of the main worksheet(s) to a table
in a summary worksheet. Here's how: Select the cells whose contents
you want to display in the summary. Choose Copy from the Edit menu.
Then switch to the summary worksheet. Now choose Paste Special from
the Edit menu, then click the button labeled Paste Link. This will
transfer the formulas and content of the cells. After that, any
time you make a change to the original worksheet that affects the
calculation, the results will change on the summary sheet as well.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Just Plain RAM
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the difference between DRAM, SRAM, EDO RAM, SDRAM and
just plain RAM?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Let's start by explaining what RAM is. It stands for
Random Access Memory, which is memory that can be used to store and
retrieve information in a personal computer or other device. The
first generation of PC memory chip was called Dynamic Random Access
Memory, or DRAM. Then came a faster kind used a technique called
Extended Data Output _ hence EDO RAM. For the past couple of years,
most new PCs have come with an even faster kind of chip called
Synchronous DRAM, or SDRAM.
</P>
<P>
   Different kinds of DRAM are incompatible with each other, so if
you're going to upgrade the memory in your computer, find out
what's in there before you buy new chips.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of COMPUTIN (76542 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  That leaves just SRAM. Short for Static RAM, it can be accessed
faster than DRAM, but it's also more expensive and requires much
more space for the same amount of data. It's used in PCs mainly for
the caches that microprocessors look in before they look in the
main RAM.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now that we've got RAM straight, here's one more: SCRAM.
</P>
<P>
   Booking Your Favorites
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do I transfer the Web sites I've saved as Favorites in
Internet Explorer to Netscape's Bookmark folder? I want both my
browsers to have the same information, but the formats seem to be
different.
</P>
<P>
   A: Indeed they are, but fortunately, several shareware and
freeware programs can be downloaded from the Web that let you
convert Favorites to Bookmarks and vice versa. Actually, this
question comes up a lot, so everybody clip out this section of the
column and tape it to the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular converter programs is a freebie called
Navex. To download it, go to &LR;  mach5.ocs.drexel.edu/navex/. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Another free program called Bookmark Converter can be found by
going to PC World's site  &LR; (www.pcworld.com) &LR;  and searching for that
title. And finally, there's a good $21 program called Bookmark
Importer from WebOBJ, which is available at  &LR; www.webobj.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  If you enter exactly the same information in lots of documents,
consider creating a macro to cut down on your typing time. Macros
are recordings of keystrokes that can either be text or a series of
commands telling the computer to carry out an operation. Microsoft
Word makes it easy to create a macro. Just choose Macro from the
Tools menu, then click Record New Macro and follow the
instructions. You can assign a keyboard shortcut to your macro or
create a toolbar button, giving you easy access to it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
