<SLUG> BC-OLY-REVOLT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC GROUP THREATENS SITE FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The palace revolt within the International Olympic Committee
began in earnest Wednesday when several dozen members vowed they
wouldn't give up the right to choose future host cities in the wake
of the Salt Lake City payoff scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IOC's executive board last month recommended that a
15-member group, not the full body, pick the site of the 2006
Winter Games in June, many of the 100-plus rank-and-file members
said it would be an insult to their integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some hurt feelings that we were being classified in
that group of guilty IOC members,'' said Jim Easton, one of the
three US members. ``It's like taking the candy away from the bad
boy _ you won't get the vote anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Picking host cities is the most cherished privilege of the IOC
members, who meet only once a year. But since more than a dozen of
them allegedly took $800,000 in cash and gifts before and after the
2002 Winter Games were awarded, the IOC has been under severe
pressure to reform the bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Besides recommending that a smaller committee with only eight
IOC members select the next site, the executive board suspended six
members pending expulsion at a special full session in Lausanne,
Switzerland, next month. One, David Sibandze of Swaziland, has
since resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have some bad apples, they should be thrown out, but
don't tell us the whole general assembly is corrupt,'' said Mario
Pescante of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Pescante said an ``overwhelming majority'' of 42 members defied
the executive board at a breakfast meeting Wednesday in Lausanne,
where the IOC is staging a major conference on doping issues this
week. ``For the first time in the history of the Olympic
movement,'' he said, ``the voice of the members is very, very
loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the board's recommendations are usually rubber-stamped by
the full body, the host city issue was expected to be delicate and
controversial. ``The members' first reaction will be that they're
being chastised,'' predicted vice president Richard Pound of
Canada, who chaired the IOC's inquiry panel which recommended the
reforms. ``It will be insulting to them. But once that is dealt
with, they'll realize that we face quite a problem and that we have
to do something dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch has already banned members
from visiting the six candidate cities for 2006 _ Sion,
Switzerland; Turin, Italy; Helsinki; Klagenfurt, Austria; Zakopane,
Poland; and Poprad-Tatry, Slovakia. But surrendering the right to
choose the host will require a two-thirds vote, which now seems
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible the general assembly will approve this
proposal,'' Pescante said. ``I'm sure the executive board will have
to find a new solution before then. If they lose at the session, it
would be a disaster for the president and the executive board.''
</P>
<P>
   As a compromise, the IOC may decide to let the smaller committee
name two or three finalists 24 hours before the vote, then have the
entire body select the victor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not unreasonable,'' Easton said. ``It's a system that
makes some sense. If (the cutoff) was done very late in the game,
there would be no chance for anyone to go out and abuse any
privileges.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the doping conference, which the IOC had hoped would
produce a global watchdog agency and uniform penalties for drug use
among sporting federations, has been beset by bitter disagreements
and distrust.
</P>
<P>
   Any chance for the IOC-proposed two-year minimum doping ban for
serious offenders appeared dead amid fears that courts would
overrule the penalty. And both the United States and the 15-member
European Union oppose having the IOC control the anti-drug agency.
``An independent organization is required, and independence means
just that _ independence,'' said Donald Vereen, deputy director of
the White House drug control office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
