<HEADER>
A0956 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAMP-SFCHRON &LR;      02-03 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAMP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Print Your Own Stamps   By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Neither rain, snow, sleet nor online bandwidth will stop the latest
form of postage from being delivered to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   As early as this summer, &UR;  &LR; Web surfers will be able to download
electronic stamps over the Internet and print them out from a PC,
creating a personalized post office. But you pay a premium for the
service, so small businesses that want an alternative to postage
meters are expected to be the biggest audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about convenience and avoiding paying for pricey
postage meters,'' said Jeff Green, co-founder of Stamps.com
( &LR; www.stamps.com &LR; ), a Santa Monica firm that is one of a quartet of
contenders in the fledgling e-postage field.
</P>
<P>
   Stamps.com, E-Stamp, Pitney-Bowes and Neopost, with the blessing
of the U.S. Postal Service, have developed technology that stores
e-postage online or in a small PC attachment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how e-postage works: You visit a Web site, where you
either register with a service or download free software that
allows you to use a credit card or electronic funds transfer to buy
postage in blocks of $20, $40, $100 and $200. The postage is stored
either on the vendor's Web server or a hardware box you attach to
your computer.
</P>
<P>
   When you're ready to mail a letter, you open the software
program or go to the Web site and type in how much postage you
need. An optional scale that can be connected to a PC weighs small
packages and determines their mailing cost.
</P>
<P>
   The Web server or hardware box ``dispenses'' the postage from
your account. Then you can print the bar-coded postage onto any
envelope, label or letter that fits into your printer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Convenience does come at a price, however. You have to buy or
lease the hardware device, as well as pay transaction fees _
usually about 10 percent of the amount of the stamps purchased.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; E-Stamp offers a dime-size device for about $100 that attaches
to a computer's printer port. Pitney Bowes and Neopost offer
similar products that lease for about $10 to $15 a month.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But don't count on pretty pictures of Elvis, birds and
beaches. Most of the digital stamps show plain bar codes, as
specified by the U.S. Postal Service. In rare instances, an
``advertising area'' next to the bar code allows limited use of
scanned images, such as company logos, as preapproved by the Postal
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The two-dimensional bar codes are crucial, however. They contain
an encrypted ID number and information about the origin of each
piece of mail, making them more difficult to forge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &UR;  &LR; Appearances aside, Sunir Kapoor, CEO of E-Stamp
( &LR; www.estamp.com &LR; ), said digital-postage systems should expedite
operations at an estimated 32.5 million small businesses and
home-based offices in the United States. The other alternative for
these businesses is postage meters, which rent for $30 to $120 a
month, and also include charges for ``resetting'' and
equipment-maintenance that can top $40 a month.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STAMP04 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Indeed, market research firm Keenan Vision Inc. in San Francisco
predicts spending on electronic postage will vault to $127 million
in 2000 and $1.9 billion in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   E-Stamp and Stamps.com have agreements with America Online to
provide e-postage for a postal center AOL is expected to launch
this year. Both have tested their digital-stamp systems in San
Francisco and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The other pair of competitors in the field _ Pitney Bowes
( &LR; www.pitneybowes.com &LR; ) and Neopost ( &LR; www.neopost.com &LR; ) _ are
extending their well-established postal-meter businesses onto the
Net.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney Bowes is particularly well positioned: The Stamford,
Conn., company is the Goliath of the contenders, having served as
the largest supplier of postage-meter services in the United States
since the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology is ideally suited for anyone or any company
who does mass mailings,'' said Bill Shannon, director of product
management at Pitney Bowes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely better than going to the post office and
waiting in line. That's a pain,'' said Isobel Bonar, area manager
at IWCC Training in Communications, a San Carlos training and
consulting firm that has beta-tested E-Stamp's product for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Lick-and-stick postage has come a long way since the visages of
Benjamin Franklin and George Washington graced stamps in 1847.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 years later, digital stamps are among the first
electronic goods consumers can buy and receive straight from the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They could eventually usher in an era of cyber post offices
offered by Internet service providers and popular Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a post office inside your personal
computer,'' Bonar said. ``We should all be so lucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
