r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETRADE-SFCHRON &LR;      02-03 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-Trade's Outage Irks Online Traders  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Trading operations of E-Trade Group broke down for more than an
hour yesterday morning, angering customers and showing once again
that computer-based investing remains vulnerable to &UR;  &LR; breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade, the nation's third-largest online broker, said
customers were unable to place orders beginning at 7:15 a.m.
Pacific time because of an error in a computer code it added to its
trading software Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   By taking out the code, the Palo Alto firm was able to restore
voice-activated telephone trading in about 50 minutes and Internet
trading a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the fix, E-Trade said about 5 percent of its clients
still had problems carrying out online trades because it hadn't
removed all pieces of the malfunctioning code.
</P>
<P>
   During the period trading was blocked, E-Trade said its Web site
remained open. Still, at one point, Keynote Systems, a San Mateo
company that tracks Internet usage, said that one out of every four
of its test attempts to get through to the site failed, compared to
a normal failure rate of less than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade apologized to its customers for the breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a company official said that expectations of
instant, error-free trading aren't realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I'd love to say technology is 100 percent reliable all
the time, frankly technology is not like that,'' said President
Kathy Levinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be as close to 100 percent as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Levinson said she didn't know how many customers weren't able to
carry out trades.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade will consider their claims individually and will make
good on genuine losses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown came at an embarrassing time for E-Trade, which is
in the midst of an expensive advertising campaign to promote its
Web site as an all-purpose source of financial information.
</P>
<P>
   Online stock trading is growing at a frenzied pace.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Credit Suisse First Boston reported that electronic
brokerage rocketed up 34 percent from the third to the fourth
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Amid surging demand, most of E-Trade's rivals have also had
service problems.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leader Charles Schwab, for example, recently said its
Internet site and telephone operations turned clients away on
several occasions in January.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ETRADE04 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  E-trade, which executed nearly 40,000 trades a day in the fourth
quarter, stressed that yesterday's breakdown had nothing to do with
its ability to handle Web traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, plenty of investors, especially the hyper-aggressive and
unforgiving ``day traders'' who aim to get in and out of stocks in
the space of a few hours, weren't interested in explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Online message boards at sites such as Yahoo and Silicon
Investor were filled with barbed ``flames'' aimed at E-Trade
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Warned one irate trader on Yahoo's site: ``Get it together
E-Trade or you're going to the E-grave.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of ETRADE04 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
