<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KTRAVEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Airlines Face Early Arrival Of Y2K Today  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
For most of the U.S. airline industry, Jan. 1, 2000, lands today.
</P>
<P>
   That's because February 4 is the first day major computer
reservation systems serving airlines like United, American and
Northwest will start booking flights for next New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Airline computer specialists who spent years and millions of
dollars testing systems to make sure the Year 2000 problem doesn't
bite are cautiously confident.
</P>
<P>
   They will also be holding their collective breaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a command center set up and will have extra people
on hand in case something might happen,'' said Jennifer Hudson,
spokeswoman for the Sabre Group, which operates one of the largest
travel reservation networks used by airlines and travel agents
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   To save data storage space, computer programs used to be written
to recognize only the last two digits of a year. The Y2K problem
could cause computers to interpret 2000 as the year 1900, which
could lead to miscalculations or system crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Today became an early Y2K deadline for the airline industry
since its computer reservations systems were designed to accept
bookings either 330 or 331 days in advance of the travel date.
</P>
<P>
   Any Y2K-related glitches are expected to cause only minor
inconveniences. Travel agents and online customers, for example,
may have to take extra steps to find and book plane tickets and
travel packages if computers fail to recognize the year.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about the safety of planes flying on Jan. 1, 2000, is a
separate issue, although the airlines remain confident problems
will be solved by that time.
</P>
<P>
   But Year 2000 observers say what happens to reservations will
provide valuable lessons for programmers working on the Y2K problem
in other industries. The reservation systems' successes or failures
may prove a harbinger of things to come the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of Y2KTRAVE (87813 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``People are keeping their eyes and ears open for any kinds of
problems they missed or things they didn't think of,'' said Robert
Martin, a Y2K director at Mitre Corp. of Bedford, Mass., a
nonprofit corporation that advises federal agencies on Year 2000
remedies. ``We always want reassurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabre Group, the world's biggest computer reservations
system handling about one-third of travel bookings, has been
working on the Year 2000 problem since 1995. The Texas company will
have staff standing by at command centers in Dallas and Tulsa,
Okla., just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tested it dozens upon dozens times, but (today) will be
the first real-time test,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, Harm Helm, director of applications systems for
United Airlines, will also be crossing his fingers as the first
results come through and also will have teams of experts standing
by.
</P>
<P>
   Helm has been working with officials from Apollo, the
reservations system used by United, on fixing and testing Y2K
problems since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in good shape, we're pretty confident that we're ready
to go and we don't anticipate any problems,'' Helm said. ``If we
get through the first day, the likelihood is that we will be OK
with booking into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though today is the acid test for U.S. reservation systems,
some systems in other countries have already been put to the test _
and passed. Carriers like British Airways and Quantas Air have
reported no Y2K glitches so far. Galileo International, the parent
firm for the Apollo system, also has already successfully processed
international flight reservations for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Hill, owner of Franciscan Travel Service in San Francisco,
said demand for travel on New Year's seems to be strong since
people want to be someplace special for the new millennium. But
with the crush of extra holiday travel and the uncertainties over
Y2K, Hill is staying on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of Y2KTRAVE (87813 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``I don't think I want to be on a plane,'' she said. ``I think
it's going to be a shambles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
