<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAROQUE-JAZZ-CONCERT-     02-03 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAROQUE-JAZZ-CONCERT-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENERABLE MUSICAL INSTITUTIONS COLLIDE, QUIETLY  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 7)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (af) 
 By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two enduring and vibrant musical institutions came
together here for the first time, on Friday evening, to explore the
common threads of musical styles born more than two centuries
apart: Baroque and jazz.
</P>
<P>
   In a concert to be repeated Sunday afternoon, the Handel and
Haydn Society, founded here in 1815 and still a leading American
Baroque chorus and orchestra, joined forces at Symphony Hall with
the jazz fusion pioneers Chick Corea and Gary Burton, who
serendipitously hooked up in 1972 and have played together every
year since.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups play their distinctive brands of music in
alternation, choosing pieces that encourage improvisation and
counterpoint, techniques that, they say, help keep them vital and
fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvisation brings excitement to what we play,'' said John
Finney, the associate conductor of the Handel and Haydn Society,
who chose the Baroque works in the collaborative program and
directs them from the harpsichord and organ. ``We work in a defined
melodic framework, but you can play a wash of sound around the
notes that will enhance and propel them. It's like when an already
beautiful woman puts on jewelry. It adds glitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Baroque mainstay, counterpoint, has long inspired
the pianist Corea, who was born in nearby Chelsea, Mass., and the
vibraphonist Burton, who has lived in Boston most of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When what I'm playing spontaneously intersects with what he's
playing, it sends off the music like a rocket that flies into the
audience and lifts us both off the floor,'' said Burton, who is
also the executive vice president of the Berklee College of Music.
``It's the thrill we live for, and it keeps the music fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part of the concert, Corea and Burton are performing
selections from their album ``Native Sense: The New Duets,'' their
first recording since 1982, which was released last year and has
been nominated for two Grammy awards, for best small ensemble and
best soloists.
</P>
<P>
   They have already won two Grammys, and what keeps the
partnership growing, they suggest, is a quality rarely extolled by
popular musicians: maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, our communication onstage has become almost a sixth
sense,'' Burton said. ``We can read each other's nuances, so what
we each are playing miraculously coincides to create something
new.''
</P>
<P>
   The Handel and Haydn Society, despite being the nation's oldest
continuously performing arts group, also keeps growing and
changing. At the moment, it is searching for an artistic director
to replace the English conductor Christopher Hogwood, who has
announced that he will leave in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrival in 1985, Hogwood has introduced 17th- and
18th-century instruments for the orchestra and, critics say, raised
playing standards to a consistently high level.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom holds that collaborative efforts like this
allow classical music to speak more directly to a wider audience.
But there may be another, more problematic side to the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baroque instruments can sound small and pale compared to the
meaty, high-cholesterol sound of modern instruments,'' said John
Gibbons, a harpsichordist and the chairman of the historic
performance department at the New England Conservatory here.
``Success is in the ear of the beholder.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hogwood, who started the society's Baroque and jazz series
10 years ago, is confident that the current program enhances the
stature of both groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a jazz duo whose 20th-century decibel level is not out
of range with our early, 18th-century music etiquette,'' he said
from his home in Cambridge, England. ``It's an experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hogwood's willingness to overhaul the Handel and Haydn
Society has helped it maintain its position at the center of the
early-music scene here, according to William R. Porter, who teaches
organ at the New England Conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1800s, the society imbued Boston with a taste for
refined European music. But by the 1960s and 70s, when this city
was a hub of early-music training and performance, the quality of
the society's performances were too often amateurish.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hogwood, Porter said, the society's switch to period
instruments and emphasis on musicianship has ``enriched Handel and
Haydn, and Boston, as a center of early music.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Hogwood, his fellow conductor Finney sees basic connections
between Baroque music and the Corea-Burton wing of jazz, which
finds inspiration in European chamber music, New Orleans jazz,
American rock and Latin rumba.
</P>
<P>
   First, Baroque music encouraged improvisation and originally
taught it as a high art form. ``Bach's improvisational performances
drew audiences from miles around,'' Finney said. ``Today, some
French cathedral organists still improvise on a theme.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Baroque harpsichord part, the bass line is written out for
the left hand, but no notes are given for the right hand. Numbers
supplied by the composer show the character of the chords above,
which the performer may fill out in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvisation keeps Baroque in the here and now,'' Finney
said. ``But jazz improvisations are different, because they play
actual variations of a melody to invent entirely new versions of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ornamentation of music with trills and the like is
important for the harpsichord and other instruments that cannot
sustain a sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding lots of little notes creates an effervescent flurry of
sounds that quickly fade away to produce a crystalline clarity,''
Finney said. ``I chose music that has a bright, quick heartbeat,
just short of frenetic, because that's what I heard in Corea and
Burton.''
</P>
<P>
   As its part of the program, the Handel and Haydn Society plays
Bach's Concerto for Two Violins in D minor (BWV 1043), Corelli's
Concerto Grosso in D (Op. 6, No. 1) and Handel's Organ Concerto in
F (Op. 4, No. 4). Corea and Burton play Corea's ``Brasilia,'' ``No
Mystery,'' ``Duende,'' ``Bud Powell,'' ``Tango '95'' and
``Rhumbata.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ornamentation is clear in Rhumbata,'' Finney said. ``Instead
of playing one note, they play a trill that bends around the
note.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, both musical styles rely on counterpoint. ``It's what
makes Corea and Burton's music so engaging,'' Finney said. ``At
times, you hear the vibe and piano clearly playing two different
melodies. Other times, they play in unison, so fast it's amazing. I
still haven't figured out how Burton can play as fast with four
mallets, two in each hand, as we play with 10 fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Burton agrees on what the two genres share. ``They also both
have a lively melodic style, familiar harmony patterns and a steady
stream of eighth notes that create a pulsing beat,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our music is a little darker at this point in life,'' said
Burton, who, like Corea, is 56, ``and our playing has taken on
greater intensity, more focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a string quartet whose ability to play together
reflects their familiarity and maturity. We'd do anything not to
break up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
