<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      02-03 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OPEN SEASON ON `ALIENS'   
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E. J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   someone set off the motion-sensing lights near the front gate of
Jerry Chap's ranch west of Patagonia, about 14 miles from the
Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's deputies from Santa Cruz County later said a smuggler
leading a group of 25 illegal immigrants had tripped the alarm by
opening the gate.
</P>
<P>
   The group ducked for cover when the lights went on, but decided
to cut through the property when it looked as if everything was
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who'd crossed into the United States that day was
25-year-old Oscar Hernandez Pinto. He told friends he'd lost his
job as a bus driver in Mexico City and was headed for Phoenix,
where he hoped to find work.
</P>
<P>
   As the group made its way past Chap's house, the lights went on
inside. According to investigators, the trespassers saw a man in a
wheelchair with a rifle. Chap is paralyzed below the waist and uses
a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   At least five rounds were fired. One of them struck Hernandez
Pinto above the right wrist. Friends bound the wound and carried
him off. Eventually, he made it to a Tucson hospital. He's now back
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days of the shooting, Chap and his wife were picked
up by sheriff's deputies on charges of attempted murder and
aggravated assault. In Arizona, deadly force is permitted only when
there's an immediate threat to someone's life.
</P>
<P>
   `NOT CONFRONTATIONAL'
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we know it was not confrontational,'' Santa Cruz
County Sheriff Tony Estrada told me Wednesday. ``There was no
threat. Of course, having people on your property can be
frightening. But that doesn't mean you can shoot them.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a spokesman for the Santa Cruz County prosecutor's
office told me the case is still under investigation and no
indictments have been issued.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Oscar Hernandez Pinto, his arm mangled, hired an
attorney and filed a $750,000 suit against the Chaps.
</P>
<P>
   That galls some people. It disgusts them. How could someone who
isn't a U.S. citizen, who was violating U.S. law, turn around and
sue an American?
</P>
<P>
   I understand their anger and frustration. I'd even go along with
them, if it weren't for one small thing.
</P>
<P>
   They're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   What if it had been a group of Boy Scouts who'd wandered off the
trail and onto Chap's property? Or a high school basketball team
whose bus had broken down? Or tourists who'd made a wrong turn?
</P>
<P>
   Trespassing is not a capital offense.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez Pinto's attorney, Fernando Gaxiola, told me, ``When we
were in Vietnam, we didn't call the people there fathers or
mothers, sons or daughters, we called them `gooks,' because it made
it easier to kill them. We call these people `aliens' for the same
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   DISLIKED BUT NEEDED
</P>
<P>
   We don't like ``aliens,'' but we need them. We need them to pick
crops and mow lawns because they're willing to do it for less money
than American workers, and without health care or retirement
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   If there were no demand, there'd be no supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you live here close to the border, then dealing with
undocumented workers is a fact of life,'' Sheriff Estrada said.
``But it is very rare that there are any confrontations. And the
ones that do occur we don't often hear much about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly because it's the illegals who end up on the short end of
the stick, or the rifle, and they're afraid to speak with U.S.
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Chap had shot an animal, he'd probably be in jail right
now,'' said Gaxiola the lawyer. ``All he shot was an `illegal
alien,' though. Some people think that's OK, that it's like
shooting a deer.''
</P>
<P>
   It's close to that, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   A man named Chap, who lives near the border, went out hunting
the other night and bagged a 25-year-old buck in his own back yard.
It was a darn good shot under difficult circumstances. The only
problem is, he doesn't have a license. Nobody does. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
