<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SEASON-2ndTAKE-NY     02-03 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SEASON-2ndTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Timberwolves . 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTRAL DIVISION:
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA PACERS
</P>
<P>
   They've been anointed favorites for two essential reasons:
Michael Jordan retired and the Indiana players ran sprints together
during the lockout. So the Pacers have a lot to prove over the next
three months. Reggie Miller is now the game's best clutch shooter
and Sam Perkins was a nice pick-up via free agency. But can Rik
Smits' chronically sore feet and Mark Jackson's aging legs hold up
three nights in a row on occasion during a 50-game, three-month
grind? On paper, the Pacers are on their way to the finals. But
more conference parity may make the road just as difficult as it
was when Michael Jordan stood in their way. Remember, Larry Bird
only coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ADDITIONS: C Sam Perkins, (free agent, Supersonics), F Al
Harrington (draft, No. 25, St. Patrick's High School, N.J.).
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: C Mark West (free agent, Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT PISTONS
</P>
<P>
   They re-signed Jerry Stackhouse and improved their front court
with Loy Vaught and Christian Laettner, who are both still
rehabilitating from injuries. Still, one of last season's
underachieving teams has put itself back in the playoff hunt again.
The main reason the Pistons will be better? Grant Hill and Joe
Dumars, expected to retire at season's end, won't stand for another
losing record.
</P>
<P>
   ADDITIONS: F Loy Vaught (free agent, Clippers), F Christian
Laettner (trade with Hawks), G Jud Buechler (free agent, Bulls).
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: F Grant Long (free agent), F Malik Sealy (free
agent, Timberwolves).
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE BUCKS
</P>
<P>
   George Karl does not have as much to work with as he did in
Seattle, but Terrell Brandon and Ray Allen still make for one of
the league's best young backcourts. Dell Curry's 3-point shooting
off the bench will help. The big question is whether Karl can get
the Bucks to play the same type of trapping, aggressive defense
that the SuperSonics did so well.
</P>
<P>
   ADDITIONS: G Dell Curry (free agent, Hornets), F Robert Traylor
(draft, No. 6, Michigan), F Donald Royal (free agent, Hornets).
</P>
<P>
   KEY LOSSES: C Andrew Lang (traded to Chicago), G Litterial Green
(free agent, Cleveland).
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA HAWKS
</P>
<P>
   Like the Bulls, Suns and Rockets, the Hawks had to rebuild on
the fly. The good news for Lenny Wilkens is that the four players
Atlanta already had under contract were starters. The bad news: his
bench is once again corn-silk thin. Steve Smith, Tyrone Corbin,
Alan Henderson, Mookie Blaylock and Dikembe Mutombo will have to
play major minutes for the Hawks to return to the playoffs for the
eighth straight season. The best off-season pickup may have been
the Sacramento shooting guard Anthony Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: G Anthony Johnson (free agent, Kings), F Kebu Stewart
(free agent, 76ers), F Scot Pollard (trade with Pistons), F Roshown
McLeod (draft, No. 20, Duke), C Mark West (free agent, Pacers), F
LaPhonso Ellis (free agent, Nuggets).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: F Christian Laettner (traded to Detroit), G Eldridge
Recasner (free agent, Charlotte).
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND CAVALIERS
</P>
<P>
   It's never a good sign when your franchise player reports to
training camp at least 20 pounds overweight, but that's what
happened. The ramifications of Shawn Kemp's girth in a short season
may prove costly for a team that otherwise has all the components
for returning to the playoffs. Derek Anderson and the 7-foot-3
Zydrunas Ilgauskas are two of the league's bright young talents and
the major reasons why General Manager Wayne Embry was named
Executive of the Year. But too many teams on the same rung as the
Cavs last season moved up a notch in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: F Johnny Newman (free agent, Nuggets), F Antonio Lang
(free agent, Heat), G Litterial Green (free agent, Bucks).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: Scott Brooks (free agent, Clippers).
</P>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE HORNETS
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Anthony Mason for the season with a ruptured biceps
tendon is a devastating blow. Gone are Vlade Divac and Matt Geiger,
7-footers who can bang and occasionally score. Derrick Coleman was
the major signing, and if he is n shape, there is no telling how
far Charlotte goes. But with Glen Rice lost to elbow surgery for 25
games and now Mason, the Hornets are another of those Eastern
Conference teams that takes a step backward.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: F Derrick Coleman (free agent, 76ers), F Chucky Brown
(free agent, Hawks), G Eldridge Recasner (free agent, Hawks), F
Chuck Person (free agent, Spurs), G Ricky Davis (draft, No. 21,
Iowa).
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO BULLS
</P>
<P>
   In less than a month, they've become the NBA equivalent of the
Florida Marlins, a once-proud championship team unrecognizable by
their new roster. Michael Jordan's retirement set off the most
disturbing domino effect the Bulls have ever seen. Toni Kukoc and
Ron Harper are back, and the acquisition of Brent Barry will make
it entertaining. So they're not world beaters anymore. But, hey,
they can still give Toronto a decent run.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: G Brent Barry (free agent, Heat), F Mark Bryant (free
agent, Suns), C Andrew Lang (trade with Bucks), G Corey Benjamin
(draft, No. 28, Oregon State), F Roy Rogers (trade with Rockets), C
Priest Lauderdale (free agent, Nuggets).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: G Michael Jordan (retired), F Scottie Pippen (traded
to Houston), F Dennis Rodman (free agent), G Steve Kerr (traded to
San Antonio), C Luc Longley (traded to Phoenix), F Scott Burrell
(free agent), G Jud Buechler (free agent, Detroit), C Joe Kleine
(free agent, Phoenix).
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO RAPTORS
</P>
<P>
   They have some so-so pieces, but none of them fit together.
Charles Oakley could complement an offensive threat in the post,
but Kevin Willis? The rookie Vince Carter could use a solid,
pass-first point guard to lead the fastbreak; Dee Brown is not that
player. Getting Michael Stewart to block shots in place of Marcus
Camby was smart, yet the Raptors have too many veterans on the
downside of their careers to make a playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: C Kevin Willis (trade with Rockets), F Charles Oakley
(trade with Knicks), G Vince Carter (draft, No. 5, North Carolina),
C Michael Stewart (free agent, Kings), G Micheal Williams (trade
with Timberwolves).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: F Marcus Camby (traded to New York), F Gary Trent
(free agent, Mavericks), C Sharone Wright (retired), G Chauncey
Billups (traded to Denver).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
