<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFIC DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES LAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Tired of the young kids getting uppity, Jerry West finally went
out and acquired veteran leadership. Although ancient by point
guard standards, Derek Harper's maturity could be more vital than
his minutes in the Lakers' continued ascension to the finals.
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant will try and resuscitate NBC's
ratings after the loss of you-know-who, and Eddie Jones is still
great bait for a veteran power like, say, Charles Oakley, at the
trading deadline. Either way, the Lakers acquit themselves much
better in the conference finals than they did a year ago. Whether
they can get past the Jazz is another story.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: C Travis Knight (trade with Celtics), G Derek Harper
(free agent, Magic), G Tyronn Lue (draft, No. 23, Nebraska), G Sam
Jacobsen (draft, No. 26, Minnesota).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: G Nick Van Exel (traded to Denver), G Jon Barry
(free agent, Sacramento).
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE SUPERSONICS
</P>
<P>
   Hersey Hawkins' consecutive starting string of 431 games _ the
league's longest current streak _ is about to end. Coach Paul
Westphal, back from NBA exile, is more comfortable with Billy Owens
at the shooting guard. Gary Payton is better than anyone at his
position and Vin Baker is not far behind as a power forward. But
the Sonics simply don't have the muscle _ a physical presence to
collect rebounds and fouls _ in order to advance to the conference
finals. Unless they trade for a veteran power forward, like, say,
Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: C Vladimir Stepania (draft, No. 27, Slovenia), F
Billy Owens (free agent, Kings), C Olden Polynice (free agent,
Kings), F Don MacLean (trade with Nets).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: C Sam Perkins (free agent, Indiana), G Greg Anthony
(free agent, Trail Blazers), F Jerome Kersey (free agent, San
Antonio), C Jim McIlvaine (traded to New Jersey).
</P>
<P>
   PORTLAND TRAIL BLAZERS
</P>
<P>
   They re-signed Arvydas Sabonis and Damon Stoudamire, and for the
most part have rid themselves of their knucklehead image. Rasheed
Wallace and Isaiah Rider can be combustible at times, but their
talent is unquestioned. The real advantage for the Blazers is that
they remain essentially the same team from last season. Over the
next 50 games and three months, built-in chemistry is a huge plus.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: G Greg Anthony (free agent, SuperSonics), G Bonzi
Wells (draft, No. 11, Ball State).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: G Rick Brunson (free agent, New York), G Gary Grant
(free agent).
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO KINGS
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, GM Geoff Petrie remade the franchise into a playoff
team. The trade with Washington for Chris Webber and the signing of
Vlade Divac and Corliss Williamson give the Kings a formidable
frontline. Throw in `97 draft pick Predrag Stojakovic, whom they
convinced to leave Greece, and the rookie point guard Jason
Williams, and Sacramento may be on their way back to the
postseason. If Kevin Johnson decides to sign with his hometown
team, the second round is not an impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: C Vlade Divac (free agent, Hornets), F Chris Webber
(trade with Wizards), G Jason Williams (draft, No. 7, Florida), G
Predrag Stojakovic (1997 draft, Greece), G Vernon Maxwell (free
agent, Hornets), G Kevin Ollie (free agent, Magic), G Jon Barry
(free agent, Lakers).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: G Mitch Richmond, (traded to Washington), F Otis
Thorpe (traded to Washington), G Mahmoud Abdul-Rauf (playing
overseas), C Olden Polynice (free agent, Seattle), C Michael
Stewart (free agent, Toronto), F Billy Owens (free agent, Seattle),
G Anthony Johnson (free agent, Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX SUNS
</P>
<P>
   So much for the owner Jerry Colangelo's sales pitch, the one
about warm weather, a team that takes care of its players and
always strives for the finals. Scottie Pippen didn't buy it.
Neither did Antonio McDyess. When the top free agents went
elsewhere, Phoenix was forced to pin its hopes on Tom Gugliotta,
whose experience as a franchise player is nil and none. Luc Longley
was a decent pick up, and you can't discount Jason Kidd's
development into one of the game's best all-around players and Rex
Chapman is good for drama. But the Suns don't have the ammunition
to go deep into the playoffs, if they get there.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: F Tom Gugliotta (free agent, Timberwolves), C Luc
Longley (trade with Bulls), F Pat Garrity (draft, No. 19, Notre
Dame), C Joe Kleine (free agent, Bulls), G James Collins (free
agent, Clippers).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: F Antonio McDyess (free agent, Denver), G Kevin
Johnson (free agent), G Steve Nash (traded to Dallas), F Mark
Bryant (traded to Chicago), F Dennis Scott (free agent, New York),
C Hot Rod Williams (free agent, Dallas).
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN STATE WARRIORS
</P>
<P>
   John Starks and Terry Cummings have already emerged as leaders.
With the Sprewell saga finally behind them, the Warriors trudge out
of the depths of the conference and return to respectability.
Re-signing rebounder extraordinaire Jason Caffey was almost as
important as making sure Sprewell didn't show up to training camp
on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: G John Starks, F Chris Mills, F Terry Cummings (all
in trade with Knicks), G Antawn Jamison (draft, No. 4, North
Carolina).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: G Latrell Sprewell (traded to New York), F Clarence
Weatherspoon (free agent, Miami), G Jim Jackson (free agent).
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES CLIPPERS
</P>
<P>
   Michael Olowokandi escaped from his Italian League contract
earlier than expected, and should show enough promise as the No. 1
pick to warrant hope for this moribund franchise. But until they
begin making long-term, financial commitments to burgeoning
All-Stars, the Clippers will have to drive to the Great Western
Forum to catch the playoffs in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Additions: C Michael Olowokandi (draft, No. 1, Pacific), F Brian
Skinner (draft, No. 22, Baylor), G Scott Brooks (free agent,
Cavaliers).
</P>
<P>
   Key Losses: C Isaac Austin (free agent, Orlando), F Loy Vaught
(free agent, Detroit), G James Collins (free agent, Phoenix).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mike Wise's Playoff Predictions: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Conference Playoff Teams: Indiana, New York, Miami, New
Jersey, Washington, Detroit, Orlando, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Western Conference Playoff Teams: Utah, L.A. Lakers, San
Antonio, Houston, Seattle, Portland, Minnesota, Sacramento
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Conference Finals: Indiana over New Jersey
</P>
<P>
   Western Conference Finals: Utah over Lakers
</P>
<P>
   NBA Finals: Utah over Indiana
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
