<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI KNOCKS OFF ST. JOHN'S AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ St. John's coach Mike Jarvis had said that an
early-season loss to Miami was the only game which had disappointed
him this season, because his team had shown none of the emotion or
tenacity that has defined its run to the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night at Madison Square Garden, the Red Storm turned
in an eerily similar performance, letting the undermanned
Hurricanes control much of the game _ and the boards _ and allowing
their offense to devolve into Ron Artest bullying his way to the
basket. Even a 14-2 run that briefly showed the familiar St. John's
spark was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Miami beat St. John's, 73-70, and moved into a tie for second
place in the Big East with the Red Storm, both at 8-3. Miami
improved to 14-5 overall, while St. John's fell to 17-6. St. John's
has lost three of its last four games and is 3-5 at the Garden this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Artest had 22 points, but he was miserable from the free-throw
line and missed one of two free throws that could have tied the
game in the closing seconds. Miami was led by Johnny Hemsley who
had 29 points, including a first-half run that seemed to stun St.
John's.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes entered the game needing a good health plan
almost as much as a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Michael Simmons was back at home still suffering
from a concussion sustained against Pittsburgh on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Jennings, a point guard-forward who left that Pittsburgh
game after just seconds with back spasms and who had not practiced
since, began the game on the bench. In fact, Miami, ranked No. 25
in the nation, had just eight scholarship players available.
</P>
<P>
   But they were enough to drive St. John's to one of its most
disjointed halves of the season. The Red Storm led, 19-9, with 11
minutes 50 seconds left in the first half, as Miami struggled with
its offense without Simmons, and it appeared that whatever funk
might have lingered after St. John's heartbreaking loss to
Connecticut Saturday would be wiped away by an exercise in revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Artest had claimed that at the end of Miami's victory earlier
this season, he saw players laughing and pointing at St. John's
players, and he vowed that things would be different this time.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis has pointed to that Miami game as the most lackadaisical
effort of St. John's season _ the only game when he has been
disappointed in his team _ and there was little in the rest of the
first half that could have pleased Jarvis. Playing a flat,
disorganized game, St. John's let Miami go on a 12-3 run _ Miami
coach Leonard Hamilton had inserted Jennings at the point with
18:02 left _ highlighted by eight points by Hemsley, who scored 18
in the first half. When Miami's pro prospect, Tim James, who had
been held scoreless for the first 13 minutes of the game by Artest,
finally scored, he tied the game, 27-27.
</P>
<P>
   A three-pointer by Erick Barkley gave St. John's the lead again.
A Lavor Postell steal gave St. John's a 3-on-1 break, but he missed
the layup. Barkley grabbed the offensive rebound _ a shocking
rarity for St. John's in the first half _ and put in the layup.
</P>
<P>
   But St. John's lack of power on the boards _ the Red Storm was
outrebounded, 23-14, in the first half, and even more unusually was
outhustled on the offensive boards, 8-3 _ which contributed to
another Miami run. The Hurricanes ran off nine straight points,
including five of James' 10 first-half points, and Miami took its
first lead of the game, 36-34, with 2:56 left.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a Bootsy Thornton three-pointer with 32 seconds left in
the half _ he had 10 points in the first half _ the Red Storm
trailed by 43-39 at halftime.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   St. John's senior forward TYRONE GRANT, who has not played since
he broke a bone in his right wrist against Seton Hall on Jan. 9,
will have the wrist re-evaluated Thursday. Even if the hard cast
Grant has worn since Jan. 19 is removed, it will likely take
several weeks for Grant to be ready to play again. Entering
Wednesday night's game, Grant was still the team's leading
rebounder, even though he had missed six games before Wednesday's
matchup against Miami. He had been averaging 11.5 points and 8.9
rebounds a game before the injury... . St. John's plays two
straight road games for the only time this season when it visits
Pittsburgh Saturday and West Virginia on Tuesday... . RON
ARTEST &UR;  &LR; was added to the list of 40 candidates for the John Wooden
award as the nation's best player.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
