<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUDER-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH GROUP PICKS CHAIRMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ronald S. Lauder was elected chairman of the largest umbrella
organization of American Jewish groups on Wednesday despite
questions about his close ties to Israel's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Lauder, the cosmetics heir and philanthropist, received the
support of 40 member organizations, with four abstentions and no
votes against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite what people might have read in the press, today's vote
showed the Jewish community's desire for unity and consensus,''
said Malcolm Hoenlein, the executive vice chairman of the umbrella
group, the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Wednesday's vote, nearly half the group's 55 members
had raised questions about whether Lauder had provided financial
support to Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   An article published last week by The Jewish Week in New York
and Haaretz in Israel, citing tax records and anonymous sources,
reported that Lauder had assisted Netanyahu in several ways, from
retaining an American campaign strategist to giving money to
right-wing causes in Israel. Foreign contributions to political
candidates are illegal under Israeli law, although indirect
donations are not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Lauder denied the allegations, and the conference's nominating
committee held an additional session with him on Monday to question
him about the reports. ``We felt he clearly answered the questions
that were posed,'' Hoenlein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
