<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0982 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTORS-UNIONS-ART-2T     02-03 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-UNIONS-ART-2TAKES(1,100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS, UNDER PRESSURE FROM HMO'S, ARE READY UNION RECRUITS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn., Calif., Del., Pa., La., Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
(dal) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As doctors grow angrier over managed care, the effort to
unionize physicians has sharply accelerated in recent months, with
more and more unions scrambling to recruit them and thousands of
doctors signing up.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a dozen unions _ including the International
Association of Machinists and the American Federation of Teachers _
are competing for them. Worried about being left out, even the
American Medical Association, long opposed to doctors' forming
unions, is setting up a unit to do collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians in New York, New Jersey, California, Connecticut and
at least 10 other states are moving to unionize at such a rate that
the number of doctors in unions is expected by labor experts to
grow by 15 percent or more each year. Already, medical experts
estimate, about 35,000 doctors, or 5 percent of the nation's
physicians, belong to unions, up from about 25,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As the trend gains momentum, HM0s are often fighting back by
asserting that doctors are independent contractors and therefore
not allowed to unionize. Hospitals that fear lower profits have
also fought unionization, and the Justice Department has opposed
one organizing effort on antitrust grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the union activity is among salaried staff doctors at
hospitals, both public and private. Unions for these physicians, as
well as residents and interns, are negotiating contracts with the
hospitals that cover wages, hours and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many doctors in private practice are joining
unions to give themselves more expertise and power when they
negotiate with HMOs. While most of the doctors are seeking help
with their own individual contracts, joining unions to get advice
on specific provisions in HMO agreements, others are pushing
increasingly to have unions bargain with HMOs on behalf of dozens
or even hundreds of practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 90 percent of the nation's physicians having at
least one contract with a managed care company, many doctors cite a
loss in their decision-making authority and a drop in
reimbursements in explaining why they want to join a union. Medical
experts expect the trend to gain further momentum because 80
percent of recent medical school graduates are taking salaried jobs
with HMOs, clinics or hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming geometrically accelerated,'' said Barry
Liebowitz, president of the Doctors Council, a union that
represents 3,400 doctors, most of them attending physicians at New
York City's municipal hospitals. ``Medicine has gone from a
mom-and-pop operation to corporatization, which has left the
provider, the doctor, out of medical decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   While a handful of doctors' unions have existed for decades, new
ones have formed in recent years and some have merged with much
larger, nonmedical unions. The Doctors Council is being wooed as a
merger partner by several million-member unions, including the
American Federation of Teachers, and is expected to make its
decision this month.
</P>
<P>
   But the push to unionize tens of thousands of additional doctors
faces several obstacles. One is the federal government. The
Department of Justice has filed an antitrust suit against a group
of doctors in Delaware, accusing them of conspiring to restrain
trade by joining a union and refusing to accept lower reimbursement
rates ordered by a managed-care organization.
</P>
<P>
   Also, under federal labor law, only workers classified as
employees have a right to form unions and bargain collectively.
This has many HMOs battling unionization by insisting that the
doctors who work for them are not employees, but independent
contractors with their own practices.
</P>
<P>
   In one battle, more than 500 New Jersey doctors doing work for
AmeriHealth Corp. say the HMO controls them to such a degree that
they should be declared part-time employees with a right to
unionize. In mid-January, the National Labor Relations Board's
office in Philadelphia completed weeks of hearings. It is expected
to release a decision later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at them as independent businessmen and contractors,''
said James Paynard, senior director for corporate communications at
AmeriHealth. ``They have their own contracts. They have their own
employees, and they run their own business. I don't see what
benefits patients would reap from the unionization of doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle is image: Many doctors believe unions are for
blue-collar workers, not professionals. And, having seen doctors
and interns strike several times in New York City since the early
1980s, many physicians say they believe going on strike would
violate the Hippocratic oath by denying care to patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand the pressure to do it, but as a physician, I
wouldn't think of joining a union,'' said Sheryl Sun, an internist
who opposes a unionization drive where she works, at the Kaiser
Permanente Clinic in Santa Clara, Calif. ``With a union, the
ultimate weapon is striking and that's something as a physician,
ethically, I'm never going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But doctors like Brian J. Moore, an internist in Bernardsville,
N.J., who supports the machinists in their push to organize 700
doctors in northern New Jersey, defend the role of unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way medicine is going right now and the way patients are
being treated by managed care is just terrible, and someone has to
stand up for proper health care,'' Moore said. ``I don't see a
physicians' union particularly like unions of the past, where we're
going to strike and carry placards. It's primarily to get the
message out that we have to improve health care.''
</P>
<P>
   One California doctor who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said he was considering joining a union because his HMO wanted him
to see eight patients an hour, limiting him to 7{ minutes per
visit. The doctors at 46 primary care clinics in the Medalia
HealthCare system in Washington State decided to unionize after the
HMO ordered many of them to schedule 36 hours of appointments each
week, up from 32 hours. The doctors said they did not have enough
time left for essential backup work, like completing paperwork,
analyzing lab results and calling HMO officials for various
approvals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managed care is bad for people, and it's bad for doctors, but
it's good for us as a union,'' said Robert Weinmann, president of
the Union of American Physicians and Dentists, a union with 5,000
members that is based in California. ``For us, it's the chief tool
for organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One bitter unionization struggle is taking place at Lincoln
Hospital in the Bronx. The unionization drive took off in July
1997, when hospital management laid off several dozen doctors and
the remaining physicians complained about shabby treatment and
being overworked. Tensions worsened when the hospital dismissed
four doctors. The union involved in the drive, United Salaried
Physicians and Dentists, said the doctors were fired for backing
the union; management said they were dismissed for insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Lincoln's 250 doctors voted to unionize, but the
ballots have been impounded pending the hospital's appeal to the
labor board, which is based on the premise that many doctors are
supervisors without a right to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   In their turn, unions are turning to Congress to pass
legislation that could accelerate unionizing by doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbed by the Justice Department's antitrust suit against the
doctors in Delaware, the American Medical Association and
traditional unions are pressing Congress to enact an antitrust
exemption that would let doctors band together to negotiate with
HMOs even when the doctors are considered independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   In Delaware last August, the Justice Department charged most of
the state's orthopedic surgeons with an illegal boycott and
conspiring to raise health care prices after they joined a union.
The doctors had dropped out of Blue Cross Blue Shield of Delaware,
saying they would not accept its reduced reimbursement rates. The
Justice Department asserted that their action forced consumers to
pay more for orthopedic services.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Seddon, executive director of the Federation of Physicians
and Dentists, the union the Delaware doctors joined, said, ``Here
you have an antitrust law that was passed to control Rockefellers
and Carnegies, but is being used against doctors trying to hold
onto their practices.''
</P>
<P>
   To skirt the antitrust barrier, many doctors are forming
independent practice associations, essentially large group
practices that allow physicians to bargain together with HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to tap doctor discontent over managed care, several
large, nonmedical-unions have moved aggressively over the past two
years to persuade doctors' unions to merge with them. Some smaller
doctors' unions have agreed to the mergers to take advantage of the
deep pockets the big unions have to finance organizing drives.
</P>
<P>
   The 9,000-member Committee of Interns and Residents, the
nation's oldest doctors' union, which was founded in 1957 in New
York City, merged with the 1.3 million-member Service Employees
International Union in 1997. And the Union of American Physicians
and Dentists, a 26-year-old, 5,000-member organization based in
Oakland, Calif., joined up in 1997 with the 1.3 million-member
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   Other major unions have joined the fray. In addition to the
machinists' union, which is trying to organize doctors in northern
New Jersey, the United Food and Commercial Workers union, which
normally represents supermarket workers, is recruiting the
AmeriHealth doctors in New Jersey. The Office and Professional
Employees International Union now has 10,000 podiatrists around the
nation as well as the 2,000 medical doctors from the MDNY health
maintenance group on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   And the AMA wants a piece of the action. ``We're moving full
speed ahead,'' said Dr. Donald Palmisano, a New Orleans surgeon on
the association's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA, which has about half the nation's 700,000 doctors as
members, is warning them not to sign up with other groups, saying
that if other members of those unions, like nurses' aides, strike
at a hospital, the doctors might be forced to honor the picket
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AMA believes it is preferable for physicians to form
independent bargaining units that are not affiliated with
traditional trade unions.'' Palmisano said. ``Physicians must not
engage in strike or any other tactic that interferes with patient
care.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Goodwin, who is the president of the office
employees union, said doctors should not look to the AMA for help
in bargaining: ``The AMA has not delivered for them and allowed
this managed care thing to get out of their control. Their fees
have dropped so tremendously over the last eight years, so now
they're reaching out to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors share the AMA's fears about strikes by physicians.
Such strikes are rare, but they have happened, for the most part in
New York City. In 1991, attending doctors at Woodhull Hospital in
Brooklyn walked out for a week, while the Committee of Interns and
Residents staged a nine-day strike in 1990 at Bronx-Lebanon
Hospital and a weeklong walkout in 1981 against seven city-owned
hospitals and two private hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The union said patient care hardly suffered because other
doctors covered or patients were moved to other hospitals. But
hospital officials said care was hurt badly and that the strikers
had violated their oaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of violation is it when the employer creates
conditions when you cannot take care of patients as best you can,
but can only pretend to do so?'' said Weinmann, president of the
Union of American Physicians and Dentists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that cause doctors to violate the Hippocratic oath? And
what about the insurance companies who don't take the oath and are
often cutting corners on providing appropriate care?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2215EST &QL; 
