<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-GOLDFISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE'S RULING FAVORS PEPPERIDGE FARM'S GOLDFISH OVER NABISCO'S 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The bottom line: the Goldfish won.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that could have broad ramifications for children's
lunches everywhere, a U.S. District judge in Manhattan ordered
Nabisco Inc. Wednesday not to sell a new line of crackers worth
millions of dollars because some of its shapes too closely
resembled Pepperidge Farm's Goldfish crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Shira A. Scheindlin also blocked Nabisco from beginning
its campaign next week to sell and promote the new product, called
CatDog, which included cheese crackers in the shape of fish, bones
and an unusual half-cat, half-dog character called CatDog, all part
of a tie-in with the Nickelodeon program of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco, which already has manufactured $3.4 million worth of
the CatDog brand crackers, said it would immediately appeal the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, Pepperidge Farm's attempt to keep our product off the
market smells rather fishy to us,'' said Hank Sandbach, a Nabisco
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   No CatDog crackers have been shipped to retailers yet, Nabisco
says.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperidge Farm, a division of the Campbell Soup Co., has sold
more than $500 million worth of Goldfish cracker products in the
United States over the last four years, the decision said. The
Goldfish product, measured in sales dollars, is the No. 1-ranking
cheese snack cracker in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperidge Farm said in a statement that the decision recognized
that it ``has carefully built the Goldfish shapes cracker into an
icon brand which consumers of all ages recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Pepperidge Farm told the judge that while adults buy
the Goldfish, it is usually at the urging of children. They argued
that Nabisco had chosen a fish-shaped product that would confuse
children and would also dilute the power of Pepperidge Farm's
famous brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many, many shapes around,'' Ethan Horwitz, a lawyer
for Pepperidge Farm, told the judge, and many ways in which Nabisco
could ``properly go after us within the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, they could not choose ``a fish that's almost
identical to ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco, which also makes Ritz, Cheese Nips, Triscuits and
Oreos, contended that it had not infringed on the Goldfish brand
and that Pepperidge Farm's fish shape should not be legally
protectable.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Scheindlin decided that Pepperidge Farm had not proven
that Nabisco's CatDog product would confuse Goldfish devotees, but
she concluded that CatDog would blur and harm the Goldfish brand.
</P>
<P>
   Although the case turned on modern-day principles of
intellectual property law, in court last week Judge Scheindlin
allowed lawyers for Pepperidge Farm to introduce evidence the
old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to pour it into a bowl, if that's all right with
you, Your Honor,'' Horwitz said, holding a box of Goldfish
crackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, pour it into a bowl,'' the judge ordered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GUN-SUIT-NYT &LR;      02-03 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUN-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS ASSAIL GUN COMPANIES IN CLOSING ARGUMENTS OF TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers for relatives of six people killed with
illegally obtained handguns presented closing arguments Wednesday
in a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, saying that 25 gun
manufacturers were liable for the slayings because ``negligent
marketing'' practices ``put the guns into the hands of the
shooters.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers held that it did not matter which companies actually
made the guns used in the killings, because the distribution
practices of all the companies fostered widespread illegal
trafficking in their products, creating a ``toxic waste flow'' of
illicitly available guns.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the manufacturers presented a sharply different
view of the month's worth of testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to hold manufacturers of legitimately produced products
responsible for the acts of these outlaws'' _ those who trafficked
illegally in guns and those who pulled the triggers _ is ``simply
wrong,'' one of the industry lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Contending that the plaintiffs' case was built on ``smoke and
generalities,'' the lawyer, James Dorr, told the jury that the
plaintiffs had presented ``no evidence that negligence by any
manufacturer was the proximate cause of these shootings.'' And he
asserted that their collective-liability theory was the equivalent
of holding all automakers liable for an injury caused by a drunken
driver in one car.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was brought by the slaying victims' relatives and a
seventh person who was severely wounded with an illegally obtained
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say it is the first suit to come to trial that
charged that industrywide negligent distribution by the nation's
gun producers made them collectively liable for shootings with guns
that they had legally made and sold but that ended up in the hands
of criminals, youths and others not authorized to have them.
</P>
<P>
   The jury was expected to begin deliberating Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is being watched across the country because the
plaintiffs' argument is similar to contentions in lawsuits that
Chicago and other cities have recently filed, or plan to file,
against the gun industry, much as states have sued the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The seven shootings at issue in the Brooklyn trial took place in
the New York City area in 1993 and 1994 and involved robberies,
disputes and, apparently, one accident. A lawyer for the
plaintiffs, Denise Dunleavy, suggested varying amounts of damages
for the plaintiffs, should the jury find the companies liable. The
suggestions ranged from several hundred thousand dollars for the
mother of one victim to as much as ``7, 8, 10 million'' for Steven
Fox, a Queens teen-ager who survived the apparently accidental
shooting with a bullet still in his brain.
</P>
<P>
   In only one of the seven shootings was a gun recovered, but
another plaintiffs' lawyer, Elisa Barnes, told the jurors that ``it
simply doesn't matter because in this illegal market, all the guns
are the same.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled that economic and statistical consultants for her
side had testified that 90 percent of handguns used in crimes in
New York state in recent years had originally been sold in other
states, often Southern states with weaker gun control laws. She
held that the manufacturers had regularly oversupplied dealers in
the states with weak gun laws and that many of the excess guns
ended up in the hands of illegal traffickers, who resold them in
states with strong laws, like New York.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Dorr, the defense lawyer, recalled testimony in
which an economist had charged that the oversupply argument was
based on flawed statistics. He told the jurors that ``there is no
oversupply'' of guns to various states and that the criminal
trafficking across state lines ``is not connected to anything in
the lawful marketing'' by the gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, he said, cooperate as much as they can with law
enforcement agencies in fighting illegal trafficking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
