A0986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREYLINGHUSEN-PROFILE     02-03 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREYLINGHUSEN-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRELINGHUYSEN FOR EVERY IMPEACHMENT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   History won't leave the Frelinghuysens alone.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Rep. Rodney P. Frelinghuysen of New Jersey, a
moderate Republican, voted to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, his father, Peter H.B. Frelinghuysen, who was also a
moderate Republican representative from New Jersey, called for the
resignation of Richard M. Nixon as the president faced certain
impeachment by the House.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1868, Rodney Frelinghuysen's great-great-grandfather,
Sen. Frederick Theodore Frelinghuysen, a radical Republican from
New Jersey, voted to convict President Andrew Johnson in his Senate
trial after Johnson was impeached by the House.
</P>
<P>
   In short, if a president faces impeachment, a Frelinghuysen is
on hand, although no doubt Johnson, Nixon and Clinton wished the
Frelinghuysens had been somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been around a long time,'' said Rodney Frelinghuysen,
the present heir of one of America's most enduring political
dynasties. Although each impeachment case was different _ and only
Peter went against his party _ both Rodney and Frederick spoke of
the process as duty.
</P>
<P>
   (Frederick, 1868: ``Walking along this narrow pathway, with
perils on either side, one is only secure as he rests his hand on
the firm support of duty.'' Rodney, 1998: ``Members of Congress
have a duty to consider President Clinton's conduct . . . we should
not change course now simply because we are all tired of the
scandal or because polls reflect the president as popular and
impeachment as not.'')
</P>
<P>
   Frelinghuysen said he didn't consult his ancestor's speech
before making his own, meaning that the common theme of duty could
be the result of the family Zeitgeist, standard political rhetoric,
or both. In any case, it was probably inevitable that three
Frelinghuysens should judge three trouble-prone presidents, given
that there have been Frelinghuysens in Congress for 50 of its 210
years.
</P>
<P>
   The family produced four U. S. senators, although no major
legislation with the family name. One of the senators, Frederick
Theodore, became secretary of state under President Chester A.
Arthur. Another, Frederick, was a colonel in the Revolutionary War
and fought at the battles of Trenton, Princeton and Monmouth. The
first Frelinghuysen in America was Theodorus Jacobus, a Dutch
Reformed Church evangelist who in 1720 settled in what is now the
horse country of Somerset County, N.J. _ a part of Rep.
Frelinghuysen's district today.
</P>
<P>
   Does the current Frelinghuysen in Congress feel burdened by the
family legacy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't,'' he said on Tuesday in his office on Capitol Hill.
``Either I would have embraced it, or I would have rebelled. And I
chose to somewhat embrace it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frelinghuysen is 52, agreeable and cautious, and you might not
hear him come into a room, although on Tuesday he had on a bright
red tie with skunks and badgers that was given to him by his wife.
His voting record in favor of mass transit for commuters and
wetlands preservation puts him exactly where most New Jersey voters
want him. He was first elected in 1994, is on the Appropriations
Committee and has a low profile on Capitol Hill. He has wanted to
be a member of Congress since he was 6, when he sat on his father's
lap on the floor of the House and campaigned with him in the
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father could never remember anybody's name,'' Frelinghuysen
said. ``And he used to say, `You go over there and get something to
eat, and when you come back I'll have figured out who everybody is,
and I can introduce you.' So my first job was to get something to
eat, and give my father some elbow room.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frelinghuysens have their roots in what is now the affluent
suburb of Morristown _ Frelinghuysen has known a fellow moderate
Republican from the neighboring horse country, Gov. Christine Todd
Whitman, all his life _ but Frelinghuysen himself grew up largely
in Washington during his father's 22 years in Congress. He lived in
the heart of the city's establishment in Georgetown, in the large
1799 federal brick house now owned by Sally Quinn and Benjamin C.
Bradlee, the former editor of The Washington Post. Frelinghuysen
went to school at St. Albans along with Vice President Al Gore,
then to boarding school at St. Mark's and to Hobart College.
</P>
<P>
   His main departure from the traditional path came after college
graduation, in 1969, when he was drafted. He served with the Army's
93rd Engineer Battalion in the Mekong Delta, and remembers it with
bitterness: ``We were the group that built the roads by day that
the Vietcong traveled at night.'' He also formed clear opinions
about his commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember when President Nixon basically said, `All
troops have been withdrawn from the delta.' And I said, `Wait, I'm
still here.' I had never had a particularly warm feeling about
Richard Nixon, and it didn't get any warmer after my service.''
</P>
<P>
   Frelinghuysen said he voted to impeach President Clinton not
under pressure from the Republican leadership, but because he
thought the president had lied to the grand jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
