<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PHILANTHROPY-NYT     02-03 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHILANTHROPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE COUPLE'S BEQUESTS ARE WINDFALL FOR BROOKLYN INSTITUTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Neb., Pa.)  (bl)  
By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For several months, administrators, teachers,
students and alumni of Polytechnic University in Brooklyn have been
debating a pleasant problem: how to spend $175 million. There are
proposals for 25 new professorships and plans for a new dormitory,
or a new academic building, or both. The graduate program may be
radically changed.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is final, and there is plenty of disagreement, but for a
university that once faced bankruptcy, the possibilities are
stunning. Maybe too stunning. Echoing a concern shared by many at
Polytechnic over how best to spend the millions, provost Ivan
Frisch said simply: ``Now comes really the hardest part. Where does
the money go?''
</P>
<P>
   It is a question reverberating across the borough. Like a heavy
snow in an unexpected place, money fell on Brooklyn last month, a
whole lot of it. Five institutions, none accustomed to lavish
donations, will receive almost half of the $750 million estate of a
Brooklyn Heights couple whose quiet lives gave no hint of their
enormous wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Othmer, a Polytechnic professor who died in 1995, and his
wife, Mildred, who died last April, began investing in the 1960s
with a hometown friend from Omaha named Warren Buffett. Buffett is
now one of the world's richest people. The Othmers did nicely, too.
</P>
<P>
   Without children and with few relatives, the Othmers bequeathed
most of their fortune to the institutions that shaped their lives,
in Brooklyn and beyond. Their alma mater, the University of
Nebraska at Lincoln, will receive $133 million. Planned Parenthood
in Manhattan, where Mrs. Othmer sat on the board, will get $65
million. The Chemical Heritage Foundation in Philadelphia will
receive more than $100 million to build a library in Othmer's
field, chemical engineering.
</P>
<P>
   But no place will feel the money as much as Brooklyn. The bulk
of the donations arrived in January at the five beneficiaries, all
important institutional pillars of the borough and all financially
needy. Consider that the five _ Polytechnic, Long Island College
Hospital, the Brooklyn Historical Society, the Plymouth Church of
the Pilgrims and the Brooklyn Botanic Garden _ will receive more
than $340 million. By comparison, if Brooklyn's application to
become an empowerment zone is approved, the federal benefits will
total $330 million.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the institutions realize that such a large donation
will probably never come again, so the challenge is to turn the
money into what Polytechnic officials call ``a transforming gift.''
Officials of Plymouth Church of the Pilgrims simply consider it a
gift from God. Once the church where Henry Ward Beecher preached
against slavery, Plymouth Church is now one of a dwindling number
of Congregational churches in New York. The Othmers sat in the same
pew every Sunday, and Mrs. Othmer left the church $10.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the Brooklyn Botanic Garden, all of the
recipients knew they were included in Mrs. Othmer's will. Some,
like Polytechnic and Long Island College Hospital, had already
received large chunks of money when Othmer died four years ago.
Judith Zuk, president of the botanic garden, said Mrs. Othmer had
volunteered at plant sales, but had done nothing more. Ms. Zuk
confessed she had never heard of Mrs. Othmer until she learned
about the $9.9 million she left the garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're absolutely elated,'' Ms. Zuk said. The money will be
placed in the botanic garden's $20 million endowment, generating
additional interest income that should increase the annual
operating budget by $400,000. Among the ideas for the money are
school-based gardening programs and training for public-school
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   If the other four institutions knew that money was on the way,
they were still pleasantly surprised when they learned how much.
Long Island College Hospital, the Brooklyn Historical Society and
Polytechnic all needed money.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the Othmers had donated $1 million toward
construction of the Othmer Cancer Center at Long Island College
Hospital, where Othmer had been on the board. But John Wren, the
hospital's board chairman, said Long Island College had had several
budget deficits. Taking bequests from both of the Othmer wills, the
hospital will receive about $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   Its interim president, Peter Kelly, said interest income from
the Othmer money will pay for technological upgrades. Money is also
intended for the nursing program and the operating rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In its landmark building in Brooklyn Heights, the historical
society has a vast, cluttered archive of maps, books and real
estate records, as well as exhibits about Brooklyn past and
present. But if the building is the society's treasure, it is also
a problem: the roof leaks, the elevator doors open between the
first and second floors, and the heating system was last upgraded
in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime board member, Othmer had contributed money to the
society in the past, and the library is named for the couple. But
now, with almost $15 million from Mrs. Othmer's will, the
historical society will close this month and reopen in early 2001
to undergo a $14 million renovation. The city has pledged $4.1
million toward the project, and the historical society has also
begun a three-year fund-raising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While an undetermined amount of Othmer money will go to the
project, Carol Clark, the Brooklyn Historical Society's new
president, said much of it will pay to enhance the library, to
expand educational programs and to create a permanent museum
exhibition entitled, ``Brooklyn Works.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Polytechnic, where Othmer made his name as a
chemical engineering professor, inventor and consultant who became
famous in his field as a co-author of the Kirk-Othmer Encyclopedia
of Chemical Technology. In its post-World War II heyday,
Polytechnic was a leader in microwave technology, aerospace
technology and fields like polymer chemistry. But in the 1970s, the
university nearly went bankrupt, having fallen behind rivals like
Carnegie-Mellon University.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators believe that the Othmer money could change all
that. The gift has prompted an ambitious planning and fund-raising
effort _ $52 million has been pledged so far _ by the university in
an attempt to reinvent itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to use it wisely, we recognize that,'' said Richard S.
Thorsen, Polytechnic's vice president of development. ``It secures
the financial future of the university. But we want to do much more
than that. It's an opportunity to really break out.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot is tentatively planned. A large if undetermined sum will
go into the endowment. There are also plans to renovate the
academic building, Rogers Hall; to build a second academic
building, and to erect the university's first dormitory. Thorsen
said Polytechnic may create 25 new professorships, costing $1.5
million to $2.5 million each. As many as 50 endowed scholarships
are under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Frisch, the provost, predicted big changes in the curriculum.
Some master's programs may be phased out. New programs in
telecommunications and biotechnology will probably be created, as
well as a continuing education program, a potentially profitable
endeavor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
