<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WELFARE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE INVESTIGATORS FIND WELFARE DELAYS IN CITY
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ Posing as poor people, state health investigators
visited eight welfare offices in New York City last week and found
that four of the offices failed to promptly provide Medicaid
applications as required by federal law, state officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, city workers must distribute Medicaid
applications ``without delay.'' But at the four welfare offices,
the workers told the undercover investigators that they would have
to return on another day to receive the forms, state officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we have concerns about what we have found,'' John
Signor, a spokesman for the State Department of Health, said
Wednesday. ``We're going to continue monitoring the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The state investigators made their visits the day after a
federal judge ruled that city welfare workers were improperly
denying applications for Medicaid and food stamps to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 25, the judge, William H. Pauley 3rd of U.S. District
Court in Manhattan, ordered the city to guarantee prompt access to
the applications. He also temporarily blocked the city from
converting any more of its welfare offices into ``job centers,''
where workers discourage the poor from applying for public
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the order, the city must produce a plan this month to
correct the problems. City officials have already vowed to retrain
hundreds of welfare workers, revise applications and post signs
clearly outlining the public's rights to government benefits. But
the problems uncovered by the investigators suggest that legal
violations continue to occur, even though city officials have
already begun training workers and posting signs.
</P>
<P>
   City welfare officials said Wednesday they could not comment on
the investigation because they had not been provided with
information about the findings.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for the poor said they were particularly concerned
that state investigators discovered such problems so soon after the
judge issued his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really saddens me that this continues after all we've been
through in the courts,'' said Helen Lee, a staff lawyer at the
Legal Aid Society, which filed the class-action lawsuit that
resulted in Pauley's ruling. ``This is something we need to fix
right away. We're talking about people's lives here.''
</P>
<P>
   In court hearings before the ruling, Pauley also criticized
state officials for failing to carefully monitor the city's
compliance with federal laws.
</P>
<P>
   That complaint has been echoed by officials from the federal
Health Care Financing Administration, which began an inquiry seven
months ago to determine, in part, whether state officials were
properly overseeing the city's Medicaid operations. During the
court hearing, a federal health official noted that state officials
had repeatedly failed to provide proof that they were monitoring
the city as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   City officials had said the problems were isolated, the
inevitable growing pains of a program created 10 months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0485 </DOCNO>
