<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-MODELS-NYT &LR;      02-03 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MODELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: MIFFED MODELS: QUIT POUTING AND ORGANIZE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fashion models in New York are hurting, and no one
feels their pain.
</P>
<P>
   The rage in fashion magazines is for covers featuring actresses
and celebrities like Courteney Cox, Michelle Pfeiffer, Oprah
Winfrey and Hillary Rodham Clinton. Editors find that these covers
sell better than ones featuring models' faces. They also find
celebrities, even movie stars, easier to work with than models.
</P>
<P>
   So there's mewling on Seventh Avenue (``The Models Are Angry''
was one recent headline) as the industry ponders the awful question
raised last week by Conor Kennedy, a booker at Company Models: ``If
magazines are making such an effort to feature Gwyneth Paltrow over
and over again, well, what happens to the next generation of Linda
Evangelistas?''
</P>
<P>
   The public's answer thus far has been a resounding: Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   As victims, miffed supermodels rank on the sympathy scale just
above Arab princes whining over low oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   But with a little effort, the models might be able to win
sympathy here on their home turf as they struggle against the
competition from Hollywood. Cover girls, after all, are one of New
York's major businesses, and the city's politicians have
traditionally provided help to any local industry that complains
loud enough.
</P>
<P>
   If millionaire stockbrokers and athletes and taxicab-fleet
owners are entitled to special treatment, why not supermodels?
Workers of Seventh Avenue, unite! You have nothing to lose but your
pouts!
</P>
<P>
   Start by forming the SOS (Save Our Supermodels) Committee and
make enough campaign contributions to get a public hearing in the
City Council. Then tearfully tell of your shattered dreams (``I,
like, had to finish high school!'') and economic hardships (``You
know, I had to pay for this dress'').
</P>
<P>
   Give testimony about ``totally unfair competition'' from
celebrities, but avoid lines like ``Excuse me, Oprah is such a
whale'' and ``That Hillary cover _ hello, total airbrush!'' Also to
be avoided: ``I mean, Courteney Cox, she's got to be 30.'' While
testifying, try not to fling your hair back while staring blankly
into the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Hire a consultant to calculate the tens of billions of dollars
generated by models for the New York economy. Count not merely the
revenues of the modeling agencies but also the money spent on
flowers, dinner, nightclubs, jewelry and cars by men pursuing
models. Include a generous ``multiplier effect'' in the
calculations _ say, two investment bankers and one real estate
developer per model.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to include the revenues of the garment industry,
which stands to lose sales because of the ineptness of amateur
models. Stress the endless hours of training to acquire the skills
needed for a grueling cover shoot. Demonstrate how a veteran runway
model can increase sales by knowing how to ``work a dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Stress the safety risks of using celebrity models. Illustrate
how easily an amateur can start a fire by knocking over a
photographer's light. Point out that fashion-show runways are
simply not designed to support the weight of modern-day celebrities
(again, do not mention Oprah by name). Sound bite: ``Celebrity
models are a tragedy waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand tax breaks. Urge the mayor to reserve curb space downtown
for models' Town Cars and to include a fashion stadium in his West
Side sports complex. Above all, advocate a new city agency: the
Fashion Models Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Taxi and Limousine Commission, the FMC would license
all working models and require them to display a medallion during
photo shoots. The courts might not allow the FMC to ban celebrities
from modeling, but it could achieve the same effect by mandating a
long apprenticeship and test. (Sample questions: What is the
private line for reservations at Balthazar? How often do you need a
glycolic facial peel?)
</P>
<P>
   If all this seems too complicated, there is a simpler solution
that requires no legislation: join the teamsters. The union could
easily negotiate contracts that prevent celebrities from ever
posing again, and there would be one fringe benefit. Once New
York's fashion editors tried conducting a photo shoot while a
veteran shop steward enforced the teamsters' work rules, no one
would ever complain again about models being difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
