<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOOK TO SLOW DOWN SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ That fast tempo promised and/or threatened by
first-year coach Chris Ford may have to begin at a trot.
</P>
<P>
   `I don't think we can get into a shootout with them,` said Ford
of his team's date for Friday's season-opener.
</P>
<P>
   `Them` refers to the Phoenix Suns, who will sprint into the
Sports Arena with a mighty 116.5 points-per-game scoring average in
two exhibition victories over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   `We have to play some semblance of defense,` said Ford, who does
not hesitate when identifying the main target of Clipper
basket-protection tactics. `Our number one concern is Jason Kidd's
ability to dominate the game with the basketball.`
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, now beginning his fifth NBA season, averaged 11.6 points
per game and shot just 42 percent from the field for the Suns last
season. Not much domination there, right?
</P>
<P>
   That's because Kidd's seminal skill is the precision pass, which
typically arrives at the end of a frantic open-court burst. The
former Cal star was second in the league in assists-per-game last
season at 9.1.
</P>
<P>
   `He goes 100 miles per hour for 48 minutes,` said Darrick
Martin, the Clipper responsible for staying between Kidd and the
hoop. `You just try to contain him as much as possible and kind of
funnel him into help.`
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to be the scheme under construction during most of
the team's Wednesday-morning workout at Veterans Park SportsComplex
in Carson. Some of the aforementioned help could come from the
shot-blocking potential of rookie center Michael Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   Ford says the NBA's top draft pick - who began practicing with
the team last Sunday -- will play, but won't start.
</P>
<P>
   `I don't think I'll put that pressure on him right now,` Ford
said. `I'll put him out there and give him a shot and see how we
all react. The better he plays, the longer he'll stay out there.`
</P>
<P>
   subhead Ex-Rebel helps his cause
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone Nesby, the rookie free agent from UNLV, continues to
shine in team scrimmages.
</P>
<P>
   `He backs down to no one,` Ford said. `I would not hesitate to
use him early. He brings us so much energy out there. It'll be
interesting to see how he does against NBA competition on a nightly
basis.`
</P>
<P>
   Against Continental Basketball Association competition this
season, the 6-6 forward averged just 16.8 minutes per game, but
still scored at a 9.8 clip. Despite his ability to penetrate,
elevate and finish in style, Nesby's field-goal percentage was only
43 percent. His quantum leap in Clipper camp has been abetted by
assistant coach Rex Kalamian, who convinced the young forward to
alter the trajectory in his flat-line jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   During one shooting drill with Kalamian, this new arch deluxe
helped Nesby make 25 perimeter shots in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead Pain still gaining
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's arthroscopy on the left knee of rookie Brian Skinner
has been judged a success. The power forward from Baylor will begin
rehabilitation today and is expected to be out 2-3 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent point guard Scott Brooks will be out 6-8 weeks,
thanks to a right-knee injury sustained last Friday in a collision
with Laker Elden Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Two more Clippers - reserve center Keith Closs and backup guard
James `Hollywood` Robinson - were held out of Wednesday drills due
to sore knees.
</P>
<P>
   A bum hamstring could cause Phoenix shooting guard Rex Chapman
to miss Friday's opener.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
