<SLUG> BC-TIMESSQUARE-RECRUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPS FOR LANDMARK: TIMES SQUARE RECRUITING BOOTH TORN DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ It was a Cold War-era relic smack in the middle of
Times Square's swirling orb of kinetic neon, but in the end
everyone seemed to want a piece of the Armed Forces Recruiting
Station before it was smashed to pieces on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After a somber pause to allow television news cameras onto the
spit of asphalt at Broadway and 43rd Street, construction workers
armed with power saws and crowbars began ripping down the most
popular _ and arguably the ugliest _ military recruiting station in
the nation. By this time next week, the building's musty remains
will have been unceremoniously buried in some out-of-state
landfill.
</P>
<P>
   By July, the old 400-square-foot station will have been replaced
by a brash new 500-square-foot station, costing roughly $1 million,
designed to fit in with Times Square's futuristic milieu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad because that's the only place you can remember how
it was 40 years ago,'' said Constantinos Poniros, watching his son,
George, the site's demolition manager, supervise the dismantling.
The elder Poniros planned to take a six-foot section of stainless
steel from the station's exterior back home to New Jersey as a
keepsake.
</P>
<P>
   In the 49 years since it opened, the station forged a special
reputation. It was the only outpost to house recruiters from all
four military branches. It was the only station that could reject
far more recruits than it enlisted _ more than 200 a year signed up
_ and still claim top honors in recruiting circles. And it was the
only recruiting station in the country without a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to go to the NYPD across the street, and the
restaurants,'' said Staff Sgt. Armando Diaz, the last Air Force
recruiter to work in the cramped station. ``I won't miss that.''
</P>
<P>
   The booth, as recruiters called it, also became a
stainless-steel magnet for protesters of wars in Vietnam and Iraq
and of the military's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy toward gay
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The booth's smoked glass windows and lusterless stainless steel
was considered slick in 1950 when it replaced an earlier recruiting
office built in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   The new station will feature American flags burning in red,
white and blue neon on the east- and west-side exterior walls. A
giant, nine-panel television screen, affixed to the north wall,
will spread the military's message to passers-by. Phosphorescent
poles (also in blazing red, white and blue) will fan out from the
station for the benefit of nighttime drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be high-tech,'' said Peter Shugert, a spokesman for
the Army Corps of Engineers, which is supervising the project. ``It
will have all the modern conveniences.'' And, he added, unlike the
shack now being demolished, ``It will have running water.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
