<HEADLINE>
HALF-BROTHER GETS A SHARE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Neb., Ind., Calif.) (With NY-PHILANTHROPY) 
 (bl) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Mildred Topp Othmer left $2 million in her will
for any ``sisters of mine, nieces of mine and children of such
nieces,'' there was no mention of a brother. Mrs. Othmer, the
second of three sisters, never had one.
</P>
<P>
   Or did she?
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, after the $750 million estate left by Mrs. Othmer
and her husband, Donald, became national news, an unexpected claim
was made. Alphonso Axel Ernie Topp Jr. had never met Mrs. Othmer,
but he believed that she was his half-sister.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer asserted that Topp was entitled to a share of the
estate, as were his 8 daughters and their 11 children.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, everyone got something. The institutions to which
Mrs. Othmer gave most of her money got more than $526 million. Her
niece in Omaha _ who, like Topp, challenged the will _ received
$17,640,909.90. Topp, a retired Army colonel in California, got
$2.4 million. His 8 daughters and their 11 children got $90,909.09
each.
</P>
<P>
   But is Topp really Mrs. Othmer's half-brother? Interviewed by
phone in California, Topp, 78, said he learned of Mrs. Othmer only
after his father died in 1965. On a visit to Denmark, where his
father was born, he said relatives told him that his father had
married and divorced in Omaha before he was born.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Mrs. Othmer's parents divorced in March 1919,
and her father, Holger Topp, disappeared. Friends of Mrs. Othmer
say she never heard from him again. Perhaps he went to Indiana. In
June 1919, a man named Alfonse A. Topp was married in Indianapolis.
This couple had one child, Alphonso Axel Ernie Topp Jr. When the
senior Topp applied for citizenship in 1942, he listed Holger as a
middle name.
</P>
<P>
   So are Holger Topp and Alphonso A. Topp Sr. the same man? ``The
parties decided that Topp's claim had some merit and were willing
to settle,'' said Theodore Wagner, the Othmers' estate tax lawyer.
``Most of the lawyers involved believe he probably is related.''
</P>
<P>
   But is he entitled to money from a woman he never knew? Thomas
Dahlk of Omaha, Topp's lawyer, said, ``It's the law.'' Topp said he
made his claim to help his grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
