<SLUG> BC-NJ-LAW-FIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIO JOINS AN INFLUENTIAL NEW YORK FIRM 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.J., Pa.)  By RONALD SMOTHERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ In an effort to extend its influence into New
Jersey, where it believes that the law business is booming, the
politically connected New York City law firm of Fischbein Badillo
Wagner Harding has acquired the law firm of former Gov. Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Florio's 13-lawyer firm, Florio &AMP; Perrucci, which is based in
Piscataway with offices in Philadelphia and business in his native
southern New Jersey, will be absorbed into Fischbein Badillo, a
103-lawyer firm whose partners include Herman Badillo and Raymond
Harding, both firms' principals said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo is a former Democratic congressman and deputy mayor of
New York City who became a Republican last June. Harding is the
chairman of New York state's Liberal Party. Both have close ties to
Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   In joining the powerful Manhattan firm, Florio, a Democrat,
follows Burton B. Roberts, the former Bronx district attorney and
chief administrative judge of State Supreme Court in the Bronx, who
signed on as a partner last week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Florio was named chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank
of New York on Tuesday, he said he would still practice law.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, Michael Perrucci and Joseph Bock of the New Jersey firm
will become partners in the consolidated law firm, although their
names will not be added to the title yet, Richard S. Fischbein, the
firm's senior partner, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fischbein Badillo's strengths are in trade, labor and employment
law as well as commercial and real estate matters and litigation.
Florio, an author of the nation's Superfund law while in Congress,
has worked extensively in environmental, international and
employment law.
</P>
<P>
   Both Florio and Fischbein were sanguine about the political
chemistry that might result from the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not hurtful that this expands all of our philosophical
bases and it will make for good discussions at lunches,'' Fischbein
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2238EST &QL; 
