</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAHARA SURVIVAL 101: OVERHEATEING BLAMED FOR ILLNESS AT SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The students at Intermediate School 135 in the Bronx,
which had been closed since Friday after about 80 pupils and
teachers mysteriously became sick there, returned to school
Wednesday. The children seemed fine, but some of their parents were
sick with worry.
</P>
<P>
   City school officials believe that excessive heat in many
classrooms was the likely cause of the widespread illness, which
left students and staff members complaining of dizziness, pain and
vomiting. But several parents said they were dissatisfied with that
explanation and complained to Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, who
made a brief visit to the school at 2441 Wallace Ave. in Bronxdale,
about his decision to reopen it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upset,'' Sarah Siegel, the president of the Parents'
Association, said to the chancellor. ``By right these children
should not be in the school today.'' Crew said he disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Spence, the Board of Education's deputy chancellor for
operations, said Wednesday that a number of city agencies and
representatives of the United Federation of Teachers conducted
environmental tests at the school over the weekend, which did not
yield any conclusive results. ``To date, we cannot find a single
possible toxic cause,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spence said officials believe that excessive heat and low
humidity, perhaps laced with a tiny amount of hydrogen sulfide from
the heating system, may have caused the illness.
</P>
<P>
   Spence said that 60 of the school's 80 thermostats were not
working, and failed to cut off heat entering many classrooms even
though they were warm enough, and that some classroom's windows did
not open. Temperatures in many classrooms last week reached 85 or
90 degrees, he said, while the humidity was less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a school that's so hot and dry it's like the
Sahara,'' he said. The three classrooms that had generated the most
complaints of symptoms will stay closed through the week so that
testing can continue, Spence said, adding that five or six people
would remain at the school with testing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   At the school Wednesday, Crew said he had decided to reopen most
classrooms because he believed they were safe. ``Every precaution
has been taken so far to make sure the problems we had will not be
repeated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Siegel, the PTA president, and several other parents who
had come to the school for a briefing by health officials,
scientists, epidemiologists and Board of Education representatives
said they had kept their children home yesterday. The school's
attendance, which is usually 90 percent or more, was at 73 percent
Wednesday, the school principal, Dr. Carole Valentino, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not safe,'' said Noelia Hernandez, whose son, Miguel, is
in the sixth grade. ``I'm going to keep my son home until we know
for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents said the briefing provided little new information,
and if they did not get answers they would insist that their
children be transferred. The Board of Education said such requests
were unlikely to be granted.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Valentino said she supported the chancellor's decision.
``In my heart today I really wanted to open the school,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The children, meanwhile, were of mixed opinions _ often
mirroring those of their parents. Katrina Lajqi, a 12-year-old in
sixth grade, said she had come for the meeting Wednesday, but did
not attend school and would not Thursday, either. ``They should
just leave the school closed today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hector Algarin, 12, said he was eager to return to school
and was not worried about getting sick. He said he hoped that
reducing the temperature in the building might alleviate the
headaches he often got in school.
</P>
<P>
   And the school did manage to turn the crisis into an educational
opportunity: Accompanied by guidance counselors, environmental
investigators went from classroom to classroom, demonstrating how
to test for carbon dioxide and poison (there was none) in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids loved it,'' Dr. Valentino said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
