<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION TO SUE NEW YORK CITY OVER WORKFARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ District Council 37, the giant union representing
120,000 city workers, plans to sue the Giuliani administration
Thursday, accusing it of violating state law by using thousands of
workfare recipients to do tasks once done by full-time city
workers, union officials said on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Several union officials said the city's use of more than 6,000
workfare recipients to rake leaves, pick up trash and do other jobs
in parks violated a law that bars communities from using workfare
workers to do work once done by city employees.
</P>
<P>
   The suit represents a reversal for the council, because its
former executive director, Stanley Hill, was accommodating to the
city's rapid expansion of its workfare program, the nation's
largest. With more than 35,000 workers, the program requires
welfare recipients to do numerous jobs to receive their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who supported Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani in the 1997
election, had to step aside after the Manhattan district attorney
undertook an investigation into kickbacks, embezzlement and vote
fraud at the union.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Saunders, the trustee for the council appointed in December
by its parent union, the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees, has said he planned to take a tougher approach
to the administration than Hill did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor and the union had a meeting, and they made clear
they disagree,'' said a senior union official who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. ``This just suggests that where there's a
difference in approach, the union will part company and take the
action it needs to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the lawsuit, to be filed in state Supreme
Court in Manhattan, would seek an injunction barring workfare
recipients from doing jobs once done by city workers.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1990, nonadministrative employment in the Parks
Department dropped to less than 1,200 from nearly 2,800, while the
number of workfare employees in the parks jumped to more than
6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Cohan, director of litigation at the Welfare Law Center, an
advocacy group, applauded the district council's lawsuit, asserting
that workfare pulls down the wages of unionized workers. ``We're
delighted that the union is working to protect its members,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
