A1007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-KIDS-POVERTY-ART-N     02-03 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KIDS-POVERTY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISE IN NEW YORK CITY CHILDREN WHO ARE BORN INTO POVERTY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
(dal) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite an improving economy in New York, more than
half of the city's children are born into poverty, according to a
report released Wednesday by a children's advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   More than 66,000 of the nearly 127,000 children born in New York
City in 1996, or about 52.2 percent, were born to families with
incomes under the federal poverty level of $23,000 a year for a
family of three, the 216-page report said. The percentage of
children born into poverty was the highest ever, surpassing 51.7
percent in 1994 and 39 percent in 1990, according to the report,
which was prepared by the Citizens' Committee for Children of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the rise were not clear, the group said. But the
report noted that there were worsening situations in related areas,
which include an increase in the number of homeless children and a
decline in the number of children reading at grade level, which
point to spending cutbacks at city agencies like the Department of
Homeless Services and the Administration for Children's Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data paint a very alarming picture,'' said Gail Nayowith,
executive director of the Citizens' Committee. ``There's a
relationship between government spending and outcomes, whether it's
the number of children living in poverty or reading at grade level.
You get what you pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   The group said that there have been spending cuts in four out of
19 city agencies that serve children, including a 16.7 percent drop
in spending at the homeless-services department from fiscal 1994 to
1998, to $378 million from $454 million.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha I. Lugo, a spokeswoman for Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani,
declined to comment on specific points in the Citizens' Committee
report. In a prepared statement, she said: ``This administration is
proud of its record in regard to children. In funds combined, we
have spent more money on children than any other administration in
the history of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nayowith said the rise in the percentage of children born
into poverty stemmed mainly from increases among white and Asian
families. The percentage of black and Hispanic babies born into
poverty stayed roughly the same: about 60 percent of black infants
and 75 percent of Hispanic babies. But the percentage of white
children born into poverty rose in 1996 to 21.6 percent from 12.8
percent in 1990, and among Asians the percentage went up to 47.7
percent in 1996 from 21.9 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited a large number of what it called ``risks to
child well-being,'' including poverty, unemployment, teen-age
pregnancies, low birth weight, juvenile arrests, and
high-school-dropout rates. The group cited scores of city, state
and federal information.
</P>
<P>
   But the group acknowledged conflicts within the data, including
different definitions of poverty. The federal data for children
born into poverty, for example, defines poverty as annual income
below $23,000 for a family of three in 1996, but for children
living in poverty as $12,500 for a family of three.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
