<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREK-PROGRAMS-NYT(ATTN: </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI RETREATS ON FUNDING FOR EARLY SCHOOL PROGRAMS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 )  By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In his State of the State Message a year ago,
Gov. George E. Pataki said it was time to ``declare, once and for
all, what we all know to be the case'' _ that prekindergarten
programs work. He promised to increase spending on such programs
tenfold by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But in his budget message last week, the governor appeared to
make a sharp turn in the opposite direction, proposing to eliminate
some early-childhood programs and cut back spending on others,
including the prekindergarten programs he praised so warmly last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan has left school districts perplexed and furious,
with some scrambling to come up with money they thought had been
promised and others wondering whether to abandon the effort
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, for example, Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew
Wednesday warned that thousands of children might lose out on
prekindergarten as a result of the governor's proposed cuts. Dr.
Crew said the city wants to offer the program to 29,000 children
next year, up from 14,000 this year, and to all 112,000 of the
city's 4-year-olds in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I am concerned, they are at risk,'' Dr. Crew said of
the universal prekindergarten classes. ``They are unfunded mandates
at this juncture.''
</P>
<P>
   The districts, from New York City to Syracuse to Buffalo, had
been counting on hundreds of millions of dollars in additional
state aid, based on an agreement that Pataki and the Legislature
reached in 1997 to phase in programs for very young students over
the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The money, which would have totaled about $1.5 billion in the
school year beginning in 2001, was intended to help the districts
provide prekindergarten classes for all 4-year-olds, smaller class
sizes in the early grades and all-day kindergarten for districts
that now have either no kindergarten, or only half-day sessions.
Some of the money was also earmarked for school construction,
textbooks and computers.
</P>
<P>
   But in his budget proposal, Pataki sought to back away from that
agreement. He delivered the promised construction money, but
proposed eliminating allocations for prekindergarten, kindergarten,
and smaller classes, offering instead to provide school districts
with a more modest cash grant that could be used for programs of
their choosing.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's proposal would have the greatest impact on New York
City, which would receive a $77 million state educational grant in
lieu of the $150 million it would have otherwise received for
early-childhood programs. The money from the original deal, school
officials said, would have enabled the city to hire 600 additional
teachers to reduce class size in the first, second and third
grades, as well as add 4,000 full-day prekindergarten slots.
</P>
<P>
   In Rochester and Buffalo, school officials had planned to add a
combined 1,536 prekindergarten slots for the coming school year.
But those plans are suddenly up in the air, according to the
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't wait until August to decide that you're going to
expand the program by several hundred slots, particularly in large
city schools that have critical classroom space problems,'' said
Georgia M. Asciutto, the executive director for the Conference of
Big Five School Districts, which represents the state's five
largest urban school districts, including Rochester and Buffalo.
``That process has to start much earlier than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the agreement Pataki reached with the Legislature in
1997 would have provided school districts around the state with
$100 million in 1999-2000 for prekindergarten classes, $75 million
for class size reduction, $10 million for full-day kindergarten,
$50 million for school maintenance, along with several smaller
allocations.
</P>
<P>
   The Governor would replace all of those programs, totaling $270
million, with a grant of $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides note that he intends to supplement the state
grant with $100 million in federal money that has been allocated to
help schools reduce class size in the early grades. But his critics
maintain that the state should not be reneging on its financial
commitment to early-childhood programs just because the federal
government is now providing money for the same purpose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
