A1013 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMC-LAWSUIT-KAN &LR;      02-03 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMC-LAWSUIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT SUES AMC, SAYING DISABLED MOVIEGOERS DON'T HAVE ACCESS
TO STADIUM SEATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Justice is suing AMC Entertainment Inc.,
saying the company isn't providing moviegoers in wheelchairs access
to stadium seating in most of its theaters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMC spokeswoman Brenda Nolte said the lawsuit, filed Friday, was
a surprise to the Kansas City movie theater company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been in discussions with them for a number of months and
have submitted seven or eight different sets of plans for their
approval that weren't accepted,'' Nolte said. ``However, we're
still in negotiations with them and plan to continue to do so in
good faith.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks an order requiring AMC to make modifications
to comply with the Americans With Disabilities Act. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a matter of basic fairness,'' said Bill Lann Lee,
acting assistant attorney general for civil rights. ``People who
use wheelchairs go to the movies and pay the same prices as
everyone else. They should have access to seats of comparable
quality to those available to most other patrons.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The snag in negotiations centers on exactly what constitutes a
good seat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some movie patrons like to sit in the back, others close to the
screen, some in the middle of a row, others next to an aisle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the definition for what is a comparable sightline for the
general public,'' Nolte said. ``But that keeps changing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMC embarked on an aggressive expansion program in the early
1990s, building megaplexes containing 18 to 30 screens, or more.
Most megaplex theaters feature stadium, or tiered, seating that
gives an unobstructed view to most moviegoers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most seating for patrons in wheelchairs and others who can't use
stairs is on a flat area in front of the stadium seating. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of AMC's new megaplexes include at least a few screens that
have elevators to give wheelchair users and other disabled patrons
access to a landing at the back of the theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMC isn't the only movie chain being called to task. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a federal court in Waco, Texas, ruled that
two Cinemark theaters with stadium seating violated the Americans
With Disabilities Act by forcing patrons who use wheelchairs to sit
in the front two rows of the theaters. That case is being
appealed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department says it also is investigating other movie
theaters and theater chains for possible violations of the act. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AMC lawsuit also asks that the company be forced to pay
damages to patrons with disabilities who did not have access to
stadium seats and that the company pay unspecified civil
penalties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lee used one of AMC's advertising slogans to drive home the
Justice Department's position. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``AMC says it is `changing the way the world sees movies,' ''
Lee said. ``We're just making sure that change complies with the
law.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
