<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO VISITS CITY HALL 
ASTROBIOGRAPHY 
AUTEUR PESTERS MUCKETY-MUCKS 
YO-YO MA DAY, YO-YO MA WAY
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who was that familiar-looking man escorting Stuart
Subotnick around City Hall Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a lobbyist,'' Alfonse D'Amato declared.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato had arranged a meeting between Subotnick, the president
of a group that owns a major league soccer team in New Jersey, the
MetroStars, and wants to organize one in New York, and Deputy Mayor
Randy Levine.
</P>
<P>
   It was a get-acquainted session, D'Amato said, and later Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani _ the two men had their differences when D'Amato
was a U.S. senator from New York _ agreed that D'Amato's visit to
City Hall was not a lobbying trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be lobbying about something that isn't even at the
point of being a bid or a contract,'' the mayor said later in the
day. ``When the city is seeking ideas and thoughts, it's not
lobbying; it's just like anybody else that can come in and talk
about possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Giuliani and D'Amato did not encounter each other.
``He wasn't in,'' D'Amato said as he left. So there was no talk of
the Senate race he lost to Charles Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here, again, with Subotnick,'' D'Amato said. ``We spoke
about soccer, soccer, soccer. Kicking the ball, not each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn the Author
</P>
<P>
   Last year, John Glenn went on his second flight in space. Now he
is writing his second book, and on Wednesday Bantam said that it
would publish it in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bantam did not say how much it was paying for the still-untitled
story of Glenn's life, which will cover his 55-year marriage and
his 24-year Senate career as well as his time in space. As with
many celebrity autobiographies, a writer has been brought in. And
the editing at Bantam will be done by Beverly Lewis, who handled
autobiographies by Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf and Beverly Sills,
the soprano-turned-arts administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's other book was ``We Seven,'' written in 1962 in
collaboration with the six other Mercury astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   Cable Complaints
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Isles called her cable company the other day to ask
why it did not carry the BET channel, which is scheduled to carry a
documentary called ``Scandalize My Name: Stories from the
Blacklist'' on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people in New York to want to see it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Miss Isles _ who had an affair with the socialite
Claus von Bulow that Rhode Island prosecutors said led him to try
to kill his wife with an insulin injection in 1979 _ made the
documentary.
</P>
<P>
   She said that one of the purposes of a screening at Lincoln
Center on Tuesday ``was to get everybody to call the number on
their bill because we don't know the muckety-mucks. Have a little
groundswell.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Time Warner Cable of New York, Geri Warren,
said the calls would have no immediate effect. ``Right now, we're
channel-locked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yo-Yo Ma Day
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The idea is to observe Yo-Yo Ma Day on Yo-Yo Ma Way.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki has declared next Tuesday Yo-Yo Ma Day. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani has renamed 46th Street between Fifth and Madison
Avenues Yo-Yo Ma Way, but only temporarily. After Yo-Yo Ma Day,
Yo-Yo Ma Way will go back to being 46th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The cellist is scheduled to spend a part of his day signing
autographs at the HMV record store on Fifth Avenue, and HMV would
like the street-name change to be made permanent.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a problem. The City Council, not the mayor's
Transportation Department, normally decides on long-term
street-name changes. And the Council has its rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person's got to be deceased,'' said Randy Orozco, a
Council spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
