u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOLOCAUST-MUSEUM-N     02-03 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOLOCAUST-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SPLIT IS REFLECTED IN DISPUTE ON MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Plans to announce a long-awaited expansion of New
York's Holocaust museum at a ceremony Thursday have been postponed
because of a heated dispute over its financing between Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George E. Pataki, whose rift appears to
widen by the day.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Giuliani said Wednesday that the city and the state had
agreed to chip in $11 million each to help pay for the proposed
expansion but that the state had recently reneged on its verbal
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration is determined to come up with more
money to cover the state's share, city officials said, but would
need the support of Peter F. Vallone, the City Council speaker, who
is out of town this week. Therefore, they decided to postpone the
announcement until at least next week.
</P>
<P>
   This version of events was described as approaching fiction by
various members of the Pataki administration.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Race, Pataki's chief of staff, on Wednesday denied that the
state had agreed to contribute the $11 million; in fact, he said,
the state had never even been asked to make such a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   And James F. Gill, whom the governor appointed as chairman of
the Battery Park City Authority _ a state-run agency that controls
the land on which the museum sits _ approached apoplexy in
disputing the Giuliani administration's version of events.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the agreement had always called for the city to
contribute $22 million, while the authority would cede the land on
which to build the expansion. ``It was always the deal _ it was the
deal at the get-go,'' he insisted. The city's contention, he said,
``is made out of whole cloth. It's nonsense. It's garbage. And
frankly I resent it.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Randy Levine, the city's deputy mayor of economic
development, said: ``If the state had kept its $11 million in, we
could have gone forward. I'm telling you, they made the
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth regarding the museum issue, it seemed clear
from the nasty charges and countercharges that the awkward detente
between the state's two Republican leaders is no more.
</P>
<P>
   It was particularly remarkable that their feud should touch an
issue as politically delicate as the Holocaust museum, given that
both men will no doubt continue to court Jewish voters and
contributors as they pursue possible national ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Those ambitions could well collide in a party that may be able
to handle only one New York Republican at a time. And the men
harbor a mutual distrust that dates back to Giuliani's decision to
back Pataki's opponent and eventual victim, Mario M. Cuomo, in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the governor and the mayor have professed to enjoy a
fruitful relationship, with Giuliani endorsing Pataki's re-election
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, the two camps have appeared to go out of
their way to antagonize each other.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, for example, did not check with Pataki last month
before proposing a plan to build a domed football stadium on
Manhattan's West Side, even though the governor controls the land
on which it would be built.
</P>
<P>
   And Pataki surprised Giuliani by recently announcing plans to
investigate the School Construction Authority, even though the
governor's appointee to the authority was at the center of recent
charges of mismanagement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
