A1027 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASHCROFT-GROUP-KAN &LR;      02-03 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASHCROFT-GROUP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHCROFT BLASTS NEWS RELEASE LINKING HIM TO ALLEGEDLY RACIST
GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri on Tuesday condemned a group of
alleged racists that a Democratic political group had linked to the
Republican in a news release last month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also sharply criticized the news release from the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee, which called Ashcroft the ``white
supremacist's presidential choice.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like the press release was offensive, injurious and
wrong,'' said Ashcroft aide Don Trigg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The campaign committee's news release was based on a televised
appearance by Gordon Baum of Bridgeton, Mo., a leader of the
Council of Conservative Citizens. The group, criticized as racist
and anti-Semitic, has made headlines recently because of its loose
ties to GOP congressional leaders, including Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott of Mississippi. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on CNN, Baum said he could support Ashcroft for
president, although at the time of the interview Ashcroft already
had dropped out of the 2000 race. Baum had first mentioned
television commentator Pat Buchanan as the candidate who ``probably
comes fairly close to us on some of the social and cultural
issues.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is being challenged for a second Senate term in 2000 by
Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its Jan. 26 news release, the campaign committee said Baum's
statement ``proves'' that Ashcroft's base of support was the
extreme right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sad to think that those fighting on his team are white
supremacists who hope to reverse the civil rights strides America
has made since the 1950s,'' Joe Hansen, the campaign committee's
executive director, said in the news release. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Michael Tucker, another campaign committee official,
said the political group stood by the news release. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
issued a news release that said, ``Just like Larry Flynt and James
Carville, Governor Carnahan's political team at the DSCC is
embracing the politics of personal destruction.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Carnahan have said the governor and his staff had
nothing to do with the campaign committee's news release or its
distribution. The governor told reporters Monday he had not seen
the campaign committee's release. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I know the facts, I'm not going to make a statement
about it,'' Carnahan said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said he considered the Council of Conservative Citizens to be
a dangerous group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's office issued news releases from the National Jewish
Coalition and the National Center for Neighborhood Enterprise,
among others, that condemned the campaign committee. An Ashcroft
aide said the senator repudiated the citizens council. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just appalling,'' said Ann Wagner, chairwoman of the
Missouri Republican Party. ``People hate this kind of sleazy
campaigning. To have it begin two years out is a real
disappointment.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
