<DOCNO> NYT19990203.0502 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1178 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOURN-PASTOR-KAN &LR;      02-03 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOURN-PASTOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS GATHER TO MOURN, PRAISE LONGTIME KC AREA MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN and HELEN T. GRAY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The words the Rev. E.A. Freeman spoke from the pulpit at First
Baptist Church were powerful, but his life was his greatest
sermon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He preached the gospel every day'' with much more than words,
the Rev. Jesse Jackson said Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackson delivered a 40-minute eulogy to about 1,000 people who
attended Freeman's funeral at First Baptist Church at Fifth Street
and Nebraska Avenue in Kansas City, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, a longtime religious and civic leader who led the
church for 50 years, died Jan. 26 at age 84. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he lived, he walked in a dark room and light came
up,'' said Jackson, whose friendship with Freeman began in the
1950s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was last on a schedule of speakers that included Kansas
City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, a United Methodist minister; Carol
Marinovich, mayor of the Unified Government of Wyandotte County and
Kansas City, Kan.; and religious leaders from throughout the
country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An entire section of the sanctuary was reserved for ministers
and their wives. About 100 ministers attended. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us here today, our careers are defined because of
Freeman's credibility,'' Jackson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 80 persons who could not fit into the sanctuary sat on
folding chairs in the church gymnasium and watched the service on
closed-circuit television. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The program called the service a ``Home Going Celebration,'' and
it was a spirited commemoration of Freeman's life. Early in his
remarks, Jackson asked those assembled to ``give it up'' in
remembrance of Freeman, and the crowd responded with a standing
ovation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rather than reflect on the sorrow and finality of Freeman's
passing, speakers chose to focus on his personality, his lifetime
of commitment and achievement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone asked me to describe Dr. Freeman,'' Marinovich said.
``What comes to mind from my discussions with him are a gentleman
and a gentle man. He will truly be missed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaker after speaker recalled the stories and jokes that
Freeman loved to tell. Some even recounted a favorite, evoking
laughter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were around him, he would find a way to make you
laugh,'' said the Rev. Wallace S. Hartsfield, pastor of
Metropolitan Missionary Baptist Church in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver read aloud a letter from President Clinton, who called
Freeman a ``strong, inspiring spiritual leader.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Said Cleaver: ``He touched people, he changed folk and lifted
them spiritually. If there were a candidate to live again, I would
nominate E.A. Freeman.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The service was led by the Rev. Ellis C. Robinson, who took over
at First Baptist after Freeman retired in 1996. As a boy, Robinson
lived next door to the Freemans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Freeman always said he wanted to die at First Baptist or
on his way to First Baptist,'' Robinson said. ``This is the only
place we could have this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robinson met with the speakers before the service and urged them
to limit their reflections to two minutes, but almost no one did,
and the service stretched to four hours. But Freeman's influence
could not be summarized in a mere 120 seconds, and Robinson
understood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to do what we ought to do, because if we did,
we'd be here for a week,'' he said. ``We are here to show Dr.
Freeman that we love him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The service was attended by representatives of the National
Baptist Congress of Christian Education and the Kansas Missionary
Baptist State Convention, both of which Freeman once served as
president; as well as the National Baptist Convention, U.S.A. Inc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was committed to bringing the kingdom of God here on
earth,'' said the Rev. Stacy Ollar, pastor of Welborn Community
United Church of Christ in Kansas City, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ollar told of how he and Freeman helped organize a group to
fight for fair utility rates in the early 1980s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two men also crossed racial lines and exchanged pulpits in
the early '80s when Ollar was pastor of the Bristol Hill United
Methodist Church in the Turner district of Kansas City, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freeman was one of a minority of black Baptist pastors who
embraced the ordination of women. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a mentor and encourager for women who dared to heed the
call,'' said the Rev. Rosetta Whitfield of First Baptist Church.
``He was our father in the ministry.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, Freeman helped heal a rift between Jackson
and the National Baptist Convention that dated to the 1950s when
the convention became uncomfortable with the high-profile activism
of Jackson's associate, the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, at his first revival, Jackson chose First Baptist as
the location for a weeklong spiritual event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At one point Tuesday, Jackson referred to Acts 13:36: ``For when
David had served God's purpose in his own generation, he fell
asleep.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Freeman,'' Jackson said, ``served his generation well, and
then he fell asleep.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-03-99 2316EST &QL; 
