<HEADER>
A1179 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THREATS-ABORTION-KAN &LR;      02-03 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREATS-ABORTION-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Jury RULES AGAINST ANTI-ABORTION WEB SITE, `WANTED' POSTERS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 cs. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal jury in Portland, Ore., ruled Tuesday that a Web site
and Old West-style ``wanted posters'' listing personal details
about abortion doctors amounted to illegal threats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jurors ordered the defendants to pay more than $107 million in
damages to two clinics and four doctors _ among them Robert D.
Crist, medical director of Planned Parenthood of Kansas and
Mid-Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the 14 defendants is from St. Louis and another is from
Wichita. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury saw the posters for what they are _ a hit list for
terrorists,'' said Gloria Feldt, president of Planned Parenthood
Federation of America, whose Portland affiliate was a plaintiff in
the case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot restore the lives of those who have been killed.But
this verdict reminds us all that while Americans have a great
diversity of thoughts and feelings about abortion, we speak with
one voice to renounce domestic terrorists.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs said their next step is to seek an injunction
that, among other things, could shut down the Web site. It remained
active late Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the jury verdict that would require it to
be taken down, but I can foresee a variety of avenues by which
people may try to get it taken down,'' said Planned Parenthood
attorney Roger Evans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The defendants said an appeal is already in the works. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said the verdict could have major implications for
the First Amendment. At issue was whether the defendants' tactics
encouraged violence against abortion doctors or were simply acts of
constitutionally protected free speech. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tactics included ``The Nuremberg Files'' _ a Web site that
lists hundreds of ``baby butchers'' and asks activists to send in
doctors' home addresses, license plate numbers and even the names
of their children _ and ``wanted'' posters offering rewards for
information about doctors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those questions that lie really at the heart of
the First Amendment,'' said Richard E. Levy, a constitutional law
professor at the University of Kansas. ``We allow speech that we
disagree with. We even allow speech that is dangerous. The line is
drawn very broadly to protect speech, and the government can
proscribe speech only in very specific circumstances.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Crist _ whose address and phone number appear
on the Web site and ``wanted'' posters _ told jurors that he was
``truly, truly frightened'' by the tactics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Crist said, when St. Louis police showed him a flier
with the heading ``Guilty of Crimes Against Humanity,'' they told
him to take it as a serious threat and compared it to a ``contract
on my life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crist said he began wearing a bulletproof vest and using armed
police escorts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear a vest even when I go to dinner with my wife and son,''
he testified. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs sued under federal racketeering laws and the 1994
Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act, which makes it illegal
to incite violence against abortion doctors and their patients.
While the clinic access law has been used numerous times against
activists who have bombed clinics or shot doctors, this case was
believed to be the first not to result from a violent attack or a
direct threat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs said the activists were terrorists
who conspired to use publications, intimidation and even killing to
scare doctors into quitting. Distribution of their ``wanted''
posters, the plaintiffs said, was followed by the killings of three
doctors and one of their escorts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though the fliers and the Web site contained no direct threats,
they said, a reasonable person would perceive them as such, given
the atmosphere of violence in which four doctors and two clinic
employees have been killed since 1993. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The defendants argued, however, that their tactics were merely a
form of protected political protest. They described the trial as an
``inquisition'' aimed at silencing their attempts to speak out
against abortion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated 4 1/2 days before issuing a verdict in the
three-week trial. But several defendants said the doctors and
clinics would have a hard time collecting any of the millions in
damages awarded by the jury. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to get anything. We're all broke,'' said Tim
Dreste of St. Louis, a member of the Missouri Republican State
Committee who served as the north central director of the American
Coalition of Life Advocates, one of the defendants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many defendants said they have made themselves
``judgment-proof'' by transferring their assets to spouses and
others. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evans, the Planned Parenthood attorney, said, ``They're
judgment-proof, but on the other hand, it clips their wings
significantly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael Bray, a pastor from Bowie, Md., and a defendant
in the case, said the verdict won't change his tactics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect I'll continue speaking the truth,'' said Bray, who
last month sponsored his fourth annual banquet in College Park,
Md., to honor activists who have killed doctors and bombed
clinics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the damages, Bray said, ``there's no money to be had.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But they don't want that,'' he said. ``They just want me to
shut up and let them kill in peace. But I don't have any intention
to shut up at this point. I will continue to call them murderers. I
may have to get creative about it, though.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
