</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `OLD DAYS,' RECRUITING WAS DIRTY BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I heard it again yesterday, like every year on national signing
day, the distant echo of Jim Wacker, pleading for mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know. I swear I didn't know.''.
</P>
<P>
   Shut up, coach. You knew. Everybody knew what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yeah. The old days, when the first week of February allowed
otherwise distinguished local citizens to dabble in Texas-style
organized crime. But, of course, it was all done in the name of an
honorable cause _ football bragging rights for dear ol' alma mammy.
</P>
<P>
   Like the infamous story of Big Bucks from SMU cutting the deal
with Fat Wallet from TCU, where a ``financial ceiling'' was placed
on the head of every local high school hot shot, therefore
controlling under-the-table costs. And this was the church-school
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer necessary to bring up the names of those most
involved, but certainly the memories linger. In this case, the old
days were the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   All that wild cheating was, well, fun, particularly from a
media-coverage standpoint, but the eventual long, hard fall trapped
the participants. To a certain extent, it brought about both the
demise of the Southwest Conference and the football program at
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   But man, is it ever quiet these days. High school recruiting
remains the lifeblood of college football, and the state of Texas
remains a national focal point, but to hear the current
participants tell it, cleanness basically prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Teaff not only lived and coached through the ``bagmen''
era, he's now the executive director of the American Football
Coaches Association. For one thing, Teaff is a clearing house for
complaints within the national coaching community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new world out there,'' said Teaff yesterday from
Waco. ``I don't even hear a whisper from members about our
association needing to do something about this coach or that coach
because his school is paying off kids. We have our problems and our
agendas, but that's a non-existent concern these days.''
</P>
<P>
   R.C. Slocum of Texas A&AMP;M was also coaching in the ``old days.''
As the high school signatures came in yesterday, the Aggies
prospered. So, of course, did the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Texas cheats, and I know we don't,'' he said.
``Believe me, neither of us would have had these quality classes if
there was a school out there still doing something.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age, a coach would be nuts to try it because
his job is on the line. Not only the job he has, but basically his
chances of ever getting another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaff will preside over the annual national meeting of the AFCA
this week in Dallas. ``I can guarantee harmony at this convention,
with coaches working together, just like it's been over the last
five years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back, however, to the '80s and we'd sit there at the
convention and glare at each other. That guy across from you was
cheating, you knew it, and you knew it had cost you a kid. It was
dog-eat-dog.''
</P>
<P>
   In Teaff's opinion, university presidents either stopped hiring
the coaching Capones or severely curbed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to make it really stick, we had to have the rule changes
on recruiting,'' he added. ``First and foremost was the removal of
alumni from the recruiting process. There was never a major
recruiting scandal that didn't heavily involve out-of-control
alums.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much a coach thought he could organize his
alums, there was always one, or more, thinking he had to do
whatever was necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also a rule change on coaches having personal contact
with a recruit, resulting in a ``dead period'' from Sunday night
until the signing day on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rule restored sanity to the process,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, most all the shenanigans took place the night
before signing day, or the morning of,'' Teaff said. ``Out of
nowhere, a kid changed his mind on you. Everyone knew why, we just
couldn't do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the AFCA, Teaff is now pushing for more changes, such as
an early signing date. He says it would eliminate ``commitment''
switching, plus cut the cost of recruiting. ``There are details to
work out on that, although I feel it's do-able,'' Teaff said. ``But
the most important thing is we now have recruiting under control,
and everything else is fine-tuning.''
</P>
<P>
   If true, that's a long, long way from the way it was, when the
only defense of a nailed coach was a feeble, ``I didn't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
