<SLUG> BC-FBC-NATIONAL-RECRUITING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UT AT TOP OF NATIONAL LISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been nearly three decades since Texas finished No. 1 in
football. Now, at least in the national recruiting race, the
Longhorns can claim a national title.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the change of mind by quarterback Chris Simms, Texas
signed a recruiting class yesterday that most experts rated the
nation's best. Simms is regarded as the nation's top offensive
player; the Longhorns also signed linebacker Cory Redding of
Houston, considered the nation's top defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Simms' decision to attend Texas was icing on the cake,''
said Bobby Burton, editor of the ``National Recruiting Advisor''.
``Their group of offensive recruits might be the best in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any coach, \RTexas'\S Mack Brown has awakened a
sleeping giant,'' Allen Wallace, publisher of SuperPrep magazine
said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas kept kids at home while going out and signing the
nation's top talent, too,'' said Tom Lemming of The Prep Football
Report. ``But Texas' class is not a dominant class like some of the
best classes in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominant or otherwise, Brown said yesterday's haul represented
``the best class I've ever been associated with'' in 24 seasons as
a college football coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a class that can jump-start us back into the
elite of college football,'' Brown said. ``Some people say being
rated No. 1 in recruiting means absolutely nothing. But you'd
rather be rated No. 1 than 50th. That's a no-brainer. The guys who
are on this list are players that everyone else wanted as much as
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' recruiting resurgence helped reverse a decade-long trend
of the top players leaving the state to play elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M, following its rival's lead, also signed a class that
is considered among the nation's best. Austin-based recruiting
analyst Bobby Burton believes the Aggies signed an excellent group
of defensive players. A&AMP;M also signed Joe Weber, a top-notch
running back from California.
</P>
<P>
   The other schools with top classes were Ohio State, UCLA,
Georgia, Notre Dame, Miami (Fla.), Alabama, Michigan and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State was disappointed when wide reciever Reggie Brown
stayed in his home state and signed with Georgia. The Bulldogs
brought in some of the nation's top wide receivers, which should
make sophomore quarterback Quincy Carter happy.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame, whose board of regents is expected to make a
decision tomorrow about the school's possible move to the Big Ten
Conference, again had outstanding recruiting success. The Irish did
especially well in stocking up on offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They signed the right guys almost to a person,'' Lemming said.
``It was perfectly planned, a masterful class.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Notre Dame was disappointed when quarterback C.J. Leak
of Charlotte, N.C., pulled one of the biggest surprises of
yesterday's signings. Leak spurned the Irish, Penn State and
Michigan State to sign with Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Burton called Leak's decision ``the biggest surprise'' of the
recruiting season.
</P>
<P>
   National champion Tennessee, which is expected to be go into
next season as the No. 1 team, signed a solid class that could have
been better. The Volunteers were jilted by several top recruits,
the most notable of which was Simms, who orally committed to
Tennessee in December.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State, which had just 12 scholarships available, made a
late rush that left coach Bobby Bowden smiling. The Seminoles
landed running back Nick Maddox plus quarterbacks Anquan Boldin and
Fabian Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quality wise, it's going to be mighty hard to beat,'' Bowden
said. ``We don't have many needs this year, and it's hard to
recruit when you can't show them they'll play right away.''
The nation's top 10 Star-Telegram college football writer Wendell
Barnhouse ranks the nation's top 10 recruiting classes: School
Conf. Class comment 1. Texas Big 12 QB Chris Simms lifts Horns to
the top 2. Ohio State Big 10 Buckeyes continue to stockpile the
talent 3. UCLA Pac-10 Another top class, but where's the defense?
4. Georgia SEC Bulldogs sign 3 of the top wide receivers 5. Notre
Dame Ind. Irish drop after losing QB C.J. Leak 6. Texas A&AMP;M Big 12
Aggies load up on defense, especially LBs 7. Miami (Fla.) Big East
Butch Davis gradually rebuilding 'Canes 8. Alabama SEC Rebuilding
'Bama gets more top players 9. Michigan Big 10 Failed to land
needed defensive linemen 10. Tennessee SEC National champs whiffed
several key signings
</P>
</TEXT>
