<HEADLINE>
CAVAN HAPPY WITH BIG CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rice went for defense, Tulsa reeled in big linemen and SMU took
a little of everything in the store, as the members of the Western
Athletic Conference's local quadrant pronounced themselves pleased
with their signing-day catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really pleased with the way things worked out,'' said SMU
coach Mike Cavan, who called his group of 24 signees ``the best
class they've had here in quite a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The group included the pitch-and-catch team of quarterback Kelan
Luker and wide receiver Cody Cardwell that led Stephenville to a
Class 4A state title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think Luker can make an immediate impact?'' Cavan said,
laughing. ``Well, considering we have only one guy on campus who
has played quarterback in a Division I game \RJosh McCown\S, I'd
say he \RLuker\S has a pretty good shot at No. 2 right away. I'm
certainly not going to play it myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also felt that Cardwell, though he received less publicity,
was just as good a catch for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope those Stephenville people start coming to our
games like they came to Texas Stadium four weeks in a row in the
playoffs. We've got plenty of room, and I'm instructing our ticket
manager to open a booth down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Other high-profile SMU signees included Carthage running back
Kris Briggs, Houston Wheatley receiver Chris ``The Comet''
Cunningham, defensive tackle Warrie Birdwell from Mission, and
Waxahachie linebacker Khalid Beard _ plus swift Marcus Carter, who
played four positions at Rusk, and 6-foot-6, 280-pound tackle
Sterling Harris from Terrell.
</P>
<P>
   Harris has already developed a warm friendship with C.B.
Williams (6-6, 270), a tackle from Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``They plan to room together so they can wear each other's
shoes,'' Cavan said. ``They each wear a size 18.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs also signed Harris' brother, linebacker Devonric
Johnson, ``who is a great student and was probably headed for the
Ivy League if he hadn't come here,'' Cavan said.
</P>
<P>
   Although 11 of Rice's 17 signees line up on defense, there are
also three quarterbacks who coach Ken Hatfield is excited about.
</P>
<P>
   One is Jeremy Hurd, who led Duncanville to a state title, has
turned in a 24-foot, 6-inch long jump, and is considered the
state's top option quarterback. Then there is Kyle Herm, a
multisport star who led Stanton to a 16-0 state championship season
as a junior and set a state Class 2A record for career touchdown
passes with 81. The third prospect, Diboll's Jeff Vanover, was
all-area at QB and all-state (3A) as a linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   And while 11 of Tulsa's 22 signees are linemen, the prize of the
class is quarterback Josh Blankenship of Tulsa Union _ the first
Oklahoma high school player of the year in 15 years to sign with
the Golden Hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa coach Dave Rader described Blankenship as ``the
prototypical quarterback for the one-back offense, and a terrific
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also the son of Union coach Bill Blankenship, who was
Rader's roommate when they played together at Tulsa 20 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
