<SLUG> BC-BBC-TEXAS-UT-ARLINGTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FINISHES SWEEP OF UTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas designated hitter Steve Woodward said a two-game
series sweep against UT-Arlington has made the Longhorns even more
excited about the upcoming weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Texas defeated UTA, 9-3, yesterday at Disch-Falk Field behind a
one-hitter through five innings by junior left-hander D.J. Jones.
The Longhorns opened the series with a 5-2 victory Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With a three-game series opening against defending national
champion Southern California on Friday, Woodward said it was
important for Texas to prove it can play every phase of the game.
Against UTA, the Longhorns did.
</P>
<P>
   Texas pounded out 12 hits, and has played the first 18 innings
of 1999 without an error.
</P>
<P>
   In the series, seven Texas pitchers allowed five runs on 10
hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we played against UTA, I think we showed we can
compete against anybody,'' Woodward said. ``Our defense made plays,
we hit the ball, ran the bases and got good pitching. You can't do
much more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas (2-0) did it with a mix of last season's veterans and some
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman first baseman Jeff Ontiveros, a native of nearby Round
Rock, gave Texas a 1-0 lead in the second inning with a solo homer
to left off UTA starter Ben Grundhauser (0-1).
</P>
<P>
   Longhorns outfielder Jason Cox drove in a run with a sacrifice
fly in the third, and Woodward hit a solo homer in the fourth to
give Texas a 3-0 lead. That was all Jones (1-0), a transfer from
Navarro College, would need to earn the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Through five innings, Jones struck out five and walked two.
</P>
<P>
   Texas scored four runs in the sixth, all with two outs, and UTA
(0-2) fell behind, 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   Texas scored seven of its nine runs with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to put people away with two outs,'' UTA coach Butch
McBroom said. ``We didn't pitch very well at all in the two games.
I thought we would eventually face somebody we would hit, but we
weren't able to keep the game close.''
</P>
<P>
   After facing Texas pitcher Ryan France for two innings without
success, UTA got some offense in the eighth inning off the
Longhorns' third reliever, Scott Hild.
</P>
<P>
   UTA second baseman Joe Kennedy hit a one-out single, followed by
a single to right by Matt Mize. John-Paul Davis made it 9-3 with a
homer to left-center field before Adam Bush grounded out to end the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys were able to build rallies and sustain them,'' Texas
coach Augie Garrido said. ``The attitude of the team was good. They
were unselfish and gave 100 percent in their roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Mize, Davis and Martin, hitting third, fourth and fifth in UTA's
order, went 8-for-21 in the series. The rest of the team went
2-for-42.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
