<HEADLINE>
MORRISON'S LEGACY: LIVE AND RACE FOR TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the final four months of 1998, Buddy Morrison put his
signature on a drag-racing season he knew he never would see.
</P>
<P>
   When the cancer that Morrison had been battling for over a year
claimed him Dec. 15 at age 54, the futures of Reher-Morrison Racing
Engines and its Pro Stock drag-racing team were secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy did everything he could to make it easy for the
business,'' said David Reher, who formed RMRE in 1971 with his
friend and fellow Arlington resident. ``From mid-September on last
year, we talked a lot about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison also spent some quality time with Bruce Allen, the
driver he chose to succeed the late Lee Shepherd in 1985 when
Reher-Morrison-Shepherd ruled as four-time National Hot Rod
Association and two-time International Hot Rod Association Pro
Stock world champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy was like a mentor to me,'' said Allen, also of
Arlington. ``One of the things we talked about a lot was not living
in the past. He said, `Today's the day when you get out there
racing.' Buddy was always looking down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Minus Big Buddy and admittedly behind in their off-season
preparation, Reher and Allen hope to begin the hard climb back
among drag racing's elite during the season-opening AutoZone
Winternationals. First-round qualifying is scheduled for today at
Pomona (Calif.) Raceway, where Reher-Morrison-Shepherd scored their
first official national event Pro Stock championship victory in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a series of encouraging quarter-mile passes during the
Pro Stock SuperBowl Challenge at Houston Raceway Park last weekend,
neither Reher nor Allen is touting any storybook endings for
Southern California. The competition in Pro Stock figures to be as
cutthroat as ever, beginning with qualifications to fill the 16-car
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Allen did not qualify for 12 of 22 national events last year,
including three of the last four. Allen, who tumbled from fourth to
13th in the points standings in 1998, did record the fastest speed
of his 14-year career in Baytown on Sunday. His top lap at 199.07
mph capped a weekend filled with elapsed times in the low
6.9-second range.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we saw other people running good,'' said Allen, driver of
The Outlaw Fuel Additives Pontiac Firebird. ``We saw Mike Thomas, a
Pennzoil teammate, run 200 \Rat 6.845-seconds\S. We want to get
into that 200 mph area.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the team plans to debut a new Don Ness-built
chassis for the season's second race at Phoenix later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have two new engines with different concepts as far as
induction and cylinder heads that aren't together yet,'' Reher
said. ``We're looking in-depth into a lot of things. It's not all
gloom and doom.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly as Buddy Morrison willed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted us to carry on as well as we could, and I think
we'll do a good job,'' Reher said. ``I'll always miss Buddy. But I
consider that he's still helping us.''
QUICK HITS HILL'S HOPES HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a one-year contract extension from Pennzoil, former
Top Fuel champion Eddie Hill of Wichita Falls continues to defy the
NHRA's timers. And Father Time.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who turns 63 next month, earned the No. 1 qualifying spot
during the PRO National Time Trials at 4.632 seconds and 297.55 mph
at Firebird International Raceway in Phoenix last month. Hill, who
also will perform crew chief duties this season, qualified for all
22 national events last year. His current qualifying streak of 40
consecutive races would be stout for a driver half his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most importantly, we're all smiling,'' said Hill, the 1993
NHRA Winston Top Fuel champion and winner of the season-opening
Winternationals in 1995. ``I can't remember the last time I was
this excited about racing.''
CLUTCH PERFORMER
</P>
<P>
   The switch is on from a four-disc to a five-disc clutch system
in Top Fuel and Funny Car, a technical innovation Cory McClenathan
believes will produce a win/win for drivers and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This five-disc clutch doesn't slam you into the back of the
seat three-quarters down the track,'' said Cory Mac, who will debut
his new black-and-green MBNA America-sponsored Top Fuel car at the
Winternationals. ``This clutch is going to help the cars run easier
and quicker and faster passes. That will make for exciting
side-by-side racing _ and a lot less smoking of the tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the season goes on, I think you'll see some big differences
in elapsed time and mile per hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time and reigning Top Fuel champion Gary Scelzi owns both
ends of the national record _ 4.525 seconds and 326.44 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we might top-out at 328 this year,'' said
McClenathan, runner-up to Scelzi the past two seasons. ``But after
what I saw in testing, we could very well see 330.''
FIRE DOWN BELOW
</P>
<P>
   No drag racer can talk his way into a competitor's head like
John Force, the reigning and eight-time NHRA Funny Car champion.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Capps, runner-up to Force last year despite winning five
national events in the Copenhagen Chevrolet Camaro Z/28, insists
that ``The Brute'' did not psyche him out down the stretch last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm good friends with John,'' said Capps, who will attempt to
defend his Winternationals title this weekend. ``He brings a little
more motivation out of me. I've built a deep-down fire for him over
the winter and want to take the title from him.''
CANNON TAKES AIM
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Cannon's debut in Funny Car figures to be a hot story at
the Winternationals.
</P>
<P>
   The outspoken Cannon is the six-time and reigning International
Hot Rod Association Pro Modified champion. Cannon, 36, earned his
NHRA license at Gainesville (Fla.) Raceway in December and plans to
debut a Pontiac Trans-Am-bodied car at Pomona, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping an eye on Scotty Cannon. He's a real
competitor,'' said Force, who is scheduled to debut a redesigned,
aerodynamic 1999 Castrol GTX Ford Mustang body tweaked by NASCAR
guru Jack Roush. ``All he \RCannon\S thinks is `win.' Those kind of
guys, they get you on the ropes and you got to fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   Capps said he recently met Cannon after watching his IHRA
exploits on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love watching the Pro Mods on TV, and how he would kick
their butts and take their names and then tell them about it,''
Capps said. ``He's going to talk some trash to Force and everybody,
but he's a smart cookie. I'm very impressed with him.''
TESTING AND TUNING
</P>
<P>
   The first of six all-day open test sessions have been scheduled
at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis for this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Saturday and Sunday, AAA Texas Test Days are
booked for Feb. 13-14, Feb. 27 and March 6. Gates will open at 10
a.m. with time trials from 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tech cards will cost
$20.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunoco Season Kickoff, a $25,000 Bracket race, is scheduled
for Feb. 20-21. First O'Reilly Drag Racing Series points meet of
the season is booked for Feb. 28.
LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they'll fall off the wagon. They're tough, and
we need to rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cory McClenathan, on 1997-98 Top Fuel champion Gary Scelzi and
owner/tuner Alan Johnson
SPOTLIGHT ON ...
MEYER BIDING TIME ON MOTORPLEX MOVE
</P>
<P>
   The pace has slowed on Billy Meyer's plan to relocate the Texas
Motorplex drag-racing facility from Ennis to Grand Prairie. That
does not mean Meyer is spinning his corporate wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reviewing plans on some expansion out there,'' said
Meyer, the Waco businessman and former Funny Car driver who has
spent 12 months negotiating a possible move into the heart of the
Metroplex's entertainment corridor. ``We are communicating with
Ennis and Grand Prairie. But I haven't been trying to force the
issue with anybody. We're quite successful where we are, and I
think we'll have quite a bit of news in the next quarter that will
be exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Two NHRA national events again highlight the calendar at the
all-concrete quarter-mile. O'Reilly Auto Parts has reached a
multiyear agreement to sponsor the NHRA Fall Nationals on Oct.
21-24. It will be the 14th edition of the race formerly known as
the Chief Auto Parts Nationals and Revell Nationals _ the
longest-running major motorsports event in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The third annual Castrol Nationals is scheduled for April 22-25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our growth rate was huge at the spring race last year _ over
20 percent,'' Meyer said. ``So that race is still in a growth
pattern. The fall race's growth was about 4 percent. But we really
can't `grow' that race on Sunday. We can grow it on Thursday,
Friday and Saturday. About the only thing spectators can do now is
be smart enough to buy tickets in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans looking for national events on TV will have to
channel-surf. ESPN, ESPN2, TNN, Fox and ABC will carry drag racing
this year, with 14 of the 20 races scheduled for either live or
same-day coverage.
</P>
<P>
   TNN, which carried 11 live events last year, is down to four one
week-delayed shows and live coverage of the U.S. Nationals on Labor
Day Weekend. Meyer said the argument that the NHRA's daylong
elimination format is an awkward fit for live TV is weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to use golf as an analogy,'' Meyer said. ``A golf
tournament is carried live, but they don't show every single inch
of the day. The process NHRA came up with has some pretty good
stuff, live and taped. Just because it's an all-day event doesn't
mean it can't be live at the end of the day. They need to improve
the show itself with competition and production.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd just as soon everybody come out and see it live.''
INSIDE THE NUMBERS Thundering across Texas
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Motorplex in Ennis and Houston Raceway Park in Baytown
have produced six of 10 current professional quarter-mile national
elapsed time and mph records in the NHRA's Winston Drag Racing
Series: Driver ET/speed Site Date Top Fuel Gary Scelzi 4.525
seconds Ennis October 1998 Gary Scelzi 326.44 mph Baytown November
1998 Funny Car Cruz Pedregon 4.807 seconds Baytown November 1998
John Force 323.89 mph Englishtown, N.J. May 1998 Pro Stock Warren
Johnson 6.867 seconds Ennis October 1998 Warren Johnson 201.34 mph
Ennis October 1998 Pro Stock Truck Larry Kopp 7.594 seconds Ennis
October 1998 John Lingenfelter 178.32 mph Pomona, Calif. November
1998 Pro Stock Bike Matt Hines 7.245 seconds Gainesville, Fla.
March 1998 Matt Hines 188.32 mph Dinwiddie, Va. April 1998
</P>
