<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN'T ALWAYS COUNT ON A COUNTEROFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some questions from the workplace: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --What are your chances for a counteroffer? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume you're a valued worker who just announced a new job
offer. Now you are waiting for your current boss to try to keep
you. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't hold your breath. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even employers who rant about high turnover and the difficulty
of retaining good people may not cough up a counteroffer. A recent
survey by Robert Half and Accountemps found that 56 percent of the
executives surveyed might try to the persuade an employee to stay,
but 42 percent said that was unlikely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because the unemployment rate is so low, willingness to counter
has increased in recent years, said Michelle Hersh, vice president
of the temporary-staffing service in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But many won't counter because they want to ``avoid challenges
to their compensation scale when other staff learn of the agreement
and question their own salaries,'' she said. Also, some employers
``may have lingering concerns about an employee's loyalty after a
counteroffer is accepted.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --What does customer service mean to you? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Kansas Citian Harry Hall, it sure isn't those convenient 800
numbers. Hall spent more than an hour on the phone Wednesday
morning trying to reach an employee who works at an AT&AMP;T office in
downtown Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hall thinks he spoke with AT&AMP;T customer service representatives
in Miami, Salt Lake City and somewhere in West Virginia. The 800
numbers are the only ones listed in the local phone book. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``For the life of me, I couldn't get to a living soul in Kansas
City,'' Hall said. ``No one would give me a phone number for the
office right here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If it had been an emergency, AT&AMP;T would have taken Hall's
message and contacted the worker. Because Hall was trying to reach
the worker for business reasons, he was out of luck _ and not happy
about it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Have you tried to give any input lately? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I sometimes write about organizations involved in
``empowerment'' or ``teamwork'' or ``flattening hierarchies.'' The
efforts are designed to improve communication with the staff and to
hear from people whose jobs would be most affected by policies or
procedures at stake. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's the goal, anyway. I recently heard a real-life story that
shows how many workplaces fall far short. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A worker told her boss, ``I have a suggestion for the suggestion
box.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aware we had a suggestion box,'' he responded, and
walked away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Do you know where your ``gig line'' is? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The smartly dressed man knows. It's the vertical axis along
which the shirt buttons, tie, belt buckle and pants zipper should
lie. A zigzagging gig is a no-no. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's from /{Attention to Detail: A Gentleman's Guide to
Professional Appearance and Conduct/}. In addition to addressing
the finer points of office attire, author Clinton T. Greenleaf III
attempts to rid the world of ``dead fish'' handshakes and other
killers of good impressions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a quick read that covers a lot. Perhaps a graduation gift?
Contact the author at clint &LR; greenleafenterprises.com or P.O. Box
291, Chesterland, OH 44026, or (440) 338-4553. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
