<HEADLINE>
TCU'S RECRUITING CLASS LAUDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A couple of weeks ago, TCU football coach
Dennis Franchione traveled to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   He was to visit with Bo Schobel, a highly recruited defensive
end who long ago said he'd be attending TCU.
</P>
<P>
   He also discovered a reminder of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the phone on the wall, there was a letter from me dated
Jan. 20, 1998, offering him a scholarship,'' Franchione said. ``And
I was there Jan. 20, 1999. So, it has a been a culmination of a
year of work and preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first year, Franchione has recruited a class loaded with
players just like Schobel, players who had a chance to go anywhere,
but, instead, chose TCU.
</P>
<P>
   TCU has secured unheard of recognition about its class from
recruiting analysts both in Texas (behind only Texas and Texas A&AMP;M)
and nationally (a Top 20 program by some analysts).
</P>
<P>
   Franchione received 19 faxes from recruits committing to TCU
yesterday, his last coming at 11 a.m. from Dallas Kimball tailback
Ricky Madison. With a junior-college fullback already on campus,
TCU finished with a recruiting class of 20.
</P>
<P>
   Faxes came from Fort Worth's most sought-after recruits _
Dunbar's twins Jerome and Jerrod Braziel, Wyatt's Donald Burrell
and Boswell's Chad Pugh _ and from recruits like DeSoto's Casey
Printers and Lamar's Tommicus Walker _ wanted by schools such as
Texas and Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think TCU just did a great job recruiting us and the players
in this area,'' Jerome Braziel said.
</P>
<P>
   When Franchione sent Schobel that letter a year ago, he had his
doubts about landing the defender.
</P>
<P>
   He faced the task of selling a 1-10 Horned Frogs team to players
also being courted by programs such as Texas, Texas A&AMP;M and Notre
Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Waco Robinson's John Glud bought into Franchione's message in
August, selecting TCU instead of A&AMP;M and Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I was the first one,'' Glud said. ``I had a feeling the
first day I went to TCU's camp that something special was going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Bishop Lynch's Matt Orlovsky, Printers and Schobel
followed soon after.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were four really good commitments right from the get-go
that not only got you some guys but got you some real quality
football players,'' Franchione said. ``You certainly have to
appreciate those guys who jumped on board when we were trying to
win instead of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Being first and early brought a few negatives.
</P>
<P>
   Glud and Schobel both had friends asking: ``Why TCU?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got tired of people asking: `Why TCU?' '' Glud said. ``That
\RSun Bowl\S victory just said: `That's why TCU.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Schobel also had a chance to go anywhere, his name littering Top
100 lists everywhere. He visited Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Family drew him to TCU. His father, Bob Schobel, played for TCU
from 1969-72. His cousins, Aaron and Matt, play for TCU now.
</P>
<P>
   A numbering system already has been planned. Matt looks to wear
No. 7. Aaron already wears No. 14. Bo says he plans to wear No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Schobel had committed long before he left for El Paso and
TCU's Sun Bowl victory against USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a lot better that day,'' Schobel said. ``I remember
thinking that we have a good chance to become a national power.''
</P>
<P>
   His fax arrived first yesterday and was waiting for Franchione
upon his arrival at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Schobel had just a few last demands before signing, including
``a guaranteed weekly supply of homemade \Rnot store-bought\S
chocolate chip cookies'' and the ``eldest daughter of the most
well-paid coach at TCU should also be made available.''
</P>
<P>
   A joke, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Smiles and laughs were plentiful at TCU, though. So, Franchione
played along, signing off on Schobel's farcical requests and faxing
back a message of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have the rest of the staff start on daughters
immediately. Just please, please sign!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
