<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-03 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1219 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     02-03 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN AMONG THOSE IMPRESSED BY PAYNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even if Oregon State loses the rest of its games,
UCLA's Steve Lavin plans to vote for Beavers coach Eddie Payne for
Pac-10 Coach of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Payne has been that much better than his competition _ turning
an amalgam of transfers and secondary recruits into a respectable
outfit that has defeated Arizona and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers are 5-4 in conference play (11-7 overall) entering
visits to USC tonight and UCLA on Sunday. That classifies as a
minor miracle in Corvallis, considering they won a total of eight
conference games from 1996-98.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers have a decent chance to finish higher than seventh
place for the first time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne has done a tremendous job getting them to buy into his
team concept,'' Lavin said. ``They've embraced the game plan and
they've identified roles. It's not so much the players they have as
the way they play.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Payne) will get my vote for Coach of the Year regardless of
how they finish.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Payne's performance unique is his seamless rebuilding
of Oregon State's core. Six players left the program after the
1997-98 seasons, including guard Carson Cunningham, who transferred
to Purdue, and guard Corey Benjamin, who entered the NBA last
spring. The Beavers start four junior college transfers and
sophomore guard Deaundra Tanner, yet they're as cohesive as
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, in his fourth year, is taking the success in stride. The
Beavers do not have the talent to sustain their current standing
(fourth place), and they have the grueling L.A. and Arizona road
trips looming this month, plus a trip to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it for a night and wake up the next day and go back to
work,'' he said of the watershed victories over UCLA and Arizona.
``But we're aware it's a journey, not a destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have much margin for error. We have to play every
possession like it's the last possession and take advantage of our
opportunities. We're still deficient from an athletic standpoint,
and we have to overcome that by being precise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers benefit from being Oregon's travel partner _
visitors have concentrated on the Ducks and dismissed Oregon State
as an easy victory _ and from a grinding style that befuddles
faster teams.
</P>
<P>
   But defense has fueled the Beavers' success. Oregon State leads
the Pac-10 in field goal percentage defense (36.5), and it has held
league foes to 18.6 percent shooting from 3-point range in Gill
Coliseum. Payne's strategy is to deny the opponent what it does
best: with UCLA, the Beavers prevented Baron Davis from
penetrating; with Arizona State, they smothered Eddie House on the
perimeter; with Arizona, they contained Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   The next step for Oregon State _ perhaps the hardest step _ is
to learn to win on the road. The lesson continues this weekend in
L.A..
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down: Granted, Lavin shouldn't have acted the way he
acted at Washington and Baron Davis shouldn't have said what he
said. But the Pac-10 office compounded the problem by mishandling
their respective punishments.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner is Davis, an emotional 19-year-old who said
something he shouldn't have _ that referee Terry Christman
``cheated'' the Bruins _ without knowing the potential
repercussions: reprimand, probation, suspension. He was embarrassed
publicly and strong-armed into an apology.
</P>
<P>
   In the other corner is Lavin, 34, who knew the rules, knew
exactly what he could say, and made several incriminating remarks.
Regardless of whether he actually used the buzzwords _
``referees,'' ``officials,'' or ``Terry Christman'' _ everyone knew
exactly what he meant. But because his comments were cloaked and
calculated, he received a private reprimand: Gee, Steve, please
don't do that again.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in offenses was not commensurate with the
difference in penalties. Davis paid a much higher price for saying
what Lavin knew enough to infer, and that's not fair.
</P>
<P>
   And by forcing Davis into an apology, commissioner Tom Hansen
undermined the credibility of the apology itself. (UCLA released a
three-sentence statement that Davis presumably did not write.)
Davis' post-practice comments Tuesday seemed sincere, but they
didn't have to be to serve their purpose. The league was so eager
to make an example of Davis, it tarnished the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Around the West: The Connecticut-Stanford collision Saturday at
Maples Pavilion lost much of its significance with the Huskies'
loss to Syracuse and the injuries to star Rip Hamilton and center
Jake Voskuhl.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has a thigh problem and is expected back this week, but
Voskuhl is out with a stress fracture. Without him, the Huskies
don't have the frontline muscle to match Mark Madsen and friends.
Stanford by double-digits....Doesn't it seem like Utah's Rick
Majerus does the best coaching job of his life every year? Quietly,
his Utes have become one of the hottest teams in the country....
The area's best non-Pac-10 game of the season takes place Feb. 19
in Malibu, where Pepperdine hosts Gonzaga in a West Coast
Conference showdown....Any Associated Press pollsters voting for
New Mexico should have the privilege rescinded. The Lobos have won
one road game, San Jose State; they lost at New Mexico State by 21,
and they scored just 39 points at home against Utah.... Now that
he's eligible at a four-year school, watch for Schea Cotton to
surface close to home, perhaps at Pepperdine or USC. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
