</P>
<P>
   NY-GUEST-ROOM (New York) _ Two- and three-bedroom apartments are
as hard to find in the Village as imperfections in a leading lady.
But three years ago, with the can-do spirit of someone who wielded
the green eyeliner in ``Aliens IV'' and made Daniel Day Lewis look
haggard _ well, almost _ in ``The Crucible,'' Naomi Donne, sank
$200,000 into a one-bedroom wreck with ceilings that reached nearly
14 feet, because she had a vision that there might be just enough
space up there to create room for guests. ``It was inevitable that
people were going to visit,'' she said nonchalantly. ``I just
wanted them out of the way.'' By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT28,29) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SWEENEY-HOUSE (Undated) _ Julia Sweeney's parents, Bob and Jeri,
have moved out of the bedroom. Her boyfriend no longer has to crash
in the office out back. The guest room is empty, save for a few
artifacts left behind when her brother Mike died. The pull-out bed
in the living room remains safely tucked under its corduroy
cushions. In other words, the comedian and ``Saturday Night Live''
veteran has her Hollywood dream bungalow back to herself. For those
who saw her one-woman show or read her book, ``God Said, `Ha!'''
(Bantam, 1997), a bittersweet memoir about living with cancer in a
reconstituted nuclear family Sweeney's parents and her brother are
familiar characters. By James Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   PALMBEACH-ANTIQUES-FAIR (Palm Beach, Fla.) _ Kristy French, a
young collector from Dallas, was at the International Art and
Antique Fair here _ which runs through Sunday _ trying to expand
her collection of 20th-century works of art. Take the Picasso.
``It's just a little picture,'' she explained. ``Cubist, from 1922.
But I just bought a Lichtenstein _ 1992 _ and it's very similar in
style. That's something I like to do: weave a thread between
them.'' Ms. French, 35, and her interior designer friend, Barry
Williams, were among the hundreds of antique lovers who gathered
here last Thursday night for the ``Vernissage'' _ Euro-speak for
``opening''_ of the city's three-year-old antiques fair. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   METALLIC-PLASTIC (New York) _ The Accent on Design exhibition at
this week's New York gift show, where manufacturers show off
products for the coming year, was awash with items for the home in
metallic plastic. These are not plastic glasses and garbage cans
spray-painted copper or silver, understand, but objects molded of a
polypropylene or vinyl where the metal color is part of the
material. Their flowing shapes, loose and liquid as some special
effect from ``Terminator 2,'' flaunt their plasticity. They seem to
inhabit some alchemical middle state between plastic and metal. By
Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-PLANTS (New York) _ Colman Rutkin and Sage Reynolds were
not about to rush around straightening up their rambling, 12-room
house on Staten Island just because a photographer was coming.
Thank goodness. In the bleak mid-winter, I was looking for people
who didn't need spring to have green, living things keeping them
company. And I didn't want them tidying up seedlings on the kitchen
sink. ``We have plants in the bathroom,'' Rutman said, ``plants in
the attic, plants in the cellar.'' I went right over. By Anne
Raver.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT16,17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-FURNITURE-FAIR (Cologne, Germany) _ Material was the
message at the International Furniture Fair, where retailers find
the broadest range of contemporary furniture available. Exhibitors
_ some 1,600 from 46 countries _ were out of new ideas about form,
stuck as they were in the minimal, spare look of the 1970s. So they
turned to substances for inspiration. The materials of the moment
are neither cutting edge nor high tech. Instead, designers
experimented with the tried and true _ wood, glass, stainless steel
and porcelain _ with surprising results. Here's a preview of the
designs likely to cause the biggest ripples when they arrive in
America this spring and summer. By Arlene Hirst.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
