<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-REDWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS, BACK TO THEIR LOSING WAYS, FALL TO RED WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Bill Stewart's coaching career in the NHL got off to a
good start, but the momentum has stopped and he is now seeing how
wretched his Islanders can play.
</P>
<P>
   After Stewart replaced Mike Milbury behind the bench on Jan. 21,
the Islanders won their first two games and then earned a tie. But
now, Stewart must try to turn his team around from his first NHL
losing streak. The Islanders lost their second in succession
Wednesday night, a 5-1 defeat administered by the Detroit Red Wings
in Joe Louis Arena. In their last two games, the Islanders have
been out-scored 14-3. They play on Thursday night in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selfish penalties,'' Stewart said, referring to third-period
infractions called against Robert Reichel and Zigmund Palffy. The
penalties made a comeback all but impossible. ``Missed check on the
second goal,'' he said, referring to Mariusz Czerkawski, who played
less than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not good enough for this league,'' Stewart added, referring to
the team in general. ``I wasn't too pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Rich Pilon, the rugged defenseman, who was knocked down
by a punch from Detroit's Darren McCarty, who also scored two
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys have to step up and start playing for the team instead of
yourself,'' Pilon said. ``You can't keep blaming the goalie or the
coaches. We're all men. You've got to be prepared to make
sacrifices.'' Pilon said his teammates should wear ``work boots''
instead of ``ballet slippers'' and that the new coach means
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to make it stop,'' Pilon said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Yzerman, Martin Lapointe and Brendan Shanahan also scored
for the Wings, who held a 3-0 lead after 26 seconds of the second
period. Sergei Nemchinov scored the Islanders' goal, cutting the
lead to 3-1 at 1:29 of the second. Shanahan's goal came in the
game's last second, beating goalie Tommy Salo, who faced 44 shots.
</P>
<P>
   In the other net, the Wings had an interesting rotation. Chris
Osgood, the regular first-stringer, did not suit up due to a case
of the flu. His replacement was Kevin Hodson, who left in the 18th
minute of the first period when a finger on his right hand was cut
when he stopped a shot. He was replaced by Norm Maracle, who
stopped 19 of 20 shots he faced. Hodson stopped the other eight
before he left.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first appearance for Maracle since he was arrested
last Sunday morning in the Detroit suburb of Royal Oak and charged
with drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I wasn't expecting to play,'' Maracle said. ``I was a
little down. Obviously, I made a big mistake, and I want to
apologize. I'm supposed to be a professional athlete and
professional athletes don't do that. We get a lot of kids who look
up to us. It doesn't look good. I know it'll never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarty, who has battled his own alcohol problem, said of
Maracle: ``Everybody makes mistakes. We're here to support him.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarty seemed especially energized Wednesday night. In
Detroit's previous game, a 2-2 tie in New Jersey, McCarty said he
regretted not avenging the deeds of Devils enforcer Krzysztof
Oliwa, who put two Wings defensemen _ Larry Murphy and Todd Gill _
out with injuries and later threw Yzerman around by the face mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's more upset about the other night than I am,'' McCarty
said. ``It's something you don't forget. It's not going to happen
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
