<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEFENSE STOPS A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With Texas A&AMP;M calling a team meeting in the
lane every time Texas threw the ball into either Chris Mihm or Gabe
Muoneke, the Longhorns had to find some other avenue to victory.
</P>
<P>
   They found it along a well-worn path _ defense.
</P>
<P>
   Texas converted 30 A&AMP;M turnovers into 30 points and finally put
away the stubborn Aggies, 71-59, last night before a season-high
Erwin Center crowd of 12,915.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns (13-9) won for the 10th time in 11 games and
boosted their Big 12-leading record to 8-1. The Aggies (9-10)
dropped to 2-7.
</P>
<P>
   UT point guard Ivan Wagner led the defensive charge with a
career-high and Big 12-record 10 steals, though he also committed
five turnovers against a well-designed A&AMP;M defensive scheme. He
scored nine points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking off the court tonight Ivan said how sorry he was about
the turnovers _ you've got to love a guy like that,'' UT coach Rick
Barnes said. ``He did a great job converting some plays when he
came up with steals.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's 10 steals tied a school record (B.J. Tyler, 1994) and
broke a Big 12 year-old standard of eight set by A&AMP;M's Michael
Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a conscious effort to step up our defense tonight
because against UMass \RSunday\S it just wasn't there,'' Wagner
said, referring to Sunday's 76-65 victory against Massachusetts.
``I thought they were telegraphing their passes, or their moves, a
lot. I tried to anticipate and stay a step ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half was as bad as we played in a long time. Our
offensive execution wasn't good at all. We raced up and down the
court with them and didn't get settled \Roffensively\S, but we
didn't lose our composure to where we felt like we couldn't win the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the attention, Mihm managed his seventh consecutive
double-double with 11 points and equaled a career high of 17
rebounds. By converting 10 of 12 opportunities from the line,
Muoneke scored a game-high 19 points. Kris Clack added only 12, but
Texas got strong bench support as guards Will Clay and Chris
McColpin scored eight each.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Aggies scorer Shanne Jones did not score for the first
time in his career in only 18 minutes. A&AMP;M now has 60 costly
turnovers in its past two games against Oklahoma State and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty seems to be our magic number,'' A&AMP;M coach Melvin
Watkins said. ``Some of those are very disturbing because we turned
it over for a lack of being able to dribble the basketball at
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to compete at the highest level and we did some
of the time. A great atmosphere. It should make for some good
basketball down the highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he wasn't surprised by the Aggies in the first
meeting between his team and Watkins'.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Melvin and know how his teams play _ they play hard,''
Barnes said. ``But this is what February is about. Teams are going
to compete and you have to be ready to handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we are right now we're going to have to take everyone's
best shot and that's great. When you do that, it makes you
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
